<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HN     02-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal gave Steve Francis a way out, an
escape from this disaster. Like falling on a stack of grenades, it
would not have been pretty or painless. But it might have beaten
the catastrophe well under way.
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Neal had stopped on his way to the free-throw line to flip the
ball back to an official. Instead, he bounced it directly off
Francis' shoulder. Francis shot back a mock glare as if considering
a re-enactment of the early-season Charles Barkley-O'Neal
Wrestlemania act.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of it. But Francis would have been better off in
the rumble. He would have given up 10 inches and 140 pounds. But he
would have come closer than he and the Rockets did the rest of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets eventually lost by only 101-85 to the Los Angeles
Lakers on Sunday, but that has become an increasingly frequent
measure of Rockets success _ how little they lose by.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent the season fighting off such ignominy, the Rockets
have been slapped around in four of the past seven games, even
without Francis choosing not to go Barkley on O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it worth a ,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``We have to work our way out of this thing somehow. This is
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, unusual. It barely stood up to the recent
no-contest collapses against the Hawks, Spurs and Nuggets. This
time, the Rockets made their too-late run a bit earlier. With the
Lakers having become as disinterested as the beat-the-traffic crowd
that deserted the high-dollar seats, the Rockets rallied from as
much as 26 back to within 12 with 5:06 left.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley, who has become the Rockets' expert trash
collector of garbage time, scored 17 points in the fourth quarter
and finished with 29. In the Rockets' four recent collapses, he has
averaged 25.8.
</P>
<P>
   But his effort did little but force Lakers coach Phil Jackson to
wake up O'Neal and Kobe Bryant and send them back to the mismatch.
Each scored the first time he touched the ball, and the Rockets
never sneaked within 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to church this morning with Ernestine Bradley (wife of
presidential candidate Bill Bradley), and I saw more energy there
than on this court,'' Jackson said. ``I thought we played an
energetic first quarter, and then we just hit the punch bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, hitting the punch bag meant the Lakers merely went
through the motions, having waylaid the Rockets from the opening
bell. The Rockets' late rally could not hide a horrible shooting
day or the way Bryant and O'Neal toyed with them.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied from the outset by Bryant's quick-footed defense,
Francis missed his first nine shots, giving him a run of 15
consecutive misses going back to the Denver disaster of Thursday.
He finished with six points and seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve just couldn't get going today,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I
mean, we couldn't do the simplest deals. I was hoping he would work
his way out of it. We talked about it at halftime, taking a little
bit of your aggressiveness out. If your ball-handling is
struggling, get into the flow of the game, letting the ball come
back to you and getting off the schneid that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to slow down. We looked at the tape a little bit at
halftime. There were plays that it had nothing to do with the
defense. He was just overanxious, kicking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis blamed himself for the loss. ``I (messed) it up,'' he
said again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But he was far from the Rockets' only problem. By the end of the
first quarter, they had fallen behind 30-13, their lowest-scoring
opening quarter of the season. Bryant cruised to 18 points in the
first 12 minutes, and the Lakers seemed bent only on winning easily
enough to rest for Tuesday's showdown with Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were so outmatched with their starters that
Tomjanovich began the second quarter with a lineup of Pig Miller,
Matt Bullard, Bryce Drew, Moochie Norris and Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an improvement, and the Rockets' 29-point half was
their worst of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But with Bryant matching his season high with 31 points and
O'Neal rolling to 24 points, 13 rebounds and eight assists,
Tomjanovich was more critical of the Rockets' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense has been horse (manure),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And with all that, the Rockets were stumped to understand what
had gone wrong since their Super Bowl Sunday upset of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no explanation, no reasons,'' Kenny Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing,'' Mobley said, ``because it was on NBC,
and to go out there and watch Kobe go for layups, dunks, laughing
and smiling, we'd have tried anything.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
