r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     02-28 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN; BLAZERS ARE NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sometime between the Lakers' last losing skid and
their current winning streak, Sunday's payback game against the
Houston Rockets became a nationally televised formality. An
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   But a necessary prelude, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers entered the day tied with the Portland Trail Blazers
for divisional supremacy, and for the best record in the league.
The rivals play Tuesday night, for the final time this season, and
for dramatic emphasis all they needed was to keep pace with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Easy enough for the Lakers, who beat up on the Rockets 101-85 at
Staples Center, thus assuring a perfect script for the date at the
Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers earlier held off the Utah Jazz, leaving them tied
with the Lakers in both win-loss record (45-11) and winning streak
(11 each).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a groove right now, we're in a rhythm, so we're going
up there with that groove we have now,'' said Kobe Bryant, who
scored a game-high 31 points. ``It's important to have a game like
we had today, nationally televised. It's good for our momentum,
good for our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And good for the soul. They needed a cleansing after a loss at
Houston last month that coach Phil Jackson characterized as
pathetic, their worst game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   There was never any danger of a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant held fleet-footed rookie Steve Francis to zero points in
the first half, and six in the game, and the Lakers shot better
than 50 percent (41 for 77) for the third game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   It took an unaesthetic second half -- in which the Lakers simply
nursed their double-digit lead -- for Jackson to find anything to
grouse about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to church this morning at the AME church downtown here.
... The AME had a lot more spirit there than we had today on this
court,'' said Jackson, who attended services with Ernestine
Bradley, wife of presidential candidate Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   It only took one quarter of spirited play to get the win,
though. Bryant hammered the Rockets for 18 points out of the gate
as the Lakers took a 30-13 advantage. It put to rest any concern
over Bryant's bruised left calf -- especially he opened the game
with a one-handed fast-break jam -- though he admitted he's still
sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bothering me,'' he said. ``On that first dunk I didn't
mean to even jump. Phil said, `What the hell are you doing?' I said
I didn't mean to. It just happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, when you have injuries, your concentration tends
to pick up a little bit. You tend to focus a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal fed Bryant for his first three scores and
finished with a game-high eight assists, once again just missing a
triple-double. He finished with 24 points and 13 rebounds to go
with five blocked shots. Glen Rice added 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bryant) played very well,'' O'Neal said. ``He took a lot of
shots, and he hit most of them. And on any given night, any one of
our top three can play that type of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to overwhelm the Rockets (21-35), and the Lakers
built as much as a 26-point lead in the second half. Then a
fired-up Cuttino Mobley almost single-handedly brought Houston
back, scoring 23 of his 29 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' Mobley said, ``because it's on NBC, just
watching Kobe lay it up and dunk it and laugh and smile. I don't
appreciate stuff like that. That team's an OK team, but without
Shaq, I just don't think, come on. It's just Shaq, he cleaned up
the whole lane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had happier thoughts about their next matchup here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news,'' said Matt Bullard, ``is that we've got the
Clippers next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
