r s BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN     02-28 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC LANDS RECRUIT HANOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC received a verbal commitment from shooting
guard Travis Hanour of Laguna Beach High on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hanour (6-foot-5, 200 pounds) selected the Trojans over Arizona,
Utah and San Diego State. He made his official visit to USC over
the weekend, and was in the locker room after the Trojans' 80-77
loss to Oregon at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   He is considered one of the rising stars in Southern California,
with many schools becoming interested in him this season. He is
considered a late bloomer, after not playing his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   Hanour is the third player to commit to USC. Shooting guard
Desmon Farmer of Flint, Mich., signed in November and point guard
Robert Hutchinson of Okaloosa-Walton Community College in
Niceville, Fla., committed in December.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy eager for return: Forward Sam Clancy has moved up his
comeback to Thursday against Stanford, but Clancy nearly made a
stunning attempt to against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy participated in pre-game warm-ups, taking jump shots and
working on some post moves, and when he felt no pain, announced he
would play against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could play but the trainer wanted me to take it
easy,'' Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy has been out since Jan. 20 with a broken foot, and a
return against Oregon would have been far sooner than expected. He
previously said he would come back for the Cal game on Saturday,
but after the Trojans' loss to Oregon, decided he wanted to make
his return Thursday in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby cautioned against false expectations when
Clancy returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally up to Sam when he returns, but Sam is not the
savior,'' Bibby said. ``We're not trying to put pressure on him.
Sam knows he's not in shape to play.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a chance Clancy will not play this weekend, if he
experiences any flare-ups in his foot in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's hurting, then I will back off,'' Clancy said. ``I
might just rest.''
</P>
<P>
   His mere appearance in a uniform Saturday was surprising enough
for his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting to see him out there,'' forward David
Bluthenthal said. ``It was kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   What's left? The Trojans (14-12, 7-7) know they need to win
their last four games for a shot at making the NCAA Tournament, but
what happens if they win three of their last four?
</P>
<P>
   That would give USC a 10-8 record in conference. Not impressive,
but no Pac-10 team that won at least 10 games has ever missed the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Working against the Trojans would be a 4-6 record in the final
10 games of the season, since that is one factor the selection
committee uses to pick at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get 10 wins, it's not in our hands to decide,'' forward
David Bluthenthal said. ``We know that we probably have to win out.
It will be tough going to the Bay Area. But not a lot of people
have given us a chance to all year.
</P>
<P>
   Guard play: For all of the focus on the offensive prowess of
forwards Brian Scalabrine and Bluthenthal, an easy way to gauge the
Trojans is the shooting of guards of Brandon Granville and Jeff
Trepagnier.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's loss to Arizona State, Granville and Trepagnier
were 9 for 28 from the field. In Saturday's loss to Oregon, they
were 4 for 18.
</P>
<P>
   But they made 9 of 17 shots in Thursday's victory over Oregon
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pounded the ball inside pretty well (against Oregon),''
Scalabrine said. ``That's usually enough for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
