<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENDEES SAY RAVES NOT ABOUT DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brandon Switzer calls himself the ``Boy Wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   As laser beams bounce over his head, the 18-year-old dances in a
sea of pulsating bodies, twirling his glow sticks to the endless,
dense, thumping beat resonating from inside a dark Mesa building
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   His smile stretches from ear to ear.
</P>
<P>
   Rave scenes have come under the microscope since the arrest of
mob turncoat Salvatore ``Sammy the Bull'' Gravano, who is accused
of financing and operating a ring that dealt the drug Ecstasy to
Valley ravers.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers deny it, but police say 90 percent of the
midnight-to-dawn revelers imbibe in Ecstasy, alternately known as
``E,'' ``X'' or ``XTC,'' which produces a euphoric high and intense
feelings``'' of alertness and well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But ravers like Switzer said that leaves out the most important
part of raves: ``Most of us are here for the music and for PLUR _
peace, love, unity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you are: Black, White, green, bisexual . . . we
don't care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer was among the estimated 1,100 young people _ some
donning neon blue hairpieces, Afro wigs and blinking visors _ who
squeezed into the renovated Nile movie theater in Mesa on Saturday
night for the ``Daylight'' party.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't deny that the designer drugs like Ecstasy and
Ketamine _ a horse tranquilizer _ permeate the scene, but shrugs
and says, ``We're just here to have fun'' and dances on.
</P>
<P>
   At the Nile, there were telltale signs of the drugs' presence _
trance-like stares, surgical masks, pacifiers. Ravers say they coat
the masks with Vicks Vapo Rub either to help them breathe or
enhance their high; the pacifiers help keep them from grinding
their teeth, a side effect common with Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the whole scene.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they spent more than $18,000 preparing for
Saturday night's event _ they had to secure a venue, pay for
lighting, sound systems and a DJ, world-famous New Yorker named
Frankie Bones.
</P>
<P>
   Security was abundant.
</P>
<P>
   Girls in tube tops and feathered boas shivered outside the
building waiting in line for security officers to pat them down.
</P>
<P>
   After a search of one teen's wallet turned up something
suspicious, security officer Sal Augone tore open the tiny package
and threw the white-powdery substance in the plastic bin along with
the rest of the confiscated items like water bottles and surgical
masks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry buddy, we can't let you in,'' Augone told the
disappointed teen.
</P>
<P>
   A few other kids huddled outside, kicked out for looking too
drugged out, Augone said.
</P>
<P>
   Others paid $25 a head to rave until 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Espinosa, 25, said electronic dance music _ whether
trance, jungle hip-hop or hard-core _ brings people together in a
safe, happy environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bump into somebody at a bar, they'll try to fight
you,'' she said. ``You do the same thing here, and they'll hug
you.''
</P>
<P>
   By 11 p.m., the theater was packed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a young crowd, with an average age of 17, dressed in
everything from simple white Polo shirts and baseball caps to silky
pajamas and pig tails to fishnet hose and nose rings.
</P>
<P>
   They wore blinking lights, edible candy and fairy wings; they
carried Pokemon dolls, water bottles and pacifiers. Glitter and Glo
sticks abounded.
</P>
<P>
   They danced on the stage, lingered by the walls and gave each
other massages. Some bounced their heads inches away from speakers,
others whirled Day-glo vials like nunchuks.
</P>
<P>
   Booths sold bottled water, Gatorade and Red Bull, an energy
drink.
</P>
<P>
   No alcohol or drugs were allowed, but that doesn't mean they
weren't there. In fact, most ravers don't deny the drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some people take `X,' '' Switzer said. ``But I don't get
why they blame it on raves.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Holcomb, an attorney who represents promoters, said there's
no way 90 percent of the kids were on drugs, as police indicated
last week, but he admitted that it's impossible to keep all
drug-use out.
</P>
<P>
   He and promoter Gino Carlucci say they do everything they can to
keep their raves clean, which distinguishes their parties from the
illegitimate parties.
</P>
<P>
   `` '' These illegal parties, which usually have no permits or
security, were the ones police targeted, Phoenix undercover
Detective Jim Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the availability of Ecstasy, GHB and
Ketamine,'' Gibbs said. ``It's pretty wild stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He said dealers advertised Ecstasy or Ketamine by wearing
T-shirts or bracelets with ``X'' or ``E'' with a circle around it
and it wasn't uncommon to see kids passed out, throwing up or lying
on the ground in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a bad rap because they think we're all on drugs,'' said
Aspen Tufares, 18. ``But you see just as many drugs here as you
would at any college party.''
</P>
<P>
   Every weekend, thousands of Valley ravers click on a Web site or
dial up recorded messages that direct them to abandoned warehouses,
airport hangers or desert areas so they, too, can join the masses
of young people who rave until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   The once-underground society has been throwing raves for years,
and has now become an international phenomenon that's more
mainstream, more commercialized, and more of a business than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the culture has remained relatively quiet in the Valley _
until now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
