<HEADLINE>
BETTER LATE THAN NEVER? NOT FOR `GRAPEVINE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Networks often yank low-rated shows amid talk of returning them
``at a later date.''
</P>
<P>
   How about eight years later, with an almost totally different
cast?
</P>
<P>
   That's the story behind ``Grapevine,'' which returns to CBS
tonight. And the moral of said story?
</P>
<P>
   Not everything's worth waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble takes us into the love lives of several attractive
young people who live in Miami. There are the cruise director, the
restaurant owner, the sportscaster, blah, blah, blah. With the
exception of George Eads as Thumper, the boneheaded sportscaster,
the cast is notable mostly for being unlikable _ especially Kristy
Swanson as the cruise director.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The original ``Grapevine'' started a six-week run in the summer
of 1992. Although summer is usually a swampy graveyard for TV, CBS
had launched the hit show ``Northern Exposure'' the previous summer
and was looking for more magic.
</P>
<P>
   No rabbit in that hat. Shot without an audience, with characters
breaking the ``fourth wall'' between themselves and viewers and
with a decided emphasis on sex, ``Grapevine'' withered _ even
though plenty of shows adopted some or all of those features in
later years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to think, `Maybe we are a little bit late to the
table,' until I saw some of our rough cuts,'' says David Frankel,
the show's creator. ``I am still convinced there is nothing like
``Grapevine'' on television.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from sitting on the CBS shelf for almost the entire
Clinton administration, there is one other interesting aspect to
``Grapevin''e: It's a show about young, beautiful people on a
network that appeals to older viewers. (CBS president Les Moonves
told critics that ``my 15-year-old daughter said it's the first
show she's ever wanted to watch on CBS.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I think it might be nice,'' Frankel says. ``The
timing might be right for this show to work on CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   It is toned down, he said. ``The old show was a lot about sex,
and how far could we push the envelope showing sex and talking
about sex,'' Frankel says. ``The new show, I like to think, is
about romance. It's a function of me being eight years older and
American culture being eight years older.''
</P>
<P>
   And with any luck, wiser _ wise enough to pass on
``Grapevine.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
