<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN FOREIGN-POLICY PERSPECTIVES: MORALISTS VS. REALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORMAN LEVINE  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (RETRANSMITTING INHERITING-1, INHERITING-2 AND INHERITING-3 FOR
THOS
 &UR; E WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED THIS SPECIAL PACKAGE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEXSTARS AVALANCHEMAKEFORGOODHOCK   02-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
 STARS, AVALANCHE MAKE FOR GOOD HOCKEY (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By JENNIFER FLOYD c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If the Stanley Cup playoffs began today, the Stars and
the Colorado Avalanche would play in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you didn't notice that's the same two teams who
spent 65 minutes last night at Reunion Arena scrapping, clawing and
banging for every inch of space in 1-1 tie in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said as he rolled his eyes
before adding, ``only if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody needing a refresher course on just how exciting, intense
and close games between these teams can be need only to watch last
season's Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars won the seven-game marathon on their way to winning
the Stanley Cup last season, but if last night showed anything it
is that it would be even closer this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams were kind of desperate,'' Stars captain Derian
Hatcher said. ``After the game we played against Chicago. They were
slipping as well in the standings. I thought both teams
concentrated on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche came in losers of three straight games and were
looking at possibly not making the playoffs. The Stars were coming
off an embarrassing loss to lowly Chicago on Friday and are looking
at a week that includes games against legitimate Cup contenders,
Philadelphia, Phoenix and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams wanted two points. Both teams were more than happy to
leave with one.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the hockey term for what took place last night at
Reunion arena is ``man's game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for weak-kneed people,'' Hitchcock said. ``It had the
feeling of a sudden death game.''
</P>
<P>
   In final 15 seconds of overtime, both teams had good chances to
go home happy.
</P>
<P>
   First, Stars winger Brett Hull came speeding in on Avalanche
goalie Patrick Roy only to have Colorado defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh
prevent him from getting off a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   The save made, Roy started the play going in the other
direction. Only this time it was Avalanche winger Milan Hejduk
skating alone up the right side and only to have Stars center Mike
Modano get a piece of it at the last second. Stars goalie Ed
Belfour made the save.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 10 minutes wasn't the greatest hockey, but the last
50 were pretty solid,'' Modano said. ``We had our opportunities,
but Roy and Belfour are two of the top goalies in the league right
now and that's the way it is against those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Belfour, the score could've easily been 4-0 after the
first period. He stopped 12 shots, making the Avs settle for 1-0.
Colorado defenseman Greg De Vries scored at 9:47 of the first
period on a shot that bounced off of Belfour's pad. He finished
with 24 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Roy made 18 saves in all, but really wasn't tested until late in
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   With two minutes remaining in the second period, a pulse was
finally detected on the home team. The line of Scott Thornton,
Brett Hull and Kirk Muller along with defensemen Darryl Sydor and
Sergei Zubov finally put some pressure on Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Stars nine shots in the period came in the
60-second span that group was on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The crease, which seats four comfortably, had six players along
with Roy crammed in the little blue space by the time the referee
blew the whistle with 54 seconds remaining in the period.
</P>
<P>
   They created the momentum. Modano capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   He drew a tripping penalty on Colorado defenseman Adam Foote
with 43 seconds remaining in the period. He scored the power-play
goal 13 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brett Hull took a shot from the point that
ricocheted to Modano in the circle, who unleashed a wrist shot.
Roy, in the process of changing directions, watched the shot sail
high and in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad break on that goal,'' Roy said. ``It hit two
skates and bounced straight on Modano's stick.''
</P>
<P>
   The third period felt like it was an extension of last season's
Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The hitting was fierce. The saves were spectacular. The whistles
were put away. Overtime loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime wasn't any different and didn't decide anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows you when hockey is played tough at that level how
gripping it can be,'' Hitchcock said. ``It was at a whole other
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, February is over. The playoffs have begun.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-TEXMODAN     02-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
 MODANO PLAYING LIKE AN ALL-STAR (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By GIL LeBRETON c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He was an All-Star, and Mike Modano wondered why.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't playing well, he argued. He wasn't helping his team.
Life after drinking from the Stanley Cup, the star of the Stars
moaned, had turned into a long, lousy burp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an emotional guy,'' coach Ken Hitchcock mused last night,
after the Stars' hard-fought, 1-1 knot with the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's been playing great. He's been playing really tough,
very tenacious. I think Mo's got a grip on this team, and he's got
a bite on this season right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A bite? For the better part of 25 minutes last night at Reunion
Arena, the Stars seemed all gums. That unofficial Patrick Roy Force
Field was up, discouraging or deflecting the home team's every
advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche's current malaise _ they've won only twice in
their past 10 games _ has left them desperate and wondering. But as
Hitchcock said, ``They're hungry. Plus, starting tonight, they were
a healthy hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado failed, however, to extend its 1-0 advantage,
Modano was able to nullify the Avalanche's opening two periods of
dominance with one swift, game-tying shot.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been following the Modano saga, the guy who moaned the
woe-is-me's at midseason now has 24 points in his past 17 games. In
the Stars' last six games, he has five goals and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Stars have taken root at the top of the
NHL's Pacific Division. Tell me a better candidate for the league's
Player of the Month award for February.
</P>
<P>
   You can't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of worrying about who's playing beside him, over the
past month Modano seems to have gotten an infusion of energy from
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's enjoying playing hard right now,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   And for a while, Modano was making it seem like it was all too
hard.
</P>
<P>
   He had a note from the doctor, of course. Several notes. Two
games into the season, on a night when he had already scored two
goals, Anaheim's Ruslan Salei gave Modano an earnest goose toward
the end boards. While Reunion Arena gulped, Modano was immobilized
and carted off on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat miraculously, the final diagnosis was only a broken
nose, a mild concussion and a damaged ligament in his neck. But as
the team swooned and piled up injuries, Modano's zest for the
season began to droop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of chats,'' Hitchcock said. ``Mike got
caught in thinking that the inn at the end of the journey was too
far. He was trying to hope that one game would turn his season
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to go and enjoy the daily stuff. Stop looking too
far ahead. I told him to not try to hit the home run, but to
contribute to the team with hard play.''
</P>
<P>
   After champagne from the Cup, Modano suddenly began to enjoy the
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Stars are 27-6-3 when Modano registers at
least one point in a game. He has again become a leader, which has
been critical with Joe Nieuwendyk, Jere Lehtinen and, until
recently, Derian Hatcher in sick bay.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock thinks the Stars' nest of young players has helped as
well _ players such as Brenden Morrow and Kirk Muller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given him life,'' Hitchcock said. ``They've got a lot
of energy and grit. I think they've given Mo a lot of juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, it was Modano's goal in the dying seconds of the
second period that gave the Stars a psychological wake-up call that
launched a playoff-caliber third period. Then, in the overtime,
after Brett Hull's breakaway on Roy was spoiled at one end, it was
Modano who hustled back to disrupt Joe Sakic's potential
game-winner just enough at the other net.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, Hitchcock pronounced it a positive start to what
looms as a week of stern testing. A gantlet of playoff
thoroughbreds awaits the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good players were good players tonight,'' Hitchcock said,
sounding satisfied with the hard-earned tie.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Mike Modano was good again. The best player of the month,
in fact.
</P>
<P>
   And this time he's enjoying it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
