<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARKE STUNS WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
 MATCH PLAY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ It is a look that the golf world has come to
recognize, a stare that could melt ice more quickly than the desert
sun.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger Woods stare.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sunday it belonged to Darren Clarke. ``He looked Tiger
Woods right in the eye and said, `I'm gonna kick your butt.' And he
did, too,'' said Butch Harmon, the swing coach to both players who
was among those who could not quite believe what had just happened
at La Costa Resort and Spa in the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship final.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, previously regarded as a gentle sort who believed in
living well more than in his golfing skills, put a 4-and-3 drubbing
on Woods that earned him $1 million, though its true worth may be
priceless. ``If he can't believe he's a great player now . . .''
said Andrew Chandler, who has managed Clarke's career since the
native of Dungannon, Northern Ireland, turned pro in 1990, and who
has striven to convince the golfer ever since of his talents.
</P>
<P>
   That should change, said Chandler, because Clarke never blinked,
never wavered, never came close to even a scent of intimidation. He
conceded Woods's superiority off the tee, but saw it as a positive.
``I think Tiger's length was to my benefit,'' said Clarke, 31. ``It
gave me an opportunity to be hitting into the greens first, so as
soon as I got in there close, that resulted in pressure for
Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? Woods embraces it, so it was no surprise to see him
roar going out, making five birdies and turning in 33. Touche, said
Clarke, who also made five birdies, the second of which came at the
par-4 fourth after he stiffed his approach to 5 feet. Incredibly,
it wiped out the only lead Woods would enjoy in the 36-hole match.
The defeat was that convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, he flat outplayed me today,'' said
Woods, who matched Clarke nearly shot-for-shot on the back side
(birdies at the par-5 12th, eight pars) to keep the match all
square heading into the afternoon 18. While Woods rushed from the
18th green to a driving range that was quite a distance from the
first tee, Clarke decided otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' said the 260-pound Clarke, who joked
frequently about his weight, ``I didn't want to walk back down the
hill again and walk back up.'' So he lit up an ever-present cigar,
had lunch, and pondered a six-birdie effort, a round of 67, and a
week that already had gone beyond his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't set any goals at the start of the week,'' said
Clarke, the 19th seed. ``Probably get through two or three rounds
would have been pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good quickly turned to quite remarkable as Clarke
duplicated his morning assault on the outgoing nine. He birdied the
first hole to go 1 up, fell to all square when Woods birdied the
par-5 second, then assumed the lead for good with a conceded birdie
at the fourth after Woods could do no better than bogey. It started
a stretch of four birdies in five holes, which put him 4 up and had
Clarke thinking one thing: ``Birdie four of the next five.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, though Clarke, after losing a hole to Woods's birdie
at the par-5 ninth, continued to hit fairways and greens, his
blueprint for success all day.
</P>
<P>
   Even if his place in the fairway was 30 yards behind Woods, as
was the case at the 10th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, from about 180 yards, played his approach to the center
of the green, safe, but on the lower tier and nothing that would
shake Woods. ``He puts it 40 feet to the right,'' said Woods,
holding a 9-iron from 156 yards and envisioning a shot that would
set up a birdie and cut the deficit to two holes. ``I had the
perfect opening to knock it on the shelf in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Woods pushed his approach right, landing it even
farther from the hole than Clarke's. ``Not to be able to shape that
shot in there,'' said Woods, ``that's frustrating. I was just
trying to find my golf swing, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration carried over to his putting stroke: a birdie bid
that he rolled 5 feet strong, and a comebacker he missed. Three
putts. Four down. But Clarke refused to breathe easy. ``I was
expecting Tiger to do a couple of special things and have a go at
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Woods birdie at the par-3 11th could have signaled a charge,
but Woods's momentum defused quickly at the par-5 12th, where he
had performed his magic in Saturday's semifinal thrashing of Davis
Love, a 6-iron from 221 yards that bent around a tree and led to
eagle. This time, Woods's pushed approach into the right bunker led
to a rally-killing par.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough lie, said Woods, who had very little green to
work with and tried to fluff it perfectly. He left it in the sand,
blasted out close, and walked away with matching pars.
</P>
<P>
   At the 13th, Clarke made his 12th birdie of the day, matching
one by Woods, to remain 4 up, and when the next two holes were
halved with pars, the thumping that everyone had expected was
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except,'' said Harmon, ``Clarke did to Tiger what Tiger has
been doing to everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
