<P>
   (NYT27) SEATTLE -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- GORE-WASH -- Al Gore during
an appearance Sunday at Franklin High School in Seattle. Washington
state, which will account for only 2.2 percent of delegates at the
Democratic National Convention this year, has unexpectedly emerged
as a battleground for the two men seeking the party's presidential
nomination, and Gore spent much of the weekend here trying to make
sure that Bill Bradley would have nothing to show for his effort to
win the state's primary on Tuesday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- SUPERSTAR-RUSSIA
-- At 50, the Russian pop star Alla Pugacheva has been touring and
singing for 34 years. On Saturday, she entranced audiences in two
shows at a 6,000-seat hall at the Trump Taj Mahal in Atlantic City.
(Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- GRAMMY-GOSPEL-CHOIR -- The
270-voice Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir singing at Sunday services this
weekend for the first time since winning its third Grammy Award,
for best gospel choir album, for ``High and Lifted Up.'' The choir
has recorded 18 albums and performed around the world, including at
Carnegie Hall and Radio City Music Hall. (Chester Higgins Jr./The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- MAGAZINES-SEX-MEDIA -- For
newsstand covers of its March issue, Redbook changed ``intimate''
to ``sex'' and added a line promoting a sex column. Things have
changed for the 97-year-old Hearst magazine and the heretofore
sacrosanct sisterhood of women's magazines - now feeling the same
pressures that have prompted many American U.S. consumer magazines
to heat up frank sexual discussion to spur sales in the magazine
market. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- ECOM-COLUMN -- David
Williams of Kozmo, an urban delivery service, outside a Starbucks
in Manhattan. Kozmo customers will be able to return merchandise
like rental videos to boxes in Starbucks around the country. (Jack
Manning/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BALTIMORE -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- Y2K-LEAP-COMPUTERS -- Tzu
Ming Yang, who owns a Baltimore restaurant, has issued $82,000 in
credits because of Year 2000 problems. ``The easy part was stopping
the charges, once we found out on Jan. 13, but we still haven't
settled everything,'' he says. Through the end of January, just 21
companies had asked the IRS for permission to delay tax payments
without penalties because of Year 2000 problems, under a special
rule adopted late last year, said Daniel Boone, an IRS spokesman.
(Tim Shaffer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- HEALTHCARE-ONLINE --
Jeffrey Arnold of Healtheon/WebMD says the company will start its
online service for the health care industry by June. ``We now have
the assets in place to execute,'' says Arnold, the 30-year-old
Atlanta marketing entrepreneur who started WebMD in October 1998
and became chief executive of Healtheon/WebMD after the companies
agreed to merge the following May. ``We will put everything we've
got into making this work.'' (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING
-- Anne Bernays, writer and teacher of writing, tries and often
succeeds in taking students into a writer's mind. ``The first time
I taught a writing class I was scared stiff,'' she admits. (Ed
Quinn/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- MAUCERI-OPERA-PROFILE --
John Mauceri, a champion of Kurt Weill's ``Eternal Road,'' is
bringing it to Brooklyn. ``When I became music director of the
Scottish Opera in Glasgow about 15 years ago, I asked Kim Kowalke,
the president of the Weill Foundation, what work by Weill needed to
be done,'' says Mauceri, now principal conductor of the Hollywood
Bowl Orchestra and the new music director of the Pittsburgh Opera.
``And he said 'The Eternal Road.' `` (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Feb. 27, 2000 --
NY-PUERTO-RICANS-3 -- A Puerto Rican flag hangs in East Harlem on
116th Street, where Mexican restaurants and Dominican bodegas are
multiplying. Being Hispanic in New York City used to mean being
Puerto Rican. But over the last decade, the number of Puerto Rican
New Yorkers decreased for the first time since they began arriving
in the city in great numbers 60 years ago - down by nearly 100,000,
or 11 percent. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- NY-PUERTO-RICANS-2 --
``Puerto Ricans in the Bronx, they sometimes feel like quitting,
but they hold on,'' says Mercedes Gerena, a single mother and
restaurant worker, left. ``They should have stayed on 116th Street,
fixed up the apartments like whites are doing now and maintained
their political base in the United States,'' says Miguel Algarin, a
poet and English professor at Rutgers University, right. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Feb. 27, 2000 --
NY-PUERTO-RICANS-1 -- Hildamar Ortiz, a lawyer born in the Bronx,
now lives in Puerto Rico. ``You belong here,'' she says. ``You feel
it; nobody questions it.'' (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- STALLED-MEMORIAL-2 --
Despite the fact that a commemorative coin did not raise as much
money as expected for the black patriots memorial, the foundation's
board and its president, Wayne F. Smith, say they remain committed
to building the 90-foot-long curving bronze bas-relief that would
honor the blacks patriots, many of whom were slaves. ``I'm
absolutely convinced that this memorial will happen,'' Smith says.
``It's when, not if.'' (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- STALLED-MEMORIAL-1-B&AMP;W -- A
