<HEADLINE>
FASSERO TUNES UP MECHANICS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-FASSERO-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Jeff Fassero is the only pitcher in baseball
who can say he was chosen to be an Opening Day starter ahead of
both Pedro Martinez and Randy Johnson, who have four Cy Young
Awards between them.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero was the ace of a Montreal staff at a time when Martinez
was just coming into his own. And after Fassero was traded by the
Expos to the Mariners in a salary dump following the 1996 season,
Seattle manager Lou Piniella tabbed him ahead of the Big Unit, who
was coming back from back problems. Fassero was the Mariners'
Opening Day starter last season, too, after Johnson was traded to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   So Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, needing a veteran
starter to replace the surgically impaired Bret Saberhagen, scored
a major coup when he signed the lefthanded Fassero as a free agent
in the offseason, right?
</P>
<P>
   Come October, maybe everyone will be in agreement, especially if
Fassero helps pitch the Sox back into the playoffs for a third
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, with Fassero graying at 37, coming off the
worst season of his career, and just 16 months removed from elbow
surgery, there are legitimate concerns that he is closer to the
final curtain than another opening.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox clearly are betting otherwise. At the moment,
Fassero ranks as the team's No. 3 starter, behind the brothers
Martinez, and is the only lefthander in a rotation that didn't have
one last season until Kent Mercker was acquired in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to forget, but you can't,'' Fassero said of last
season, when he went 5-14 and had an earned run average of 7.20,
the highest ERA for a pitcher with at least 150 innings in 62
years. ``I'm not going to deny it was a terrible year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year like that eats away at your confidence. But I have a
mindset where I'm determined to go out and prove that last year was
not really me. It's no way to end a career.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero is hoping he can jump-start that career again by
reuniting with Joe Kerrigan, pitching M.D., his mentor for five
years in Montreal. Each morning, before the dew has even dried on
the freshly mown grass here, Fassero and Kerrigan have trudged to a
practice mound for a daily session of shadow pitching, in which
Fassero simulates his delivery without throwing a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mechanics were horrible last season,'' Fassero said. ``Joe
knew me for five years, which helps a lot. He looked at film of me
in Montreal and told me, `I know what you're doing wrong, I know
what we can do to correct you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Fassero won 13 games for the Mariners, the fourth
straight season in which he had won 13 or more games, and he also
threw 224 2/3 innings, the seventh-highest total in the league. But
his elbow had begun to bother him as early as March that year, and
in October, Fassero had surgery to remove bone chips and shave bone
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   He admits his fouled-up mechanics the following season may have
been due to the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good possibility I could have subconsciously been doing
things to protect my elbow,'' he said. ``Your mind and body want to
compensate for an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a situation I just couldn't get out of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, already reeling from the absence of Johnson, were
in full retreat when they finally sent Fassero to the bullpen in
mid-June. The Texas Rangers, looking for a lefthanded starter for
the stretch run, picked up Fassero in a late-August waiver deal and
he won all three of his starts, but they wound up putting him in
the bullpen, too, and made no effort to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, after flirting with the idea of signing lefthanded
Angels ace Chuck Finley before the asking price soared, signed
Fassero three days before Christmas. Sunday morning, Fassero faced
live hitters for the first time this spring, and he appeared
self-conscious as he attempted to implement the corrections
Kerrigan had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back leg has been collapsing, which makes my front shoulder
go up too high,'' said Fassero, who last season did not have his
usual command of his off-speed pitches, most notably his forkball.
``We're working on keeping my shoulder level. It feels pretty
comfortable, the way it needs to feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek was a young catcher in the Seattle system when
Fassero was at the top of his game. He recalls catching him only
once or twice, but he watched him plenty and, of course, has faced
him as an opposition batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Fassero can still be a dominating lefthanded
pitcher,'' Varitek said. ``His problems last year were just
mechanical. I think he's going to be a guy we're going to be able
to rely on. Joe (Kerrigan) will get him back to where he's pitching
naturally. I'm very confident that this is a guy who just had one
off year, really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
