<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0458 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-28 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ The good news is that Rudy Tomjanovich has a new
four-year contract to get him through days like this.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: That extended time will feel like 28 in dog years
if the Rockets continue to feed him such a steady diet of
Alpo-inspired efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Woof! Woof!
</P>
<P>
   The young nucleus of which the organization is so proud might as
well have been a litter of puppies chasing their tails for the
production they had Sunday against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   They rolled over. They played dead.
</P>
<P>
   They needed a flea dip.
</P>
<P>
   It is not losing 101-85 to one of the hottest teams in
basketball that is cause for concern, but more the way they did it.
Or rather, didn't.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tap, Kobe Bryant, Shaquille O'Neal and the
Lakers appeared bigger, stronger and quicker, while the Rockets
looked uncoordinated, out of control, even disinterested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like they were playing a different game than us,''
Tomjanovich said. ``This is the kind of thing I expected earlier in
the year. It's not pretty, not fun to sit there and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite some of the highlight-film images we have been
presented by rookie sensation Steve Francis and a few memorable
wins along the way _ i.e., over the Lakers on Jan. 30 _ what is
important to keep in mind is that the Rockets are a lot farther
away from returning to the level of playoff contenders than Houston
wants to let itself think.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a lack of patience or a low pain threshold, the
next couple of years might be a good time to find a hobby or start
watching PBS until Rudy T can slowly, steadily get this thing up on
two strong legs again. At this point, the Rockets can barely crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already beaten the Lakers twice this season and should
have beaten them a third time,'' Francis said. ``I think we were
all excited about coming out here on national TV and doing it to
them again. I guess we got a whole lot carried away.''
</P>
<P>
   We guess.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets last met and beat the Lakers, it was Super Bowl
Sunday, so long ago it was still football season. Now, as February
gives way to March, it is indisputably basketball season, and these
are clearly two teams headed in entirely different directions.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, after suffering through their own period of malaise,
are back rolling again, playing cohesively on offense and
aggressively on defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, after a brief fling with a six-game winning streak
in early January that gave them an inflated sense of themselves,
are now playing like a team without a sense of purpose or pride.
</P>
<P>
   What is alarming is that in their last seven games, the Rockets
have been blown out four times. Not just beaten, but thoroughly
whipped, beaten and destroyed. Too many times they have looked like
a team that is not ready to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my fault,'' said Francis, who is never shy to take the
burden. ``Rookie or not, it's my job to get us into the game and
playing with a rhythm. Today it was like I was out there with my
own drum.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he struggled again on offense, finishing with just six
points on 2-for-11 shooting and seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than Francis. It was all of them, shooting just
36 percent, getting hammered on the boards, falling behind 30-13
after the first quarter and 48-29 by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are physical problems to consider. Shaq and Kobe are
a bundle to handle, and the Rockets are playing without the injured
Kelvin Cato, and Hakeem Olajuwon had to leave after just 13 minutes
because of unexplained fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   But this has happened of late in Atlanta, in San Antonio, at
home against Denver. A lack of commitment, of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Before anybody starts planning parade routes for the next
championship, it would be wise to wait for the heart of this young
team to prove itself over the long haul rather than one hot week or
two.
</P>
<P>
   What we know about Cuttino Mobley is he'll create one-on-one
opportunities for himself to score. We know Kenny Thomas has a
spark. We know Francis is spectacular but can be spectacularly bad.
We know Bryce Drew is, well, still here.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know is how they'll grow or if they'll grow
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in a good team is that it won't always bring
its A-level game,'' said Matt Bullard. ``That's not possible. But
it always will bring the same kind of effort. It's getting your
mind ready. We're not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the good news is that we've got the Clippers next.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the Clippers are saying the same thing
about the young pups of the Rockets, who are still far more bark
than bite.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
