<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER SIGN OF RED SOX' REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Tommy Harper is back with the Red Sox, and
his presence in a Boston uniform says a lot about how far the ball
club has come in the area of race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years ago, Harper was Rosa Parks in Fenway's first base
coach's box. He was a black man brave enough to answer questions
truthfully about club policies that condoned racism at the club's
spring site in Winter Haven. The words cost him his job, which led
to a discrimination suit against the ball club. In 1986, when the
Red Sox played in the World Series, Harper was hanging out at an
auto body shop near Fenway Park. His suit eventually settled, he
spent two years out of baseball, then joined the Montreal
organization, where he worked until now.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed since Harper left. The Red Sox organization in
the early '80s was polluted by employees and attitudes held over
from the 1940s and '50s. An institutional racism colored hiring and
scouting, making Boston a tough place to work if you didn't look
like Dave Stapleton or Glenn Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   No more. The 2000 Red Sox clubhouse _ long a sanctuary for
average white guys _ is a study in racial and cultural diversity.
It's where Jin Ho Cho, Israel Alcantara, Rheal Cormier, and Pedro
Martinez dress alongside Michael Coleman, Tomokazu Ohka, and Derek
Lowe. The Sox don't have a single player named Whitey. They've
beefed up international scouting, set up a baseball academy in the
Dominican Republic, and reached out to Boston's inner-city
community with both arms. They've washed their hands of old sins,
and the hiring of Harper is both practical and symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like night and day,'' said the 59-year-old first base
coach. ``This is a different atmosphere altogether. It's
refreshing. It's not the same as it was. It's a lot better, and the
Red Sox as an organization have done it quietly. They don't go
around beating their chest and saying, `Look what we've done.'
They've just done it. Let people write or let people see what they
see. You don't have to say, `We have X amount of minorities.' We're
just an organization . . . taking people who can do the job. I
don't feel like there's a number, or that I'm a number.''
</P>
<P>
   He wears No. 35 and will work in the box vacated when Dave Jauss
took a position as minor league field coordinator. Harper still
holds the Sox record for steals (54) in a season, and he helped
Carlton Fisk steal 11 bases when he worked as a first base coach
for Don Zimmer and Ralph Houk. The Expos led the majors in steals
three times under Harper's tutelage.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure how much the Sox will run this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to know more about how Jimy (Williams) runs his
games,'' said Harper. ``Now all I can do is focus on the players
who have speed and work on fundamentals. The theory part as to when
to run always comes with the manager. I have to find out what Jimy
likes to do and when he likes to run and doesn't like to run. That
will come later. Now all I do is work with the runners and get
their techniques down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that the better the hitters are on your team, the
less you have to take a risk on the bases. But there are times when
base stealers feel it's not much of a risk. There are times when
the runners have to help the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, who lives year-round in Sharon, played for the Sox for
three seasons and worked in the organization for six more years
before he was banished by his own words.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't remember, this is why he left:
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox trained in Winter Haven for a quarter-century, and
before Harper spoke, the club allowed representatives of the local,
whites-only Elks Club to leave courtesy passes on the chairs of the
white players and coaches. As far as anyone knows, nobody ever used
the passes, but the Globe's Michael Madden discovered the practice
and asked Harper about it. Harper validated the story, and the
fallout was fierce and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that the story even had to come out,'' said Harper.
``I wish that it could have been taken care of internally, which I
tried to do. I went to the organization a year before Mike Madden
asked me the question. I had said that this thing could become an
embarrassment to the ball club at some point. It was agreed that
that was a fact, but a year later the same things occurred. I
thought they were going to take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was well known by a lot of people, but it just wasn't out
there. I didn't go to the writer, the writer came to me. Had I said
anything different, people would have known it was a lie because
people all knew. It was difficult at times. My main concern was
that I liked baseball and wanted to be a part of baseball. At the
time I didn't have a job, and it was very tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a little sticky for me. I never discussed it with
anybody because I wasn't angry. I never was. It was something that
happened, and I wish it didn't have to happen that way and
everything could have been taken care of and I never would have had
to leave in the first place. It was just an unfortunate thing. It
got the Red Sox a whole bunch of bad publicity and national
exposure for the wrong reasons, and people were angry with me
within the organization. The toughest thing for me was that people
that I thought were my friends were angry because I answered a
question. But that's the way I felt. I felt it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It was wrong and it was corrected. And the Red Sox seem to have
learned from past sins. All these years later, Harper is back on
the Boston baseline, where he belongs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
