<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS FOCUS ON RODMAN, NOT HIS ANTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ You have to go back to the 1980s, when Detroit
was Rock City and the world champion Pistons were the NBA's Bad
Boys, to recall the Dennis Rodman of yore, the one Tony Battie
fondly remembered Sunday as being ``a levelheaded guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup, you read that right.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman . . . levelheaded guy.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the villainous acts Rodman has perpetrated in his NBA
career _ don't even get Karl Malone started _ being ``levelheaded''
is one thing he's never been accused of before. NBA scofflaw? Yes.
But levelheaded? NBA commissioner David Stern would probably
convulse in laughter to hear that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of things in common with him kind of right now,
because we both went to the same high school (South Oak Cliff) and
we both grew up in Dallas,'' Battie said after practice Sunday in
preparation for Monday's 7 p.m. visit from Rodman and the Mavericks
at the FleetCenter. ``We're not looking to turn it into a circus
event or anything like that. We just want to go out and help the
Celtics win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Battie knows their Texas ties are where all similarities
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is one of the best _ if not the best _ rebounders in
the game,'' Battie said. ``So we have to take this game serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the day when he was considered a bit actor in Detroit's
championship cast of Isiah Thomas, Bill Laimbeer, John Salley, Joe
Dumars, and Vinny (The Microwave) Johnson, Rodman was just your
average, run-of-the-mill rebounding fool.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has embraced a bohemian lifestyle, discovered
sparkle lip gloss, wed and then divorced Carmen Electra after an
all-nighter in Las Vegas, done time recently in a Miami jail with
said ball-and-chain (oops, that's Mrs. ex-ball-and-chain),
co-starred with Jean-Claude Van Damme in an entirely forgettable
action flick, and written in his outrageous tome about his desire
to play his last NBA game in the nude, he is fancied a fool who can
really rebound.
</P>
<P>
   A recalcitrant rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Malone will tell you, Rodman has a tendency to cause a
stir on the court. What exactly does he do to cause such a
distraction?
</P>
<P>
   ``He outhustles you. He taunts you. He gets away with a lot of
stuff,'' said Danny Fortson. ``But he's won seven NBA rebounding
championships and a couple of world championships, so I guess he's
able to do stuff like that. That's what frustrates a lot of young
players who go up against him, because he gets away with a lot, but
you just have to keep your cool and keep going hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six games he's played since signing with the Mavericks
Feb. 3, Rodman has been hit with five technicals, ejected from two
games, fined $10,000 and suspended for one game, and slapped with
another $3,500 fine for failing to leave the court in a timely
manner following an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, they should have suspended me,'' Rodman told the Dallas
Morning News after Saturday night's 98-96 victory over the visiting
Denver Nuggets, a game in which Rodman picked up yet another
technical for arguing about a foul. ``I'm surprised they didn't,
because it seems like they're trying to prove some kind of point.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Rodman proves to be a distraction on the court is
not Rick Pitino's concern. ``The only thing I'm concerned about is
rebounding,'' said the Celtics coach. ``The other stuff I'm not
concerned about, because he's a ferocious rebounder. They won seven
out of eight prior to Rodman's arrival, so they have excellent
talent. But Rodman just gives them one of the premier rebounders
and defenders in the game. Each game that goes by, he just gets
himself into better and better shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Through six games, Rodman is averaging 14.8 rebounds, having
collected 89 total (including 65 on the defensive boards). His
offense (2.7 ppg), meanwhile, has left much to be desired. ``Ahh,
that's because he's got no offense,'' Fortson added with a laugh.
``Simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pitino, ``We've got to rebound with two people, because one
is not enough against Rodman. What happens a lot is that you feel
he's not an offensive factor on the perimeter, so you go to help
out, and he pushes you from the baseline and grabs the offensive
rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   With scorers such as Michael Finley (22.3 ppg), Cedric Ceballos
(18.5), and Dirk Nowitzki (17.3), who needs offense from Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got confidence in scorers like that and then
you've got some security down there with a guy who's going to bust
his butt to get the rebound,'' Battie said, ``it takes a little bit
more pressure off those guys shooting it, knowing that Dennis is
going to grab the board and get it back to them.''
</P>
<P>
   By any means necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
