</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- MAUCERI-OPERA-PROFILE --
John Mauceri, a champion of Kurt Weill's ``Eternal Road,'' is
bringing it to Brooklyn. ``When I became music director of the
Scottish Opera in Glasgow about 15 years ago, I asked Kim Kowalke,
the president of the Weill Foundation, what work by Weill needed to
be done,'' says Mauceri, now principal conductor of the Hollywood
Bowl Orchestra and the new music director of the Pittsburgh Opera.
``And he said 'The Eternal Road.' `` (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Feb. 27, 2000 --
NY-PUERTO-RICANS-3 -- A Puerto Rican flag hangs in East Harlem on
116th Street, where Mexican restaurants and Dominican bodegas are
multiplying. Being Hispanic in New York City used to mean being
Puerto Rican. But over the last decade, the number of Puerto Rican
New Yorkers decreased for the first time since they began arriving
in the city in great numbers 60 years ago - down by nearly 100,000,
or 11 percent. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- NY-PUERTO-RICANS-2 --
``Puerto Ricans in the Bronx, they sometimes feel like quitting,
but they hold on,'' says Mercedes Gerena, a single mother and
restaurant worker, left. ``They should have stayed on 116th Street,
fixed up the apartments like whites are doing now and maintained
their political base in the United States,'' says Miguel Algarin, a
poet and English professor at Rutgers University, right. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Feb. 27, 2000 --
NY-PUERTO-RICANS-1 -- Hildamar Ortiz, a lawyer born in the Bronx,
now lives in Puerto Rico. ``You belong here,'' she says. ``You feel
it; nobody questions it.'' (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- STALLED-MEMORIAL-2 --
Despite the fact that a commemorative coin did not raise as much
money as expected for the black patriots memorial, the foundation's
board and its president, Wayne F. Smith, say they remain committed
to building the 90-foot-long curving bronze bas-relief that would
honor the blacks patriots, many of whom were slaves. ``I'm
absolutely convinced that this memorial will happen,'' Smith says.
``It's when, not if.'' (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- STALLED-MEMORIAL-1-B&AMP;W -- A
commemorative coin featuring Crispus Attucks, an escaped slave who
was the first patriot to die in the Boston Massacre, did not raise
as much money as expected for the black patriots memorial. Despite
the early backing of General Motors, which remains a supporter, the
foundation seems to have lost the interest of other major
supporters like Philip Morris. (United States Mint/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- MINT-DIRECTOR-PROFILE --
Philip N. Diehl is the director, but the new star at the Mint is
Sacagawea - the Shoshone woman who courageously guided Lewis and
Clark in the 19th-century expedition that redefined America, and
whose handsome image adorns the distinctive new, gold-colored
dollar coin that Diehl cleverly marketed. The demand for the coin
is so great that production has already been doubled to 200 million
coins in this first month. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PASADENA, Calif. -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- CALIF-REPUBS-2 --
Dorie Hilton, a lifelong Republican living in Pasadena, says she
supports Sen. John McCain. ``I was very much for George Bush, but I
think he's just waffled,'' she says. Hilton is precisely the kind
of voter McCain must target to win a state where only Republican
votes will count in choosing delegates March 7. (Monica Almeida/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SAN DIEGO -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- CALIF-REPUBS-1 -- Sen.
John McCain, campaigning in San Diego on Friday in advance of
California's March 7 primary. As the presidential campaign moves to
the biggest states, McCain and George W. Bush are battling squarely
for the biggest prize of all: California. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NABI CHIT, Lebanon -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- HEZBOLLAH-FUTURE
-- Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, flanked by guards, speaking at Nabi Chit
on the anniversary of Israel's killing of his two predecessors as
Hezbollah leader. Abbas Moussawi, pictured in the large mural at
right and in front of lectern, was killed in 1992, and Ragheb Harb,
at left in the picture, was killed in 1984. (Courtney Kealy/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-6 -- Former
Mayor David N. Dinkins, speaking at First Sharon Baptist Church in
Harlem on Sunday, called on the parishioners to make widely known
their opposition to the verdict acquitting four police officers in
the shooting death of Amadou Diallo. Words of anger, frustration
and concern Sunday rose from pulpits across the city, and more than
1,000 demonstrators took to the streets for a third day of prayer
and protest. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-5 --
Demonstrators marching Sunday from the United Nations to City Hall
as part of a third straight day of protests against the acquittal
of four police officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.
Despite sometimes volatile language, the day passed without
violence. But there were tense moments when the crowd at the U.N.
began to head down Second Avenue, disrupting traffic until police
officials appealed to protest organizers to contain the march.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-4 -- Chanting,
``Police tactics 101, it's a wallet, not a gun,'' protesters wave
wallets in the faces of police officers near the United Nations on
Sunday. Politicians joined thousands of demonstrators in the shadow
of the U.N. as part of a third straight day of protests against the
acquittal of four police officers in the shooting death of Amadou
Diallo. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-3 -- Norman
Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil Liberties
Union, helping to disperse a crowd blocking Second Avenue near the
United Nations on Sunday. Politicians joined thousands of
demonstrators in the shadow of the U.N. as part of a third straight
day of protests against the acquittal of four police officers in
the shooting death of Amadou Diallo. (Michelle V. Agins/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-2 --
Politicians joined thousands of demonstrators Sunday in the shadow
of the United Nations as part of a third straight day of protests
against the acquittal of four police officers in the shooting death
of Amadou Diallo. A group called ``Mothers in Mourning'' wore black
veils and held Diallo's photo in a symbolic gesture at the peaceful
rally, which was followed by tense moments as angry departing
protesters led a spontaneous march through midtown Manhattan.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS -- The
76ers' Eric Snow had a chance to win the game Sunday in Madison
Square Garden, but ran into Chris Childs, left, Allan Houston and
Patrick Ewing in the final seconds, and the Knicks escaped with an
89-88 victory. The Knicks fell behind by as many as 12 points but
never lost sight of the Sixers, despite 26 points by Allen Iverson
and 19 points and 20 rebounds by Tyrone Hill. No. 33 led the home
team with 18 points and 10 rebounds. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- KOSOVO-NATO --
Smoke still rises Sunday from a sports and shopping complex in
Pristina after a fire that started in the basement Friday. Because
of the risk to the soldiers, the Pentagon has refused to allow
American troops to return to northern Mitrovica, senior United
Nations and Western officials said. Gen. Klaus Reinhardt of
Germany, the commander of the NATO-led peacekeeping forces in
Kosovo, said in Pristina on Sunday that negotiations are
continuing. (Steven Erlanger/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- DIALLO-REACT-1 --
Politicians joined thousands of demonstrators Sunday in the shadow
of the United Nations as part of a third straight day of protests
against the acquittal of four police officers in the shooting death
of Amadou Diallo. A group called ``Mothers in Mourning'' wore black
veils and held Diallo's photo in a symbolic gesture at the peaceful
rally, which was followed by tense moments as angry departing
protesters led a spontaneous march through midtown Manhattan.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 2000 -- NYPD-DIALLO-6 -- An
estimated 2,500 demonstrators marched down Fifth Avenue Saturday to
protest the acquittal of four police officers in the shooting death
of Amadou Diallo. The procession prompted the police to shut down
traffic. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
