<HEADER>
A0467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      02-28 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DEALING WITH DEFICIENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The struggle continues, and so does the search. With
the NHL trade deadline only two weeks away, the Bruins need more
than John Grahame, a rabbit's foot, and a box of Lucky Charms if
they're going to keep alive their faint dream of playing beyond
April 9.
</P>
<P>
   They need bodies, specifically a capable scorer or two and a
presence back on the blue line. The two players they picked up
along the way _ winger Joe Murphy and defenseman Marty McSorley _
both are now, shall we say, otherwise engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was a hothead who got himself fired. McSorley went
swinging for the fence and got himself knocked right out of the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   For a roster already depleted by injuries and the ever-present
budget concerns, the Murphy-McSorley losses were two more crushing
blows. They also should have been a call to action for the front
office.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell, who was with the club
over the weekend for the win in Washington (3-0) and the tie in
Pittsburgh (2-2), said trade talks have been ongoing but, to date,
unpromising. ``Yeah, we've been making calls, and other clubs have
been calling us,'' said O'Connell. ``We'll keep looking, but right
now, there's no one being offered who interests us.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, don't count on the cast of characters changing much,
even with lingering injuries to Byron Dafoe (knee), Anson Carter
(shoulder), and Rob DiMaio (torn hand ligament), and the loss of
No. 1 pivot Jason Allison (wrist surgeries) for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the club's most tradeable commodity, Sergei Samsonov
struck for goals in Washington and Pittsburgh, only the second time
he has scored in back-to-back games all season. If the little left
winger could start mirroring the promise he showed in his freshman
and sophomore seasons, that would be a major boost to what has been
a moribund offense.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of badly needed personnel aside, a couple of very
encouraging signs emerged last week. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   --The Bruins finally began to skate. Head coach Pat Burns
finally implemented a more aggressive forechecking scheme 3-4 weeks
ago that has brought a number of positive results. Not only is the
opposition held at bay a little more, relieving pressure on the
defense, but it also has the entire five-man unit more routinely
skating forward rather than standing still in the neutral zone or
lost in retreat. For one period in Edmonton, and for all three
periods in Washington, it looked like a club with a replaced clutch
and a new transmission. Given the Bruins' talent level, no one can
expect an Indy race here, but at least they appear to have stopped
playing Demolition Derby.
</P>
<P>
   --The play of Grahame in net brought an obvious and badly needed
spark. In fact, the boost he provided was as obvious as the club's
improved skating. The Bruins broke to the lead in Washington and
Pittsburgh. Grahame, hot here before being demoted after Dafoe
ended his monthlong holdout, did not allow one bad goal in two
nights and both times was awarded the No. 1 star. Count on Burns
rolling him out again Tuesday night when the Senators come to town.
If he stays sharp, he'll remain the No. 1 goalie for the full final
quarter of the regular season. Simply put, Grahame is the single
best thing the club has going for it right now.
</P>
<P>
   The microcosm of the Washington-Pittsburgh swing provides some
important math. The Bruins collected three of four points, .750
efficiency, in the two stops. Keep that number in mind. With 20
games to go, and considerable ground to make up in hopes of landing
the No. 8 playoff berth, the Bruins essentially have to hit three
for four the rest of the way. Based on how they've played for the
majority of the season, that doesn't seem realistic, but a hot
goalie and a slightly uptempo skating game make it far more a
possibility than it was a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, though atypical of a classic turning point, last Monday
night, when McSorley bashed Vancouver's Donald Brashear, will be
remembered as the time the season bottomed out. When everyone
around the club was wondering if things could get worse, suddenly
things got better. At least for two games. The skating fell off
some Saturday night, but that could be expected after the effort in
Washington and the fact that it was the fifth game of a five-game
sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, Paul Holmgren and ex-goalie Ron Hextall,
respectively assistant general manager and scout for the Flyers,
were seen in the press box. Rumors have circulated for two seasons
that Philly will make a deal for a No. 1 goalie. Perhaps Holmgren
and Hextall were there in hopes of rating Dafoe, who was back in
Boston having his knee examined.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins are convinced that Grahame is their guy in net for
the rest of the season, and if they are equally convinced he is
their guy for the future, then that could convince them the time
could be right to deal Dafoe. In return, they would have to ask for
a legitimate goal-scoring winger. A goal-scoring center would be
fine, too, especially now, but that role should be filled
adequately by Allison and Joe Thornton for many years. The two top
names to fit the description in Philly are, of course, Mark Recchi
and John LeClair, neither of whom would be available. After them,
it's a considerable drop to Daymond Langkow, who in the '95 draft
was the No. 5 pick overall by Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, of course, is purely speculation. Chances are, the
Bruins won't do a thing to change personnel between now and March
14. The past two years, they've let the trade deadline come and go
like any other, which, come to think of it, might be why they woke
up Sunday in 12th place in the Eastern Conference, looking at the
prospect of not reaching the playoffs for the second time in four
seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
