<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA VOWS TO SHOW JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
 LA HOYA-COLEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kevin Kelley was watching at ringside. The former
featherweight champion knew exactly what Oscar De La Hoya was doing
Saturday night as he steadfastly pursued Derrell Coley until he had
knocked him to his knee for a 10-count at the end of the seventh
round at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sending a message to (Felix) Trinidad and (Shane)
Mosley and the rest of the guys who want to fight him,'' Kelley
said. ``He's coming to hurt people now.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya had promised such a thing in the weeks following his
controversial loss to Trinidad last September, a fight in which he
blew a comfortable lead by running for the last three rounds
instead of fighting, thereby losing a split decision and the right
to complain about it.
</P>
<P>
   Now De La Hoya is on the verge of either a rematch with Trinidad
June 10 at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas or a fight against Mosley,
the undefeated former lightweight champion now campaigning as a
welterweight, June 17 at the Staples Center in Los Angeles. Either
way, De La Hoya promised Saturday he will use the same stalking
style he employed against Coley, whose steps he dogged from the
opening bell to the final crushing shot to the liver that destroyed
his opponent's will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighter you saw is the fighter I am,'' De La Hoya said.
``I'm not going to box anybody (anymore). No more Mr. Nice Guy. Let
them adjust to my style instead of me adjusting to theirs. Whoever
it is, I'll be ready. I'll be strong. My goal for 2000 is four
fights, four knockouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping Coley is one thing, however. Stopping the quick-moving
Mosley or the power-punching Trinidad will be quite another.
</P>
<P>
   As De La Hoya made these boasts from a makeshift dais in the
Garden rotunda, Mosley stood in the back watching, wearing an
impeccable suit and a wide smile. He had come to see the ``new''
Oscar De La Hoya unveiled, the one who promised mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw, though, was not what De La Hoya promised. At least
not to Mosley's trained eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Coley didn't come to fight,'' Mosley said. ``He was
in to survive. I think I can trade with anybody. I want the fight
because it's a good fight for the fans all over the world and an
opportunity for me to make my reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not sure it can be made now. It will depend on what
happens with Trinidad and David Reid.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two fight next weekend, and if Trinidad wins the 154-pound
title, he is likely to relinquish the welterweight belts he now
holds, one of which will be assumed by De La Hoya. Then they'll
have to agree on a catch weight between 147 and 154 pounds, and the
rematch will be on. But following his victory Saturday night, De La
Hoya said he did not want to go up more than 2 pounds to meet
Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, everything is all but set, but some things could change
if Trinidad loses. Then it would be on to Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I boxed (Trinadad) for 12 rounds,'' De La Hoya said.
``Obviously that didn't work. Thank you, Trinidad. That loss will
bring out the best in me. That loss is the best thing that ever
happened to me. It was unfair, but it got me back to being who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya believes he is a stone killer again, as he was at
130-140 pounds. He believes he can fight with cold eyes at 147 and
win, and that is how he says he will fight Trinidad or Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   But you will not see Oscar De La Hoya challenging bigger men any
time soon. Not a 154-pound Trinidad, not Reid, and not IBF champion
Fernando Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, 147 pounds is my weight,'' De La Hoya said. ``I've moved
up four weight classes already. I'm not going to go up more just
because I have to fight a guy. This is my weight, and I'll stay
here for 1 1/2 to 2 years. Then I can move up to junior
middleweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime, I'm staying at 147.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying a welterweight stalker looking for one thing: three more
guys to knock out this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
