<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIANS SEEK SPIRIT OF '76 
</HEADLINE>
 BOXOFF-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ The US Olympic boxing team at Sydney could
be the nation's best ever. Even better than the 1976 team, which
produced five gold medalists and future professional champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than six of these guys could be world champions, from 106
(pounds) up,'' coach Tom Mustin said after the Olympic box-off
trials ended Saturday. ``Nobody sticks out like a Ray Leonard. It's
more a blue-collar team of hard workers. They will sneak up and
win, like they did at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making any predictions on how many medals they will
win. But last year was the first time we ever won four at the World
Championships, and some of the guys I predicted would win there
didn't. It was the guys who worked the hardest who won.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1976 US fighters, who included Howard Davis, Leon and
Michael Spinks, Leonard, and Leo Randolph, combined the traits of
amateur eclecticism and professional brutality, bringing a high
national profile to Olympic boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati lightweight Ricardo Williams's style recalls that of
the '76 group. But Mustin warns success depends on the basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams is the most talented guy we have,'' Mustin said.
``But unless he does the work he needs to do, some strong guy will
knock him off, like in the World Championships. A lot of times it's
not the best boxer, but the guy who is the strongest, who has the
most stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step is the Americas qualifying round, scheduled for
March 27-April 1 in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   The US team received a seal of approval from 1996 Olympic coach
Al Mitchell, who works at the US Olympic Education Center in
Marquette, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be a good team because they are good kids and they
have good training, good coaching,'' Mitchell said. ``They are more
blessed than in '96, not with skills, but because everyone has gone
pro. In '92, it was only the Russians who had come out, but now you
have Russians, Germans, Hungarians, Poles in the pros. The only
team that doesn't have to start new is the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I worry about is the back-to-back fights. They
have to qualify, then qualify again. They are going to have to
watch that they don't overwork them, give them rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The US team won eight medals, including one gold, at the Atlanta
'96 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the World Championships, I predicted four gold medals
in the Olympics,'' said Gary Toney, president of USA Boxing. ``When
people look back, I believe this team will be compared to the 1976
team. I don't think that puts any pressure on them at all. They
will definitely match the eight medals and win more than one gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1997 World Championships, we only won one bout. In
1999, we won four golds and the team title. We went from the bottom
to the top. Our philosophy has changed. We are competing in more
international tournaments, and our coaches are gaining experience
and seeing different styles. It has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   US training methods have become more sophisticated,
acknowledging the influence of computer-based scoring methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the fighters we are not trying to change their style,
but enhance their style,'' Mustin said. ``They are fighting against
the computer, and there are some things they need to do to compete
in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to step and run more. They need to make sure the
judges see that their punches are connecting, so that means less
flash. Before, we weren't studying how to score against the
computer. Other countries did. We didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial elements of the trials surround the
granting of an Australian visa to heavyweight Michael Bennett, a
convicted felon, and a charge of racism by coach Ted Palac, whose
son, Arthur, was defeated, 10-9, by Jeff Lacy at 165 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 28, served seven years in prison for armed robbery.
Australia does not grant visas to felons, except in special cases.
USA Boxing executive director Paul Montville said the Illinois
Parole Board has approved Bennett's travel plans, and a verdict
from Australia is due in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bennett) has paid the price and tried to turn his life
around,'' Toney said. ``He is a fine individual, a fine person. I
can't imagine they won't let him in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Toney said Palac has not made an official protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that one of our coaches would make such a
comment, and it is absolutely untrue,'' Toney said of the racism
charge. ``We want the very best boxers to advance to Sydney, and
that has nothing to do with race or ethnic background.''
</P>
<P>
   Palac said no white boxer has made the Olympic team since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at that as evidence,'' Toney said. ``The best
boxers won. Arthur Palac is a good boxer, but the judges felt he
did not win the fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
