u s BC-SAIL-AMERICA'SCUP-BOS     02-28 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIWIS CAN WAIT TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ If you discount a few hundred
journalists rechecking their plane reservations, the only agony of
Sunday's nonrace day belonged to Italy's Prada.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the merchants, restaurateurs, and barkeeps around
this city could not be happier about more race cancellations.
Spread this thing out until June, for all they care. Saturday's
scheduled race was postponed because of light air. It was the third
such postponement of this America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Every day and night, the America's Cup Village is packed with a
growing crowd of Kiwis awaiting the coronation of their repeat
heavyweight champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiwi sailors are loving this. They find it increasingly
difficult to hide their cat-with-the-canary grins. Russell Coutts
was even seen smiling on the last leg of Race 3 Friday, something
out of character for the superfocused Kiwi skipper.
</P>
<P>
   The longer this Cup finale hangs on, the longer Team New Zealand
has to relish its moment in the sun. That moment could end this
week in an explosive celebration when the boats go out to race
Monday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Team New Zealand has a 3-0 lead over Prada in the best-of-nine
series.
</P>
<P>
   So only the Prada team is not enjoying this suspended lull of
windless high summer across New Zealand. More such weather is in
the forecast. How long, they wonder, must it take us to lose this
thing? ``Pradamania,'' which gripped Italy as nothing else has
since the country's World Cup-winning soccer team in the '80s, is
now a balloon without much air.
</P>
<P>
   But the Prada sailors are still talking bravely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can just win a start,'' said tactician Torben Grael.
``If we can win the start and get in the controlling position,
maybe we will be the boat with no passing lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, maybe. And maybe if the Patriots learn to block, protect
the quarterback, develop a running game, and get receivers open,
they won't be the playthings of the NFL next season.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, controlling the opposition is not something you
hope and pray for in a match race. It's something you earn.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Kiwis have been dominant in every phase of sailboat
match racing. Their boat, NZ60, is faster over a range from 5 to 35
knots. There is no magic going on here, just a package that has
been optimized in every department.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years of development, said Tom Schnackenberg,
New Zealand's design coordinator and on-water navigator, ``we
worked out a relationship between the sailors and designers that
let us push every idea to the testing stage. If a sailor had an
idea, we'd try it and see if it worked. That's the relationship
that sailors and designers should have.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of such development has been telling. There has been
no one big breakthrough, like the famed revolutionary ``winged
keel'' of Australia II in 1983, but rather a long list of minute
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schnackenberg, when the Kiwis brought the Cup home
after their 5-0 thumping of Dennis Conner's team in 1995, they
decided to review every system and see how they could improve them.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the longer waterline achieved by the spoon bow, or
``knuckle,'' just below the foredeck, these advances range from
their ``millennium'' rig to their gybing technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these little bits of things _ no one is that important,
but all together they make the boat that much faster,'' said Nippon
skipper Peter Gilmour.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the crew. Former Cup tactician and now TV sailing
analyst Gary Jobson put it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at all 16 sailors on TNZ, and then took an
all-star team of the top 16 sailors from all the challengers, I
can't think of one Kiwi sailor I'd replace with one challenger team
member.''
</P>
<P>
   Prada's development was different. With superiority over most of
the challengers, Grael and skipper Francesco de Angelis learned to
win from a front-running position. Rarely did they fight from
behind until late in the challenger trials, when Paul Cayard's
AmericaOne forced Prada into its first hard-fought series of races.
</P>
<P>
   So facing this overwhelming mismatch against the Kiwis _ who are
now 8-0 in the America's Cup match races they have sailed since
1995 _ Prada's remaining hope is that it will be over soon.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Grael, they do have a strategy. Prada plans to sail a
superaggressive start and fight for the right, where, in steady
breezes, the control of the race is found.
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis and Grael have a slim chance of succeeding, even for
one race. But at least the next five minutes in this America's Cup
finale should be more interesting than the last six hours have
been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
