<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     02-28 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DEFEAT OILERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Craig Hartsburg admitted it wasn't perfect, Teemu
Selanne said the performance wasn't pretty, but the Mighty Ducks
know they can't afford to be picky these days.
</P>
<P>
   And when compared to the recent crash-and-burns that Anaheim has
suffered through in recent weeks, Sunday's 3-2 over the Edmonton
Oilers before a sellout of 17,174 at The Pond ``was pretty sweet,''
according to Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Ducks pick up two desperately needed points,
they managed to hold a third-period lead and Guy Hebert made a
successful return to the nets after a nine-day boot camp of sorts
with goalie consultant Francois Allaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll only play if I'm playing well,'' said Hebert after the
Ducks held a team to less than three goals for the first time since
Feb. 1 (a span of nine games). ``We need somebody to drive the
car.'' After a series of sub-par performances, Hebert admitted he
was ``heavily motivated and excited to play'' and said he thought
about the game all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things didn't weren't going to work out the way I wanted
them to, it wasn't going to be because of a lack of preperation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks as whole certainly came out motivated. They scored on
their second shot of the game -- Marty McInnis banging home a
rebound of a shot by Oleg Tverdovsky at 1:06. Anaheim made it 2-0
on its fourth shot, a nice three-way passing play that Fredrik
Olausson finished off at 2:32 by faking Edmonton goalie Tommy Salo
to the ice. Kevin Haller gave the Ducks a 3-0 lead at 19:07 when he
took Mike Leclerc's pass and beat Salo on the short side from 40
feet.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been well documented, the Ducks hadn't dealt with
success well in the six previous games -- blowing two-goal leads in
five of them and settling for a 2-2-2 record in that stretch. And
history looked as if it was going to repeat itself on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton cut Anaheim's lead to two just 8.4 seconds after
Haller's goal when Ethan Moreau scored. The Oilers pulled within
3-2 at 10:35 of the second period when Leclerc lost track of Jim
Dowd in the slot and the winger beat Hebert easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we got scared or what because the second
period was awful,'' said Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't look particular good for the Ducks -- considering
that Edmonton has outscored its opponents 60-44 in the third
period, while the Ducks have been blitzed 67-49 in the final
period.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first weeks Anaheim appeared confident in the last
20 minutes and as result the Ducks (26-27-10-1) pulled within four
points of San Jose and Colorado in the battle for the final playoff
spot in the Western Conference. Tuesday they will have a chance to
draw within two of the Sharks when they play in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally showed some good poise and character,'' said
Hebert. ``I felt everyone had learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between periods I was thinking there's no way I'm giving up a
goal and think everybody else felt the same way. As the period went
on we played with more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence was something Hebert has been searching for, and he
picked up a great deal of it when he slid across the crease to stop
Todd Marchant on a two-on-one shorthanded break early in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the pass and got over there,'' he said. ``That's a save
I haven't been able to make lately, so it felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert also stopped the speedy Marchant on a breakaway with a
minute left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the biggest save of the game,'' said
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who stopped 25 of 27 shots, certainly was spectacular,
but the Anaheim coach said ``Guy doesn't have to be spectacular, he
has to be solid.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hebert was just that, much to the delight of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our guy, if we want to go any further we need him,'' said
Tverdovsky. ``We need him, he's a huge part of our team. He was
great tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For any team goaltending is huge,'' said Selanne. ``He's
hungry and he's back. It's great to see him with his confidence
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
