<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS ADD BJORNSON TO BACKUP FILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots' search for second-tier players
led them to tight end Eric Bjornson over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cowboy, 28, was a backup for David LaFleur the past
two seasons. Bjornson has been plagued by injuries, starting only
nine games the last two years after starting 24 in 1996 and 1997.
He caught only 10 passes last season for 131 yards and no
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   No contract details were available on Bjornson.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in this free agent period, the Patriots signed running
back Raymont Harris, who missed the entire 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Bjornson is represented by agent Leigh Steinberg, which could
mean the Patriots and Steinberg are discussing a new deal for
quarterback Drew Bledsoe as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots released five-time All-Pro tight end Ben Coates
earlier this offseason and will throw Bjornson in with Rod Rutledge
to compete for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots signed wide receiver Troy Brown to a five-year, $13
million deal Saturday. They have now signed two of their own free
agents _ the other is strong safety Lawyer Milloy _ and have let
guard Heath Irwin (Miami), cornerback Steve Israel, wide receiver
Shawn Jefferson (Atlanta), and defensive end Chris Sullivan
(Pittsburgh) seek other deals. The Patriots may still sign
linebacker Tedy Bruschi.
</P>
</TEXT>
