<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST STRAW, AT LAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe today, we'll find out if Darryl Strawberry
has any lifelines left in his version of ``Who Wants to be a
Million-Airhead?''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Boy Selig's final answer shouldn't have anything to do
with the precedent set by those before him who perpetuated Steve
``Snow Day'' Howe's situation until it reached ridiculous
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a lifetime ban, not just a one-season ban, is the
statement that needs to be made for baseball's version of Ike
Turner. The other three major pro leagues wouldn't tolerate a third
drug-related lapse. Why does hardball have a soft core?
</P>
<P>
   Selig has used the ``integrity of the game'' stance to keep Pete
Rose's lifetime-ban appeal for gambling from even being considered
again. Straw's been gambling, too - with his life. He should be
held to the same standards and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Various employers (including the Dodgers) have done more than
required to assist this employee in getting treatment, but when he
plainly violates probation terms less than a year after we
applauded him for beating cancer, maybe it's a sign for him to try
another profession. One where $30 million (his lifetime earnings)
aren't so easily at his disposal, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   We feel for ya, Straw. We tried. Time to stop rolling the
dice....
</P>
<P>
   Just as stock in Strawberry crashes, the company known as
YankeeNets, which runs the New York Yankees and New Jersey Nets, is
selling $250 million in high-risk junk bonds to complete the
acquisition of the baseball team. The company, already $380 million
in debt, is also trying to buy the New Jersey Devils....
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is a shot in the dark, but putting a bow and arrow in
the hands of Justin Huish right now doesn't sound like such a smart
idea....
</P>
<P>
   New Blue Jays outfielder Raul Mondesi told the Toronto Globe and
Mail: ``Some people say there's too much pressure for the players
in L.A. People say a lot of things, you can't concentrate.... I was
in a slump for a couple of weeks (last year) and a lot of people
started to say something and talk a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what about the fact new teammate David Wells has complained
about the team getting Mondesi in exchange for Shawn Green? Mondesi
has justified that in his head by answering: ``Some people told me
he said some things. To me, that doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   What your teammates say doesn't matter, but what fans say
does?...
</P>
<P>
   After what happened at the Grammys, Rafael Santana should
consider a comeback....
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lavin has the rollover contract. His players just roll
over....
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Harrick, our IRS agent will see you now. And bring your
son....
</P>
<P>
   Stop releasing tapes of 911 calls to the public through the
media. It is one of the most invasive, unnecessary acts of non-news
judgment ever allowed.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the most hilarious clip in circulation is Tonya
Harding's boyfriend making his distress call after she allegedly
smacked him in the nose with a hubcap....
</P>
<P>
   As far as Kings fans are concerned, Marty McSorley need not
worry about being remembered as a stick-swinging maniac. He'll
always be a blade-bending meathead....
</P>
<P>
   Ray Romano just finished his round at Pebble Beach....
</P>
<P>
   Two events the Los Angeles Sports and Entertainment Commission
has targeted to get are the 2003 NBA All-Star Game and the 2006
U.S. Open golf tournament....
</P>
<P>
   So was that dress supposed to distract people from looking at
Jennifer Lopez's backside?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
