<HEADLINE>
GYORFFY SETS COLLEGIATE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Early Saturday afternoon, Harvard coach Frank
Haggerty said his prized high jumper was ``in a class by herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, Dora Gyorffy proved her coach right.
</P>
<P>
   Gyorffy, the Budapest native with an eye on the Olympics,
cleared the bar at an NCAA record-tying 6 feet 5 1/2 inches to
highlight the 53d Heptagonal Championships at Dartmouth's Leverone
Field House.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with the superb performance of Brenda Taylor, who
won the 55 high hurdles, 55 meters, and 200 meters, helped propel
Harvard (109 points) to its first Heptagonal title in a decade.
Brown (92 points) and Cornell (69) wrapped up the women's top
three. Princeton (121.33 points) won the men's championship for the
third straight time, ahead of Brown (90) and Navy (88).
</P>
<P>
   Gyorffy leaped her way to a share of the record set by Amy Acuff
of UCLA in the NCAA Championships in 1995 and equaled by Erin
Aldrich of Texas in the Canon Invitational in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gyorffy raised the bar to 6-6 3/4 in an attempt to set a new
record. She failed in two attempts and bypassed the third when the
side of her shoe tore away.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in as many years that Gyorffy has set the
Heptagonal record. As a freshman in 1998, she jumped 6-3 1/4 to
shatter the previous standard by 5 inches; last year, she added a
quarter-inch to that with a leap of 6-3 1/2. Sunday's jump beat her
career best of 6-4 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Gyorffy, who won Sunday when Princeton's Shawneequa Callier
failed in three attempts to clear 6- 1/4, wasted no time in inching
her way to the record-tying jump. On her first tries, she easily
hit 6-2, 6-3 1/4, and 6-4 1/4. She missed her first attempt at 6-5
1/2, but on her second, went over with room to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could have set (the record) if my shoe hadn't
split,'' said Gyorffy. ``It tore apart just when I planted and it
affected my plant. I'm so pleased, though, because it's the
second-best jump in the world this year. I still can't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The record-tying high jump was just the beginning for Gyorffy.
An hour later, she moved over to the triple jump pit and won with a
Harvard-record leap of 41-9 3/4, breaking by an inch her own mark.
</P>
<P>
   The record-tying and record-setting efforts earned Gyorffy her
third straight Heptagonal Outstanding Performer Award.
</P>
<P>
   As great as Gyorffy's performance was, one can't overlook the 30
points Taylor brought to the table. She edged her twin sister,
Lindsay, of Brown, in the hurdles and breezed in the 55 and 200
meters. When Taylor and teammate Marna Schutte finished 1-2 in the
200, the combined 18 points put them ahead of Brown _ and they
never looked back. Schutte also won the 400 and anchored Harvard's
winning 4 x 400 relay team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they're fabulous talents who don't know how to
lose,'' said Haggerty of Gyorffy and Taylor, who combined for 50 of
Harvard's 109 points. ``They gave us everything we expected of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth's men enjoyed a slight lead on Princeton before Scott
Denbo won the shot with a throw of 59-3 1/2 to put the Tigers in
front for good. When John Mack followed by winning the 400 meters,
and Ryan Smith, Chris McFadden, and Matthew Notary went 2-3-4 in
the 800, Princeton was home free . . . The Harvard men finished
last in the nine-team field with 19.33 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
