<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REID-TRINIDAD IS HUGE GAMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Rumors in the boxing world are that the Felix
Trinidad-David Reid fight on Friday in Las Vegas might not come
off.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it. The promotion has picked up too much momentum
to turn back now.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: At least a small part of promoter Don King
would love to scrap the fight at the last minute because he and
others - including Trinidad, his client - stand to lose a fortune
on two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that he'll need a pay-per-view audience of at
least 400,000 to break even when a more realistic number might be
closer to 100,000. At the same time, the live gate at Caesars
Palace isn't expected to be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Rival promoter Bob Arum said King could lose $5 million on the
fight and he might not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the proposed two-fight deal between Trinidad and De
La Hoya - who knocked out Derrell Coley here on Saturday - on June
10 and in September in which the fighters would share a monstrous
$80 million if they can reach terms.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is Friday's fight: If Trinidad loses - which many
experts believe is likely - the deal with De La Hoya is off.
</P>
<P>
   Forty million each ... down the drain ... just like that.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, who might never again command that kind of money, will
make a relatively paltry $4 million (to Reid's $3 million) for
Friday's fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the decision to fight Reid, made in good part because King
didn't want to be dictated to by Arum, is among the most stupid in
the history of boxing from a business perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take that kind of risk for $4 million instead of $20
million to fight De La Hoya may prove to be the worst business
decision in sports since the Red Sox traded Babe Ruth,'' one boxing
insider said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing could be more stupid: If Trinidad wins and he
(begin ital)still(end ital) doesn't agree to fight De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, that's possible given that Felix Trinidad Sr., the
fighter's father and tzar of his camp, has been reluctant to
compromise on any aspect of on-going negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The key sticking point could be weight.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, and King, who handles Trinidad,
have a working agreement that the fight would take place at a catch
weight of 151 pounds - about midway between the welterweight and
junior middleweight limits.
</P>
<P>
   But neither De La Hoya, who fights at 147 pounds, nor Trinidad,
who has moved up to 154, has agreed to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, it's difficult to believe they wouldn't. Forty million
dollars is quite an incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Interested bystander: Shane Mosley of Pomona will be rooting for
Reid on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Trinidad loses, the former lightweight champion is expected
to fight De La Hoya on June 17 at Staples Center in his first truly
big-money, big-exposure fight.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations already are under way for that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me a little uncomfortable having to wait to see
what's going to happen,'' Mosley said. ``That's the way it is if
you're following isn't as big as some fighters (read: De La Hoya).
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, everything will work out and (begin ital)I'll(end
ital) have that kind of following and be in a better position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center is holding the date in the event Trinidad
loses and the De La Hoya and Mosley camps can reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If Trinidad wins and ends up fighting De La Hoya again? Mosley
said he'll probably fight WBA welterweight champ James Page and
ultimately would like to unify the welterweight titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to fight everyone in the division - everyone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Job well done: De La Hoya fought the right fight against Coley:
He fought with controlled aggression.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't run, as he did in the first Trinidad fight. And he
didn't bang, as he did in the second fight with Julio Cesar Chavez.
He found a happy - and efficient - medium that might best suit him
the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   His performance might've been more striking had Coley
cooperated. But Coley realized early in the fight that he was in
over his head and settled into survival mode.
</P>
<P>
   And when a skillful boxer such as Coley decides he doesn't want
to fight, it's very difficult to catch him with many meaningful
punches.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, De La Hoya did all he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chopped him down,'' he said. ``It's like a tree. You take
out the bottom and the whole thing falls down.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he? Was De La Hoya hurt early in the fourth round?
</P>
<P>
   Coley, who landed a right to De La Hoya's head that appeared to
at least stun him for a few dramatic moments, said ``I know'' I
hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't hurt,'' he said. ``When he had the confidence to
throw combinations, at the same time, I was thinking it's a matter
of time that he'll get tired. I wasn't throwing punches back
because I was kinda like bringing him in, opening the door so he
could get tired.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... It was part of like a little game plan we had, but he
never did hurt me, I'll be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those at ringside believe otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Clarification: De La Hoya backed off somewhat from his threat to
boycott the major sanctioning bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that we have to pay sanction fees and I personally
think it's a lot of money,'' he said. ``I have to be very smart
about it. I'm not going to give my money away.
</P>
<P>
   ``...It may be about negotiating and finding out what
organizations are respectable. ... I have to really think about who
I'm going to fight for.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya won the fringe IBA title on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mismatch: Arturo Gatti's brutal knockout of Joey Gamache on the
De La Hoya-Coley undercard magnified a serious problem in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters weighed in Friday at 141 pounds. But at fight time,
Gatti weighed 160 to Gamache's 146. It was like a middleweight
fighting a welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a physical mismatch,'' said Lou DiBella of HBO. ``You
don't have to be a rocket scientist to see that that's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighters should be weighed a second time on fight night and
scratched if they balloon more than a designated number of pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield watch: It's hard to imagine Evander Holyfield in
anything but a megafight at this stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But his tentative bout with No. 1 WBA heavyweight contender John
Ruiz on May 27 in Las Vegas is hardly compelling, even if it turns
out to be for the WBA version of the heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the fight would be for the No. 1 ranking and the
right to fight for Lennox Lewis' WBA crown. But King, Holyfield's
promoter, reportedly is pushing the WBA to strip Lewis of his title
because King says Lewis reneged on an agreement reached before he
beat Holyfield to fight the top WBA contender.
</P>
<P>
   How good is Ruiz? He was knocked out in 19 seconds by David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is scheduled to defend the unified heavyweight titles
against Michael Grant on April 29 at Madison Square Garden in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Former six-time world champion Julio Cesar
Chavez will face journeyman Bobby Elkins in a 12-round welterweight
bout on the Reid-Trinidad card, although rumors are that Chavez has
threatened to pull out unless his purse is increased.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is expected to face WBC junior welterweight Kostya Tszyu
if he wins. ...
</P>
<P>
   In all the hoopla surrounding the De La Hoya and Trinidad-Reid
fights, a bout between WBA bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala, The
Ring magazine's fighter of the year for 1999, and Johnny Bredahl
has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The fight is scheduled for Saturday at the Mandalay Bay in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Oba Carr will face Yory Boy Campas in an interesting junior
middleweight bout on the card. ...
</P>
<P>
   Correction: The result of the second Marco Antonio
Barrera-Junior Jones fight was incorrectly reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jones won by decision, not by a knockout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
