<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORNING-SHOWS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATIE COURIC OF NBC LEADS THE MORNING PACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ As its morning show ratings fell last spring,
ABC brought back former morning hosts Charles Gibson and Diane
Sawyer and built an $80 million set overlooking Times Square in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   As ratings fell last fall, CBS recruited its high-priced, failed
prime-time star Bryant Gumbel, dropped $30 million on its Central
Park-adjacent set and hired the mastermind behind the ``Today''
show's success, Steve Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   NBC did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's'' Katie Couric still reigns supreme in the network
morning TV competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who don't watch CBS because they don't like
Bryant Gumbel,'' observes Robert Thompson, founding director of the
Center of the Study of Popular Television and a professor of film
and television at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who don't watch ABC because they don't like the
people on that show. But there's no one who doesn't watch NBC
because they don't like Katie. (italics) No one (end italics)
doesn't like Katie.''
</P>
<P>
   Morning is the only time period in which network TV viewership
is expanding _ unemployment has been down for several years, so
more people are simply getting up to go to work and flipping on the
set. Thus, competition in that lucrative 7-to-9 a.m. time slot has
heated up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' has been the No. 1 morning show for five consecutive
years, boasting 6.3 million viewers daily; the show cleared a
reported $100 million in profit last year.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' averages 4.2 million viewers;
``The Early Show,'' CBS's umpteenth revamping of its morning news
program, trails with 2.7million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The morning's biggest audience isn't even watching television _
National Public Radio's ``Morning Edition'' draws 8.8 million
listeners daily.
</P>
<P>
   Morning, coincidentally, is the time when the audience's viewing
habits are most firmly entrenched, and ``Today,'' which has been on
the air nearly half a century, has become for many a morning
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bigger hill to climb than nearly any time slot,''
Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morning is logically the time when the remote is least in use
_ you're running all over. The tendency is to settle on one show
and watch it throughout. And that tradition is to watch `Today' _
and it has extended for generations. There's not that habit for
CBS. In fact, the habit for generations is (italics) not (end
italics) to watch CBS, and they've gotten good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years on top is an eternity,'' notes Steve Friedman,
executive producer of ``The Early Show.'' Before his current job,
Friedman spearheaded ``Today's'' march to the top. ``Part of it is
`Today's' a good show; they have great people both on camera and
behind it. But much of that time, `Today' had no real
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Diane and Charles came back, there was not a ton of
competition in the morning,'' agrees ``Today'' spokeswoman Allison
Gollust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The additional competition makes us work harder. We can't get
complacent. Just because you're on top today doesn't mean you'll be
there always. No one is just kicking back and enjoying the view.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the success of ``Today'' seems to be the chemistry
between Couric and co-anchor Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC was extremely fortunate that we got Matt and Katie at the
same time,'' admits Gollust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are highly talented individuals, and for them to
have walked through the doors at the same time and turned up on our
morning show is a huge reason why the show does so well. That
chemistry is not something you can just make happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That chemistry attracts the audience _ both television viewers
and New York City tourists standing outside the show's ground floor
studio windows at Rockefeller Plaza. The window segment was brought
back to the ``Today'' show five years ago to wild success. Dave
Garroway first used it in the 1950s when the ``Today'' show set the
standard for morning TV.
</P>
<P>
   In adding their own outdoors segments, Thompson says, ABC and
CBS look like copycats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those segments are always specious, five minutes of people
giving T-shirts to the weatherman. But they make the show appear
open and friendly _ that's what CBS is responding to, but they're
so pathetic to follow in those footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, CBS's fortunes have bewildered many industry observers.
Lori Robinson, assistant managing editor for the American
Journalism Review magazine, says, ``I'm surprised it hasn't done
better. There was so much hype before it came on, and lots of
people respect Bryant. I thought people would be interested in
tuning in to see the show, but that hasn't happened. I'm not sure
what CBS can do to turn things around.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman concedes that outside of staging live executions of
millionaires, CBS's options to increase its viewership are limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is it's almost impossible to do anything
significant to change the equation _ the other side has got to
(screw) up for you to grow. It's difficult to get them to change.
It's extremely difficult for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A possible window of opportunity could open for CBS after the
May sweeps period, when Charles Gibson or Diane Sawyer, or both,
may exit ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
