<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0487 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MORNING-SHOWS-2ndadd-     02-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORNING-SHOWS-2ndadd-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: Morning America.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``GMA'' executive producer Shelley Ross says, ``Charles and
Diane are having a ball _ they're excited to come in; they like
each other and the show.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers find it hard to believe that Gibson and
Sawyer, who can call their own shots, will stick around forever.
ABC already has credible possible replacements for them in Jack
Ford and Elizabeth Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a time frame, but we will never again surprise
viewers with some radical change,'' Ross says, referring to times
in the past when new anchors such as Lisa McRee were foisted on the
audience, to extreme indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens will occur over a slow period of time. It
will be a transition that viewers will be in on.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson observes: ``Anchors make a huge difference. If Gibson
and Sawyer leave and viewers are not happy, certainly, that's a big
chance for CBS to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the focus of CBS's hopes for ``The Early Show'' _ as
well as its woes _ has centered on Bryant Gumbel, who was a 15-year
veteran of ``Today'' and hosted a failed prime-time news magazine
on CBS, ``Public Eye.'' Gumbel's professionalism has never been
questioned; how viewers perceive his sometimes prickly personality
and his personal life is another matter. He didn't win many fans
when he slagged Couric in an interview last year, and now he's
going through a messy divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great asset to the people who like him, and a liability
to the people who don't,'' Thompson says. ``He's a celebrity, and
he carries the baggage of someone with a public image.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Friedman responds: ``He's the best live interviewer on
morning TV; he brings a heft to the show. The show got instant
credibility when he signed on. There's no one better in the morning
arena. His edge is what morning TV lacks. Anyone who doesn't like
him, I invite them to watch the other morning shows.''
</P>
<P>
   A spotlight has also turned on co-anchor Jane Clayson, a
heretofore unknown who, most critics suggest, appears out of her
element.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman defends her, saying, ``Jane is coming on like
gangbusters.'' When Bryant was in Florida hosting a charity event,
Friedman says, ``She ran the show, and she was crisp and
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, on Friday, news reporter Julie Chen handled the
hard-news interviews on the death penalty and drugs in sports;
Clayson contributed a fluff piece on attending a movie premiere.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has suffered through a revolving-door programming policy in
its morning block for nearly 20 years. Whatever it has been called
_ ``The Morning Program,'' ``CBS Morning News'' or, more recently,
``CBS This Morning,'' it has failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS This Morning'' was roundly considered a flop, but since
its incarnation, ``The Early Show'' has struggled even to match
that program's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a really bad sign,'' says Thompson. ``When you start
something new and the numbers go up just a little, that's a little
disappointing. But if you do something entirely new and the results
go down _ that's saying something that has to be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS was successful before it went the news route, when it aired
the long-running children's series ``Captain Kangaroo.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Thompson: ``CBS never did better than when they had
`Captain Kangaroo.' When he left the air, it was a sad, sad day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
