<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMBINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA CORNERBACK TRIES TO CATCH THEIR EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - As a college football player, Ralph Brown, a
cornerback for the Nebraska Cornhuskers, was nothing but special.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a graduate of Bishop Amat High in La Puente, Calif.,
earned a unique distinction this season when he became the only
Cornhuskers non-kicker since World War II to start every game of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Attending the annual scouting combine in Indianapolis this
weekend, Brown is hoping that his track record for longevity will
translate into a roster spot somewhere in the league for the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL brought more than 300 of the nation's top players to the
combine, where the athletes will undergo a battery of physical and
psychological tests that could determine their pro future.
</P>
<P>
   Doing well can make a player an early-round draft pick. Doing
poorly might guarantee a one-way ticket to NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first day of workouts for defensive backs, Brown
said he was comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect at first, but it's not as bad as
some of the players make it out to be,'' Brown said as he carried a
set of X-rays from the RCA dome to his room at the Indianapolis
Crown Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the coaches are nice, and I'm just taking everything
with a grain of salt and I enjoy being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is part of a class of defensive backs that includes likely
first-rounders Mario Edwards of Florida State and Dwyane Goodrich
of Tennessee. But, he's not fazed by the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to stay relaxed and focused and not worry about
everybody else,'' Brown said. ``The reason I'm here is to try to
raise my stock and meet the coaches. Hopefully they'll like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about every NFL team has interviewed Brown and he expects
to undergo more interviews before the combine ends this evening.
Like everyone else, he's also met with several doctors and
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to meet with every doctor,'' he said. ``You go through
the same thing every time. They check your knees, back, shoulders
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   A cursory background check would reveal some pretty impressive
facts about Brown.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Brown, 5-foot-9 and 184 pounds, was selected as one
of 12 semifinalists for the Jim Thorpe Award, which is given to the
nation's premier defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started every game of his career at Nebraska and set
school records for breakups in a game (seven), season (14) and
career (42).
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Brown led a Huskers defense that ranked in the top
eight in all four defensive categories, including seventh in
passing efficiency and third in total defense.
</P>
<P>
   His Nebraska coaches know exactly what Brown brings to a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the ... years I have worked with Ralph Brown, he has only
played at one speed,'' Nebraska secondary coach George Darlington
said. ``There has never been one instance, not in practice or in a
game, where he didn't go 100 percent. As a coach, I appreciate
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his fortunes over the next few months, Brown said
he is content with what he has accomplished so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached a lot of goals and more goals that I never even
thought of, like starting every game for four years,'' he said.
``Just being All-American and one of the highly touted cornerbacks,
so I've achieved a lot of my goals that I set out before going to
college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
