<SLUG> BC-HKN-CHRISTENSEN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
SORRY ENDING FOR McSORLEY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marty McSorley's legacy is now complete. The
former Kings defenseman will not be remembered as a marginally
talented player who worked hard and actually rose above his
so-called ``enforcer'' status, especially during his years with the
Kings. Instead, McSorley will be remembered as a guy who didn't
have the foresight to use a legal stick in a crucial moment of the
Kings' only Stanley Cup finals appearance, and the pathetic figure
left near tears after inexcusably slashing Vancouver's Donald
Brashear in the side of the head last Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   His image could, and did, survive the first black mark. Time
heals many wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley being penalized for using an illegal stick more than
likely cost the Kings a Stanley Cup title in 1993, but he was still
such a popular figure in Los Angeles that former-owner Bruce
McNall, without informing then-general manager Nick Beverley,
brought McSorley back to the team by trading Tomas Sandstrom and
Shawn McEachern to Pittsburgh in Feb. 1994, less than five months
after he had been traded away. The deal that lives in Kings infamy
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   It will be much harder, perhaps impossible, to forget his
cowardly act on Feb. 21, 2000. Not only did it scar McSorley, it
brought the NHL exactly the kind of attention hockey doesn't need.
Just three nights before McSorley went head hunting, Paul Kariya
and Oleg Tverdovsky combined for a goal that was pure magic. But if
you weren't at the game or watching the telecast how many times
have you seen it?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McSorley's brutal act has been splashed over front
pages and sportscasts by newspapers and television stations that
normally all but ignore the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have to end this way. McSorley, 37, could have gone
out the people's champion instead of a pale imitation of Mike
Tyson. Instead trying to chase down the young gun (Brashear),
McSorley could have left as an inspiration to those with limited
skill levels, but the willingness to work at improving.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, McSorley certainly was a man of the people.
Wayne Gretzky may have turned the town on to hockey, but it was
Marty McSorley and Luc Robitaille who captured their hearts.
Perhaps it was only fitting that McSorley assisted on Gretzky's
record-setting 802nd goal.
</P>
<P>
   With his long, blond hair and hard-hat work ethic, McSorley
appealed to both the casual and hardcore fan. Three times he was
named Los Angeles' most popular player in his first six years with
the Kings, Gretzky won the award twice.
</P>
<P>
   Never to busy to talk, he was a reporter's dream. He would stay
hours after practice filling up notepads with articulate responses
to any and all questions.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1992-93 season McSorley became almost larger than life.
Asked to play a bigger role by new coach Barry Melrose he scored a
career-high 15 goals and 41 points while accumulating a league-high
399 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then in what should have been the defining moment of his 17-year
career he almost singlehandly changed the momentum in the
conference semifinals with his hit on Doug Gilmour late in a Game 1
loss. That set the stage for Gretzky and the Kings to upset the
Maple Leafs and head to Montreal for the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series began, Gretzky, proudly spoke of how much it
meant to see his protector turn into a legitimate NHL player, not
just a hired gun.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley had become such a valued member of the Kings, that none
dared to single him out for the illegal stick call just a few days
later. For years he had covered their backsides, now they were
covering his.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for McSorley that's something nobody can, or
should, do now.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The McSorley incident has renewed the long-standing argument
that fighting should be banned in the NHL, as it is in Europe and
college hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel such a policy would reduce the chances of something
like this happening again.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody shares that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya played NCAA hockey at the University of Maine, where
fighting isn't allowed and full masks are required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the most serious stick incidents I've seen were in
college,'' said Kariya. ``I don't think stick incidents would go
down, I think they would go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg was even more adament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think fighting has anything to do with it (stick
fouls),'' he insisted. ``We've got people that don't watch our game
talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a right to voice their opinion, but they don't have
a clue about our game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
