<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0552 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAMPART-PEREZ-LADN     02-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-PEREZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALSE NAME TIPPED POLICE TO CROOKED COP
</HEADLINE>
 By GREG GITTRICH 
and BETH BARRETT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The name on the Rampart Division evidence room's
sign-out sheet for the eight pounds of cocaine was Perez, and the
badge number belonged to Los Angeles Police Department Officer Joel
Perez. The name fit the crime, but it was the wrong Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Perez wasn't even working at Rampart when Rafael Perez
decided to use Joel's badge number to steal cocaine from an
evidence locker March 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So when Joel Perez received an overdue property statement a week
later, saying a large quantity of cocaine had been charged out to
him in a case in which he was not involved, he thought it must be a
clerical error, sources close to the investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, when the cocaine still had not been returned,
the department's computer issued a second notice, this time to
supervisor Lt. John Cooney, who asked Joel Perez about it, sources
said. Cooney could not be reached immediately for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, he gets the second notice and goes, wow, I
didn't check out that dope,'' said Ted Hunt, president of the
Police Protective League.
</P>
<P>
   Mystified and concerned, Joel Perez went to the property room,
where the clerk who checked the drugs out confirmed he was not the
one who had requested them, sources said. Handwriting samples
verified that someone else signed for the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That launched the investigation that led to the arrest of Rafael
Perez, who eventually turned informant and exposed the worst
scandal in LAPD history, a litany of crimes and rights abuses that
may have sent hundreds of people to prison on frame-ups and almost
certainly will lead to massive reforms in the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Sources confirmed that the Internal Affairs Division began its
investigation March 27, 1998, one day after Joel Perez received the
second notice, and that he was interviewed three days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joel did exactly what he was supposed to be doing,'' a source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said Joel Perez is an honest officer who wanted his name
and badge number cleared immediately and sought the union's advice
on how to do it. Hunt said he believes Joel Perez's actions
prompted the department's inquiry, an assertion that LAPD
investigators dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine Internal Affairs acting that rapidly,'' Hunt
claimed, if the union had not prodded. According to Hunt, the
union's general counsel said Internal Affairs investigators were
not working on the case until the union got involved.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Rafael Perez chose a forgery victim with the same
last name, so he could flash his own badge if questioned in the
property room, but with a different serial number, so the sign-out
would be difficult to trace.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Perez was sentenced Friday to five years in prison on a
plea deal in exchange for providing information on alleged
widespread corruption within the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The honest Perez had nothing to do with it; the crooked Perez
was forging the honest Perez's name,'' Hunt added.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said that if Rafael Perez had substituted flour for
cocaine and returned the evidence bags, as he had done in the past,
he might have gotten away with the crime in Joel Perez's name.
Narcotics were not routinely retested when officers returned them
from court, with only random tests before evidence is destroyed
after trial.
</P>
<P>
   As the LAPD reels from Rafael Perez's testimony that hundreds of
cases may have been tainted by dozens of dirty cops, Hunt said Joel
Perez's honesty and cooperation illustrates what is routine for
most police officers. ``He did what every honest cop should do,''
Hunt said. ``You take care that all your cards are on the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 0211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0553 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EARTH-APOCALYPSE-ECON     02-28 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-APOCALYPSE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
