<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX     02-28 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Love's last gasp on Fox TV
 &HT;    (Eds: An updated column photo is available from Rick McKay at
the Cox Washington Bureau, 202-887-8348.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love did not have a good February, the very home of Valentine's
Day. It was as if Eros took the month off and went slumming.
</P>
<P>
   Few sights are sadder than that of new love, just lit, guttering
out before its flame can come to full glow. Yet, alas, there's no
getting around it: annulment seems the certain future for Rick
Rockwell and Darva Conger.
</P>
<P>
   They're the lovebirds who met and married on national TV in some
fraction of a nanosecond and were whisked away on their honeymoon
before the bride could cry ``Help!''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the reliably shabby Fox network's ``Who Wants
to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' _ ratings fodder that had 23
million viewers hanging on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sally into family values turned out to have the odd glitch
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Conger dutifully kissed the groom than, as in a
fairy tale run backwards, Prince Charming started turning into a
frog.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, it turned out, was a multi-millionaire only if you
scraped everything together, down to the change in his sofa
cushions, and swept his yard with a metal-detector in hopes of
digging up beer cans that would wow the Antiques Roadshow.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell's movie career consisted entirely of a part in ``Killer
Tomatoes Strike Back,'' the little-awaited sequel to ``Attack of
the Killer Tomatoes.'' According to its web site _ oh, yes, there
is _ the movie is currently unavailable in theaters or on TV. You
can't find it on video and DVD, too.
</P>
<P>
   To boot, spoilsport journalist snoops, cutting sentiment no
slack, not even giving romance a teensy chance, rooted up an old
restraining order that a court had issued against Rockwell to
protect a former girlfriend, a bobble Rockwell sloughed off in his
winning way as the result of a misunderstanding. You know how
ex-girlfriends can be.
</P>
<P>
   And, crucially, the bride sensibly wanted nothing to do with her
pop-up husband. Indeed, when she was picked, Conger looked less
moonstruck than like she'd been poleaxed. Her feelings seemed to go
downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Fox's contribution to love consisted only of
inadvertently making the case for chaperoned honeymoons. It was the
first really good press duennas have had in, oh, three or four
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   And no sooner had we romantics resigned ourselves to one love's
sad decline into cross squabbling on morning TV shows than further
disillusioning word came. Tonya Harding, the tough little thugette
of figure skating, had been charged in Seattle with beating up her
live-in boyfriend and slugging him in the face with a hubcap. The
boyfriend is now said to have moved out, which would seem prudent.
</P>
<P>
   The court will have the last say, but in the meantime, what we
do know for sure is that the Harding love nest is one that has
hubcaps lying around, which, I suppose, ought to tell us something.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid, come next February, may be tempted to swap his quiver for
a Kalishnikov.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
