A0659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEENEDITORIAL-SKOOLS2     02-28 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENEDITORIAL-SKOOLS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Schools can't help prodigy
 &HT;    EDS: PHOTO IS AVAILABLE
 &HT;    By Tomasz Macura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the best of my knowledge, I am the youngest person ever to
attend college full-time in the state of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   I was accepted to Augusta State University in the winter of 1998
at age 11, after scoring 1340 on the SAT (790 mathematics, 550
verbal). I never attended middle or high school or studied material
taught there.
</P>
<P>
   Today, I am 13 and I have college junior standing. During the
last two years, I took 26 classes for a total of 69 credit hours
and earned a 3.45 cumulative GPA.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I go to college so young? Because American K-12
education is the worst in the developed world. College seemed like
the only reasonable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, there are several reasons for the poor quality of
K-12 education in this country. Unfortunately, a majority of
teachers are not that smart or compassionate, which is not
surprising given that some of the worst college students are
becoming teachers.
</P>
<P>
   It's stupid to let people who never were good learners
themselves be in charge of instilling to kids that education is
important.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers need to be taught less about how to teach and more
about what to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the negative school atmosphere. It is very
uncool to be smart and to know and understand things.
</P>
<P>
   I am always asked how I like college, and I always answer that I
love it. Studying in college lets me choose the quality and
quantity of my education. Sometimes I take 25 credit hours,
sometimes 18, and sometimes 20. Additionally, I can choose my
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain once said that he never let schooling get in the way
of his education. I am trying to do the same. I strongly believe
that you cannot get intelligence by going to college. This is
something you get in your genes and are taught by your parents.
</P>
<P>
   College tells you what books to read and offers you the digested
wisdom of professors who have spent their lives digesting wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   I would much rather play than study. That is normal. But as far
as schooling is concerned, college works much better for me.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, I have extra time to be a child because I am in
college. Had I gone to middle or high school, I would have been in
class most of the day and then have homework to do.
</P>
<P>
   In college, I have classes only in the morning. After a one-hour
break for lunch, I do homework and study. I have two extra hours of
free time each day by not going to ``normal school.''
</P>
<P>
   I like to scuba dive, sail, swim and play with Legos and
computer chess programs. I also practice martial arts, Tae Kwon Do.
</P>
<P>
   Before I entered college, we, as a family, went through a long
battle. We talked to two principals, one county superintendent, one
assistant superintendent and even contacted the state school
superintendent's office. We tried to find some assistance,
compassion and help. There was none. It was all a waste of time and
energy. It is all behind us now, and we are very glad we overcame
all the problems, real and invented for us.
</P>
<P>
   However, I am sure that many other bright kids and their
parents, who were disillusioned about public education, gave up
earlier, tired of fighting windmills and red tape.
</P>
<P>
   If it had not been for my parents' persistence, I still would be
one of the many nameless 8th-graders instead of a college junior.
How many others like me are there and will stay there? Don't they
deserve your help?
</P>
<P>
   Give kids a chance they earned: a chance to study, and you will
be amazed what they can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasz Macura is a junior at Augusta State University.
</P>
<P>
   Email: stu11886(at)aug.edu
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
