<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Marching for Fidel
 &HT;    For release March 1, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ These are the best of days for Fidel Castro. How he must
be chortling. As he has been so capable of doing the past four
decades, he has solidified his rule based on a highly successful
``offended party syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   When things need boosting, there is always someone to blame.
Yesterday it was the embargo, last month it was the Cuban exiles in
Miami -- referred to even by Cuban grandmothers as a ``mafia.'' Now
it's a Cuban diplomat alleged to have been involved with a Cuban
exile accused of spying for Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing issued T-shirts citing the cause of the day and waving
issued Cuban flags, they march by the thousands in the streets of
Havana, blindly following the lead of the Castro regime. If
anything ever was staged, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   They are told by Castro that Jose Imperatori was not a spy, that
somehow this was linked to the Elian Gonzalez tug-of-war. And so
they march, not the slightest bit knowledgeable about whether
Imperatori was involved directly or indirectly with accused INS
operative Mariano Faget.
</P>
<P>
   This is succor for Castro's reign. It takes the spotlight off
his show trials, his muffling of dissidents, his failed economy.
Periodically, events inspire him -- and he struts out his uniformed
marchers in a show of unity and national pride.
</P>
<P>
   I've lost track of how many marches there have been about the
Elian mess but they have been frequent. Now, there's the booted-out
diplomat Imperatori.
</P>
<P>
   Also playing a role in Castro's favor is the deepening chasm in
relations between exile Cubans and non-Hispanics in this city.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Miami and the larger Miami-Dade County community,
controlled extensively by Hispanics, are unique among the cities
and counties of this nation in that they have their own foreign
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The governmental bodies have enacted laws regarding any form of
traffic with Cuba -- even with entertainers and cultural events.
This has not set well with the non-Hispanics who complain that the
Cubans are doing the very things Castro is doing to his people;
denying them what we have come to call First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   That non-Hispanics are furious about the area's foreign policy
is an understatement. Just last week, after it was learned that a
Cuban-made film would be shown during the annual Miami Film
Festival, the Miami-Dade County Commission voted to withhold
$50,000 in funding for the festival, citing its policy of not
dealing with anything Cuban or anyone who might be dealing with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   This was but another in a long series of events that prevents
any cultural link with Castro Cuba. Interestingly, these same Cuban
performers or academicians are accepted everywhere else in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami policy is broken every day when hundreds of exiles
travel back to Cuba to visit relatives and distribute medicines,
food and money. The politicians and activists turn a blind eye to
this.
</P>
<P>
   And Fidel laughs again. The exiles bail so many people out of
their poverty and hunger that Castro doesn't have to be blamed for
their condition.
</P>
<P>
   No policy initiated by the United States, or local governments,
has been able to shake the foundation of the Castro reign. He has
lasted this long, not because of improvement on the quality of life
on his island, but because of those who would see him gone.
</P>
<P>
   He has feasted on the ruse that all of Cuba's problems are
created by the United States and that ``mafia'' in Miami. Exiles
carry bumper strips on their cars that read ``No Fidel, No
problema.'' Behind that wishful thinking, however, is the fact that
Fidel still is there and the ``problema'' is seemingly
never-ending, from the White House on down to the preposterous
local politicians.
</P>
<P>
   From this, Fidel has survived when perhaps he might have fallen
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
