<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX     02-28 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Lessons in life from the great
outdoors
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By G.C. Irvine Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Special to Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A magnolia tree stood straight and tall on a narrow ridge at the
northeast end of Big Pond, and next to it a giant holly, and next
to the holly a giant white oak, the sentinel of the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   On the smooth bark of the magnolia were carved the letters LUM
BENSON, the landmark for my grandfather, my dad, my son in our
hunting territory.
</P>
<P>
   The area was located 8-10 miles west of the Southeast Texas town
of Kirbyville, which was where grandfather and dad lived the better
part of their lives. Grandfather named the hunting grounds the
Ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfather was a dedicated squirrel hunter. He loved the hunt
and he loved the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the insistence of my grandmother would he occasionally
bring her a duck or a half-grown raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother could make a culinary delight out of anything.
She canned squirrel meat just like she did chicken, the vegetables
from the garden, soups and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Money was scarce and nothing was wasted. Grandfather instilled
in me to never shoot anything I was not going to eat and to make a
clean kill with one shot. Shells were valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfather gave me my first shotgun, a little .410 gauge, on my
10th birthday, and I made my first solo hunt the following fall of
1942.
</P>
<P>
   But for several seasons prior to that time I had followed --
without gun _ in the footsteps of dad or granddad, learning the
woods and everything I could about them, yearning for the time I
would be old enough to go it on my own.
</P>
<P>
   We would often stop for a rest and a snack on Lum Benson Ridge
under the magnolia tree, sipping hot coffee from a Thermos and
downing a baked sweet potato and biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   I got much of my education under that tree, from early childhood
well into my teen years, sometimes tutored by grandfather,
sometimes by dad _ and sometimes just by sitting quiet and still,
watching, listening and seeing, feeling the breeze upon my face,
the spirit and character and of that great tree and that great
place.
</P>
<P>
   Late evenings just before it was time to meet dad and granddad
back at the car, I would linger on the ridge listening to the
frogs, the wood ducks and the owls, reluctant to call it a day.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes quail that had been scattered earlier in the day would
begin calling to one another trying to get back together before
dark so they could roost as a covey.
</P>
<P>
   They would eventually assemble on the ground in a tight circle,
tails toward the center, heads facing outwards, so they could burst
into flight in every direction, should some critter like Mr. Fox
disturb them.
</P>
<P>
   I would have to hurry to arrive at the car before dark.
Grandfather would always begin blowing his fists about sundown if I
had not yet made it, cupping his hands and blowing through his
thumbs, making a sound like the toot of a toy train's whistle.
</P>
<P>
   That was our way of communicating with one another. We never
hollered -- just three short toots blown from someone's cupped
hands and then there would be a similar reply.
</P>
<P>
   I do not know how the name Lum Benson came to be on that
magnolia tree. I only know that it marked a time, a place and a
part of our history for four generations of Irvines who hunted that
land without having to pay a fee, never finding a lock on a gate to
block our way.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, there came a day when I got to sit my son down on that
ridge holding the same little .410 my grandfather had given me.
</P>
<P>
   He was so young and small, fragile and frightened, yet eager to
be free to hunt on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, I walked away, trusting him to the watch care,
tutoring and wisdom, and strength that came with sitting under the
Lum Benson tree.
</P>
<P>
   G. C. Irvine Jr. lives in Vidor, Texas. He has printed a book,
``When I Was A Boy,'' to pass along family stories to his
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
