<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LEBANON-MILITIA-BOS &LR;      02-28 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-MILITIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLOGY OF LEBANESE FIGURE BREAKS SILENCE ON CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In the decade since Lebanon's civil war ended, this
country has tried to rebuild from the ruins by forgetting the
brutality of the past.
</P>
<P>
   To many Lebanese, it seemed the only way out of a conflict in
which all sides committed unspeakable atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   But Asaad Shaftari, 44, who rose to second in command of the
right-wing Lebanese Forces during the 15-year civil war, stunned
Lebanon this month with a statement extraordinary in its simplicity
and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   He publicly asked for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to his victims ``both living and dead,''
he became the first high-level militia leader to apologize for the
thousands that he and his Christian militia contributed to the
70,000 deaths in Lebanon's agony of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something I have wanted to do for a long time. In fact,
something I wanted to do for ten years. But I have never had the
courage,'' he wrote in the Feb. 10 edition of An Nahar newspaper, a
mainstream daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize for the horror of war and what I did in this civil
war in the name of `Lebanon' or `the cause' or `Christianity,' ''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that my call be understood as the only way out of
the Lebanese dilemma, the only way to purify the souls of those
tormented by the pains of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was not prominently displayed but discreetly placed
in a corner of page 5. Nevertheless it touched off a writhing
critique of ``state-sponsored amnesia,'' as one journalist put it.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 25th anniversary of the beginning of the war
as well as the 10th anniversary of the end of the war. So Lebanon
finds itself with bookends of time that could prompt more
reflection. But until recently, there has been only silence.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon has no public memorial for the victims of the war. Film
directors who have explored the depths of the conflict have seen
their work censored. Books seen as going too far in assigning
responsibility for war crimes, such as British journalist Robert
Fisk's ``Pity the Nation,'' have been banned.
</P>
<P>
   The only visual symbols for meditation on the conflict are the
ravaged buildings along Beirut's ``Green Line'' that divided the
city, and where massive construction is under way. Some of the
shelled buildings are staggered like broken concrete accordions.
Some are punched by mortar fire, and through the gaping holes poor
Syrian immigrant workers can be seen living amid the rubble. Window
casings and balconies were chewed down from daily machine-gun
barrages.
</P>
<P>
   It is considered impolite in Lebanese conversation to ask
someone about the war. And when a foreign reporter does ask, the
questions are often met with blank stares, shakes of the head, or
polite evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Karam, who was the Lebanese ambassador to Washington in
the early 1990s in the aftermath of the war, said, ``The danger is
the problems will inevitably push to the surface again. The past
cannot be buried. We can't simply tear down the bombed out
buildings and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of this collective amnesia, as Karam points out, is not
only personal pain but a public policy endorsed by a government
made up of many of those who committed atrocities in the war.
</P>
<P>
   There are many leaders of the militias _ from all sides of the
fractious conflict that pitted rival Christian, Muslim, and Druse
militias against one another in an orgy of violence _ who are now
highly placed government officials. Eli Hobeika, for example, the
former head of the Lebanese Forces, is now a leading member of
parliament. Druse militia leader Walid Jumblatt is also a member of
parliament and until recently headed the powerful Ministry of the
Displaced. A 1991 amnesty law granted immunity to those involved in
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   These warlords-turned-politicians are too fearful of their
political futures, critics say, to publicly confront their role in
the war.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts of this absence of memory are the disappeared. There
are still 17,000 Lebanese who disappeared during the war and have
never been accounted for. Various governmental committees have long
delayed and foundered on investigating their fate. Last month, the
government established a committee, but few believe it will produce
results.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, loved ones of the disappeared live on in agony. For
them the war remains a reality of daily life. The questioning never
stops. Are their sons and brothers and husbands and friends
actually dead, or is it possible they could be languishing
somewhere, perhaps in an Israeli or Syrian prison?
</P>
<P>
   Wadad Helwani, 48, founder of the Committee of the Families of
the Kidnapped and Disappeared, hopes her husband, Adnan, is still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Adnan Helwani was not a member of a militia, his wife said, but
was an activist in a left-wing political party that provided social
service to war-torn Muslim West Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 24, 1982, he was taken from their home. It was the
height of the Israeli invasion, and he was taken by two
plainclothes men carrying guns and ID cards from the Lebanese
Army's intelligence services. It was not clear whether the two were
in fact acting as members of the Army or agents of the Lebanese
Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Wadad Helwani carries herself with strength and dignity. But as
she talked of her husband's disappearance, of her sons growing up
without a father, she began to chain-smoke. She seemed shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need to be strong before, before Adnan was kidnapped.
I relied on him,'' she said, her eyes watering with sadness.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Shaftari's search for forgiveness, she
stiffened. She responded sharply, ``It isn't enough to apologize
just like that out of thin air. He has to be forgiven by the
individuals he hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long afternoon shadows in the lobby of the Commodore
Hotel, where journalists and diplomats stayed during the war,
Shaftari met with reporters last week. He wanted the letter to
speak for itself, but he was willing to answer a few questions.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't look like a killer.
</P>
<P>
   And if the memory of his militia's victims was torturing him, it
wasn't visible in his calm demeanor. The once-rigid posture of a
warrior who carried a machine gun had given way to a slight paunch
hidden under a white sweater vest and blue blazer.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaftari, an electrical engineer who is married with two
young sons, was compelled to write the letter after a recent
television interview with Robert Maroun Hatem, better known by his
nom de guerre ``Cobra'' and a shadowy figure in the Lebanese
Forces. Lebanese Forces is a sanitized name for the Christian
Phalange militia, which traced its origins to the fascist ideology
of Franco's Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Hatem's interview caught attention by offering a glimpse into
the violent workings of the Lebanese Forces, including an alleged
assassination attempt against Salim Hoss, now the prime minister.
Hatem also alleged that Hobeika's Lebanese Forces played a role in
the 1982 massacre of Palestinian refugees at Sabra and Shatilla, as
has long been suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Shaftari said he was angered by ``the bickering'' about Hatem's
comments, and at the former warlords' running for cover. Shaftari
lives a quiet life and said he has no motive other than a spiritual
search for redemption. It was simply the heavy weight of the past,
he said, that overwhelmed him and led him to write the letter. He
said it poured out of him in ``a matter of minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief in God gave me the strength to write this letter,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to study what happened on an individual basis
before the general one. You can't just put the blame on those in
charge. We were all responsible: those holding the guns, those
giving the orders, even the civilians applauding it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Young, a columnist for the English-language Beirut Daily
Star newspaper, applauded Shaftari's repentance but suggested he
also provide practical information to help survivors, especially
families of the disappeared, bring closure to the war. People need
to know what happened, he says, not just hear an apology.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that Lebanon's denial of its past has weakened the
foundation for its future. But he seemed reluctant to suggest
Lebanon is ready to plunge into catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaftari's repentance, Cobra's tattling, and the government's
newly found interest in the disappeared suggest that the postwar
edifice is not as secure as its architects planned,'' he wrote.
``However, before full-scale catharsis is decreed, thought is
required. Asaad Shaftari may be a pleasant surprise, but a legion
of Shaftaris could drag Lebanon down irreparably.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Kim Ghattas contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
