<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      02-28 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOP DREAMS TAKING HOLD ACROSS AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe _ His first shot caught nothing but air. The
next few hit the rim with the bluntness of bricks. But a boyish
grin, more in the eyes than the mouth, never left Fortune Sithole's
face. It fixed with a kind of taunting certainty that soon he would
slip by an opponent, or jump higher, or fade away, the ball arcing
perfectly. Nothing but net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good at jamming,'' said Sithole, down at the Barrow Street
Courts one recent evening. ``But I'm also quick like Scottie
Pippen. He's got speed. He anticipates his opponent. Pippen made
Michael Jordan. He's my guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny conversation for the African bush? Not anymore. Basketball
may not be as popular yet as soccer or cricket, but hoop dreams are
sweeping across the continent. Egyptians are known for their fast
break. Mozambique has basketball postage stamps. And in Zimbabwe,
even the girls got game.
</P>
<P>
   Around Bulawayo _ it means ``the place of killing'' in the
Ndebele language _ it's not hard to find a pickup game if you know
where to look. The town has 21 teams, with about 500 players, most
of them in their late teens and 20s. They practice on weeknights in
public parks and schoolyards, behind churches. They play
tournaments on Saturdays that last from early afternoon until after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to satellite TV, everyone talks about the National
Basketball Association. Terrance Chawanda saw his first game a
decade ago. He was 10, and Magic Johnson was with the Lakers. Every
day after that, he would practice dunking with a tennis ball on a
small, homemade hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams loves the Sacramento Kings and even started his
own basketball Web site. Belia Phiri, captain of one of the girl's
teams, tries to move like the Lakers' Kobe Bryant. And, of course,
they all want to be like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a sport that started picking up in Zimbabwe in
the past four to five years,'' Durall Adams, coach of the City
Knights, said during a practice outside the Revival Center
Ministries church, where a bright spotlight illuminated an asphalt
half court. ``My auntie in Boston, Desiree Sayer, sends me a lot of
magazines on basketball to give us ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an unmistakable familiarity about the hoop scene here.
Dreams of overseas college scholarships float over the hard
realities of being young and African _ and of being besieged by
crumbling economies and the threat of AIDS, which afflicts as many
as one in four adults in southern Africa. Given the reticence that
cloaks discussions of sex in African societies, most youths come of
age with little guidance and protection.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball provides shelter. The 21 teams in Bulawayo run in
threes. Each club as an `A' and `B' team for boys as well as a
girl's team. They often practice and travel together and watch out
for each other. ``Teams socialize with us like brothers. They
protect the girls,'' said Charmaine Chirinda.
</P>
<P>
   Sithole agrees. ``There is so much peer pressure to drink and
smoke and have sex,'' he said. ``Basketball teaches us that we have
this precious thing to protect. It gives you a healthy and strong
mind. I am what I am because of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sithole and others are frustrated by the limits of the game.
There are four regional leagues in Zimbabwe, all amateur. Teams
scramble for sponsors to pay for travel and equipment. Most of the
time, the money isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Sithole, who is about 6-foot-5 and straight and thin as
a maypole, played on the national team in the All Africa games.
``We were hammered by the Kenyans,'' he said. He was 21 then and
filled with ambitions. He hoped to return four years later when the
games reconvened. But Zimbabwe could not afford to keep the team
together, and Sithole, sure he'd reached a dead end, hung up his
jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But basketball is on the upswing again in Zimbabwe, and the man
with moves like Scottie Pippen is back on the court. He's rusty,
but confident. ``Just let me warm up,'' he said before a one-on-one
match. ``Just let me warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kurt Shillinger is a Globe correspondent based in Johnannesburg.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
