<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-EYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EYE OF LONDON: A NOVELTY WITH A PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ On a clear day, you can see forever.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, you can see Windsor Castle. Which, at 25 miles
from the top of the London Eye, is nothing to sneeze at.
</P>
<P>
   Barring unforeseen difficulties, which given the Eye's history
are impossible to rule out, the 443-foot-high structure, also known
as the Millennium Wheel, will open to the public on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That would be two months after its New Year's Eve debut had to
be canceled because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   That would be three months after the wheel's raising had to be
abandoned because one of the anchors that fastens the structure to
the South Bank of the River Thames had come loose.
</P>
<P>
   Built by British Airways, the London Eye has replaced a smaller
structure in Japan's Yokohama Bay as the world's tallest
observation wheel. It's not a Ferris wheel; more on that later.
</P>
<P>
   The Eye's troubles getting off the ground have mirrored the
recent woes of its owner, which has seen profits tumble and thus
may have to lay off several thousand employees.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of a plan to turn its fortunes around, British
Airways has sunk $56 million into the wheel. So despite its
difficult birth, the London Eye seems destined to become the
capital's hottest tourist attraction this year, and some say it
could eventually be to London what the Eiffel Tower is to Paris. It
has become the towering landmark on central London's skyline,
dwarfing Big Ben across the river.
</P>
<P>
   While the Millennium Dome, the $1 billion exhibition center a
few miles down the Thames, was supposed to have been the focal
point of Britain's millennium celebrations, it has opened to mixed
reviews and half-filled houses. Perhaps because the London Eye is
not nearly as ambitious as the Dome, which bills itself as an
extraordinary day out _ although many describe it as quite ordinary
_ the Millennium Wheel is in a better position to fulfill lower
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful way to spend a half-hour, with stunning views
of one of the world's greatest cities,'' said Jamie Bowden, the
indefatigable spokesman for the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden acknowledges that the wheel is a critical part of British
Airways' marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 30 million foreign tourists who come to London every
year, 15 million of them fly, and we carry 12 million of them,''
Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways officials hope that having the world's tallest
observation wheel is one more reason that tourists will come here.
</P>
<P>
   And OK, here's the deal on the wheel: This is not a Ferris
because it is supported by an A-frame from one side only, and
because the 32 egg-shaped passenger capsules are fully enclosed and
do not hang from, but are fastened to, the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 50,000 people have taken ``preview rides'' in February.
About 750,000 tickets have been sold, and British Airways predicts
that it will carry more than 2 million passengers a year. Bowden
said that about 30 percent of the tickets will be reserved, and
that the rest will be allocated for walk-up sales. Tickets are
about $12 for adults and $8 for children.
</P>
<P>
   For Londoners like the Davis family, from Kennington on the
south side of the city, that's a lot cheaper than a trip to the
Dome, which would cost them at least three times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Alex-Rae Davis, 6, was leery of getting on the wheel the other
day, so in awe of its size as she stood directly beneath it. But
with her mother Linda's encouragement, she got on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she doesn't want to get off,'' Linda Davis said, as the
wheel neared the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see Canary Wharf,'' Alex-Rae said, pointing down the
snaking Thames where Britain's tallest tower stands.
</P>
<P>
   Alex-Rae's 10-year-old sister, Robin, was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's boring,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Dennis Davis, wouldn't say it's boring, but as a
taxi driver, who knows London like the back of his hand, he felt he
was seeing the roofs of buildings he sees every day. While
Londoners try to find their neighborhoods, Davis said he believes
tourists will take to the wheel more than natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one more thing you can do with the kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of sentiment British Airways is banking on,
especially when London is flooded with Americans and their kids,
beginning with spring school vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel has permission to remain at its site, adjacent to
County Hall and the London Aquarium, for five years. But the
structure has been built to survive for as long as 90 years, and
British Airways officials are hoping it will become so popular that
there will be a consensus to extend its life indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden observed, ``When the Eiffel Tower was built, it was only
supposed to be up for a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
