<HEADER>
A0723 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX     02-28 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tree people, lawn people in yard clash
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ There are two kinds of yards _ tree yards
and grass yards. People like to fool themselves into thinking they
can have the best of both. Forget it. You are on one side or the
other. And it's a bigger divide than you think.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, other varieties of yard exist here and there, but their
numbers are insignificant. Pebbly xeriscapes and shoreline
underbrush yards appear in odd places but their numbers are few.
Some damaged and distressed yards don't seem to fall into one
category or the other, but look closer. Each has aspirations in one
direction or another. Some represent the failure of trees. Some
represent the
</P>
<P>
   failure of grass. Almost all represent the failure of water.
</P>
<P>
   Like all great social divides, the lawn/tree division tends to
fall along predictable social fault lines.
</P>
<P>
   Tree people are more likely to be romantics, nature lovers and
slobs who wear Hawaiian shirts before Labor Day. Lawn people tend
to be rationalistic, order lovers and tense people who iron their
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn people put lawn ornaments in their yards. Tree people leave
bicycles in their yards, often overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn people see tree people as irresponsible drags on property
values. Tree people wonder at the time, treasure and tension
involved in bringing a little bit of a golf course into the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn people fear being crushed by falling giant oaks. Tree
people fear being poisoned by pesticides and lawn chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   In their formative years, tree people were freaks. Lawn people
were geeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these are overgeneralizations. But the lawn/tree divide
also exposes a deep, fundamental and all-too-often ignored social
rift. This division is not merely a matter of yard preferences. It
unearths far deeper divisions in aesthetics, personal credo and
opinions about life, the universe and everything.
</P>
<P>
   Here, I must pause to register a conflict of interest. I write
this not as an unbiased xeriscapist, apartment dweller or
out-of-town anthropologist, but as a tree person. My lot is a leaf
farm that grows thick with scrub oaks of several varieties. Its
pitiful lawn struggles with shade and dead leaves and twigs. Only
an aggressive cat, helped by teen-agers in cars, keeps the squirrel
population at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The trees are so thick they twist like corkscrews to compete for
the little bit of sunlight available. The yard is shady and
welcoming to birds. Fern grows better than grass.
</P>
<P>
   Overreacting to the first warm days of the year, I strung a
hammock between a pair of bluejack oaks that are finally thick
enough to support me. At last, I reaped the rewards of my patience
and devotion to silviculture.
</P>
<P>
   Snoozing there, I hear birds, kids at play and the distant drone
of small gasoline engines at work on lawns. While I rest, they are
at work, cutting lawns and blowing tree leaves. The sound is like a
rebuke, but I can live with it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when tree-lovers were the majority and
lawn-lovers an upstart movement. I look at any pre-World War II of
my part of Florida and the most striking natural feature is most
likely to be the trees. Great canopies of oak where U.S. 1 now
runs. Mossy scrub oaks stunting the grass growth in front of houses
with porches. Overdressed people posing by the impossibly large
live oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Road safety engineers, power and phone lines and the demand for
green, green lawns changed that landscape block by block, lot by
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Tree people have beat a slow and steady retreat for a
half-century. And because it takes a long time for an oak to get
dangerous and dramatic, it only takes only one sale to a lawn-lover
to make a yard change its allegiance forever.
</P>
<P>
   We are holdouts, even rebels, in this streetscape. But every
time I am awakened on a Saturday by the scream of a lawnmower, I
know this is the path for which I was destined.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
