r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX     02-28 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to extend children's schooling beyond nine-month term
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ America's public schools are being dragged down by
``an old agrarian schedule, an outdated factory model and an
antiquated wage system.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a quote from Education Secretary Richard W. Riley, who
called on U.S. teachers to work year-round in his seventh and final
address on the state of American education.
</P>
<P>
   It's a joy to hear a cabinet-level education official call the
American education model outdated and summon the political courage
to say teachers need to work year-round the same as other
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 100 years, American education has been defined by
certain assumptions,'' Riley told students, educators and elected
officials at Durham, N.C.'s Southern High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``One assumption was that the job of a teacher lasted nine
months,'' he said. ``The second assumption was that we would always
have a ready supply of dedicated teachers, mostly women, who for
relatively low wages would teach our children their lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   America's nine-month school year has zero to do with education.
It's about child labor. Teachers weren't needed in the summer.
There were no children to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Until about 70 years ago, most Americans either lived on farms
or in rural areas dependent on agriculture. Children were needed to
work on their family farms during the summer. School had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been practically no need for child labor on
family farms for decades, the United States stuck with this
outmoded agrarian schedule long after European and Asian nations
adopted much longer school years, which may have something to do
with the reason U.S. students score well below their foreign
counterparts on core subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that students learn while they are in school, the less
time they spend in school, the less opportunity they have to learn.
That's not rocket science, it's elementary logic.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was careful to avoid calling for year-round school for
children, only for teachers. He said school schedules for students
should be left to states and local school boards.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the 2.5 million-member National Education
Association and the American Federation of Teachers endorsed
Riley's year-round plan for teachers if it is accompanied by an
appropriate pay increase to compensate for the extra work. That's a
start.
</P>
<P>
   The welcome movement to hold students to higher measured
standards means many youngsters who have been promoted without the
skills needed to succeed at higher academic levels must have
additional teaching to keep them from falling farther back.
</P>
<P>
   Mentors are good. Community volunteers are welcome. Teacher
aides are fine. But competent, professional teachers are best.
</P>
<P>
   Students need the opportunity to learn earlier in life, later in
the day and all year long.
</P>
<P>
   If students are to be held accountable for their learning,
teachers should be held accountable for their teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Standards to become a teacher should be raised considerably.
Teachers should teach in their specialties. Bad teachers should be
fired. Good teachers should be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Riley noted in his speech that experienced teachers with
master's degrees earn an average of $32,000 a year less than their
counterparts in other fields.
</P>
<P>
   That needs to be changed to match the way other professionals
are paid, which is based on merit for year-round work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that making teaching a year-round profession is the
future of American education,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a start. Student learning is the key to America's future.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
