r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX     02-28 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On assignment aboard the Orient Express
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ For over 20 years now, my friend Gail and I
have shared a dream that always begins with us making a last-minute
dash through Paris' Gare de l'Est railway station, trailing luggage
and porters in our wake as we step onto the platform of our
Wagon-Lits car the very moment the conductor urgently shouts his
final: ``En voiture, messieurs, s'il vous plait. En voiture.''
</P>
<P>
   All aboard the Orient Express.
</P>
<P>
   As we are settling into our compartment, laying out dressing
gowns, and remarking how odd to find coreopsis blooms in the
crystal vase this time of year, the attendant will discreetly tap
on the door and remind us champagne is being poured in the salon.
Naturally, we will attend.
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative, you see, that we meet our fellow travelers,
and the sooner the better. We're not here to play, my companion and
I. We are more than the foolish, ultra-glamorous women of the world
we might appear _ much more.
</P>
<P>
   We are undercover operatives on a top-secret assignment. ``Find
the fat man with the microfilm,'' the Chief had instructed just
before he sent us into the chill midnight of a Paris street. ``The
fate of the entire free world is balanced precariously on your
well-manicured fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's pretty hokey, but fantasizing about a trip on the
Orient Express has been our rainy afternoon entertainment for as
long as we can remember. We've read the books, watched the movies,
and bought each other ``genuine replicas'' of the brass lamps that
used to subtly light the dining car tables. We've even put together
a 1000-piece jigsaw puzzle of two elegantly turned out ladies
boarding a Pullman car with COMPAGNIE INTERNATIONALE DES
WAGONS-LITS emblazoned down the side.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not enough. We want to take the ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Orient Express, in its golden years, carried a democratic
mix of passengers. It was, after all, a money-making business, so
if Joe Shmoe from Kokomo had the bucks, he was only a passport away
from sharing wheels with Leopold II of the Belgians, or Charlie
Chaplin, or even the Duke and Duchess of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand I of Bulgaria had been born to the deepest of purple
and therefore was suitable to occupy any vacant throne upon which
Victoria of England and Bismarck of Germany might have wanted to
place him. But instead, much to his displeasure, he found himself
the ruler of what he termed a ``ridiculous country.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Orient Express that carried Ferdinand on state visits
to the Sultan of Turkey, the Kaiser of Germany, and the King of
Greece. It was, in fact, on one such trip that in the middle of the
night when he found himself unable to sleep, this Czar of Bulgaria
pulled the emergency cord and demanded to be allowed to drive the
train. The alarmed engineer protested, but Ferdinand insisted that
since the train was within Bulgarian territory it was his to do
with as he wished.
</P>
<P>
   It took the crew four hours to release the brakes that the Czar
had locked up when he'd yanked on the emergency cord. The
Compagnie, in order to ward off any future delays, came to an
arrangement with the King. He could drive the train within
Bulgaria, but he could only take over at a scheduled stop.
</P>
<P>
   According to E.H. Cookridge's book on the Orient Express, the
letter of the agreement was observed, but not the spirit. One day
as the train was laboring up a steep gradient, it came upon a
horsedrawn carriage parked astride the track. The train stopped in
time to avoid a collision, and was greeted by the driver, a tall,
burly gentleman in a splendid uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the Czar of Bulgaria,'' he proclaimed, ``and as the train
is on my territory, I desire to drive it.'' Years later,
Ferdinand's son Boris took over his father's place in the
locomotive, dressed in white overalls that had been tailor-made for
his position as royal engineer _ but only within the confines of
his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Gail and I, on the other hand, not having inherited a small
European kingdom, are left with our dream. This summer we're going
to go practicing on Amtrak's Empire Builder. We'll be the veiled
ladies in the club car _ but don't stop to chat. We're on
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
