<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGAMER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Babies will have a ball with new program
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There's no doubt where Knowledge Adventure
stands in the ongoing debate about the merits of computing for
infants. The company has recently released JumpStart Baby with Baby
Ball ($30; www.knowledgeadventure.com.) The Baby Ball is an
oversized blue push pad/roller ball. We connected this computer
peripheral, which comes with no installation instructions, to a
serial port and then installed the software. Ten-month-old Brooke
went to work. She turned to the monitor after seeing the bright
images and hearing the animated talking bear from the ``JumpStart
Baby'' learning software. Brooke's initial reaction was to beat on
the keyboard and play with the mouse, but when we placed the big
blue ball in front of her, she was intrigued and discovered quickly
that banging on the ball produced a noise or on-screen reaction.
She broke into a big smile, for instance, after pressing the ball
caused an animated toy chest to open. Weaker hands than Brooke's
might not be able to press down hard enough to activate the
software. But with practice and help, maybe this challenge can be
overcome. JumpStart Baby, meanwhile, reinforces the concepts of
cause and effect, color and sound _ and upholds Knowledge
Adventure's excellent reputation for educational software.
JumpStart Baby with Baby Ball is intended for ages 9 months to 24
months.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS, AMUSE YOURSELVES WITH AMELIA
</P>
<P>
   Good software for girls is so rare it's impossible not to find
lots to love with the lastest title from American Girl, Your
Interactive Notebook With Help From Amelia ($30 for Windows and
Mac; www.mattelmedia.com), which turns the popular children's books
by Marissa Moss into a fun and funky virtual diary. With sound
effects, stamps, tons of patterns and pens, password protection
and, most fun, an ``Ameliarizer'' that turns key words into wacky
illustrated type, this is a great introduction to what is
essentially desktop publishing. In a tutorial of sorts, the
9-year-old narrator walks the user through all the available tools.
On the downside the interface is not intuitive enough, requiring
adult help that undercuts the whole point of the program _ doing it
yourself. And finally, in what might be the best argument for using
the program, our third-grade critic, after initially spending an
hour or two on it, lost interest in the computer version and
devoted her time to her print journal with real stickers and real
crayon drawings. What parent can complain about that?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
