<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA0229-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life uncovers online game-playing surprises
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Husted
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you think you spend too much of your time on the
Web goofing off, then at least you're in good company. Yahoo
Internet Life magazine, in its March issue, takes a look in its
cover story at who is playing games on the Internet. Some of the
answers will surprise you. For instance, more adults than kids are
playing Web-based games; more women than men. And the kind of games
being played aren't the trendy ones. In fact, the article says in a
cover headline: ``More bingo than `Quake.''' While you're reading
the issue, take a look at a list of the 40 best free games on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Upside magazine, in its March issue, takes a close look at the
merger mania of the Internet. Inspired by the planned America
Online-Time Warner merger, the magazine decides that it's one thing
to buy a presence on the Internet but that ``getting out with the
loot is quite another.''
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   The hackers who brought Yahoo, CNN.com and eBay to their knees
did it by literally taking over home PCs belonging to unwitting
users. The problem is that most home users don't have any security
at all while logged on to the Internet. It's easy, even for a
novice hacker, to break into these machines. Businesses and
government use software programs called firewalls to protect their
networks. Obviously, firewalls don't always keep hackers out but
are better than nothing. If you'd like to download a free firewall
program, go to www
</P>
<P>
   .zonelabs.com and look for ZoneAlarm 2.0. Not only will it help
protect your computer, it will tell you if someone tries to break
in.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to hear some of the inside gossip from newsrooms
and TV stations, it isn't necessary to find a local hangout for
newspeople. Instead, there is a Web site that circulates the latest
gossip _ complaints and the rumors that never make it on the air or
into print. You can find the site, called Jim Romenesko's Media
News, at www.poynter.org/medianews.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   If you're preparing to upgrade your PC from Windows 95 to
Windows 98, you may have some fears about the things that can go
wrong. Usually, it's an easy and painless task. But, if you worry,
there is a program called UpgradeAID 98 that serves as a safety
net. You'll pay about $30 in most retail stores, and the program
comes with a $5 off coupon for the purchase of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   For the typing-impaired, a program called QuicKeys for Windows,
also about $30, helps automate many typing tasks. You'll save
frequently used phrases and words in tiny programs called macros
that can be played back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
