<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-REPORT0229-COX     02-28 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT0229-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lab wants to clone your pet
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technological innovation usually is about making
something better. E-mail is a faster way to get a letter to and
from someone. E-commerce, really, is just shopping from a Web site;
it is the catalog's son, the popular one who spends all his free
time at his computer.
</P>
<P>
   But ever so often, something comes along that promises to do
something truly remarkable: to create.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Genetic Savings &AMP; Clone want to offer people the
chance to clone their pets. It is unclear when _ or if _ they will
be able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   For now, they're trying to clone Missy, a mutt that is part
border collie, part Siberian husky. Missy's owners gave Texas A&AMP;M
University $2.3 million to start the Missyplicity Project, an
attempt to clone their dog. Information about the effort can be
read at www.missyplicity.com.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the scientists working to clone Missy said
they had formed a separate company to store the genes of other
people's pets using the same technique developed on the Missy
project.
</P>
<P>
   The company will store DNA on other species as well, including
livestock.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure can be performed on live animals as well as ones
recently deceased. The company stores the DNA at two places; one is
a backup in the event of a fire or natural disaster. The storage
tanks have alarm monitors and, eventually, the company hopes to
make them available for viewing via a Web site camera. The yearly
maintenance fees range from $100 to $150. The first year's
maintenance is included in the initial service fee.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in carbon-copying your cat or dog, you'll
have to wait until the technique is improved. In the meantime, the
folks at GSC (www.savingsandclone.com) have provided answers to a
few basic questions about removing and storing pet DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does gene banking hurt the animal?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``No. The procedure is done under general anesthesia _ by
your own veterinarian in his/her office. When the animal awakens,
it will have two small stitched areas _ one in the abdomen and one
in the mouth. Animals can be a bit 'woozy' when recovering from
general anesthesia, but we have not observed any discomfort after
that. ... For most animals, the worst part about having stitches
removed is being in the veterinarian's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much does it cost to gene bank an animal's DNA at GSC?
</P>
<P>
   A:''We offer four grades of service, starting at $1,000,
depending mainly on how quickly you need the work done. ... GSC's
Gene Banking services do NOT include the cost of tissue sampling to
extract the DNA _ a procedure that is performed (and billed) by
your veterinarian, using resources supplied by GSC. The fee for
this service is between you and your veterinarian, but for
comparison purposes, the cost for tissue sampling at the Texas A&AMP;M
Small Animal Clinic ranges from $100 to $700, depending on the
condition of the animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long after death can you obtain viable DNA?
</P>
<P>
   A:''After numerous experiments and actual post-mortem jobs, we
are currently setting the limit for extraction of viable DNA
following death at seven days, regardless of how the body has been
preserved. Please be aware that the actual limit can be much
shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   How long can DNA last when stored using your methods?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no known limit. Cellular DNA stored in liquid
nitrogen has been regrown after decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When pet cloning is possible, how much will it cost?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``It's difficult to say. We are spending over $2.3 million
cloning Missy. We're certain that as soon as we're successful,
we'll be able to offer this service commercially at a small
fraction of what it cost to clone Missy. However, even a small
fraction of millions of dollars could still be a large sum for the
average consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless, we expect the price to drop quickly as our
techniques improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
