 &HT;    A taxi driver serves up sci-fi fare
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Every now and then you run across a piece of
science fiction that ascends the piles of books about aliens and
space travel, stands atop and calls attention to itself. Charles
Clotfelter's We Aquatus ($27, www. area51pub.com) is such a book.
Clotfelter is a taxi driver in Las Vegas and an author on the side.
His book details a race of aliens who have been living on Earth for
thousands of years and have recently decided to announce
themselves. The book, which blends philosophy and history into a
seamless tome, is fresh, lively and thought-provoking. Especially
satisfying is the exciting denouement. This is a great fireside,
weekend read. And to help you see your books while reading by the
fire, might we suggest the newest in book lights. The Fliplite
Junior ($10, www. BarnesandNoble.com) is a compact, folding book
light you can take just about anywhere. The light clips onto the
back of the book and works well with hardbacks and paperbacks.
You'll also look up-to-the-minute when you use the light: It comes
in a fashionable salmon color with a yellow plastic cover for the
light.
</P>
