r l BC-NETWATCH0229-COX     02-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0229-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media buzz sends Smoking Gun digging for obscure documents
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the world, or at least the portion of it that
watches the Fox network, was wondering if the hapless marriage
between multimillionaire Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger was going
to last as long as the TV show did, the Smoking Gun Web site was
busy checking out the facts.
</P>
<P>
   They found out that Rockwell, with an estimated net worth of
about $2 million, also had a restraining order placed on him by a
former girlfriend nine years ago. According to the public court
documents Smoking Gun obtained, the girlfriend, Debbie Goyne, told
the court that Rockwell would ``find her and kill her.'' All of the
offical documents are posted for anyone to see on the TSG Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of this sordid story is old news now. NBC's
``Dateline'' interviewed Rockwell, who said he and Ms. Conger are
probably not going to grow old together.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about millionaires getting hitched on national TV.
It's about the Web site that's in the business of ferreting out
legal documents of all kinds _ scholars call them primary source
materials _ on the Web for anyone with an interest in current
events or pop culture to look at.
</P>
<P>
   This Web site should not be confused with Matt Drudge's Drudge
Report (www.drudgereport.com). Drudge relies on tipsters and
disgruntled employees faxing documents to him under cover of night.
Smoking Gun (www.thesmokinggun.com) practices online enterprise
journalism the old-fashioned way. They dig for it. They comb police
files, court records and anything else they can get access to. They
do research that's entirely legal, and the information obtained and
posted on their site is available to anybody who has the
inclination to look.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking Gun specializes in posting exclusive documents,
described as ``cool, confidential and quirky.'' The documents and
articles posted on the site come from a wide variety of government
and law enforcement sources via Freedom of Information Act requests
for public documents that the law requires be made available.
Furthermore, Smoking Gun guarantees that all the news and documents
it posts are the real deal _ 100 percent authentic. A notice on the
site reads, ``The Smoking Gun is a Pierre Salinger-free zone'' _ a
cheeky reference to Salinger's 1996 touting of a document claiming
a U.S. Navy missile shot down TWA Flight 800 that turned out to be
nothing more than an Internet rumor making the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   What Smoking Gun typically comes up with is the kind of ``gee
whiz'' documents that you didn't know existed, and if you did know
they existed, you'd never know where or perhaps even how to track
them down.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to uncovering a variety of documents related to the
TV wedding, Smoking Gun also looks into more serious issues such as
the fate of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy whose flight
to America has triggered a bitter custody fight between the
American and Cuban governments.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documents on Smoking Gun are rough going _ wading
through court papers requiring Gonzalez to appear before a U.S.
judge isn't as scintillating as restraining orders against
millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking Gun specializes in debunking rumors, hearsay and hype.
When the Andy Kaufman bio-pic opened in December, rumors started
circulating on the Web that Kaufman had faked his death and was
probably hanging out in a bar somewhere with Elvis and other
members of the celebrity undead. However, it was the Smoking Gun
that actually did the legwork and found Kaufman's death certificate
(www.thesmokinggun .com/archive
</P>
<P>
   /kaufmandeath1.shtml) and noted sarcastically that ``in the long
and sleazy history of motion picture promotion, this is the first
use of renal failure as a marketing tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially poignant are the records Smoking Gun found
documenting a ``Real Life Private Ryan,'' who, like in the movie of
the same name, was a private who lost all of his brothers in World
War II combat (www.thesmokinggun.com/ryan/ryan.shtml).
</P>
<P>
   Smoking Gun makes great use of both its staff, which seems to
come up with the goods on the newsmakers and pop culture trivia,
and the Web, where documents can be posted and examined at leisure.
The site has made a nice niche for itself as a media watchdog with
plenty of bite.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
