<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What factors limit my speed on Internet?
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Could you please tell me the different aspects of speed involved
in an Internet connection, beginning with my computer/modem,
requesting a Web page and downloading something? Between port
speed, Internet speed and download speed, is there a way to
determine how good my connection is compared to a standard? Is my
connection faster than my friends'? I'm using a 56k bps modem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gordon Franklin
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Do your friends' computers seem faster? Maybe you should
be using their Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: OK, that's one option. Let's get real. There are tons of
variables. Speed can depend on your location, phone line quality
and how many people are hitting the same site and downloading
items. Even the day of the week and time of day can affect speeds.
No matter how good your connection, if the page is full of graphics
and colors, it will take longer to view. It's like driving a
Ferrari down I-75 at rush hour; you can't go full speed because of
the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Here's a way to check connection speeds. Most dial-up
programs will display how fast you are connecting to the modem of
your Internet service provider (ISP). You may have a 56k bps modem,
but it will make a difference if your ISP's modem only connects at
36k bps. Check your ISP's Web site for a list of modem numbers and
speeds. We checked EarthLink and AOL, and they have helpful
listings.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Is it better to turn off the computer after each use? When I
turn it on each day, I just leave it on all day. My husband says it
wastes electricity. Does booting it up a lot wear it out? _ Dorothy
Ringsrud
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: So ask your hubby how much energy the average football
game consumes. Don't tell me he never falls asleep in front of the
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: If you turn off your computer after each use, and you use
it several times a day, the repair bill for a new power supply
could be hubby's wake-up call. Basically, you are right. It's OK to
leave your computer on all day. The power supply takes a hit when
you're constantly turning the computer off and on.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   How do I get graphics and photos from the Web into my Microsoft
PowerPoint presentation?
</P>
<P>
   _ W. Steven Allen
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: It's a no-brainer _ as easy as copying and pasting. Any
graphic, photo or link on the Web can be captured by ``mashing''
the mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Are you going to explain what ``mash'' means? Steven, if
you're on a Mac, hold down your mouse button over the item you want
to copy. Right-click if you're on a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You will get a pop-up window with several options. Select
the copy option, go to your PowerPoint presentation and paste in
the item.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
