<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-28 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ENOUGH TO MAKE ONE LEAP FOR JOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time to break out those festive Leap Day decorations and
party like there's no tomorrow, or like tomorrow is a bonus day,
which it is.
</P>
<P>
   Leap years have been with us since 46 BC, when Julius Caesar
decided to reform the Roman calendar. Caesar's Greek astronomer,
Sosigenes, figured that the Earth takes 365 1/4 days to go around
the sun, which was almost right. In fashioning a new calendar, he
gave every fourth year 366 days, which worked, for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth century, the Venerable Bede calculated that
Sosigenes's year was 11 minutes and 14 seconds too long. Over the
centuries, the minutes and seconds added up. In 1582, Pope Gregory
XIII noticed that the vernal equinox had slipped backward by about
10 days. He decreed that the day after Oct. 4, 1582, would be Oct.
15 and in one stroke rid the calendar of those 10 troublesome days.
He solved the problem of accumulating days by ordering that only
centennial years evenly divisible by 400 would be considered leap
years, thus abolishing three leap years every 400 years and,
centuries later, tossing a wrench into computer codes all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first century leap year since 1600, which accounts
for the tremendous excitement surrounding Leap Day. You can feel it
in the air, no?
</P>
<P>
   Leap Day must be the least commercially exploited occasion on
the calendar. Where are the Leap Day cards? The Leap Day TV
specials? The Leap Day parades?
</P>
<P>
   Almost nobody observes a festive Leap Day except for people who
were born on Feb. 29 and the odd establishment that dares to
feature a Leap Year Ladies' Night, a bow to the old tradition that
allowed women to ask men to marry during Leap Year. No one seems to
know for sure where that custom originated, but it dates back to at
least the 13th century, when it was a matter of Scottish law. The
custom seems quaint in these days of no-holds-barred courting when
many women have no compunctions about asking men to marry, or
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   We could use another February celebration, February being what
it is. If they had to tack an extra day on a month every four
years, why did it have to be February? Why not August? Augustus
Caesar, for whom the eighth month is named, would have approved. He
fiddled with the calendar, stole a day from February, and tacked it
onto August so his month would be as long as July, named for the
original Caesar. Did modesty prevent him from adding another day to
his month? Or did he want to avoid offending the gods?
</P>
<P>
   As old traditions fade, new ones rise to take their place.
Commerce hasn't really neglected Leap Day. Businesses have noticed
that one extra day a year on the calendar means one extra day to
buy stuff. Here is a press release from Best Buy, which
commissioned a survey asking people what they planned to do to
``turn on the fun on Leap Day.'' The survey revealed that the
majority would turn on their fun with technology _ CD players,
stereos, computers, DVDs, and other gadgets that can be purchased
at _ surprise _ Best Buy.
</P>
<P>
   However, the most striking thing about the survey results may be
the proportion of those who responded ``Don't have time for fun
this year'' _ 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Leap Day should be more of a holiday, one on which we
could celebrate the mysteries of time and spare just a little time
for fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
