both common and uncommon. Whenever the subject of politics came up
in phone conversations, she hung up her extension and let my father
and I solve the world's problems. Alice Cooper Morse was the
daughter of English immigrant mill workers, and she inherited their
love of work and family. She sold her last house three days before
her heart failed, and had been tending to my hospitalized father.
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Even though the bride wants an
annulment, the groom was once slapped with a restraining order and
the prospect for a second or third installment is zero, ``Who Wants
To Marry a Multimillionaire?`` is a genie escaped from its bottle.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   RETURN-ADDRESSES (Lafayette, Calif.) _ My wife and I have
reached a glorious point in our existence. Neither of us will ever
again have to write our return address on an envelope. Should we
both to live to a hundred, we can write or type the addressee and
dismiss the return address from our minds. Because WE'VE GOT
LABELS! We've REALLY got labels. By KEN ALEXANDER.
</P>
