 (Repeating for all needing)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
  FEEL-GOOD STYLE MAY NOT PAY OFF    By L.M. SIXEL  c. 2000 Houston
Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Companies like to tout their touchy-feely sensitivity,
but evidence has surfaced that innovative employment practices
don't necessarily benefit the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, for example, have rushed to put programs into place
that turn managers into coaches and mentors. But Watson Wyatt
Worldwide, the human resources consulting firm, says this new
management approach doesn't have much impact on a company's market
value and, consequently, on shareholder return.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does conducting an employee opinion survey, said Ann
Venier, an account manager with Watson Wyatt in Houston. The Watson
Wyatt study that led to that conclusion looked at 405 companies.
</P>
<P>
   The results surprised William R. Bufkins, director of special
projects, including human resources, for Spacehab in Houston.
Surveys can be helpful in keeping in touch with what is going on in
an organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the people surveyed were responding to questionnaires
that weren't well-designed or were too superficial, Bufkins said.
Or perhaps the companies didnove its performance.
</P>
<P>
   Nice perks and a company being on top-employer lists also
attract top workers, said Kathleen M. Fenninger, senior director of
human resources for Enron Corp. It got 1,500 resumes the day after
Fortune put Enron on its list of America's most-admired companies.
</P>
<P>
   But it all boils down to creating a workplace in which employees
feel they're learning and being challenged in a cutting-edge
environment, said Fenninger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;  $$$
</P>
