<SLUG> BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP'S TENT FLAP MAY BE CLOSED TO SOME AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - What do `gooks,` Bob Jones University and the
Confederate flag have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Easy. An early indication that the GOP big tent is perhaps not
as spacious as one might hope.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with `gooks.`
</P>
<P>
   In a 1973 interview with `U.S. News and World Report,` future
Arizona Sen. John McCain used the word liberally, according to
press accounts.
</P>
<P>
   There's context. Five years as a prisoner of war in North
Vietnam will tend to cause some bitterness. So, though it wasn't
good judgment to use the word even then, we can understand the
feelings that the brutality of his captors might have produced.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1999. McCain, now a contender for the Republican
presidential nomination, still used the word while talking to
reporters on his ``Straight Talk Express.'' Others picked it up,
and the Senator has been scrambling this week to recoup, explaining
how brutally he and his fellow POWs were treated by their captors.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but if they were the senator's target, he used the wrong
weapon. `Gook` is an H-bomb word, loaded with offense no matter how
it's used. So, as they say in the military, there is now plenty of
collateral damage. This was no surgical strike. There are civilian
casualties aplenty. Heck, I'm not even Asian-American and I'm
angry.
</P>
<P>
   And that's because this is a word that, no matter how it's used,
tars an entire group.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the senator apologized, renounced offensive language
and said he would no longer use the word. Good, but there is
something else, besides remorse, we value highly in a president:
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy had a boat blown out from under him during World
War II and suffered a serious, lifelong back injury as a result.
George Bush, the elder, got his World War II Navy plane shot down.
I don't recall either one of them using the word `Jap` in public,
though they, too, probably had bitter memories from war.
</P>
<P>
   No, they had the good sense to recognize epithets.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is now a presidential candidate, and a lot of us would
have preferred he had the same good sense. His use of the word,
unfortunately, says something about him and his presidential
timber. Straight talk, OK. But if the straight talk is racist, what
does that say?
</P>
<P>
   On to Bob Jones University in Columbia, S.C., where other
presidential candidates have made appearances in the past. George
W. Bush was there earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   This is no ordinary university. It lost its tax-exempt status in
the '70s because it wouldn't admit Black students. At the time, it
also forbade interracial dating. It now admits Blacks but still
doesn't allow interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. The Christian fundamentalist university has
espoused anti-Catholic views. The school's Web site has attacked
Catholicism as a ``cult.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones Jr., the son and school chancelor in 1982, had this to
say: ``The pope is the greatest danger we face today. He's doing
more to spread anti-Christ communism than anyone around. The papacy
is the religion of the Antichrist and is a satanic system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones, the father, said that God created the races to be
separate from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been backtracking ever since. He says he's not
anti-anything, has a Catholic (his brother Jeb) in the family and
that his appearance did not signal he accepts the school's tenets.
Instead, he was trying to sell it on his.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but his appearance gives the school, and by extension its
views, legitimacy. If the governor had used the opportunity to make
a major address against racism and for religious tolerance, that
would be one thing. He didn't. It was a stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very simple. He needed the social conservatives for
that South Carolina win. The word for that is `pandering.`
</P>
<P>
   So now I'm left wondering precisely where is the compassionate
part of that compassionate conservatism of his?
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the Confederate flag, still flying proudly
over the state capitol in South Carolina. And that, according to
Bush and McCain, is just fine with them.
</P>
<P>
   This too is simple. That flag, flown in a war the South waged
partly to preserve the evil known as slavery, is a symbol of
hatred. Both candidates should have said so. They didn't. Decency
demanded they should have. Unfortunately, politics often trumps
decency. (Note to Gov. Bush: The flag doesn't belong over any
public building in Texas either).
</P>
<P>
   So, what about this GOP Big Tent? Well, so far the two leading
contenders for ringmaster are telling me that what they have in
mind for me and people like me is the back row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
