<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STICK TO SIMPLE LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEN ALENANDER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My wife and I have reached a glorious point in
our existence.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of us will ever again have to write our return address
on an envelope. Should we both to live to be 100, we can write or
type the addressee and dismiss the return address from our minds.
</P>
<P>
   Why? you ask. Because we have labels!
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure everybody gets these little return labels from ``do
gooder'' organizations once in a while, but I'll wager few folks
are as inundated as we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do gooder'' is a pejorative tag. I prefer ``charitable.'' But
it is proof that everybody in the money-seeking trade _ for-profit,
nonprofit or what have you _ swaps sucker lists.
</P>
<P>
   We're swimming in these little gifts because we support, in a
very modest way, certain well-intentioned and beneficial groups.
Just a small donation here and there in the hope that it'll further
the good work we have heard they do. Those we support respond with
thanks and a new supply of labels; they also must alert every
organization with any charitable connection that here's a live one.
</P>
<P>
   In case you'd like to amass your own supply of labels, here is a
list of the ones we have crammed into a large plastic bag: National
Foundation for Cancer Research, Teach Tolerance, Southern Poverty
Law Center, Habitat For Humanity, Paralyzed Veterans of America,
Cystic Fibrosis Foundation, National Wildlife Federation, World
Wildlife Federation, Wildlife Land Trust, Marine Mammal Center,
Defenders of Wildlife, World Wildlife Fund, Shriners Hospital,
American Diabetes Association, Doctors Without Borders, American
Bible Society, Rainforest Action Network, Wilderness Society,
American Cancer Society, National Parks Trust, National Parks and
Conservation Association, Center for Marine Conservation, USO,
National Audubon Society and seven others who don't have their
names on the labels, just ours.
</P>
<P>
   Also, we don't have just one batch from each. Some, especially
the wildlife-related groups, send a new offering every few months.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, we don't donate to all these groups; if we did, we
couldn't afford to eat. We support perhaps six or seven,
intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   Choice of the labels we actually use depends on the design and
whether they are for either one or both of us. The flow swells
around Christmastime, with all sorts of seasonal designs. This
makes them useful for addressing greeting cards, but eliminates
them from the active list for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   So here are a couple of suggestions for you label-sending
organizations. Not that we will cough up additional contributions,
but we might use your labels over others. Hence, they'll be seen by
more people who might send you a buck or two and then you can put
them on your mailing list:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make your label attractive but not garish.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have to include your name, make it unobtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go easy on the Christmas motif; it has a short shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   _ If possible, make your label a bit larger than the standard
5/8 x 2 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't send too many. Thirty or so at a time is enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ,
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Alexander, now retired, was an editorial cartoonist for the
San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
