<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO WANTS TO BE A SLEAZEBALL? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ the bride wants an annulment, the groom was once
slapped with a restraining order and the prospect for a second or
third installment is zero, ``Who Wants To Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' is a genie escaped from its bottle.
</P>
<P>
   After all, some 14 million people tuned in to Fox TV in early
February to watch 50 women parade in front of an alleged
multimillionaire, who then picked one dame and married her in an
on-air civil ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more folks have made red-hot properties of the three
new ``greed shows,'' including ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire?''
And they've spawned several ``reality'' game competitions, such as
a ``Lord of the Flies'' show called ``Survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can possibly believe that good taste, restraint or (please)
morality will win out over the prospect of 14 million viewers? How
hard is it to imagine the following in the old cable TV creative
pipeline right now:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Who Wants To Be a Hooker?,'' followed by ``Who Wants To Be a
Pimp?'' (Wednesdays, 8 and 8:30 p.m., E!).
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Randy Thornhill and Craig T. Palmer, authors of ``A
Natural History of Rape: Biological Bases of Sexual Coercion,''
this double bill is broadcast live each week from a different
Nevada brothel. (Like gambling, prostitution is legal in Nevada.)
</P>
<P>
   To qualify as a contestant, wannabe hookers must establish their
amateur status by proving they have never taken actual money in
exchange for sex. Responsible for their own make-up, clothing and
line of dirty talk, they audition before a co-ed panel of real
madames and ``frequent-flyer'' johns.
</P>
<P>
   The winner gets her own room for a night at the brothel with a
full load of clients and lunch with Hugh Grant.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30, the tables turn and a panel of veteran prostitutes
selects the one man who manages to persuade them to give him most
of their earnings. (No on-air drug use or physical violence
permitted.) Mr. Pimp-for-a-Night gets to choose three regular
employees of the brothel, keep 75 percent of whatever they are paid
for a month, and drive off in a pre-owned but mint-condition, gold
Mercedes Benz.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Who Wants To (Bleep) Tonya Harding?'' (Saturdays, 4 p.m.,
ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from the rapidly growing pool of people who have found
themselves on the receiving end of the troubled figure skater's
ire, contestants for this show can be male or female.
</P>
<P>
   The star-studded premiere is hosted by Nancy Kerrigan, Harding's
ex-husband, Jeff Gillooly, and recent beau, Darren Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Unique to this competition, contestants need only show up and
explain why they want to (bleep) Tonya Harding to win the
opportunity to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And it's up to each of them to define just what ``bleep'' means.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Who Wants To Be an Executioner?'' (Sundays, 11:30 p.m.,
Court TV).
</P>
<P>
   Working in conjunction with the corrections departments of every
state that has capital punishment, this show's producers match
death row inmates _ whose appeals are exhausted _ with ordinary
citizens who harbor fantasies of murder.
</P>
<P>
   The governors Bush _ George W. of Texas and Jeb of Florida _
alternate as hosts, providing a detailed review of the doomed
inmate's crime and a tour of the specific gas chamber, gallows,
electric chair or lethal injection room in which he/she will die.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants, who have the option of appearing with a black hood,
get three minutes to convince the judges that they deserve to pull
the switch, even though they're not personally connected to the
killer or any victim(s).
</P>
<P>
   Composition of the panel varies from venue to venue but always
includes six maximum-security prison guards, three wardens and a
pro-death penalty politician up for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   The winning executioner collects his/her prize at 12:05 a.m.,
immediately after the show, and takes home a souvenir video.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Who Wants To Be Lolita?'' (Fridays, 7 p.m., UPN).
</P>
<P>
   With the very same care taken in conducting background checks
for ``Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire?'' this show's
producers promise that the so-called girls (or boys) being offered
up for underage sex won't really be children; they'll be at least
18 but will just look like grade schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring pedophiles will be able to view the ``kids'' _
cavorting on swingsets, monkey bars and playing hacky-sack _ from
an onstage automobile with darkened windows.
</P>
<P>
   Prizes for the winning contestant include a new wardrobe from
Old Navy, front-row seats at a Ricky Martin concert and an
all-expenses-paid cruise to Mexico, sharing a first-class state
room with ``Uncle'' or ``Auntie'' X.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-28 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN POLITICS, MOTHER KNEW BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My mother and I never talked politics. She was
the smart one in the family, the one with sense, both common and
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the subject of politics came up in phone conversations,
she hung up her extension and let my father and me solve the
world's problems. She didn't care whether John McCain or George W.
Bush was the least bad Republican candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't care who was a Republican and who was a Democrat, or
that I'd registered Republican to vote against Bush _ or maybe now
against McCain, who's beginning to seem the more dangerous of the
two. It was just her eldest son up to his usual stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, at least since Adlai Stevenson was defeated the second
time, politics didn't matter much to her.
</P>
<P>
   People mattered. As a real estate broker on Cape Cod, she worked
hard for all her clients, whether they were rich stockbrokers
buying summer homes or young people who needed a rental so they
could study at my father's beloved Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   As a broker from another agency said at my mother's funeral
recently, ``Alice made our profession look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Cooper Morse (one of the few people she disliked was the
male rock star who brazenly stole her maiden name) was the daughter
of English immigrant mill workers, and she inherited their love of
work and family. She sold her last house three days before her
heart failed, and had been tending to my hospitalized father.
</P>
<P>
   A friend found my mother dead with a New Yorker magazine open on
her chest. The cop who came to the house said she had died
peacefully. He also said the entire police force of Falmouth,
Mass., knew her and loved her.
</P>
<P>
   What is the world of politics and issues compared to that?
</P>
<P>
   My mother was political in one big way _ political with a
capital P for ``personal.'' She took injustice personally.
</P>
<P>
   As a scholarship student at Rollins College in Florida, she
worked as a nurse's aide at the local county hospital, and was
shocked to find that black patients were consigned to shacks.
</P>
<P>
   A drama major, my mother gave a speech protesting this
inhumanity, a speech broadcast over a local radio station. She was
called a communist. She went back to New England.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have to guess what she would have thought of John McCain
using the word ``gook.'' McCain acted as if it were a four-letter
word like any other.
</P>
<P>
   My mom wouldn't let him get away with that. She hated all bad
words, but knew that the G-word was far worse than the F-word. It
hurts people, not just the ears. That's unforgivable.
</P>
<P>
   My father is the political junkie in the family, a friend to
Roosevelt's brain trusters, a former Pentagon official under the
great public servant Paul Nitze and campaign chairman for the late
Mayor Carl Stokes of Cleveland. My dad is a great guy to spend time
with solving the world's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sense, my mother's life has offered me the greater
political education.
</P>
<P>
   She had the unpaid career that gave America its strength after
World War II. She supported her husband while he followed his
career. She raised children almost single-handedly. Any blame for
how we turned out is solely our own, now that we're past Freud.
</P>
<P>
   After we kids had grown up, I'm told she said, ``I want to have
my own life now.''
</P>
<P>
   Over my dad's vague objections to having a working wife (where
did guys get that idea?), she got a real estate license and soon
brought home her first commission check for $14,000. Suddenly my
father was a women's liberationist, and for 30 years my mother
never stopped bringing home those checks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she's still owed a few checks for homes she sold in the
last weeks of her life. She started a life of her own at the age of
48 and never quit.
</P>
<P>
   My brother and sister and I found old pictures of our mom and
placed them around her casket. The service was called a
``visitation'' because there were no speeches or religious
ceremonies. My mother liked things plain and unhypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone toured the pictures of the little girl with golden
bangs feeding her doll, the high school beauty acting in plays at
the Maine men's college where she met my dad, the young mother on
the dock holding her first son and his first salmon.
</P>
<P>
   There were all the stages in an admirable life, including a
picture with Lyndon Johnson, but it wasn't the political that
mattered. What mattered was that two kids from modest hard-working
families made a good life for themselves and did the right things
in trying times, with at least one trying son.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have to face the March 7 primary in California as a
registered Republican, which wouldn't matter to my mother. But I
don't think she'd approve of her son voting for either a layabout
like George W. Bush or a misanthrope like John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   So I guess I'm now a Gore or Bradley Republican. My mother would
just shake her head and wonder who's apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
