<SLUG> BC-NY-SHARPTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE LEAVES SHARPTON'S STATURE ENHANCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's the cat with nine lives. There's the phoenix
rising from the ashes. And then there's the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of another public figure who has not merely
bounced back from so many disasters, but bounced to ever-loftier
heights with each return.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquittal of the four white police officers who killed
Amadou Diallo and the case's angry aftermath, Sharpton has emerged
once again, and more than before, as New York City's clear black
leader, crying out with equal passion for justice and nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let not one brick be thrown . . . not one epithet of violence
come from us,'' he declared after the verdict Friday. While he may
not deserve all the credit for the peaceful nature of the protests
so far, few would deny him a large share of it.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from 10 and 15 years ago, when Sharpton made his
mark as an aggravator of racial tension in a racially tense time.
It is a far cry from 1995, when black street vendors picketed a
Jewish-owned clothing store in Harlem. Sharpton joined them,
calling the owner a ``white interloper''; a few days later, one of
the pickets burned down the store, killing eight people trapped
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Few thought Sharpton would recover from just two years ago, when
Stephen Pagones successfully sued him for defamation of character.
In 1988, in one of the most racially polarizing episodes of recent
New York history, Sharpton accused Pagones, then an assistant
district attorney, of raping a black teenager named Tawana Brawley.
Even after Brawley's tale had been discredited, Sharpton continued
to defend her and to insist Pagones was guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton had just finished a close second in the Democratic
mayoral primary when that long-delayed trial got underway in 1997.
He had considered running for US Congress that fall. But, as one of
his aides said at the time, the backlash over the Brawley case,
which ended with a verdict against Sharpton in July 1998, put an
end to that notion.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed a lower profile. It seemed for a moment that his
dreams of being ``the Jesse Jackson of New York'' might be
finished.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in February last year, four white police officers fired 41
bullets at Amadou Diallo, a West African immigrant who stood
unarmed outside his apartment building in the Bronx. Sharpton
immediately and forcefully stepped in to his customary role as
advocate and protest-leader, and he was embraced by Diallo's
parents as their spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He had tried to assume this role in a similar incident the
previous summer when a Haitian immigrant, Abner Louima, was
tortured and sodomized by a police officer inside the bathroom of
the 70th Precinct stationhouse in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, however, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani leapt into
action, appearing repeatedly at Louima's hospital bedside,
denouncing the officer who committed the heinous act, and
appointing a bipartisan commission (which he later disavowed) to
recommend reforms in police practices.
</P>
<P>
   After the Diallo shooting, Giuliani hesitated, withheld
judgment, and waited a little too long even to go meet with
Diallo's parents _ by which time Sharpton was already on the scene,
and in control.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Sharpton led one of the longest and most broadly
attended string of antipolice protests that this city had ever
seen. Thousands of citizens of all races, including prominent
politicians, marched on police headquarters and had themselves
arrested for civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani enhanced Sharpton's image further by waving the scene
off as ``silly'' and a ``publicity stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sharpton was looking like not only a local leader but
an international statesman, accompanying Diallo's parents to Guinea
for their son's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Many white New Yorkers, and many black ones, still hold Sharpton
in contempt for his past actions and for the streak of opportunism
that they still see in his current campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even his critics would not deny that Sharpton, at age 45,
is a political force and a player at the big table.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, Bill Clinton went to a Rainbow Coalition dinner and
denounced Sistah Souljah,'' Sharpton said in a recent interview,
referring to the rap singer whom the president criticized in an
attempt to show white voters that he was not too beholden to
certain blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Hillary Clinton and Al Gore both have to come up here and
see me. What does that tell you?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, when black politicians meet in Washington, D.C., with
US Justice Deptartment officials to discuss the possibility of
trying the officers on federal charges of violating Diallo's civil
rights, it will be Sharpton who leads the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   But the full sign of Sharpton's arrival came two weeks ago
during the debate between Gore and Bill Bradley at the Apollo
Theater in Harlem. Sharpton helped set up the event, the first
presidential debate ever to take place in New York's black
community.
</P>
<P>
   The moderator, Bernard Shaw of CNN, started things off by giving
the first question to Sharpton, who he said ``has played an
instrumental role in bringing about this dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton stood in the audience, to respectful applause, wearing
his three-piece suit and his well-combed pompadour, and asked what
the candidates would do to stop racial ``profiling'' without
causing an increase in crime.
</P>
<P>
   It was a subtle question, acknowledging that even unjustly
aggressive police tactics have contributed to a reduction in crime,
and wondering how to restrain the cops without unleashing the
robbers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate really answered the question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
