<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLOVER PLAN PUTS IRA IN DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I put 15 percent of my earnings into my employer's 401(k)
plan, with various matches from my employer. My 401(k) from a
previous employer has $135,000 in Fidelity Overseas, $4,000 in
Fidelity Magellan, and the rest in other funds. The former employer
has been taken over by a large corporation, and the 401(k) plan is
soon to be liquidated. I have opened an IRA brokerage account with
Fidelity Investments and plan to roll the 401(k) assets into this
account. I plan to be very aggressive, splitting the money into
about six technology and overseas markets funds with no load and no
transaction fees. I am considering Fidelity Aggressive Growth,
Fidelity Growth Company, Fidelity Overseas, Janus Global
Technology, Janus Mercury, Janus Olympus, Internet, Warburg Pincus
International Small Company, Warburg Pincus Japan Small Company,
Warburg Pincus Japan Growth, Matthews Korea, and Matthews Japan I.
What selections would you make? I plan to retire at 70.
</P>
<P>
   M.J., Chelsea, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Rather than choose from these funds, I'd rather try to
dissuade you from the approach you're contemplating. With your
focus on transaction fees, it seems your plan involves putting the
rollover IRA in some pretty risky funds, as well as trading
actively.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of high-risk funds and an active trading pace
boils down, in my opinion, to little more than speculation. Some of
these funds' returns are mighty spectacular. The Internet fund in
1998 and 1999 returned 196.1 percent and 216.4 percent,
respectively, for example. But with such results comes a lot of
volatility and risk.
</P>
<P>
   If you leave the $140,000 in fairly conservative stock funds for
the 32 years until you retire and get average annual returns of
only 10 percent, you'd have $2,955,928. Can you really afford to
risk that by fooling around in the very hot but volatile markets
many of these funds operate in?
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: Invest no more than 30 percent of the rollover
IRA in high-risk funds. You might begin by putting 40 percent in
Fidelity Spartan Market Index _ substantially a clone of Vanguard's
Index 500 fund, right down to the low expense ratio _ and 30
percent in Fidelity Overseas fund.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to pick funds from your list for the final segment of
the portfolio, I'd put 10 percent into Janus Global Technology and
10 percent in Janus Mercury and split the final 10 percent between
the Internet fund and Fidelity Select Health Care (one that's not
on your list). Fidelity Select has a 3 percent front-end load, but
if you do what I hope you will do with it _ hold it for a quarter
century or so _ that load will soon seem very easy to bear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to retire at 60. I am a partner in a small business
and earn $160,000 a year and put $34,000 a year into a tax-deferred
Keogh plan and a Roth IRA. My partner will buy me out when I am 60
for $250,000 in today's money, adjusted for inflation. At 62, I'll
have my late husband's pension, which will be $31,000 a year, also
inflation-adjusted. At 63, I will receive Social Security of
$8,315; at 64 it will increase to $25,694. I will need $111,000 a
year to live on. Are my investments too risky? How much will my
$760,000 come to in nine years with additions of $34,000 a year?
How much will the total be worth in inflation-adjusted dollars? How
much income might I expect with a 7 percent yield, adjusted for
inflation?
</P>
<P>
   S.C., Boston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You should be in very nice shape _ especially if you reduce
the risk. Your holdings would be fine if you were 10 years younger,
but since you're entering the period in which you should begin
getting more conservative, I suggest a number of moves, all
designed to begin the process toward a yield-oriented portfolio in
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math: If you achieve average portfolio returns of 8
percent and add $34,000 a year to savings, you would amass
$1,959,507 in nine years. If inflation averaged 3.5 percent, you'd
have about $1,438,000 in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   As for financial needs, again using current dollar values, from
your savings you would require $61,000 at ages 60 and 61, $21,685
at ages 62 and 63, $4,306 at age 64, and thenceforth $54,303 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   So basically what you are trying to work toward is a portfolio
evenly divided among stocks, which should protect you against later
inflation, and bonds, which would supply the lion's share of your
needed income. If half the portfolio were in fixed-income
investments with an average yield of 7 percent, that would supply
you with an inflation-adjusted yield of $50,330.
</P>
<P>
   I'd simply withdraw the extra $10,670 from the stock side during
the first two years of retirement, then replace it during years
three, four, and five, when your income will exceed your needs. If
the yield from the fixed-income portfolio doesn't quite fulfill
your needs after age 65, you could withdraw the yield (but not the
capital gains distributions) from your stock portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I use an 8 percent growth estimate because it appears to me that
you can greatly reduce risk in the portfolio and still comfortably
achieve your goals. In the process, you can balance the portfolio a
little better, getting away from the heavy over-reliance on the
large-cap growth and large-cap blend funds that now dominate the
portfolio. Now, the only fixed-income element is the 37.2 percent
of the Janus Balanced holding, which is in cash and bonds; that
works out to 3.6 percent of the portfolio. (That calculation may be
off a bit, because the fund balances you supplied add up to
$741,400 rather than $760,000; perhaps you forgot a holding. If
that's the case, I hope it was a bond fund.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I suggest taking half the balance in seven large-cap
funds _ Fidelity's Dividend Growth, Blue Chip, and Contrafund and
Janus's Equity Income, Growth and Income, Mercury, and Twenty _ and
transferring the proceeds to the bond side.
</P>
<P>
   With Fidelity, I'd put half of the money in Fidelity Ginnie Mae
fund, a quarter in Fidelity Short-Term Bond fund, and a quarter in
Fidelity Capital and Income.
</P>
<P>
   I'd move half of the Janus balances _ plus $46,120 from Janus
Worldwide _ and invest in a similar portfolio, with 50 percent in
Janus Flexible Income and 25 percent each in Janus Short-Term Bond
and Janus High Income.
</P>
<P>
   Thatr would bring the fixed-income side of the portfolio
(including part of the Janus Balanced holding) to 35 percent. I'd
then suggest using your ongoing contributions to slowly enlarge the
fixed-income side, so that by the time you retire you have an even
balance of stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money musings: Recent letters have asked about building a
separate portfolio (in addition to regular retirement savings) to
cover emergency health care costs, instead of buying one of the
expensive extended health care policies _ in effect a
self-insurance scheme. One writer proposed funding the pool with
$25,000; another was planning on $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   I am unenthusiastic. Extended-care policies are designed to
protect against enormous, unpredictable, extended bills, and even
with a $100,000 investment there might not be enough money to cover
a serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   Self-insurance might work for a few _ people whose names appear
on magazine lists of the nation's wealthiest individuals _ but for
the rest of us, I fear, self-insuring is a luxury we can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
