   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-MILITIA (Beirut) _ Call it collective amnesia. Recently,
the second-in-command of the worst Christian militia admitted
responsibility in Lebanon's civil war, which began the same month a
quarter century ago that Vietnam ended. It was the first such
admission. By Charles M. Sennott. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Zimbabwe) _ Deep in Africa, young Zimbabweans
spurn soccer and cricket to pursue hoop dreams of their own. By
Kurt Shillinger. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-EYE (London) _ Riding the London Eye is nothing to sneeze
at, given the view. By Kevin Cullen. 835 words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-NEW-ENGLAND (New Haven) _ To the campaigns, New England
is viewed as a vital megastate, with 102 delegates, one more than
New York and an immense prize by any standard. By Michael Kranish
and Michael Crowley. 1850 words.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-PHENOMENON (Undated) _ John McCain is the war hero to
Bill Clinton's draft evader, the truth-teller to Clinton's trimmer,
the reformer to Clinton's special interest fundraiser, the adult to
Clinton's habitual adolescent. Al Gore, are you watching? By Scot
Lehigh. 1890 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAULTY-SUITS (Washington) _ The Pentagon says hundreds of
thousands of protective suits worn by military personnel may be
