<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-PROJECTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BIG DIG OFFICIALS, NOTHING COMPARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Hoover Dam was supposed to cost $155 million and
take seven years to build. Turns out, it was cheaper and quicker to
tame the Colorado River than most predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came in at $151 million . . . and they did it in five
years. Actually, four years, 354 days, if you want to be exact,''
said Pete Mayes, a guide at the Hoover Dam, the largest structure
of its kind when it was completed in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Bridge project was also on budget and on time,
completed in 1937 after about four years of laboring. The cost: $35
million, not counting the $39 million in bond interest, all
financed with tolls.
</P>
<P>
   One may not think such fast, frugal construction projects _ born
of the Depression-era when workers formed lines to be chosen for
jobs and their bosses made them toil harder and faster to trim
payroll costs _ could be accomplished today, especially as cost
estimates for the Big Dig climb over $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Just to plan and approve earthquake-proofing additions to the
famous San Francisco Bay span took nine years, and the job itself,
which began in 1997, is budgeted at $300 million. ``The
bureaucratic process,'' lamented bridge spokeswoman Mary Currie.
</P>
<P>
   However, the $20 billion Chek Lap Kok Airport, which relocated
Hong Kong's airport to a man-made island in 1998, was completed
largely on schedule. Despite tales of corruption and technical
glitches, the project also came in $1 billion under budget.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Boston's $12.2 billion Central Artery/Tunnel project
struggles with cost overruns and delays _ although officials insist
it is now on schedule _ engineers defend the Big Dig as being
unique in scope, scale, and complications, just as the Golden Gate
Bridge and Hoover Dam were for their time.
</P>
<P>
   Project officials say a booming economy, unforseen problems
underground, and the logistics of keeping a city running as
smoothly as possible while about 80 miles of lanes are built
beneath it, are what make this project different.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distinguishes this project from every other major
public-works project ever done is we are tunneling under an active
city through very uncertain ground. It's basically all fill,'' Big
Dig project spokesman Terry Brown said. ``We are finding out what
it costs to go through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Channel Tunnel that connects England and France _
also overbudget and off schedule when it opened in 1994 _ was
underwater but not under a city.
</P>
<P>
   And the Panama Canal project grappled with disease and a harsh
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took 10 years. We are taking 14,'' Brown said of the
Central America shipping lane. ``We don't have jungle, earthslides,
and malaria; we have a city, and we have to keep that city open.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, when preset decibel levels for
construction were annoying businesses and keeping residents awake
at night, Big Dig officials ``had to go back and customize noise
specifications on downtown contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   The project had to pay for such things as insulating windows and
building a ``noise curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   John Connelly, a Peabody &AMP; Arnold partner who specializes in
construction law, said urban construction is often more costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any project where you are dealing not out in a desert, but in
a city with all the limitations and restrictions that imposes on
you, it's going to take you more time and it's going to be more
expensive to do,'' he said. ``Often I view it in terms of the way
most cities and towns in Massachusetts are dealing with schools.
The time it costs to renovate a school that is unoccupied versus
the time and cost of renovating a school that is operating . . . is
going to be more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Less easily moved than students is the existing highway
structure near the FleetCenter in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The inverted Y-shaped bridge being constructed to connect the
downtown with Interstate 93 has a distinctive-looking cable design,
not simply for aesthetic reasons but because the current elevated
roadway is in the way of construction and must remain in place
until the new span is complete.
</P>
<P>
   In California, a difficult urban project had to be abandoned
recently. In 1998, voters, disgusted with construction problems,
cost overruns, and corruption dropped a $300 million-per-mile
subway extension in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Channel Tunnel, which in many ways is
comparable to the Big Dig in that both have had to move a lot of
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Chunnel, as it is called, moved 20 million cubic-meters of
earth and rubble, the equivalent to 14 pyramids of Cheops. The Big
Dig will have moved enough dirt to fill Foxboro Stadium 13 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Chunnel also cost $15 billion, nearly twice the estimate,
and was more than a year behind schedule, although it fulfilled a
200-year French dream of re-connecting the continent with England.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig, in some ways, could feel less historic.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Facts and Figures about the Central Artery/Tunnel
Project,'' a Big Dig reference guide, when construction is
complete: ``There will be normal urban rush hours of a couple of
hours in the morning and evening on the underground expressway,
with traffic moving at about 30 miles per hour.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
