<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-WORKERS-BOS &LR;      02-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WORKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CITES LACK OF EMPLOYEE TRAINING EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts is renowned for universities that educate
the best and brightest in business. But a new study has found that
neither the state nor private companies are doing enough to train
lower-skilled workers and help them move up to take the
higher-level jobs being created by a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of training programs for low- and middle-income workers
has also contributed to the gap between their pay, which is
stagnant or declining, and the rising earnings of college graduates
in management or highly technical jobs, according to the report by
MassINC, a Boston think tank. The report was funded by Mellon New
England, a unit of Pittsburgh-based Mellon Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is experiencing a ``quiet crisis,'' said Jack
Donahue, a coauthor of the report and a lecturer at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sunbelt states with expanding populations, Massachusetts'
population _ and workforce _ barely grew during the 1990s. As a
result, its pool of skilled workers has dried up and its
middle-class has shrunk in the midst of an unprecedented economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``States with lower living costs are doing a better job of
attracting new workers,'' Donahue said, ``so we have to make the
most of every worker we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor shortage is a theme that MassINC, which stresses its
nonpartisan agenda, has struck in prior reports. The newest report
attempts to explain the source of the problem: significant gaps in
training people who are employed but need new skills to move into
better jobs that are increasingly reliant on personal computers or
other sophisticated technology.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' community colleges are a key place to educate
workers, but the state's network could do more to reach workers,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``commuter colleges,'' notably Middlesex Community College
and Springfield Technical, offer extensive training for adult
workers. Yet, only 1.2 percent of Massachusetts residents are
enrolled in community colleges, compared with 3 percent or more in
California and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said Massachusetts government spending ranks
near the bottom for programs to help workers improve their skills
and pay. In a survey of 47 state-funded programs, Massachusetts
ranked 46th with spending of 50 cents per worker, on average, for
skills training in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Employers' own training programs are also lopsided and often
geared to employees at the higher end of the pay scale, according
to US Bureau of Labor Statistics data gathered for the report. For
example, more than half of Massachusetts employers provide advanced
training for their salespeople or computer technicians and
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   A much smaller percentage of employers _ between 18 and 27
percent _ train lower-level workers in clerical, service, or
production jobs who need basic skills such as mathematics or
computer operation.
</P>
<P>
   With the state's unemployment rate at 2.9 percent in January,
companies are under intense pressure to train workers they already
have. Some _ namely Intel Corp., EMC Corp., and Lucent Technologies
Inc. _ work with community colleges to create courses designed to
train workers, said Tom Chmura, vice president of economic
development planning at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But, even companies with big training efforts said it is still
extremely difficult to fill empty jobs. Economists believe that a
shortage of skilled workers has crimped the state's growth in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon said it funds a 16-week training program for prospective
employees. But the financial company typically has 150 unfilled
positions for accountants of all types and other work because
skilled workers are in such short supply, said spokeswoman Joannie
Jaxtimer.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura said that the state has an interest in helping businesses
train rank-and-file workers. Individual companies' decisions about
which employees will receive training, he said, are based on where
they ``get the best return.'' There is a bigger payoff from
``keeping the software engineer up to date rather than the
entry-level'' employee.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Massachusetts lawmakers agreed to provide $18
million for a job-training fund in return for reducing the
unemployment insurance tax charged taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   More could be done, concluded the authors of the MassINC study,
``Opportunity Knocks: Training the Commonwealth's Workers for the
New Economy.'' In addition to Donahue, coauthors were Lisa Lynch,
professor of international economic affairs at Tufts University,
and Ralph Whitehead Jr., professor of public service at the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   The study was released with an eye to taking advantage of big
changes in federal job-training legislation that MassINC said could
give Massachusetts more lattitude in designing the next generation
of training programs. In June, the federal Job Training Partnership
Act will expire and be replaced by the new Workforce Investment
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Under WIA, for example, new programs could permit employees to
choose training they feel they need, the study coauthors said. Or,
people who already have jobs could become eligible for training
under WIA. The JTPA job program, now nearly 20 years old, was
largely limited to helping the most marginal or unskilled workers
enter the workforce, sometimes for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Harneen Chernow, director of education and training for the
AFL-CIO in Massachusetts, said federal funds would not be expanded
when WIA goes into effect, however, setting up a possible
competition among more workers for the same money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
