<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-POETRY-THERAPY-ART-BO     02-28 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POETRY-THERAPY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 POETRY AT MCLEAN, FOR RHYME AND REASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERVILLE, Mass. _ In the fourth collection of poetry Douglas
Holder has published at his Ibbetson Street Press here, he includes
a poem of his own, titled ``A Simple Nod.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I saw him walking in Harvard Square,
</P>
<P>
   happily walking with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   As we passed each other
</P>
<P>
   we exchanged a simple, understated nod.
</P>
<P>
   Our silence was a friendly conspiracy
</P>
<P>
   a reminder of where he once was
</P>
<P>
   and where he was,
</P>
<P>
   now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The where is never stated _ although two words, ``the ward,'' a
few lines further on provide a hint. Holder, 44, is a mental health
counselor, and for the past six years he has been conducting poetry
workshops at McLean Hospital in Belmont for its patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been working there 17 years, and I'd had my poetry
published in small journals,'' he says. ``I wanted to add another
dimension to my job and help a few folks out.''
</P>
<P>
   While Holder would not think of ranking himself with Anne
Sexton, who won the Pulitzer Prize for poetry in 1967, he does
invoke the legendary poetry workshops she conducted at McLean in
the late 1960s. Sexton, a patient at the Belmont hospital in 1973,
committed suicide in October 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Holder claim that the hospital today resembles the
institution of those years. ``It's not like the old McLean's,'' he
says, ``with patrician types sitting around drinking tea from bone
china.'' That was the McLean of Harvard fullbacks, Porcellian Club
members, and ``Mayflower screwballs.'' That was the McLean that
Robert Lowell, a frequent patient there in the 1950s, memorialized
in his poem ``Waking in the Blue,'' and that Cambridge writer
Susanna Kaysen, a patient in 1967, recalls in her best-selling
memoir, ``Girl, Interrupted,'' now a major motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Holder says, the members of his poetry groups are more
likely to be the homeless, ``coming in with a bit of doggerel.''
</P>
<P>
   He runs two workshops, one on Thursday afternoons for patients
in the hospital's open-ward program, which meets in a converted
Victorian mansion, and the other on Friday evenings for patients on
the two locked wards where Holder works. Neither is open to an
outside visitor.
</P>
<P>
   But whether in the mansion or in the more institutional setting
of the locked ward, Holder says, ``I try to have sort of a
coffeehouse atmosphere. We'll have a round of applause when someone
reads a poem.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't always work out as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Holder remembers reading Allen Ginsberg's ``Howl'' at his very
first workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty enthusiastic then, and a bit naive,'' he says.
``I thought they'd like it. I saw the poem _ with its lament about
`the best minds of his generation lost to madness' _ as a haunting
cry that would be a catalyst for a discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, with some self-deprecation, ``I thought they'd
think of me as, `Hey, this guy knows where I'm coming from.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``they were angry and one of them walked out,'' he
says. ``And one of them told me: `Why do I have to hear this? I
live that life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Holder says, a young woman became hysterical and
ran out when he read a poem of his own about a kosher butcher in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that the young woman had a painful experience in
her life, which she associated with chickens, and she couldn't take
it,'' Holder says. ``I had a lot of explaining to do with the
clinical staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he adds, ``when you might hit a vein.''
</P>
<P>
   That problem is compounded, Holder says, by the fact that
today's hospital stays tend to be shorter _ a week or two instead
of several months. ``You don't always know what to expect,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that the workshops aren't quite the institutions
they were in Sexton's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get in their face about it,'' Holder says. ``I'll go around
to the rooms on my wards and ask: `Are you coming to the poetry
group tonight?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And sometimes, I'll have a doctor or another staff person tell
me that so-and-so is a well-known writer, so I'll make a special
effort to get them to come.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of poems written by patients in these workshops have
been published _ usually anonymously _ in the now-defunct Boston
Poet and other small poetry magazines. But not in his own magazine,
which shares the name of his small press, Holder says, because that
would violate hospital policy.
</P>
<P>
   Because he believes that poetry can play a healing role, Holder
started Ibbetson Street Press out of his house in Somerville _
naming it after the street where he lives with his wife, Diane
Robitaille, a poet and geriatric nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Holder, who got a master's degree in literature from Harvard's
extension school while working at McLean, had been publishing his
poetry in small magazines and especially in Spare Change, the
monthly journal for the homeless. ``I write a lot about
homelessness and mental health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting a small press to publish local poets, Holder says, was
``a way to get connected.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent issue _ 38 pages on 8 1/2-by-11 paper with a
paper cover, bound with a black slip-on plastic binder _ sells for
$4 and contains 40 poems; an interview with Ed Galings, an elderly
small-press poet; and several reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Among the poets are a number of first-time writers and others
described as ``mainstays'' of Holder's press. There are also two
professors of literature _ John Hildebidle, who teaches at MIT, and
Robert K. Johnson, who teaches at Suffolk University _ as well as
Don Divecchio, the poetry editor of Spare Change.
</P>
<P>
   Ibbetson Street Press has also published a number of chapbooks,
an old English term for a small collection of poems or ballads,
most recently ``Poems From 42nd Street'' by Rufus Goodwin, a poet
and journalist who lives in Boston; and a collection called ``Poems
for the Poet, the Working Man and the Downtrodden,'' by A. D.
Winans, who publishes a small poetry magazine in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distinguishes our journal,'' says Holder, ``is that it
contains poems that anyone can read.'' They deal ``with everyday
life. There's not a lot of arcane words or funny verse patterns.''
Anyone, he adds, ``can get something out of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
