<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-MADONNA-BOS &LR;      02-28 1854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MADONNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADONNA: STILL EXPRESSING HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madonna is curled up on the sofa in a plush hotel
room in Manhattan. She is totally and completely in her element,
doing what she does second-best to being Madonna _ that is, talking
about being Madonna. She is also in an unavoidably strange
position: chatting politely and smiling sweetly for people who will
probably be tearing her limb from limb in the coming weeks. But she
has come to expect this. Thick-skinned adventuress that she is,
Madonna keeps making movies.
</P>
<P>
   Her new film _ ``The Next Best Thing,'' a romantic dramedy in
which Madonna stars with her real-life best friend, Rupert Everett
_ opens Friday. And so, the 41-year-old icon is gamely discussing
everything from her psyche to her underwear. She is thrilled to
learn that the reporter is a music writer rather than a film
critic. The reporter is thrilled that there is no trace of the
horrid English accent Madonna often trots out for public
consumption. She fusses incessantly with her watch; it's the only
tic in her otherwise serene demeanor. Her hair _ perhaps the most
consistent barometer of Madonna's morphing incarnations _ falls in
golden, unfussy waves over her shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   This is Madonna, circa 2000: Cabala Devotee. Yoga Student. Very
Strict Mommy. She is tinier and lovelier and funnier than you'd
expect. Her bra is famously exposed under a striped silk shirt;
it's exquisite, covered in black crystals and beads, and probably
cost more than the reporter's entire pathetic outfit. This
realization is tempered by the even more startling observation that
the skin on Madonna's heels, poking daintily through the rear of
her spike-heeled patent-leather slingbacks, is dry and cracked.
Regular Girl Alert. Is it possible that Madonna really isn't so
different from Abbie after all?
</P>
<P>
   Abbie is the regular girl Madonna plays in ``The Next Best
Thing,'' which follows the comic/tragic lives of a straight woman
and gay man who conceive a child one depressed, cocktail-saturated
afternoon and decide to become a family. Abbie is meticulous,
self-absorbed, and love-challenged. Robert (Everett's character) is
witty, charming, and love-challenged. They are best friends. It
sounds, and is, like a not-so-distant cinematic cousin to ``My Best
Friend's Wedding,'' another gay-confidant movie starring Everett
and Julia Roberts. It also sounds like real life. Indeed, the
production notes prepared by Paramount quote the actress as saying
that she ``can totally relate to the idea of getting to a certain
age and not feeling like I had met my soulmate and being in a state
of panic about having a child.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
On Abbie and motherhood &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, you can't believe everything you read. ``No, I don't
really identify with Abbie,'' says Madonna matter-of-factly. She is
nearly always matter-of-fact, even when contradicting herself.
``When I decided I wanted to have a baby, I was in a relationship
(now defunct, with then-personal trainer Carlos Leon) and I was in
love. So it wasn't like I had a panic attack or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much more about Madonna's portrayal of Abbie that seems
misrepresented. But let's leave that to the film critics. There are
certain undeniable parallels. Abbie has miserable luck in love. So
has Madonna. ``I've made some mistakes,'' she says. ``Definitely. I
think I've passed some pretty incredible people by because I was
really selfish and whatever. I'm still kicking myself.'' And then
there are the so-called men who simply couldn't handle hitching
their wagon to the superstar express. ``I've found myself in
situations with men where, like Abbie, I've said, `Wait a second.
You mean if I had less to offer you I'd have a better chance in
this relationship?' There have been many situations where my
accomplishments and success have actually hindered the relationship
from taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbie has a young child. So has Madonna. Of course, the two
navigate totally different parenting scenarios. Abbie solves the
child-care dilemma by letting her son Sam help out at the reception
counter in her yoga studio; Madonna solves the child-care dilemma
by enrolling 3-year-old Lourdes, whom she calls Lola, in four
preschools _ in London, New York, Miami, and LA. She has a nanny,
too. But motherhood has a way of leveling the playing field no
matter what the tax bracket or celebrity quotient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be honest, there are times when I just go, `uh, I
can't do that because of my daughter.' I've turned down a lot of
things. I've given up going on world tours,'' Madonna announces,
bringing into bold relief the notion that sacrifice is very much a
relative thing. ``I don't want to make a movie where she couldn't
go to school. And I want to make sure that she and her father have
a regular and steady relationship. That's very, very important.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Balancing act &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman whose singular moniker could so recently be given as
the antonym for compromise feels, it would seem, as if she's made
one. ``Yeah, sometimes it does feel like that. I've given up a lot.
But,'' she adds, ``nothing compares to the rewards. I think I'm
just not as ambitious. Before, I said yes to everything. I want to
do this, I want to do that. I'll make a record, then do a movie,
I'll do this, I'll do that. You know I just can't do it. I can't do
it. I can't do that and have a relationship with my daughter. So I
just pass.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't expect Blonde Ambition Part 2. The quest
for notoriety won't be the defining feature of Madonna's future
that it was during the first decade of her career. (Although she's
adamant that having a child hasn't changed her feelings about
sexual and religious content in art: ``There's no way to avoid it;
it's a big part of be-
</P>
<P>
   ing a human being.'') She and Lola, who was baptized a Catholic
even though her mother is not at all sure how she feels about
organized religion, say their prayers together every night before
she goes to bed. These days Madonna gravitates more toward women
with children because ``you can pick their brains and complain with
them.'' Not that she's given up gay men, who constitute the bulk of
her social circle. Madonna expects to have another couple of years
of the good gypsy life and then ``throw down the anchor,'' for
Lola's sake, probably in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not confuse ambition with determination. Take
Madonna's film career, which at its most promising presented her as
variations of herself (the sassy, streetwise title character in
``Desperately Seeking Susan'' and the powerful cultural matriarch
in ``Evita'') and at its worst (``Who's That Girl?'' and ``Shanghai
Surprise,'' a true-blue debacle made with Sean Penn, her husband
from 1985 to 1989) was bad enough to put a stake through the heart
of a lesser icon's dreams. Madonna, being Madonna, perseveres.
Critics be damned. She wants to be an actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the creative impulse has to come from a selfish
place,'' is how she explains her willingness to keep returning _
perpetually smarting from the last bout _ to the ring. ``I don't
think you can begin by thinking how it's going to affect other
people. I do the best that I can possibly do, because that's the
only chance I'm going to have when it comes to audience reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Her chances with critics, she believes, are essentially
nonexistent. Madonna is rarely if ever, as far as she's concerned,
given a fair shake in the press. Suddenly her civil tone of voice
seems a supreme act of will. She folds her hands in her lap.
``Anybody who's successful in one area is given a much harder time
if they try to go into another area. It's very begrudging. Instead
of going `OK. God bless you,' everyone's like `let's just see if
this can happen.' You'd think people would be more encouraging
about it, about people being adventurous. But no. No.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Motivational matters &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems the right moment to shift the discussion toward
something more inspirational, such as where on earth Madonna finds
her motivation _ how she stays hungry in her head _ sitting on top
of the world? The question is accompanied by a coughing fit. The
reporter asks politely for a glass of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Madonna says. ``You have to choke.'' She is
matter-of-fact even when she is being humorous. ``That's what you
get for asking such a provocative question.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet she thinks about this for a good long time. ``I guess,''
she says slowly, and the rest of the words come haltingly, ``it's
all got to do with the way I perceive myself. I always feel, to
this day, no matter where I've been and what I've done, I always
see myself as this kind of insecure girl from the Midwest who
doesn't know very much and has so much to learn and so far to go
and so much to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna's music, and the stream of mesmerizing musical personas
she's created over the last 15 years, feeds off that insatiable
hunger to prove herself. The pitch of Madonna's speaking voice
rises when she starts talking about her new album, which she's
recording in London with electronica guru William Orbit, who
produced 1998's Grammy-winning ``Ray of Light.'' The new music
isn't as dreamy and ethereal as her last album, Madonna says,
although it's still immersed in electronics. ``It's much more
stripped-down and minimal, and edgier-sounding.'' Also working on
new tracks is Mir Wais, a French songwriter and producer who hit
the jackpot _ to say the least _ when he sent an unsolicited demo
to Madonna's record company, Maverick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it and I was like, `Oh my God! I gotta work with this
guy.' He comes from that whole French electronic world. He's a
genius, a real visionary, and I'm so honored to be working with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's music, and movies, a new David Hare play that she's
interested in, and her beloved child. She'd like another. Madonna
has a boyfriend _ 31-year-old British director Guy Ritchie (``Lock,
Stock and Two Smoking Barrels''). She'd rather not jinx it by
discussing him. No, she's not pregnant, as the rumor mills have
been declaring the past few months. Life for Madonna _ she's the
first to admit that this is an understatement _ is full. ``I never
know what to write when I'm filling out the card on the airplane,''
she laughs. So does the reporter. It's hard to imagine Madonna
filling out the card on the airplane. ``Sometimes I write singer,
sometimes I write actress, sometimes I write mother. It depends on
the mood I'm in. Lately, I write entertainer, and I feel like that
sort of covers all the areas.''
</P>
<P>
   There must, it seems, be a singular goal, a galvanizing sense of
purpose, that set her on this remarkable trajectory. If there's one
quality that defines Madonna, it's strength. But what, exactly, is
the nature of that strength? ``I don't know,'' Madonna says after a
long silence. ``Ask some other people.'' She sighs. She scans the
walls of the hotel room. She wants to answer this question.
Finally, she lets her gaze settle straight ahead. ``I'm
insatiable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-PBS-MITCHELL-BOS &LR;      02-28 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-MITCHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A WING AND A PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a scene from ``The Muppet Movie,'' Kermit the Frog and Fozzie
Bear are tooling down the highway, bound for Hollywood, when they
spot an oversized yellow fowl waddling toward them.
</P>
<P>
   It's none other than Big Bird, who (in the movie's plot conceit)
is an unknown, not yet the winged embodiment of the Public
Broadcasting Service. Offered a ride, Big Bird trills: ``No thanks.
I'm on my way to New York City to try to break into public
television.'' A dubious Fozzie wishes him luck.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pat Mitchell, a onetime Boston TV reporter who
became a documentary producer and CNN executive, will break into
public television _ at the top. Mitchell will need loads of luck to
go along with her undeniable skill, because as the first woman
president of PBS, she inherits a system facing what one of her
predecessors, Lawrence Grossman, calls ``horrendous challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS ``has to redefine itself in a major way,'' warns Grossman,
or ``be left for roadkill on the information highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it seems as if public television is always in crisis;
PBS is a political football that's been kicked around Capitol Hill
for years, especially during appropriations time.
</P>
<P>
   But friend and foe alike agree that this is a particularly dicey
time for PBS. The telecommunications revolution of the past few
years has chipped away at the very rationale for the existence of
public broadcasting, while measurably weakening PBS's hold on
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nielsen Media Research, there's been a 20 percent
drop in audience since the mid-1980s, and the average PBS program
draws fewer than two million households _ one-tenth the audience
that tuned in for that ennobling TV milestone, Fox's ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   For a system always vulnerable to charges that it serves only a
narrow slice of America, those are ominously low numbers. ``If
there were no PBS today, you wouldn't have to create it,'' asserts
Robert Lichter, head of the Center for Media and Public Affairs, a
Washington-based research group.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that a whiff of desperation comes from PBS these
days. Most telling example: Beset by funding pressures that make
merchandising spinoffs more important than ever to the bottom line,
the system that gave us ``Sesame Street'' and ``Arthur'' lowered
its standards to make room for . . . ``Teletubbies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``PBS is trusted by the public. They're supposed to be a special
station; they're not supposed to take advantage of children,'' says
Dr. Alvin Poussaint, clinical professor of psychiatry at Harvard
Medical School and a consultant on the Nickelodeon program ``Little
Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the need for money has escalated without a significant
increase in the funds they have available to them,'' says
Poussaint, insisting that Congress must shoulder some of the blame.
``Now, when they start developing programs for children, they have
to think about merchandising toys as a way to bring money into
their coffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Internally, many of PBS's 350 member stations are rebelling
against the parent organization's central control at a time when
unity is needed to coordinate the expenditure of billions of
dollars on the transition to digital technology. (That costly shift
will intensify PBS's funding woes). Some affiliates want to control
their own schedules _ in other words, preempt PBS programs for
profit-generating local specials. ``Their feeling is `I want to do
it my way,' '' says Peggy Charren, founder of Action for Children's
Television and a staunch supporter of PBS. ``They really don't want
to be part of a network.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, PBS president from 1976 to 1984, says the system is
also bedeviled by ``a lot of these bureaucratic turf battles (that)
end up seriously affecting the quality of what gets on the air.''
CNN's Jeff Greenfield, host of a new series of finance shows airing
on PBS, agrees that the system is ``all wrapped up in fights over
power and money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that they don't do good stuff,'' says Greenfield.
``But the thing I hear from people in public broadcasting is
frustration with the pace of movement, the decision-making process,
the fiefdoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration with PBS is not confined to insiders. The system is
under increasing attack for succumbing to commercialism by airing
``underwriting messages'' that bear a suspicious resemblance to
plain old TV commercials, and for deferring to corporate interests
with business-friendly programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``PBS has to move out of the business of selling audiences to
advertisers, get corporate influence out of the decision-making
process, and move away from commercialism and sterile insiderism,''
says William Hoynes of Vassar College, author of several studies on
PBS. ``They need to focus on their founding mission of connecting
to the public in ways that view the public as citizens, not just as
audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, from the right, the old charge of liberal bias _
which had begun to dissipate _ sprang back to life when the GOP-led
Congress discovered last year that PBS affiliates, including
Boston's WGBH-TV (Channel 2), were swapping membership lists with
mostly Democratic organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying problem facing PBS is one that all
broadcasters are grappling with: that viewers, diverted by the
shiny baubles glittering on the cable side of the dial, are
steadily drifting away. Since PBS starts from a much smaller base
than ABC or CBS or NBC, every nosebleed has hemorrhage potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with the Republicans is the easy part,'' says Lichter.
``Dealing with a 500-channel universe is the hard part. And
commercial television has developed an upscale division.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Everywhere PBS turns, it now finds an interloper
occupying ground to which it once laid virtually exclusive claim.
For instance, PBS once stood alone in offering high-quality,
educational children's programs. But Nickelodeon now boasts an
equally impressive lineup, with The Disney Channel coming on
strong. Even ABC is investing heavily in kids' fare.
</P>
<P>
   Serious documentaries? They're just a click away, on The History
Channel or CNN. Science? The Discovery Channel. A little something
for the culture vultures? The Bravo channel. Odes to our
four-legged friends? The Animal Planet channel. Public affairs
programs? Get real: Issues are masticated within an inch of their
lives on MSNBC, Fox News Channel, or CNN. Dramatic fare? The A&AMP;E
Network and TNT serve up plenty, and the most talked-about dramatic
program of the past year, ``The Sopranos,'' came from HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel will have none of it. As she takes over the leadership
of PBS, she is adamant that while ``there are cable networks that
do some similar kinds of genre programming . . . what PBS does is
unique and distinctive and different.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that few other networks can match the consistent
quality of ``The American Experience,'' ``NOVA,'' or Ken Burns's
epic documentaries. ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,'' ``Masterpiece
Theater,'' and ``Mystery!'' have passionate followings. Big Bird
and the rest of the gang still make ``Sesame Street'' a TV address
where learning is fun.
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard not to sympathize with PBS. The system is held _
and holds itself _ to a higher standard than the broadcast and
cable networks with which it competes. PBS is operating in a
marektplace that does not reward _ indeed, that penalizes _ classy
restraint. On balance, PBS remains, in the words of Marvin Kalb,
``an oasis of tasteful calm in a continuing storm of
commercially-driven pressures and programming.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is such a thing as being too calm. As HBO and Showtime
have muscled into the arena with ambitious, contemporary dramas
like ``The Sopranos,'' ``Sex and The City,'' and ``Beggars and
Choosers,'' PBS has allowed itself to still be associated in the
public mind with stuffy, British-accented period pieces.
</P>
<P>
   With so many options available to viewers, PBS needs to take
more chances and create more buzz about its programs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even while facing this urgent challenge, PBS has languished
without a permanent chief of programming _ the key link to the
``creative community'' of producers, writers, and actors _ for
nearly a year. Mitchell herself wasn't hired until four months
after her immediate predecessor, Ervin Duggan, resigned. Those are
symptoms of a system in stasis.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for PBS aficionados is that Mitchell seems ideally
suited to provide the shot of institutional adrenaline the system
needs. Traditionalists will like the fact that she speaks fervently
of PBS's commitment to ``education and outreach and public
service.'' The innovators may be pleased that with three decades of
experience in commercial television, and as the first TV producer
ever to head PBS, Mitchell will bring a set of pragmatic skills
that may equip the system better to operate in the rough-and-tumble
arena that is contemporary television.
</P>
<P>
   A top priority is hiring a programming chief. Says Mitchell: ``I
want to make sure the creative community thinks of us first, that
when they want to do their very best work, their most impactful
work . . . that they're going to think first about coming to PBS.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge that will define Pat Mitchell's tenure, and PBS's
future, is whether she can find a way to get viewers to do the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Don Aucoin is a Globe television critic.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1412EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FOOL &LR;      02-28 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FOOL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR INTRODUCES AN ALMOST PERFECT `FOOL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL G. PRAGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FOOL 
By Frederick G. Dillen 
Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill, 302 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guy who said that ``nobody loves a fool but his mother''
never met Barnaby Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   That he has been a fool all his life is not in question; it's
one of the first things Barnaby knew about himself. And the
evidence of his life has supported the conclusion: He never quite
connected with his folks, his marriage was loveless, and when he
not only lost his livelihood but was humiliated in the process, his
daughters showed they cared more about his money than about him.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnaby Griswold, so much the fool that Gloucester, Mass.
author Frederick G. Dillen names his new novel after this trait, is
undeniably lovable, even if it is a feeling that begins in
sympathy. Dillen introduces his character near the end of the
finals of the Winott Point tennis club championship, and Barnaby's
prospects appear bleak. He has never been much of an athlete, but
his suspension from the securities business has given him time to
get in shape. It has been a foolish goal, to win the trophy,
because even if he wins, his losses will be complete by the end of
the day. The divorce decree says he must leave Winott Point, a
North Shore Yankee enclave where he spent summers growing up, by
midnight. He's left friendless, jobless, loveless, and now
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, his fortunes in the match turn, almost in spite of
himself, and he does indeed emerge victorious. But with no one in
the crowd to play for, to share his win with, it is a hollow
victory. His fantasy of donning his championship pants, mingling at
the tourney dinner with thrice-divorced women, quickly grows stale.
Eventually, he is on a second-floor window ledge, hoping to hit the
ground just right for maximum damage, when the call arrives that
will begin his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It is the totality of Barnaby's foolishness that brought him to
the ledge, but one horrible episode was the catalyst. Five years
earlier, he had foreseen the drop in oil prices, sold short, and
made a bundle. It was just a good call. But flimsy, misleading
evidence surfaced, and then it was insider trading. He'd avoided
jail, but at the price of penury and public humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Dillen unfolds these two tales in alternating chapters over the
first third of the book. In the volleying back and forth, both in
the tennis match and between the two story lines, Dillen creates a
delicious suspense that many mystery writers would envy, and
re-creates it throughout. It is just one of the delights ``Fool''
has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Another is the deftness Dillen displays in detailing Barnaby's
makeup, and others' as well. Dillen sounds a scale of notes that
may be universal, or might just be personal to me, but they are
real. There is, for example, the conversation in his head after he
concludes a fairly successful date: She'd kissed him, called him
``Tiger,'' and volunteered her phone number, even though she'd be
leaving town and was uncertain about her return. Before he can even
leave the lot where they part, he has convinced himself that she
never wants to see him again: ``This was what they told you when
they didn't want you. This was what they'd told Barnaby always.
Except for (his wife) Win who'd made an honest mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd first spoken to the woman, a waitress, as she cleaned him
up from a beating he'd taken at the hands of men who'd lost
everything, while he made a killing. He knew immediately: ``He
wanted to court this lovely girl for real, but he was a fat boy.''
He hadn't been a boy for decades, and he was in the best shape of
his life, but in the presence of a pretty girl, he is still fat in
his head.
</P>
<P>
   And Dillen is no more on target than when he tells one of
Barnaby's deepest truths: ``He felt as if all his victories were
ridiculous and his failures were true. It was a way he'd often
felt. That was who he was.'' We have met the enemy, and he lives
inside; how could we love him not?
</P>
<P>
   It would be overstating it to say that this is the perfect
``Fool.'' Dillen can ruminate too long, to the point of provoking
impatience. And sometimes his devices can confuse: Near the end,
for example, when he serves another volley of concurrent story
lines in alternating chapters, it is only annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, the whole of ``Fool'' is just like the fool
within: flawed, but entirely lovable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
