<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      02-28 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH, ENGLAND: LAND OF MYSTERY AND MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somehow being in England makes mystery and detective fiction
seem so much more important. The Agatha Christie industry alone
would float the economy of many a small nation. ``The Mousetrap,''
her legendary play, is not only a classic but now ``a landmark'' in
its 48th year, still showing eight times a week in London.
</P>
<P>
   English Heritage includes tours of places in southwest England
associated with her books. And one finds, even on a wet and
miserable day, one or two people moving about in the churchyard at
Cholsey in search of her grave.
</P>
<P>
   A book I overlooked when it was published in the United States
in the fall takes on resonance when read in England in the winter.
I write of ``Skull Mantra,'' by Elliot Pattison (St. Martin's
Minotaur, $24.95), which I devoured this month with great pleasure
after having laid it aside only a few weeks ago in a different
edition.
</P>
<P>
   This is Pattison's first novel, though he has written on
international matters a good bit. Shan Tao Yun, once a Chinese
police inspector and now just one more cipher in a prison camp work
gang transported to Tibet, is ordered to investigate, and quickly
resolve, the murder of an apparent American near the camp. The
corpse is headless, and the man's death has defiled the area, so
the Buddhist monks at the prison camp refuse to work until te site
is sanctified, which the Communist leaders refuse to do. A
solution, any solution, is demanded of Shan. Yet, to his surprise,
he finds one or two honest bureaucrats who want the crime solved,
not swept into one of the skull-filled caves in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison weaves a fine mystery, with one or two good surprises
at the end, and he provides a surreal yet convincing backdrop to
the investigation by describing Tibetan religious practices with
great skill. Those in favor of more trade with China will think
again after reading of the realistically described human rights
abuses against the Tibetans here. Reviewers frequently compare a
new writer to Tony Hillerman: Here is a truly possible successor.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlock Holmes is also basic to the British canon, and Martin
Booth's biography, a little of Holmes but actually of Sir Arthur
Conan Doyle, is a sensible and very readable reexamination of all
that we know about the good doctor. ``The Doctor and the
Detective'' (St. Martin's Minotaur, $27.95) is the perfectly
apposite title. There is much here that would not have appeared in
such a study a generation or so ago, about cocaine and sexuality
and reading habits, and though I find Daniel Stashower's recent
biography of Holmes, praised here recently (and not mentioned in
Booth's bibliography) the better book, this one is a fine
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie R. King is not British, but the Oxford Times has just
referred to her as a local author on the strength of her marriage
to ``an Anglo-Indian'' who is here at Oxford, and her first Mary
Russell novel, ``The Bee-Keeper's Apprentice'' _ about the young
woman who eventually marries Sherlock Holmes _ is appearing
locally. Simultaneously in the United States, King's fifth Kate
Martinelli mystery is being published: ``Night Work'' (Bantam,
$23.95).
</P>
<P>
   Martinelli is with the San Francisco Police. King explores
feminist issues extremely well with or without Martinelli, who's a
lesbian, but I prefer with. A young Indian girl is burned to death,
and Kate is drawn in when an activist woman with experience in
India argues that the girl had been murdered because she was not
producing a male (or indeed any) child.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, men who have been rapists and wife beaters are
being found killed, a bit of candy in their pockets, and some
observers are inclined to blame the Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence, a ``gay/lesbian/bi and/a-few-straights protest group''
which has hitherto used ridicule and embarrassment as its form of
attack. King is very, very good at looking society in the face and
reflecting on the way it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Two other books fall short of these three but nonetheless
provide food for thought and enough action to keep one reading late
into the night. Ryne Douglas Pearson's ``Top Ten'' (Putnam, $22.95)
is about a serial killer who is, of course, mad and, of course,
brilliant, and who is offended that he is not named numero uno on
the FBI's most-wanted list. He works at being the honoree by
killing all the others, and though the FBI and the various local
police forces spot what he is up to, they seem unable to head him
off.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the descriptions are rather grisly, so Lise McClendon's
``Nordic Nights'' (Walker, $23.95) is a good antidote. Set in
Jackson, Wyo., in midwinter, this book tells of the theft of some
valuable rune stones, explores a bit of archeology, and has a
terrific sense of place. Too bad McClendon says the famed Vinland
Map is in the British Museum when it is in Yale's Beinecke Library.
I guess the British will still win every time when crime is afoot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robin W. Winks teaches history at Yale University and, this year,
at Oxford, and reviews mystery fiction for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
