<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-THOMAS-BOS &LR;      02-28 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-THOMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TILSON THOMAS'S EXTREME SYMPHONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Tilson Thomas is in his fifth season as music director
of the San Francisco Symphony. The partnership has captured the
imagination of a town whose heart has always belonged to opera; it
has also resulted in a series of best-selling, award-winning
records for RCA/BMG _ a situation in which Thomas and his band
stand virtually unique among American orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Now Thomas is bringing the San Francisco Symphony to Symphony
Hall, the building where he made the spectacular start of his
career in 1969 as a 23-year-old assistant conductor of the Boston
Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chemical relationship between Thomas and the San
Francisco Symphony. ``They play with enormous rhythmic propulsion
and security, a fearlessness about turning corners, which is
reflection both of my nerve endings and of theirs; it is a good
relationship. The players feel absolutely comfortable playing in
areas of musical extremes and everything in between, in terms of
dynamics and articulation, moving across the full range of what an
orchestra can exhibit. Because an orchestra is what it is, 100
people playing together, a middle-of-the-road kind of expression
can very easily result, the least common denominator. My process as
a conductor is about encouraging musicians to be comfortable about
exploring extremes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is pleased to report that the process seems to be
working. ``Our concerts are absolutely sold out and there is a
tremendous ardent furor around them that is a lovely thing to
experience. Our audience is very diverse and becoming younger. And
after the renovation, our hall is terrific, with a warm, grand
sound which deals a little more with spaciousness of sound rather
than specificity of sound. Few halls have both warmth and focus.
Symphony Hall is one of the greatest in the world but there is a
limited amount of sound it was architected to accept. But it does
mean that in something like Beethoven's Second Symphony you can
hear the scurrying 16th notes that follow the theme as something
more than a decorous murmur.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston Celebrity Series chose the most adventurous of
Thomas's touring programs. Arcadi Volodos will be on hand for the
Tchaikovsky Concerto (``I haven't met him yet, but he's a fiery
youngster, and I'm sure we can work something out''), but the rest
of the program is less familiar. Copland's ``Inscape'' was his last
major piece. The Boston Symphony has played it only once, under the
composer's direction, at Tanglewood. It opens with one of the most
astonishing chords in the repertory. ``It's one of those
Aaron-lays-down-the-law chords,'' Thomas says. `` `Inscape' may be
a 12-tone piece, but it's totally Aaron in every gesture and every
note. In it there's an issue of pacing and voice, more than in any
other piece he wrote; the performers have to realize a pattern of
nuances which coincide with the cadences of a spoken voice, in this
case Aaron's.''
</P>
<P>
   The program closes with one of the major works of Thomas's San
Fancisco contemporary John Adams, ``Harmonielehre.'' ``This was
written for the orchestra and I've been doing it for a number of
years; it holds up. There's a lot of phrasing to be done in it.
When I was first struggling with these enormous lines, I called up
John and said, `What do you wnat me to do? Should I phrase this or
hang glide?' He said, `If you want to phrase it, you can,' so I do.
We've worked with the sequences, with the breaths in the piece, and
made the music more specifically personal. Everything that can be
done to make the orchstra more luxuriously upholstered has already
been done. I am interested in inflections, in the spontaneous mood
and character you normally get only with a soloist, above all a
singer.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra has followed a big Stravinsky recording project _
which won Grammys for classical album and orchestra performance
last week _ with discs that will be devoted to Ives and to Copland.
``We are coming to the end of our contract with BMB but we are
still talking about things well into the future. We know we will be
making music in the future and making musical products, but how
these are going to financed and distributed will change. There are
experiments to be done and formats to be explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas devotes 18 weeks a year to the San Francisco Symphony and
otherwise spends his time with the New World Symphony in Miami (12
weeks a year) and the London Symphony Orchestra. He owns homes both
in San Francisco and in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The New World Symphony was created to help conservatory
graduates cross the bridge into professional orchestras. Players
from all the great orchestras travel to Miami to work with the
young musicians _ among the Bostonians have been Ralph Gomberg,
Roger Voisin, Mary Lou Speaker Churchill, Douglas Yeo, Ronald
Feldman, Harry Shapiro, and New World Symphony alumnus Keisuke
Wakao. ``Being in the orchestra is a tremendous experience for
these young musicians _ the average stay is 1.79 years. No matter
what you've learned in school, the profession is something
different; there are all sorts of things you really do have to
learn _ things they don't teach you in school. They have usually
worked with the same teacher for years. Now they encounter people
from diverse perspectives and with different approaches. There are
many ways to accomplish what you want to do, many ways to think
about music. This experience helps them musically, technically, and
temperamentally to work better. It is as inclusive as possible and
a great resource for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has done relatively little opera since founding the New
World Symphony, a choice he has made. And he does very little guest
conducting. ``I receive lots of invitations I wish I could say yes
to, but my other commitments preclude it. I would love to conduct
the BSO sometime again. Most of the players from the BSO of my
youth are retired. It was a wonderful relationship I had wtih that
orchestra, and it made a huge contribution to my life. At some
point I want to pay homage to that gratefully and generously. Now I
have to think about the amount of time I have left to do what I
want to do. I am very committed to my Yiddish theater projects, and
I am very interested in film and video projects, things that only I
can do. Could I conduct a terrific `Tristan' or `Invisible City of
Kitezh'? Of course I can, but it is very important to make sure
that you do the things that you uniquely can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what BSO managing director Mark Volpe and the search
committee for Seiji Ozawa's successor should be looking for, Thomas
says, ``It should be a total matter of chemistry. It is essential
for the orchestra to search for someone who has the temperament,
the personality, the possibilities for communication, to bring the
orchestra into a different place. It must be someone that the
orchestra finds comfortable and at some level different enough to
take them into some new, exciting and engaging place, and that can
only come out of their own temperament and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 55, Thomas feels his own Boston successes of 30 years ago
came about because what he was after was so different from what the
orchestra was doing under Erich Leinsdorf and William Steinberg. He
came from a family prominent in the Yiddish theater, and his
Thomashefsky roots are very important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra had been developed and inspired by Leinsdorf,''
Thomas says, choosing his words carefully. ``But it was constrained
spiritually. The rule was to keep within the box, and then I came
along with all my young enthusiasm and Russian-Jewish connections,
and some way or another the players associated me with the days of
Koussevitzky and Munch, when the attitude was, ``We believe in
this, so let's go for it.' Lots of the sounds I heard from the BSO
back then are still in my ears to this day. What I had to go
through as an artist was to learn to take this enthusiasm and
imagination and absolutely relentless and compromising ear for
emotional involvement and translate it into much more efficient,
specific kinds of instruction. I've held on to the ardency of the
early days, but I've become a good director who can in a very few
words focus on what the issue is.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is feeling particularly content these days because he has
rediscovered a calling as a composer. This is a new thing that has
brought him back to an old one _ as a young man, he had studied
with Stravinsky's protege, Ingolf Dahl. ``I have written chamber
pieces and two orchestra pieces. Last year I composed three song
cycles that took things to a more intense level. Now I'm writing a
new song cycle for Renee Fleming and a new orchestral piece.
Composition is coming more into focus, and I am getting much better
at disposing of notes that don't need to be there. What I am trying
to write is tonal music, but adventurous tonal music. The ultimate
test is whether I can sing it through in the bathtub from beginning
to end. Of course I'm not your usual bathtub singer. Years ago,
Oliver Knussen and I used to sit around and sing Stravinsky's
Aldous Huxley Variations from beginning to end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
