<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-EGGERS-BOS &LR;      02-28 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EGGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE THAT, YOU MEMOIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A HEARTBREAKING WORK OF STAGGERING GENIUS 
By Dave Eggers. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 375 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To call this book brazen is like calling a blizzard white _it's
true, but it leaves out most of the story. Dave Eggers's
memoir-maybe is a defiantly Not Tragic soliloquy; it's also hip,
funny, wildly intelligent, and as flushed with narrative energy as
anything I've read in some time. Eggers doesn't just send up the
conventions of memoir and commercial publishing; he stomps on them,
then tries them on as weird hats. By the time you've emerged from
the book's 40-page, small-font preface _ which contains tips on
metaphors, a note of thanks to the Armed Forces, and instructions
on how to get part of your money back _ you either want to kill him
or have him move in next door. No, never mind; that wouldn't work;
he'd be ringing your doorbell at all hours, wanting to use your fax
machine, blathering on about cultural imperialism or his old
girlfriends, or wanting to borrow your dog for Frisbee or a photo
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   You see? That's how he does it. You open your door a crack, and
Bam: His sensibility has found its way into your head.
</P>
<P>
   Its say-you-will title notwithstanding, ``A Heartbreaking Work
of Staggering Genius'' is, along with everything else, emotionally
wrenching, in part because of the willfully dry-eyed narrative that
delivers its central story. The third of four children, Eggers was
21 when his parents died from cancer, in the early 1990s, within a
month of each other. Eggers left college to go back to Lake Forest,
the Chicago suburb where he was raised; the day his mother went to
the hospital for the last time, he carried her to the car. When the
funerals were over, the kids split up the post-mortem bedlam: Bill,
the oldest son, took care of the financial decisions; Beth, the
next in line, handled the paperwork; and Dave _ who clearly
wouldn't have allowed it any other way _ got his 8-year-old
brother, Toph.
</P>
<P>
   So beyond its narrative hijinks and 3-D irony, this is the story
of a young man and his little brother: a child whom Dave Eggers
loves so fiercely and unequivocally that he panics when he has to
leave the boy with a baby sitter. All the Eggers children will
relocate in California, with Bill in LA and Beth in law school at
Berkeley and Dave and Toph hovering nearby, creating a domestic
situation only mildly more poignant than it is insane. Here is
Toph's schedule: school (religiously, but always late); Little
League practice (with Dave screaming from the bleachers with the
other moms); dinner at home (tacos and oranges, no frills, few
deviations).
</P>
<P>
   If their housekeeping wouldn't please Martha Stewart, it's hard
to imagine a child-welfare expert finding fault with the Eggers
brothers for their emotional milieu. They are Batman and Robin;
they are mother bear and cub. Trying his damnedest to spend one
night with a girlfriend _ Toph is sleeping at Beth's _ Eggers goes
home at dawn, just in case: Otherwise, Toph ``would know I had
stayed elsewhere, and would not understand this, and would grow up
to sell crack or sing in a harmonizing pop group from Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not worried about Toph, though if he ever gets too far away
from his brother _ the two have since relocated to Brooklyn _
boredom may prove to be a problem. Setting up house in Berkeley
also meant working, of course, and Eggers, whose background seems
to be a blend of art, graphics, and cyber-smarts, did temp work in
graphics design when he wasn't attending baseball practice and
parent-teacher conferences. With the dozen or so Chicago friends
who had also relocated to the Bay Area, he founded and produced
``Might,'' a smash-the-state periodical that wanted to change the
world but forgot to pay its rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Heartbreaking Work . . .'' provides a chronicle of these
first few transitional years, establishing a narrative scaffolding
from which Eggers can take flight: back to the bedside of his
mother before she died, back to the ``loud, semi-violent alcoholic
household'' of his childhood, back to the funerals where too few
mourners came and no words or eulogies would ever be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding within a hall-of-mirrors self-awareness and a kind of
post-Beckettian humor, Eggers's memories show up in various guises,
from mildly fictionalized interviews (an audition for the MTV hit
``Real World'') to occasional visits from a literary superego (part
muse, part snooty conscience).
</P>
<P>
   But these creative devices don't deserve much emphasis beyond
their narrative achievement: If they didn't work so well in giving
us Eggers's voice and story, they wouldn't matter at all. For the
most part, they work demonically well; this is one of the few
examples I've seen where a mind exposed to multimedia saturation _
to good-bad pop culture, rock 'n' roll, cyberspace creativity _
actually results in a superior literary narrative. It's a carnival
ride of insights from a writer who can be breathtakingly
articulate, and who (it must be said) comes off sounding like a
really cool guy.
</P>
<P>
   There's great potential for the opposite: It would be easy to
rely merely upon the brainpower and technique of ``A Heartbreaking
Work . . .'' and come off sounding like a jerk, filled as it is
with diversionary tactics. But Eggers knows when to get out of the
way of his story, whether it's the night he dementedly confronts
six people messing with him on a beach or the account of his return
to Lake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   What's consistent throughout is the full-throttle voice: the
sensibility of the man who grieves (and maybe loved and maybe
hated) his parents, who safeguards his brother, who knows that his
own presence here can walk the line between ``self-conscious'' and
``self-devouring.'' Occasionally you're aware that Eggers is
fleeing heartache by waxing manic, which can wear pretty thin; this
is particularly true when he's immersed in the story of ``Might,''
say, instead of where you know he belongs. But the last 70 pages of
his book have the momentum of an engine opened up on an empty road
out West. It's Stephen Daedalus bumping into Hunter S. Thompson _
Eggers the anti-martyr on a sunny afternoon, a moment of grief
caught in the hand, then transformed into something pastoral before
it's gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1418EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
