<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-VOICE-RECOGNITION-HNS     02-28 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-RECOGNITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE VOICE OF REASON MAY NOT BE HUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Humans have always hurled invective at
technology, cursing balky tools, snapping at telephone answering
machines, and sputtering furiously at the flashing ``12:00'' on
video recorders. Now technology is talking back, and it is being
much nicer to us than we have been to it.
</P>
<P>
   Because of amazing improvements in speech recognition
technology, you can buy a plane ticket or check a stock price
without talking to a living soul. Simply dial the right number and
converse with a human-sounding computer, a computer that never
loses patience, acts bored, or sounds like it is chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, for example, uses the voice of an engaging
young man _ actually a computer _ to provide arrival and departure
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal (is) to put the caller at ease,'' said Mike Phillips,
chief technical officer for Boston-based SpeechWorks, the company
that developed the phone-answering system for United. ``There's
been huge amounts of progress. Each year we're making these systems
and the technology better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Speech-recognition technology, which for decades seemed like the
backward stepchild of computing research, is starting to fulfill
its potential.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of a 100 percent natural-sounding conversation between
humans and computers remains elusive. But technological
developments may soon make buying a plane ticket from a computer
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dramatically different way of communicating,'' said
Steve Ehrlich of Nuance Communications in Menlo Park, Calif., which
has sold its own speech-recognition innovations to more than 70
companies in eight countries.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance developed the voice-recognition system used by Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co., the San Francisco-based brokerage, to provide callers
instant information about stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement about the technology is incredible,'' Ehrlich
said. ``Often I get a voice mail message saying, `Was that a
machine? That was incredible!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's no easy trick to create a computer system that not
only understands a wide range of human speech dialects but that
sounds helpful and amiable enough to encourage the caller to stay
on the line, rather than hang up in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The maturation of the technology stems from decades of tedious
research, nourished partly by innovations in fields such as
artificial intelligence and fuzzy logic.
</P>
<P>
   Even more crucial has been extensive, trial-and-error lab work
by human factors engineers who work with professional speakers to
develop computerized voices.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance has developed flight-reservation systems so sophisticated
that they can distinguish between similar-sounding words such as
``Oakland'' and ``Auckland.'' To avoid mistakes, the computer
always repeats what the caller has said, to get confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a U.S. phenomenon,'' Ehrlich said. ``The
technology has evolved to the point where we can not only recognize
different dialects and accents, but also the dialects and accents
within every language. In the UK, we can recognize the Cockney
accent or the Irish-UK accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Blade Kotelly, a human factors engineer at SpeechWorks, designs
speech-recognition systems based on several premises, among them:
The late oceanographer Jacques Cousteau's remark that ``The best
way to understand a fish is to become one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotelly said ``we try to get into the heads of our users and our
customers'' by understanding exactly how they might feel, second by
second, as they navigate the anxiety-inducing world of telephone
answering systems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would want to be treated intelligently on the phone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kotelly developed the United voice by working with people who do
voiceovers for commercials. ``The big thing for us is conveying
sincerity and meaning so that you'll think, `They're really trying
to help me out,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This entails filling the computerized statements with ``little
pauses'' and other subtle inflections to make it sound as natural
as possible. It is important, Kotelly said, that the voice not
sound imperious or ``like a radio DJ either, (because) very quickly
it sounds ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotelly definitely doesn't want the system to sound like HAL the
computer in the film ``2001: A Space Odyssey.'' HAL's voice,
Kotelly said, is ``a little bit subdued and manipulative in a
subtle way ... sinister. We want to avoid that sinister quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a phone system is sent to a corporate buyer, Kotelly
tests it on focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see their faces grimace we know we have to change
it,'' he said. ``And when we see them smile we know that we're on
the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the technology would deprive humans of jobs, Ehrlich
said the machines free people from the drab, monotonous job of
answering phone calls and allow them to tackle tasks that are
intellectually more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' he said, ``the technology is a `win' for
everybody _ for businesses because they save money, and for
consumers because they can get their business done far more
efficiently than ever before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
