   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Feb. 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-RIGHT (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ Sen. John McCain denounces
Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``agents of intolerance'' and
criticizes the ties that George W. Bush and Republican leaders have
to them. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline to kum) _ George W. Bush's campaign day. By
Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-DEBATE (Seattle) _ After weeks of smooth sailing on the
scheduling of debates, a look at why McCain pulled out of Thursday
night's debate in Los Angeles. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS (Dateline to come) _ On the two contenders: Bill Bradley
heads for California on the final day of his Washington state
stand. Al Gore is in Colorado, Arizona and California. By James Dao
and Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With Bradley photo, NYT3, and Gore photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NY (New York) _ Bill Bradley's New York campaign staff
is demoralized by his seeming inability to grab hold of the state.
By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   More to come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MOTHERS-DRUGS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to
hear a case from South Carolina over the practice of a city-owned
hospital that routinely and secretly tested women coming in to give
birth for drugs, and then told the police about positive results.
Critics say it amounts to an illegal search. By Linda Greenhouse.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-NAVY (Washington) _ The governor of Puerto Rico meets
the White House chief of staff and Navy secretary to discuss
implementing an agreement on the Vieques bombing range. By
Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   HSIA-TRIAL (Washington) _ Final arguments are presented in the
trial of Maria Hsia on charges related to her role as a Democratic
fund raiser. By Neil A. Lewis. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO (New York) _ Following the acquittal on criminal
charges, we look at the prospects for a civil rights prosecution at
the federal level against four officers accused in the death of an
unarmed man. By Jane Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DEBATE (Undated) _ A recent study by the research
arm of the National Academy of Sciences has declared that the
``apparent disparity'' between surface and atmospheric temperatures
``in no way invalidates the conclusion that surface temperature has
been rising.'' The surface warming ``is undoubtedly real,'' the
study panel said. But the dissenters are a long way from conceding
the climate debate, and they have seized on some other aspects of
the panel's report in an effort to bolster their case. By William
K. Stevens. (2075 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DISPARITY (Undated) _ Two skeptics in the climate
debate discovered that in some ways the satellite and surface
trends roughly matched. Both sets of measurements found substantial
warming over Northern Hemisphere continents, for instance, and the
timing of year-to-year temperature fluctuations was about the same
in both. But unlike the surface record, the satellites revealed no
underlying warming trend for much of the free atmosphere, up to
about five miles, mainly in the tropics. In fact, the raw numbers
showed a cooling there. By William K. Stevens. (850 words).
</P>
<P>
   For other ScienceTimes stories, see the separate science budget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TECH-WORKERS (Bombay) _ A growing though still modest
number of India's biggest American success stories, high-tech
workers whose lives are now firmly rooted in the United States, are
beginning to come home to India, and not just to visit relatives,
but also to start companies, invest their capital and indulge their
philanthropic instincts. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (New Delhi, India) _ The hijacking trial of the
deposed prime minister of Pakistan _ already a cavalcade of the
unexpected and the bizarre _took another odd twist over the weekend
as his entire defense team quit in protest of alleged government
unfairness. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (United Nations) _ China, faced with the Clinton
administration's determination to have Beijing's human rights
record condemned at this year's U.N. Human Rights Commission
session, is mobilizing its defense by using the kind of U.N.
mechanisms that can make it relatively easy to avoid censure when a
country is big and powerful. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-ELECT (Dakar) _ Results of the presidential election. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AIDS (Jerusalem) _ A storm erupts in Israel after the
newspaper Haaretz says that an idolized singer who died last week
at 41 had AIDS. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-EXTRADITE (Undated) _ The head of the House Foreign
Relations Committee is invoking a rarely used power to block $6
million in aid to the Dominican Republic unless it hands over a man
wanted in a 1991 murder in New York's Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-BANK (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Deutsche Bank has 1,500
local offices and seven million retail banking customers. They are
the biggest bank-branch network in Germany, but the network barely
ekes out a profit and consistently drags down the bank's overall
performance. Now Rolf-Ernst Breuer, the chairman of Deutsche Bank,
is hinting at something more radical: the possibility of giving up
a controlling stake in his own branches. Few analysts believe
Deutsche Bank will simply sell off its brick-and-mortar branch
network. But Breuer is clearly impatient and also seems convinced
that traditional banking is withering and radical changes are
necessary to survive. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CITIBANK-RETIRE (New York) _ John Reed announces that he will
retire as co-chief executive of Citigroup in April. Sandy Weill to
become sole CEO and chairman. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks again go their separate ways: at 2:20
p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 275 points. The
Nasdaq composite, however, was down 20 points. Treasury prices were
lower. European stock markets were also lower: London was down 1.69
percent and Frankfurt down 1.68 percent. The Nikkei closed down
0.49 percent; the Hang Seng ended down 1.26 percent. Crude oil was
trading at $30.05 a barrel. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-EARNINGS (Detroit) _ DaimlerChrysler reports
fourth-quarter earnings that are slightly better than forecast,
helped by sales of Mercedes-Benz, Chrysler and Jeep vehicles. By
Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   HONKGONG-TELECOM (Hong Kong) _ Developments re bids for Cable
and Wireless HKT, Hong Kong's flagship telephone company. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
