<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0935 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-LEAP-YEAR-BIRTHDAY-HN     02-28 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAP-YEAR-BIRTHDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEAP YEAR BIRTHDAY CAUSE OF CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: For a photo, call the San Antonio Express-News at
210-250-3297)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANIEL J. VARGAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Mary Medina will celebrate a milestone on Tuesday,
the day she turns 15.
</P>
<P>
   And in preparation, her closest friends organized her ``quince
anera'' on Saturday, maintaining the Hispanic tradition of
celebrating when a girl turns 15.
</P>
<P>
   But in Medina's case, the 15-year-old is really marking 60 years
of life that included marriage and motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Medina is a leap-year baby and technically celebrates her
birthday only once every four years, when February gains a 29th
day. So the quince anera had special meaning this year, both as a
celebration of an age milestone and her deep friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was so well-loved,'' Medina said before
Saturday's party. ``This has got to be a blessing from God.''
</P>
<P>
   Medina's party was something of the opening page in her life's
latest chapter. Her husband, Eddie, died in May, and she only
recently made the transition from lifelong housewife to working
woman. The party's theme was ``Friends and Butterflies Forever'' _
dedicated, she said, to the foundation that keeps her steady and to
the creatures that signify new life and adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm moving on and having a new life,'' said Medina, a
maintenance worker at the San Antonio Jewish Community Campus.
``Butterflies come out in the spring from their cocoons, and they
dress up the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad my husband is not here but I'm having to start over
again, this time without him. I'm totally in charge of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hispanic culture, it's customary to have a quince anera with
sponsors who pay for the celebration. Medina has the customary 14
madrinas who pitched in money for the food and the rented hall at
Holy Rosary Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Spearheading the party were Dora Lopez and Flo Maley. The
stay-at-home moms nicknamed themselves ``domestic engineers''
because they would shop together, baby-sit one another's children
and make prizes for PTA functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the real comadres,'' Medina said.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez recalls meeting Medina at a PTA meeting. Medina, who has
two sons, is the godmother of Lopez's two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a lifetime you meet someone who's worth any amount of
trouble and Mary is that someone,'' said Lopez, a close friend of
28 years. ``The blessings she has brought us cannot be counted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
