<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DEBATE (Undated) _ A recent study by the research
arm of the National Academy of Sciences has declared that the
``apparent disparity'' between surface and atmospheric temperatures
``in no way invalidates the conclusion that surface temperature has
been rising.'' The surface warming ``is undoubtedly real,'' the
study panel said. But the dissenters are a long way from conceding
the climate debate, and they have seized on some other aspects of
the panel's report in an effort to bolster their case. By William
K. Stevens. (2075 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DISPARITY (Undated) _ Two skeptics in the climate
debate discovered that in some ways the satellite and surface
trends roughly matched. Both sets of measurements found substantial
warming over Northern Hemisphere continents, for instance, and the
timing of year-to-year temperature fluctuations was about the same
in both. But unlike the surface record, the satellites revealed no
underlying warming trend for much of the free atmosphere, up to
about five miles, mainly in the tropics. In fact, the raw numbers
showed a cooling there. By William K. Stevens. (850 words).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DARK-MATTER (Undated) _ New conclusions about the nature of
dark matter, which makes up most of the universe, based on a
conference in Florida. 1,000 words. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTOR-ERROR (Undated) _ Doctors have amputated the wrong
leg, killed patients with overdoses of medications and committed
other serious errors for centuries. So why only now is a United
States president calling for the first national plan to reduce such
errors? The reasons behind the new concern are as complex as
medicine itself and as varied as recent changes in society,
including medical advances, greater complexity of care, increasing
challenge to medical authority and new techniques to pinpoint
sources of errors in the maze of systems that doctors and hospital
staffs use every day. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1940 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANT-GENES (Undated) _ An Australian scientist is trying to
reshape the tangled global debate over the role of genetic
engineering in agricultural biotechnology. He argues that the high
degree of genetic overlap among all living things suggests that
much of the gene swapping among species may be unnecessary.
Perhaps, instead of moving a valuable trait like resistance to cold
from a fish to a plant, genetic engineers could achieve the same
result by goading the plant into a mutation that activates genes
for cold tolerance already present in its DNA. By Barnaby J. Feder
(1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VOLCANOS (Undated) _ The Earth's habit of forever remaking
itself in paroxysms of fire and violence is sometimes hard on its
inhabitants, a lesson borne out again last week when villagers near
Legazpi, in the Philippines, fled eruptions of the deadly volcano
Mayon. In a new book, ``Vulcan's Fury: Man Against the Volcano,''
(Yale University Press) the writer Alwyn Scarth uses eyewitness
accounts to tell the tale of 15 great eruptions and of the people
who lived through them. Some samples of the work (1880 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT8,9,10.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on life
after pollution, desert locusts and the perils of garbage
collection. By Henry Fountain. (675 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-DISCRIM (Undated) _ An introduction to pro-con
commentaries on an executive order dealing with genetic
discrimination. (128 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-PRO () _ President Clinton's executive order on
genetic discrimination is a significant step toward ensuring that
advances in genetics will be to the benefit, not to the detriment
of individuals in society. To quote President Clinton: ``My goal is
to set an example and pose a challenge for every employer in
America, because I believe no employer should ever review your
genetic records along with your resume.'' By Wendy R. Uhlman. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-CON () _ President Clinton's recent ban of
genetic discrimination by federal employers is not in response to
any widespread practice, or even any collection of documented
cases, of federal agencies misusing genetic information. Instead,
the executive order responds to growing, and somewhat unfounded,
fears about the potential misuse of genetics. The main purpose of
this law is to calm public fears to spur development of genetic
technologies and help genetic researchers recruit subjects for
their studies. By Mark A. Hall. (1190 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ACNE (Undated) _ Medical science has now taken on the lowly
pimple _ and with unheralded but nevertheless fairly astounding
success. New treatments, some developed only in the last few years,
mean that pimples can be a thing of the past. By Clara Hemphill.
(1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photo, NYT11.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column: Doctors had
long assumed that exclusive breast-feeding for at least the first
six months of life and delaying the introduction of allergenic
foods like peanuts, cow's milk and eggs was the best way to stave
off allergies. But several new studies indicate that there are
limits to the long-term effectiveness of this approach for babies
most at risk for developing allergies. By Jane E. Brody. (1300
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-TRAIN (Undated) _ Sports-specific exercise used to
be limited to high-stakes, elite-level competitors. But now growing
numbers of recreational athletes, who participate in a wide-range
of sports, are hiring trainers to help them build specific muscles
and hone their technique to meet more modest goals. By Linda
Villarosa. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and note on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Yale say they have proven that the human
tongue, under the right conditions, perceives certain temperatures
as very specific tastes. Warm, for example, tastes sweet and
sometimes bitter, while cold can produce a sensation of saltiness
or sourness. (360 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Feeling hopeless is not just unpleasant: it may also be bad
for your health. A new study suggests that people who suffer
persistent periods of hopelessness may be at greater risk for
hypertension, researchers at the University of Michigan School of
Public Health report. (175 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study reports that doctors who treat terminally ill
people routinely overestimate how much time their patients have
left to live, and, as a result, may deprive them of the kind of
care they need. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ When it comes to teen-age pregnancy and childbearing, American
teen-agers are best compared to those in the Russian Federation or
in troubled, former East Bloc countries like Bulgaria, a new study
finds. Teen-age pregnancy and childbearing rates here are at least
four times those in France, Germany and Japan, said researchers
from Alan Guttmacher Institute, an American group that researchers
reproductive health. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new team of researchers has weighed into the debate over
whether infants should be routinely screened for hearing loss at
birth. Although some experts believe that such testing is
unwarranted, researchers from the University of Colorado at Boulder
are offering evidence to the contrary. (250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Do parrots and
other birds that talk have any special physical equipment in the
larynx or tongue that helps them speak? By C. Claiborne Ray. (290
words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
