<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISON-RIOT-HNS &LR;      02-28 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-RIOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRISON WATCHOG CALLS FOR FEDERAL PROBE OF RIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A prison watchdog group has called for an
independent investigation of the bloody riot at Pelican Bay State
Prison and whether any officers failed to prevent the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Prison Law Office, a nonprofit organization that has
successfully sued the California Department of Corrections to
improve conditions at Pelican Bay and other prisons, on Saturday
said outside agencies should investigate the riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI, the state inspector general or the Legislature, or
all of them, ought to look at what happened,'' said Steven Fama, a
staff attorney at the San Rafael branch of the Prison Law Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not confident, given the department's track record, that
the public should entrust the investigation of this serious
incident solely to an in-house team,'' Fama said.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 inmates fought in one of the prison exercise yards on
Feb. 23 in what officials have described as a clash between mainly
Hispanic and black prisoners. Thirty-two inmates were stabbed or
slashed with homemade weapons.
</P>
<P>
   When inmates did not stop fighting after official warnings and
nonlethal measures, officers opened fire, shooting 16 inmates, one
fatally, in the state's worst prison riot in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The officers' use of force is already under investigation by a
special Department of Corrections team that is working with the Del
Norte County Sheriff's Department. Pelican Bay houses about 3,200
of the state's maximum security inmates.
</P>
<P>
   There have been past incidents of violence against inmates at
Pelican Bay, as well as recent tensions between some prison staff
and black inmates, Fama said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, who was at the prison following the riot, said he
saw a videotape of the clash that confirmed officials' earlier
statements that the melee was racial.
</P>
<P>
   The video was shown to Fama and others appointed by a federal
judge to monitor court-ordered improvements in prison conditions, a
result of a 1991 civil rights suit.
</P>
<P>
   The video, he said, showed a larger number of Hispanic inmates,
some of whom seemed to be armed with homemade weapons, launch an
organized attack on a smaller group of mostly unarmed black
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The video did not capture the full sweep of the yard, but
spanned the duration of the fighting, which lasted about 10
minutes, Fama said. Some other accounts had reported that the
fighting lasted 30 minutes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have said they seized 89 homemade weapons from
prisoners after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Fama questioned how so many inmates could slip weapons past
officers, who, he said, on other occasions have screened prisoners
before letting them on the yard.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawyer, since December 1998 tensions have grown
between black inmates and some officers. And in the last month,
there have been two alleged instances in which black prisoners were
assaulted by other inmates who were supposed to be locked in their
cells, but mysteriously were allowed out, Fama said. One of the
inmates was assaulted while leaving a shower, and the other was
attacked as he was being returned to his cell, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a Pelican Bay officer was convicted of conspiracy to
assault an inmate, and this month a second officer was convicted in
San Francisco federal court of civil rights violations in
connection with the shooting of another inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two former Pelican Bay guards were charged with
violating the rights of inmates by arranging assaults against them
in the early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1520EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
