<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
 (bl)  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping a Stiff Upper Lip During the Barrage
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to win the presidency, really,'' Gov. George
W. Bush told a reporter on the day after a 6-point loss to Sen.
John McCain in the Michigan primary. Under the circumstances, he
sounded like one of the heroic optimists who got London through the
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   How to weather the insurgent barrage of McCain, whose clean
sweep Tuesday also included his home state of Arizona, was a matter
of growing concern for the Bush campaign, which has already spent
$60 million and has beaten McCain in only one fully engaged
head-to-head contest, South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the open Michigan primary thanks to independents and
blue-collar voters, moderates and suburbanites. What he didn't get
was many Republicans: only 29 percent of Republican voters cast
ballots for McCain, which could spell trouble for him on Super
Tuesday, March 7, when primaries in crucial states like New York
and California will not allow crossover voting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a conservative record in Congress, McCain, because of
his unorthodox positions on issues like campaign finance reform, is
being viewed by voters as a progressive alternative to Bush,
alienating the party's conservative base. To win back support on
the right, McCain is proclaiming in a new commercial running in
California, ``I'm a proud Reagan Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is practically the label Bill Bradley tried to hang last
week on his Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore. In a
feisty debate Monday at the Apollo Theater in New York City's
Harlem, Bradley all but shoved a copy of Gore's congressional
voting record in his face in an effort to show Democrats that the
vice president has been far more right-leaning on abortion and gun
control than they think.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's insurgent campaign, overshadowed by McCain's, is
making a stand in Washington state in anticipation of the primary
there Tuesday. His concentration in a state that is essentially
holding a beauty contest shows how critical it has become for
Bradley to win a primary somewhere, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   But Will It Have Toll Booths? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll call it the Ho Chi Minh Highway. In a hopeful
lunge at development, Vietnam announced it would carve a
north-south road through its western mountains along the route of
the former Ho Chi Minh Trail.
</P>
<P>
   That trail _ really a shifting network of hidden supply routes
that snaked in and out of neighboring Laos and Cambodia _ was one
of the wonders of the Vietnam War, one more proof of the
persistence and ingenuity of North Vietnam's guerrilla fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of the new plan is a little more difficult to
embrace. Vietnam already has a north-south route, Highway 1, that
runs along the coast through most of its major cities. The new
road, while presumably avoiding the old trail's detours into its
neighbors' territory, would still travel 1,000 miles through
remote, difficult mountain terrain.
</P>
<P>
   And it would tax Vietnam's treasury at an announced cost of some
$678.6 million in a country that lacks basic resources and is
struggling to pull itself up from poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The very notion of building a jungle highway in three years
might seem unrealistic. But for Vietnamese officials, who are
struggling through a long, discouraging economic slump, the allure
of the trail's symbolism may be irresistible. Once again, they can
mobilize the masses and, with patriotic fervor, show the world what
they can do.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   Signals on Interest Rates Confuse the Stock Markets  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street went through a confusing week, with the Dow Jones
industrial average losing 3.5 percent and closing below 10,000 for
the first time in 10 months. Its performance contrasted with the
technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index, which is up 12.81
percent this year and which showed a small gain for the week. The
divergence seemed to reflect expectations that the Federal Reserve
will continue raising interest rates, and that this will hurt
traditional companies more than it will hurt new technology
companies, since the Old Economy organizations are more dependent
on bank loans for raising capital.
</P>
<P>
   A Finger Is Pointed At Milosevic
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, has been making life
difficult for NATO peacekeepers in the troubled Kosovo city of
Kosovska-Mitrovica. NATO and Clinton administration officials
acknowledged they had intercepted radio transmissions between Serbs
in the northern part of Mitrovica and Milosevic's security police
in Serbia proper. As well, Milosevic has been sending plainclothes
police into the city to help train and encourage Serb militants who
want to expel the remaining Albanians in northern Mitrovica. NATO
commanders vowed they would ensure the return of Albanian residents
who fled their homes in the north. Whether that can happen seems
likely to be a fundamental test of the administration's Kosovo
policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE PERLEZ
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: JANE PERLEZ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gumshoes on the Danube
</P>
<P>
   With globalization making it as easy for the mob as it is for
the corporation to operate across borders, the FBI is going abroad
in pursuit of the Russian mafia _ really, a collection of mafias _
whose tentacles have spread globally and now reach into Brighton
Beach, South Miami, Philadelphia and Los Angeles. When the mob
leaders are not in Moscow, they have been hanging out in Budapest,
a pleasant city on the Danube and a fine way station on the path to
Western Europe. So that is where, next month, the FBI will be
opening its first full-fledged office beyond U.S. shores.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RAYMOND BONNER
</P>
<P>
   Making Teaching A 12-Month Job
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to boost teachers' salaries _ and status _ Education
Secretary Richard Riley proposed that teaching become a year-round
profession. He left to states and school districts the question of
whether to extend the school calendar for students as well, but
said teachers need more professional development in this era of
high-technology and high-stakes testing, ``The educational paradigm
of the factory age is no longer appropriate,'' the secretary said
at a high school in Durham, N.C., in his seventh annual address on
the state of American education.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatric Drugs for Tots
</P>
<P>
   A study published in the Journal of the American Medical
Association reported a ``troubling'' rise in the number of
preschool children being medicated with stimulants, antidepressants
and other psychiatric drugs. From 1991 to 1995, it found,
stimulants including methylphenidate, the generic form of Ritalin,
increased two to three times for children aged 2 to 4 in the
programs studied, while antidepressant use doubled and the use of
clonidine, a blood pressure drug, also jumped. It was the first
study to document an increase among children younger than 5.
</P>
<P>
   Following Moses
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt to follow in the steps of Moses, Pope John Paul II
began his long-awaited spiritual pilgrimage by also retracing
modern religious tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The pope had long hoped to use his visits to biblical sites to
seek reconciliation between Christians, Muslims and Jews. He was
warmly received by Egypt's most authoritative Sunni Muslim leader,
Mohammad Tantawi, but he spent most of his time in Egypt seeking to
smooth relations within the Christian world and renew Vatican
dialogue with Egypt's Coptic Orthodox church, which rejects the
primacy of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALESSANDRA STANLEY
</P>
<P>
   Curtains for `Cats'
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, musicals like ``Les Miserables'' and
``Phantom of the Opera'' have anchored the Broadway industry,
drawing millions of tourists to Times Square and keeping their
theaters lit during even the hardest of times. The specter of a
world without them is harrowing to many who make their living along
the Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   So an announcement that ``Cats,'' the longest-running show in
Broadway history, would close at the end of June set off a fervent
guessing game among amateur handicappers: which mega-musical might
be the next to shutter? In the meantime, ``Cats'' was enjoying a
renaissance. By week's end, the show had sold more than $1 million
in tickets, making it once again the hottest ticket on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JESSE McKINLEY
</P>
<P>
   One More Strike
</P>
<P>
   His teammates on the New York Yankees were surprised when they
learned that Darryl Strawberry had flunked a drug test _ he took
cocaine _ but none seemed particularly shocked, speaking in
monotones about the terrible burden of addiction. They have been
through this many times before. This is Strawberry's third strike
under baseball's drug aftercare program, and he has received
suspensions of 60 and 120 days in the past; commissioner Bud Selig
is considering suspending him for the entire season this time.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   A Claim of Bias in the Secret Service
</P>
<P>
   Led by Reginald G. Moore, a Secret Service agent who once held a
top spot on President Clinton's protective detail, black agents
last week filed a class action discrimination complaint with the
agency charging systematic bias in promotions, assignments and
transfers. Although Moore had received outstanding performance
evaluations, he was denied a promotion last year to the agency's
managerial ranks, required to train the white agent promoted ahead
of him and transferred to a counterfeiting squad in Dallas. The
agency would not comment on the complaint, but said that it had
worked hard to create a diverse work environment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   A No to Internet Censors
</P>
<P>
   Every parent faces the dilemma: Restrict a child too much and
she may learn little, but let her roam free and she may run into
trouble. That conundrum lies at the heart of an acrimonious dispute
in western Michigan over whether Internet access at public
libraries should be restricted to protect children from
pornography. Christian conservatives put the issue to a referendum
there and lost, as some local residents contended that software
filters restricted free speech and would inevitably block access to
some useful sites, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
</TEXT>
