<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER     02-28 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S LAIRD TO YOU, MISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no longer very hard to enjoy the trappings of a financial
mogul or earn an aristocratic title conveying pomp and privilege.
Just visit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is filled with outfits that cater to these desires. For
example, type in ``offshoresecrets.com'' and enter a world
promising ``fast, safe, private and affordable offshore services.''
</P>
<P>
   Those services include banking charters in such obscure locales
as Nauru and Vanuatu for a fee of about $20,000. ``Yes! I want to
order my own bank now!'' the site encourages visitors, noting that
such banks allow users to take deposits, give loans and ``operate
free of tax on profit,'' with no ``need to maintain a physical
presence'' in the host country.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, the site can help you get a college degree or
even a legal title of nobility. ``With a Title in front of your
name you will experience a difference in people's attitudes,'' the
site notes. ``The moment they know you are a `Sir, Lady, Lord,
etc.' you'll be treated like some sort of royalty or famous film
star.''
</P>
<P>
   An individual identified as Eytan Gold, who operates
offshoresecrets.com from Israel, declined to be interviewed.
Neither he nor his site have ever been charged with wrongdoing. But
his site and others like it have drawn the attention of U.S.
regulators and legislators, who suspect they may be fronts for
money laundering and other financial shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole purpose of many of these banks is to provide havens
for criminals,'' said Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., in an
interview. ``Any criminal worth his salt knows that if you want to
avoid detection, you go offshore _ and with the Internet, you can
point, click and launder.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $5 trillion to $6 trillion is sheltered in offshore
accounts, according to reports from the International Monetary
Fund, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and the State Department. Schumer and
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., have introduced money-laundering
legislation that targets ``instant banks'' being peddled on the
Internet. The legislation would prevent those kinds of banks from
having transactions with U.S. financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at one site, offshoreprofit.com, operated from
Venezuela by an individual identified as Lord Antonio D. Gonzalez,
suggests how easy it is for just about anyone to shelter money
abroad. For $399, the site will establish an account in ``one of
Estonia's largest banks'' and throw in a free ``Maestro Card.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's ``Millennium Freedom Package,'' bargain-priced at
$2,299, offers an offshore trust account in Belize, an ``ID Free
Visa card,'' a mail-drop address and a ``full year of personalized
advice'' that includes information on where to get ``a second, or
even third diplomatic passport.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site, privacyworld.com, also offers offshore trusts
and bank accounts, ``legal tax avoidance'' services, press or
travel agent identification and international driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   For the very ambitious, the site will establish ``anonymous,
bearer share'' corporations that will let owners bank abroad using
encrypted telephone, fax or e-mail connections.
</P>
<P>
   The site, operated from Switzerland by Third World Trading
Corp., says it allows clients to ``get rid of lawyers, spouses,
etc., forever.'' The operators of privacyworld.com could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some offshore operators scoff at the notion that they are
selling anything more than a sought-after luxury: privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet makes it easy to protect our and our clients'
privacy,'' an individual calling himself Robert Smith said in an
e-mail response to questions about his site, offshoreprofit.com.
``We are located outside the U.S., our actual location being a
secret to avoid interference and sabotage attempts, which have
destroyed or are in the process of destroying other, more
high-profile offshore operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also observed that most illegal activities occur in
onshore banks. In fact, the biggest money-laundering investigation
in history is underway at the Bank of New York, where $7 billion in
suspect funds from Russia are being examined. The bank has not been
charged with wrongdoing and is cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some offshore banks and services are used by those who
want to break the law,'' he said. ``However the same thing is true
for onshore banks. In fact, the vast majority of international
money laundering doesn't take place in the Caribbean or in Austria,
but in New York and London. That's where the truly powerful people
launder their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you aren't interested in stashing away money, the sites
point out that many of their products make great gifts. For just
$495 ($795 for couples), offshoresecrets.com will make you a laird,
knecht, viscount or marchioness. And the cachet that comes with
that title, you'll discover, is just priceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines will often upgrade you,'' the site promises. ``Bank
managers just can't help you enough. It says more about you than a
Gold or Platinum credit card. For personal confidence and
self-esteem a title will change your life for the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER     02-28 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S LAIRD TO YOU, MISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no longer very hard to enjoy the trappings of a financial
mogul or earn an aristocratic title conveying pomp and privilege.
Just visit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is filled with outfits that cater to these desires. For
example, type in ``offshoresecrets.com'' and enter a world
promising ``fast, safe, private and affordable offshore services.''
</P>
<P>
   Those services include banking charters in such obscure locales
as Nauru and Vanuatu for a fee of about $20,000. ``Yes! I want to
order my own bank now!'' the site encourages visitors, noting that
such banks allow users to take deposits, give loans and ``operate
free of tax on profit,'' with no ``need to maintain a physical
presence'' in the host country.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, the site can help you get a college degree or
even a legal title of nobility. ``With a Title in front of your
name you will experience a difference in people's attitudes,'' the
site notes. ``The moment they know you are a `Sir, Lady, Lord,
etc.' you'll be treated like some sort of royalty or famous film
star.''
</P>
<P>
   An individual identified as Eytan Gold, who operates
offshoresecrets.com from Israel, declined to be interviewed.
Neither he nor his site have ever been charged with wrongdoing. But
his site and others like it have drawn the attention of U.S.
regulators and legislators, who suspect they may be fronts for
money laundering and other financial shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole purpose of many of these banks is to provide havens
for criminals,'' said Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., in an
interview. ``Any criminal worth his salt knows that if you want to
avoid detection, you go offshore _ and with the Internet, you can
point, click and launder.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $5 trillion to $6 trillion is sheltered in offshore
accounts, according to reports from the International Monetary
Fund, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and the State Department. Schumer and
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., have introduced money-laundering
legislation that targets ``instant banks'' being peddled on the
Internet. The legislation would prevent those kinds of banks from
having transactions with U.S. financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at one site, offshoreprofit.com, operated from
Venezuela by an individual identified as Lord Antonio D. Gonzalez,
suggests how easy it is for just about anyone to shelter money
abroad. For $399, the site will establish an account in ``one of
Estonia's largest banks'' and throw in a free ``Maestro Card.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's ``Millennium Freedom Package,'' bargain-priced at
$2,299, offers an offshore trust account in Belize, an ``ID Free
Visa card,'' a mail-drop address and a ``full year of personalized
advice'' that includes information on where to get ``a second, or
even third diplomatic passport.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site, privacyworld.com, also offers offshore trusts
and bank accounts, ``legal tax avoidance'' services, press or
travel agent identification and international driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   For the very ambitious, the site will establish ``anonymous,
bearer share'' corporations that will let owners bank abroad using
encrypted telephone, fax or e-mail connections.
</P>
<P>
   The site, operated from Switzerland by Third World Trading
Corp., says it allows clients to ``get rid of lawyers, spouses,
etc., forever.'' The operators of privacyworld.com could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some offshore operators scoff at the notion that they are
selling anything more than a sought-after luxury: privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet makes it easy to protect our and our clients'
privacy,'' an individual calling himself Robert Smith said in an
e-mail response to questions about his site, offshoreprofit.com.
``We are located outside the U.S., our actual location being a
secret to avoid interference and sabotage attempts, which have
destroyed or are in the process of destroying other, more
high-profile offshore operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also observed that most illegal activities occur in
onshore banks. In fact, the biggest money-laundering investigation
in history is underway at the Bank of New York, where $7 billion in
suspect funds from Russia are being examined. The bank has not been
charged with wrongdoing and is cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some offshore banks and services are used by those who
want to break the law,'' he said. ``However the same thing is true
for onshore banks. In fact, the vast majority of international
money laundering doesn't take place in the Caribbean or in Austria,
but in New York and London. That's where the truly powerful people
launder their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you aren't interested in stashing away money, the sites
point out that many of their products make great gifts. For just
$495 ($795 for couples), offshoresecrets.com will make you a laird,
knecht, viscount or marchioness. And the cachet that comes with
that title, you'll discover, is just priceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines will often upgrade you,'' the site promises. ``Bank
managers just can't help you enough. It says more about you than a
Gold or Platinum credit card. For personal confidence and
self-esteem a title will change your life for the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-REFORM-PARTY-REVIEW-N     02-28 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE $12 MILLION MAN: BUCHANAN WAITS FOR THE PARTY TO BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all the money and fury being invested in the
parallel primary campaigns of the two major parties, there is
another presidential war game going on under the radar, among the
mud-spattered troops of the Reform party slogging through their own
wilderness campaign. Sooner or later, however, the winners of the
Democratic and Republican fights will have to pay attention. For,
barring direct intrusion by Ross Perot himself, the current
expectation among political professionals is that the Reform line
could very well be resurrected this fall by none other than Pat
Buchanan, the turncoat Republican and chronic presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five months, Buchanan has been quietly laboring to
build his own Reform machine and get a lock on the nomination. No
small attraction in his quest is the $12.6 million federal election
subsidy that is the Reform nominee's entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buchanan's waiting in the weeds for the primaries to end,''
said Jim Jordan, a Democratic campaign strategist who anticipates
serious tri-corner mischief if Buchanan manages to seize the third
line. ``Pat knows how to use a political wedge better than anybody
in the business,'' Jordan added, wondering, for example, whether
the GOP's right-wing Christian bloc might become miffed enough in
the current Republican fray to be tempted by a Buchanan alternative
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Following Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's angry departure from
the party, speculation is growing that Perot might try to dictate a
nominee. But Buchanan, deep into Reform politics by now, insists he
is ready for any eventuality, including recent speculation that
Perot might seek to give his party's blessing to Sen. John McCain,
or that Perot might decide to run again himself.
</P>
<P>
   More an impulse than an organization, the party that Perot built
is out of season right now, shards of ill-managed klatches in 21
states, each hoping for someone to unite it into a once more
fearsome vehicle. The Bush family remembers well that fearsomeness;
President George Bush saw his potential margin of re-election
siphoned off in 1992 when Perot drew 19 percent of the vote to the
Reform line and Bill Clinton was elected as a plurality President.
Now the son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is suffering a healthy
dose of insurgency from McCain and neither can afford to focus on
the Perot reformers conspiring on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   As he retreated, Ventura described the Reform Party as
``hopelessly dysfunctional.'' But actually he was quitting
preemptively, having failed to win the national party leadership.
In a way, the party proved quite functional, for the Perot
loyalists reclaimed the party gavel in Nashville at a raucous
convention shoving match worthy of the Moscow Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Reform party enthusiasts heart-stricken at the spectacle should
remember that big money has a way of focusing the attention of even
the most obstreperous politician. And the early teasing about this
prize is ending.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump, as self-fantasized a politician as ever trod the
tabloid runway, instantly withdrew his pompadour from the ring when
his sole patron, Ventura, was pinned by the Perot forces. And
political specialists point to election laws and impenetrable
Reform procedures that would make a McCain endorsement difficult,
if not impossible. More to the point, the idea of being the Reform
Party nominee has been rejected outright by McCain, who cites the
Bull Moose folly of his hero, Theodore Roosevelt, and says he would
welcome all sorts of endorsements, Reformers included, once he wins
the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Reform Party is in its familiar Godot mode, waiting
for Perot. Associates who claim to know his mind say that Perot may
try something new. He ran a second time in 1996 with some
embarrassing results. His popular support was halved at the polls
as critics judged him less of a reformer and more of a
laughingstock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one is watching more intently for the hand of Perot
than Buchanan. He jumped to the Reformers when his serial campaign
for the GOP nomination lagged into single-digit polling doldrums.
Since his conversion, Buchanan has been laboring to build his own
personal Reform machine, state by state. With Ventura now gone,
Buchanan counts one fewer dragon to slay on the road to the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm that troll still waiting out there under the bridge,''
Buchanan likes to laughingly announce.
</P>
<P>
   His core strategy is to win the $12.6 million and use it as a
credential with which he could not be fairly denied entry into the
real prize for him, next fall's televised debates. There, he likes
his chances as the quick-witted populist who delights in contrarian
polemics.
</P>
<P>
   But first Buchanan must hack his new side-door path to the
political arena where he last stunned the Republican establishment
by defeating Bob Dole in the 1996 New Hampshire primary. Buchanan
is spending $2 million organizing petition drives and field workers
in the 29 states that do not now have Reform ballot lines. In the
other 21 states, he has been courting disparate gatherings of
uncertain Reformers, right down to a bowling alley caucus one night
in Fleetwoods, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   When he opportunistically jumped his life-long Republican
traces, Buchanan predicted, ``Ross Perot will be a benign
neutral.'' Now he admits he has to wonder what might happen as the
quixotic Texan silently weighs McCain's success in tapping voter
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about footsteps,'' Buchanan insisted of
Perot as he claimed his first Reform victory of sorts in Ventura's
quitting the party. ``I always said this would be like running an
Iroquois gantlet,'' Buchanan said, beginning to savor and so far
master the wayward politics of his new party. ``It's a volatile
situation in America,'' the newly minted Reformer said, smiling at
the possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-REFORM-PARTY-REVIEW-N     02-28 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE $12 MILLION MAN: BUCHANAN WAITS FOR THE PARTY TO BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
