<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Feb. 27, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOBJONES-REVIEW (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's
advisers say his speech at Bob Jones University was the single most
ill-considered decision of his presidential campaign. It was
clearly not just another mere bump on Bush's path to the GOP
nomination. By this weekend, Bush's aides were huddling to come up
with a way for him to publicly admit the visit was a mistake _
without stirring up more bad publicity. By Richard L. Berke. (Moved
in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-REVIEW (Moscow) _ From the outside, seven months
of Chechen conflict seems a bloodbath to rival anything since World
War II. Chechnya is a wsteland; its capital, Grozny, obliterated.
Tales of atrocities are rife, and 300,000 refugees have fled. But
inside Russia, almost no one sees it that way. The Kremlin's
official line, which so far has been accepted by the Russian
public, is that Chechnya was a noble crusade against terrorists and
bandits, waged by an army intent on liberating innocents, not
executing or raping them. By Michael Wines. (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-IMPACT-REVIEW (New York) _ After an Albany jury acquitted
four New York City police officers in the killing of Amadou Diallo,
the judge declared the book closed. That is true as far as the
courtroom goes. But it may take a while before the book closes, if
it ever does, on the troubled collective conscience of New York and
perhaps elsewhere in America. It was hard for many New Yorkers to
shake the sense that this had all come out wrong. Even if heads
said the jury had done its job, hearts ached. By Clyde Haberman.
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-POLICE-REVIEW (New York) _ Although the officers who
killed Amadou Diallo were found innocent of all charges, their
trial testimony was instructive in how police expect you to behave
when they confront you. Speak when asked to speak. Stop when
ordered to stop. Keep your hands in plain view. And never _ EVER _
make a sudden move. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-SONGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ An innocent man slain by police
is remembered in songs. Some excerpted lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-JOURNALISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Even the high drama of
disaster, violence and political upheaval that dominates the news
can lose its luster for many journalists who entered their
profession mainly to seek new experiences. After a time, a news
writer may begin to sense a kind of sameness in most of the events
that pass as news. But a lucky few discover that in science, almost
alone of all human endeavors, there is always something new under
the sun. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-TREATMENT-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at trends in relieving
pain in cancer patients and others in severe discomfort.
Comprehending the magnitude of pain that accompanies some medical
conditions is very difficult for those who have not themselves
suffered. Among the several difficulties inherent in the
misapprehensions about the treatment of pain is the troublesome
fact that there has never been any accurate way to measure its
severity. But this may be changing. By Sherwin B. Nuland.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ For all the money and fury
involved in the primary campaigns of the two major parties, there
is another contest going on under the radar, among the
mud-spattered troops of the Reform Party slogging through their own
wilderness campaign. Eventually, the Democratic and Republican
victors will have to pay attention. For, barring intrusion by Ross
Perot, the expectation among political professionals is that the
Reform line could be resurrected this fall by Patrick Buchanan. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's no longer hard to
become the financial mogul _ replete with an aristocratic title
conveying pomp and privilege _ that you've always dreamed of
becoming. Just visit the Internet. There are throngs of outfits on
the Web that cater to these desires. For example, just type in
``offshoresecrets.com'' and enter a world promising ``fast, safe,
private, and affordable off-shore services.'' Those services
include providing customers with banking charters in such obscure
locales as Nevis and Vanuatu for a fee of about $20,000. By Timothy
L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Grammy Awards can be seen as a
sort of musical Land That Time Forgot, a place where the best
surprise is no surprise. This is where the music business tries to
place its imprimatur on the ungovernable energies of American pop
culture. ``Old people _ the Grammy voters _ like to be reminded
that the young people aren't taking over, which is ironic when
you're talking about pop music,'' notes popular culture critic
Robert Wilonsky. For instance, the organization once awarded Petula
Clark a Grammy over the Beatles. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN-REVIEW (Beijing) _ Who lost Taiwan? Even the
possibility that this question may some day be asked must be
horrifying for China's leaders. For in China's history-laden
politics, almost nothing matters more than the idea of Taiwan's
eventual return to the motherland, especially now that Hong Kong
and Macau are back. And this emotional truth may aid the
interpretation of the White Paper they issued last week, warning
more explicitly than before that Taiwan's foot-dragging in
negotiations, let alone a declaration of independence, could force
China into ``drastic measures.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REFORM-REVIEW (Tehran, Iran) _ United by little more than
antagonism toward the insular clerics who have tried desperately to
maintain their monopoly on ideas, the self-styled reformers have
now gained the upper hand following their victory in the first
round of parliamentary elections Feb. 18. The reform movement is
partly a backlash against a conservative clerical cartel that fears
change and has tried to stifle it with arrests and violence. It is
also a natural by-product of the theocratic regime that has ruled
Iran since the 1979 Islamic revolution. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
