<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-ANCIENTCHINESE-AMERIC     02-28 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCIENTCHINESE-AMERICAS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SAILED TO MEXICO MILLENNIA AGO, TCU SCHOLAR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mike Xu (pronounced Shu) walks briskly into
the faculty lounge at Texas Christian University and quickly
canvasses the room. It's midafternoon and the lounge is nearly
empty, which appears to be to his liking. He places several
magazine articles on a table _ the one on top is in Chinese _ and
begins the conversation with a disclaimer.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about self-promotion, says Xu, a professor of
Chinese Studies at TCU; this is not a personal crusade. This is
about presenting evidence and letting people reach their own
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Xu, who was born in Shanghai and came to the United States 14
years ago, advocates a theory that Asians _ notably the Chinese _
sailed the Pacific Ocean to the New World 3,000 years ago, landing
in what is now southern Mexico, near the border of Guatemala. The
boat crossings would have occurred in 1100 B.C., centuries before
the Vikings or Columbus made it to our shores.
</P>
<P>
   If substantiated, this would mean that the Mesoamerican period
in the history of the New World was directly influenced by the
Chinese. Some might go a step further and argue that it shows the
Chinese were actually the first to discover the Americas, though Xu
says even Chinese scholars won't go that far.
</P>
<P>
   His evidence supporting trans-Pacific contact by the Chinese is
the inscriptions found on jade artifacts during excavations in
Central America in the region where the Olmec established what is
considered to be Mexico's first society. The Olmec writing symbols
are nearly identical to those used in the writing system of the
Shang Dynasty, which ruled northern China during 1100 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Xu thumbed through several pages of a Chinese journal that
published his examples of the Olmec and Shang writing systems.
Pointing enthusiastically to various symbols, he says the
similarities are too strong to be a coincidence. His theory has
widespread support among ``diffusionists,'' those who believe that
society in the Americas was influenced by different civilizations
thousands of years before the time of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolute evidence of contact,'' says Betty Meggers, a
research archaeologist at the Smithsonian in Washington. ``No one
can suggest that the same writing system was invented twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although universities are usually considered bastions of free
speech and new ideas, it isn't every day that a member of the
faculty suggests that history may have to be rewritten. Think of
all the lesson plans that would have to be revised, the history
books that would have to be amended.
</P>
<P>
   By endorsing what mainstream scholars say is an unsubstantiated
theory about how civilization evolved in Central America, Xu is
attracting attention that's making him somewhat uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make you part of the lunatic fringe,'' he says. ``I
have really not been actively involved in the debate. But I believe
the academic discipline is to be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream scholars, or ``nativists,'' as they are sometimes
called, attempt to debunk the theory of direct Chinese influence
during the Mesoamerican period, claiming the Olmec were indigenous.
They also dismiss claims that visitors from Africa and Europe
visited the New World before Columbus made his voyage and that
those visitors had an influence on how society evolved here.
</P>
<P>
   Nativists believe that the first inhabitants of the Americas
crossed the land bridge that formed over the Bering Strait (between
Siberia and Alaska) after the Ice Age, 12,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Their descendants migrated southward over the centuries,
eventually settling in North, Central and South America. American
Indians, for example, are considered descendants of these
aboriginals.
</P>
<P>
   Although scholars acknowledge that the Vikings may have preceded
Columbus, they say there is no suggestion that they had an
influence on civilization in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that these theories imply that a superior culture
group thus brought civilization to them,'' says David Grove, an
archaeologist at the University of Illinois. ``They are actually
stealing the rich heritage of Mexico's great civilizations from all
people of Mexican descent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, artifacts unearthed in various excavations over the years
appear to indicate some direct contact. New Scientist, a weekly
magazine based in London, recently reported that Roman Hristov, an
anthropologist formerly associated with Southern Methodist
University in Dallas, tested a black terra-cotta head that was
first unearthed in 1933 in the Toluca Valley near Mexico City. The
Roman head, which is just a few centimeters tall, represents a
bearded man, which researchers and art experts say dates to A.D.
200.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Grove says the head could have been taken from a Roman shipwreck
off the coast of Mexico centuries later. Acknowledging that he may
be accused of ``academic snobbery,'' Grove says he always tells his
students that ``belief does not constitute proof.'' He says Xu's
evidence of Chinese contact in Central America is limited and that
the writing systems of the Olmec and Shang have only vague
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   He also cites a lack of similarity in other examples of Olmec
and Shang culture, for instance, pottery and the lack of Shang
metallurgy. Grove says that the prevalence of crocodiles in Olmec
art, which diffusionists say mirrors the Shang Dynasty's depiction
of dragons, simply reflects a formidable creature that inhabits the
tropical rivers where the Olmec lived.
</P>
<P>
   Pragmatists add that surviving a trans-Pacific crossing in
primitive craft 3,000 years ago would have been out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Xu) is on a mission to spread his ideas,'' Grove says.
``He has no background in Mexican archaeology or scientific method.
If there were one shred of evidence, then great bunches of
archaeologists would jump on that and build their fame. It's (a
theory) reborn every decade or so. Now, it's Mike Xu's turn to
reinvent the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu says he is not interested in getting in the middle of a
debate between diffusionists and nativists. He understands that
because he is not an archaeologist or anthropologist, his opinions
carry less weight. His interpretation of the Olmec and Shang
writing systems was even rejected at first in China. In effect, he
is seen as digging in someone else's dirt.
</P>
<P>
   But what endears Xu to diffusionists is that his Chinese
heritage gives him credibility; he is more qualified to interpret
the writing systems of the Shang and Olmec. The inscriptions he
found on Olmec artifacts were not random, he says. They include
consecutive symbols that convey complete thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You're just the kind of person needed to get at
this,''' Meggers says. ``The progress he's made is amazing,
especially in reading the script.''
</P>
<P>
   Grove says that if you believe in ancient contact, you might as
well credit space aliens with influencing civilization in
Mesoamerica as well.
</P>
<P>
   But why all the fuss? The Americas today are a melting pot of
cultures from around the world. What would be so wrong with
suggesting it may have been so thousands of years ago, too?
</P>
<P>
   Meggers says that nativists want to believe that culture in the
New World evolved independently to show that, in effect, mankind
could reinvent itself. That is more comforting than accepting the
theory of cultural integration during human history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the burden of proof may be on diffusionists, mainstream
scholars may find it difficult to continue explaining away findings
of ancient contact unearthed in excavations throughout the
Americas, Meggers says.
</P>
<P>
   She points to excavations in South America that have uncovered
sites at least 12,000 years old. No one who crossed the land
bridge, she says, could have migrated that far south that quickly.
</P>
<P>
   She also has found similarities between pottery made in Japan
and that found at a site in Ecuador dating back almost 5,000 years.
Some researchers say that aboriginal Australians may have sailed to
South America 15,000 years ago, predating even the land-bridge
crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Xu, however, is limiting the debate to the Olmec/Shang
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it is possible for people to migrate here 12,000
years ago, but not 3,000?'' he asks. ``I went to museums in Mexico
and archaeological sites; I saw motifs (figures) identical to ones
in China. There are 200, 300 writings _ quantity and quality.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that in 1996 he finally convinced the most prominent
scholar in China of trans-Pacific contact; subsequently, Xu has had
a 16-page article on the Olmec/Shang comparisons published in
China's most prestigious publication, the Shanghai Journal of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   He is excited but cautious. He knows the debate is not new and
may continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say the mystery is solved,'' Xu said. ``We
don't have to agree, but we cannot assume we know everything. I
just want the evidence to speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pete Alfano is a staff writer for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7985, or e-mail:
palfano(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
