<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      02-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH JOINS TAKEOVER BID FOR HONG KONG PHONE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK LANDLER with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Rupert Murdoch's foray into the takeover battle for
Hong Kong's local phone company, Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, scrambles
what had been for many people here a contest between a home-town
hero and a foreign interloper.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's News Corp. confirmed Monday that it would invest $1
billion and create an Asian joint venture with Singapore
Telecommunications, which is negotiating with Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC
of Britain to acquire control of its Hong Kong subsidiary.
Executives close to Singapore Telecommunications said it had
sweetened the cash portion of its offer for Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT by
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The revised offer could enable the Singapore company to regain
the momentum in its battle with Pacific Century Cyberworks, which
on Sunday offered to acquire Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT in a
stock-and-cash bid that values the company at $35 billion.
Singapore Telecom's first bid had been slightly lower than Pacific
Century's, executives involved in the negotiations said, but the
bids were now comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century Cyberworks was founded nine months ago by
Richard Li, the 33-year-old son of the powerful Hong Kong tycoon,
Li Ka-shing. The younger Li's stock has enjoyed one of the most
spectacular rides in the history of the Hong Kong stock exchange.
Although he is using those volatile shares to support his bid, he
has created an aura of inevitability about his campaign for Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT.
</P>
<P>
   But with Singapore Telecommunications adding $1 billion in cash
to its offer, the directors of Cable &AMP; Wireless may cast a colder
eye on Li's proposal, which is more than two-thirds financed by
stock. Moreover, analysts said the benefits of the investment
extended beyond cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attractiveness of the deal to SingTel is a lot more than
that,'' said Dylan Tinker, a telecommunications analyst at Deutsche
Securities here. ``News Corp. gives them content for an Asia-based
satellite satellite programming service, which is what they want to
create.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement between News Corp. and Singapore
Telecommunications, the companies will create an Internet,
television and mobile-phone joint venture. Among the venture's most
ambitious goals is to create an Internet-access service for
cellular phone subscribers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Singapore Telecom is clearly the right partner for us in
fulfilling our goal of building the premiere digital delivery
platform in Asia,'' Murdoch said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, News Corp. set up a joint venture with Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT to offer pay-television and Internet-related services
through high-capacity lines. This joint venture would be similar,
though with a mobile-phone dimension. If Singapore Telecom acquires
HKT, the ventures could be combined _ creating an Internet-access
service that reaches nearly a million cellular subscribers in Hong
Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said News Corp.'s programming venture with Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT is one of the company's main drawing points for
Pacific Century. Li is planning a satellite-delivered Internet
service of his own, to be called Network of the World. But his
company lacks programming.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Singapore Telecommunications said, however,
that Murdoch would probably unravel the venture if Pacific Century
acquired Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT. In 1995, Li sold News Corp. the Star
TV satellite network for $950 million. His plans for a new
satellite network are seen as a competitive threat to Star TV,
which is finally turning a profit after years of losing money.
</P>
<P>
   After confirming Monday morning that it made a formal offer for
Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, Pacific Century left the Hong Kong market in
a state of confusion. The company initially said it would hold a
news briefing to discuss its bid, only to cancel it in the
afternoon. Pacific Century's shares were suspended for a second
consecutive session, which had the effect of locking in the value
of its stock-and-cash offer. Some market experts said the halt in
the stock _ combined with the lack of details about the bid _
raised troubling questions of disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have let it trade today,'' said Marc Faber, the
head of an investment firm here. ``My feeling is that the shares
would have been substantially lower than they were last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, Faber said he thought Li was wise to use his
stock to bid for a company with genuine assets. Aside from a
portfolio of investments in Internet start-ups, Pacific Century
Cyberworks is a company that exists largely in blueprints. It has
no customers and no operating profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heyday of Hong Kong Telecom is over,'' Faber said. ``But
when you've got free money like Richard Li does, any purchase is
better than none.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the bidding war, News Corp.'s investment
is fresh evidence of the role that young entrepreneurs are taking
in major deals in the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   The point man in this deal was James Murdoch, 27, the second son
of Rupert Murdoch. The younger Murdoch was named head of News
Corp.'s worldwide Internet holdings last November. He traveled to
Hong Kong to hammer out the details of the joint venture with Lee
Hsien Yang, 42, the chief executive of Singapore Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is the second son of Lee Kwan Yew, the founder of modern
Singapore. The elder Lee's status there is probably even more
exalted than that of Richard Li's father in Hong Kong or Murdoch's
father in Australia. But together, the three young men are a
striking example of how young people can play a pivotal role in
Internet-age deal-making _ provided they have the right parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
