<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-GAY-MARRIAGES-HNS &LR;      02-28 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLL SHOWS SUPPORT FOR BAN ON GAY MARRIAGES IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new poll shows that Californians remain
solidly supportive of a ballot initiative that would bar the legal
recognition of gay marriages in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Of 650 likely voters surveyed last week, 55 percent favor
Proposition 22, 38 percent oppose it and 7 percent are undecided.
The election is March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The results the poll, conducted for the San Francisco Examiner
and KTVU-TV, are consistent with every poll published since
October. All have shown that the measure is supported by slightly
more than half the state's voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will be interesting is what both sides do from now till
then,'' said pollster Del Ali of Research 2000 in Rockville, Md.
``I've seen initiatives with 50 percent lose in the last week. It's
rare, but it does happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest statewide survey is the first since the campaign
against Proposition 22, also known as the Knight Initiative,
launched its television advertising campaign in the Bay Area and
three other populous regions. The results suggest the ads have
swayed few minds so far since the ads began appearing four weeks
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is sponsored by state Sen. William ``Pete''
Knight, a Republican from Palmdale who has tried unsuccessfully to
get the state Legislature to pass laws against same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   While gay marriage is not legal in California or any other
state, Proposition 22 would define marriage here as ``between a man
and a woman only.'' And it would prohibit California from
recognizing gay marriages performed in other states, should they
ever become legal there.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty other states have adopted similar laws since Hawaii came
close to legalizing gay marriage in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new poll results, Proposition 22 is favored by
every demographic group in the state and every region except the
San Francisco Bay Area. The margin of error is plus or minus 4
percentage points. According to the poll:
</P>
<P>
   _ Men (59 percent) support the initiative more strongly than
women (51 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ Republicans (66 percent) back it more than Democrats (51
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Breakdowns show no differences among racial and ethnic groups,
despite Yes on 22 advertising that targeted Hispanic voters. Just
over 50 percent of all groups support Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   The only pocket of opposition is the Bay Area, where the
statewide numbers are reversed: 40 percent of those surveyed favor
Proposition 22 and 57 percent oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers have been remarkably stable,'' said Mark
Baldassare of the Public Policy Institute of California. He has
done his own polling on the ballot initiative, among other
statewide issues, and his results have shown the same consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the money and efforts by the no side _ and by the yes
side for that matter _ we continue to see a slight majority in
favor of Prop. 22,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare said his statewide surveys show Californians
overwhelmingly favor gay rights, from domestic partnership benefits
to the ability to serve openly in the military. But voters surveyed
say they oppose gay marriage, and by the same proportion they
support Proposition 22, according to Baldassare's polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``California, if anything, is more liberal than the nation on
gay marriage, but it's not ready at this point to support gay
marriage,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
