<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT &LR;      02-28 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARIF'S LAWYERS WILL BOYCOTT PAKISTAN TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The hijacking trial of the deposed prime
minister of Pakistan _ already a cavalcade of the unexpected and
the bizarre _ took another odd twist over the weekend as his entire
defense team quit in protest against alleged government unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an attorney and my job is to help my client, but that has
become impossible when the court has placed an embargo on his
rights,'' attorney Ijaz Batalvi said Monday in a telephone
interview from Lahore. ``For months, my client has been scandalized
and maligned. By what authority is he now being denied his turn to
speak?''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Judge Rehmat Hussain Jafri accepted a prosecution
request that any testimony by the former prime minister, Nawaz
Sharif, be given in secret. It would be released to the public only
after the court determines that nothing is ``likely to tarnish and
affect the security, integrity and solidarity'' of the nation, the
judge said. Pakistan has been under military rule since Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers immediately criticized the decision, and on
Sunday, Batalvi and his colleague Khwaja Sultan Ahmed announced
that they would boycott the trial, leaving their client's fate to
``God Almighty who is guardian of truth and savior of the
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution reacted angrily, saying the defense team's
objections were ``a mere pretext in light of overwhelming
evidence'' against Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   The ousted prime minister, his brother Shahbaz and five others
face charges that include hijacking, treason and attempted murder.
Hijacking is a capital offense in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   At present, only two of the accused _ Ghous Ali Shah, once an
adviser to Sharif, and Rana Maqbool, the former inspector general
of police in Sindh province _ are represented by lawyers. The
trial's next session is set for Wednesday. By law, the court must
appoint new defense attorneys, though the defendants can reject
them and appear as their own counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking charge stems from Oct. 12, when Sharif fired the
army chief of staff, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, and then allegedly
conspired to deny landing rights to a commercial plane that was
carrying the general to Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   As the aircraft meandered through the skies, its fuel supply
dwindling, the military coup took place. Army officers took command
of air traffic control. By the time the plane landed safely, Sharif
was in custody and Musharraf was in charge of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Under international pressure to restore democracy, Musharraf has
repeatedly promised that the trial will be held in complete
openness.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, like all criminal defendants here, is required to read a
statement to the court. It was expected he would lambaste his
military successors and make an emotional appeal to his countrymen
and the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Nawaz Sharif has to say is of no danger to the
nation, only to the regime that has seized its control,'' Batalvi
said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has yet to decide whether to add Pakistan to
his itinerary during a visit to India and Bangladesh next month, a
decision e made complicated by the coup. Last month, Musharraf
demanded that all higher court judges either resign or swear an
oath of loyalty to the military government.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being held in a special anti-terrorism court, a
creation of Sharif himself, who wanted speedy justice for heinous
offenses. The court's expedited proceedings preclude the appeal of
a ruling like the one Jaffri made Friday on Sharif's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has been an on-again, off-again presider in the case.
During pre-trial hearings, the military decided to change some of
the nation's anti-terrorism laws, deciding that only a high court
judge could hear such important matters.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shabir Ahmed took over, but he resigned on Jan. 12,
complaining that so many government intelligence agents were
present in the courtroom that ``I cannot provide a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned the case to Jaffri, who again had to deal with the
consistent complaints of the defense attorneys: that they were
being denied the right to examine prosecution evidence, that they
were kept from meeting with their clients, that their hotel rooms
were bugged.
</P>
<P>
   The chief witness against Sharif is Amanullah Chaudhry, the
former director of the Civil Aviation Authority. He was originally
one of the defendants and had complained, through his attorney,
that he was under such emotional strain he was considering suicide.
Not long after, he became a prosecution witness, testifying that
Sharif personally called him three times, ordering him to divert
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
