<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-RACIAL-SLURS-HNS &LR;      02-28 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-SLURS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SLURS ARE WORDS THAT HURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The celebrated African-American poet Counte
Cullen wrote about visiting Baltimore as a small child and smiling
at another youngster the same size.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he poked out his tongue and called me `nigger.'/ I saw the
whole of Baltimore/ From May until December;/ Of all the things
that happened there/ That's all that I remember,''
</P>
<P>
   Cullen wrote his poem, ``Incident,'' 75 years ago. But the slur
that inspired it has just as much power today.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of that, the ``N-word'' and other blatant ethnic
slurs are rarely heard in public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   But when they are _ as in the recent case of GOP presidential
hopeful Sen. John McCain's use of the slur ``gook'' _ the public
outcry they provoke is a reminder of their undiminished force.
</P>
<P>
   ``These symbols are powerful,' said anthropologist and
folklorist Alan Dundes of the University of California at Berkeley.
``They have tremendous emotional repercussions and associations.
They are fighting words.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has apologized for using the slur to describe his North
Vietnamese captors. The former Navy flier was tortured during his 5
1/2 years as a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized by Asian-American groups and others, McCain said he
held the people of Vietnam in the highest regard and would no
longer use the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret any pain I may have caused by my choice of
words,'' McCain said. ``I apologize and renounce any language that
is bigoted and offensive, which is contrary to all that I represent
and believe.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain remarks have spurred debates around America's water
coolers, dinner tables and in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Some defend him, saying he was justifiably expressing his hatred
for his captors. Others condemn him for using the slur, which does
not just apply to Vietnamese but is regarded as a generic slur
against all Asians, including Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Allen, a University of Connecticut sociologist, said that
while gook is ``clearly an offensive word, its power, like that of
other slurs, depends on the circumstances. In his 1990 book,
``Unkind Words, Ethnic Labeling from Redskin to WASP,'' Allen said
the devastating meaning of slurs really lies in what the words
``mean to the speaker, the hearer, their relationship and the
social context in which the words were said.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's poet laureate, Janice Mirikitani _ a
third-generation Japanese American who was interned in a U.S. World
War II camp at age 1 with her family _ says that when someone uses
a term like gook, ``it again alienates us from who we are as a
rightful part of the fabric of America.''
</P>
<P>
   For San Francisco Supervisor Mabel Teng, the word brings back
memories of growing up as an immigrant in Ann Arbor, Mich., where
high school kids called her ``Chink.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Ching Chong Chinaman, never eat your vitamin,' that's what
they said to me,'' Teng recalled. ``They thought it was funny. I
did not think it was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   For John Rickford, an African American who is a Stanford
University linguist, the term gook conjured up Cullen's poem as
well as an incident two years ago in which Rickford's then
13-year-old son was called ``nigger'' in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't really know, don't have a sense of the power of
those symbols until they walk in other people's shoes,'' said
Rickford.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the power of words is such that the late Peter Opie, an
expert on children's lore, once suggested that the well-known
doggerel on name-calling should be rephrased to say: ``Sticks and
stones just break my bones. It's words that really hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen calculates that nearly 2,000 words would qualify as
epithets.
</P>
<P>
   Some are surprising in their common usage among some Americans,
such as ``to welsh'' (or renege) on a deal; to ``jew'' someone down
(to bargain ruthlessly) or to ``dutch,'' meaning to ruin with
malice. Even ``Scotch'' tape originally had a pejorative meaning by
implying a cheap way of repairing something, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   The profusion of ethnic slurs in American English stems from the
country's history of ethnic conflict, Allen says. ``Words are
weapons, and hurling epithets is a universal trait of hostile
intergroup relations,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive words have ``long, convoluted and sometimes idiotic''
histories. In America, slurs had their beginning when British
settlers started calling Native Americans ``Redskins.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, slavery brought an even ``larger torrent of verbal
abuse,'' Allen wrote. ``As other groups arrived and the country
became more ethnically diverse, the number of slurs grew in direct
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain follows a number of public figures who have made ethnic
slurs. President Richard Nixon referred to ``Jew boys.'' Former
Agriculture Secretary Earl Butts had to resign after making
insulting jokes about blacks in front of reporters. And the Rev.
Jesse Jackson used the term ``Hymie'' referring to Jews and
``Hymietown'' referring to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities also heap pejoratives on whites: ``marshmallows,''
``vanilla,'' ``white bread'' and ``soda cracker.''
</P>
<P>
   But ethnic majority groups are far more likely to make ethnic
slurs since, Allen says, ``they had the greater interest in keeping
other groups down.''
</P>
<P>
   The most visceral of slurs, experts agree, is the N-word. Yet
some blacks have appropriated that slur and used it in a jocular or
even affectionate fashion within their group, a linguistic process
known as semantic inversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's still a very sharp line,'' said Rickford of
Stanford. ``It's like `queers' can call themselves `queers,' and
that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the same privilege isn't open to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Dundes, of UC-Berkeley, would place gook in the same category as
the N-word and `kike,' referring to a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows quite what the origins of gook are, though most
believe the term arose out of the many wars American soldiers have
fought in Asia. It is particularly associated with the Vietnam War
and has since morphed into a generic slur for Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Der, deputy superintendent of education for California
schools and a longtime civil rights activist, said the term gook
``reinforces stereotypic racism, animosity, hateful feelings toward
an individual who looks Asian. It's similar to people using `Jap'
or `Chink' to anyone who looks Asian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
