<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CHURCHES-GUNCONTROL-T     02-28 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHES-GUNCONTROL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM JEWS AND OTHER GROUPS MAKING GUN CONTROL A `RELIGIOUS
OBLIGATION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Schools, churches and community centers _ once considered safe
havens for people _ have become the sites for recent violence close
to home and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the leaders of Reform Judaism are calling on
congregation members to aim straight for the means of that
violence: guns.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the Union of American Hebrew Congregations in
December, the president of the organization of Reform Jewish
synagogues urged congregation members to ``go on the moral
offensive, and send the message to our legislators that we care
deeply about this issue and we will hold them accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see the control of guns not as a political problem,
but as a solemn religious obligation,'' UAHC President Rabbi Eric
Yoffie said at the group's 65th General Assembly in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The UAHC has long been in favor of gun control, said Rabbi David
Saperstein, director of the Religious Action Center of Reform
Judaism in Washington. But after the shootings at Columbine High
School near Littleton, Colo., Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth
and a Jewish community center near Los Angeles, gun control gained
top-billing at the UAHC biennial convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been an important issue,'' Saperstein said.
``What is new is that the president of our movement urged our
congregations to make this a major priority for the coming year.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its emphasis on gun control, the Religious Action
Center is urging local synagogues to launch voter registration
drives, Saperstein said. The center also has developed a package of
educational materials that will be sent to hundreds of Reform and
socially active synagogues. The packets include suggestions on how
to teach conflict resolution and organize local gun turn-in
programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue we can actually do something about,''
Saperstein said. ``It is the lack of political will or willingness
to stand up to the gun lobby that has thwarted Congress for many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control has long been an issue some religious organizations
have tried to do something about.
</P>
<P>
   The Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) first adopted a resolution
favoring controls on the sale and possession of guns in 1968, said
the Rev. Kathy Lancaster, the denomination's associate for criminal
justice national ministries.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church has in its ``Book of Resolutions''
statements in support of federal legislation to regulate the
``importation, manufacturing, sale and possession of guns and
ammunition by the general public.'' The resolution calls for a U.S.
ban on handguns with exceptions for police, military security
guards and pistol clubs. It also supports a ban on assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic bishops also have made statements on violence and
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But not all groups of faith have taken a stand on this issue.
The Southern Baptist Convention does not have a resolution on the
books regarding gun control, said Dwayne Hastings, spokesman for
the convention's Ethics and Religious Liberty Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he was not sure why the convention had not tackled
the issue but guessed that perhaps there was ``not a consensus of
belief within the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptists, if nothing else, are very diverse at their being,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though religious organizations have resolutions in favor of gun
control, opinions on the matter may vary within the membership,
said Bill Powers, director of public affairs for the National Rifle
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would only hope that religious organizations would respect
the right for law-abiding citizens to peacefully own firearms as
they would expect citizens to respect freedom of speech and
religion,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pages of paper produced by some religious
organizations, control of guns has rarely topped the list of issues
that grab the attention of the faithful, said Mike Beard, president
of the Coalition to Stop Gun Violence, a research, education and
lobby group founded more than 25 years ago by the United Methodist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those issues that sort of bubbles along near the
top but never breaks through to the top,'' said Beard, whose
organization counts many religious organizations among its 45
members.
</P>
<P>
   In part, gun control gets lost in the shuffle because it's a
perennial issue for many religious organizations, Saperstein said.
With high-profile debates within denominations about homosexuality
or abortion, gun control sometimes loses its urgency.
</P>
<P>
   But religious organizations have a powerful _ if not always
well-funded _ voice on Capitol Hill, Saperstein and other religious
leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   For example, efforts to bring Third World debt to the minds of
congressional leaders has been effective, religious leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an understanding that no response is a political
response,'' said Peter A. Sulyok, coordinator for the social
witness policy for the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A). ``... If you do
not proclaim your faith, then you are allowing other people to make
the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   For Saperstein, ending gun violence by controlling weapons is a
theological imperative for Jews and other people of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are partners with God in helping to shape a fair and more
just world and better world for our children,'' Saperstein said.
``An essential goal that we are entrusted with is shalom (peace).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about bringing peace and healing to a land that
is filled with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
