<SLUG> BC-IRS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS HIRED PROCESSORS WITH CRIMINAL BACKGROUNDS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new government audit faults the Internal Revenue
Service with ``pervasive'' management flaws that included hiring
workers with criminal charges to process cash, checks and taxpayer
information.
</P>
<P>
   The report, to be issued Tuesday by the U.S. General Accounting
office, the non-partisan investigative arm of Congress, also says
the tax-collecting agency can't balance its own books and handles
unpaid assessments poorly, risking ``potentially billions of
dollars in lost revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings in the audit, an advance copy of which was
obtained by Cox Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
   _ The IRS hired 4,835 workers to process tax returns before
receiving results of their fingerprint checks. The agency later
learned that 138 of these employees had questionable backgrounds,
including charges of theft, assault and weapons violations. Of
these workers, 65 were either fired or forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employee thefts of receipts reached a reported total of $1
million in fiscal 1999, the year covered by the audit.
</P>
<P>
   _ At one of the 10 IRS tax processing centers, officials gave a
courier a $28 million deposit without asking for identification,
although the courier was unknown to them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency made $51 million in bookkeeping errors that its own
accountants failed to discover during an unsuccessful attempt to
reconcile IRS accounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly $16 million in ``potentially fraudulent'' refunds were
discovered in the first nine months of last year after the checks
were mailed. But the full amount of the invalid refunds mailed by
the IRS ``could be in the billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency took as much as 10 years to record some tax
payments, and it took longer than the law allows to remove tax
liens on property in about a quarter of a sample of cases.
</P>
<P>
   IRS and Treasury Department officials were scheduled to appear
before a House Government Reform subcommittee Tuesday morning to
respond to the critique, the latest in a series on the agency's
persistent management problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the concerns about the IRS operations are similar to
ones raised in audits going back to 1992, when the agency first
began issuing its annual financial statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to GAO's findings, the IRS conceded that
it has systemic problems and blamed the agency's outmoded computers
for many of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wenzel, deputy IRS commissioner for operations, wrote that
``many of the solutions to the IRS's problems can only be found in
new or enhanced automated systems,'' which he said would take years
to bring on line.
</P>
<P>
   The formal response offered no explanation for hiring workers
before criminal background checks were complete. In the past, IRS
officials have blamed such mistakes on the rush of the tax filing
season.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO auditors credited the revenue service with some
improvements in its record-keeping and computer security and for
instituting a new rule forbidding sending large sums of money by
unarmed bicycle couriers.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also concluded, as it did last year, that the huge
100,000-person agency managed to accomplish its central tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the monumental management challenges it faces, in
fiscal year 1999 IRS succeeded in collecting about $1.9 trillion in
taxes, processing hundreds of millions of tax returns, and paying
about $185 billion in refunds to taxpayers,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the auditors said many of the tax returns
could be improper. They cited the politically popular Earned Income
Tax Credit program, which sends payments to working families with
annual incomes of up to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   IRS examiners used a screening process last year that targeted
573,000 tax returns claiming $1.5 billion in credits from the EITC,
and they found $1 billion of the claims to be improper.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO noted that the improper payments were often discovered
after the checks had already been sent.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors also panned the IRS for trying to force its
accounts to match the totals reported by the Treasury Department
going back as far as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is similar to an individual not reconciling his or her
checkbook with monthly bank statements for years, and then
adjusting the checkbook to agree with the balance per the latest
bank statement without first verifying that the bank had not made
any mistakes,'' said the report.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
