A1015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-28 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S `GREAT RIDE' STIRRING THE VOTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ John McCain's insurgent presidential race, as he
points out, has been a ``high wire act.'' But, win or lose, it may
be the only kind of campaign that the Arizona senator can run
because it so closely reflects his risk-filled life.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by strong victories in Michigan and Arizona, McCain's
maverick, anti-establishment campaign is on a roll. But if he
eventually trips and falls, it clearly won't be the worst thing
that has ever happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   Political setbacks and even victories can quickly be put in
perspective by a former Navy pilot who has already survived some
for-real, near-death experiences, including five and one-half years
in a North Vietnamese prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've crashed a few airplanes,'' he told crowds in Michigan
last week. ``I was in a hotel where there were no mints on the
pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   Only months before he was shot down and seriously wounded over
Hanoi, McCain had to scramble for his life in an inferno on the
flight deck of the U.S.S. Forrestal that killed 134 other
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that his campaign style is outspoken, often
humorous and sometimes irreverent. Compared to what he has been
through, the contact sport of politics is almost child's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to take more risks,'' said John Weaver, the Texan
who is political director for McCain's campaign. ``No matter how
tough things may get on the campaign trail, he's been through much
tougher times.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said McCain's entire campaign ``has been a series of
risks,'' including his in-the-face challenge of the Republican
powers-that-be, his open courting of Democrats and his early
decision to ignore the traditional Iowa caucuses and bet on a
strong showing in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for his background, he probably wouldn't be
running, much less running a campaign like this,'' Weaver added.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that McCain has a strong desire to be
president and will continue to fight hard. But his background may
remove any sense of urgency ``that he needs this job in order to
define himself. I don't think you have that with McCain,'' said L.
Tucker Gibson, a political science professor at Trinity University
in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the ``big bounce'' that he enjoyed temporarily after
his victory over Texas Gov. George W. Bush in New Hampshire and the
giant boost that he received from his twin victories in Michigan
and Arizona, McCain has run most of his campaign as an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   He has had less to lose than Bush by constantly talking
on-the-record to reporters on his campaign bus and taking
unscreened questions from voters in dozens of town hall-style
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   When a radio talk show host in New Hampshire asked him on the
morning of the primary what he planned to do while people voted,
McCain joked, ``I may go out and tear down some of my opponents'
signs.''
</P>
<P>
   His accessibility has produced a few awkward moments. Once,
answering a reporter's hypothetical question in New Hampshire, he
initially said he would let his 15-year-old daughter decide whether
to have an abortion if she were to become pregnant. But, realizing
that answer didn't square with his strong anti-abortion message,
the senator later said that he had ``misspoken.``
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, addressing another sensitive subject, McCain
refused to apologize for using an ethnic slur, ``gooks,'' to refer
to his North Vietnamese captors. But he made it clear that he was
talking only about his former guards and not about Vietnamese or
Asians in general.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also can be sarcastic.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting a questioner in New Hampshire who wanted to legalize
marijuana for medicinal purposes, McCain said he disagreed and then
cracked, ``Good luck with your crop.''
</P>
<P>
   And the tough-guy fighter pilot has emerged in recent campaign
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's against me,'' he almost yelled at the high school
rally in Saginaw, Mich. ``All the governors, all the senators. But
we're going to kill them, right?``
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Phoenix, he added: ``We're a high-wire act, an
insurgency campaign, and we've had a great, great ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in fund raising and organization may soon derail the
senator. And the insurgent faces a strong lineup of closed
Republican primaries in new battleground states, where he will have
to wing it without the independents and Democrats who so far have
been crucial to his success.
</P>
<P>
   But, meanwhile, the ``ride'' continues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
