r l BC-WORK-FAMILY-LIFEBEAT-     02-28 1796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-FAMILY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECOMING `MOMMY' AGAIN: HOW TO LEAVE WORK AT THE OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (th) 
 By JULIA A. SAVACOOL 
 c.2000 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clock above Jamie Speyer's desk reads 5:05 p.m. It's 25
minutes until time to pick up her son at day care, and she's still
in her Portland, Ore., office in the middle of preparing for the
next day's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   She calls her husband, Sam, but he's stuck in a meeting. She
dials her neighbor's number, but there's no answer. With no other
choice, Jamie throws her work in her bag, grabs the night's grocery
list, and runs out of the office with a cell phone glued to one
ear.
</P>
<P>
   She makes it to the day care center in time but out of breath,
hurries her son, Jonathan, out the door, and finds herself so
distracted by the mess she left behind at the office that his
cheerful babbles barely register during the car ride.
</P>
<P>
   When she pulls into the driveway, she's relieved to see that Sam
and her 7-year-old, Lynn, are already home. Lynn is eager to see
Jamie, too, and lets her know it by running up to squeeze her,
sending her bag flying through the air, scattering work papers
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thinks it's very funny, but Jamie isn't laughing.
Although she'd been looking forward to being back home with her
family since she left in the morning, her mind is now on overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our best intentions, slipping out of work mode and into
the role of parent doesn't automatically happen just because we've
walked into our home and reunited with our family. Rather, a
successful transition hinges on how quickly we can change our
mindset _ so, of course, shifting gears goes more smoothly at some
times than at others.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there is a five-step plan for those of us who find the
work-to home adjustment challenging.
</P>
<P>
   FIND TIME TO DECOMPRESS
</P>
<P>
   Step one in securing a smooth integration into family life
requires a bit of mental preparation. ``Walking through the front
door when your mind is still on problems at work is like jamming
the air waves,'' said Dr. Susan Heitler, author of ``The Power of
Two: Secrets to a Strong &AMP; Loving Marriage.'' The solution,
according to Heitler, is making a mental shift from focusing on
office issues to your family.
</P>
<P>
   After 2-year-old Matthew's birth Charlotte Friedlander of White
Plains, N.Y., found household life was dominated by her new baby's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At work, I worried about the shopping list that kept growing
or the laundry I hadn't done, while at home I worried about what I
needed to do at the office,'' said Friedlander, who works full-time
for AT&AMP;T. She began using part of her hour-long train commute to
jot down To Do lists of tasks to accomplish that evening. The
result, she says, is that she feels better prepared when she
arrives home, which helps her to relax and enjoy time with her
family more.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents lack the luxury of commuting time for collecting
their thoughts. As a freelance medical writer, editor and mother of
two in Brookline, Mass., Lisa Underhill works primarily from her
house. She spends mornings in her home office while Miranda 5, and
Gabriel 7, are in school, and devotes afternoons to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no clear demarcation for where my work ends and
family life begins,'' Underhill said. ``It's all contained in the
same environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the mental leap from one world to the other can be
difficult, she conceded: ``I'll be playing with the children and
hear my office phone ringing. It's taken some practice, but I've
learned to tell myself `This is family time' and let the answering
machine pick up the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Positive mental imagery can help ease the transition from work
to family, Heitler said. Whether during your commute or on your way
to meet the school bus, before reconnecting as a family, take a few
minutes to escape into fantasy. Picture greeting your kids, hugging
them, asking them about their day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure to focus on the positive ways you will interact with
your family. This puts you in control,'' she said. But avoid
``unrealistic expectations about how your kids or spouse will act,
which sets you up for failure.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, imagining that your tantrum-prone toddler will
suddenly turn into a saint is an unlikely fantasy and one you have
little control over. But imagining that when your child's tantrum
strikes you will respond in a calm loving manner can better prepare
you for the reality of home life.
</P>
<P>
   PUT KIDS FIRST
</P>
<P>
   By the time you walk through the front door, your To Do list is
probably longer than your grocery list: Open the mail, check the
answering machine, start dinner. But for your little one, a
parent's return means it's playtime _ right now! Finding time for
yourself takes sensitivity and planning.
</P>
<P>
   As for those nights when you feel like disappearing into your
bedroom just for a minute to get a little breathing space, think
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking 10'' immediately upon arriving home is not always the
best plan of attack for parents of young children. Dr. Frances
LaBarre, a psychologist in private practice in New York City, said:
``Babies and toddlers may believe that Mommy disappears because
she's angry or doesn't want them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, spend 15 minutes or so with your child when you get
home. This lets him know that his wants are a priority for you,
said LaBarre. ``Your child feels secure knowing that you are tuned
in to his needs. Spending those few minutes focused on your child
reassures him that he is what is most important to you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   BE SURE TO FIND TIME FOR YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   Together, Friedlander and her husband, Michael, have worked out
a routine. When Friedlander returns from work, she relieves the
sitter and spends some time playing games with her son. Half an
hour later Michael arrives home, and while he reacquaints himself
with Matthew, Charlotte takes off for a short jog to clear her head
and have a few minutes of ``me time.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents need to find what works for them, said Dr. Heitler.
``Every family has its own rhythm,'' she said. Good communication
and a joint effort can lead to a routine that works for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Because her husband's long hours as a systems analyst mean he
often arrives home late, Underhill juggles two children, family
dinner preparations and household chores single-handedly on many
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers are always cutting corners to save minutes and the
first thing to go is time for yourself,'' Underhill said.
Unfortunately, this strategy eventually backfires. ``You find
yourself snapping at your kids, or keeping it all inside and just
stewing,'' Underhill admitted. So now, in the midst of chaos,
Underhill reminds herself that once the children are asleep, she
can steal a few moments of relaxation during her nighttime bath.
</P>
<P>
   LET YOUR CHILDREN IN
</P>
<P>
   How you establish a connection with your children can make or
break the rest of the evening. A friendly hug and warm words are
the first steps toward breaking down the walls we erect around
ourselves during the, workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work and home are two very different cultures,'' Heitler said.
``It's like speaking a different language. It can take time to
decompress from the pressure of job situations.''
</P>
<P>
   You can ease the transition by saving any serious discussions
with your kids until you've had a chance to settle in. ``As a rule
of thumb,'' said Heitler, ``reserve touchy topics for a time when
you are neither tired nor hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling irritable can instigate unpleasantness that might
otherwise have been avoided. In other words, now may not be the
time to lecture your child about doing chores.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you've had a particularly rough day at work? Should
you tell your children? Absolutely, said Underhill. ``I don't
unload on them, but it I'm honest. I explain that Mom is cranky but
it has nothing to do with them. Sometimes, they'll give me a big
hug and say 'It's OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   LaBarre agreed: ``If you are feeling really stressed, don't
ignore your own needs,'' but rather than pushing your kids away,
let them be involved. The key is to get yourself in the moment and
be present for your child even if you're not feeling so hot.
</P>
<P>
   You might say, ``I'm so glad to be home and to see you,
sweetheart, but I've had a hard day. I want very much to see the
picture you drew today, but first Mommy has to put her purse down,
take off her coat, and write a note to herself. Why don't you come
with me and keep me company while I do it?''
</P>
<P>
   This way you include your child in your transition, LaBarre
said, and your stress can be soothed by what you both were looking
forward to all day: spending time together at home.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE IT MEMORABLE
</P>
<P>
   ``Transition time can become a period of celebration for a
family,'' Heitler said. Occasional treats, for example _ such as
having a favorite breakfast food, like pancakes, for dinner or
drawing a picture before eating supper _ can be a great way to
start the evening off on the right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Easing into family time with a good children's book is another
great starter because it helps you unwind and helps your children
focus and calm down from afternoon activities.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, along with the happy days, we all have some
not-so-great periods of family time. But knowing how to avoid
uncomfortable or upsetting snags in the job-home transition process
puts you one step closer to end-of-the-day success.
</P>
<P>
   After all, since work meets family at least five times a week,
this is one rendezvous that is important to get right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julia A. Savacool frequently writes about health and well-being
issues for Child magazine. She lives in New York City.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
