<P>
   GOP-GOVERNORS (Washington) _ Four Republican governors who have
endorsed Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the Republican nomination
say they will work hard to elect Sen. John McCain if he wins the
nomination. One of the governors says a McCain-Bush ticket or a
Bush-McCain ticket would be a ``blockbuster.'' By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-McCAIN (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ John McCain stood in the
headquarters of the Christian right and slammed its top two leaders
as ``agents of intolerance.'' He said that Republican leaders,
including rival George W. Bush, are ``pandering to the outer
reaches of America'' to the detriment of the GOP. Bush responded
that McCain ``obviously wants to divide people into camps'' and
accused him of playing on ``religious fears.'' By GREG McDONALD and
R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-PARTY (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ In Cleveland last week an
angry woman shoved a leaflet at a young man suggesting that John
McCain would not protect the rights of the unborn. ``They're trying
to do everything they can to stop him _ even lies,'' the woman, a
McCain supporter, told him. The leaflet is an example of some of
the tactics being used by Republican leaders and their allies in
special interest groups that are opposed to campaign finance reform
and other issues McCain has championed. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Seattle) _ Al Gore has a solid lead, and he knows
it. With the closest thing to a Democratic primary in Washington
state Tuesday, Gore is trying to protect that lead with few news
conferences, no new policy initiatives and few attacks on former
Sen. Bill Bradley. Bradley, however, is campaigning all out in
</P>
<P>
   Washington state, hoping for a win to jumpstart his lagging
effort. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-MOTHERS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to decide
whether public hospitals can test pregnant women for drugs without
their consent and then tell the police if they test positive. The
court will examine a Charleston, S.C., hospital's policy designed
to find pregnant women who use drugs, especially crack cocaine. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS (Mexico City) _ As the Clinton administration nears
a Wednesday deadline in deciding which countries to certify as
drug-war allies, it is becoming increasing apparent that drug
addiction, which has long been a U.S. problem, is now becoming a
challenge for a growing number of Mexican families. By MICHAEL
RILEY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEAP-YEAR-BIRTHDAY (San Antonio) _ Mary Medina will mark a
milestone on Tuesday. And in preparation, her closest friends
organized her ``quince anera'' on Saturday, maintaining the
Hispanic tradition of celebrating when a girl turns 15. But Medina,
who was born in another leap year _ 1940 _ is really marking 60
years of life that has included marriage and motherhood. By DANIEL
J. VARGAS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Humor, when used carefully, can be a
political asset in a campaign. But spontaneous wit can get the
gagster in trouble, as Sen. John McCain occasionally discovers.
Still, he vows to keep the jokes coming if he wins the White House
``to lighten things up.'' By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ John McCain's insurgent presidential
race, as he points out, has been a ``high wire act.'' But, win or
lose, it may be the only kind of campaign that the Arizona senator
can run because it so closely reflects his risk-filled life. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
