<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CHAIRMAKING-LIFEBEAT-     02-28 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAIRMAKING-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,100&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRASH COURSE IN CRAFTSMANSHIP AT THE WINDSOR INSTITUTE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Color photos to
illustrate this article are available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  (th) 
 By MATTHEW HOLM 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it has something to do with our goal-oriented American
lifestyle, but many of today's travelers are going on vacation not
to relax and ``do nothing,'' but rather to attempt an activity
they've never tried before, learning new skills along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Busy people are definitely ``trying to maximize their vacation
time,'' said Caroline Haberfeld, editor of Fodor's Great American
Learning Vacations (Fodor's; $17). Whether they enjoy cooking,
gardening or woodworking, more and more Americans are choosing to
visit interesting, out-of-the-way destinations where they can
pursue new interests and bring home more than just snapshots or a
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: the 15 men, including myself, who traveled to
Mike Dunbar's Windsor institute, in Hampton, N.H. Over the course
of five eight-hour days, we hoped to learn how to transform pieces
of raw oak and pine into sack-back Windsor chairs that we would be
proud to display in our living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   My classmates included contractors, a carpenter, an engineer, an
anesthesiologist and a nurse anesthesiologist (co-workers who came
together), a truck driver and a retired shop teacher, among others.
Nearly all have workshops in their garages or basements. Most of
these people, however, rarely find the time to use them. Planning a
vacation at the Windsor Institute forces some 300 people a year to
set aside enough time to actually complete a project.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students received this ``learning vacation'' as a
birthday or anniversary gift from their wives. But pupils often
bring their families along: While students wrestle with wood,
spouses and children can relax and play in Hampton, a historic
seaside resort located less than an hour's drive north of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Skill levels varied widely in my class. I was admittedly the
least-experienced woodworker in the bunch, but Dunbar was quick to
tell me not to be intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a Windsor chair is the great equalizer,'' he
proclaimed. ``When people tell me they don't have any experience, I
say, 'No problem. You can make a chair because it's like nothing
else you've ever done.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he was right. I could immediately tell by the awkward ways
in which other students handled the unfamiliar drawknife, pommel
knife, scorp, gutter adze, spokeshave, travisher, reamer and spoon
bit that all the carpentry experience in the world does not matter
if you've never laid eyes on any of the specialized tools before.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar discussed the history and characteristics of the Windsor
chair for a few hours the first morning, then we headed to the
shop: four students to a bench, each with his own vise.
</P>
<P>
   We gathered to watch as Dunbar demonstrated each step in the
process. Afterward, we would set out to try the technique ourselves
while Dunbar and his assistant, Dan Faia, circulated among us,
offering hands-on help when needed.
</P>
<P>
   We started out with lengths of unshaped, split red oak, which we
fashioned into bows, arms and spindles using a drawknife, a
spokeshave and a plane. Each task posed a new challenge, but the
learning curve was quick: The first back spindle I whittled was
precariously thin; my seventh looked nearly as round and even as
one of Dunbar's.
</P>
<P>
   The most invigorating _ that is to say, terrifying _ step may
have been shaping the seat. To hollow out the saddle, we laid the
rough pine plank on the floor and, standing on top of it to keep it
in place, swung an axlike gutter adze into the wood, just a few
inches from our toes. It sounds risky, but as Dunbar assured us,
``No one has ever drawn blood.'' Still, I'm glad I wore work boots.
</P>
<P>
   While my classmates were all male, many classes are coed. One
out of every 10 students is a woman, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see my tool bag,'' said Brandy Ward, of Nashua,
N.H., who made a sack-back at the Windsor Institute last year.
Ward, who had scant woodworking experience, almost did not take the
class after she was discouraged by a professional chairmaker who
``just didn't think a woman _ especially one with no experience _
could make a chair. Fortunately, Mike told me different,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Building Windsors can be habit-forming _ one of my classmates
had come back to Hampton for his third session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stated purpose is to have you go home and make more
chairs,'' Dunbar said. Just be careful that you don't suddenly find
yourself in the chairmaking business, as some 10 percent of
graduates do. ``And never sell a chair that you've made,'' he
warned jokingly. ``For me, this was just a hobby that got out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   After five days of whittling, drilling and gluing, my chair was
assembled and surprisingly sturdy. I brought it home to my wife,
who is trying to decide where to place it in our apartment _
perhaps beside the writing desk in the foyer. I'll leave that up to
her; I'm too busy trying to figure out how I might fit a workbench
and a steam box into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Wood and instruction for the Windsor Institute's sack-back class
cost $600; prices for advanced classes vary. Faia also offers a
tool-sharpening course the Sunday before each five-day session and
a finishing class the Saturday after for $100 each.
</P>
<P>
   Call Dunbar (603-929-9801) for recommendations about local
lodging, food and transportation, as well as a materials list. The
institute will lend out a number of woodworking tools, but many
students prefer to buy their own.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   OTHER WORKSHOPS
</P>
<P>
   Each summer, women escape to Marshall, N.C. (nestled in the
Smoky Mountains), for Country Workshops' women-only wood working
course. Relaxed and noncompetitive, the class teaches women basic
carpentry skills as they each build a small cabinet (828 656-2280).
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the state, any would-be woodworker can spend
a week on Albemarle Sound in Hertford, N.C., at the picturesque
Beechtree Inn. There, Benjamin C. Hobbs shows how to craft a Queen
Anne-style bench or a queen-sized pencil post bed (252-426-7815).
</P>
<P>
   For an urban workshop experience, visit John
Alexander/Greenwoodworking in Baltimore, where students make chairs
and stools from lumber they've split from logs (410-685-4375).
</P>
<P>
   And at the Woodworker Academy in Alameda, Calif., across the bay
from San Francisco, students can learn to make anything from a
small sofa table to a wall-size display cabinet (510-521-1623).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
