<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      02-28 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MENTAL HEALTH: When Despair Invades the Blood Vessels &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Feeling hopeless is not just unpleasant: it may also be bad for
the health.
</P>
<P>
   A study suggests that people suffering persistent periods of
hopelessness may be at greater risk for hypertension, researchers
at the University of Michigan report. Their study, in the latest
issue of the journal Hypertension, said they had come to their
conclusion after analyzing health records of 616 middle-aged men
who took part in a major study in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Over four years, 20 percent of the men studied became
hypertensive, defined as having blood pressure above 165 over 95.
But the figure shot up to 37 percent of the men considered ``high
in hopelessness'' and 23 percent of those considered to feel
moderately hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling hopeless is often a sign of depression, but the
researchers said it appeared that hopelessness was a better
indicator of potential hypertension problems than depression.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TESTING: Early Intervention for Babies' Ears &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new team of researchers has weighed into the debate over
whether infants should be routinely screened for hearing loss at
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Although some experts believe that such testing is unwarranted,
researchers from the University of Colorado at Boulder are offering
evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a meeting last week of the American Association for
the Advancement of Science, Dr. Christine Yoshinaga-Itano said that
earlier detection and action helped hearing-impaired children
achieve normal language skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studies of more than 350 deaf and hard of hearing children
show a very short critical period of normal language development in
this population,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that when doctors, using state and federal
grants, were able to conduct so-called universal screening of
newborns, congenital hearing loss was identified at about 2 months
of age, instead of what they said was now the average: 2.5 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among deaf children who received their diagnoses by the time
they were 6 months old and received treatment, 90 percent developed
vocabulary skills for use in sign language that were considered
within the range of normal. Of those identified as having hearing
problems later in life, only the top 25 percent were able to gain a
vocabulary similar to the bottom 10 percent of children with normal
language development.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SENSATIONS: Acquiring a Taste for Cold Weather &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's not just various foods that cause the tongue to experience
the pleasures and discomforts of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Yale say they have proven that the four major
tastes _ sweet, sour, salty and bitter _ can, under the right
conditions, also be produced by changing the temperature of taste
buds. Warm tastes sweet and sometimes bitter; cold can seem salty
or sour.
</P>
<P>
   Why? No one is certain. It may be part of the body's attempt to
make sense of the mass of information it gets from food, said Dr.
Barry Green, an otolaryngologist, who reported the findings in
Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said they were simply examining the temperature
sensitivity of taste buds when they made the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   A research assistant, Alberto Cruz, detected a slight sweet
taste when a tiny part of his tongue was chilled and then reheated.
Similar results occurred when the researchers tried to test
themselves. Then, they decided to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   When they tested 24 subjects, 21 said they could discern at
least one kind of taste associated with temperature, and 19 could
taste two or more.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, it is not clear how much this all affects
a person's sense of taste (although it raises the possibility that
some people may experience ice cream as being ``saltier'' than
others).
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the effect, Green said, the tongue, must first be
chilled to 68 degrees and then rewarmed _ ``and that just doesn't
happen in the course of normal eating.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: The Two Worlds of Teen-age Pregnancy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The United States may be at the top by most economic measures,
but for an important measure of social health _ teen-age pregnancy
and childbearing _ it moves among the poorest.
</P>
<P>
   American teen-agers are best compared to those in the Russian
federation or in depressed Eastern European countries like
Bulgaria, a new study finds. Teen-age pregnancy and childbearing
rates here are at least four times those in France, Germany and
Japan, said researchers from Alan Guttmacher Institute, which
researches reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's president, Sara Reims, said the problem was in
part the result of poverty and inequity, but also the reflection of
insufficient sex education and low-cost, easily obtainable
contraception. ``Our young people deserve better,'' she said in a
statement, adding that Americans had much to learn from Western
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the 1990s, the report said, Americans saw a 17 percent
decline in adolescent pregnancy and childbirth. This mirrored a
larger trend over the last 25 years among industrialized nations,
as well as an overall decline in childbearing among women of all
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers suggest that the decline was a result of several
factors, including greater emphasis on education and employment,
more motivation to delay sexual intercourse among teen-agers, and
whatever their limits, improved sex education and contraception.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher said the most recent birthrate among girls 15 to
19 was 54 per 1,000 in the United States, 49.6 in Bulgaria, 10 in
France and 3.9 in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROGNOSIS: Undue Optimism When Death Is Near &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it just doesn't pay to be optimistic, or, at least,
overly so.
</P>
<P>
   A new study reports that doctors who treat terminally ill people
routinely overestimate how much time their patients have left, and,
as a result, may deprive them of the kind of care they need.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Chicago studied the cases of
343 doctors and 468 patients admitted to hospices over 130 days in
1996. Dr. Nicholas A. Christakis and his colleagues, reporting in
the British Medical Journal, asked the doctors to predict how long
their patients would live. The median survival was 24 days, but
some 63 percent of the doctors overestimated the time, by a factor
of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the implications were troubling: the optimism could
delay referral to hospices, which emphasize management of pain and
grief. This could explain why patients on average spend about a
month in hospice care, when the ideal is considered to be three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors who do not realize how little time is left may miss
the chance to devote more of it to improving the quality of
patients' remaining life,'' the researchers wrote. And, they added,
the doctors may contribute to patients' making bad choices,
including seeking aggressive but futile treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the better doctors knew their patients, the
more optimistic the doctors seemed to become. One solution, they
said, may be to get second opinions from disinterested
practitioners, especially specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who know our patients longer often become attached
to them,'' Dr. Julia L. Smith, medical director of a hospice in
Rochester, N.Y., wrote in an accompanying article. ``We, too, hate
to admit that death is near.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
