<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REARWINDOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE LIKES TO WATCH. AND SO DO WE. WHY `REAR WINDOW' STILL
MESMERIZES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm a mystery woman. Let me rephrase that: I'm a woman who loves
a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Paperback sleuth stories? I use them up faster than Hercule
Poirot uses up mustache wax. TV lawyer shows with unexpected
twists? I've got a regular Wednesday night date with Lennie Briscoe
and ``Law &AMP; Order.'' Big-screen thrillers? I'm there before you can
say whodunit.
</P>
<P>
   So I speak from a position of some experience when I say that
one of the best suspense movies ever made is about to hit movie
theaters _ again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window,'' a diamond in Alfred Hitchcock's gem case and my
personal, all-time, latte-mug-runneth-over favorite movie, was
re-released to movie theaters in a restored version over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this 1954 film so special?
</P>
<P>
   First, the cacophony of city life. The story takes place in an
apartment building in Greenwich Village where a photojournalist is
confined to his home by a cast the length of his leg. Having
planted himself beside a window overlooking the building's
courtyard _ the rear window _ the bored and cranky ``Jeff'' passes
his days by watching his neighbors. The camera spins 'round the
building: There's the frustrated composer, the dancer, the
quarreling couple, the newlyweds, Miss Lonely Heart. We see their
stories as Jeff sees them, peeking through their windows, sneaking
into their lives. Music spills into the courtyard, as does a little
dog.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery itself is small. No tale of international intrigue,
just an ordinary little murder. But the suspense in the final third
of the movie is as hold-your-breath thrilling as any of Hitchcock's
best, with the photographer's inability to move out of harm's way
adding to the feeling of terror.
</P>
<P>
   There's a top-notch cast. Jimmy Stewart as Jeff is smart,
intensely restless and just a bit dark in his obsession with his
neighbors' business.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Burr, a friend of mine from old ``Perry Mason'' shows
(did I mention that I like mysteries?), is a surly villain. Thelma
Ritter's wry nurse adds a dose of humor.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's ice princess Grace Kelly at her elegant best.
Though I could picture other actors in Stewart's role, it's hard to
imagine any other actress bringing such supreme confidence to the
role of Stewart's society girl/model girlfriend, Lisa, who gamely
jumps into the fray. What woman wouldn't secretly want to be Lisa?
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this add up to? Let's just say it's no mystery
where I was Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      02-28 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: LINKING ALLERGY, ASTHMA AND INFANT DIETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Calif., Ariz.)   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Allergies and asthma in children are on the rise in
industrialized countries and medical scientists are searching for
ways to stem this mysterious trend.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had long assumed that exclusive breast-feeding for at
least the first six months of life and delaying the introduction of
allergenic foods like peanuts, cow's milk and eggs was the best way
to stave off allergies. But several new studies indicate that there
are limits to the long-term effectiveness of this approach for
babies most at risk for developing allergies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast-feeding is still good, still the best way to feed a
baby, but if the parents are highly allergic, the baby can still
get allergies,'' said Dr. Yalamanchi K. Rao, a pediatric allergist
affiliated with New York-Methodist Hospital in Brooklyn. ``Mothers
who breast-feed should not be made to feel guilty because their
babies developed allergies.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he and other experts believe that breast-feeding along
with other protective measures can at least postpone if not prevent
the emergence of an inherited allergic tendency.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the value of breast-feeding to a child's health.
In a study of 545 infants published in January 1998 in The British
Medical Journal, Scottish researchers found that those who were
exclusively breast-fed for at least 15 weeks had about half the
risk of getting respiratory infections in the first seven years of
life than did children nursed for shorter periods or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   But a different and more complicated picture emerged regarding
allergy protection. There are a slew of contradictory findings. For
example, a 17-year study of 236 infants in Finland found that
eczema and food and respiratory allergies were significantly
reduced in children who were breast-fed for more than six months.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, last fall a research team from the Arizona
Health Sciences Center in Tucson found in a study of 664 children
followed from birth to age 11 that the allergy-preventing benefits
of breast-feeding depended upon the allergic status of their
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the children whose mothers had low levels of
allergen-provoked antibodies, prolonged breast-feeding was
associated with low allergic responses at ages 6 and 11. But among
the children whose mothers were most allergic, breast-feeding for
four months or longer resulted in more allergic reactions than
shorter periods of breast-feeding or no breast-feeding at all.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tucson researchers suggested a number of possible
explanations, no one yet knows the real reason. One possibility for
which there is some evidence is that one of the main benefits of
breast-feeding _ its ability to protect babies against infections _
may indirectly increase allergic tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the best of circumstances, a balance develops in babies
between two kinds of immune-response cells, Th1 , which helps to
fight off infections, and Th2 , which sets off an allergic response
to innocent proteins. When babies are challenged by infectious
organisms, as most babies are in the developing world, the Th1
response is primed and predominates over Th2. But when babies are
protected against infection by a semisterile diet, the Th2 system
may have an opportunity to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   A study of 480 air force cadets in Italy, published in February
in The British Medical Journal, lends support to this explanation.
The researchers found that respiratory allergies were less frequent
in the cadets who had been heavily exposed to infectious organisms
transmitted through foods and water. They suggested that ``hygiene
and a Westernized semisterile diet'' might foster allergies by
changing the pattern of normal and pathogenic organisms in the gut,
``thus contributing to the epidemic of allergic asthma and rhinitis
in developed countries.''
</P>
<P>
   What, then, is a mother to do? For starters, whenever possible,
babies should be fed the colostrum produced by the breast right
after childbirth before the mother's milk comes in. Colostrum is
rich in a substance called transforming growth factor-beta
(TGF-beta) that induces tolerance to substances in foods that might
otherwise provoke an allergic response, like eczema, in the infant.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, TGF-beta fosters maturation of the babies' gut,
which would also promote tolerance and prevent food allergies later
in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of further protective measures should be based on a
baby's risk of developing allergies. If neither parent has
allergies, their offspring have a 10 percent chance of developing
allergies. If one parent is allergic, the risk rises to about 20
percent to 30 percent. And if both parents are allergic, their
children have a 40 percent to 70 percent chance of also developing
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Dr. Robert S. Zeiger, chief of allergy at the Kaiser
Permanente Medical Center in San Diego, among infants at high risk
of developing allergies showed that those who were given no cow's
milk, eggs and peanuts during infancy and whose mothers also
avoided those foods while breast-feeding developed fewer food
allergies and less eczema in the first two years of life. Other
potentially allergenic foods that might be avoided by both the
infant and nursing mother include fish and shellfish, soy milk,
chocolate, strawberries and tree nuts. However, before giving
birth, it is no longer considered necessary for a woman to avoid
such foods if she is planning to breast- feed.
</P>
<P>
   Rao urges allergic mothers who intend to breast-feed their
babies to insist that the babies not be given any formula in the
hospital, a practice that is common when the mother is asleep at
feeding time. Even one or two bottles of a cow's milk formula may
be enough to sensitize a newborn infant and cause an allergic
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   If a nursing mother trying to curb allergies in her baby is not
going to be around for a feeding, she should pump breast milk and
store it to be fed to the baby while she is away. Alternatively,
the baby can be given a hypoallergenic formula _ Nutramigen or
Alimentum _ in which the cow's milk proteins have been broken down
to a point where they would not provoke an allergic response.
</P>
<P>
   No solid foods should be given to the baby before 6 months of
age, and then foods should be introduced one at a time, starting
with rice cereal prepared with water, then vegetables, then fruit
(with citrus fruits last). Peanuts and egg whites should not be
given before one year of age. The yolk is OK if the egg is first
hard-boiled and the yolk removed free of any contaminating white.
Make sure to avoid feeding prepared foods, like ice cream and
cookies, that are made with whole eggs or egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the risk of respiratory allergies, smoking should not
be allowed anywhere in the baby's environment, a Hepa air filter
should be used in the baby's room, the crib mattress should be
enclosed in an allergen-proof cover, no stuffed animals should be
in the baby's room and no furry or feathery pets should be in the
baby's home. Adults who regularly care for the baby should avoid
handling allergenic pets. And the baby's clothes and bedding should
be washed with a mild, unscented detergent like Arm &AMP; Hammer and
rinsed twice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
