<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Feb. 29. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-U.S. (Beijing) _ A request by Taiwan to buy one of the
American Navy's most advanced warships has caused a split in the
Clinton administration and threatens to complicate the delicate
three-way relationship among Taiwan, China and the United States.
By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MOTHERS-DRUGS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to
hear a case from South Carolina over the practice of a city-owned
hospital that routinely and secretly tested women coming in to give
birth for drugs, and then told the police about positive results.
Critics say it amounts to an illegal search. By Linda Greenhouse.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-RIGHT (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ Taking his presidential
campaign to a stronghold of Christian conservatism, Arizona Sen.
John McCain delivered a harsh attack Monday on the ``self-appointed
leaders'' of the religious right, depicting them as egotistical and
intolerant empire builders who ``have turned good causes into
businesses'' while attempting to exclude all but ``card-carrying
Republicans'' from the party. McCain singled out for criticism two
of the Christian right's best-known leaders, Pat Robertson, the
founder of the Christian Coalition, and the Reverend Jerry Falwell,
founder of the Moral Majority. He compared Robertson to ``union
bosses who have subordinated the interests of working families to
their own ambitions,'' and he accused both men of attempting to
distort his pro-life position and ``smear the reputations of my
supporters.'' By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SHELTERS (Washington) _ Calling the rapid growth of abusive
corporate tax shelters ``the most serious compliance issue
threatening the American tax system today,'' Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers in a speech Monday announced a three-prong
attack against corporate conduct that ``undermines the integrity of
the tax system.'` By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-RETIRE (New York) _ Ending one of the most
extraordinary careers in American finance, John S. Reed, co-chief
executive of financial services giant Citigroup, said he plans to
retire on April 18. Upon the 61-year-old Reed's departure, the
chief executive's reins at the company will be held solely by
Sanford I. Weill, who helped Reed orchestrate the megamerger of
Citicorp and Travelers Group to create Citigroup in 1998. By
Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DEBATE (Undated) _ A recent study by the research
arm of the National Academy of Sciences has declared that the
``apparent disparity'' between surface and atmospheric temperatures
``in no way invalidates the conclusion that surface temperature has
been rising.'' The surface warming ``is undoubtedly real,'' the
study panel said. But the dissenters are a long way from conceding
the climate debate, and they have seized on some other aspects of
the panel's report in an effort to bolster their case. By William
K. Stevens. (2075 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-DISPARITY (Undated) _ Two skeptics in the climate
debate discovered that in some ways the satellite and surface
trends roughly matched. Both sets of measurements found substantial
warming over Northern Hemisphere continents, for instance, and the
timing of year-to-year temperature fluctuations was about the same
in both. But unlike the surface record, the satellites revealed no
underlying warming trend for much of the free atmosphere, up to
about five miles, mainly in the tropics. In fact, the raw numbers
showed a cooling there. By William K. Stevens. (850 words).
</P>
