A1059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-POLL-HNS &LR;      02-28 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN GAINS ON BUSH IN CALIFORNIA PRIMARY  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush retains his
comfortable lead over Sen. John McCain in the California primary
jackpot, but a new survey shows the Arizona senator is gaining more
Republican converts as the two presidential hopefuls fight for the
soul of their party.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed Vice President Al Gore maintaining a
commanding lead over former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley in the
Democratic primary. Bradley's message that Gore is too conservative
apparently has not impressed increasingly wealthy and older
California voters.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted for the San Francisco Examiner and
KTVU-TV by the Research 2000 polling organization in Rockville, Md.
Both the Democratic and Republican primaries are March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has made big gains in California, McCain's challenge
remains large. The poll showed that Bush, who is supported by most
of the GOP's upper echelon, still leads McCain among all voters
and, crucially, would beat him by an 11-point margin among
rank-and-file Republicans. Although Democrats and independents can
vote for a Republican in California's primary, registered
Republicans are the only ones who count in selecting delegates to
the national convention this summer in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain is gaining ground. In an Examiner/KTVU poll taken
last month, he had only 16 percent of the Republican vote compared
with 49 percent for Bush, with 24 percent undecided. Now, according
to the new poll, McCain has nearly doubled his Republican base and
doubled his support among all California voters surveyed,
independents and Democrats included.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show California could provide this unconventional
campaign with another shocker. Democratic voters who believe Gore
is the sure winner, as the polls show, could defect during the
primary and vote for McCain in large numbers. McCain could win the
beauty contest among all California voters, while Bush could get
the GOP votes and all 162 delegates for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters and advisers don't buy the split-decision
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great, fun diversion,'' said state Sen. Jim Brulte,
a Republican from Rancho Cucamonga, ``but I think the one who gets
the most Republican votes is also going to be the one who is the
first vote-getter in California, and I expect that to be George W.
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5
percentage points, was conducted Feb. 21 through 23 among 803
Californians who say they regularly vote. Among Republican voters
only, the margin of error is 6 percentage points because the sample
size is smaller.
</P>
<P>
   When the poll was taken, McCain was coming off a stinging defeat
in South Carolina, then surging with an important win in Michigan
and Arizona. So the survey results could show an unrealistic
``bounce'' in favor of McCain, said the Research 2000 pollster, Del
Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the poll shows GOP voters statewide are
increasingly split between McCain and Bush, who only weeks ago was
perceived as the anointed nominee. While rank-and-file Republicans
favor Bush by wider margins, McCain is attracting a healthy number
of Democrats and a huge number of independent voters _ the same
scenario that gave him victories in the Michigan and New Hampshire
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The poll shows that McCain, however, suffers from a gender gap.
Women voters are more likely to pick Bush than McCain if they are
voting for a Republican. Gore does the best among women voters
overall, followed by Bush. Among ethnic groups, McCain doesn't
appear to have suffered from his use of the word ``gook'' to
describe his captors during the Vietnam War. He gets just about the
same amount of support from Asian voters as Bradley and Gore in
one-on-one matchups.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans only 35 percent of the voting electorate in
California, Bush acknowledges he will have to reach out to
Democrats and others during the general election. But right now his
fight is for Republicans and ``like-minded'' independents, and he
said Democrats might try to ``hijack' the GOP primary by voting for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus is on GOP delegates,'' Bush said. ``If I were
cruising along and winning every primary, it would be one thing.
But I'm in a battle. I've won some and I've lost some. ... There is
going to be ample time to set the tone for the general election
between when the nomination is secure and when people start paying
attention to general election politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said: ``What has been
disconcerting has been the attempt by partisan Democrats to make
mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has drawn parallels to his efforts to broaden the
Republican appeal to that of Ronald Reagan, the former president
and California governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting the Reagan coalition back together,'' said Dan
Schnur, McCain's communications director. ``Independents and swing
Democrats have been crossing over to vote for John McCain because
they want to get the special interests out of government. They've
been hearing his message of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Republican fight is over who could beat Gore, the
presumed Democratic nominee, in the November general election. The
Examiner/KTVU poll shows Bush losing to Gore by 7 percentage points
and he is statistically tied with Bradley. McCain is virtually tied
with Gore and beats Bradley by 5 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
