<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and cold winds will persist across eastern Maine on
Tuesday as wet snow tapers off near the Canadian border. Low
pressure east of Sable Island will move slowly into the North
Atlantic. The remainder of the Northeast will be bright, but breezy
and not quite as cool. High pressure crested over the Carolinas
will promote very pleasant weather from the Appalachians to the
central Gulf coast. Abundant sunshine will combine with light
breezes and low humidity to produce a pristine day.
</P>
<P>
   A flow of warmer and more humid air from the western Gulf into
the Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes will trigger showers and a
few thunderstorms in the eastern Plains and the western Lakes.
Gusty breezes from the south will reach 30 mph or more in Oklahoma,
Missouri and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Two low-pressure systems will move east in tandem across the
Plains. The stronger disturbance in Manitoba will push a cold front
into Minnesota and eastern Nebraska. The second low, over Kansas,
will drag a front into north Texas and New Mexico. Only slightly
cooler air will follow in the Rockies and northwest Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Fair and seasonable conditions will dominate the Southwest with
high pressure over the Four Corners. A new surge of cool, moist air
from the north Pacific will enter the West Coast from San Francisco
to Seattle, with rain in the lower elevations and decreasing snow
levels in the Cascades and northern Sierra. A gusty cold wind will
be noted at the shore. Clouds and showers will reach the interior
West and parts of southern California at night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Leap Day Records
</P>
<P>
   February 29, that exceptional calendar date that poses problems
for programmers, also creates conundrums for climatologists. How
special are records set on this date compared to the rest of the
year? Of course, there are fewer occurrences of February 29 than
any other dates. Therefore, the chance of recording an extreme
value is greater than on February 28 or March 1, since the range of
weather conditions recorded for the 29th is less. But, February 29
occurs only once in four years, so the opportunity to rewrite the
record book is reduced by 75 percent compared to other dates.
</P>
</TEXT>
