<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Life After Pollution &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Few structures have come to symbolize environmental decay better
than industrial-size metal smelters. They are often huge, hulking
monsters, belching plumes of pollutants skyward and surrounded by
slag heaps.
</P>
<P>
   So it is nice to know that if a smelter cleans up its act, the
impact can be felt relatively quickly. That is the conclusion of a
study of two species of insect-eating birds near a copper smelter
in southwest Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The study by two Finnish ecologists, reported in the journal
Nature, showed that the birds' breeding success improved over seven
years as emissions of heavy metals were reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies of the birds near the smelter had shown that one
species, the pied flycatcher, produced smaller clutches of eggs,
and that both it and the other species, the great tit, produced
fewer live fledglings. The eggshells were thin and porous,
conditions linked to consumption of heavy metals, which found their
way into tree leaves, then into leaf-munching insects, then into
the insect-munching birds.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1997, pollution controls were instituted at the
smelter, resulting in the reduction of lead and other contaminants
by as much as 95 percent. Over that period, at points within about
a mile of the smelter, the average number of eggs for the
flycatcher increased, as did the average number of fledglings for
both species.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the pollutants had a chain effect, so too, apparently,
did the cleaner air. The scientists suggest that the improved
conditions led to the recovery of local forest vegetation. Better
foliage growth, in turn, aided the recovery of insect populations,
and more insects meant more larvae for the birds to feed their
young.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Bug's Bug &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Desert locusts are usually loners, but when they get together,
often by the billions, the result can be widespread destruction of
crops. What causes these grasshoppers to swarm, at least in part,
is their sense of smell: they detect pheromones and other compounds
in their feces and in the surrounding air that lead to behavioral
changes, turning solitary insects into gregarious ones.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists have determined the source of one pheromone
component, and it is an unlikely one. The chemical, guaiacol, is
produced not by the locust itself but by bacteria in its gut. It is
a bug that helps cause the bugs to swarm.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the University of Bath in England, showed
that bacteria were responsible by raising locusts without them in
the laboratory. Analysis of the fecal pellets of these germ-free
insects showed an absence of guaiacol; later experiments, using
locusts with just one species of intestinal bacteria, did produce
the chemical. The studies were reported in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers noted that the mix of bacteria in the locust's
gut was a relatively simple one, and was acquired from its food.
The adaptation by the insect of the bacterial-produced chemical,
the researchers suggest, has wide implications for understanding
the roles of gut bacteria in insects.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pickup Up After a Pickup &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Garbage collection is supposed to make a community cleaner, but
a recent University of Florida study has found that this isn't
always the case.
</P>
<P>
   The study, of a 100-home subdivision in Gainesville, Fla.,
showed that on some days, the amount of litter on the streets more
than doubled after garbage trucks came through.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers with the university's Florida Center for Solid and
Hazardous Waste Management said that much of the litter was spilled
when cans were emptied into garbage trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers also said that homeowners were partly to
blame, overstuffing garbage cans and failing to use bags. And even
e-commerce might play a role _ the researchers noted that one of
the biggest litter problems was those foam peanuts used to pack
goods for shipping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
