<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SEX29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAGAZINE SURVEY SHEDS LIGHT ON TEENS' VIEWS ON SEX
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fifty-five percent of American youths aged 15 to 19
have engaged in oral sex, according to a national survey conducted
for seventeen(cq) magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said the survey, conducted at shopping malls
nationwide, was intended to highlight the misconceptions, lack of
information and social pressures that shape teen attitudes toward
sexual issues. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ One-third said they are not getting enough information from
their parents on birth control or on the biological and emotional
aspects of sex.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventy-five percent said they thought sex education should be
taught in schools by the age of 13.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventy-five percent believed that most teens are having sex,
but only 40 percent of them reported having done so.
</P>
<P>
   When the magazine conducted a similar survey in 1991, it didn't
even mention the topic of oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey found that half of teens 15 or older did not
think oral sex was ``as big a deal'' as intercourse, and that only
45 percent thought that it ``counted'' as sex. Fifty-five percent
of respondents thought the practice was ``gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings of the survey:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-four percent said they were not bothered by
homosexuality, compared with 17 percent in the 1991 survey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nineteen percent of boys said peer pressure was their main
influence for having sex, compared to 9 percent of girls.
</P>
<P>
   The firm that conducted the survey collected 1,105
questionnaires from people aged 13 to 19 at shopping malls
nationwide, and the results were weighted to to represent a
national sample.
</P>
<P>
   More details of the survey results will appear in the April
issue of seventeen magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the survey results, the Kaiser Family Foundation
is teaming up with the magazine to launch a year-long campaign
called SexSmarts. Through articles and surveys in both Seventeen
and on the magazine's Web site (seventeen.com), the campaign will
address topics ranging from sexually transmitted diseases to how to
say no to pressure for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
