<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GENES ARE DECODED, WHO SHOULD SEE THE RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (Eds: If you use the GENE-DISCRIM-PRO and GENE-DISCRIM-CON stories,
please include the following precede in italics)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton issued an order this month prohibiting federal
agencies from using genetic information in any decision to hire,
promote or dismiss workers. The order protects 2.8 million federal
employees, and Clinton said Congress should pass legislation to
prevent private employers from discriminating against workers on
the same basis. Such legislation has been introduced by Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., and Rep. Louise M. Slaughter, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As the possibilities for using genetic tests to help identify
people with increased risk of developing certain diseases grows,
The New York Times has asked two experts in the field to examine
the issue and comment on the need for such safeguards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-CON-     02-28 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-CON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN GREATLY OVERESTIMATES THE RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 Mark A. Hall is a professor of law and public health at Wake Forest
University in Winston-Salem, N.C.  
 By MARK A. HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's recent ban on genetic discrimination by
federal agencies is not in response to any widespread practice, or
even any collection of documented cases of agencies' misuse of
genetic information.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the executive order responds to growing, and somewhat
unfounded, fears about the potential misuse of genetics. The main
purpose of this order is to calm public fears to spur development
of genetic technologies and to help genetic researchers recruit
study subjects.
</P>
<P>
   These are worthy goals, but they reveal that this is mostly a
hortatory, not a regulatory, order. In addition to reassuring the
public, the ban on federal agencies is meant to promote a social
norm that private employers will emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Many laws have important symbolic features that shape attitudes.
Fashioning laws for this purpose can be good public policy. The
social impact of genetics is an arena well suited for such
techniques. But symbolic laws can also be poorly designed,
ineffective or have unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Consider similar state laws that bar health insurers from using
genetic information to set rates or determine coverage. My
systematic study of these laws and of industry practices found the
laws are indeed effective in discouraging health insurers from
considering genetic test results.
</P>
<P>
   Even in states without such laws, health insurers have little or
no interest in using predictive genetic information, out of a sense
that this is wrong and legally problematic.
</P>
<P>
   But state health insurance laws have not been effective in
reassuring the public. Patients, geneticists and genetic counselors
greatly overestimate the risk of discrimination by health insurers.
I suspect the same is true for discrimination by employers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, people heavily involved in genetics
underestimate the effectiveness of the state protections, viewing
them as untested and potentially full of loopholes. If anything,
these laws may have worsened the situation by conveying the false
impression that a real problem exists.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a recent study of the Minnesota law limiting
employers' use of genetic information found that it had no effect
and was poorly understood.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that a prominent presidential order will be
more effective. But even if it is, symbolic laws can impose a cost
if they fail to take accurate aim at misuses of genetic information
or to block potentially beneficial uses. This is especially
difficult to do when the law is enacted in advance of any actual
experience.
</P>
<P>
   On first reading, the executive order successfully distinguishes
between good and bad uses of genetics. It clearly bars using
genetic information simply to exclude workers who will have high
health insurance costs. But it allows testing to monitor the
effects of workplace hazards.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to worker qualifications, the order charts a middle
course. It allows federal agencies to consider genetic information
that helps to diagnose an existing condition that might hamper
``essential functions of the position.'' But the order prevents
federal agencies from considering genetic information that is
merely predictive of future conditions or problems.
</P>
<P>
   This compromise may not be as successful as it first appears.
First, with respect to workplace safety, there are two important
uses of genetic technology: screening for susceptibility to toxic
exposure, and monitoring the progressive effects of toxic exposure.
The president's order, for no apparent purpose, allows only the
latter, not the former, at least according to my reading.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the Nuclear Regulatory Commission were subject
to the new order, which it is not now, it could check whether its
inspectors had suffered chromosomal damage from radiation exposure,
but the commission could not screen inspectors for genetic
susceptibility to radiation-induced cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The order has a second potential flaw. It is easy to imagine
situations in which it may be important for an employer to consider
genetic predisposition to future conditions that affect job
performance. Consider, for instance, a hypothetical genetic marker
that strongly predicts sudden, fatal heart attacks. The executive
order would bar using such information to evaluate a candidate for
an air traffic controller's job.
</P>
<P>
   But the order does not bar other, less accurate ways to assess
the same risk. Thus, if the same gene were loosely associated with
another characteristic _ say, premature male balding _ the Federal
Aviation Administration might be tempted to hire younger men only
if they were fully coifed. (This isn't as silly as it seems. Recent
evidence points to statistical association between some types of
heart disease and certain forms of balding.)
</P>
<P>
   The result would be merely to shift the focus of
``discrimination'' to a less accurate, and therefore more
invidious, characteristic. Allowing employers to consider genetic
information might create job opportunities that otherwise would not
exist for some qualified applicants and could conceivably more
accurately bar jobs only to those who were truly risks to public
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, this is a far-fetched hypothetical. But one is
forced into such speculations for the very reason that currently
available genetic information has so little actual relevance to
employment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For now, these potential deficiencies in the order are largely
moot. But, when it becomes more relevant, its hortatory and
regulatory features may come into conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The more finely crafted a law or order is, the more potential
there is for actual or perceived loopholes, and, therefore, the
less protective it will appear to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But making a measure more sweeping will tend to bring its
positive and negative effects into conflict. This uncertainty
should not prevent us from trying, however. It should only caution
us that symbolic laws are not be taken lightly. They too need to be
crafted and monitored with care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
