<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-PRO-     02-28 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENE-DISCRIM-PRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID PROTECTIONS AGAINST INTRUSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 Wendy R. Uhlmann is a genetic counselor at the University of
Michigan and the president of the National Society of Genetic
Counselors.  
 By WENDY R. UHLMANN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's executive order on genetic discrimination is
a significant step toward ensuring that advances in genetics will
be to the benefit, not to the detriment of individuals in society.
To quote President Clinton: ``My goal is to set an example and pose
a challenge for every employer in America, because I believe no
employer should ever review your genetic records along with your
resume.''
</P>
<P>
   Every one of us is at risk for having a condition that has an
underlying genetic component. Advances in genetic testing will
eventually make it possible to offer a number of predictive tests
to determine what we actually are at risk for developing.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests have been available for years but have been
limited primarily to newborn and prenatal screening, to carrier
testing for genetic conditions common in certain ethnic groups
(like Tay-Sachs disease in Jews and sickle cell in blacks) and to
tests applicable to those families with known genetic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But with the rapid advances that are being made in the Human
Genome Project, genetic testing may become available for common
conditions like cancer, heart disease and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Such advances in genetic testing hold great promise for
surveillance and preventive treatments, yet also hold the potential
for stigmatization and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   There are important ways that genetic tests differ from standard
medical tests, in that genetic tests can have significant
implications for other family members and also can identify
conditions for which a person might not develop symptoms for years.
Now, predictive tests are available for hereditary neurological
conditions like Huntington's disease, hereditary cancers and other
genetic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In general, these are dominantly inherited conditions with onset
in adulthood; each child of an affected parent has a 50 percent
chance of inheriting the genetic alteration.
</P>
<P>
   People often express concerns about how a present or future
genetic condition will affect their insurability and to a lesser
extent, their employability. Take the typical case of a woman in
her 30s who had a predictive test that was positive for
Huntington's disease. She felt she had little choice but to remain
at the same job. She voiced concerns similar to those expressed by
others with positive results: that this information could affect
their ability to be hired and to obtain insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   To date, reports of genetic discrimination have been anecdotal,
with few studies conducted to assess the incidence, largely because
genetic testing has been available only to a small group and
because of the difficulty in documenting discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   One 1996 study by a group known as the Genetic Alliance, which
represents more than 300 support groups, and by Georgetown
University found that about 13 percent of 332 support group
respondents reported that they or relatives had been denied jobs or
dismissed from them because of genetic conditions in their
families, although the study did not document such claims.
</P>
<P>
   Whether cases of employment discrimination are fully verifiable
or just perceived, the fact is that fear of such discrimination is
already affecting people's decisions to have genetic testing. In
the same study, 9 percent indicated that they or relatives had
declined genetic testing because of fears of genetic
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The public's fear about use of genetic information was also
documented in a study released in 1998 by the National Center for
Genome Resources, a nonprofit research organization, which found
that 63 percent of respondents would be inclined not to take
genetic tests if results were accessible to employers or insurers;
respondents included more than 1,000 randomly selected adults who
participated in phone interviews.
</P>
<P>
   People need to be assured that their decisions to seek genetic
information will not affect their employability. Some feel that
existing legislation is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   While the 1990 Americans With Disabilities Act was interpreted
by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission in 1995 to include
healthy people who carried genetic alterations for developing a
genetic condition in the future, the extent of this protection was
limited and has yet to be tested in court.
</P>
<P>
   It does not prevent employers' access to genetic information and
it means that having a genetic alteration has to be regarded as a
``disability.'' Twenty-three states have passed laws prohibiting
employment discrimination based on genetic information, but the
level of protection varies widely in terms of what constitutes
genetic testing and what information is actually protected.
</P>
<P>
   The president's executive order sends a strong message to
federal agencies and sets a standard that should be adopted by
employers in the private sector. To quote Dr. Francis S. Collins,
director of the National Human Genome Research Institute, the
executive order on genetic discrimination is practicing
``preventive policy making _ to put in place the kind of
protections that the public needs and deserves before we find
ourselves in a needless crisis situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
