<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EDUCATION-AID29-COX     02-28 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-AID29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP SAYS COLLEGE AID FORMS HAVE FLAWS
 &HT;    360&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans attacked the Education Department
on Monday for ``persistent, serious problems'' with the form used
by millions of students to apply for federal aid for college.
</P>
<P>
   They said that early applicants for grants and scholarships in
the 2000-1 school year have been plagued by errors in the software
that calculates eligibility, by slow connections to the Web-based
version, and by the awkward wording of a question designed to weed
out some applicants with recent drug-related convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proper field-testing of the form is not happening, and that is
a major concern for us,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman
of the House Committee on Education and the Workforce.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter faxed Monday to Education Secretary Richard
Riley, Goodling and three other Republicans gave Riley two weeks to
explain why the aid form ``is not being prepared, distributed and
processed in a more customer-friendly manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Freeman, an Education Department spokeswoman, said all
software fixes were completed by the Jan. 15 deadline. She said she
didn't know of any problems with the Web-based version of the form.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed that the question on drug convictions was confusing.
But, she said, ``There is absolutely no question that we're doing a
better job of processing loans and grants today than we were a year
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, about 10 million people are expected to fill out the
``Free Application for Federal Student Aid,'' or FAFSA form, which
is also used by many private givers to make decisions about
scholarships and loans. About 8.5 million of last year's applicants
received more than $50 billion in federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   The FAFSA form has to be changed each year to keep up with
changes that Congress and the president make in the laws. The
newest version of the form has ballooned to contain 104 questions
and several worksheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year is a learning experience,'' Greg Woods, chief
operating officer of the Education Department's Office of Student
Financial Assistance Programs, said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were most concerned about the fact that more
than 100,000 of the first 500,000 applicants for next year's grants
and loans didn't answer a question on drug convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The question was added to the form because a new law states that
under certain conditions some students can and other students
cannot receive federal financial aid within a year or two of
convictions for possessing or selling illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The question reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``28. If you have never been convicted of any drug offense,
enter '1' in the box and go to question 29. A drug-related
conviction does not necessarily make you ineligible for aid; call
1-800-433-3243 or go to http://www.fafsa.ed.gov/q28 to find out how
to fill out this question.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the toll-free number leads to a voice-mail menu that is
supposed to help the applicant decide whether to write ``1,''
``2,'' or ``3,'' in the box. At the Web site, applicants can
download a worksheet or answer a number of questions on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question and the worksheet worked well when we
pilot-tested it with different groups of students,'' Woods said.
``But in the context of the entire form, it was apparently
confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said, ``This year's problems are only the most
recent.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, 3.5 million printed versions of the FAFSA form
contained errors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the department's scanning equipment couldn't read more
than one million of the applications.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a fight over the education budget caused the forms to
be mailed late.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
