<P>
   COKESUIT-BLACKS _ ATLANTA _ For the first time since the racial
discrimination lawsuit was filed nearly a year ago, black employees
at Coca-Cola are in motion. Up until two weeks ago, most
African-American employees sat on the sidelines while lawyers
battled in court and a few local civil rights leaders expressed
support for the suit. But now, more black employees are getting in
gear, primarily because the massive job cuts under way at Coke has
changed the dynamics of the situation. For laid off
African-American employees, the suit and the job cuts have been
interlocked, forcing them to make a difficult decision. On
Saturday, hundreds of employees are expected to meet at St. Philip
A.M.E. Church in Decatur to discuss what may become a galvanizing
issue as the layoffs and lawsuit play out in the ensuing months.
(Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-BELLSOUTH _ America Online, Inc. today announced its plans
to deliver popular AOL features and services to millions of
wireless consumers, including BellSouth's, through a series of
agreements with top wireless data carriers, device, and mobile
phone manufacturers. These agreements mark a major advance in the
Company's ``AOL Anywhere'' (sm) strategy to make AOL vailable to
online consumers across a range of devices. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL _ ATLANTA _Bass Hotels &AMP; resorts, which has its North
and South American operations here, has acquired Bristol, a big
Holiday Inn licensee in Dallas. Mark Woodworth of PKF Consulting
said the deal represents Bass deciding to focus more on real
estate/hotel business as the parent Bass PLC gets out of
brewing/pub biz. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
