<HEADER>
A1089 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER29-COX     02-28 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If something doesn't seem right, don't hesitate to consult
another physician.
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to second opinions in medicine, too many of us are
simply too polite. But such a lack of assertiveness could cost
patients their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, patients should heed their own intuition about their
health and speak up when things simply don't feel right, says Dr.
Jerome Groopman, author of ``Second Opinions: Stories of Intuition
and Choice in the Changing World of Medicine'' (Viking, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   So why do patients shy away from something that obviously makes
good common sense?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because so many patients still view obtaining a second opinion
as an insult to the doctor,'' says Dr. Michael Andrews, president
of the Georgia Society of Clinical Oncology. ``We try to encourage
second opinions _ we don't take it personally. Because in the end,
it's in the best interest for the patient and for me: The patient
comes back feeling better about everything, and for me, oftentimes,
it puts the patient back on the same page because they are more
confident about what I'm recommending.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's how to become more assertive and get that useful
second opinion:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The little things matter. Dress neatly, even professionally,
for a meeting with your doctor to discuss getting a second opinion.
Be courteous and direct about wanting one, advises Dr. Robert
Schreiner of Kaiser Permanente of Georgia. And always ask for a
referral, even if you don't plan to use it. It shows you respect
your doctor's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If your doctor seems petulant or irritated about your request
_ or even refuses to give you a referral _ consumer advocates say
to fire him or her and find another doctor. Most doctors don't mind
patients asking for a second opinion; if yours does, it could
indicate trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If your insurance won't pay for a second opinion because your
doctor won't approve it _ since managed care plans often require
patients to go through their primary physician before seeking
outside specialists _ find out about the appeal process. Also, ask
for a case manager, suggests Dr. Charles Cutler, chief medical
officer for the American Association of Health Plans. Case managers
are especially helpful because they can coordinate second opinions
from health professionals outside your plan, such as those
affiliated with academic centers that may be far away.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're getting nowhere with your doctor or insurer, contact
your employer's human resources department or the Georgia Insurance
Commissioner's Office. Its consumer hotline number is 404-656-2070.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And finally, once you get approval for a second opinion, make
sure the second doctor receives copies of all office notes, lab
test results, X-ray films (yes, the actual films) and pathology
slides. Don't depend on doctors' offices to communicate or make
sure this happens.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, while consumer advocates have long pushed for
getting second opinions, in the past 20 years the motivation has
changed. At one time, second opinions were urged in order to make
sure recommended operations, such as hysterectomies, were actually
needed _ a result of traditional indemnity insurance plans under
which patients could get any procedure at any time. Today, second
opinions are often recommended to make sure patients are getting
the treatments they need.
</P>
<P>
   Says Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of the Public Citizen Health
Research Group in Washington: ``Patients need to remember they're
the ones whose bodies are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
