<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MOLLY-IVINS-BUSH-HNS &LR;      02-28 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLY-IVINS-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MOLLY IVINS' NEW BOOK ON GEORGE W. _ A LOOK AT HIS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOAN SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is anyone in journalism who can make reading about
politics a rollicking good time, it's Molly Ivins, the nationally
syndicated columnist from Texas. Granted, she has a point of view.
</P>
<P>
   She once referred to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich as a
``political sociopath'' and wrote that ``having [New York Sen.
Alfonse] D'Amato conduct an ethics investigation is like watching
Mike Tyson run a sensitivity training seminar.'' But she is also an
indisputably great reporter. She edited the Texas Observer, was
Rocky Mountain bureau chief for the New York Times, and has worked
for the Houston Chronicle, the Minneapolis Star &AMP; Tribune and the
Dallas Times Herald. Her column for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram is
syndicated to more than 200 newspapers, and she has published
collections of her columns in two hilarious best-selling books _
``Molly Ivins Can't Say That, Can She?'' and ``You Got to Dance
With Them What Brung You: Politics in the Clinton Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ivins' latest book  &Cx1f; _ a biography of the man from her home
state who hopes to be president _ isn't all that funny. ``Shrub:
The Short but Happy Political Life of George W. Bush'' is ``a
straightforward look at the political record _ no sex, no drugs, no
Freud,'' says Ivins in a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ivins, who invented the botanical moniker for Bush (popularized
by her friend, former Texas Gov. Ann Richards), complains that the
problem with looking at his political record was finding it in the
first place. ``The single, most-common misconception about `Dubya'
(as she calls him) is that he spent the last 5 1/2 years governing
a large state,'' she explains. ``But in Texas we have what is
called a weak-governor system _ it's not much of a job. By
constitutional arrangement, the governor is about the
fifth-most-powerful person in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ivins and her co-author, Texas Monthly editor Lou Dubose,
committed themselves to guiding us step-by-step through the
governor's remarkably uninspired career. ``Young political
reporters are always told there are three ways to judge a
politician,'' they write. ``The first is to look at the record. The
second is to look at the record. And third, look at the record. So
here we are, with a record about property-tax abatement and tort
reform, and if that's not a by-God recipe for bestsellerdom, you
can cut off our legs and call us Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, those are the only issues in Texas that ever
really got Bush's administrative juices flowing, according to Ivins
and Dubose.
</P>
<P>
   In a state with the worst environmental problems in the country,
Bush blocked an attempt by his advisers to force 850 industrial
plants responsible for a third of the state's air pollution to
comply with clean-air laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a state with people living along the border in communities so
poor and benighted that they've had to go to the capital of Austin
by the busload just to fight for water and sewage hookups, Bush's
idea of a `legislative emergency' was tort reform _ making it
harder for people to sue big business. Ivins cites a Los Angeles
Times analysis of Bush's spectacular fund-raising success that
shows he raised $4.5 million just from the businesses that
supported Texas tort reform, a ``figure that left us all
whomper-jawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivins and Dubose also look at Bush's official biography and come
up with a couple of what you might call little whoppers. They
include his claim during his first congressional race that he was
on active duty during the Vietnam War when he was really skipping
to the top of a waiting list of 100,000 men to join the Texas
National Guard, a feat he still insists he managed (despite
convincing testimony to the contrary) without the help of any of
his father's friends.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Bush the oilman. ``The governor's oil-field
career can be summed up in a single paragraph,'' write Ivins and
Dubose. ``George W. arrived in Midland in 1977, set up a shell
company, lost a congressional election in 1978, restarted building
the company he'd put on hold, lost more than $2 million of other
people's money, and left Midland with $840,000 in his pocket. If
Bush does make it to the White House, he and Laura should have Ken
Starr over for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   If Starr hadn't so abused the power of his office, Congress
might have re-authorized the independent-counsel statute. That
could have left the door open for a court-appointed prosecutor to
investigate a president's son who flipped his oil companies faster
than a Texas S&AMP;L can daisy-chain a Dallas condo, and who, as a
corporate board insider, unloaded his stock shortly before its
price plummeted. He walked away from the whole mess with more money
than Bill Clinton ever dreamed of making on a little real estate
deal known as Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also took a look at his `compassionate conservatism,'''
says Ivins. ``Looking for the compassion part, we really didn't
find much, though his work on behalf of `big bidness,' as we so
reverently call it in Texas, does give new dimension to the phrase
`corporate welfare.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ivins says she finds the election ``real interesting. I spent a
year and a half arguing with most of my colleagues that there is
nothing inevitable about the nominations of George Bush and Al
Gore, and now it's become conventional wisdom. Not to mention the
fun and frolic over there in the Reform Party. I think it's a
fabulous show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1092 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-INTERNET-COX     02-28 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do those supplements work?
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deciding whether to take nutritional supplements can be
nightmarish. Some offer real benefit; others can be dangerous if
they aggravate an underlying medical problem or cross-react with a
drug you're already taking. Almost all are cleverly packaged and
heavily hyped; relatively few offer scientific evidence for their
presumed effects. (Federal law classifies supplements as foods, not
drugs; that categorization prevents manufacturers from making
medical claims but relieves them of doing the rigorous testing that
pharmaceuticals are subjected to.)
</P>
<P>
   So what's a consumer to do? The answer is to do your own
research. Web sites such as Supplement Watch (www
</P>
<P>
   .supplementwatch.com) are making it easier.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old site, created by a self-described ``small group
of scientists, physiologists, nutritionists and other health
professionals'' in Utah, provides pithy, free and apparently
independent reviews of more than 100 types of supplements and
individual products. Though basically friendly to supplementation,
the reviewers don't hesitate to name names when urging people to
``hold off for now'' or ``don't waste your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Points in the site's favor: It lists citations so you can look
up scientific research, and it has no easy-shopping links to online
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds on the horizon: The site is soliciting advertisers, so
its neutral-seeming presentation may not last.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
