r l BC-INTUITION-SIDE29-COX     02-28 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTUITION-SIDE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books to help you start listening to your body
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his respect for the power of intuition in medicine, Dr.
Jerome Groopman has a lot of company. A half-dozen new books advise
patients to be attentive to their own emotional and physical
symptoms. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dr. Judith Orloff's Guide to Intuitive Healing: 5 Steps to
Physical, Emotional and Sexual Wellness'' by Dr. Judith Orloff
(being published next week by Times Books, $24). A psychiatrist and
professor at the University of California at Los Angeles, Orloff
describes herself as a ``practicing intuitive'' who uses her
internal guidance in treating patients. In this book, her second,
she counsels patients to evaluate feelings and situations through
five steps: ``Notice your beliefs, be in your body, sense your
body's subtle energy, ask for guidance and listen to your dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Intuitive Healer: Accessing Your Inner Physician'' by
Marcia Emery (St. Martin's Press, $23.95). A psychologist and
corporate consultant, Emery guides readers through a technique she
calls the Mindshift Method, a sequence of relaxing, concentrating
and interpreting internal imagery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Awakening Intuition: Using Your Mind-Body Network for
Insight and Healing'' by Dr. Mona Lisa Schulz (Three Rivers Press,
$14). Schulz is a neuropsychiatrist and works with Dr. Christiane
Northrup, a popular author on women's holistic health, who wrote
this book's introduction. Like Northrup, Schulz believes that
emotional and psychological disturbances surface in specific
organs, and must be addressed before physical healing can take
place.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Women's Intuition: Unlocking the Wisdom of the Body'' by
Paula M. Reeves (Conari Press, $15.95). A therapist and workshop
leader who lives in Stone Mountain, Reeves coaches readers into
understanding emotional conditions and disease states via a
practice she calls Spontaneous Contemplative Movement.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
