<HEADER>
A1096 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ACNE-ART-NYT &LR;      02-28 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ACNE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CURE FOR ACNE, A TREATMENT FOR ANGST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent as NYT11 to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By CLARA HEMPHILL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Courtney McGrath now is a confident, clear-skinned
undergraduate at Cornell. But when she had teen-age acne, she was
so shy she hated to go out.
</P>
<P>
   At a junior high school party, boys called her ``the girl with
the zits all over her face.'' A stranger on a bus gave her
unsolicited advice on home remedies. ``It was all I could do not to
burst into tears,'' McGrath said. ``When you are the one with the
worst case of acne, you think it's the worst thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Pimples have long been a painful rite of passage for
adolescents. At a time in life when children are most concerned
about their appearances, even the pimples of superficial acne can
cause a loss of self-confidence, shyness, and, in severe cases,
depression. And the inflamed cysts of deep acne can leave permanent
scars.
</P>
<P>
   But medical science has now taken on the acne. New treatments,
some developed only in the last few years, mean that pimples can be
conquered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-five percent of people can be treated,'' said Dr.
Darrell S. Rigell, president of the American Academy of
Dermatology. ``That doesn't mean you'll never get a pimple for the
rest of your life. But more treatments are available, and they are
much more effective and with fewer side effects than they were 20
or 30 or even five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients are seeking out treatment for acne partly because new
therapies are available and partly because nowadays more patients
can afford to treat conditions that are not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is a little freer so people are more likely to go to the
doctors for what might be considered a cosmetic problem,'' said Dr.
Guy F. Webster, the vice chairman of the dermatology department at
Jefferson Medical Center in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who suffered from acne themselves do not want their
children to repeat their experiences. ``I think there's been a
change in attitude,'' said Dr. Anne W. Lucky, a pediatric
dermatologist at Children's Hospital Medical Center in Cincinnati.
``Rather than grin and bear it, people come in to get treated.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 85 percent of adolescents and young adults suffer from
acne. A surprisingly large proportion of women _ estimates range
from 8 percent to 50 percent _ escape outbreaks of acne as
teen-agers only to experience them for the first time as adults.
</P>
<P>
   While many such cases are mild and disappear without treatment,
others need medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be considered trivial,'' said Dr. Alan R.
Shalita, the chairman of the dermatology department at SUNY
Downstate Medical Center in Brooklyn. ``It can have serious,
long-lasting psychological effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Acne among adolescents is caused by overactive oil glands
stimulated by the surge in male hormones called androgens, present
in both boys and girls, at the onset of puberty.
</P>
<P>
   Among grown women, acne is caused by hormonal fluctuations
connected to the menstrual cycle. Some doctors believe acne is
caused by or exacerbated by stress.
</P>
<P>
   Acne starts when the fatty glands attached to the skin's hair
follicles produce too much oil, called sebum. Normally, the cells
lining the hair follicles slough off regularly, and the oil passes
to the surface of the skin.
</P>
<P>
   But when there is excess oil production and when the skin cells
fail to flake off, a pore becomes plugged, and it may become
infected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pore gets clogged and bacteria grow in the hair
follicle,'' said Dr. Gary M. White, a dermatologist in the Los
Angeles area. ``The body's immune system doesn't like the bacteria
and fights it. The red you see is the battle going on where the
immune system is trying to kill that bacteria. If you can unclog
that pore you can empty out the bacteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Greeks used sulfur to control pimples, a substance
still in use today. Benzoyl peroxide, an over-the-counter
medication sold under brand names like Clearasil and Benzac; oral
antibiotics; and birth control pills have also been used for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1982 researchers developed Accutane, a vitamin A
derivative that, taken in pill form, was a more effective
treatment. But, as its maker, Roche Laboratories, warns, Accutane
can have side effects ranging from chapped skin to birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors often require women of childbearing age who take it to
use two forms of birth control. All patients taking Accutane must
have regular blood tests to check their liver functions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers have been developing a wide array of
prescription gels, creams and lotions that can be applied to the
skin singly or in combination with other remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous explosion in what we are able to do,''
said Dr. Seth J. Orlow, a specialist in pediatric and adolescent
dermatology at New York University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The newer treatments are topical _ creams or gels spread on the
face _ and are less likely to have side effects. They include
tazarotene (sold by Allergan under the name Tazorac) and and
adapalene (sold by Galderma under the name Differin).
</P>
<P>
   Both are retinoids that function like vitamin A derivatives. So
women who plan on becoming pregnant are also advised not to take
Tazorac or Differin, because their effects on the fetus are not
known.
</P>
<P>
   But these topical creams are less irritating to the skin than
Accutane. They loosen the cells and oils that clog the pores and
also prevent creation of new acne lesions.
</P>
<P>
   Oral and topical antibiotics are used as well, sometimes in
combination with other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Antibiotics decrease the bacteria that cause the infections.
Another new therapy is azelaic acid (made by Allergan), an
antibacterial cream, approved by the Food and Drug Administration
in 1996, that unclogs the pores that cause pimples.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors now agree that many things long linked to acne _ like
failing to wash adequately _ in fact have no effect. ``Thinking
about sex, eating chocolate and pizza doesn't cause acne,'' said
Dr. John J. Russell of Abington Memorial Hospital in Abington, Pa.,
who wrote an article on new acne treatments in the January issue of
American Family Physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hormonal thing,'' Russell said. ``It's not a problem of
hygiene. There are teen-agers who wash their faces 10 times a day
and they still get acne.''
</P>
<P>
   The severity of acne is in part indicated by how early children
get their first pimples. ``Girls who get acne before they start
they menstrual periods are more at risk of severe acne,'' Lucky
said. ``If you've already had your period for three or four years
and you get acne, you're probably not going to get it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, the Cornell student, used countless over-the-counter
remedies and was treated by several doctors over the course of four
years, without success.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dr. Diane S. Berson brought her acne under control with
a strong dose of Accutane. ``I was so excited,'` McGrath said. ``It
definitely altered my social experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
