<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DOCTOR-ERROR-ART-     02-28 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTOR-ERROR-ART-2TAKES(835)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE CORE OF MISTAKES IN MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors have amputated the wrong leg, killed patients with
overdoses of medications and committed other serious errors for
centuries. So why only now is a U.S. president calling for the
first national plan to reduce such errors?
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the new concern are as complex as medicine
itself and as varied as recent changes in society, including
medical advances, greater complexity of care, increasing challenge
to medical authority and new techniques to pinpoint sources of
errors in the maze of systems that doctors and hospital staffs use
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, mounting complaints about managed care have intensified
concern about the quality of health care, and placing a spotlight
on medical errors grabs public attention in a way that other
quality of care issues do not.
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Mark R. Chassin, a former New York state health
commissioner, put it: ``Talk about overuse and underuse of health
care, issues that are as important as errors, and everybody goes to
sleep. But mistakes can happen to anybody, and they provoke a
visceral fear that is real.''
</P>
<P>
   The spark for President Clinton's plan was a report in November
from the Institute of Medicine of the National Academy of Sciences
that said up to 98,000 patients died from preventable medical
errors in American hospitals each year, but that the number could
be halved in five years.
</P>
<P>
   In adopting most of the institute's recommendations, Clinton has
called for a new patient safety center in the government to conduct
research on reducing medical errors. He has also called for
mandatory reporting systems for deaths and serious injuries, and
voluntary reporting for less serious injuries and close calls.
</P>
<P>
   Development of an avalanche of effective therapies has brought
its own problems. Until mid-20th century, doctors had little to
offer seriously ill people. Now many new, effective therapies for
heart disease, cancer and other ailments have raised public
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But the newer therapies have also increased enormously the
complexity of medicine and the risk of errors. And because many
therapies are so powerful, tiny errors in doses can increase the
risk of life-threatening complications.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can no longer rely solely on their own experience in
treating patients. ``Do that and you will inevitably commit
malpractice,'' said Chassin, who is chairman of the department of
health policy at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York City and
was on the panel that wrote the institute report.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, doctors depend more on findings from scientifically
controlled trials to provide quality medical care. The number of
such trials has surged beyond any doctor's ability to keep abreast,
rising to 10,000 a year now compared with about 100 in 1966,
according to Chassin's survey.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for national attention to medical errors is that
the public has replaced paternalism with consumerism. It is a rare
scene today in which a family, told that a loved one died simply
because the patient could not withstand a procedure, accepts the
bad news without questioning the doctors and hospital staff.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to medical authority has brought malpractice suits
and, as their number and costs have soared, a few pioneering
doctors looked to computers and the aviation industry, which uses
simulators for training, to develop ways to identify and prevent
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Anesthesiologists, for example, found that applying a simple
device to the skin to monitor oxygen levels during surgery could
sharply reduce the rate of death, brain damage and other
complications. Some hospitals are developing drills to be followed
before doctors and nurses start an operation, much like pilots'
using checklists before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   In a number of hospitals, doctors now enter prescriptions and
other orders on computers to eliminate errors from illegible
handwriting. Clinton has urged greater use of bar code systems to
prevent potentially fatal transfusions from mismatched blood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan is also based on a radical recent change in the
payment of health care. The government now pays for much of the
costs of medical care, research and education _ even in private
hospitals and managed care systems. Thus, the government can
collect information that could not have been obtained when medicine
was strictly a private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Because such findings have provided a glimpse into the
previously secret workings of medicine, and health care has become
so costly, many news organizations have increased their coverage of
health care issues and their watchdog role over them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, journalists have recently reported on a cluster of
highly visible horrendous medical errors at prestigious teaching
hospitals, including the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston,
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City and the
University of Chicago Hospitals. With reports of errors elsewhere
being added frequently, what may seem like a new epidemic is really
an old problem.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   An Achievable Goal
</P>
<P>
   Although many health experts quibble over the institute's
figures, most agree that medical errors, whatever the precise
number, can be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are preventable errors and that we should be
putting more energy and resources into preventing them,'' said Dr.
Nancy W. Dickey, the immediate past president of the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only acceptable error rate is zero, which means that as
long as there is an error rate above zero, we must continue putting
substantial effort into reducing the error rate still further,''
Dickey said. However, she said, the AMA has not set a target for
the lowest achievable error rate, in part because no one knows what
it is.
</P>
<P>
   New York and 17 other states now have mandatory systems for
reporting medical errors that vary in their policies and
thoroughness. The medical association does not want to dismantle
them, but does oppose their expansion, in part, because evidence is
lacking that mandatory reporting has reduced error rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not sure whether it works or how to make it work, why
create a costly new bureaucracy as Clinton plans to do,'' Dickey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chassin agreed, saying: ``Unless you're prepared to send an army
of auditors in to verify the reporting, you can't be sure that the
reporting is equally reliable or thorough, and no state will
support that kind of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Tackling errors, Dickey said, ``is such a huge problem that we
need to get our arms around pieces of it, make measurable progress,
and then add another piece rather than being so overwhelmed that we
don't know where to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said the medical association supported research efforts
to identify and then reduce the three most important types of
medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, reporting is working to reduce errors. For
instance, New York state now achieves 97 percent survival rates
from coronary bypass surgery to rank highest among the states.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable improvement came from the five hospitals in Maine,
New Hampshire and Vermont that perform heart surgery and that
voluntarily cooperate to analyze their death rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says that an increase in liability
has not been seen in states with mandatory reporting and contends
that reducing errors would decrease litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the medical association said mandatory reporting could
``have the perverse result of driving errors underground.'' Doctors
also fear that information from frank discussions could become
grist for malpractice suits because written reports can be used by
plaintiffs' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Need to Define Errors
</P>
<P>
   One AMA objection to mandatory reporting is the lack of standard
definitions for different degrees of medical errors. Yet the
association did not develop such definitions before the institute's
report, and Dickey conceded in an interview that it would have been
wiser to have made it a priority. ``That's a valid point,'' Dickey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine borrowed from behavioral psychology to
define medical error very broadly as ``the failure of a planned
action to be completed as intended or the use of a wrong plan to
achieve an aim.''
</P>
<P>
   But the institute report focused mainly on medication errors. It
cited a small number of published studies in estimating that 7,000
patients died each year from medication errors.
</P>
<P>
   One definitional problem is that a certain number of
complications from drugs, surgery and other therapies are
unpredictable and not preventable. For example, a drug or operation
may have well-known complications, but often there is no way to
predict which people will get them. So when such a complication
occurs, is it an error?
</P>
<P>
   Classifying falls as errors, as the report did, is also a murky
area because they happen commonly in homes and on the street.
Doctors tend to take more responsibility for falls when they occur
in hospitals and nursing homes, where many can be related directly
to errors, like drug combinations that sedate too much or cause
fainting from dropping blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If elderly patients fall in a hospital and they might have
fallen at home, is that an error?'' Dickey asked. ``Probably not.
But if patients fell because they were sedated with medications so
their balance was impaired, that may be a potential error. If they
were sedated, the lights were all turned off so they were
disoriented, and the bed rails were not put up to discourage them
from walking, then you have several potential errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Although medicine prides itself on a tradition of exposing its
errors, at least internally, through self-scrutiny, ``we have not
met our ideals,'' said Dr. Kenneth M. Ludmerer, of Washington
University in St. Louis, the author of ``Time to Heal'' (Oxford
University Press, 1999), a history of American medical education
over the last century.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's report did not discuss the role of autopsies,
which had long been the profession's traditional tool for teaching
and quality control. But the autopsy rate has plummeted to the
current level of fewer than 10 percent of deaths in hospitals from
about 50 percent in the 1950s, in part because of the belief that
CT scans, MRI scans and other modern technology can accurately help
diagnose conditions during life. But studies have shown that
autopsies still often turn up surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital conferences aimed at improving patient safety and that
are aided by autopsy findings have dropped in number and
attendance, lessening the profession's internal monitoring, critics
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's uncertainty in medicine,'' Ludmerer said, adding,
``We're misguided in doing fewer autopsies and we need to retain
our humility, learning from mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical leaders could have addressed many ways to reduce medical
errors before managed care magnified the problem, Ludmerer and
others said. The pressure to see 50 or so patients in a day and to
spend six or so minutes with each one is not enough time to say
hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ill-guided emphasis on doing things quickly, rather than
well, has certainly accentuated the problem of error,'' Ludmerer
said. ``You just make too many mistakes if you're doing things
quickly and have to cut corners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
