<SLUG> BC-JANET-MCTEER-IN-TUMBLEWEEDS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BRIT GRIT: JANET McTEER'S UNLIKELY ROAD TO OSCAR NIGHT  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Janet McTeer in a scene from
``Tumbleweeds.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's hard to miss Janet McTeer.
 &HT;    The statuesque, 6-foot-tall brunette would be an imposing figure
even without a vocabulary peppered with enough four-letter words to
make a sailor blush.
 &HT;    But the Academy Award-nominated star of ``Tumbleweeds'' laughs
heartily when told that the film's director, Gavin O'Connor, has
described her as ``a broad in the best sense of the word.''
 &HT;    ``I guess he means I swear a lot,'' McTeer say, grinning. ``I
don't pull any punches, and I'm not particularly girly. I say what
I think _ and I have a voice that sounds like I've just had a
bottle of whiskey and a pack of cigarettes.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, she's irresistible. The British actress snared
Hollywood's attention by winning a 1998 Tony Award as the star of a
controversial, in-your-face adaptation of Ibsen's classic ``A
Doll's House.'' Then she captivated Academy voters as a single mom,
complete with Southern drawl, dragging her young daughter across
the country in search of love and new beginnings in
``Tumbleweeds.''
 &HT;    ``Mary Jo is attracted to men and she's very sexy,'' McTeer
says. ``I think she's been brought up to feel that she needs a man.
Unfortunately she ends up with the wrong guys, because the right
guys seem too boring.''
 &HT;    O'Connor spotted McTeer by chance, when she appeared on Charlie
Rose's PBS talk show during her Broadway run.
 &HT;    ``I tuned in by accident,'' he recalls in a separate interview.
``I envisioned I'd be watching this very proper, slightly pompous
English actress, and instead I saw this brassy and totally engaging
woman.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `My God, this is Mary Jo!'''
 &HT;    McTeer was smitten enough by the ``Tumbleweeds'' script _
written by O'Connor's ex-wife, Angela Shelton _ that she agreed to
star even though its financing was shaky at best.
 &HT;    The biggest challenge, of course, was mastering the character's
thick North Carolina accent _ not merely well enough to do it, but
so perfectly that she wouldn't have to think about it, leaving her
free to act.
 &HT;    ``I just wanted to be able to talk the talk and forget about
whether I was sounding right,'' she says. ``I worked very hard on
it. I also realized that American women have a different kind of
body language, a little more open and expressive than a Brit, so I
worked on that, too.''
 &HT;    To learn more, she joined Shelton for reconnoitering jaunts into
the North Carolina countryside.
 &HT;    ``I was sort of overwhelmed by all the space,'' she recalls.
``In Britain there isn't as much land, and there are a lot more
people on it. It's extraordinary to go to a place where they have a
big house with a porch, where they sit drinking whiskey sours or
whatever.''
 &HT;    Mary Jo's precocious 12-year-old daughter, Ava, is played by
14-year-old Kimberly Brown. In a separate interview, Brown reports
that she and McTeer clicked almost instantly.
 &HT;    ``I remember seeing this enormously tall woman as I sat down on
a couch with my script,'' Brown says, smiling. ``All of a sudden
she lunged on the couch and gave me a huge hug. I was sort of
freaking out _ and then we both started to laugh, and we made each
other laugh for the rest of the production.''
 &HT;    The two became inseparable, even though a ``swear box'' on the
set filled to overflowing with quarters, one for each curse word
the British actress let fly.
 &HT;    ``Every time Janet started talking,'' Brown says, rolling her
eyes, ``I had to do a double-take at what was coming out of the
mouth of this person from very proper Britain.''
 &HT;    Both actresses cite as their favorite scene a potentially
awkward one in which Mary Jo tries to tell her daughter how to use
a sanitary napkin.
 &HT;    ``It was completely improvised,'' McTeer recalls. ``We thought
of the most hilarious stuff, and we were literally rolling on the
floor with laughter.''
 &HT;    The only tension during production arose from Brown's determined
effort to convince McTeer to give up smoking.
 &HT;    ``Every single day she'd tell me I had to quit,'' McTeer says
with a sigh. ``It became unbelievably irritating, especially when
she started hiding my cigarettes. Finally it became clear that the
only thing that would save our friendship was if I stopped smoking
_ so I did.
 &HT;    ``I gave up last November, and I haven't had a cigarette
since.''
 &HT;    Mary Jo isn't everyone's idea of a great mother, hauling her
daughter away from their home in pursuit of a California dream and
often leaving her on her own while Mary Jo pursues her latest
boyfriend.
 &HT;    McTeer shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I think Mary Jo and Ava are best friends,'' she says. ``It
might seem like a dysfunctional relationship, but I saw it as
incredibly healthy. Both of us are trying to live our lives as best
we can _ fighting our way through it, loving our way through it and
coming out bigger and better people.''
 &HT;    Her performance as Mary Jo had people murmuring about an Oscar
even before the film was released, but McTeer says that she still
was thrown off-balance when she heard she'd been nominated.
 &HT;    ``I'm reminded of the Tony,'' she says, ``which was absolutely
terrifying because everyone was absolutely convinced I was going to
win it. Actually, about 30 people came over (from England) to the
ceremonies because they wanted to watch me win. I kept thinking,
`Jeez, if I don't get it, look at all the money these people will
have wasted on airline tickets.'
 &HT;    ``So, when I won the award, the only thing I honestly felt was
relief,'' she says. ``I was like, `Thank God, now I can have a
drink.'''
 &HT;    McTeer, who grew up in York and became interested in acting
through a job selling coffee at a local theater, says that the idea
of winning an Oscar never crossed her mind until recently.
 &HT;    ``The Academy Awards are so American that they aren't part of
the fantasy of a British kid,'' she says. ``When I started to work
as an actress, being nominated was the furthest thing from my mind.
Now I find it a little funny, to be quite honest.
 &HT;    ``I take it all with a bucket of salt _ which I guess is rather
British, isn't it?''
 &HT;    Any ``Tumbleweeds'' fan who catches McTeer's next couple of
films will find her hard to recognize as Mary Jo, the actress
promises.
 &HT;    ``I did `The King is Alive' in the Namibian desert,'' she says.
``It was sort of guerrilla filmmaking, with no lighting, no hair
and no make-up. It was very intense and very hot, but I found it
interesting.
 &HT;    ``Then I'm going to be back in North Carolina in `Song Catcher'
_ without a Southern accent,'' she says. ``I play a
turn-of-the-century Harvard professor.
 &HT;    ``The worst part was wearing a corset,'' she adds with a
grimace. ``It really changes your shape. I can understand why women
of that period used to faint all the time.''
 &HT;    Whether McTeer collects a golden statue or not, it isn't likely
to detract from the fun that the transplanted Brit is having making
American films.
 &HT;    ``I don't think about being a star,'' she says. ``In Hollywood
you can be a star because you're famous and not because you're
good. I think of stars like Judi Dench and Vanessa Redgrave who are
both. I never want to be famous for its own sake _ I want people to
like me for my work.
 &HT;    ``And, so far, I've managed to pay my rent.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
