<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-ANJELICA-HUSTON-IN-AG     02-28 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANJELICA-HUSTON-IN-AGNES-BROWNE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANJELICA HUSTON, DIRECTING IN A GIANT SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Anjelica Huston with Marion O'Dwyer in a
scene from ``Agnes Browne.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    When Anjelica Huston calls ``Action!'' a formidable shadow hangs
over her.
 &HT;    After all, the Oscar-winning actress is the daughter of John
Huston, whose string of classic films includes ``The Maltese
Falcon'' (1941), ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' (1948) and
``The African Queen'' (1951).
 &HT;    The great director, who died in 1987, remains a vivid presence
for his daughter. If she closes her eyes, she says, she can see him
immediately.
 &HT;    ``At first, I see the tallest man in the room, with the deepest
voice,'' Huston says. ``I see the man with the most charm. He's
playful. Ironic. Deeply intelligent. Challenging. Critical.
Darling.
 &HT;    ``I also have a later image of a much more frail man in a
wheelchair, hooked up to an oxygen tank,'' she adds, more soberly.
``And basically he's sort of furious that it all had to end this
way.''
 &HT;    As her brother Danny did years ago, Angelica Huston is following
in her father's footsteps as a director. Her first feature, ``Agnes
Brown,'' will open nationwide on March 3.
 &HT;    ``I learned about directing from watching my father,'' Huston
says. ``He is my influence _ I'm proud to be linked with him.''
 &HT;    In ``Agnes Brown,'' Huston plays the mother of seven children
growing up in rural Ireland in 1967, toiling to keep the family
together while longing for one extravagance _ a getaway to see her
favorite singer, Tom Jones. It's sweet, gentle and unabashedly
sentimental.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, sentimentality has a dirty connotation,'' Huston
says, settling in for an interview at New York's Regency Hotel.
``But I am sentimental about Ireland because I grew up there. I
also have a deep belief in Irish charm _ I have a deep belief in
the possibility of small miracles, which is what this film has at
its core.''
 &HT;    Originally Rosie O'Donnell was slated to play Agnes, with Huston
staying safely behind the camera.
 &HT;    ``And then she adopted another baby,'' the director says, ``and
I guess her work load was a bit too much. She backed out at the
last minute.
 &HT;    ``Believe me, it was not my first choice to have Miss Huston
star,'' she adds. ``I set out to direct this film, I didn't set out
to act in it. Doing both is too much work, too crazy. Not enough
time _ a nine-week schedule in which you act and direct seemed
preposterous to me.''
 &HT;    But as the film's start date loomed, she decided she had no
other choice.
 &HT;    ``If I had to go to other actresses, it would have been
prohibitive in terms of money and time,'' she says. ``I had to act
in the movie in order to save it.''
 &HT;    Not that she didn't relish the role, once she had it.
 &HT;    ``If I hadn't been directing, it would have been unlikely I
would have been offered this role,'' she admits. ``It's not very
often I'm offered benign parts where I play ordinary people with
real smiles.''
 &HT;    Huston based her performance on several people she knew as a
child.
 &HT;    ``She's based on my Irish nanny Kathleen Shine,'' she says.
``And my mother, of course. Also there was another woman, the wife
of the man who looked after my father's horses, who lived on our
estate. She was the mother of seven.''
 &HT;    Many who worked with John Huston have commented on his brusque
directorial style, but his daughter says his reputation was
somewhat misleading.
 &HT;    ``My father certainly didn't direct with bombast,'' she says.
``He was very, very quiet and quite deadly. If he didn't like what
you were doing, you could expect to be there for the rest of the
week doing the same scene.
 &HT;    ``If he liked what you were doing,'' she adds, ``he would very
calmly say, `You got it. Let's move along.' I never saw him raise
his voice on set. I never saw him wave his arms.''
 &HT;    For herself, Huston says, she takes a considerably different
approach.
 &HT;    ``I'm the kind of director who smiles at her actors,'' she says.
``I'm touchy-feely _ I hug everyone in the morning. I think it's
important to the work that you develop strong friendships on a
movie set. In my experience, that's what makes it possible for
people to give more.
 &HT;    ``You have to create an atmosphere of trust.''
 &HT;    Raised in Ireland as the daughter of the director and his fourth
wife, ballerina Enrica Soma _ with whom he split when she was 11 _
Huston was only 15 when she decided she wanted to be an actress.
 &HT;    ``At first I didn't want to work with my father,'' she recalls.
``I wanted to work with practically anyone else on earth. I wanted
to be free and not have the hardship of parental control.''
 &HT;    In particular, she wanted the lead in Franco Zeffirelli's
``Romeo and Juliet'' (1968).
 &HT;    ``Franco Zeffirelli was looking for his girl at my school,'' she
recalls, ``and I wanted very much to be in that movie. My father
ended up writing Zeffirelli a letter saying I shouldn't be
considered, because I was going to make a film with him.''
 &HT;    Huston was devastated. It didn't help that her film debut _
other than a bit part in her father's ``Sinful Davey'' (1969) _
turned out to be ``A Walk with Love and Death'' (1969), one of his
worst films.
 &HT;    ``It was not a happy experience,'' she says. ``I wasn't in love
with the script. And my father's reaction was, `Who do you think
you are, Katharine Hepburn?'
 &HT;    ``The whole thing made me withdraw from acting for several
years.''
 &HT;    She wouldn't work with her father again for 16 years, by which
time she had established herself as an actress in her own right.
Their professional reunion was the far better ``Prizzi's Honor''
(1985), which won Huston an Oscar as Best Supporting Actress for
her role as a conniving Mafia princess.
 &HT;    She later appeared in her father's final film, ``The Dead''
(1987), and earned Oscar nominations for ``Enemies, a Love Story''
(1989) and ``The Grifters'' (1990). To many, however, she's best
known as Morticia Addams in ``The Addams Family'' (1991) and
``Addams Family Values'' (1993).
 &HT;    Huston's directorial debut was nearly as troubled as her acting
debut. ``Bastard Out of Carolina'' (1996) was filmed for Ted
Turner's TNT cable network. Its controversial treatment of child
molestation and rape drew criticism, however, and after viewing the
finished film Turner personally canceled the project.
 &HT;    ``I never expected that its parent company would reject it,''
Huston says. ``Of course, they had seen dailies every day. I don't
know if Ted Turner was looking very carefully at his properties at
the time. I don't know if he was fully aware of the subject matter
of `Bastard Out of Carolina.'''
 &HT;    Huston shrugs.
 &HT;    ``The contract says it's his film,'' she says. ``If it's his
choice not to show it, so be it. As it was, I was invited to Cannes
with the film. It got seen, it got reviewed. It enjoyed quite a
success.''
 &HT;    The film was eventually purchased by Showtime and shown in its
original form.
 &HT;    ``If it hadn't been seen at all,'' Huston says, ``I would have
been a lot more bitter about it.''
 &HT;    It certainly didn't frighten her off from directing, but for now
she has other things on her mind.
 &HT;    ``I'm happy because this movie is done and I'm off on a Jamaican
vacation with my women friends next week,'' Huston says, laughing.
``I haven't had a vacation in years.
 &HT;    ``I can't wait to get away and not even think about movies
anymore.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
