<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-NEVE-CAMPBELL-IN-DROW     02-28 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVE-CAMPBELL-IN-DROWNING-MONA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVE CAMPBELL: THE `PARTY' IS OVER, AND SHE FEELS FINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Neve Campbell in a scene from ``Drowning
Mona.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Neve Campbell was terrified.
 &HT;    No, she wasn't getting threatening telephone calls from a guy
with a creepy voice. No black-clad sicko was chasing her with a
knife.
 &HT;    Actually, what had the ``Party of Five'' star thinking twice was
the script of her new movie, ``Drowning Mona.'' Its touchy blend of
black humor and satire was scarier than anything she faced as
Sidney Prescott in three ``Scream'' films.
 &HT;    ``It's always scary to try new things,'' Campbell says. ``You
hope you'll be able to pull it off. On the other hand, I'm really
trying to do that, to try different things, to challenge myself and
grow as an actor.
 &HT;    ``If I'm not willing to take risks, then I might as well stop
now.''
 &HT;    Campbell co-stars with Danny DeVito, Bette Midler, Jamie Lee
Curtis and Casey Affleck in ``Drowning Mona,'' due for release on
March 3. It's an offbeat story set in Verplanck, N.Y., where
everyone drives Yugos and no one seems to care much about the death
of Mona Dearly (Midler).
 &HT;    Her character, Ellen Rash, isn't much like the real-life
Campbell. Where the actress wears her straight, brown hair pulled
back and looks great in a simple gray sweater-and-skirt combo,
Ellen sports hideous hair and a closetful of fashion-don't clothes.
 &HT;    Another difference: Campbell is a smart, worldly and sensible
26-year-old, while Ellen is ... well, let's just say that she isn't
the sharpest pencil in the drawer.
 &HT;    ``The character is absolutely ridiculous,'' Campbell says during
a conversation at New York's Essex House. ``The film itself is
absurd. I read the script and thought, `I have to do this.'
 &HT;    ``So I just decided to be as silly and ridiculous as possible,''
she says. ``I've done comedy in the past, but usually as the
straight man.''
 &HT;    The experience of making the film was both exhilarating and
unnerving, the young actress reports.
 &HT;    ``It was intimidating,'' she says, ``because you're working at
comedy with a bunch of people who have done many comedies in the
past and been very successful at it.
 &HT;    ``But it was also freeing, because I was laughing my head off
the whole time,'' she says. ``With that kind of character, you have
to not be concerned about how you're going to come across. You just
have to commit to it, do it and hopefully it will work.
 &HT;    ``It's like shooting in the dark.''
 &HT;    That kind of gamble doesn't come easily to the thoughtful,
ambitious Canadian actress who, even as she was making a name for
herself as ``Party of Five's'' put-upon Julia Salinger, was already
pondering the often-treacherous transition from television to film.
 &HT;    From her debut role in the surprise-hit supernatural thriller
``The Craft'' (1996) through the slasher movie/self-referential
comedy ``Scream'' (1996) and its two sequels, as well as the
noirish thriller ``Wild Things'' (1998), in which she played a
sluttish, machiavellian social outcast, Campbell has always had a
plan in mind.
 &HT;    ``It was really important for me to start looking for scripts
even for my first hiatus,'' she says, tugging on her sweater. ``For
me, what I had to focus on was my acting. I've tried to find things
that are different from Julia.
 &HT;    ``My first character in a feature was the girl in `The Craft,'''
Campbell says. ``She was interesting, and she had issues. Sidney is
much stronger than Julia in a lot of ways, though still messed up.
That's why it was important for me to do Suzie Toller in `Wild
Things' _ I played something on the other extreme.
 &HT;    ``Each time I do a project, I'm very concerned about not doing
the same thing the next time around.''
 &HT;    The only exceptions, of course, were her appearances in ``Scream
2'' (1998) and ``Scream 3'' (2000).
 &HT;    ``It was a very difficult decision,'' she says of the latest
installment. ``The very reason a sequel is made is because the
first one was so fantastic or people loved it so much. To think you
can possibly stand up to what that was is a huge challenge _
especially because Kevin Williamson didn't write `Scream 3.'
 &HT;    ``When I knew Wes Craven was going to be there and the cast
would be there, that it would be the last one and a nice way to
finish it, then I was willing to do it.''
 &HT;    Though ``Scream 3'' killed at the box office, taking in more
than $75 million in its first few weeks, all involved are still
insisting that this was the final go-round for the still-potent
franchise.
 &HT;    Speaking of endings, the actress has also decided to depart
``Party of Five'' at the end of this season, whether or not Fox
decides to renew the long-running series, whose ratings have
slipped in recent months.
 &HT;    ``It's bittersweet,'' she says quietly. ``I've spent 15 hours a
day, five days a week, for six years with these people on `Party of
Five.' I've spent more time being Julia than being myself in a lot
of ways, which is frightening.
 &HT;    ``So I am sad to see it go,'' she admits. ``It is the reason I
came to the States. It's why my face got out there. It's been great
for me _ it's been a great way for me to work my muscles every day
as an actor, which not many people get to do.''
 &HT;    She feels much the same way about the ``Scream'' series _ happy
to have done it, even if she's also happy to be able to move on.
 &HT;    ``I've had a blast,'' Campbell says. ``We just have so much fun
together on those films. So I am sad to say goodbye to them, but
I'm also really excited about new opportunities and growing and
staying inspired.''
 &HT;    And getting some rest, adds the actress, who politely declines
comment on her relationship with actor John Cusack, but waxes
enthusiastic about a recent vacation in Hawaii and her current
mission to learn Spanish.
 &HT;    ``I will definitely slow down,'' Campbell says. ``My schedule
can't ever be as hard as it has been for the last six years,
because I won't be doing nine months of a television show and then
at least two movies at hiatus.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe and maybe not. After all, Campbell has already
completed ``Panic,'' co-starring William H. Macy. And, only 10 days
after wrapping production on ``Party of Five,'' she'll jet off to
Berlin to star with Nick Nolte in Alan Rudolph's drama
``Investigating Sex.''
 &HT;    ``What I'd like is just to do films and to be able to choose my
scripts and take time off,'' Campbell says, smiling. ``I think it
will be easier to spend time with myself.
 &HT;    ``So I'm scared and I'm excited about the opportunities,'' she
concludes. ``I hope it will work out.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
