<SLUG> BC-SIZE-DOES-MATTER-ON-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHAPE OF STARS TO COME: WHY SIZE STILL MATTERS ON TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 EDITORS: Note possibly offensive language in final paragraph. 
 (Includes a color slide of Calista Flockhart in a scene from ``Ally
McBeal.'') 
 By CATHERINE DAWSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada before March 12, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Hollywood, where image is everything, the latest formula for
actresses seems to be: Skinny  &QC;  Stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Stick-figure celebrities are all over the big and small screens,
and we've watched their weights drop until their bones show
through. The roster includes Jennifer Aniston and Courteney Cox
Arquette on ``Friends'' and ``Ally McBeal's'' Calista Flockhart.
Debra Messing of ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' Paula Devicq of ``Party of
Five'' and Lara Flynn Boyle of ``The Practice'' are often
punchlines in late-night monologues. ``Frasier's'' English beauty,
Jane Leeves, has noticeably lost inches, as have Helen Hunt and
Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, size-four comedian Kathy Griffin of ``Suddenly
Susan'' felt she had to undergo a liposuction operation that ended
in an allergic reaction to an anesthetic and a bladder infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I lost,'' Griffin told Glamour magazine, ``was about
$6,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's more to this trend than skewed aesthetics
or celebrity follies. These superthin actresses are role models to
their fans, especially teen-age and pre-teen girls, whose yearning
to emulate their idols can result in serious, even life-threatening
eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a beauty ideal that people have strived
toward,'' says Barb Callaghan, assistant program director at the
National Eating Disorder Information Centre in Toronto. ``We do set
a certain value on being thin and what thinness means. If you look
at the media, they perpetuate that. Thinness is success. Thinness
is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion magazines are the worst offenders, Callaghan adds, but
films and television aren't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Hollywood industry you have to look a certain way to
get the parts,'' she says. ``It's a standard that's been set.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is toughest on actresses struggling to land that
first big break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you find out you didn't get a job because you
weren't pretty or thin enough,'' says Sarah Paulson of ``Jack &AMP;
Jill.'' ``I want them to put me in that movie _ do I conform to
what their form of beauty is, or do I stick to my own guns?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard _ you fluctuate back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, male actors don't face nearly the same
challenge. They may feel pressured to ``look the part,'' but it's
not a career-killer for a man to be overweight _ he can even earn
slightly tongue-in-cheek status as a sex symbol.
</P>
<P>
   When ``NYPD Blue's'' 235-pound Dennis Franz bared his behind in
a 1994 episode, the media hype was deafening. But how many
235-pound female's butts will television viewers ever see?
</P>
<P>
   On doctor's advice, Franz shed about 35 pounds last year, yet he
says his low-carbohydrate diet nonetheless allows him to eat ``vats
of Jell-O and whipped cream.'' It's a rare quote to read in a diet
story, and unimaginable in one about a female star.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rare venues where talent triumphs over dress size is
the ratings-challenged sitcom ``Veronica's Closet.'' Its two leads,
Kirstie Alley and Kathy Najimy, are women who unashamedly have real
meat on their bones.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the show's funniest scenes have belonged to Najimy, who
often speaks out against the only-thin-is-beautiful ideal. Earlier
this year she put her body where her belief was, modeling
plus-sized lingerie for a New York fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   The standard bearer for a more inclusive definition of beauty
is, of course, ``The Practice's'' Camryn Manheim. Her ``fat girls''
acceptance speech at the 1998 Emmy Awards quickly become the stuff
of Hollywood legend, and her autobiography, ``Wake Up, I'm Fat''
(Broadway Books, 1999), is a virtual manifesto for her cause.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she feels that even now her size hampers her career
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as a leading movie role and making it romantic,'' she
says, ``I don't see that around the bend anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys have it easier, especially on the small screen. One key
story line on ``The Drew Carey Show'' is the sexual tension between
beer-bellied Carey and his svelte girlfriend Kate (Christa Miller).
The characters reportedly will consummate their relationship in a
much-hyped episode later this season.
</P>
<P>
   Manheim notes, however, that while a woman who by female
standards was as large as Carey would rarely be viewed as
attractive, even he is subject to an arbitrary standard of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had fatty breasts, that would not be right,'' Manheim
says. ``Men with beer guts aren't considered fat, but men with
breasts are considered fat _ it's like a masculine and feminine
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as a lot of actors are concerned, the media is as
responsible for the cult of thinness as any producer or casting
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has gotten out of hand this past year,'' says
Michael Badaluco, the tall, stocky co-star of ``The Practice.''
``All you read about in magazines or tabloids is whether this
actress is anorexic. I guess it sells magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it should really be people's private business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensational stories about too-skinny stars do sell, however, and
there's not much that the actresses themselves can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have control over what people write,'' Cox Arquette
says. ``If they say we're too thin, I can't take responsibility for
that. I happen to like the way I am _ or maybe I don't, but that's
nobody else's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Aniston, who has experienced a full-court media press because of
her relationship with Brad Pitt, says that all a performer can do
is to try to ignore the tabloid stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you realize that these are people doing a job and they
have to put entertainment in magazines, you can take things less
personally, the good and the bad,'' she says. ``You realize it's
only one guy in a room writing something to make you feel bad. One
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability and he knows that _ that's his little
thrill for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's harder to ignore direct questions during interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I anorexic? Am I bulimic? I get that question all the
time,'' says Jaime Pressley of ``Jack &AMP; Jill.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressley started her career as a dancer and gymnast, but says
she couldn't find work as an actress until she lost the thick
muscle in her legs and torso.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I did press interviews,'' she recalls, ``I had 80
people in a row ask me if I was anorexic, why I was so thin. Why am
I losing all this weight? Do I think I need to? Am I eating? What
do I eat?''
</P>
<P>
   She motions to her baggy sweater and loose-fitting khakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I dress this way _ I'm so tired of it,'' she says.
``I couldn't be more sick of people looking at my body and telling
me I'm too thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about who's got a beautiful ass or a scrawny ass.
It's because I can act.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Catherine Dawson is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
