<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOVERNORS-BUSH29-COX     02-28 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-BUSH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP GOVERNORS: LET'S RUN A BUSH-McCAIN TICKET
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican governors would clearly like to see one
of their own, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, in the White House. But
as they met here Monday, there were signs that they would be almost
as happy if Sen. John McCain won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President McCain would be an excellent president,
compared to a Vice President (Al) Gore or a Senator (Bill)
Bradley,'' Gov. Bill Owens of Colorado told reporters. ``My choice,
in order, is George Bush and then John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments were promptly echoed by two fellow Republicans
from two other probable battleground states in the November
election: Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Even more intriguing to the political trio, who came to a press
lunch during the annual winter National Governors' Association
winter meeting, was the idea of a Bush picking McCain as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a blockbuster ticket,'' said Ridge, who himself
is thought to be on the Bush vice-presidential radar scope should
Bush prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Owens went further in suggesting that Bush should agree to run
in the second spot with McCain if the Arizona senator wins the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a rational unifying gesture by either of those
candidates to go to the second-running candidate and make that
offer,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited as a model ``the 1980 experience'' at the Republican
National Convention in Detroit, when former California Gov. Ronald
Reagan went to George Bush, his former top challenger, to offer him
the vice-presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the Reagan chairman in my county in Colorado, and I know
how that helped bring the party together for the general
election,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   The governors largely discounted the increasingly harsh tone of
the current campaign as possibly standing in the way of an eventual
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ridge: ``I know there's tremendous mutual respect between
the two of them. That's true despite what their surrogates are
saying and the accusations that are now flying back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   After last week's Michigan primary, which McCain won, Gov. John
Engler, a Republican, said he ``thought McCain was a very likely
person to be on the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has yet to indicate a choice of a running mate should his
quest for the nomination prove successful. But McCain, who has
served 18 years in the Senate and chairs one of its most powerful
committees, has made it clear on numerous occasions that he's not
interested in the vice-presidential post, should it be offered to
him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press'' last December, ``Would
you accept the vice presidency from George Bush?'' McCain
responded, ``Under no circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
