<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-BRADLEY-HNS &LR;      02-28 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA A GOLD MINE FOR BRADLEY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Opinion polls give Bill Bradley little chance of
winning California's Democratic primary contest on March 7. But
there is one key constituency that favors former New Jersey senator
over Vice President Al Gore: checkbook Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   According to Federal Election Commission records, Bradley raised
more political money in California in 1999 than the vice president,
$4.2 million to $3.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The records show that Bradley outperformed Gore in part because
of hefty donations from computer executives in the Silicon Valley.
According to the records, Bradley got more money than Gore from
most other California interest groups as well: financial
institutions, managed care companies, agricultural interests and
the real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Hollywood and among lawyers _ two California
constituencies cultivated by President Clinton _ did the vice
president raise more money than Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where Democrats are dominant, Bradley and Gore
together managed to raise only about $1 million more than Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential hopeful, has
raised alone.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has visited California more than 50 times since he
became vice president in 1993, began 1999 with a big fund-raising
advantage here over Bradley, records show, but they also show that
donor enthusiasm for the vice president began to cool last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bradley's fund-raising surged. One mega-event, a
Sept. 30 fund-raiser in the Silicon Valley that reaped $635,000,
put the challenger ahead of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   According to the records, executives at the state's financial
institutions were another big source of campaign cash for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and brokers gave him $744,000 _ $300,000 more than Gore
_ but only half that they donated to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest bundle of all came from the Palo Alto high-tech law
firm Wilson, Sonsini. Thirty-nine lawyers there, including partner
Larry Sonsini, combined to write $37,000 in checks for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley raised more money in the San Francisco Bay Area than
either Bush or Gore _ $2.4 million. He also was the top political
fund-raiser in San Francisco, where he raised $685,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's biggest fund-raising success came in the state's
communications industry, where be received $619,745, more than
either Bradley or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did especially well in Hollywood, where Clinton was a
hugely effective fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Warner Brothers gave him $36,000, those at
Paramount Pictures gave $33,750 and those at Dreamworks SKG, the
movie studio headed by David Geffen, Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey
Katzenberg, contributed $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among celebrities donating $1,000 to Gore: television producer
Norman Lear; Simpsons creator Matt Groening; filmmaker Oliver
Stone; and actors Candice Bergen, Kevin Costner, Ted Danson,
Michael Douglas, Tom Hanks, Suzanne Somers, Mary Steenburgen and
Billy Dee Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz pianist Herbie Hancock and singer Sheryl Crow each gave
$1,000, and the Eagles combined to give $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also did well among the state's lawyers, getting $570,000,
$27,000 more than Bradley and $112,000 more than Bush. Partners
from Los Angeles' O'Melveny &AMP; Myers ($17,550) and San Francisco's
Morrison &AMP; Foerster ($14,250) gave the most.
</P>
<P>
   But among most other interest groups, Gore trailed both Bradley
and Bush. The state's financial industry gave him slightly more
than half what Bradley obtained and $1 for every $3 that Bush
received.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein was the top elected official to donate to
Gore ($1,000). Other prominent Democrats, including Gov. Gray Davis
and Sen. Barbara Boxer, did not donate to either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore got two-thirds of his money from Southern California, and
most of the rest from the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley dominated most interest groups, he raised
surprisingly little money from one industry segment he knows the
best: pro basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The former New York Knicks star got $4,800 from state basketball
executives, including $500 from the Los Angeles Lakers' Jerry West
and $300 from the Golden State Warriors' Al Attles.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did much better with executives from another sport:
big-league baseball. He received $8,000: $2,250 from the San
Francisco Giants, $1,000 from the Los Angeles Dodgers and $4,750
from the San Diego Padres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1130 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-PUMPKINS-STEELYDAN-90     02-28 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKINS-STEELYDAN-900(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMASHING PUMPKINS, STEELY DAN ISSUE EAGERLY AWAITED CDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On paper, Steely Dan and the Smashing Pumpkins have nothing in
common _ not their music, not their age, not their audience, not
their visibility during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Pumpkins hail from Chicago and in the past eight years have
become one of the biggest alternative-rock (if such a thing still
exists) bands on the planet, arguably ``the'' biggest, selling
millions of CDs and embarking on lengthy arena-filling tours as
songs such as ``Cherub Rock, 1979'' and ``Bullet With Butterfly
Wings'' have become as well-known to rock fans under 30 as
``Stairway to Heaven'' was in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The Dan is the partnership of Donald Fagen and Walter Becker,
who in 1972 began releasing a string of slick jazz-meets-rock CDs
that became enormously popular between 1972 and 1980 on the basis
of a string of impeccably produced, lyrically odd and musically
adventurous LPs.
</P>
<P>
   What links them, then? They both have eagerly awaited CDs out
Tuesday. So there.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At least half the fun of being a Steely Dan fan in the '70s was
not knowing what it would do next _ and the other half was knowing
exactly what it would do next.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade obsessed with musical prowess _ which often
translated as bloated, self-indulgent art- and jazz-rock _ Donald
Fagen and Walter Becker made truly admirable music. Their forte was
combining jazz sensibilities with a pop aesthetic that featured odd
and sometimes obscure lyrics about fringe characters and agreeable
singalong choruses.
</P>
<P>
   And their output _ seven LPs and at least as many era-defining
songs in a mere eight years _ was astonishingly high, even if they
didn't tour and apparently lived in expensive recording studios in
Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Admirable guys, these two: highbrow but funky, oddly compelling
but archly distant, capable of playing kick-butt rock 'n' roll but
astutely cerebral. At its best, Steely Dan was all things to all
people _ writers of catchy radio fodder that had a nasty, knowing
underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   And then they went away. For more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   And then they came back _ sort of _ to do a few shed tours that
only left their legions of fans wanting more. Much more.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the expectations surrounding ``Two Against
Nature,'' the Dan's first studio recording since 1980's tepid
``Gaucho,'' are unrealistic: They've had 20 years, right? So this
has got to be a classic record, on a par with or better than
``Countdown to Ecstasy'' or ``Aja.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, no. Although superbly crafted and possessed of a number
of worthy mellow pop grooves, ``Two'' too often feels vapid _ not
empty, but hardly ever fully realized.
</P>
<P>
   Or to put it another way, the surprise factor is way down. All
the pieces we know and love are in place: Fagen sings in that weird
little voice about weird people, the band percolates along but
hardly ever really chugs _ much less rocks with the sort of
conviction of a ``My Old School'' _ Becker plays a beautifully
sculpted but uncompelling jazz-rock solo, the chorus is repeated,
over and out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slickly agreeable sound, to be sure, but the twists and
turns and odd little corners that used to be the most welcome parts
of Dan records are now the exception.
</P>
<P>
   What we're too often left with, on ``Gaslighting Abbie,'' ``Two
Against Nature'' and elsewhere, is far more about pure sanded-down
craft than fresh inspiration. It's a vanilla milkshake rather than
a chocolate one, a CD that only serves to remind us of the almost
endless delights of every one of the band's previous releases save
``Gaucho,'' with which ``Two'' shares a sort of tame, conservative
tunefulness.
</P>
<P>
   And this, too, must be said: Fagen (52) and Becker (50 last
week) seem to have a sort of creepy fascination with vulnerable
young women. ``Janie Runaway'' is the story of a guy who becomes a
sugar daddy to a homeless girl he meets in a New York park and
contains the tease ``Who gets to spend her birthday in Spain?
Possibly you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's icky _ but far ickier is ``Cousin Dupree,'' which
concerns a loser who is sponging off an aunt and who becomes
attracted to his much younger cousin, Jeanine. ``How about a kiss
for your Cousin Dupree?'' is the chorus; one line in a verse is
``What's so strange about a down-home family romance?'' Well, lots
if the girl is still a teen-ager, old sport.
</P>
<P>
   These songs, and ``Negative Girl,'' suggest that the pair have
decided to substitute a perhaps sexist smugness for the
subversiveness that they brought to the best of their stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Against Nature'' is not without its charms, but most of
those charms can already be found _ done better _ on records 20 or
more years old.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Steely Dan
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Against Nature''
</P>
<P>
   Giant Records
</P>
<P>
   3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   SMASHING PUMPKINS
</P>
<P>
   Billy Corgan needs an editor.
</P>
<P>
   I say this as a writer, and a Smashing Pumpkins fan, and I would
say it to him if His Baldness ever called me up, which he won't.
</P>
<P>
   Corgan is a man of many talents: As leader of the Smashing
Pumpkins, he spent the band's first three CDs _ ``Gish,'' their
1993 breakthrough ``Siamese Dream'' and '95's monumentally
successful two-CD ``Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness'' _
constructing a metal/alternative/art-rock hybrid and an
angry-little-boy-lost persona.
</P>
<P>
   This made Corgan one of the most famous men in rock 'n' roll,
reviled as a control freak by some, embraced as a voice of a
generation by the twentysomethings who filled arenas around the
world. In Corgan they found a kindred spirit, a guy proud to
display his emotional scars while serrating the ears with some of
the sharper hard rock guitar riffs in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   But what he does not know is when to shut up. Not that he should
``shut up,'' quit making records forever _ although he hinted
broadly that he was about to do just that in the most recent issue
of ``Rolling Stone.'' But he should, perhaps, learn the art of
judicious pruning: ``MACHINA/the machines of God,'' the Pumpkins'
new CD, is an embrace of life and the search for love. And big,
loud rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it's exactly the kind of record the Pumpkins needed to
make: The band's last CD, 1998's ``Adore,'' was a downcast, subdued
affair that found Corgan wrestling with the end of his marriage,
the loss of his mother, Martha, to cancer, and the OD of tour
keyboardist Jonathan Melvoin and subsequent firing of drummer Jimmy
Chamberlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``MACHINA'' is all about better days, moving forward, looking
ahead, falling in love with rock 'n' roll again. Usually hopeful,
the 15 songs here swerve from metal to pop and back again, with
Corgan singing of blue skies and possibilities and so on. ``Away
with everything you've grown to hate,'' he sings on the sailing,
upbeat ``With Every Light.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, ``MACHINA'' is overlong, overstuffed, chock-full
of songs that have more noisiness than real intensity. The CD is
more of a retrenchment _ to big, up choruses and thick, brawny
guitar _ but Corgan hardly ever sounds as convincing a hopeful guy
as he did a post-Robert Smith miserabilist searching for
connections even as he was making the amps bleed.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the band sounds great: Having Chamberlin back in the
fold has helped immeasurably. But all too often all that means is
pro-forma Pumpkins: sturdy pop on ``Stand Inside Your Love,''
hammering hard rock on ``The Everlasting Gaze,'' and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not much else besides two of the worst songs the band has
ever recorded: ``Heavy Metal Machine'' is just dumb, and the nearly
10-minute ``Glass and the Ghost Children'' is an arty, pretentious
uber-mess.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving these two _ and ``Wound,'' and ``The Crying Tree of
Mercury,'' and ``The Sacred and Profane'' _ on the cutting-room
floor would have made ``MACHINA'' a much stronger record. Then
again, even the songs that remain are not among the strongest the
band has ever done, or even close.
</P>
<P>
   Corgan may be a happier camper these days, but the overall
impact of his work has taken a dip since the heady days of 1993-95.
``MACHINA'' will sell very well, but it doesn't advance the band's
story much.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Smashing Pumpkins
</P>
<P>
   ``MACHINA/the machines of God''
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Records
</P>
<P>
   3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
