<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-AID _ WASHINGTON _ House Republicans attacked the
Education Department on Monday for ``persistent, serious problems''
with the form used by millions of students to apply for federal
college aid. Since mid-January, the department has admitted that it
incorrectly programmed a formula used to calculate eligibility and
it crafted a new question on drug-related convictions is so complex
that one-fifth of the applicants didn't answer it. Last year, 3.5
million printed versions of the form contained errors. (Mollison,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-SEX _ WASHINGTON _ More than half of teens aged 15-19 have
engaged in oral sex, according to a national survey of teenagers'
sexual practices conducted by Seventeen magazine. (Wilson, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-CARS _ WASHINGTON _ A new Internet site tells car buyers
whether their vehicle was affected by last year's catastrophic
North Carolina floods. (Livingston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IRS _ WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service hired 138 tax
processors whose backgrounds included theft, assault and weapons
charges. The IRS put them to work before receiving clearances from
their fingerprint checks, the General Accounting Office says in a
report to be made public Tuesday. The study, an advance copy of
which was obtained by Cox Newspapers, lists dozens of weaknesses,
including findings that the IRS can't balance its own checkbook and
misstates the amount of funds put into Social Security and Medicare
trust funds. The GAO also cites careless handling of money,
including giving a courier $28 million for deposit before asking
for an i.d. Administration officials are scheduled to discuss the
problems Tuesday at a House subcommittee hearing. (Geewax, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RECORDS _ ATLANTA _ The future of the Atlanta Olympic
records the newspapers and state attorney general fought so hard to
make public last year is in jeopardy. Atlanta Olympic officials
have dissolved their corporation and transferred ownership of
thousands of boxes of documents detailing the bid and organizing
committee operations to the Colorado Springs, Colo based USOC,
which will either transfer the records to Colorado or incinerate
them. Either option puts the vast majority of documented Olympic
history out of reach of the Atlanta public. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
