<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER29-COX     02-28 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Birds of a feather?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain condemned Christian conservative leaders Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``agents of intolerance'' Monday and
warned his Republican Party against ``pandering to the outer
reaches of American politics.'' In a stinging rebuke delivered in
Virginia, the evangelists' home state, McCain, with Gary Bauer on
stage with him, was careful to say he wasn't attacking religious
conservative voters, only ``a few of their self-appointed
leaders.'' He added: ``Neither party should be defined by pandering
to the outer reaches of American politics and the agents of
intolerance, whether they be Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton on the
left, or Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell on the right.''
</P>
<P>
   SHIELD AGAINST MCCAIN'S `MISSILES'
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to John McCain's assault on ``agents of intolerance,''
George W. Bush said the party needs a presidential candidate who
would unite people instead of playing ``a political game'' of
``pitting one group of people against another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing the religious card; that's not Reaganesque,''
Bush said. ``That reminds me of the current administration.'' Sen.
John Warner (R-Va.) also was critical of McCain's remarks: ``I have
to tell my old friend to pull back on his throttle and quit trying
to fire heat-seeking missiles up everybody's tailpipe.''
</P>
<P>
   HE COULDN'T GO _ BUT IF HE HAD . . .
</P>
<P>
   While John McCain upbraids George W. Bush, ABC News says it has
learned that McCain also was in discussions with Bob Jones
University about a possible visit. Terry Haskins, speaker pro-tem
of the South Carolina House and McCain's South Carolina
representative confirmed the discussions. ABC reported that talks
lasted only a few days before McCain's national office said the
schedule wouldn't allow for an appearance there. McCain has
repeatedly said he would have given a more courageous speech on
tolerance in contrast to Bush's, if only given the opportunity.
McCain, on the discussions: ``None serious, because there was no
invitation extended.''
</P>
<P>
   `BEAUTY CONTEST' WITHOUT CROWN AND SASH
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, spending six days campaigning in Washington
state's ``beauty contest' primary today, said Monday the state's
voters can send a message across the nation. But they'll have to
remember to send it again in the party caucuses a week later _
because that's when the delegates will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   END COULD BE NEAR FOR BRADLEY
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley's insurgent campaign seemed on the verge of
overtaking Al Gore last fall, but since losing in Iowa and New
Hampshire, it seems to have run out of steam. Though Bradley
continues to campaign and is not yet willing to concede defeat,
most Democratic observers say he is unlikely to make it beyond
March 7, the day primaries are held in 16 states. Even those inside
the campaign admit the prospects are dim. Said Rick Wright, who had
helped Bradley raise $27 million: ``Everyone is realistic. We can
all count. We can all see the calendar. We all see the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE AS CAMPAIGN TOOL
</P>
<P>
   Even as Al Gore was campaigning in Colorado on Monday, he was
keeping an eye on Washington state. He phoned in drive-time
interviews to Seattle radio stations this morning before heading to
rallies in Denver and Pueblo. Gore told interviewers he was
``optimistic'' about today's primary and answered questions about
smoking marijuana in his youth (``I certainly encourage young
people not to get involved in that.'') and labeling of
objectionable music lyrics (``I think parents deserve that.'').
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE A LOW ITEM ON SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   With California's March 7 primary approaching, a high-profile
showdown in California seemed threatened when John McCain said he
wouldn't appear at Thursday's scheduled debate in Los Angeles.
McCain said Monday that George W. Bush dallied in committing to the
event, and by the time Bush agreed McCain already was locked into a
campaign schedule he didn't want to change. Bush denied causing
delay and demanded an explanation from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND SWEEP IN TERRITORIES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush swept presidential contests in four U.S.
territories over the weekend, walking away with 26 delegates to the
national convention. Bush got 93 percent of the vote against John
McCain in Sunday's primary in Puerto Rico to win all 14 delegates
from the island. He also won caucuses held a day earlier in Guam,
American Samoa and the Virgin Islands, getting four national
convention delegates from each. The weekend's 26 delegates pushed
Bush's total to 93; McCain has 96. A candidate needs 1,034
delegates to win the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   OH, THE IRONY OF IT ALL
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush may have reason to be kicking himself now for
favoring a primary in Virginia instead of more-easily controlled
caucuses. Virginia Republicans used to pick delegates by caucuses
and, as noted by the New York Post, Bush would have been a
``shoo-in, with no need to spend much time or cash.'' But the Bush
campaign wanted a primary to help him hold off a more conservative
candidate backed by the religious right. Now, the right is in
Bush's corner.
</P>
<P>
   AHEAD WHERE IT REALLY COUNTS
</P>
<P>
   In California on Monday, a new poll found George W. Bush leading
John McCain by 20 percentage points among the Republican voters who
will choose delegates, but tied with McCain for the popular vote
that includes Democrats and independents. The Field Poll found Bush
leading McCain, 48 percent to 28 percent, among likely Republicans
voters. The poll, conducted Tuesday through Sunday, has a 3
percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE, BRIMSTONE AND AN APOCALYPSE
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the University of Virginia, Alan Keyes ``railed
against what he called the federal government's abuse of power _
running the gamut from his opposition to abortion rights and the
World Trade Organization to his support for the Second Amendment
and teaching creationism in public schools. Keyes also told a
Regents University audience, according to the Richmond
Times-Dispatch, that the nation ``will soon crumble and the world
will face a century of unspeakable horror.''
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR BILL VS. DR. LAURA
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley lashed out at radio talk-show host Laura
Schlessinger, saying her disapproval of homosexuality should
disqualify her from getting a television program. Bradley, in an
interview broadcast over a Web site (www.gaybc.com) that caters to
homosexuals, said Schlessinger's ``total misunderstanding of what
it means to be gay and lesbian'' makes ``me sick to my stomach.''
He also said Paramount should drop its plans to run ``Dr. Laura''
on television this fall.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURA WOULD DO TAG-TEAM WITH MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, who recently dropped his
affiliation with the Reform Party, told the Minneapolis
Star-Tribune that although he won't endorse anyone for president
until late summer, he'd be glad to listen if John McCain asked him
to be his vice president. Later, Ventura stressed that he'd
consider being McCain's running mate only if McCain loses the
Republican nomination and becomes an independent.
</P>
<P>
   PENNY FOR HIS THOUGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Despite taking early steps toward a campaign, former Rep. Tim
Penny (D-Minn.) said Monday he's decided not to run for the Senate
this year. ``For strictly personal reasons, I have decided to let
this opportunity pass me by,'' Penny, 48, wrote in a statement. He
didn't immediately elaborate. Sen. Rod Grams (R-Minn.) is seeking
re-election to a second term in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
