<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAP-YEAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAP OF FAITH: `29ERS' DESCEND ON TINY TEXAS TOWN FOR CELEBRATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over second n in quinceanera) 
 
By MARTY RACINE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTHONY, Texas _ Don Porto's family thinks he's nuts. And, he
admits with a laugh that borders on a cackle, ``They might have a
point there.''
</P>
<P>
   Porto, a data processing consultant with a wife and two
children, has driven alone from New York to the desert Southwest to
celebrate his 14th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he was born 56 years ago. But Tuesday is leap day, that
24-hour appendage to February that occurs every four years. And in
this bypass hamlet straddling the Texas-New Mexico line just north
of El Paso, Porto is really 14. And he's sharing the occasion with
scores &UR;  &LR; of other ``29ers'' in the self-styled Leap Year Capital of
the World, where a calendar's asterisk is accorded cult status.
</P>
<P>
   Leap year dates to the Roman Empire, when in 46 B.C. Julius
Caesar decreed that an extra day be added to February every four
years to keep the seasons in sync with the universe. Astronomers
had calculated that Earth's orbit around the sun took 365 days, 5
hours and 48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By the 16th century the adjustment put the calendar days out of
kilter, so Pope Gregory XIII subtracted 10 days from 1582 and
ordered the omission of leap years in centuries not evenly
divisible by 400. Thus, 1700, 1800 and 1900 were not leap years,
but 2000 is, making this turn-of-the-century leap year even more
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   But 29ers, or ``leapers,'' find any leap year magical, as if the
sun shines overtime just for them. Even as children they were never
deprived, Porto says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother used to feel just heartsick that I had no (annual)
birthday. She would say, `You were born the day after Feb. 28, so
we'll celebrate your birthday March 1.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd have a birthday party, and she'd invite the relatives
over. But it didn't take me very long to figure out that I was born
the day before March 1, so the week before I'd really pester her.
She would have a party for just her and me on the 28th.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I used to have two birthdays every year. And when it came
to be leap year, I'd only get one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE IS IT? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony is literally nowhere, situated at Exit 0 on Interstate
10. Anthony, Texas, is incorporated, with its own city services. As
for the New Mexico side, ``We're a long way from (state capital)
Santa Fe,'' says resident Judy Horton.
</P>
<P>
   But even the locals don't differentiate. ``We're in New Mexico _
I think. I'm never quite sure,'' says a festival volunteer at
Anthony Park in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're standing in Texas,'' another says at the same site.
</P>
<P>
   No quirk of nature blessed Anthony with more leap-year babies
per capita than anyplace else. (Statistically, one of every 1,461
people is a leaper.) But this quiet town, population 3,500 or so in
Texas, seized the notion of a festival in 1988, when Mary Ann
Brown, now 17 leap years old, proposed it to the Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chamber through the years had kicked around having some
kind of celebration,'' she says. ``Some members plain didn't want
to do the work, and we couldn't agree on any.''
</P>
<P>
   When she suggested the idea to the chamber, ``They kind of all
looked at each other. But there was a man named David who'd been
sent out here to be head of the Alpo dog food plant, and he said,
`Well, I think it sounds like a good idea.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Worldwide Leap Year Birthday Club was formed, and
Anthony proclaimed itself Leap Year Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community should get down on its knees and thank (Brown)
for what she's done,'' says Jan Risher, a former resident and
volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 29ers attended the 1996 party. But several thousand
others turned out for the festivities. This year's four-day bash,
which concludes Tuesday, drew 29ers from as far away as
Switzerland. The events include a golf and fishing tournament, hot
air balloon rides, a chuckwagon breakfast, 5K walk and 10K run,
wine tasting, parade, concerts and an arts and crafts fair.
</P>
<P>
   The kicker Tuesday night is a performance by Graham Nash of
Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young; Nash's wife is a 29er.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT'S MY BIRTHDAY' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose idea it was to come here? It wasn't his,'' Susan Nash
says of her husband as she strolls into the lobby of the Holiday
Inn Express on the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had complained, ``You know, we're shutting this whole
tour down for your birthday, it's costing us a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my birthday,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not playing in a high school gymnasium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's my birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   So that was Graham Nash, looking like anything but a rock star,
signing autographs in Anthony Park on Sunday. He had flown in after
performing in Minneapolis while his green-and-silver tour bus was
driven from an earlier Denver concert the day before to pick up
Susan, her mother, their son and friends at the El Paso airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Nash entourage wore matching &UR;  &LR; olive green sweatshirts
imprinted with Susan's birth certificate. The birthday queen, a
first-timer in Anthony, also wore a crown her daughter had earned
in an AIDS walkathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a good idea. What else are you going to do? I
don't think you can come down here and be serious about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan has gotten a kick out of Anthony, and her son is
videotaping the proceedings. ``This is a pretty cute little event,
isn't it? We're good in small towns. We fit in real well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nashes maintain homes in Los Angeles and on the Hawaiian
Island of Kauai.
</P>
<P>
   It is remarkable that Graham is even on tour or in Anthony. Or
that he participated in Monday's golf tournament. Five months ago
he broke both legs in a boating accident when he lost his balance
on a wave. They were shattered, Susan says, like Rice Krispies.
</P>
<P>
   She went into shock. ``I couldn't face him, his feet going the
wrong way, his face gray. I didn't know if he was paralyzed or was
going to have a stroke. When your husband's always been `so there,'
to see him that vulnerable ...''
</P>
<P>
   The tour had been already scheduled, and Graham willed himself
to make it. ``I'm sure he made it happen. I cried to see him walk
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A LEAP-YEAR FAMILY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jesse and Diane Perez are as excited as their daughter, Jesika,
3 leap years old. Along with their other children, Jacob and
Jacqueline, they will be attending Tuesday's leap-year parade. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting them out of school early, but they're A/B honor
roll,'' says Diane, a substitute teacher for the El Paso
Independent School District.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse, an emergency medical technician at El Paso International
Airport, is also making time for family. ``I'm starting my four-day
weekend. I'd normally go back Tuesday, but I'm taking it off
because it's my daughter's birthday. She's been waiting a long time
for this day.''
</P>
<P>
   A leap-year family must occasionally live in multiples of four.
``You've heard of quinceanera (the 15th birthday celebration),''
Diane says. ``With Jesika, it's going to be a Sweet Sixteen.''
</P>
<P>
   Angie Vincent, 18 leap years old, is visiting from Grand Rapids,
Mich., with her husband, Eugene, a retired firefighter, and an
extended family of 12. They're folding her birthday into the annual
family reunion that began in 1986 after the death of three
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen more of each other the last few years than we did
for a lot of years,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Susan O'Brien, a secretary in the Department of Justice in El
Paso, is 14 leap years old Tuesday. Growing up in North Platte,
Neb., she basked in being the only leap-year child in school _
until the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset, because it was my birthday, and I didn't want to
share it with him.''
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager's need to conform didn't unnerve her, she says. ``I
think you want to look like everybody else, and you want to go to
the same places, see the same movies, but really, to have something
that differentiates you _ it was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien will attend the Graham Nash concert, but that was not
the drawing card. ``Meeting the other people is the thing. You have
something in common. It's a starting point for conversation. It's a
lot better than `What's your sign?'''
</P>
<P>
   Don Porto, who arrived at 5 a.m. Saturday in his motor home,
wouldn't have missed it for a job. In fact, he risked a new
contract to come to Anthony for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me, and I said, only under one condition. You can
write it right on the contract: I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
