<SLUG> BC-COURTMOTHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT TO DECIDE IF SECRET DRUG TESTS ON PREGNANT WOMEN ARE
LEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
public hospitals can test pregnant women for drugs without their
consent and tell the police which ones tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   The court will examine a challenge to a Charleston, S.C.,
hospital's program designed to find pregnant women who use drugs,
especially crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital suspended the practice in 1993 after being sued by
10 women who had been patients there but has stated it will
consider reinstating it if the Supreme Court approves.
</P>
<P>
   The women claimed the practice violated their Fourth Amendment
protections against unreasonable searches.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision, which is expected late this year or early
next year, could determine whether the hospital can reinstate the
program and whether other hospitals can use similar procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question before the court is whether pregnant women have
lesser constitutional rights than other Americans, and, as a
result, can be searched for evidence of a crime in their private
doctor's office without Fourth Amendment protection,'' said Simon
Heller, director of litigation at the Center for Reproductive Law
and Policy. The center is a New York City-based legal and advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical University of South Carolina, a public hospital in
Charleston, began the program in 1989. It was an effort to help
prosecute women who use drugs under a state law that makes it a
crime for mothers to refuse to provide proper care for their
children to the point where the child is ``endangered.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 the South Carolina Supreme Court ruled that a viable
fetus _ one able to live outside the uterus _ is protected by the
child-endangerment law and that the statute could be used against
pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   No other state's top court has allowed similar use of
child-endangerment laws, and the highest courts in Florida,
Kentucky, Nevada and Ohio have explicitly disallowed them.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hospital's program, if a woman's urine test indicated
cocaine use, she would be arrested for distributing the drug to a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1990 the program was changed to give drug-using
patients a choice between being arrested and enrolling for drug
treatment. In suing the hospital in 1993, the 10 women contended
that the urine testing, which was performed without court warrants,
amounted to unreasonable searches that violated their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-week trial, a federal jury ruled against the women.
The Fourth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that verdict last
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the documented health hazards of maternal cocaine
use and the resulting drain on public resources, (hospital)
officials unquestionably possessed a substantial interest in taking
steps to reduce cocaine use by pregnant women,'' the appeals court
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also said the urine tests were ``minimally
intrusive'' and that the hospital's policy helped protect unborn
children.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court concluded that the searches were
constitutional under a ``special needs'' exception to the Fourth
Amendment's requirement that a search must be authorized by court
warrant or based on ``probable cause'' to suspect a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Heller argued that the appeals court took the ``special
needs'' exception too far in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeals court would permit law enforcement and other
governmental officers to engage in searches as a means of gaining
evidence for arrests and prosecutions without a warrant or
individualized suspicion, so long as the government can present a
health or safety reason for its actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
