A1139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BIZMAGS29-COX     02-28 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune unveils 'hip' new substitute market indexes
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do the traditional stock market indexes tell us what's
really happening on Wall Street? The editors of Fortune (March 13)
didn't think so and came up with two of their own. They are
introduced in the magazine's 70th anniversary issue that goes on
newsstands March 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Fortune 500 Index is based on the magazine's famous annual
list of the 500 biggest companies ranked by revenue. The magazine
says a size-based index is more objective than the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500, which is based on subjective decisions as to which
companies should be in the index.
</P>
<P>
   The other index is a product of the ``new economy,'' the Fortune
e-50 index of companies that are ``shaping the Internet economy.''
The index includes e-companies such as America Online and Yahoo,
communications companies such as AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom, software
and service companies such as Microsoft and Oracle and hardware
companies such as IBM and Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Bethany McLean, author of the article describing these indexes,
said Fortune established them because ``new economic conditions
demand a new set of measurements.'' She said the current indexes
``aren't hip enough for the new century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is the Dow (Jones industrial average) way too tiny _
a mere 30 stocks _ but it is also weighed down by the remnants of
industrial America, making it no longer relevant to huge swatches
of the stock market,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   RUTHLESS EFFICIENCY
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Wal-Mart, the retail behemoth, have suffered recently
with other stocks that make up the Dow Jones industrial average.
But a Worth (March) profile of the company finds ``a ruthlessly
efficient retail machine'' beneath the company's ``corny yellow
smiley-face mascot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has dealt heavy blows to competitors such as Kmart and
Sears, and all by itself accounts for 1.5 percent of U.S. gross
domestic product, the magazine says. For investors, the downside is
the company's lofty market valuation. But on balance, Worth says
Wal-Mart ``should be a core, long-term holding in every
growth-oriented portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   HARD LABOR IN ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta's economy has gotten a big boost from thousands of
foreign workers, many of them Latinos from Mexico. But Business to
Business (March), an Atlanta business magazine, says their living
conditions are often poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because many are in the country illegally, they're cheated
out of wages and exploited by some employers. For too many
immigrant workers, legal or not, earning the American dream in
Atlanta is hard labor,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Business Week (March 6) looks for the Federal Reserve to raise
interest rates several more times this year, since ``for the first
time in years, risks are cropping up in the inflation outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   _ With tax time fast approaching, Forbes (March 6) warns that
``con artists are peddling bogus trusts to people seeking tax
shelters.'' When those shams implode, Forbes adds, ``the IRS isn't
sympathetic to the taxpayers who fell for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
