</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-CARS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLOOD-DAMAGED CARS BEING SOLD OUTSIDE NORTH CAROLINA
 &HT;    360&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By GINGER LIVINGSTON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Used car buyers across the United States are being
warned that the great deal they are being offered may be all wet.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina vehicles caught in flooding caused by Hurricane
Floyd last September are starting to pop up on used car lots across
the United States, said Jason King, a spokesman with the American
Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is not always easy to find out if a vehicle was
damaged during flooding, the AAMVA is providing some information on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Car buyers can log on to www.aamva.org and learn if the vehicle
they want to buy came from North Carolina and if it was in the
Hurricane Floyd flooding, King said.
</P>
<P>
   The AAMVA links to the North Carolina attorney general's Web
site, which lists vehicle identification numbers of
``water-damaged'' or ``flood'' vehicles, King said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no uniform federal definition for ``water-damaged''
vehicles, King said. That means a vehicle with a ``flood'' title
listing in North Carolina may not have that listing on its title in
another state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina definition of a ``water-damaged'' or
``flood'' title vehicle is a vehicle that has ``been submerged or
partially submerged in water to the extent that damage to the body,
engine, transmission or differential has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we've found is it usually takes six months to a
year for these cars to be repaired (and) to be sold,'' said Ashley
Westbrook, a spokeswoman for the North Carolina attorney general's
office.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,000 North Carolina vehicles were issued flood
titles, said George Leggett, an investigator with the attorney
general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 60 to 70 percent are no longer in North Carolina. They
have been sold to wholesalers outside the state,'' Leggett said.
</P>
<P>
   One Arkansas wholesaler reportedly bought between 2,500 to 3,000
vehicles with flood titles, Leggett said. It appears the cars are
being prepared for shipment to Texas and Colorado, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of cars are also appearing in Tennessee and
Florida, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Leggett refused to comment on whether any wholesalers who
purchased flood title vehicles are under investigation. Unless the
vehicle is sold in North Carolina, Leggett said, his office had no
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has received five written
complaints and five calls from consumers who believe they had
purchased a flood-damaged vehicle, Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina attorney general's Web site cautions its
listing is not a complete listing of the damaged vehicles. The list
is from the state Division of Motor Vehicles, and the agency is
relying on insurance companies and vehicle owners to notify them
that a car has been damaged by water or flood.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 vehicles were damaged during the Hurricane
Floyd flooding. Not every vehicle was given a flood title, Leggett
said. Some were repaired and others were issued salvaged titles, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   People who suspect their newly purchased used vehicles may have
come from North Carolina can receive a complete title history by
calling the North Carolina Division of Motor Vehicles customer
service line at 919-715-7000 (a toll call) to receive a request for
motor vehicle information application.
</P>
<P>
   The application can also be downloaded from the AAMVA Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston's e-mail address is gingerl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
