<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GOPDAY-COX     02-28 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain rips into Falwell, Robertson and Bush
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. _ Arizona Sen. John McCain on Monday tore
into Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, eager to turn the religious
right leaders into Gov. George W. Bush's cross to bear as the GOP
presidential battle moves into a crucial week.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of today's primaries in Virginia and Washington
state, and caucuses in North Dakota, McCain branded Bush-backers
Robertson and Falwell as ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of Ronald Reagan, not Pat Robertson,'' McCain
said. ``We are the party of Abraham Lincoln, not Bob Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Governor Bush is a Pat Robertson Republican who
will lose to Al Gore,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Bellevue, Washington, accused McCain of
trying to turn a political battle into a fractious religious war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is playing the religion card. That is not Reaganesque,''
said Bush. Bush said the McCain campaign, as it did in Michigan, is
making telephone calls to tell Washington voters that Bush's Feb. 2
appearance at Bob Jones University in South Carolina makes Bush
anti-Catholic. Jones believes Catholicism and Mormonism are
``cults.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York, and other
Catholic leaders, Bush has said he regrets not condemning the
anti-Catholic policy during his speech at the fundamentalist
school.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who frequently tells audiences a person can be judged by
the company he keeps, said Monday he should not be defined by his
backing from Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition, and
Falwell, founder of the Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're supporters of mine, but I've got all kinds of
supporters,'' Bush said. ``What the Republican Party needs is to
have somebody who can unite our party.'' Monday's action came as
both candidates battled for 87 delegates available today in
Washington, Virginia and North Dakota. Next Tuesday, battles in 12
states will determine the allocation of more than half the
delegates needed to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In addressing the significance of what McCain said Monday, one
of his top strategists, John Weaver, said: ``This is a defining
moment for our party and for our campaign. We're at a fork in the
road. The party can choose the well marked path of ... exclusion
and ultimate defeat, the path George W. Bush is taking with Jerry
Falwell and Pat Robertson as his Lewis and Clark. Or we can choose
a new path of inclusion that will produce a Republican victory and
sweeping majority in November.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Virginia Beach speech, McCain mentioned Bush just once by
name but made it clear that he wants Bush to be boxed in as a
candidate tied so closely to the religious right that his
nomination would ensure a Democratic victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   In primaries so far, McCain has fared poorly among Republican
voters while picking up unprecedented support from independents and
Democrats in states with open primaries. The March 7 primaries in
California and New York are limited to registered Republicans, and
McCain is hoping that the more moderate Republican voters who are
numerous in those states will reject Bush's ties to religious
conservative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and Falwell, both based in southern Virginia, so fear
McCain's efforts to change campaign finance laws that they have
attacked him as a disloyal Republican and question his commitment
to conservative policies.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Combs, executive vice president of the Christian
Coalition, which Robertson founded, called McCain's remarks ``a
transparent effort to divide one American from another on the basis
of religion'' and predicted the group's conservative message would
draw record numbers of
</P>
<P>
   voters to the polls. There was no immediate response from
Falwell, founder of the Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They distort my pro-life positions and smear the reputations
of my supporters,'' McCain said, adding that he represents the
GOP's best chance to become a majority party. He said the criticism
from Falwell and Robertson ``surprises me, since the essence of
evangelism is to seek converts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My campaign is bringing new people into the Republican Party
every day. I don't apologize for this. No, I wear it as a badge of
honor,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain compared Robertson and Falwell to ``union bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer
reaches of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether
they be Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton, on the left, or Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell on the right,'' McCain said in speech
to about 1,500 people at Cox High School.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's gambit counts on a belief that many Republicans are
tired of the influence of Robertson and other religious leaders in
determining their party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, there may not be much to lose. Long before Monday's
speech, the religious right was fully mobilized against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their intensity level already is a 10,'' said McCain campaign
manager Rick Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McCain was careful to confine his remarks to
leaders in the religious conservative movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an attack on Christian right voters,'' he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At McCain's side was Gary Bauer, the Christian conservative who
ended his Republican presidential campaign earlier this month and
endorsed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were an attack on Christian conservative voters, I
wouldn't be here. '' Bauer told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the McCain effort to glue him to the religious right
is a strange twist of political fate. The Christian Coalition was
never enamored of Bush's father and have been, at times, lukewarm
to Bush's tenure as governor.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, at the Texas Republican Convention at which Bush
was a political deity, he was absent and unmentioned at the Texas
Christian Coalition's big banquet.
</P>
<P>
   On the banquet buffet line that day, Christian Coalition members
like Sam Gaines of San Antonio expressed concern about Bush's
``degree'' of commitment to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be articulating it, but I'm not hearing it,'' Gaines
said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
