<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAL-MART-UNION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION TOEHOLD IN EAST TEXAS WAL-MART LIFTS LABOR'S HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Texas _ All Maurice Miller, a Wal-Mart meat
cutter, wanted was a $2-an-hour raise.
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't get it, the barrel-chested butcher took on the
nation's biggest retailer _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   In, of all places, anti-union East Texas, Miller, 45, organized
the country's first successful union vote in a Wal-Mart store. In
the labor movement, the chance of getting a toehold in Wal-Mart is
akin to the loss-prone Chicago Cubs sweeping the World Series. The
Arkansas-based chain, founded by Sam Walton, had tenaciously fought
unionization for decades without losing a battle until now.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's problems began when, on the assurance of a promised
pay raise, Miller took out a loan for a new pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was promoted and got that $2 an hour, I wouldn't even
have thought union,'' said Miller, a ponytailed man with 24 years'
experience who lost the tip of his ring finger in a work-related
accident. ``I'd be happy as gold. I just don't appreciate being
lied to.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 eligible meat cutters, seven voted for union
representation on Feb. 17, despite Wal-Mart's ``open door''
approach to labor relations and profit sharing, which the company
says alleviates the need for unions.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.4-million-strong United Food &AMP; Commercial Workers union
sees the East Texas chapter as a crucial foothold and believes that
unionization will quickly spread, noting moves toward a union vote
in nearby Palestine and preparations in Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine-based organizer Brad Edwards said many Wal-Mart
employees in the Fort Worth-Dallas areas and elsewhere have called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get a toehold or a foothold, it is significant,''
said professor David A. Larson, 45, an expert of labor law and
dispute resolution at Hamline University School of Law in St. Paul,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like scaffolding or cracking the citadel,''
Larson said. ``People will hear about this and get empowered. And
if it happens in a place like Texas, a right-to-work state not
historically sympathetic to labor, they will think they'd have a
respectable chance anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart emphasizes that only 10 of the store's 350 employees
participated in the vote, and the company says it is challenging
the ballot result. If it gets no satisfaction with the National
Labor Relations Board, it will try the courts, spokeswoman Jessica
Moser said from the company's headquarters in Bentonville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our store as a whole voted, the outcome would have been
different,'' Moser said. ``We know and they know they don't have
support in these stores. Thus, they are limiting the vote to a
small handful of associates.''
</P>
<P>
   The company cites ``sexual titillation'' as an inducement to
vote pro-union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to these objections,'' said the United Food &AMP;
Commercial Workers' Edwards, who said a meat cutter had asked him
to meet at his regular hangout, a topless bar. ``They're fishing.
The workers stood up for the union.''
</P>
<P>
   The union won the right to organize by so-called ``appropriate
units'' of, say, in-store meat cutters, pharmacists or optical
staff members while trying to win a vote at a Wal-Mart in
Jerseyville, Ill. But Wal-Mart got the vote delayed for two years
through legal challenges. By then, pro-union staff had left through
natural turnover, the union said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jacksonville store is the first with a unionized
unit in the United States, there has been one union Wal-Mart in
Canada since 1996. Stores in Germany and elsewhere overseas are
unionized, said Moser, emphasizing that unions mean different
things in different countries.
</P>
<P>
   The union victory in this traditionally anti-union East Texas
town of 12,765 about 27 miles south of Tyler has left residents
``scratching their heads,'' said Mike Traylor, 40, sales manager of
the Texas Basket Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an aberration, a fluke,'' said Mike McEwan, 54, who owns
Cherokee Real Estate Co. ``Jacksonville is an unsophisticated,
essentially blue-collar community where the consensus, I would dare
say, is that unions are pernicious and wreak havoc on the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with the right seed, the right individual, it
could have happened anywhere,'' said McEwan, a former personnel
specialist with the Beall's apparel chain. ``If what Miller said
was true, the seed was a disingenuous supervisor who did not
realize the consequence of his insincerity. The guy was wronged and
felt it needed righting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these small communities, false cohesiveness keeps the
peace. It could be an unhappy family down there,'' he said of
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   And he's apparently right.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stewart, who voted against the union, churned out 200
anti-union badges on his computer and passed them out apparently
with management's blessing. His pro-union colleagues in the meat
department no longer greet him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses didn't do anything when he split the seas compared to
the situation here,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
