<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LEAPYEAR29-COX     02-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAPYEAR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    February's last day or lost day?
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Today, Betty Bell turns 19. She doesn't
look a day over 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to teach high school, and I used to tell the kids I was
younger than them,'' the Boynton Beach resident says. ``But no one
believed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell was born Feb. 29, leap day. Her birthday comes only once
every four years. If that makes her a little ornery, it's payback
for all those lost birthday presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been given a raw deal,'' Bell says. ``There has never
been enough publicity about these poor people who are born on Feb.
29 and get short-changed every year.''
</P>
<P>
   One in every 1,461 people is a leap day baby. There are about
200,000 in America, 4 million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those folks, who call themselves ``leapers'' and
``29ers,'' have become leap day evangelists. Take the dusty town of
Anthony, on the Texas/New Mexico border. After encouragement from a
local leap baby, it was proclaimed ``Leap Year Capital of the
World'' in 1988. The town of 10,000 hosts a festival each leap day.
</P>
<P>
   This year's is the biggest yet, says Ruth Ashby, president of
the Anthony Chamber of Commerce. In commemoration of the first-ever
millennial leap year, and the first centennial leap year since
1600, the town is pulling out the stops. There'll be a leaping
contest over the Texas/New Mexico border, and Graham Nash _ of
Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash _ will perform.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the festivities, 29ers think there's something
rotten in the state of Texas. And New Mexico. And every other
commonwealth, state and sovereign nation around the world. Look at
the box marked ``Feb. 29'' on your calendar. You'll see what
they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's there. No logo, no insignia, no mention that this day
_ today _ is leap day.
</P>
<P>
   That ticks Ashby off.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them have it,'' the sister of a leaper says. ``It's
not even acknowledged on the calendars, much less celebrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this be true? You betcha. Phone calls to calendar
companies confirmed Ashby's complaint. Four admitted they had never
seen a calendar that gave leap day its due.
</P>
<P>
   One representative fell on his sword: ``I honestly have had no
idea'' why the recognition isn't there, said Linda Starr,
acquisitions director at Cedco Publishing in San Rafael, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Another went down swinging: ``This is a design decision,'' said
Susan Shearer, owner of Minneapolis-based Shearer Calendars. ``I
think if you start listing every possible thing in the boxes, there
won't be any room in the grid for people to write down plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to 29ers and they'll point out there's nothing else to
put on Feb. 29. In fact, prominent members of the leaper community
suspect it's something more than a ``design decision,'' something a
bit more insidious _ something, perhaps, like a calendar company
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we think,'' Ashby says. ``We're on a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Raenell Dawn. The Salem, Ore., resident is the co-founder
of the Honor Society of Leap Day Babies. For the past 16 years, the
29er has been trying to persuade calendar companies to change.
She's lost count of the letters, calls and e-mails she's sent out.
</P>
<P>
   But she remembers how many replies she's gotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``None,'' she says. ``I've never heard back from any of them.
And I contact them in plenty of time: One or two years in
advance.... People don't take this seriously. People think this is
some kind of a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Calendar representatives denied any complaints, and one even
chuckled at the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor dears,'' said Joni Miller, a calendar editor for the
Workman Publishing Group in New York City. ``It must be very
distressing for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for leap day, we'd be celebrating Christmas in
the summer and planting crops in the winter,'' Ashby says. ``Not
having that day marked on the calendar robs our young people of a
significant part of their education.''
</P>
<P>
   But one publisher is prepared to help.
</P>
<P>
   Sundance Press Inc., a company based in El Paso, Texas, printed
this year's El Paso Sunrise Rotary Club calendar. In the box of
Feb. 29, there is a cartoon of a man blowing a horn. The
inscription beside it: ``Leap Day!''
</P>
<P>
   That was president Michael Moses' call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've worked with the people in Anthony,'' he said.
``I did it on the basis that I would be able to meet Graham Nash.''
</P>
<P>
   A hollow victory, but leapers haven't lost hope. If enough 29ers
start to rally, they think, the industry will listen. They could be
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about what our customers think,''
insisted Susan Krick, general manager for calendars.com. ``We want
to make people happy. If that's what the public wants, and that's
what the outcry is, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller is skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect the leap day lobby needs to find itself a celebrity
born on that day,'' she said. ``That way, they might be able to
finesse the calendar companies.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, how about Italian superhunk Antonio Sabato Jr.? The
1972-born 29er would be the perfect poster boy: heartthrob, action
star (he was in ``The Big Hit''), father.
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait by the phone, says his publicist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's something Antonio would like to be
deemed the spokesperson for,'' Craig Schneider, of Kane and
Associates, says. ``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to stop Dawn; she'll keep writing those
companies. The show will go on in Anthony, Ashby says. And Betty
Bell will be partying with 100 friends at a country club in Boca
Raton tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I used to get upset, because I really felt
shortchanged,'' she says, smiling. ``I only had three birthdays
before I was 16. But after that, it's a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, who wants people to know how old you are after 20?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
