<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-SUPPORTINGACTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11-YEAR-OLD DESERVES HIS OSCAR NOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Academy Awards nominations were announced last week,
gossip columnist (and Fort Worth native) Liz Smith kvetched about
Haley Joel Osment's nomination for Best Supporting Actor for ``The
Sixth Sense.'' It's not fair, Smith contended, that veterans such
as Tom Cruise should have to compete with an 11-year-old who was
virtually unknown till last year, despite having worked on TV and
in movies since 1994. Cruise and fellow nominee Michael Caine have
worked hard over the years; why should they have to worry about
losing to a kid?
</P>
<P>
   This would be fine logic if the Best Supporting Actor award were
a lifetime achievement award. It isn't _ at least, it's not
supposed to be. But the academy has a way of bestowing Oscars on
people who've been passed over in the past, a tendency that favors
Cruise, who was nominated for his performance as an incredibly
piggish men's-group leader in ``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruise is that oddest of underdogs _ the superstar who spends
much of his career trying to earn respect on his merits, not for
his magazine covers _ and he has been nominated twice before, for
Best Actor in ``Born on the Fourth of July'' and ``Jerry Maguire.''
The academy might be more willing to give him a supporting actor
win, and it doesn't hurt that his ``Magnolia'' performance is
arguably his most acclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, though, the character he plays could hurt him. Cruise
is maybe a little too convincing as Frank T.J. Mackey, the type of
guy who sees women as receptacles and is foul-mouthed enough to
singe the most jaded ears; it's an abrasive role that has led to
some of ``Magnolia's'' walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with Osment, who endeared himself to audiences
with his turn as the haunted little boy in ``The Sixth Sense.''
Osment's appeal was apparent even in the movie's trailers, which
focused on his increasing fright; the movie went further, revealing
the young actor's instinct for compassion. Most important, though,
is that ``Sixth Sense'' hinged on Osment's performance;
``Magnolia,'' an ensemble piece, could have lived without Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   You could also say that the success of ``The Green Mile'' hinged
on a performance, that of nominee Michael Clarke Duncan as a Death
Row inmate with miraculous healing powers. This is the first time
in five years that African-Americans have been nominated in two
major categories (the other being Denzel Washington's nod for Best
Actor for ``The Hurricane''), and although Duncan is excellent,
cynics may say his nomination is a response to recent criticism of
the academy for neglecting black actors. Backlash is just as likely
to hurt Duncan, though, as several critics have panned ``The Green
Mile'' for its story about a slow-witted black man who becomes a
savior for some unusually progressive white guards.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's odds look better than Michael Caine's, though. Caine is
solid as a kindly New England abortionist in ``The Cider House
Rules,'' the first time the British actor has played an American.
But he already has a win under his belt, for 1986's ``Hannah and
Her Sisters,'' and he seems unlikely to gain a second Oscar in a
year when the competition is so strong.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more of an upset, however, if Jude Law won for his
role as a privileged young man in ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'' Some
critics even said that Law and his co-star Matt Damon were miscast,
and that Law should have played the lead role, a not-so-privileged
young man who desires the good life so much that he's willing to
kill to get it.
</P>
<P>
   This is nonsense. Damon, his blinding smile aside, still has a
touch of the working-class attitude that he displayed in ``Good
Will Hunting;'' he looks like the type of guy who would envy a
glamour boy like Law. If anything, the nominations should have been
switched _ this is Damon's best performance, and he seemed like a
good bet for a Best Actor nod. But he was passed over, and Law was
acknowledged in this category instead. He seemed like not just a
surprise, but an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Tom Cruise rides academy good will to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Personal pick: Osment may be young, but his performance is the
best in this category this year.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit www.star-telegram.com/justgo for
complete Oscar coverage and entertaining multimedia, including the
full list of nominees, news, trailers, quizzes, polls, wallpaper,
reviews, gossip, slide shows and a bulletin board. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
