<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MOVES TO THE MIDDLE TO ATTRACT MODERATES IN WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASCO, Wash. _ Continuing a prolonged zag to the political
middle, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas campaigned furiously in
Washington state on Monday and reached out to moderate voters by
focusing on issues such as education and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to large and enthusiastic audiences in one gymnasium
after another here in Washington, which votes on Tuesday, Bush
sounded conciliatory and inclusive themes that are likely to play
well in forthcoming contests.
</P>
<P>
   After the South Carolina victory, aides complained that his
rival, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, was defining Bush as an
intolerant, far-right candidate, and the governor now seems
determined to position himself more firmly in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches Monday, Bush focused his scorn on Vice President
Al Gore and the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But in answer to questions about McCain's criticism of his ties
to the Christian right, and in a media briefing, Bush mocked McCain
as a negative campaigner and said the senator's style was very
different from that of President Ronald Reagan, whose heir both
candidates claim to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He claims he's a Reagan Republican,'' Bush said here in Pasco,
a town in the rural eastern side of Washington. ``Ronald Reagan
didn't run those kinds of campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   At another appearance, Bush said: ``Ronald Reagan didn't point
fingers. He never played to people's religious fears, as Senator
McCain has shamelessly done.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to phone calls placed to Catholics, taking Bush to
task for not criticizing the anti-Catholic views of some of his
supporters, Bush declared, ``Senator McCain should be ashamed of
making those phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also charged that those calls were being made
to voters in Washington state and Virginia. ``It appears to be a
stealth campaign,'' said Karen Hughes, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Bush emphasized his ideas for raising standards
in public schools and his own experience in Texas on revising the
school system. Bush spoke sympathetically about charter schools and
home schooling, and he argued that any school that gets federal
money should have three years to attain acceptable standards for
its pupils.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he said, the money should be taken from the school
and given to the parents so that they could send their children
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also called for legislation that would protect teachers and
principals from what he called frivolous lawsuits arising from
attempts to maintain classroom discipline. He said that schools
should teach more about character as well.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Bush sounded inclusive themes, mentioning concern for
minorities or single mothers, in front of audiences that appeared
virtually entirely white and well-heeled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Republican Party better have people who not only hear the
entrepreneurs, we better have someone who hears the voices on the
outskirts of poverty as well,'' Bush told one packed audience at a
school.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush spoke about the importance of faith in providing hope
to people's lives, he went out of his way to refer inclusively to
``churches, synagogues and mosques.'' He talked about summoning
``the armies of compassion'' from faith-based groups to help people
having trouble with drugs or the law.
</P>
<P>
   He also showed off his Spanish, which is quite fluent, by firing
off a sentence in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to foreign policy questions, Bush said he would
redefine America's relationship with China by ending what the
Clinton administration has called its ``strategic partnership''
with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to say, we're not strategic partners but
competitors,'' Bush said. But he added that even competitors can
work together, and he emphasized that he intended to keep an open
trade relationship with China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked about American commitments abroad, Bush said that American
troops were overdeployed and raised the issue of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must work toward a political settlement,'' Bush said. But
it was not clear whether he meant that Washington should try and
reach a political settlement with Slobodan Milosevic, the hard-line
nationalist leader of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's foreign policy adviser, Condoleeza Rice, and his policy
aide, Josh Bolten, did not return calls to clarify Bush's position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
