<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      02-28 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 &HT;     If you want to enjoy the parade, you'll need a shovel 
 &HT;     By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for our next big wave of presidential primaries
comes exciting news from Bangkok that researchers have found a way
to turn elephant dung into natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The Thailand Ministry of Science's Bureau of Energy Development
and Production declared last week that fermented pachyderm
excrement makes a dandy, low-cost and environmentally sensitive
energy source, according to USA Today. The average elephant
produces 88 to 110 pounds of dung a day, which is roughly enough to
power the kitchen stove for a family of two or three.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you and yours, but my family of three was
cooking with gas just watching and reading about the GOP candidates
last week. They did their mascot proud.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runners George W. Bush and John McCain are growing
increasingly nasty in their fight for the nomination, so much so
that GOP leaders are warning the two men that their in-your-face
remarks could prove costly in the fall battle against the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The same warning holds true for Democrats Al Gore and Bill
Bradley, who've generated a supply of alternative fuel at least
sufficient enough to prepare an after-dinner snack of popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   The crankiest member of the donkey squad of late has probably
been Bradley, whose campaign passed out fliers last week featuring
the candidate declaring, ``I won't spend my time attacking my
opponent on votes from long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a debate hours later, he proceeded to blast Gore for a
series of votes from long ago, including one in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, one of the most odoriferous moments last
week was Bush defending his decision to speak earlier this month at
Bob Jones University, a South Carolina school with a
less-than-glorious past or present.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the university lost its tax-exempt status for
refusing to admit blacks. Today, it accepts black students but
forbids them to date or marry whites. It bans gays and even
declares its property off-limits to alumni who later reveal they're
gay. The university's founding family once portrayed the pope as
the ``anti-Christ'' and the Catholic Church as a cult.
</P>
<P>
   For many politicians, those facts would make the school about as
inviting as a back slap from David Duke or a bear hug from Louis
Farrakhan, but Bush and others, including Alan Keyes (on
Valentine's Day, no less), paid a visit anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since, Bush has been deluged with criticism from
McCain, among others, about the visit. Bush told The Washington
Post he made the right decision to attend because ``it also gives
me a chance to remind people what's wrong with that kind of
thinking. It gives me a chance to stand up and say, `I don't
support that kind of thinking.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bush never really stood up and informed the Bob Jones
crowd he doesn't support that kind of thinking. He was too busy
slapping backs, giving bear hugs and asking for the votes. But
nearly a month after his South Carolina victory _ hoo boy _ he's
letting them have it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Jones visit stirred up a lot of trouble all the way out
in Michigan, where McCain triumphed last week, probably thanks in
part to phone calls reminding Catholic voters of the company Bush
kept in South Carolina. Initially, McCain denied his campaign aides
had anything to do with the calls, then admitted they did.
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist Pat Robertson and his minions, meanwhile, were
also busy on the phone in Michigan attacking Warren Rudman,
McCain's national chairman, as a ``vicious bigot.'' Robertson is
apparently appalled that Rudman once had the effrontery to
criticize the political views of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Barry Lynn, executive director of Americans United for
Separation of Church and State, last week criticized the whole
Republican gang _ as well as Democrats _ for using religion as a
divisive weapon in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is ironic, he said. ``Right now in Iran, voters are
trying to separate religion and politics. Unfortunately, here in
the United States, we appear to be going in the opposite
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but we're exploring new energy sources. It may smell funny
now, but it'll blow over. Probably.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
