<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-GOVERNORS-HNS &LR;      02-28 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GOVERNORS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     GOP GOVERNORS VOICE SUPPORT FOR McCAIN IF HE IS NOMINEE  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four Republican governors allied with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush said Monday they would work to elect Sen. John
McCain if he wins the hard-fought Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four governors urged Bush or McCain to choose the
runner-up as his vice presidential running mate to help unify the
GOP at the end of the fractious nomination struggle, just as Ronald
Reagan offered the No. 2 job to his rival George Bush in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge Ridge, citing what he called the
``tremendous mutual respect'' between Bush and McCain, said a
ticket with both Bush and McCain would be ``a blockbuster ticket''
to regain the White House for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, recalling the salutary effect that a
Reagan-Bush ticket had on the divided Republican party in Colorado
in 1980, said it would be ``a rational and very unifying gesture
for either of these candidates to go to that second-rung candidate
and make that offer to unify the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge and Owens, joined by Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci and
Michigan Gov. John Engler, said that they would work tirelessly to
elect McCain president, in the event that the Arizona Republican
prevailed over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain upset Bush in the Michigan and New Hampshire primaries,
sidetracking Bush's march for the GOP nomination. Bush is the clear
choice of the Republican establishment, having won endorsements
from 38 senators and 175 House members, in addition to 26 GOP
governors.
</P>
<P>
   Engler, a strong Bush supporter who suffered a stinging defeat
when McCain won the Michigan primary last week, said he would work
for McCain if the senator gets the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Republican will say there are two words _ `Al Gore' _
and those two words make Alan Keyes, John McCain or George Bush
acceptable,'' said Engler, a three-term Michigan governor.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said all GOP governors would support McCain ``as
aggressively as we could'' if McCain defeats Bush. Owens said he
would work to deliver Colorado for McCain because the Arizonan
would be ``an excellent president when compared to a Vice President
Gore or Sen. Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, ceding that McCain is far ahead of Bush in
Massachusetts, said that he has no concerns about McCain's
temperament or ability to forge bipartisan unity to get things
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fear him,'' Cellucci said in responses to a question.
``What I fear is what Al Gore will do to him if he is the nominee.
Al Gore will go after the 18-year record in Congress _ everything.
He'll attack him with a vengeance that's what I worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The governors, in remarks to reporters, said they remain
confident that Bush will prevail over McCain as the presidential
primary calendar shifts to closed contests where only Republicans
can vote.
</P>
<P>
   But two GOP governors expressed concern about Bush's delayed
apology for an appearance at Bob Jones University in South Carolina
where the Texan failed to repudiate the school's anti-Catholic
teachings and prohibitions on inter-racial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Bush released a letter on Sunday to New York Cardinal John
O'Connor, the nation's most prominent Roman Catholic leader,
expressing regret that his Feb. 2 appearance at the predominantly
Baptist school was a ``missed opportunity, causing needless
offense, which I deeply regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, dubbing the issue ``more radioactive than plutonium,''
said he ``personally'' wished that Bush's repudiation had been
``louder and earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ridge added that he did not expect Bush's appearance or
McCain's efforts to highlight the school's anti-Catholic teachings
would have much effect in Pennsylvania's primary, where Roman
Catholics are a large constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said that Roman Catholics in Massachusetts are heavily
in favor of McCain already, due to the spillover effects of
McCain's victory in the Feb. 1 presidential primary in neighboring
New Hampshire. But Cellucci elliptically criticized Bush's efforts
to court southern Baptists in South Carolina who helped deliver
victory in the state's Feb. 19 contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you bring your message everywhere,'' Cellucci said.
``You don't choose to bring it only to a certain part of the state;
you bring it everywhere. `'
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
