<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-MONSTERTRUCKS29-CO     02-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MONSTERTRUCKS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPN takes monster trucks to TV
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FELLSMERE, Fla. _ Talk about a spectacular made-for-TV moment.
</P>
<P>
   A 10,000-pound mechanical beast roars around a muddy race
course, whipping 5,000 fans into a deafening frenzy. Scorpion, the
monster truck demon, is seconds away from beating Bigfoot, an
equally impressive souped-up truck, to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The sign-toting crowd (``Bigfoot is Mac Daddy!'' ``Vavoom,
baby!'') is on its feet. The pungent smell of burned rubber fills
the chilly night air.
</P>
<P>
   VROOOOOOOM!
</P>
<P>
   One last ramp remains. Scorpion hits it going 50 mph, but the
loose sand throws the truck off balance. Suddenly, the powerful rig
flips over twice, going down hard like a fallen T-Rex. Out rush the
police. An ambulance. The crowd is now hushed.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the driver, Gene Patterson, walks out unhurt. He
smiles weakly, then waves to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And UPN has it all on tape.
</P>
<P>
   The upstart network known for pro wrestling is now turning its
sights on _ what else _ monster trucks. Its sweeps special,
``Monster Trux 2000: The New Thrillennium,'' which airs today at 9
p.m., was filmed here in this small town near Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   UPN hopes ``Monster Trux 2000'' gets monster ratings. Hosted by
fitness expert and Playboy model Jennifer Goodwin, the one-hour
special combines the bite-your-fingernails thrill of monster truck
racing with the outlandish soap opera-like plots seen on UPN's
wildly popular ``WWF Smackdown!'' You'll definitely see more than
two huge trucks barreling down an S-shaped race course. There's
enough make-believe scandal, intrigue, rivalries, villains and
curvy babes behind-the-scenes to populate five ``General
Hospitals.'' Eight actors were hired to play everything from
fiendish truck owners to man-stealing home wreckers. And since this
is UPN, TV's most macho network, expect sizzling sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean girls in short skirts and tight bras?'' says Barry
Frank, the show's executive producer, with tongue firmly planted in
cheek. ``Nah, we wouldn't do anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds talent coordinator Mike Mathis: ``We were looking for
character types who could take it over-the-top and women who were
stereotypically beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The network says if ``Monster Trux 2000'' attracts enough
viewers, it might become _ gulp! _ a weekly series.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. Monster truck racing has a loyal _ and rabid _
following. Nine to 10 million live spectators see monster trucks
shows each year. The sport's major promoters produce more than 200
events annually. Minor promoters, fairs and racetracks stage 400 to
500 events each year. And at a time when tasteless and often
downright boorish specials are watched by millions, UPN's ``Monster
Trux 2000'' is jumping into the anything goes TV game at the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, many TV insiders snickered when UPN put ``Smackdown''
on its fall schedule. But thanks to that testosterone-heavy series,
the network recently lured 600,000 more viewers than the WB. That
UPN is airing ``Monster Trux 2000'' during February sweeps
indicates how much confidence it has in the special.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure,'' admits Frank. ``We put this
together in six weeks from a standing start. We have a lot riding
on it. Everybody's pretty tense and pretty excited because we all
know what's at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   That's quite obvious on this cool evening. It's two hours before
show time and the scene at Mesa Park, a dusty, 100-acre outdoor
facility, can only be described as hectic. Drivers are milling
around, checking their rigs one last time. Several TV production
staffers are scurrying about. A giant fire-breathing dinosaur
repeatedly crushes the same car in the middle of the race track.
There are the inevitable last-minute script changes, and the actors
sit nervously while munching on fish and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite like doing `Gone With The Wind','' cracks
Frank, while surveying the chaotic scene, ``but it sure feels like
it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the madness is a throng of wide-eyed onlookers who
have arrived to meet and greet Rena Mero,
</P>
<P>
   a k a Sable, the former WWF wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does Mero know about monster trucks?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're big, they're loud and they can run things over,'' the
shapely Florida native says after signing autographs. ``I used to
have a four wheel drive truck, but I like small sports cars.''
</P>
<P>
   While the former Playboy cover girl is here to lure people to
UPN's special, she seems more interested in talking about her
upcoming projects. In a brief two-minute interview, the public
relations savvy Mero amazingly plugged her Web site (renamero.com),
book (she's writing it now), and upcoming syndicated TV series
co-starring NBA bad boy Dennis Rodman (``The Consultants,'' in
which she plays a Las Vegas undercover police officer).
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a difficult period,'' says Mero, who filed a
$100 million lawsuit against the WWF (it was later settled out of
court). ``But I've put the past behind me. Working with the WWF was
a wonderful experience and it opened up a lot of doors for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mero may not know a monster truck from a Tonka toy, but
``Monster Trux 2000'' host Goodwin certainly does. She bought a
white Dodge Ram over a year ago and has always been intrigued with
oversized trucks. The producers often tell Goodwin, who's been
featured on ``Days of Our Lives,'' ``Baywatch'' and in numerous
fitness magazines, to tone down her excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``She certainly knows all the lingo and the drivers,'' says
Frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``What fascinates me about trucks is the power, and, ooooooh,
the noise,'' Goodwin coos.
</P>
<P>
   But is Goodwin talking about a monster truck, or a lantern-jawed
hunk?
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my truck when I left my fiance, so let's just say the
truck is there for me like no man has been,'' she says, laughing.
``If it breaks down, I just get it fixed. It doesn't talk back.
Sometimes a truck is better than a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, is better than Scorpion's accident. Word
spreads, however, that the accident may have been staged. Producers
say no. So does Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going for it,'' swears the 37-year-old driver.
``It's the nature of the beast. It wasn't part of the show. If it
was, I should get a big raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Goodwin: ``That's why this stuff is so great, you never
know what's going to happen. We're making this up as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   But will viewers care?
</P>
<P>
   ``We know people love racing and we know people love conflict,''
says Camilla Noble, who plays Dusty, a naive race car driver
girlfriend. ``Now they get both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
