</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-PROTESTERS-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN PROTESTERS USE THE INTERNET TO SEEK REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ With his one-day beard and tousled hair,
Park Byung-ok retains a hint of the look of the student protesters
who lobbed rocks and Molotov cocktails at the police, who responded
with tear gas and rubber bullets, in the often turbulent 1980s
here.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Park, 39, and his associates are launching
nothing more lethal than e-mail messages _ many thousands _ to
officials and political parties from civic groups that are
sprouting around the country. The effects are rocking this country
in ways never imagined by the radical opposition that many of the
protesters belonged to a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent Asian economic crisis, ``Koreans endured
tremendous hardships, while politicians fattened themselves and
spent their time bickering,'' said Park, director of the Citizens'
Coalition for Economic Justice, one of the groups that are
reshaping politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Koreans have realized that politicians will not bring about
reforms of their own accord,'' he said. ``Civic groups like ours
are creating an avenue for people to vent their frustrations and
demand change.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea led the region in its response to the crisis, as the
government of President Kim Dae-jung moved vigorously to break up
the hidebound conglomerates. In the last few months, as if by
reformist contagion, civic groups like Park's have been forcing
major changes on a long-static political class.
</P>
<P>
   This country has long known periods of sudden, intense civil
activism, usually in the form of radical student politics or
hard-line nationalism. What sets the current movement apart is that
it is mostly led by middle-class people with moderate politics,
linked together by the Internet in ways that would have been
impossible two or three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coming together online in January under the banner of Citizens'
Solidarity, more than 500 civic groups and nongovernmental
organizations have shaken the established parties. One result was a
revision of the electoral code this month.
</P>
<P>
   The groups are now demanding the elimination of reportedly
corrupt politicians from their slates in a nationwide legislative
election in April. To enforce their demands, the groups have sought
to shame the three main parties by publishing a list of politicians
who they say are unworthy of office.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, the critics are publishing reports on what they
say are the politicians' shady dealings, poor attendance records in
the legislature or votes for unpopular bills.
</P>
<P>
   The normally cautious newspapers and television stations have
rushed to try to match the civic groups' information, or at least
report it, so as not to appear irrelevant. In a country where
political demonstrations remain tightly restricted, the new groups
have invented what they call Internet rallies, in which new members
sign up, opinions are exchanged, letter-writing campaigns are
organized and policies are debated and published.
</P>
<P>
   At rallies, Park said, his group's Internet home page, which
averages 50,000 hits a day, has sometimes been so deluged that it
has been briefly knocked out of service.
</P>
<P>
   That has been made possible, of course, by the explosive growth
of computer ownership and Web use in South Korea, where more than a
quarter of the population regularly use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, our goal is political reform,'' said Jang Won, 44,
a professor of environmental studies whose group is a major player
in the civic coalition. ``We want to drive out corrupt politicians.
We want to force the parties to adopt transparent processes for
selecting candidates, and we want to break the pattern of politics
run by charismatic leaders who play on regional differences.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although political analysts describe such reforms as a very tall
order in a country like South Korea, where the dominant political
leaders, including the president, have been fixtures since the
1960s, and where regionalism runs deep, they are not writing off
the possibility of real change.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1987, the year of our democratization, we saw a huge amount
of civic activity,'' said Hoon Jaung, a professor of political
science at Chung Ang University here, referring to the first direct
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the 13 years since, things have been quiescent. But in
this period, the parties have failed to build institutions that are
responsive to the needs of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still fresh from their early victories, the civic groups are
already setting bigger goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the computer-filled office of his group, People's Solidarity
for Participatory Democracy, Kim Hyung-Wan, 40, a former
legislative assistant who fairly brims with reformist ambitions,
said, ``The disqualification of political candidate and driving out
corruption are just our immediate objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   His group generates $50,000 a month in contributions and has a
staff of 50. ``Our main objective,'' Kim added, ``is really to
democratize Korean society by getting people involved in social
causes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
