<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-BELLSOUTH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL aims to provide service via wireless phones, pagers
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online announced a series of deals Monday
aimed at making the service available across the country to users
of wireless phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the arrangements, including a pact with BellSouth, AOL
hopes to gives subscribers a way to read e-mail, exchange instant
messages, check stock prices, get driving directions or check movie
listings _ the kind of features available via the Internet from
desktop computers using AOL and other online services. No financial
arrangements were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its ``AOL Anywhere'' strategy, the Virginia-based
company made several sweeping moves to extend its service, which,
with 22 million subscribers, is already by far the largest Internet
membership. AOL has joined with paging services, a national phone
company and several of the companies that make the wireless devices
used by those services.
</P>
<P>
   With BellSouth, AOL has forged a deal to let subscribers get
instant messages and e-mail via the company's national wireless
data network.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth believes the deal will give a dramatic boost to its
wireless service, which has mostly appealed thus far to mobile
professionals. ``It puts us, for the very first time, in the
consumer marketplace,'' said Janet Boudris, senior vice president
for BellSouth Wireless Data. ``This also will raise awareness.
Frankly, our biggest challenge has been that people don't know
about the service.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has a similar deal with another national paging company,
Arch Communications. AOL declined to say when users would be able
to get the service via pager or what it would cost. AOL also
announced a deal with Sprint to deliver a version of AOL content
via at least some wireless phones by autumn. The company also
joined with manufacturers Nokia, Motorola and Research In Motion,
the company that makes the interactive pagers used by BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   For AOL, which recently announced plans to buy Time Warner,
Monday's announcements laid further claim to the future of
communications since technology has clearly been rushing in the
direction of wireless. In Europe, especially, wireless users have
been on the Net for months.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Patrick, newly named president of AOL wireless, cited
projections of 1.3 billion wireless users by 2005. Moreover, that
research predicts that within three years, one-third of Internet
users will be reaching the Net via a wireless device, he said. AOL
members send more than 110 million e-mails and 1 billion instant
messages every day. AOL also says that 70 percent of its member
households own a wireless phone, pager or both.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is by no means the only one to notice the trend.
EarthLink _ the nation's second-largest Internet provider _ also
announced a deal Monday to put its Internet service on phones from
Sprint. The arrangement extends the relationship of Atlanta-based
EarthLink to Sprint, its largest shareholder. ``With Sprint PCS, we
will be able to extend the EarthLink Internet experience to the
wireless world by providing a mobile version of the content and
services that we deliver daily to our members on their home or
office PCs,'' said Garry Betty, EarthLink chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
