u a BC-SCI-VOLCANOS-1STLD-WR     02-28 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VOLCANOS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIEF HISTORY OF BEAUTY, TERROR AND TRIAL BY FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes ``1873'' to ``1783'' in graf that begins ``On June 8
...'') 
(Eds: Words in boldface should be set in italics. Double
parentheses should be set as brackets.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT8, -9, -20 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The earth's habit of forever remaking itself in paroxysms of
fire and violence is sometimes hard on its inhabitants, a lesson
borne out again last week when villagers in Legaspi, Philippines,
fled eruptions of the deadly volcano Mayon. In a new book,
``Vulcan's Fury: Man Against the Volcano'' (Yale University Press),
Alwyn Scarth uses witnesses' accounts to tell of 15 great eruptions
and of the people who lived through them. Here is a sampling. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Vesuvius, A.D. 79
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vesuvius, looming 4,200 feet over the Bay of Naples, has
erupted at least 200 times in the last two millenniums, most
famously and lethally in A.D. 79 when it smothered Pompeii and
other villages in ash. Among the casualties was the Roman scholar
Pliny the Elder, whose nephew, Pliny the Younger, provided an
eyewitness account of the catastrophe: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On 24 August, about one in the afternoon, my mother pointed out
a cloud with an odd size and appearance that had just formed ....
From that distance, it was not even clear from which mountain the
cloud was rising _ although it was found afterward to be Vesuvius.
The cloud could best be described as more of an umbrella pine than
any other tree, because it rose high up in a kind of trunk and then
divided into branches .... Sometimes it looked light-colored,
sometimes it looked mottled and dirty with the earth and ash it had
carried up. Like a true scholar, my uncle saw at once that it
deserved closer study ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The next day: &LR;  The carriages we had ordered began to lurch to
and fro, although the ground was flat, and we could not keep them
still, even when we wedged their wheels with stones. Then we saw
the sea sucked back, apparently by an earthquake, and many
creatures were left stranded on the sand ....
</P>
<P>
   From the other direction, over the land, a dreadful black cloud
was torn by gushing, twisting, flames and great tongues of fire
like much-magnified lightning .... The cloud sank down soon
afterward and covered the sea, hiding Capri and Cape Misenum from
sight. ... Ash was already falling by now, but not very thickly.
Then I turned round and saw the thick black cloud advancing over
the land behind us like a flood. ``Let us leave the road whilst we
can still see,'' I said, ``or we will be knocked down and trampled
by the crowd.'' But it was not the darkness of a moonless, or
cloudy night, but just as if all the lamps had been put out in a
completely closed room ....
</P>
<P>
   We could hear women shrieking, children crying, and men
shouting. Some were calling for their parents, for their children,
or for their wives, and trying to recognize them by their voices
.... Some people prayed for death because they were so frightened
of dying. Many begged for the help of the gods, but even more
imagined that there were no gods left and that the last eternal
night had fallen on the world.
</P>
<P>
   Laki, 1783
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On June 8, 1783, fissures split open on the flanks of a
mountain ridge known as Laki near the southern coast of Iceland.
Over the next eight months, more than three cubic miles of lava
poured from the fissures and a sulfurous blue haze spread over the
countryside. A farmer, Jon Steingrimmson, wrote this report. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The hairy sand-fall and sulfurous rain caused such
unwholesomeness in the air and in the earth that the grass became
yellow and pink and withered down to the roots. The animals that
wandered around the fields got yellow-colored feet with open
wounds, and yellow dots were seen on the skin of the newly shorn
sheep, which had died.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By the end of July, according to The Leeds Intelligencer in
England, the haze had spread over Europe: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The foreign papers mention that the haziness, which has lately
prevailed here, is general throughout all the southern part of
Europe. It is even observed upon the most lofty of Alps. In Italy,
it has occasioned great consternation, as the same appearance of
the air was remarked in Calabria and Sicily a little previous to
those dreadful earthquakes that had destroyed so many cities. The
people of France, too, began to forebode some dire calamity. The
Paris Gazette mentions that the churches are most unusually
crowded, and the shrines of their saints uncommonly frequented.
</P>
<P>
   Krakatau, 1883
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Aug. 26, 1883, the explosion of Krakatau, in the Soenda
Straits between Sumatra and Java, was heard as far away as
Australia. It disgorged some five cubic miles of ash and dust. Most
of the Krakatau's 36,000 victims died by drowning in tsunamis. This
rice farmer, five miles inland on Java, barely survived. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden there came a great noise. We ... saw a great
black thing, a long way off, coming toward us. It was very high and
very strong, and we soon saw that it was water. Trees and houses
were washed away .... Not far off was some steep sloping ground. We
all ran toward it and tried to climb up out of the way of the
water. ((The wave)) was too quick for most of them, and many were
drowned almost at my side .... There was a general rush to climb up
in one particular place. This caused a great block, and many of
them got wedged together and could not move. Then they struggled
and fought, screaming and crying out all the time. Those below
tried to make those above them move on again by biting their heels.
... Some ... dragged others down with them. They would not let go
their hold, nor could those above them release themselves from this
death grip.
</P>
<P>
   Montagne Pelee, 1902
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Montagne Pelee, or ``Fire Mountain,'' on the Caribbean island
of Martinique, &LR;   &UR; had been thought to be harmless until a series of
earthquakes and explosions in the spring of 1902 transformed its
4,000-foot summit into a hellish landscape of fissures, cinder
cones and a lake of boiling water. On May 5, an earthquake breached
the lip of the new lake, releasing a wall of mud down the Blanche
River valley. Near the mouth of the river, Auguste Guerin was about
to board his yacht with his family when he turned back toward his
house for a moment: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Then I heard a noise I can't compare with anything else _ an
immense noise _ like the devil on earth! A black avalanche, beneath
white smoke, an enormous mass, full of huge blocks, more than 10
meters high and at least 150 meters wide, was coming down the
mountain with a great din. It ... rolled up against the factory
like an army of giant rams. I was rooted on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   My unfortunate son and wife ran away from it toward the shore
.... All at once, the mud arrived. It passed 10 meters in front of
me. I felt its deathly breath. There was a great crashing sound.
Everything was crushed, drowned and submerged. My son, his wife,
and 30 ... people and huge buildings were all swept away .... Three
of those black waves came down ... making a noise like thunder, and
made the sea retreat. Under the impact of the third wave, a boat
moored in the factory harbor was thrown ... over a factory wall,
killing one of my foremen, who was standing next to me. I went down
to the shore. The desolation was indescribable. Where a prosperous
factory _ the work of a lifetime _ had stood a moment before, there
was now nothing left but an expanse of mud forming a black shroud
for my son, his wife and my workmen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
