<SLUG> BC-MONOPOLY-HOT-TIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUY YOUR OWN CHUNK OF MONOPOLY PROPERTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As any Monopoly fan knows, when it comes to buying property,
it's location, location, location.
</P>
<P>
   A newsstand on St. Charles Place, for instance, is going to be
cheaper than a hotel on Park Place, so when the folks at Monopoly
created a collection of miniature businesses based on the
65-year-old board game, they used that old real estate rule.
</P>
<P>
   The limited-edition collection by Department 56 is called
Monopoly Citylights and features small resin buildings reminiscent
of 1930s architecture. The front entrances resemble deed cards and
feature tiny pewter game tokens by the doorway. And when the eight
buildings are lined up, letter discs on the facades light up and
spell out the game title, Monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   According to spokeswoman Rebecca Herbst, a Bank and Trust
building, featuring marbleized pillars built in the pastel colors
of Monopoly money, is offered as a gift when you buy the entire
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to real estate values, the newsstand is $37.50 and
the hotel is $60, and all are available at specialty shops,
including Sparky's in Universal City, Calif., and Allied Model
Trains in Culver City, Calif. For more information, call (800)
624-9027. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
