<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Feb. 29 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-RIGHT (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ Taking his presidential
campaign to a stronghold of Christian conservatism, Arizona Sen.
John McCain delivered a harsh attack Monday on the ``self-appointed
leaders'' of the religious right, depicting them as intolerant
empire builders who ``have turned good causes into businesses''
while attempting to exclude all but ``card-carrying Republicans''
from the party. McCain singled out for criticism two of the
Christian right's best-known leaders, Pat Robertson and the
Reverend Jerry Falwell. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DIVIDE-ASSESS (Washington) _ News Analysis: Gov. George
W. Bush and Sen. John McCain are now running for two separate
Republican parties. As the bitter contest between them hurtles
toward a new set of primaries, it is deepening long-standing fault
lines in the Republican coalition and turning the race into a
fierce debate over what the Republican party of the future should
look like. By Alison Mitchell. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-U.S. (Washington) _ More terrorism plots are linked to
Osama bin Laden. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TECH-WORKERS (Bombay) _ A growing though still modest
number of India's biggest American success stories, high-tech
workers whose lives are now firmly rooted in the United States, are
beginning to come home to India, and not just to visit relatives,
but also to start companies, invest their capital and indulge their
philanthropic instincts. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SHELTERS (Washington) _ Calling the rapid growth of abusive
corporate tax shelters ``the most serious compliance issue
threatening the American tax system today,'' Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers in a speech Monday announced a three-prong
attack against corporate conduct that ``undermines the integrity of
the tax system.'` By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTOR (New York) _ The Bronx district attorney
vigorously defended on Monday his office's handling of the Amadou
Diallo case, attributing the acquittals of four police officers in
the shooting to the transfer of the case to the Albany courts.
Responding to assertions from jurors that his office presented a
weak case, Robert T. Johnson said that he would not do anything
different were he to try the case again. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-INFANT-MORTALITY (New York) _ In central Brooklyn _ where
storefronts are boarded, housing projects stand in defiant
opposition to the boom times, and the hospitals are more or less
broke _ too many babies are dying. They die at rates that the city
as a whole has not seen in nearly two decades. And they die, in
some cases, at a rate double what the federal government has set as
the infant mortality goal for the nation. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
(1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
