<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER REPORTS 16 PERCENT RISE IN PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ DaimlerChrysler AG said Monday that its profit for
1999 increased 16 percent, in line with analysts' expectations, as
it benefited from cost cuts, stronger vehicle sales and a rich mix
of high-profit models.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, which posted its results in euros and dollars,
said its adjusted net income for 1999, its first full year of
operation, increased 16 percent, to 6.2 billion euros, or $6.3
billion, compared with $5.4 billion in 1998. That translated to
6.21 euros, or $6.25, a share, compared with $5.62 a share in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted operating profit increased 20 percent, to 10.32 billion
euros, or $10.4 billion. Revenue rose 14 percent, to $151 billion.
Results reflect one-time effects of the sale of its stake in
Debitel communication services and the reorganization of its
Adtranz rail unit.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, DaimlerChrysler's adjusted net profit
increased 32 percent, to $1.6 billion, or $1.60 a share. Its
adjusted operating profit rose 37 percent, to $2.7 billion. Revenue
rose 20 percent, to $41.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were pretty much in line with what we were looking
for,'' said David M. Garrity, an auto analyst at Dresdner Kleinwort
Benson in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were cheered by the results, lifting shares of
DaimlerChrysler by $2.1875, or 4.4 percent, to $65.6875 in New
York. In Frankfurt, Germany, shares rose 1.38 euros, or 2 percent,
to 67.28 euros.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday at DaimlerChrysler's headquarters in
Stuttgart, Germany, company officials attributed the profit gain to
savings, improved sales and a better mix of high-profit models.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher sales volume and mix of models were the biggest
factors,'' said Robert J. Eaton, the company's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide sales, led by the surprisingly strong markets of
Europe and the United States, increased to almost 4.9 million cars
and trucks, up from 4.5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Mercedes-Benz vehicles and the Smart city car, which
finally hit its sales target of 80,000 units a year, increased to a
record of more than 1 million vehicles worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Mercedes-Benz became the best-selling
luxury brand for the first time in history. Chrysler Group sales,
which include the Chrysler, Dodge and Jeep brands, rose to 3.2
million vehicles in 1999, up from 3.1 million in 1998, accounting
for nearly half of DaimlerChrysler's annual revenue. Vehicle sales
were buoyed by the introduction of nine products in 1999 and strong
sales of high-profit models like Jeep sport utility vehicles and
Mercedes luxury vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's profits further benefited from about $1.4
billion in savings derived from combining purchasing, sales and
other functions of the former Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp.,
which merged in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outperformed modestly in terms of cost savings through
synergies,'' said Garrity, who predicts that DaimlerChrysler will
continue to enjoy ``a favorable blend'' of strong sales and savings
this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The issue this year are the competitive conditions in North
America, especially on light-truck sales, and the model changes the
Chrysler operations face this year,'' said Garrity, who predicts a
challenging first half but a strengthening second half for the
automaker in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The results were good news for U.S. employees of the Chrysler
side of DaimlerChrysler, who will receive profit-sharing checks
averaging $8,100 this year, a record.
</P>
<P>
   The bonuses cap a lucrative year for employees of U.S. auto
companies. Ford Motor Co. will send out checks averaging $8,000 to
109,000 employees on Friday. And about 154,000 hourly employees of
General Motors Corp. will get profit-sharing checks of about $1,775
in March _ also an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its strong 1999 performance, DaimlerChrysler will
maintain its current dividend of $2.37 a share. ``We believe it's
important to have a dividend that we can sustain,'' Eaton said at
the news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using its approximately $18 billion in cash reserves
to pay higher dividends, the automaker will ask its shareholders at
its April 19 annual meeting in Berlin to authorize the company to
buy back up to 10 percent of its shares. DaimlerChrysler's stock
has been underperforming in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Cash reserves also will be used for other investments, including
plants, equipment, and research and development, company officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it would join the bidding for Daewoo Motor
Co. Ltd. of South Korea. Other bidders include GM, Ford, Fiat of
Italy and Hyundai Motor of South Korea. Daewoo had sent letters to
the carmakers inviting bids for Daewoo and its sport utility arm,
Ssangyong Motor, early this month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, DaimlerChrysler has been in talks with other
automobile manufacturers, including PSA Peugeot Citroen of France
and Fiat, to develop a small-car strategy that won't lose money as
its Smart car has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've indicated that we believe with stricter European fuel
requirements in the future, we will need to expand our small car
offerings,'' Eaton said. ``We're looking at a number of ways to do
that, but we're in absolutely no rush. The stricter requirements
take effect in 2008, so we have plenty of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
