<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DECLARES HE IS THE `REFORM CANDIDATE PLUS' 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley finished his five-day stand
in Washington state on Monday, the day before its primary, with
appeals to students, women and independent voters, describing
himself as the real ``reform candidate'' who would wash corruption
out of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   At an outdoor rally at the University of Washington that
attracted more than 2,000 students despite a cold drizzle, Bradley
sounded the kind of upbeat, populist tone that has marked his
recent Washington events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich ought to have the right to buy as many houses as they
want,'' Bradley said as he called for revamping the campaign
finance system to reduce the influence of special interest groups.
``But they should not have the right to buy our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case in recent days, Bradley avoided mentioning
Vice President Al Gore, his lone rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination. But he implicitly criticized the vice
president for having voted for restrictions on federal financing
for abortion.
</P>
<P>
   And he described the Democratic race as a choice between new and
old, between a party that is ``the protector of the established
interests'' and one that will fight against ``selfishness,
indifference and complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference earlier in the day, Bradley repeatedly
sought to differentiate himself from Sen. John McCain, the
conservative Republican insurgent. McCain is drawing support from
the same kinds of disaffected Democrats and independents that
Bradley has sought, running on a similar kind of outsider message.
In Washington and some other states, voters from any party can vote
for any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the reform candidate plus,'' Bradley said at the news
conference. ``Meaning that you can have a reform candidate who is
also pro-choice, pro-gun control, invests in education and health
and is strong on the environment. All of which I think are relevant
to independent votes across their country that want reform but also
don't want the most conservative agenda in the world, which is what
you get with the Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   During a morning event outside a women's health clinic here,
Bradley touted his efforts as a senator in fighting for abortion
rights, the Equal Rights Amendment and legislation requiring
hospitals to allow new mothers to stay 48 hours after childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   He also asserted that his plan for extending private health
insurance to almost all Americans would benefit women more than
men, because, he said, women have lost health coverage at a faster
rate than men in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who work part time, work temporary jobs, often in order
to be with their children, rarely have any option when it comes to
their insurance,'' Bradley said. ``So many women these days are
forced to choose between their own health and the health of their
children. Women should never have to make such a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Bradley flew to San Francisco, where he was to
kick off at least two days of campaigning in California. He is
expected to return to New York after a debate on Wednesday night
with Gore in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley devoted much of his time and resources to Washington, at
the expense of campaigning in larger states, on the premise that a
good showing here would give him a much-needed lift on March 7,
when 16 states will hold caucuses and primaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
