<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DIALLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO TRIAL'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The verdict in the Amadou Diallo case only settles one score.
The Bronx case of four white police officers accused of murder for
killing Diallo, who is black, ended in acquittal on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There were protests but no riots _ an impressive public display
of nonviolent outrage over a shooting that occurred because police
thought Diallo had a gun. What police saw turned out to be his
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A civil law suit against the four officers is likely. But gaping
issues remain unaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   How do New Yorkers and the nation move forward from here? Both
minority and white citizens point angrily to excessive police
activities. How do police departments at least dampen the
likelihood of another such tragedy? Should policies and procedures
be changed? Should New York's Street Crime Unit _ the special team
the four acquitted officers belonged to _ be overhauled? How do
police departments convince African-American and other minority men
that they are not reflexively considered guilty until proven
innocent?
</P>
<P>
   These are questions with national implications. No matter how
good their local police force is, some people across the country
will conclude that the Diallo case is business as usual, that under
the banner of public safety minority lives are chewed up and spit
out by police. It's a corrosive impression that threatens the
genuine progress of police forces and communities that work
together successfully.
</P>
<P>
   New York touts its zero-tolerance policing. But a 1998 report
prepared for the Department of Justice suggests that these policies
can erode police legitimacy. Minor examples include ludicrous
crackdowns such as the case of a woman stopped in Brooklyn during a
``safety sweep'' and arrested for having failed to pay a ticket for
driving with a broken tail light. The worst result is an outrageous
death.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's death should be heeded as a commandment to improve
frayed police-community relationships everywhere. This could take
many forms: public meetings, advanced training for police officers,
innovative school programs, more research on effective policing.
The name Amadou Diallo should now be a rallying cry for change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
