<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAUGH WITH ME, NOT AT ME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Much of Sen. John McCain's public appeal is due to
his legendary candor and spontaneous wit, although humor has always
been risky and subject to misinterpretation in political combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate was grilled Sunday on ABC
News' ``This Week'' about some of his jokes that struck segments of
the population as offensive and distinctly non-funny. ``People say,
`Is that the way President McCain would speak in public about
things?''' the questioner observed disapprovingly.
</P>
<P>
   McCain chuckled. ``Yes. President McCain will use humor wherever
he can. Sometimes it will be poorly done and sometimes it will get
President McCain in trouble You can count on President McCain to
try to use humor to lighten up things ''
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. Politics is often a grim business. It needs all
the good-natured lubrication it can get. Smiles can help to bridge
the huge psychological and emotional gap between an isolated
president and the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Laughter is indispensable in a democracy. It allows us to get
along with one another socially while disagreeing intellectually
over public policy. And sometimes those who laugh together even
learn how to vote together.
</P>
<P>
   But jokes and quick quips shouldn't be examined too closely.
They are not meant to be taken literally but to make us smile. Like
frogs, they die if dissected.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's humor often has a cutting edge, although he is not as
sardonic as Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican nominee renowned for
having one of the quickest wits in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A typical McCain line was his reaction to a friendly food fight
in a restaurant between reporters and some of his staff. Instead of
tut-tutting, he joked, ``That's what happens when you recruit from
the prison-release program.''
</P>
<P>
   Our most popular recent presidents were those with an infectious
sense of humor. Who could forget President Ronald Reagan, rushed to
a hospital with a grave wound from a would-be assassin's bullet,
telling his doctors from his sickbed, ``I forgot to duck''?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton does well with the public funny bone too. His good
humor has carried him through impeachment and personal humiliation.
He is a master of the self-deprecating putdown. He once observed
that when he and Hillary Rodham Clinton arrived at the White House
in 1993, a veteran reporter demanded a security deposit.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy was the first modern president to embrace humor
as an essential governing tool. His chief speech writer, Theodore
Sorensen, recalled in his post-assassination book, ``Kennedy,''
that ``no laugh-getter once used or even considered was ever
discarded.'' But Kennedy was wary. In 1952 and 1956 Adlai
Stevenson's sophisticated, elitist humor had not prevented two
losses to Dwight Eisenhower, who had a nice smile but no comic
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candor and humor, when combined, can be dangerous weapons
politically; so at times he (JFK) had to restrain his natural
instincts in this direction,'' Sorensen wrote, in classic
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Even Kennedy's younger brother Robert, not known for a natural
sense of humor, understood its uses. ``I'm not ruthless,'' he told
a crowd during his 1968 presidential campaign. ``If I find a man
who says that, I'll destroy him.''
</P>
<P>
   But we have managed to live with presidents who have no sense of
humor. We solve the problem by laughing at them, rather than with
them. Richard Nixon, that sour paranoid, comes first to mind. ``How
do you like your job?,'' he once asked a motorcycle cop lying in a
street who had just taken a tumble and broken his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter's killer rabbit was roundly ridiculed, in large
part because he didn't see the comical aspects of his claim that a
bunny was pursuing the presidential boat in a pond at Plains, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush was more often funny when he wasn't trying
than when he was. His tongue-tanglers were historic. His son, Gov.
George W. Bush, displays the same predilection for garbled syntax.
He seems like a genial enough fellow but he does not have McCain's
quick, whimsical temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has a ready wit that he usually
suppresses but has flashed frequently during his debates with the
dull, droll former Sen. Bill Bradley. If we want laughter in the
White House, our best bet is a contest between McCain and Gore.
Rolling in the aisles is no substitute for peace and prosperity,
but it is better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, we are far beyond the days when a man determined to
keep his mouth shut like Calvin Coolidge could be president. ``You
don't have to explain something you haven't said,'' was his mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Let McCain be McCain and the explanations fill the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
