<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-RUSSIANS-CENSUS &LR;      02-28 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-RUSSIANS-CENSUS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOVIET LEGACY LEAVES CHALLENGE FOR AMERICAN CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Owen S. Good is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By OWEN S. GOOD   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over coffee in her Ocean Avenue apartment in
Brooklyn, Fira Stukelman recalled the Communist Party man coming to
her village in Ukraine, with census forms and orders to answer all
the questions. Each time she denied that she and her children were
Jewish, and hoped the state would leave them alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were afraid to say you were Jewish,'' said Stukelman, 66,
who immigrated to the United States in 1989. ``Everyone who was
Jewish said their language is Russian. It would be terrible for
your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, education and homes _ anything controlled by the
government _ was in play if someone's answers didn't fit the
seemingly arbitrary purposes of the Soviet head count. The Soviet
Union is no more, but it has left a unique challenge for the U.S.
Census Bureau in its attempt to count the nation's Russian-speaking
community for the first time. Census workers must overcome
immigrants' mistrust of the former Soviet Union, especially for
Jews, who constitute a large majority of Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about people leaving the Russian government,
the most mistrustful government in the world,'' said Alex Krasny,
41, a Brighton beach businessman and member of Community Board 13.
``They come from being under pressure for many years, where you
couldn't say, `No, no,' and not answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the government man spreading the word about census
participation isn't dreaded. That's because Gene Borsh, 52, a
``community partnership specialist'' with the Census Bureau, is
also Russian, Jewish and a recent immigrant. He is one of hundreds
working full time with the Census in the New York metropolitan area
to help its count in ethnic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to determine exactly how many Russians live in the
city. The city's most recent figure for Russian-speaking immigrants
says 106,954 were living in all five boroughs in 1996. The census
does not count immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   Krasny has no idea how many Russian immigrants live in Brighton
Beach. ``Some people are saying 100,000,'' he said, ``some say
20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   With most of the Russian emigres arriving since the breakup of
the Soviet Union in 1991, this will be the first chance to formally
count how many are living here. Since last summer, Borsh has held
meetings with civic and religious organizations and pushed his
message to the influential Russian-language newspapers in the
attempt to get everyone on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different that what we had back in Russia,'' Borsh said.
``It's the only way [for people) to express their needs to the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress disburses some $180 billion dollars in Federal funding
each year, according to the Census Bureau, and much of that is
based on population data. Undercounts deny funding, and especially
hurt emerging communities. Brooklyn Borough President Howard
Golden, in an October 1999 letter of support for the Census, said
his borough was under-counted by 472,000 in 1990, and claimed a $1
billion loss in Federal aid for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Borsh says he points up figures like these and plays to
Russians' willingness to integrate with American society. But for
recently arrived Russian-speaking immigrants, it can be a tougher
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Stukelman, vice president of the Association of Holocaust
Survivors from the Former Soviet Union, did not answer the 1990
census, which circulated less than a year after she arrived. Her
husband died before she, her two adult children and grandchildren
left the Soviet Union in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Stukelman remembered being ``too scared to pick up the
telephone,'' and said even going through the checkout line at a
grocery store was a frightening experience if one couldn't speak
the language.
</P>
<P>
   Krasny, who has worked with Borsh through Community Board 13,
said this is typical of recent immigrants. He said there are many
in the community concerned with family first and citizenship
second.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only about five minutes to answer the short form, which
will be mailed to every household beginning in April. One in six
homes will receive a longer questionnaire the Census uses in
sampling more complex demographics. Some of the questions _
household income, nationality, language spoken _ are similar to the
ominous-sounding Soviet queries. Borsh suspected that several might
answer ``Jewish'' for nationality, knowing now that it won't be
used against them.
</P>
<P>
   Max Norat, a spokesman for Census 2000 in New York City, doesn't
think the questions will create many problems, and said there will
be nearly 70 Russian-speaking volunteers staffing Census help desks
in the metropolitan New York area.
</P>
<P>
   In other emerging immigrant communities, Norat said, illegal
immigrants who suspect a deportation trap are the toughest to
convince they should participate. That doesn't appear to be an
issue for Russians, which constitute the city's largest source of
new, legal immigrants. Of the estimated 5 million illegal
immigrants in the country, 19,000 come from the former Soviet
Union, according to Immigration and Naturalization Service figures.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Kvasnyuk, a community partnership specialist working
with the Seattle-area Russian community, said apathy is also a part
of why some Russians avoid the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who came from the Soviet Union are pretty
indifferent toward government,'' he said. ``They don't want to have
anything to do with it. There's no time or desire to even think
about the census.''
</P>
<P>
   Kvasnyuk also has no idea how many Russians live in the
Seattle-Tacoma area; the 1990 census put it about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Once candidates for elective office become aware of how many
Russian voters are living in Brooklyn, Krasny reasoned, they will
begin to include them in their campaign. Norat agreed the Census is
often the first step an emerging community takes in gathering
political power.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also hope that being included in the census data
will result in Americans seeing them as more a part of the
community, and break down stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say there is a `Berlin wall' between the
Russian-speaking people and American-born people,'' Krasny said.
Much of this is based on Russian senior citizens who participate in
government entitlement programs. Stukelman said that relationship
is a new experience for many Russians, who had long accepted they
had little say in their government.
</P>
<P>
   The census is also helping some put their past in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there is a mistrust that those people brought from
the Soviet Union,'' Krasny said, ``but little by little it's going
away.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
