<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-FASHION-FORECASTE     02-28 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-FASHION-FORECASTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FROM DENIM TO FUR, FASHION FORECASTERS SEE IT FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Elisabeth Franck is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ELISABETH FRANCK   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That whole '80s glitzy sequined thing is back. So are
reptile skins, jeweled sandals, polka dots, ruffles and ripped
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Unappealing, you think? Think again. When ``fashion forecaster''
Pat Tunsky first announced that jean jackets were back, people in
the industry thought she was crazy. Four years later, denim is
everywhere, from the latest Gap ads to clothes racks at
Bloomingdale's and Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   A forecaster with the Doneger Group in Manhattan, Tunsky is paid
to think well ahead of the times. Twice each year, she meets with
designers or retailers who want to know what colors, trends and
fabrics will be hot for the next season. Her firm charges $7,000
for a year of forecasts, while other forecasters charge as much as
$150,000 for big projects. Industry analysts say the results are
worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's expensive, but you can't afford not to use forecasters
anymore,'' said John Simone, a professor at New York's Fashion
Institute of Technology. ``The mentality now is that a major
mistake in direction can result in a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting emerged as a consulting niche in the 1970s, after
the failed transition from mini- to maxi-skirts saddled retailers
with thousands of shin-grazing skirts. Today, forecasters intervene
at all levels of the industry, Simone said, advising clothiers on
the wants and needs of the public, and giving Wall Street
investment banks a window on the viability of fashion houses going
public. Since most high-end designers do their own forecasting, the
cottage industry of forecasting firms is geared towards retailers
and brand names that sell millions of units per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing frou-frou about forecasters,'' said Prof.
Polly Guerin, another professor at FIT. ``They are the eyes and
ears of the industry, and are a vital part of the auxiliary fashion
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth Intelligence, a company that forecasts fashion and other
trends for the youth, advises Levi's, Calvin Klein's CK line and
Benetton. The firm's president, Jane Rinzler Buckingham, said Youth
Intelligence finds trends by following fashion-forward designers,
scoping out the streets of London, Los Angeles or New York, and
monitoring eclectic boutique wares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for people with great intuition and great passion,''
she said, ``who care about trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters who specialize in technical aspects of the business
like colors and fabrics also rely on extensive knowledge of the
industry and common sense. Tunsky, whose expertise is colors,
credited her 26 years in advertising, retail and forecasting with
bolstering her ability to look into the future.
</P>
<P>
   To forecast the comeback of jean jackets, for instance, she took
note of young women in Europe wearing denim jackets juxtaposed with
work clothes for the office, and noticed also that cutting-edge
designers like Helmut Lang showed denim on their runways.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting may have begun as a safety net for retailers, but
Tunsky says there is less pressure for each firm to be accurate
today because retailers often consult more than one forecasting
firm. She encourages her clients to subscribe to more than one
service. Saks Fifth Avenue, a Doneger client, also uses the
forecasting firm Here and Now, ``just to make sure everybody is on
the same wavelength,'' said Saks fashion coordinator Diane
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasters admit the road to new trends is littered with
past season's failures. Few, however, will acknowledge having
goofed. Tunsky insisted that she has never bombed. Rinzler
Buckingham said she was sure her company had made ``lots'' of
mistakes, but couldn't remember any.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting trends is easy compared to the challenge of changing
the retailers' mentality, forecasters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers want to be safe, and stick with what sells, at the
risk of saturation,'' Tunsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent cargo pant overload, for instance, was a trend
saturation, with retailers unwilling to pull back when forecasters
advised them to do so. Unsold cargo pants filled storerooms all
over the country. The next saturation, Tunsky predicts, will come
with ``the whole bohemian, gypsy embellished look,'' a trend she
says hasn't even peaked yet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their complaints about the stodginess of retailers,
forecasters themselves are sometimes accused of lacking
originality. Simone, of FIT, dubs them ``the fashion equivalent of
polling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have helped the business in many ways,'' he added, ``but
have hurt it by stifling creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Daudin, a forecaster at Victoria's Secret, said that
among top designers, forecasters are still a dirty little secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a `snobisme,''' Daudin explained in his native French.
``The biggest designing houses will never tell you that they buy
forecasting services, it makes them look weak.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, the industry is changing and more designers
admit to relying on trend forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   So what are other long-term trends foreseen by industry experts?
</P>
<P>
   The comeback of ``neo-classicism,'' a put-together look
epitomized by ``Yves Saint Laurent in the '70s,'' said Tunsky.
</P>
<P>
   As to the forecasters' own wardrobes, sometimes less is more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get so caught up in trends,'' Rinzler Buckingham
explained, commenting on her ``boring black dress,'' ``that you
just get really tired of the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
