<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ACTIVIST-NEWSPAPERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISM OR ACTIVISM? BRONX NEWSPAPERS TOE THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Nathan Hegedus is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATHAN HEGEDUS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Potholes large enough to swallow small children
dotted the streets of the Highbridge section of the South Bronx.
For years, however, city agencies had made no move to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   Then last autumn, the monthly Highbridge Horizon turned its eye
to the deteriorating streets. Horizon reporters, all local
residents trained in weekly journalism classes, published the
Department of Transportation's pothole hot line number, wrote
blistering articles, and, just in time for Halloween, recruited
local youth for the Great Pothole Hunt. Children decorated and
photographed the most horrific potholes, and the pictures ran in
the November issue.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after The Horizon hit the streets, work crews from the
Department of Transportation and the Department of Environmental
Protection started repairs. Mark Patterson, a spokesman for the
Department of Transportation, insists that The Horizon's role would
not have prompted the work. ``If they want to take credit, fine,
but nobody influences the DOT to fill potholes. I could have gone
past this pothole and called it in.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not convincing the Horizon staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only took them about five days to finish,'' says Yolando
Romero, 50, a Horizon reporter and community activist with
Neighbors in Highbridge, the group that started the paper in
December 1998. ``People said, `Wow, the paper can really make a
difference.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The monthly Horizon, in English and Spanish, covers a scant 10
blocks in a neighborhood slowly recovering from decades of violence
and poverty. ``The paper reports on issues that encourage more
people to become involved in improvement projects,'' says Joseph
Ryan, the 26-year-old editor in chief. He works for the federal
government's Volunteers in Service to America and is the only
non-Highbridge resident on staff. ``If residents take control of
the neighborhood, that can spread to surrounding areas.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy makes The Highbridge Horizon one of a handful of
small nonprofit newspapers that do more than cover the news; they
encourage community activism. Scraping by with private grants and
sometimes paid advertising, they are crusading journalists who see
their role as helping to spotlight and improve Bronx neighborhoods
long overlooked by the mainstream press.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Lee, editor of the 13-year-old Inner City Press, says
news outlets like his serve a hungry readership. Lee occasionally
searches the Sunday New York Times for references to the Bronx. He
describes his count from a recent issue: ``Seventeen mentions of
the Bronx _ a few crimes, 12 weddings and a death in Riverdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Highbridge Horizon, The Inner City Press, which has
evolved primarily into a website, has a particular bent. A group of
activists started the paper as a way to inform and organize
residents of the South Bronx around housing issues. Soon they found
themselves directly involved in legal and political battles against
banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injustice was so great,'' says Lee. ``People would knock
on our door after a article and ask, `So what are you going to do
about that?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who refuses paid advertisements, fosters an attacking style
of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to think through `objective' journalism and veer from
the idea that the reporter has no active role,'' he says. The
news-starved communities in the Bronx apparently did not care about
this break with traditional journalism. At one time, before the
switch to the Internet, the paper circulated 32,000 free copies on
local stands and in bodegas, Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   The scrappy Bronx papers are not shy about claiming credit for
any improvements in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   The biweekly nonprofit Norwood News, serving the neighborhoods
of Norwood, Fordham Road and Bedford Park, says it helped speed the
construction of the long-delayed Public School 20 in Norwood. From
1994 to 1996, The News ran a barrage of stories and editorials
blasting the School Construction Authority for slow and sloppy
work. Although the construction ran three years over the original
three-year timetable, the News's publisher, Jordan Moss, is
convinced it would have dragged on even longer without pressure
from the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got that story first and kept their feet to the fire,'' he
says. ``The SCA is still having problems all over the city but not
here. We had four schools built on time this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Over in Highbridge, The Horizon continues its crusading ways by
publicizing a Neighbors in Highbridge campaign to improve local
mail service. The paper complains that the mail often is delivered
after 5 p.m. and sometimes is unceremoniously dumped in building
lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``After our stories on the mail service, we got people drumming
on the door complaining about the post office. Then we refer them
to Neighbors in Highbridge,'' Romero says.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, the owner of Ralph's Grocery, Rafael Berrios,
agrees that The Horizon fosters community spirit. ``Since it came
out, a lot of people take it and talk about it,'' he says. ``It has
all the information, what is good and bad in Highbridge. It is just
one part of this whole neighborhood getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
