<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1212 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-RETIRED-DANCERS &LR;      02-28 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-RETIRED-DANCERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCERS SEARCH FOR NEW LIVES OFFSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Alexa Jaworski  is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ALEXA JAWORSKI   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the age of 27, Isabel Kimmel reflects on her youth
as if it were 50 years ago, not just a few.
</P>
<P>
   Back then she was a professional ballerina with the New York
City Ballet in Lincoln Center. It was a world of ``exuberance and
innocence,'' she says. She and the members of her ballet company
referred to the world beyond the ballet as the ``outside world,''
and the people that belonged to it as ``civilians.'' A wonderful
bubble, she calls that former world in which she sailed across the
stage for the simple purpose of pleasing the eyes and moving the
hearts of an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of it as my very youthful time,'' said Kimmel, a woman
with wide, pensive brown eyes and the poise and lithe build of a
former ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years, 8 of which were devoted to the New York City
Ballet, Kimmel sensed it was time for her to move on to that
outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was spending my life in this theater with no windows,'' she
said. ``I felt there was so much out there that I wanted to be
exposed to. I felt there was a lot I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Symphony in C,'' a Ballanchine ballet, was her last dance,
performed in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., in the summer of 1998. It was
also the first ballet she performed when she moved to New York from
Atlanta as a teen-ager in order to attend the American Ballet
School, the official school of the New York City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Now a senior at Barnard College in New York, majoring in English
literature, Kimmel said she thought of leaving ballet for a long
time. ``Dance is a short career. I wanted to leave while I felt
young and capable. I wanted to get my undergraduate degree before
age 30. I could have stayed for another five to eight years, but
then I'd be pushing it. The later I stayed, the less of an
advantage I'd have.''
</P>
<P>
   While many in other fields are reaching the peaks of their
careers, professional dancers find themselves thinking about an
unusually early retirement. As their bodies, as well as their
minds, tire of long rehearsals and constant travel and scrutiny,
dancers search for new careers, new friends, new lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's letting go of an identity,'' said Suzie Jary, director of
client services at Career Transitions For Dancers, a national
nonprofit arts service organization that helps professional dancers
identify and pursue new careers through career counseling.
Thirty-five percent of dancers who come to Career Transitions do
not have a college degree, Jary said. Besides providing career
assistance, the center also offers grants to help dancers, who
usually do not earn high salaries, pay for an education.
</P>
<P>
   A former dancer herself, Jary is now a licensed social worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working with people who had their dreams or are working at
them, not people trying to find their dreams,'' she said, adding
that usually her own colleagues in social work help those searching
for their goals. The transition from dancer to ``civilian,'' Jary
said, is a kind of ``grieving process'' for a dancer that requires
letting go of something that has defined him or her for most of
their lives. Dancers ``don't have the credentials, income and
prestige of others.'' she said. ``For doctors, even if they retire,
they retain their title.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving show business in his 50s, Ron Young, a former
dancer, singer, actor and director, found a new career in the
corporate world. Now an assistant vice president of corporate
heritage services at Merrill Lynch in New York, Young recalled his
own concerns upon retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided I wanted to leave, I had no idea I had
transferable skills,'' he said. ``I didn't have any work outside of
show business.'' Through Career Transitions, he said, he learned
that he had and could develop marketable skills. The center
provided him with funding for computer training.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers have a high work ethic, he also noted. ``Dancers would
never dream of stopping in the middle of a dance routine,'' he
said. ``We finish the task at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Now out of dance for four years, he said he never expected to be
wearing a suit and tie. However, he is happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In show business you are judged every day of your life. It's
wearing after a while. I felt a burden removed.'' In his new
career, life is much more stable, he said, and the paycheck is
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the loss of a life-encompassing livelihood causes a
sense of loss and confusion for dancers, many agree that there is
something else even more painful to leave behind _ their company.
The lifestyle of a dancer can be hard to leave, Jary said. ``Your
company becomes your family,'' she said. ``People miss that part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was hard,'' said Leda Meredith, 37, who retired from
performing two years ago. ``All of a sudden there would be entire
days when it was just me and my school books and I didn't talk to a
single soul. I had to learn to create a social life. I had to learn
to call people I hadn't seen, and reach out more.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally from San Francisco, Meredith moved to New York to
dance with the American Ballet Theatre II for several years, then
alternated between dancing for Jennifer Muller/The Works, a modern
dance company, and Dances ... Patrelle, both based in New York. At
35, however, Meredith decided to devote herself to a second
interest that had always competed with dance _ herbal medicine.
With the help of a grant from Career Transitions, Meredith began
taking courses in ethnobotany at the New York Botanical Gardens.
She expects to receive her bachelor's degree in a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this second interest, Meredith said her transition
was somewhat easier than it is for other former dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had other things I was eager to begin to learn about,'' she
said. ``I started becoming more fascinated with things outside the
studio.'' And there was also the age factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance is short-lived,'' she said. ``I can work with plants
until I'm 90.'' Still, she keeps one foot on the stage by
choreographing and teaching dance.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel is still thinking about what career she will pursue after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would dance again,'' she said. ``I feel better about having
a degree.'' When she watches performances, she said she misses it.
``I've only been out of the company for a year and a half. I have a
big sense of nostalgia.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
