<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Feb. 29. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Phoenix) - `We sit somewhere in between, I like to think,
HBO and the traditional Big Three (networks). When we get it right,
it's cultural-phenomenon time. And when we get it wrong, it's
ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, chairman of the Fox Television Entertainment
Group, spoke those words to TV critics last month. Just a guess,
but I'd say `Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire,` the shipwreck
that just gets worse as the days go on, falls into the latter
category. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the `L` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - No sooner did an Arizona production
company announce its plans to make a ``cute and fun'' movie about
Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio when serious casting problems
set in. Arpaio sees Robert DeNiro or Al Pacino in the title role of
a film to be based on his book, ``America's Toughest Sheriff,''
though he says he's willing to settle for Joe Pesci. The problem is
finding a ``cute or fun'' way to cast the role of Scott Norberg,
killed in a struggle with guards in Arpaio's jail. By E. J.
MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PIMENTEL (Phoenix) - What do `gooks,` Bob Jones University and the
Confederate flag have in common? Easy. An early indication that the
GOP big tent is perhaps not as spacious as one might hope.
</P>
<P>
   By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL. Story moved in the `K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
