<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1214 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-RICH-IMMIGRANTS &LR;      02-28 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-RICH-IMMIGRANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATING FROM RICHES TO RAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Rebecca Webber is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 
 By REBECCA WEBBER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service    
  NEW YORK _ Yassine could be running his father's bus company in
Casablanca, Morocco, earning $5,000 a month. Instead, at 22, he
waits on tables at an Italian restaurant in SoHo, pocketing about
$50 _ on a good day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Casablanca, Yassine lived between his mother's home and a
spacious apartment he rented with friends. Now he sleeps on the
couch or the floor in a cramped one-bedroom he shares with two
other young Moroccans. He traded in his shiny blue Mercedes for the
commuter-packed E train.
</P>
<P>
   New York sees no shortage of transplants like Yassine who defy
the immigrant stereotype. Rather than attempting to replace native
poverty with American prosperity, these newcomers are here for a
good time. To get it, they have swapped comfortable lives abroad
for a mean Manhattan experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume that those who go live in another country are
desperate,'' says Peter Stalker, a United Nations Development
Program expert on international migration. ``But it can be an
extension of their life experience. It's what's always happened
internally with kids moving to cities.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in 1998 on a tourist visa, Yassine, who declined
to use his last name because he is in the country illegally,
anticipated a monthlong American vacation. He quickly met many
fellow foreigners and replaced the comforts of home with the
comfort of a close-knit young immigrant community that populates
some of the most fashionable neighborhoods of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he risked parental disapproval, financial
security and legal complications to remain on after his visa
expired, Yassine answers, ``To have an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of foreign-born New Yorkers has risen
steadily, there is no count of the underground population to which
Yassine belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, all the major international economic centers
attract people from all over the world,'' says Saskia Sassen, a
sociology professor at the University of Chicago and expert on
globalization. Young people, with few obligations in their native
countries, find the lure of what Sassen terms ``global cities''
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Orban, a Belgian who married an American woman, explains,
``New York is what Paris used to be 30 years ago. Paris has become
boring, now New York is the place to go.'' Orban says that the
well-publicized turnaround of the once crime-infested city and the
affordability of international travel have increased the temptation
for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Young immigrants say they come to New York for a few years of
freedom after finishing school and before establishing careers.
After a few years in New York, some change their minds about
returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Max DiMatteo, 24, a former architecture student who came from
Italy in 1997, works as a waiter in a restaurant owned by his
cousin. He won't return to Italy now ``because the mentality is too
much behind.'' Though during his first months in America, he was
``feeling the distance,'' he says he now has adjusted to American
culture and married an American.
</P>
<P>
   Fara, a 21-year-old Parisian, ditched her mom's home and her
economics study at college to overstay her tourist visa in New
York. Working as a restaurant hostess in SoHo, she plans to return
to Paris in ``about five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Fara and Yassine, don't even bother to see if the
cumbersome immigration bureaucracy would grant them legal resident
permits and green cards for work. They say they have little trouble
finding jobs, often in stores and restaurants run by fellow
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Teiki Takamatsu, a SoHo jewelry store salesperson, says
opportunities to take on undocumented workers are prevalent,
although she said her store, with a ``Help Wanted'' sign in the
window, resists the temptation. ``We just turned away an Israeli
guy who doesn't have a green card,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even some who sneaked into the country hoping for bigger things
say they accept the lowly status of a busboy or coat checker
because their time in New York is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The mean Manhattan experience can teach ``what you can really do
by yourself,'' Yassine says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are having a more interesting life,'' says Stalker.
Financial calculations don't always matter so much depending on
``where they place their emphasis, what they value.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
