<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1215 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-FITNESS-MARATHON-TRAI     02-28 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITNESS-MARATHON-TRAINING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAKING OF A MARATHONER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Most marathoners come from poor families. We know how to
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rolando Vera, after running the New York Marathon in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The dragon spires of Mann's Chinese Theater in Hollywood mark
the first steps on many marathoners' Boulevard of Broken Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Los Angeles Marathon, mile 18. Muscles running on
empty. That coveted ``runner's high'' a dim memory. Some 33,660
footfalls down, roughly 15,300 more to go. Mostly uphill.
</P>
<P>
   Stop now and experience the closest thing to rigor mortis a
living person can feel. Runners call it ``the wall,'' a barrier
made up of dozens of aches and a million reasons to quit. That's
when mind becomes more important than muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, ultimately, all mental,'' said Dr. Joseph Haraszti, a
Pasadena physician and psychiatrist who has crossed the finish line
in six marathons. ``A marathon is full of ebbs and flows in the way
you feel. People talk about hitting the wall and getting a second
wind. I can tell you there's not just a second wind, but a third, a
fourth and a 10th wind.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, more than 21,000 runners will test their mental and
physical mettle against the L.A. Marathon's grueling 26.2-mile
course. Last year, 16,827 of the 21,630 people who signed up
crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Marathoners are unique human beings. Months of conditioning
transform them, almost literally, into running machines. Their
bodies burn waste faster, conserve energy longer and pump blood
more efficiently than most people's. They also have an iron will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human body is amazing,'' said Dr. Rudra Sabaratnam, a
veteran runner and medical commissioner of the L.A. Marathon. ``You
can train it to do lots of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Marathon running is old-school extreme sport. As legend tells
it, in 490 B.C. an Athenian named Pheidippides inadvertently
invented the sport with a solo run _ 25 miles from Marathon to
Athens _ at top speed to deliver news of a crucial battle victory.
</P>
<P>
   Then he dropped dead.
</P>
<P>
   Pheidippides' fatal finale lingers in many beginning
marathoners' minds _ &UR;  &LR; especially when things get tough between
miles 18 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a daunting task,'' Haraszti said. ``Before I ran my first
marathon, I had this incredible anxiety. Somehow it just seems very
unnatural for any human being to run 26.2 miles; it seems we're
just not made for that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unnatural, in a way.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``collapse distance'' _ the point where the human
body shuts down _ is about three times the normal exercise regimen.
Encino running coach Pat Connelly said people can generally push it
for about 15 miles before giving out. Anything beyond that requires
special training.
</P>
<P>
   Marathoners spends months tweaking their physiology to cover
those extra 9.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   As a runner trains, increasing long-distance runs each week
(usually up to 18 or 20 miles about three weeks before the race),
the body learns to conserve glycogen _ muscle fuel. The heart gets
used to pumping faster and blood vessels stay constricted to keep
blood flowing to muscles. And as long as the runner takes in plenty
of fluids, electrolytes and carbohydrates, his or her body will
hold enough energy in reserve to finish a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The training process is similar to climbing Mount Everest.
Climbers increase their altitude in increments to acclimate
themselves to thin air. Runners do it with distance.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate marathoners are slim and not too muscular. For
example, Arnold Schwarzenegger would have a tough time running a
marathon. Muscles heat up as energy is burned and cool down through
the release of sweat, which saps the fluids. More muscles mean more
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing can be another peril. Many runners _ especially men _
find their nipples are bleeding after only a few miles. The
condition is so common it has a name: ``runner's nipples.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At mile six, the first medical station, we get bombarded by
people who need Vaseline,'' said Sharon Zlotowicz, co-coordinator
of the L.A. Marathon's medical team. ``We go through 350 pounds of
it. When you run for so many miles, you start to chafe wherever
there are seams.''
</P>
<P>
   The feet also take a beating. Each step _ there are 49,000 in
all, according to coach Connelly _ puts three to four times the
runner's weight on the foot. Good shoes are critical shock
absorbers.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains are inevitable. But they don't make the race
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Poor old Pheidippides would have appreciated the modern
amenities of the L.A. Marathon: 28 water stations (serving 50,000
gallons of water), 16,000 Mylar blankets, 11 medical units and 450
medical volunteers, 167 massage therapists and more than 21,600
runners. City of Angels Medical Center even has a field hospital at
the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The mental hurdles are lowered by constant encouragement from
fellow runners and millions of spectators. At mile 25, the agony of
mile 18 (or 20 or 24, depending on where the wall first pops up)
vanishes in a rush of the brain's feel-good chemicals, adrenaline
and endorphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last mile is actually easier,'' Haraszti said. ``As you
near the finish line, your mind kind of takes over. You begin to
feel the end is in sight and dig deep. In my case, some of my best
mile times came at the end of a race. Your endorphins are working
overtime. It's almost like a drug high when you finish.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1218 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-REVOLUTIONARY-SIT     02-28 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-REVOLUTIONARY-SITES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN TRIES TO PRESERVE 1776 HISTORY FEW KNEW IT HAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(EDS:Base Ball in graf 15 is cq) 
(mp) 
(Will Morton is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 
 By WILL MORTON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While tourists often seek Revolutionary War sites in
Philadelphia, Valley Forge or Yorktown, a historical group wants to
draw them to a place better known for Coney Island and a baseball
team that left for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the First Battle Revival Alliance is trying to build
a hiking trail as part of a $1 million effort to bring attention to
Battle of Brooklyn, the fledgling U.S. Army's first battle in the
Revolutionary War. All that remains today are a few obscure plaques
and a little-known monument in 526-acre Prospect Park.
</P>
<P>
   The group formed four years ago to restore a 17th-century Dutch
farmhouse, known as the Old Stone House, the site of a climactic
battle in August 1776 in which Maryland troops fought the English
as George Washington and his soldiers escaped across the river to
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too few Americans are aware that the survival of our nation
depended on this little known Battle of Brooklyn,'' said Susan
Miller, a retired schoolteacher who heads the historical group.
``Brooklyn's Revolutionary War history is second to none in
America, and yet the story is not known. A lot of people have
turned their backs on it because they feel Washington was
defeated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn historians, like John J. Gallagher in his 1995 book
``The Battle of Brooklyn 1776,'' assert that the valor shown at the
Old Stone House allowed Washington's troops to live to fight
another day.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed hiking trail is aimed at people like Alexis
Rehrmann, a 24-year-old theater administrator, who admitted she
knows ``almost nothing'' about Revolutionary War history in
Brooklyn. She heard about the restored farmhouse from a friend, and
she happened to move to Park Slope, the neighborhood of Brooklyn
brownstone homes that grew up east of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to check it out because it's a nice day, and I've heard
some story about George Washington watching the battle,'' Rehrmann
said. ``It never occurred to me that there were battles fought'' in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   A Battle of Brooklyn Trail would trace the course of the
fighting from British landings at the Narrows, where the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge stands today, along routes they followed
to the Old Stone House and other battle sites. Like one in lower
Manhattan, the entire trail would be viewable by car, bus or
bicycle in about two hours. Visitors could walk along three
downtown segments, culminating at the Old Stone House, in about an
hour. The project, which is still in the planning stages, includes
several key parts:
</P>
<P>
   _ A two-by-three-foot tourist map would show a dozen key sites
on a map of colonial Brooklyn superimposed on the modern street
grid. Developing and printing several hundred thousand copies would
cost at least $100,000, though advertising could defray printing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two-by-three-foot signs would mark the key locations, and more
than 50 sites could receive smaller signs. A tentative budget pegs
the cost at $577,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Old Stone House would receive a memorial garden with
benches, a statue a 100-foot flagpole and plaques for about
$225,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ A special Battle of Brooklyn re-enactment in 2001 would
commemorate the 225th anniversary of the fighting and could cost
more than $80,000. Re-enactments this year and from 2002 to 2008,
marking the anniversary of British occupation of Brooklyn, would
cost about $40,000, or $5,000 each year.
</P>
<P>
   _ About $10,000 would be spent on ground-penetrating radar,
which can detect differences in density, such as stone walls or
loose earth such as burial fill. Other devices would detect minute
variations in the earth's magnetic field caused by buildings that
burned. The equipment would help locate the unmarked graves of
Maryland troops buried near the Old Stone House and remnants of a
small fort that stood in Prospect Park in 1776.
</P>
<P>
   First Battle Revival Alliance expects the project would take 5
to 10 years to complete at a cost of at least $1 million. The money
would be raised through grants and donations from individuals,
businesses and public sources, Miller said, discussing a
preliminary proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch immigrant built the Old Stone House in 1699 with
two-foot-thick walls near the Gowanus Creek, now a stagnant,
little-used shipping canal. During the Battle of Brooklyn in August
1776, the British used the house as an artillery position to fire
on American soldiers, many of whom drowned while trying to retreat
across the creek. Late in the 1800s, the building served as the
first clubhouse of the Brooklyn team of the National Base Ball
league, later known as the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Katie and Wade Beltramo, who moved last summer to just a few
blocks from the Old Stone House, are the kind of people the
organizers hope to attract. They volunteer in nearby Prospect Park,
where they heard about the battle at the Old Stone House during a
park ranger tour. They said they recently read about the
Revolutionary War, and joked they probably know more about it than
most Brooklyn residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that say? That's a pretty sad statement,'' said Wade
Beltramo, 28, an attorney who moved to New York City five years
ago. He grew up in Iowa, which has no Revolutionary War history and
became a state only in 1846. New York history attracts him, he
said, because he can visit the spots where events took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living right around the corner from this historic house,
which was the clubhouse for the Brooklyn Dodgers,'' he said.
``Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the history group leader, is holding early talks with
other historical groups to determine which sites to include on the
map. Developing the trail is a mammoth project, and she seeks
tourism partners and help from businesses and museums.
</P>
<P>
   One local official praised the ``creative and ambitious
agenda,'' but worried the thorny New York City bureaucracy could
frustrate organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally if there's some way we could support something like
that, we would,'' said Craig R. Hammerman, district manager of
Community Board 6, the neighborhood government body that covers the
area. ``I like the idea of the maps.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn's official borough historian, John B. Manbeck, worried
that raising money also could challenge the group's effort.
Restoration of the Old Stone House came only after the Brooklyn
Borough President wrangled $750,000 for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Revolutionary War is a popular war,''
Manbeck said. ``It doesn't have the attraction that the Civil War
has. Maybe it's too primitive to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Battle Revival Alliance remains undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nationally significant site that really too few
Americans know about,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
