<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA REFUSES CUBAN DIPLOMAT PERMANENT PROTECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Caught between two friends, Canada Monday took an
uncharacteristically tough line with Cuba, refusing to provide a
haven for a Cuban diplomat expelled from the United States after
being accused of spying.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said Canada would not grant a
Cuban government request to allow Jose Imperatori to remain at the
Cuban embassy in Ottawa, where the diplomat took refuge after being
ousted from the US over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays, he will be here illegally,'' Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
   The implicit threat to take hard measures if Imperatori refuses
to leave voluntarily was the latest wrinkle in a strange saga that
one veteran Canadian diplomat described as ``theatre of the
absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori, meanwhile, said through a spokesman at the Cuban
Embassy that he would continue a hunger strike to protest his
ejection from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He did not make clear whether he would abide by Canada's request
that he immediately depart and return to Havana. For its part,
Canada did not make clear what, if anything, it can do if
Imperatori remains holed up at the embassy, which is sovereign
Cuban territory under international law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bizarre situation,'' Perry Sterling, a former
Canadian envoy to Cuba, told CBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The drama started last week when the US accused Imperatori of
conspiring with an official of the US Immigration and
Naturalization Service in acts of espionage. On Saturday night, he
was taken into custody by the FBI and flown aboard a US government
plane to Montreal, where he was supposed to board a commercial
flight to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomatic deal brokered by Canada between Cuba and the
US fell apart when Imperatori failed to board the plane to Havana,
instead bolting for Ottawa and the Cuban embassy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Havana started issuing public statements
accusing the US of dragging Canada into the fray and urged Ottawa
to allow Imperatori to remain in Canada until the US apologizes for
the spy allegations. Cuba claimed the 46-year-old vice-counsel at
the Cuban interests section in Washington was just a victim of the
high-profile battle over the fate of a Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez,
who was plucked from the sea and taken to Florida by US rescuers
after his mother drowned last year while fleeing Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori Monday repeated threats to starve himself in Canada
to protest the US action. ``I have become the victim of a major
slander,'' he declared through an embassy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's initial befuddlement at the escapade turned to anger as
it became plain that Havana hoped to use Canada as a sort of pulpit
from which to denounce the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has for decades been one of Cuba's most ardent defenders
on the international scene, and with the collapse of the Soviet
Union has emerged as perhaps Fidel Castro's most important economic
ally. Canadian firms are among the heaviest investors in Cuba, and
Canadian tourists represent a major source of hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   Those ties are an irritant to Washington, which has maintained
an economic embargo against the Western hemisphere's only communist
regime since 1963. Canada usually likes to flaunt the Cuban
connection as proof it maintains an independent foreign policy from
its overwhelming neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Canada's championship of Cuba started to cool last year
after Castro _ ignoring pleas from Ottawa, European nations, and
human rights groups _ continued to suppress political dissidence,
imprisoning four well-known opposition activists after they
publicly called for democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy had no words of sympathy for Imperatori's situation.
``All we were doing was providing a diplomatic courtesy,'' Axworthy
said. ``There will be no extension of his transit visa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-BLACK-ART(TRIMS) &LR;      02-28 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BLACK-ART(TRIMS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE COUPLE, AFRICAN-AMERICAN ART COLLECTION IS A LABOR OF
LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: DC, Ga . , Mo . , NC, NY)   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Daisy Nguyen is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By DAISY NGUYEN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  NEW YORK _ As John and Vivian Hewitts' marriage has flourished
over the past 50 years, so has their collection of African-American
art, which now includes hundreds of paintings and drawings in one
of the nation's most comprehensive private collections.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bank of America bought 58 pieces of art from the
couple. The assembled artwork, now known as The Hewitt Collection,
is currently touring the country and will be permanently housed in
the Afro-American Cultural Center in Charlotte, N.C., beginning in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some major artists in their collection, and it
captures the breadth of African-American artists' works over the
last 50 years,'' said June Kelly, 50, owner of a SoHo art gallery
that features works by African-American artists.
</P>
<P>
   The Hewitt Collection, comprising works by important black
artists that show a broad range of styles and periods, is the
result of the Hewitts' interests in documenting black history,
people, and everyday life and display the couple's pride in their
own African-American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collection challenges the idea of what African-American
art could be,'' said Todd Smith, 34, curator of American art for
The Mint Museum of Art in Charlotte, N.C. ``It doesn't just have
art that depicts the so-called black experience but it speaks to
the individual interests of the artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic collection includes a painting by Henry O. Tanner
(1869-1937), a black artist who is best known for the religious
themes he developed in his career. Tanner is the first American
artist of African descent to gain worldwide recognition. His
landscape painting, ``Sand Dunes at Sunset, Atlantic City,'' in
October 1997 became the first artwork by a black painter to enter
the White House's collection.
</P>
<P>
   The Hewitt Collection also features two paintings by Jonathan
Green, whose works illustrate the young artist's desire to narrate
and record the seaside activities and traditions of the Gullah
culture, central to black communities on small islands off the
South Atlantic coast. Green's painting graces the cover of the
catalog for the traveling exhibition, entitled ``Celebration and
Vision: The Hewitt Collection of African-American Art.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hewitts had an abiding love for art long before they met. As
a child, John would clip illustrations from magazines to decorate
his walls. Vivian, meanwhile, was fascinated by a reproduction of
Francois Millet's ``The Gleaners,'' which decorated her childhood
home.
</P>
<P>
   They met in Atlanta in 1949, where he taught English at
Morehouse College and she taught library science at Clark Atlanta
University. ``We had a whirlwind romance,'' Vivian said, relaxing
with a cup of hot tea in their Upper West Side apartment. ``We met
in September and got married in December of that year.''
</P>
<P>
   They began collecting art when they spent their honeymoon
visiting museums in New York City. With the cash they received as
wedding gifts, they bought reproductions of modern masterpieces by
Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque. Vivian said the posters were the
first of many more artworks to adorn their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, they moved to New York City, where they slowly began to
circulate in artistic circles. John's sister, Adele Glasgow, ran a
gallery named ``The Marketplace'' in Harlem in the late 1950s that
featured African-American artists, and the Hewitts came to know
many of them. Soon the couple was buying and building their own
collection of African-American art, acquiring about five or six
works of art per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use birthdays, anniversaries, Mother's Day, Father's Day,
and Valentine's Day as an excuse to buy each other paintings,''
Vivian said.
</P>
<P>
   Being of modest means _ he worked as a reporter for scientific
magazines and she worked as a librarian _ the Hewitts often
struggled to close deals. Still, they found ways to invest in art.
``We bought what we liked and what we could afford,'' Vivian said.
``If we saw a piece that was beyond our means, we'd arrange for a
layaway plan with the gallery or the artist.'' They also focused on
Haitian paintings because they spent many of their vacations there
and because the pieces were affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it helps to have friends in the art world. In 1963, they
purchased their first abstract painting from the African-American
artist Eugene Grigsby. Grigsby, an art professor at Arizona State
University, is also Vivian Hewitt's cousin and he helped introduce
them to the leaders of Harlem society. John Biggers, a painter and
retired art professor at Texas A&AMP;M, is also related to Vivian.
Through their connections, the couple inherited a Jacob Lawrence
ink illustration in 1979 from the poet Langston Hughes, who was a
friend of Glasglow's. Over the years, they let artists use their
spacious apartment as a gallery space to show their artworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unique about the collection is that the majority of the
artists are people the collectors knew,'' said Smith, the
exhibition's curator who wrote an introduction and essay for the
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's relationship with the artists can be seen in many
of the artworks. An inscribed poster by Jonathan Green, for
instance, hangs by the entrance door of their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hewitts have always shown their enthusiasm for my art over
the years,'' said Green, 44, who now lives in Naples, Fla. ``They
have been instrumental in introducing other collectors to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Their contribution to the black art world includes philanthropic
work as well. They have donated their art to several public
collections, including Vivian's alma mater, Geneva College. They
regularly lend their art to national touring exhibitions such as
``Hidden Heritage,'' a groundbreaking show that introduced
African-American artists to the country in the late 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in their 70s the couple is in retirement. Last December,
they renewed their wedding vows at Harlem's St. Philips Episcopal
church. They live quietly and travel occasionally. John, whose
health has been failing lately, has been staying at home while
Vivian attends the openings and closings of their exhibits. (From
Feb. 14 to April 23, the Hewitt Collection will be at the Clark
University Art Gallery in Atlanta. From May 15 to July 23, the
collection will be at the Portfolio Gallery in St. Louis. And from
Aug. 13 to Oct. 14, the collection will be at the Howard University
Art Gallery in Washington, D.C.) ``Each time I go to a new venue,
the art collection looks different and new to me because they're
displayed in different ways,'' she said gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Begin OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the artworks remain in their spacious apartment. The
first Haitian painting they bought hangs above the kitchen cabinet.
Entitled ``Three Haitian Women,'' the colorful tempera painting by
Luckner Lazard features the heads and torsos of three women. ``My
husband, my son John and I love the color and the composition of
this one,'' Vivian said. She pointed to a recent purchase, a small
painting that shows a group of Haitian dancers by the Cuban artist
Emilio Sanchez, which she likes ``for its simplicity.'' Vivian said
she doesn't have a favorite painting, insisting that she and John
love all of their paintings equally. ``You live with your art and
they become like your children so you love them all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple also mentor young collectors interested in
African-American art by introducing them to artists and gallery
owners. They continue to donate their art to exhibits to serve as
an educational tool. ``We want young African-Americans to take
pride in their heritage and be an inspiration for other modest
people who want to start an art collection,'' Vivian said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She advises aspiring collectors to study art, visit galleries
and museums, and buy art pieces that are appealing and affordable.
Vivian recommends starting small, first by buying signed posters
and lithographs since they are cheap but will gain in value over
time. ``Buy what you love, use your own judgment and instinct. Over
time, your purchases will increase in value,'' she said. ``Anyone
can start collecting. You don't have to be an art expert and you
don't have to have to be rich to collect art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
