<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-WEB-ACTIVISTS &LR;      02-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WEB-ACTIVISTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER EAST SIDE ACTIVISTS TAKE TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
 (EDS: Web addresses below use (tilde) to indicate a tilde symbol)  
(mp) 
(William Siss is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By WILLIAM SISS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a cramped, unheated room at ABC No Rio, a
community center on Manhattan's Lower East Side, 10 bundled
volunteers smoke cigarettes and discuss how to save local gardens
from destruction by using the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   They're creating the Interactivist Network Webcasting System
(www.interactivist.net), a Web site participants hope will
revolutionize the way protesters organize, demonstrate and inform.
The site is set to go online in late February. Under a $5,000 grant
from Manhattan Neighborhood Network, a cable company, ABC No Rio
will use photographs, reports, video and discussion boards to
examine one issue at a time, and to show other activists how to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building a news information service that is
nonmediated, where people involved in news events can communicate
with the public,'' said a volunteer, Eric Goldhagen, 33, whose pale
face and scruffy beard give him the look of a cloistered
technophile. ``We are interested in showing the possibilities to
other nonprofits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interactivists' first project, ``Under the Asphalt,''
highlights a local issue with national ramifications: the sale of
gardens maintained for decades by community groups. The site will
show how protesters and lobbyists can block the auctioning of
garden land by the city. In the future, the site may transmit
rallies and panels on such issues in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Tamra Raven, 30, is donating two one-minute segments to the Web
site, taken from her digital video documentary about community
gardens, ``From Rats to Roses.'' An activist since the age of 5,
Raven said the Internet streamlines the way activists communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Group e-mailing has been a powerful, mobilizing tool,'' she
said. ``You can disseminate in a quick way: `Please come to a rally
on June 5.' You can send it to your hundred friends on e-mail, and
they can send it to their hundred friends, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Raven is a recent addition to the 20 Web-savvy artists who
started meeting last fall to weigh in on each portion of the site.
In discussing their upcoming ``War on the Homeless'' project,
members decided not to exploit the homeless by showing their faces
on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ABC No Rio members meet at a decaying, four-story tenement at
156 Rivington St., which since 1980 has been home to punk bands,
poets and graphic artists as well as groups like Food Not Bombs,
the Coalition to Free Mumia Abu-Jamal, Act Up and the Rainforest
Activist Network.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, the space has maintained a free computer center,
complete with scanner and laser jet printer. Much of the equipment
was donated or sold at a discount by corporations like the
McGraw-Hill Companies and smaller dealers like Tekserve.
Neighborhood residents use the space a few hours each week to print
resumes, send e-mail to relatives abroad, or write letters to their
landlord.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to create a link, you need to fulfill the need of
the people you want to organize,'' Goldhagen said. ``The big issue
is computer and Internet literacy becoming as valuable as being
able to read. If we hope to be a real organization for change, it
starts with making changes in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interactivist Network joins the Web at a time when protester
organization is humming. For example, The Anarchy Organization
(TAO), (www.tao.ca), coordinates through its server a clearinghouse
for web sites by Books to Prisoners Seattle (btp.tao.ca), the
Institute for Social Ecology (www.tao.ca/(tilde)ise) and the
Socialist Forum (http://www.ta.ca/(tilde)socialistforum), among
others. It also supports the Direct Action Media Network
(damn.tao.ca), a multimedia news service that chronicles protests,
marches and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for the network, Rachel Rinaldo, 27, said that
stories about protests are often more accurate coming from
independent Web sources than from television networks, which have
time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Activists used the Internet to organize an estimated 35,000
demonstrators to march on the World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle last November. And they took a cue from an unlikely source:
big business. Just as companies like Time Warner and America Online
merge, so do groups as disparate as loggers and environmentalists,
who marched side by side to emphasize workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Interactivist Network may continue this trend of
collaboration, said Steven Englander, ABC No Rio's project
director, but more important, it should inspire others to create
their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to show what happens here, and show what works
and what doesn't,'' Englander said. ``Others can walk away from the
site and learn that lesson. If we are able to pull this off well
with modest means, then any group of people can do this sort of
thing. But you need to get the right team together.''
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit of sharing, the group may produce a how-to
CD-ROM. In the meantime, the volunteers will continue to develop
projects on prison labor, ``workfare,'' parks and housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see all these issues interrelated,'' said Goldhager. ``The
policies behind arresting the homeless, profiting from prison
labor. If we just put information online, the connections will be
obvious. We don't have to propagandize, we just inform.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
