<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHOSTAKOVICH-THEATER-     02-28 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOSTAKOVICH-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERSON QUARTER MAKES THEATER OF SHOSTAKOVICH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When you've played all 15 Shostakovich string
quartets in five programs over three weeks at Alice Tully Hall,
what do you do for an encore? If you're the Emerson String Quartet
(which has also recorded the works in a fine new release from
Deutsche Grammophon), you play the 15th Quartet all over again and
build an intricate theatrical program around it.
</P>
<P>
   So, beginning Tuesday night, the Emerson is to take part in a
most unusual collaboration, ``The Noise of Time,'' a production by
the Theatre de Complicite conceived and directed by Simon McBurney,
the company's artistic director. Six performances are to be
presented through Sunday at the John Jay College Theater near
Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this crowning touch was in any sense an afterthought.
The concert series itself grew out of a more ambitious notion
hatched four years ago by Philip Setzer, one of the Emerson's
violinists and its chief idea man. Setzer began with the vague
thought that it might be interesting to present all 15 Shostakovich
quartets in a theatrical treatment, with the Emerson in some sense
acting, or at least dramatizing the music. So he approached Jane S.
Moss, vice president for programming at Lincoln Center, to explore
the possibility of doing so in the Great Performers series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the idea and ran with it,'' Moss said. Well, walked.
At the time, she was just giving shape to an idea of her own, New
Visions, a series intended to bring other dimensions _ most notably
the visual and the theatrical _ to bear on the presentation of
classical music. She sensed potential in Setzer's concept but knew
it would take time to develop, and other projects were closer at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   So she first dispatched the Emerson on another compleatist
venture, playing all 16 Beethoven string quartets, interspersed
with works from the 20th century, in eight concerts over two
seasons. She enlisted McBurney and his brother, Gerard, a composer,
teacher, writer and broadcaster with a consuming interest in
Shostakovich, to refine the original idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Theatre de Complicite, a cutting-edge theatrical company
based in London, is best known in New York for its dramatic work at
the Lincoln Center Festival: ``Three Lives of Lucie Chabrol'' in
1996 and ``The Street of Crocodiles'' in 1998. McBurney also
directed ``The Chairs'' on Broadway in 1998. But Moss said that the
main reason she chose McBurney for the project may have been his
affinity for music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acting at its best is a musical profession,'' he said
recently. ``When you act onstage, the musical function is almost
more dominant than the emotional one. On film, an actor can call up
`real' events and relive them. You can't do that night after night
onstage. It's too draining. You deal with fake emotions based on
musical principles: rhythm, tempo, harmonies, upbeats, downbeats.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties ultimately deemed it best to limit the theatrical
aspect to a single work, a decision for which all must be grateful
now that it is clear how much intensive effort goes into such a
production, at least a McBurney production. Yet exactly what form
this production has taken is by no means clear, even to one who saw
part of it in rehearsal and heard the rest extensively discussed
around a table of drinks with the Emerson players and the
McBurneys: extensively but guardedly, especially on the part of
Simon McBurney.
</P>
<P>
   The second half, the part rehearsed, is a performance of the
work by the quartet, straightforward in audio terms. But visually,
the performance becomes a spectacle. The Emerson members roam about
the stage while playing, tethered, more or less, to scores and
working around an array of chairs left from the earlier drama.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the production, kept more mysterious, uses
four actors and draws on documentary and archival material in a
multimedia presentation. ``It is not a reading, not a play,''
McBurney said. ``No one is pretending to be Shostakovich. Instead,
we are attempting to meditate on him, understanding that the `him'
will be present in the 15th quartet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators agree that Shostakovich is indeed present in
this quartet, perhaps more than in any other except the Eighth,
which bears his explicit musical signature throughout. He wrote the
15th in a hospital in 1974, the year before his death. Remarkably,
its six movements, totaling about 35 minutes, are all in the same
key, E flat minor, and all marked ``adagio'': a slowness heightened
to ``adagio molto'' in the fifth movement (``Funeral March'') and
part of the sixth (``Epilogue'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The bleak introspection and elegiac cast of its unprecedented
succession of six adagio movements left no doubt in his
contemporaries' minds that the String Quartet No. 15 ... could be
regarded as a personal requiem,'' Laurel E. Fay writes in her new
biography of the composer. (The work's nearest precedent, in terms
of sheer sustained slowness, may be Haydn's ``Seven Last Words of
Christ,'' where the meaning is less personal.)
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich spoke of the 15th Quartet in typically sardonic and
paradoxical terms. ``Play it so that flies drop dead in midair and
the audience starts leaving the hall from sheer boredom,'' he
suggested once. ``The first movement is a novella, the second a
scherzo, and the finale is an adagio in memory of Beethoven; but
don't let that inhibit you. The music is bright, bright and
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon McBurney takes his cue from the music. ``It is partly
about memory,'' he said of his production. ``Shostakovich
remembering. Others remembering him.'' Voices and music are to be
heard, drawn from hours of archival audio material. The actors will
evidently move within a shifting context of props and projections.
The performance of the Emerson is to emerge seamlessly from the
theatrical segment and carry it through. The players _ Setzer and
Eugene Drucker, violinists; Lawrence Dutton, violist; and David
Finckel, cellist _ enter from the rear, wearing midcentury
Soviet-style suits, and move forward as they play.
</P>
<P>
   At the rehearsal, which started with the second movement,
Finckel was seated on a platform amid the sea of chairs. Setzer and
Dutton were at either side, and Drucker brought up the rear. As the
performance progressed, this circle narrowed, player by player at
varying speeds, until they were all seated on the platform with
Finckel. McBurney interrupted repeatedly to choreograph footsteps
and bow strokes, incorporating suggestions from the actors.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from what was seen or, in the absence of stage lighting
and machinery, otherwise gleaned, the platform will gradually move
to the front of the stage, and the players (including Finckel) will
rise while still playing, seeming to crowd right onto listeners'
consciousness. The lights will be doused at the end, a sure-fire
theatrical effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that's the way it is now,'' Finckel said in
good-natured exasperation. ``It changes every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Gerard McBurney chimed in. ``The very fact that you've
been told of this means that it will all be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon McBurney, who is notoriously leery of letting people see
his work in progress, evidently felt vindicated by expressions of
puzzlement directed at him. ``That's what happens,'' he said. ``You
come here perplexed, you don't know what you're looking at, and you
go away more perplexed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is to give listeners a dynamic experience, to
give people the experience of listening in a different way,'' he
added. ``We have no preconceptions about which way they should hear
it. There are many ways. Avenues will be opened because of a series
of shocks that we give.''
</P>
<P>
   Finckel's little joke aside, the Emerson players profess to be
sold on the project and on the experience of working with McBurney
and the actors, concentrating intensively on body language if not
quite dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience is affecting the way we play the piece and all
pieces,'' Finckel said. ``It gives us a different level of
awareness and makes us conscious of every movement. It's easy to
become self-absorbed in the experience of performing. This helps us
to be aware of crossing the footlights, to realize that people are
affected by everything that happens onstage, the way we hold
ourselves, even the way we hold our bows.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps McBurney should be turned loose on the many orchestral
players who seem unaware that they communicate from the stage with
their every gesture, for ill as well as good. But now, seeming
frayed and preoccupied, he had to rush off and sort through the
makings of the multimedia portion of the show, which he referred to
as ``the mess on my floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, even now,'' he said, ``I get the
feeling that I should just have my brother get up on the stage and
say a few words about the music and leave it at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
