<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MARKET-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI SECURITIES DEALERS SEE NASDAQ AS A THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story, first sent on Feb. 25 and then held, is now
released.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl/lb) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When the chairman of the Nasdaq stock market visited
Israel recently, he was not a traveling salesman drumming up
business. He was more like a potentate inspecting the outer realms
of a fast-expanding empire.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman, Frank G. Zarb, reminded his hosts at every
opportunity, nearly as many shares in Israeli stocks are traded on
his computerized exchange as on the Tel Aviv stock market itself.
There are more companies on Nasdaq from Israel _ 91 _ than from any
other country outside North America, and Nasdaq lists more Israeli
companies than all other foreign bourses combined. And most of them
are not traded in Israel at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital has no passport,'' said Zarb, chairman of the National
Association of Securities Dealers, Nasdaq's owner, during a two-day
visit in mid-February, when he was received like royalty by the
prime minister, the finance minister and high-technology business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli securities dealers worry that high-technology
investment capital does carry a passport _ a U.S. passport. And
they fear that Nasdaq's Israeli portfolio could soon eclipse the
entire Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, both in sheer size and growth
prospects, relegating the local market to sluggish, traditional
state-dominated industries.
</P>
<P>
   The only alternative, they say, is to authorize automatic
listings in Tel Aviv for Israeli companies traded on Nasdaq and
other U.S. markets, a proposal resisted by government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Israeli companies listed abroad can also be listed
here, the Tel Aviv exchange has no future,'' one exchange official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 78 Israeli companies that are now listed only on Nasdaq
include the country's highest-flying technology dynamos, led by
Check Point Software Technologies, a 7-year-old Internet security
specialist, now capitalized at about $14 billion. That is three
times the size of Bezeq, the national telephone company, which has
long been the biggest industrial company traded solely in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching Bezeq in capitalization are several other
Nasdaq-only Israeli companies, like Gilat Satellite Systems, valued
at $3.6 billion, and ECI Telecom, at $3.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly unstoppable trends indicate that Nasdaq's Israeli
companies, worth an aggregate $67 billion at the beginning of
February, will soon surpass the Tel Aviv market's 669 listed
companies, valued collectively at about $75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen older Israeli companies are listed on both Nasdaq and
in Tel Aviv, most notably Teva Pharmaceutical Industries, a generic
drug manufacturer that is the current Israeli market leader, with a
value of about $4.85 billion. But most high-technology start-ups
seeking riches from initial public offerings jump directly to
Nasdaq and do not look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand why they would want to do an IPO on Nasdaq,
considering the valuation they could get, but we also want to see
them listed here,'' said Yair Ogler, chairman of the Tel Aviv Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ogler says Tel Aviv cannot compete with the giant American
exchange, where a billion shares are often traded daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Tel Aviv 100 market index jumped a record 62 percent in
1999. But the Nasdaq 100 soared 102 percent, fueled by upstart
companies with the coveted Internet software offerings and wireless
data technologies in which Israel increasingly specializes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, Nasdaq reports, Israeli companies raised $729
million through initial public offerings there. The most successful
was Partner Communications, Israel's third-place cellular phone
company, which took in $263 million. Since 1995, according to
Nasdaq figures, Israeli companies have collected $1.7 billion
through new Nasdaq stock offerings and another $1.4 billion through
secondary offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli high-tech revolution has combined with an
unprecedented boom on Wall Street to create a feeling among local
market leaders that unless they act soon, they will wake up one day
to find that Israel's stock market has fled to America,'' Guy
Rolnik, a financial commentator for the daily newspaper Haaretz,
noted in his column.
</P>
<P>
   For at least seven years, Ogler says, market executives have
tried to persuade authorities that any Israeli-owned public company
satisfying the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission's reporting
requirements should automatically qualify for a spot in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   But securities regulators here find fault with the SEC's more
lenient rules for foreign companies, which file 20F financial
statements, instead of the more thorough 10K forms demanded of
companies incorporated in the United States. In addition, they
contend, Israel is more stringent than the SEC in reporting trades
by major stockholders, and companies registered only in Tel Aviv
could be penalized by a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Ogler and others respond, is that successful Nasdaq
companies like Check Point say they have no interest in registering
shares in Tel Aviv if it requires preparing different and demanding
financial and legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq would welcome dual listings with the Israeli exchange,
Zarb said here. ``We encourage it,'' he said. ``It will help Tel
Aviv, and in the long run it is good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarb's visit appears to have galvanized the government into
action. Two days after he left, Finance Minister Avraham Shohat
called industry executives and regulators into his office and gave
them two weeks to help his deputies prepare a new proposal for dual
share listings.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Ministry team responded with detailed
recommendations for new rules that they say would make the local
registry of Israeli Nasdaq stocks virtually automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak also spoke in favor of a dual system,
announcing that he and Zarb had ``agreed to establish joint
professional teams to examine ways for the state of Israel and
Nasdaq to cooperate and deepen relations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
