<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-PARTY-HNS &LR;      02-28 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-PARTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
GOP LEADERS ATTACK McCAIN AS HE FORGES NEW GROUND 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Cleveland last week an angry woman shoved a
leaflet at a young man suggesting that John McCain would not
protect the rights of the unborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to do everything they can to stop him _ even
lies,'' the woman, a McCain supporter, told him.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflet bears the image of a baby and criticized McCain, a
senator from Arizona, for approving fetal tissue research in an
effort to portray Texas Gov. George W. Bush as the only
anti-abortion candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This little guy wants you to vote for George W. Bush,'' the
leaflet said, referring to the baby.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain and Bush oppose abortion except in cases of rape or
incest or if the life of the mother is endangered.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflet is an example of some of the tactics being used by
Republican leaders and their allies in special interest groups that
are opposed to campaign-finance reform and other issues McCain has
championed.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflet circulating against McCain in Ohio is the same one
that was distributed by the National Right to Life Committee in
South Carolina to help Bush win the Republican presidential primary
there.
</P>
<P>
   California Assemblywoman Marilyn Brewer told reporters that
party leaders in her state would risk tearing the Republican Party
apart just to deny McCain the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scared to death of change. ... He's forging new
ground. He's changing the party, and a lot of people are afraid of
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said they also ``hate'' the idea that McCain, if elected in
the fall, would use his White House bully pulpit to promote
campaign-finance reform, which would effectively end the unbridled
raising and expenditure of special interest ``soft money,'' which
most often is used to distort the positions of a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is literally reforming and remaking the Republican
Party with his campaign,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the anti-McCain ``rumor mill'' is already working
overtime in California putting out ``negative stuff'' about the
senator's personal life, his voting record and his position on
issues ranging from abortion to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happened in South Carolina, which Bush won by 11
points Feb. 19. Republican and Christian leaders helped Bush by
using everything from anti-abortion leaflets to press releases
portraying McCain as a supporter of gay lifestyles as evidence that
McCain is not a true conservative.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he does not approve of gay lifestyles, but he and
Bush agree on the Clinton administration's ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy on gays in the military. But unlike Bush, McCain has
spoken out about discrimination against gays and has met with the
Log Cabin Republicans, the GOP's largest gay organization. Bush has
refused to meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   Republican televangelist Pat Robertson recorded a telephone
message to thousands accusing McCain of being allied with
``vicious'' anti-Christian bigots; a Republican professor at Bob
Jones University sent out e-mails with an unsubstantiated rumor
about McCain's personal life; and other e-mails criticized McCain
for adopting a Bangladeshi daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign at first denied any connection with the smear
effort. But Sunday, Bush adviser Karl Rove acknowledged that the
Texas governor's campaign had paid for some of Robertson's
telephone calls, which are also being used now in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Rove complained that Bush has also been ``on the receiving end
of all kinds of ugly'' ad campaigns aimed at trashing the
governor's record.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts included one that the McCain campaign at first
denied, then acknowledged, supporting: a phone campaign that
suggested Bush was an anti-Catholic bigot for not repudiating the
policies of Bob Jones University and the prejudices of its founder.
</P>
<P>
   The heat generated by that attack compelled Bush to issue a
blanket apology to Catholics on Sunday for the ``missed
opportunity'' to disassociate himself from the school's attitudes
when he campaigned there earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   And a McCain supporter, South Carolina Speaker Pro Tempore Terry
Haskins, resigned Monday from the Arizona senator's state campaign,
saying he was offended that both Bush and McCain were using
religious beliefs as political props.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outrage expressed by McCain supporters and aides,
Republican pollster Frank Luntz, a close ally of House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and other GOP congressional leaders, said
the negative effort directed at the senator ``is just how politics
is played in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said what Republicans leaders really resent is that McCain
has hit on a successful campaign formula that has alluded them in
the last two congressional races. If they don't adopt ``McCain's
campaign style,'' as he put it, the GOP could end up losing control
of Congress in November.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, he said, is pretty simple. Instead of preaching the
conservative party line, McCain is reaching out to all voters with
a message of tolerance for all views. In many ways, his message is
similar to the ``compassionate'' big tent Republicanism that Bush
preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said McCain's history of bucking his own party on
campaign-finance reform and budget matters has also helped him. But
he said the senator's promise to always tell Americans ``the truth,
no matter what'' is the magnet that's drawing new independent and
crossover Democratic voters to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing, and it's what Americans are looking for,''
said Luntz, who used to promote Bush as the best hope for
Republicans winning the White House again.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz spent the weekend at a Republican leadership retreat,
where he urged House members to adopt McCain's campaign style in
the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I tell Republicans is ... learn from John McCain's style
even if you disagree with him on the issues,'' Luntz said. ``What
he's doing has consequences for the party. If nothing else, we
should learn from his style and the way he reaches out to voters.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aide Mark Salter agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has shown them how to keep their majority in Congress.
It'll be interesting to see whether or not they get the message.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
