desperate for a better life. A few, particularly young people, are
already rich and come to New York, sometimes illegally, to live in
cramped conditions and have what one calls ``an experience.'' By
Rebecca Webber.
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED-DANCERS _ The professional life of the dancer is often
short, and some find the adjustment to the ``outside world''
difficult, devoid of the close-knit communities and support they
receive while on stage. By Alexa Jaworski.
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVIST-NEWSPAPERS _ Some small community papers in New York
City find themselves crossing the line between journalistic
objectivity and community activism, and they are not all
apologetic. By Nathan Hegedus.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-INDIANS _ Cultural centers for Native Americans were set
up in major cities as places newly arrived Indians could gather and
socialize. But increasingly, the centers find themselves counseling
for the same alcoholism and unemployment problems their clients
faced on the reservations. By Sameer Yerawadekar.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-FORECASTERS _ Before retail stores place their orders
for seasonal fashions, they are turning more and more to fashion
forecasters, whose job is to spot the trends that will sell and
avoid the trends that will gather dust on the racks. By Elisabeth
Franck.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-CENSUS _ In the Russian community of Brighton Beach,
Brooklyn, memories of the dreaded Soviet head counters are still
fresh, presenting a particular challenge as the United States
census approaches. So members of the community who are also also
members of government are working to make sure as many emigres are
counted as possible, trying to dispel the sense of unease and
mistrust that the immigrants may feel. By Owen S. Good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
