<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1236 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     02-28 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A FINE FEATHERED FIESTA OF POETIC LICENSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of a San Francisco party last week for 6,500, ``a
magazine of poetry, fiction and pictures of men and women in
sweatshirts,'' said 6,500 pigeons would be released into the
auditorium of New College of California,to ``swoop, coo and eat
pinto beans during a poetry reading.'' Afterward, said the
announcement, a pigeon wrangler would use a giant net to remove the
birds from the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Said editor  &UR; Katie Degentesh &LR; , ``Pigeons and poetry are two
images of the same thing: the desire to move freely in three
dimensions while living in a place with lots of people.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the ``fiction'' aspect of the journal, the
pigeon release didn't exactly occur. Organizers decided, poet
 &UR; Paul LaFarge &LR;  told Personals, that ``Pigeons are already free'' and
``there was nothing poets could do but make them freer.'' They used
a parrot instead, which LaFarge says ``sat freely'' on the finger
of Degentesh, who owns it. ``We didn't release the parrot, but we
did read poetry to it,'' said LaFarge.
</P>
<P>
   Did the parrot enjoy the poetry? ``Who can be sure,'' asked
LaFarge, realizing the limits of human comprehension, ``what a
parrot feels?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMANS CASH IN ON AUSTRIAN POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A German company selling ski trips in the United States ran
full-page newspaper ads recently picturing rightist Austrian leader
 &UR; Jorg Haider &LR; . The ad line, as quoted in Advertising Age: ``For all
those who now don't want to go on a skiing holiday in Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider never gave permission for his photo to be used, and
 &UR; Peter Westenthaler &LR;  of his Austrian Freedom Party, told Ad Age that
the case is in the hands of a party lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The company that placed the ad, tiss.com, told the magazine that
it is still arranging for trips to and from Austria, and the ad was
a ``nod to current events'' rather than an attack on Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SAD TALE OF MOTHERS AND PUBLISHING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Blauner &LR; , who was a professor of sociology at UC Berkeley
for 30 years, sold his first nonacademic book to the famously hot
editor  &UR; Judith Regan &LR; , whose hit parade had included books by
 &UR; Howard Stern &LR; ,  &UR; Rush Limbaugh &LR;  and  &UR; Kathie Lee Gifford &LR; .
ReganBooks, an imprint of HarperCollins, was to publish ``Our
Mothers' Spirits,'' an anthology of writings ``on the death of
mothers and the grief of men,'' in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But that fall,  &UR; Princess Diana  &LR; died, writes Blauner in the
current issue of Brill's Content, so Regan and her minions pushed
up the publication date to November 1, asked him to write a preface
focused on the princess and slapped a picture of Diana and her two
sons on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   The cover ``was a completely vulgar display,'' writes Blauner
and ``one that shamelessly exploited Diana and her sons.'' He tried
to fight it and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine put the book on the ``DiPloitation Watch,'' and
Entertainment Weekly reported that Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders found
it so offensive that they were questioning whether to stock the
book. (They did.)
</P>
<P>
   After what Blauner describes as a ``near-boycott of my book,''
fewer than 3,000 copies sold. Regan, whom Blauner accuses of
masterminding the Di debacle, chose not to comment to Brill's
Content.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ruth Dewson &LR; , owner of Mrs. Dewson's Hats on Fillmore Street,
is throwing a breakfast Friday morning for Republican candidate
 &UR; Alan Keyes &LR; , who will be in San Francisco that day. Dewson's most
famous customer is &UR; Willie Brown &LR; , whom she's staunchly supported in
every campaign, but nonetheless, she admits, ``I'm not a
Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Becky O'Malley  &LR; notes that the only house in her Berkeley
neighborhood with a Yes on 22 sign promoting the ``sanctity of
marriage'' is owned by the Unification Church, which conducts
hundreds of arranged marriages at a time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential campaign probably has more in common with
children's theater than with any other form. Like a bad production
of `Chicken Little,' the candidates run madly while squawking their
negative `sky is falling' message. And as in real life, the
children in the audience behave better than the unbelievable
characters onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; David Thompson &LR;  of Agnes Scott College in Atlanta, analyzing
the presidential campaign as theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
