<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW-     02-28 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A JOYFUL NOISE': HANDEL'S HOLY WORK, BORN OF SCANDAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a great story behind the creation of
Handel's ``Messiah.'' The London premiere of the work was nearly
sabotaged by the vehement opposition of the church, political
conspiracies, dueling divas and a sex scandal. Handel is a great
story unto himself, this stout, imperious, German musical genius
and savvy theatrical entrepreneur who settled in London and had a
long streak of success writing exotic Italian operas for an
enthralled English public, until tastes changed and the composer
panicked.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Tim Slover thought that the true background tale
of this iconic oratorio might make a nifty play. The result is ``A
Joyful Noise,'' which had its premiere late last year at the Lamb's
Players Theater, a San Diego-based performing arts organization.
That production, with one cast change, has come to the Lamb's
Theater on West 44th Street. Though the inherent story is
fascinating, ``A Joyful Noise'' is a contrived play, directed by
Robert Smyth with no apparent consistency of style. The actors
engage in all manner of overly broad physical comedy and
boisterously loud delivery of the text.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfortunate, because Slover has done his homework. Many
facts about the premiere are in dispute, but those that are known
the playwright has utilized faithfully. The situation as presented
is essentially correct.
</P>
<P>
   In 1741, Handel, then 56, was in debt and in crisis. His royal
patron and ardent admirer, Queen Caroline, the wife of King George
II of the House of Hanover, had died in 1737. His Italian operas
were losing popularity. He was suffering from the aftermath of a
partial stroke. In the summer of 1741, Charles Jennens, a wealthy
squire and music connoisseur, who had written the libretto for
Handel's oratorio ``Saul,'' sent him a new script. It had no
characters; it simply told the story of the Messiah using biblical
scripture compiled by Jennens. At first Handel was baffled by it.
But when a performance opportunity arose in Dublin, he composed a
score in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All the characters in Slover's play are based on historical
people, and they are quite a gallery. Susannah Cibber (performed by
Mary Miller), was a singer and actress who had married the
co-manager of the Drury Lane Theater to assist the flagging career
of her brother, the composer Thomas Arne. She was ruined by her
part in an adultery scandal, the salacious details of which were
circulated in a best-selling book at the time, the Starr report of
its day, as Slover has called it. The play includes quotes from the
book and the trial transcript. The Dublin and London premieres of
the ``Messiah'' were Cibber's comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Her nemesis was Kitty Clive (Deborah Gilmour Smyth), a popular
comic actress whose robust soprano voice enticed Handel to use her
in ``The Messiah.'' A humorless, self-inflated Jennens (Paul
Eggington), the German-born King George (Smyth), Mary Pendarves
(Linda Bush), an eccentric art patron loyal to Handel, and other
historical characters are also here, but in preposterous
stereotypes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Slover's aim was to render the story as a compelling comic
drama in the manner of Peter Shaffer's ``Amadeus,'' it doesn't
work. Handel could be imperious and peremptory in his treatment of
singers and servants, but he was a good-humored, self-possessed
fellow and his sallies were apparently of the stinging-wit sort.
Here Handel is portrayed by the portly Tom Stephenson as a
bellowing, manic hothead, a wigged 18th-century John Belushi. What
passes for his wit is pretty lame: ``Madam, I never make sport,''
he tells Kitty Clive, ``I am German.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intimate size of the theater, almost all of the
actors shout their lines hysterically, with the exception of Smyth,
the director, who brings some restraint to the role of King George.
Why didn't he exert some control over his cast? Doren Elias, as
Handel's copyist and treasurer John Christopher Smith, apparently
thinks that screaming his lines in an exaggerated English accent is
terribly British and utterly hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   David Thayer's simple unit set and lighting and Jeanne Reith's
period costumes work well. Excerpts from Handel's music, some
played on tape, some sung by Miller and Smyth, and culminating in a
performance of the ``Hallelujah'' chorus by the entire cast, though
not exactly elegant, provide welcome relief from the aggressive
comedy of the play and the production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1240 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-28 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ((RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. A &UR; LSO MOVING IN
THE ``E'' CATEGORY)) Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of
new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``ROBIN HOOD WAS RIGHT'' &QL; 
By Chuck Collins and Pam Rogers (Norton, $28.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wait! Don't mail those checks yet. Collins and Rogers have
advice about charitable giving that will help you donate your money
with thought and purpose rather than with guilt and self-interest.
Americans gave $109 billion to charity last year, yet one in four
top earners gave nothing, the wealthy gave smaller portions of
their assets than did the poor, and only 13 percent of the money
went to direct public benefit through human service programs (most
went to churches, the arts, elite private universities and
hospitals). Here, the authors attempt to redefine modern
philanthropy in order to affect change _ instead of focusing on the
immediate symptoms of social or economic problems, they want our
dollars to chip away at the CAUSES of those problems. Collins and
Rogers are dedicated, energetic, knowledgeable and frankly, a bit
daunting in their zeal. But you'll learn something if you listen to
them. As Alfre Woodard writes in her preface, ``Robin Hood was
right. And he had a damn good time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``HAWKE'S COVE'' &QL; 
By Susan Wilson (Pocket, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's one for the ``Bridges of Madison County'' crowd, another
novel that attempts to parlay yearning and denial into a bad but
bittersweet bestseller. A young journal-keeping woman named Vangie
retreats to her grandmother's farm in a small coastal town (note
the title) to recover from the death of her baby and to wait for
news of her husband, who is overseas fighting in World War II. It's
not long before a down-on-his-luck stranger named Joe shows up, and
we know what that means. Vangie hires him to work on the farm, they
drink tea and lemonade, they watch each other through lowered
lashes, they swim (``There is,'' Wilson writes, ``a strange
intimacy in swimming . . .''), she spreads ointment on his
blistered hands. When Vangie's husband is declared missing in
action, she and Joe have a hot night together in the hayloft, but
word comes the very next morning that the husband is still alive.
Denial commences. Years pass. Violins play. Their children grow up
and get nosey. Have you been here before? You betcha. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``FOREVER LIESL'' &QL; 
By Charmian Carr (Viking, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were hoping to find some dirt here, but according to Carr,
there was precious little of it on the set of ``The Sound of
Music.'' Until now, the only relief from the unrelenting sweetness
of the film was an anecdote about Christopher Plummer, who played
Baron von Trapp and who allegedly hated the movie so much he called
it ``The Sound of Mucus.'' But Carr, who played the von Trapp
daughter Liesl, debunks that story, saying that Plummer himself
denies it (he did despise the song ``Edelweiss'' and tried to have
it tossed from the film). Mostly, this book is a cheerful report on
a cheerful experience, with some funny moments on the side. When
she attended the Mexican premiere (the film was called ``La Novicia
Rebelde,'' or ``The Rebellious Novice''), the unsuspecting Carr was
taken to a bullfight. The matador dedicated the bull to her, and
she watched in horror as the bull was tormented by the matador and
the matador was then run over by the bull. She visited the matador
in the hospital, as Liesl certainly would have done if she'd been
there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE VISION OF EMMA BLAU'' &QL; 
By Ursula Hegi (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hegi's new novel is a family saga that begins in the early
1900s, when scrappy teenager Stefan Blau comes to America from
Germany (specifically from Burgdorf, which figures into Hegi's
earlier books, ``Stones From the River'' and ``Floating in My
Mother's Palm''), and sets out to make his fortune. After a fire in
the New York restaurant where he works, he leaves the city and goes
to a small town in New Hampshire because a fellow immigrant has
told him it reminded him of Germany. There, Stefan marries twice
and loses both wives to the births of his children before he
returns to Burgdorf to bring back and marry Helene Montag, his
childhood friend and the character through which Hegi explores the
difficult adjustment of the German immigrant. Serving as a backdrop
for the story is the Wasserburg, the grand and glorious apartment
building that Stefan builds, which reflects the fortunes of his
family. Hegi's characterization is superb, part of a story that is
as well-constructed as the Wasserburg itself.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0382 </DOCNO>
