<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-WEISS-COX     02-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-WEISS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recharged Weiss happy to be playing
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ After another season of injuries and
disappointment, Walt Weiss got little relief in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss spent those months in fear that the Braves would acquire
another shortstop _ a younger version with a bigger bat and less of
a propensity to popping muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves traded for Jose Hernandez in July after Weiss
struggled to return from a quadriceps pull. The Braves didn't
re-sign Hernandez after the season, but they were linked to
Toronto's Alex Gonzalez, and the organization was excited about
19-year-old prospect Rafael Furcal.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the December deal for Reggie Sanders and Quilvio Veras
to revamp the top of the order, and Weiss' job appeared to be safe
again. Weiss still isn't completely convinced, but he is recharged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when the Braves didn't sign Jose Hernandez back, I still
wasn't sure the Braves had lost confidence in me or not,'' Weiss
said. ``I still don't know. Given my injuries the last two years,
I'm sure it's a concern, and justifiably so. But at the same time,
I feel real good about this year. There's no doubt in my mind I can
go out and perform and be a vital part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss was hitting .279 and riding a 13-game hitting streak when
he pulled his quadriceps May 26. He took a week off and tried to
come back, but three games later he went on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't return to the lineup until July 1, and by then his
swing felt foreign. He finished the year hitting .226, his worst
average since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, as bad as it was, I think if I hadn't missed that
time, I don't think it would have been an issue, the shortstop
position,'' Weiss said. ``When I came back after a month, I
struggled to find it again. And then after three weeks, they
brought Jose in. I didn't have any opportunity to salvage the
season. I'm not complaining, or blaming Bobby (Cox). With Javy
Lopez going down and Cat (Andres Galarraga) not playing, we needed
some more punch offensively. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, 36, knows he can do little about injuries, so he's doing
his best to put them in the back of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm in as good a shape as anybody, regardless of age,
because of what I do in the winter,'' he said. ``The only thing
that will make the questions subside is me going out and
performing. When you're younger, people are waiting for you to play
well. When you're older, they're waiting for you to play poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss took consolation in the postseason when he not only earned
his starting job back but made the defensive play of October by
stabbing a grounder to save the Braves in a bases-loaded situation
in a Division Series win over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been in the middle of whatever's going on with the
club,'' Weiss said. ``Last year in the second half, I wasn't part
of much. . . . The postseason meant a lot to me, because all of a
sudden I was a big part of some real big games. Without the
postseason, last year would have been awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss takes some comfort in returning to the eighth spot in the
order, which is much more natural to him than hitting leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play defense,'' Weiss said, ``sneak back into the eighth
spot and just kind of ride on everyone else's back (offensively).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
