<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-AUBURN-PORTER-COX     02-28 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN-PORTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn star admits taking agent's money
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auburn basketball star Chris Porter told school and SEC
officials that he took slightly more than $2,000 from a possible
agent in order to keep his mother from being evicted from her home.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the admissionwill save the college career of the senior
forward has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, a candidate for national player of the year, was
declared ineligible before Sunday's game at Florida. Auburn
officials had learned that Porter had accepted money from an agent
or the representative of an agent.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Gainesville, Fla., on Saturday night but immediately
was flown home on an Auburn University jet when coaches were
informed of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn coach Cliff Ellis confirmed Monday that Porter had
accepted the money and that the school would appeal to the NCAA to
have him reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What transpired is there was a transaction that took place;
Chris has admitted to that,'' Ellis said on the SEC's weekly
conference call of coaches. ``We are now going through it to make
sure all the pieces of the puzzle fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that Porter will not be available for Wednesday
night's big SEC game with LSU in Auburn. But if Porter repays the
money, school officials hope that Porter could be reinstated before
next week's SEC Tournament in Atlanta or the beginning of the NCAA
Tournament on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn lost to Florida on Sunday and now is 21-6, 9-5 in the
SEC. The Tigers are ranked 19th by the Associated Press and 13th in
the USA Today/ESPN coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   Porter missed Thursday's practice to visit his mother, Emily,
who lives in Abbeville, Ala., approximately 100 miles from Auburn.
Apparently, it was at that time that Porter received the money to
help his mother with some financial problems. By Saturday, Auburn
officials had heard about it and called Porter home from
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Porter told Auburn and SEC officials that he did not know the
man who provided the money was an agent or the representative of an
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Porter was projected to go in the first-round of the NBA draft
when he decided to return to Auburn and play his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   An obviously frustrated Ellis insisted that Porter should be
given the benefit of the doubt, given his circumstances and his
willlingness to come back to school this season and pass on the
NBA's millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he goes and tells the truth, which I believe he has,''
Ellis said, ``then let's move as smartly as possible, as wisely as
possible, and let him come back and play the game that he decided a
year ago to come back to.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-EVANDER-COX     02-28 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield extends quest to be undisputed champ
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After considerable prayer and a commitment to a
career-long ambition, former heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield
is extending his 14-year professional boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't over yet,'' the 36-year-old Holyfield gleefully
proclaimed Monday. Holyfield, who lost the undisputed heavyweight
championship to Lennox Lewis in November, said he will fight again
May 20. Neither the opponent nor the site has been agreed to, but
Holyfield probably will fight one of four contenders _ Henry
Akinwande, David Tua, John Ruiz or Ray Mercer. The place probably
will be Las Vegas or New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is that I didn't want to do it out of ego,''
Holyfield said. ``There is no reason more than praying about it and
realizing I can still do it. My body and health are good.
Everything just lines up right.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's attorney, Jim Thomas, outlined a scenario that could
grant his client and friend a championship fight: The WBA title
would be vacant if Lewis is stripped of that belt for fighting
Michael Grant instead of the mandatory bout against No. 1-ranked
Akinwande. Then, the No. 2-ranked Holyfield could return to meet
Akinwande for the chance to become the only heavyweight in history
to win four titles.
</P>
<P>
   That route would expedite his plan. The quest to retire as the
undisputed champion _ and his belief that he still possesses the
skills and durability to regain the title belts now belonging to
Lewis _ overrides the expected public outcry that Holyfield should
quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people are going to say; I've heard people say I
should retire since '92,'' he said. ``That doesn't bother me at
all. I have to do what I want to do, not what anyone else wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he is looking at a larger picture than what
continuing his career will do for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will inspire people not to quit,'' he insisted. ``If you
believe you can still accomplish what you want, go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing the close decision in the rematch with Lewis,
Holyfield wanted to announce that night that he would fight again.
``I felt like saying, `Yeah, I want to do it,' because I felt I did
well, that I won the fight. But I didn't want to come off as crying
about the decision,'' he said. ``I needed to show dignity and let
Lennox have his day. And I didn't want it to be so quick that it
seems like an ego thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big reason is that I set a goal to be the undisputed
heavyweight champion,'' Holyfield said. ``If I had won, I would
have gone around the country and world putting on exhibitions to
show loyalty to the fans. I lost, but I didn't lose sight of the
goal. I've always had to overcome something. Now, I've got to
overcome something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
