<SLUG> BC-BREASTRECONSTRUCTION-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBUILDING THE BREAST WITH SKIN-SPARING MASTECTOMIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a mammogram and biopsy identified two malignant tumors in
her right breast a year and a half ago, all Carolyn Walls-Purvis
wanted was to get them out _ fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cut from my collarbone to my waist in almost a V. The
scar was very big, very ugly. They took out all the muscle and
lymph nodes, and the skin was stretched and pulled tight and ugly.
With chemotherapy and radiation, it was even more drawn,'' she
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Before she finished chemo, her oncologist found a lump in her
other breast. Walls-Purvis was horrified.
</P>
<P>
   Still in shock, she was referred by her Denison doctors to Fort
Worth for a second mastectomy and immediate reconstruction on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Her left breast was removed through a ``keyhole'' incision,
using a new skin-sparing surgical technique, on May 6, 1999,
exactly a year after the first surgery, a modified radical
mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Both breasts were reconstructed using her own abdominal tissue
in what is known as a TRAM flap reconstruction (named for the
transverse abdominal myocutaneous muscle).
</P>
<P>
   What a difference for Walls-Purvis, 52.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the way it looks is like I never had any breast surgery,''
she says. ``My `before' pictures of the right side are really,
really bad. Now it looks almost as good as the other. They both
look and seem so natural. They did within weeks, and it's all my
own tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed this right one looks so good. There's just a slight
hairline scar at the top, and the left one never had a scar because
the surgeon here left all the skin so it could be used as a pocket.
It just looks like my normal breast. They didn't keep the nipple
but built complete new ones for both sides out of little skin tabs
they made. The nipples were done in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls-Purvis says she recently purchased a ``regular swimsuit''
so she could start using her hot tub again. Her husband, Steve,
says he has to look twice to remind himself she has had a
mastectomy, even without a swimsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can tell. She looks good, and the cancer is gone. She's
healthy again. That's what's important,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, a tummy bulge as well as scars from two previous
C-sections and a hysterectomy were eliminated with reconstruction,
and Walls-Purvis has a perfect new navel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle, just a miracle,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mastectomies today are increasingly done with reconstruction in
mind. Surgeons save the breast skin as a form, filling it
immediately with living tissue from the patient's abdomen. A
follow-up surgery reconstructs a nipple. The result is a
natural-looking breast.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the reconstructions we are doing now are designed to give
the patient the look of her original breast and quite possibly
improve on it,'' says Dr. Shujaat Khan, the Fort Worth plastic
surgeon who reconstructed Walls-Purvis' breasts.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases today, that means removing the tumor through a
keyhole incision and using a flap of the patient's own abdominal
tissue _ skin, muscle and blood vessels _ to reconstruct the breast
mound immediately. Tissue from the back can also be used in
reconstructing smaller breasts or when abdominal scars are a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, when a patient was evaluated for breast
reconstruction, the goal was to provide a mound so she could fill
her clothes and not have to use an external prosthesis that slips
and slides,'' says Dr. Brian Burns, a Plano plastic surgeon who
specializes in breast reconstruction at St. Paul Medical Center in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when we see someone for breast reconstruction, our goal
is to make her look better after surgery than she did before she
knew she needed a mastectomy,'' says Burns. ``If you can work with
the general surgeon to save as much of the skin as safely possible,
results are amazingly good. The more skin they can leave us, the
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skin-sparing surgical techniques are the best thing that's
happened in the last couple of years,'' Burns says.
</P>
<P>
   The surgical method allows a modified radical mastectomy through
a circular cut around the nipple and a straight incision just to
the edge of the breast to remove lymph nodes or a simple circular
incision and separate small incision under the arm to remove the
nodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It totally changes the concept of how natural reconstruction
can look,'' Khan says.
</P>
<P>
   Skin-sparing surgery and a new procedure to enhance blood
circulation to the abdominal muscle before it is used in
reconstruction are the latest improvements in the ever-evolving art
of breast reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is not enough tissue to (make the breasts) match, you
can add a tissue expander or an implant, but 99 percent of the time
with an abdominal flap and skin-conserving mastectomy, there is no
need for an implant. We can reconstruct the breast entirely from
abdominal fat,'' says Khan, who has now done about 1,000
reconstructions with abdominal flaps immediately following
mastectomies.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it is an extremely gratifying surgery.'' he says.
``We are now down to doing them in less than two hours, and
patients seldom need a transfusion. When reconstruction is done
with autologous (the patient's own) tissue, there is no difficulty
with radiation or chemotherapy following surgery, and no problems
with finding any future recurrence of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new procedure to enhance circulation, almost anyone is
a good candidate for reconstruction, Khan says.
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetic advances in breast reconstruction are made
possible by earlier diagnosis, says Dr. John Freese, a surgical
oncologist who has performed many mastectomies during his 36 years
of practice in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the concept of radical mastectomy was developed in the
1890s, the breast, muscles, lymph nodes and most of the skin were
all taken, and a skin graft was almost always required just to
cover the surgical site,'' Freese says. ``But for many years, they
were dealing with advanced tumors, usually so advanced they had
broken through the skin. That's the only way they knew they were
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, for 30 or 40 years, we did surgery as soon as we could
feel the tumor. Now we remove them as soon as they show up on
mammograms _ usually they are 1/4 to 1/2 inches in diameter, and
often they are too small to feel,'' Freese points out.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, surgeons can leave most of the skin. The
original envelope of the breast is there, so any difficulties with
placement or size or position of the nipple are resolved. The
nipple is taken because milk ducts run up in the nipple and can
hide tumor tissue, but almost all the rest of the breast skin is
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next big step now is prevention,'' says Freese, who has
been performing about 100 mastectomies a year. ``We have got to
find ways to prevent breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW WITH IMPLANTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The silicone scare of the '90s inspired doctors to find better
ways to use a patient's own (autologous) tissue for breast
reconstruction and prompted scientists to look for better materials
for breast augmentation.
</P>
<P>
   Most breast cancer patients now are choosing immediate
reconstruction with a football-shaped wedge of tissue from their
own abdomens.
</P>
<P>
   But other types of implants are still an option for mastectomy
patients _ and for the increasing numbers of women who opt for
breast-enlargement surgery. In the past couple of years, the number
of women undergoing breast enlargement surgery has risen about 25
percent, according to the American Society for Aesthetic Plastic
Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical studies before and since the scare show silicone breast
implants are, in fact, safe. Last fall, they were cleared by a
special panel of scientists appointed by the federal judge
overseeing cases nationwide. In 1998, after an independent review
of the research on silicone breast implants, a 12-member National
Science Panel appointed by the U.S. Institute of Medicine found no
convincing evidence of any association between implants and
disease, including autoimmune diseases and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have learned from all this is that implants have a
shelf life,'' says Dr. Shujaat Khan, a Fort Worth plastic surgeon
who specializes in breast reconstruction. ``We should be checking
them (all implants) at least every five years to be sure they are
in good condition,'' not leaking or disintegrating.
</P>
<P>
   Now a lot more autologous tissue is being used for
reconstruction, but women who choose implants for reconstruction
want silicone, and they have been among the few who could get
silicone under Food and Drug Administration restrictions that still
allow the silicone implants only for breast reconstruction, implant
replacement and treatment of severe sagging.
</P>
<P>
   Saline-filled breast implants have been the mainstay of breast
augmentation procedures since the FDA's 1992 ban on silicone
gel-filled implants.
</P>
<P>
   But, for mastectomy patients, silicone gel gives a much more
natural look if an implant is needed, says Linda S. Cornelison, a
Fort Worth breast cancer survivor and health educator. ``With
almost no loose breast tissue, saline doesn't work nearly as well
for reconstruction as it does for augmentation when the original
tissue is all still there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicone gel has regained popularity primarily because it
produces the most natural-feeling breast,'' says Dr. Scott Spear,
author of an article on implants in the October issue of
``Aesthetic Surgery Journal.'' ``With scientific studies supporting
its safety, a number of manufacturers may decide to take the steps
defined by the FDA as necessary for the return of silicone
gel-filled implants to non-restricted use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, new materials are being tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, they are using a wonderful new gel implant that has
the consistency of a solid Jell-O. It is solid enough that you can
slice it in two with a knife and it doesn't flow. It moves, very
lifelike. It jiggles,'' says Khan.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, almost 40,000 of the cohesive silicone gel
devices that hold their shape have been implanted.
</P>
<P>
   Another type of implant that is expected to enter the U.S.
regulatory process by the end of this year is a polyvinylpyrolidone
(PVP) device, which was originally introduced in the late 1980s,
then reformulated for the '90s. Like silicone, PVP has a long
history of medical applications. Its new hydrogel formulation for
breast implants has been tested and used in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   FDA approval of both the cohesive gel and the PVP implants is
expected within the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolyn Poirot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
