<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-28 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE ILLEGALLY GAGS ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Information received from a Freedom of Information Act request
is presumed to be in the public domain _ or the federal government
would not have released it. That's basic law. But a judge in New
Mexico inexplicably sees it differently. He has stopped an
environmental group from sharing information with the public that
it gained from an FOIA request.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1998, Forest Guardians, an environmental group based in
Santa Fe, N.M., filed an FOIA request with the U.S. Forest Service
seeking information regarding banks that hold grazing permits on
public lands administered by the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't widely known that numerous banks in the West hold USFS
grazing permits on loans made to ranchers under the Forest
Service's escrow-waiver program.
</P>
<P>
   When a rancher defaults on one of these loans, the bank sells
the grazing permits along with the private property that was the
base for the permits and the loan. The grazing permits are, in
every sense, treated as property by these banks _ despite federal
appeals court rulings that a permittee has no legitimate claim of
entitlement to a grazing permit.
</P>
<P>
   If a rancher cannot treat his grazing permits as property, then
neither can a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Some ranchers in New Mexico, Utah, Colorado, Wyoming and Montana
hold USFS grazing permits on public-land acreage that far exceeds
their private property base. A rancher may own 1,000 acres and have
grazing permits on 80,000 adjacent acres. Naturally, the rancher's
grazing permits enhance the value of his private property.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Guardians wants to make any information concerning the
use of USFS grazing permits as loan collateral available to the
public _ the banks involved, the total amount of loans made on
grazing permits, the number of permittees, permits and acreage
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service complied with a portion of the Forest
Guardians' FOIA request. However, the agency blacked out some
information that was pertinent to the request. After negotiations
came to a standstill in June 1999, the Forest Guardians filed a
lawsuit in federal court to get that missing information.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Forest Service and Forest Guardians came to an
tentative agreement to provide that information.
</P>
<P>
   However, that same month before the lawsuit could be resolved, a
group of ranchers and banks filed a motion to intervene in the
case. They argued that the information released to Forest Guardians
should not be made public, that making such information public
violates the federal Privacy Act. They filed a motion to that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. District Judge for the District of New Mexico Edwin
L. Mechem has allowed the ranchers and bankers to gag the Forest
Guardians since December. The judge has stalled and stalled on the
ranchers' and bankers' request for a temporary order to forbid the
distribution of the information about the widespread use of escrow
waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The judge is stalling for good reason. Legally, the judge cannot
prohibit the distribution of information gained through an FOIA
request.
</P>
<P>
   In a response to the motion by the ranchers and bankers, the
U.S. attorney's office in Albuquerque told the court it had no
legal authority to grant such a motion and ``it should be denied
out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom of Information Act only allows a federal court to
prohibit a federal agency from withholding agency records and to
order the release of records improperly withheld. The act does not
provide the court with any legal basis to stop the distribution of
information gained through an FOIA request.
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason that any information released under an FOIA
request is public information. That's why the government was forced
to release it under the Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   And the Privacy Act only authorizes a civil action against an
agency improperly releasing records. The act does not authorize an
action against those who received those records.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the information that the Forest Guardians have thus
far been prohibited from distributing to the public is available to
the public in every county courthouse in the West. A county
courthouse records deeds, loans and promissory notes on properties
within the county. And that information is available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the judge continues to stall on Forest Guardians'
right to distribute the information on USFS grazing permits used as
loan collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Mechem set a possible date for hearing arguments in May, but
that will be set further back because of a new filing by the cattle
and banking industries. In other words, the judge has put into
place a de facto illegal injunction that indefinitely prohibits
disseminating information on the USFS escrow-waiver program.
</P>
<P>
   Mechem, the former governor of New Mexico back in the 1950s,
shames himself by his actions in this case, and shames the robes he
wears as a federal judge. However protective he may feel about the
ranching industry, Mechem cannot legally gag the Forest Guardians.
The information they received from the Forest Service belongs to
the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
