<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-LEFTY-DRIESELL-COX     02-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEFTY-DRIESELL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Title would have Driesell basking in distinction
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Bradleyc. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Lyndon Johnson was president. The inaugural Super Bowl
was 10 months away. The transplanted Braves were about to open in
the new Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium. It was 1966, and Lefty
Driesell was coaching in his first NCAA Tournament. Or as the
proceedings were then known, the nationals.
</P>
<P>
   His Davidson team was playing Syracuse, which was headed by a
guard who would become the 1967 NBA rookie of the year. Driesell
tried to inspire Dick Snyder, his own fine guard, by taping
Snyder's picture alongside Dave Bing's. The coach added this
message: ``Will the real All-American please stand up?''
</P>
<P>
   Driesell smiles wryly. ``Bing stood up,'' he says. ``Snyder
wasn't bad, but Bing was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse would win 94-78. Near the end, an assistant coach
wondered if Davidson should call a timeout. ``No,'' Driesell
remembers saying. ``I want to get out of here as fast as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Driesell coaches Georgia State. On Saturday his Panthers
tied for the Trans America Athletic Conference regular-season
championship. If they win the TAAC Tournament this weekend,
Driesell will find himself swimming in distinctions. He will
become:
</P>
<P>
   _ The second coach to take four different schools to the NCAA
Tournament, Eddie Sutton being the first. ``And Eddie's been a lot
better places than I have,'' Driesell says.
</P>
<P>
   _The first coach to grace the NCAA Tournament in five different
decades, having taken Davidson in the '60s, Maryland in the '70s
and '80s and James Madison in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   _The coach with the longest span between his first and latest
NCAA appearances. Lou Henson holds the mark at 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't bother with that (statistical) stuff,'' Driesell says.
``I just want to go for the players. None of them has been to the
NCAA.''
</P>
<P>
   Driesell is 68, a grandfather eight times over. Yet here he is,
in his third season on the unassuming Concrete Campus, still
craving after all these years. Referring to the TAAC Tournament, a
visitor says, ``If you win . . . .'' Driesell flares. ``You mean,
`When we win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, who lost their first six games, are 16-11. They
will be seeded No. 2 in Jacksonville, and they already have beaten
top-seeded Troy State. It could happen. Thirty-four years after
being torched by Dave Bing, the Lefthander could be part of March
Madness again. ``It's a lot different now,'' he says. ``It's almost
gotten too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1966, nobody watched the selection show on CBS. No such
program existed. ``My AD would call me,'' Driesell says, ``and tell
me who we were playing.'' Not until 1969 would the tournament be
carried by a major network. The whole affair was so low-key that,
on the day before the 1970 championship game, Sports Illustrated
reported that ``Lefty Driesell of the host University of Maryland,
whose ambition it is to make his school `the UCLA of the East' . .
. upstaged the team workouts (by announcing) the signing of two New
York City high school stars.''
</P>
<P>
   An SI cover featuring Len Elmore, one of those New Yorkers, sits
on a shelf in Driesell's windowless office. The place could serve
as a museum. A framed collage commemorates Maryland's 1986 victory
in the Dean Dome. A black-and-white photo shows Driesell aloft on a
sea of shoulders after a 1971 upset of No. 2 South Carolina. A
newspaper clipping, mounted and yellowed, recalls Driesell's first
collegiate victory. The date was Dec. 2, 1960. The opponent was
Wake Forest. The Demon Deacons' leading scorer, with 17 points, was
Billy Packer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep saying I'll quit coaching when I start losing,''
Driesell says. ``When we were 0-6, I thought this might be my year.
But it's getting to be fun again. I want to get Georgia State
going. I think this can be a real good basketball school, like
Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   He is wearing his 1984 ACC championship ring, which he seldom
does. He can't decide whether to show it to his players. ``It might
fire them up,'' he says, ``but you've got to be careful. I don't
know whether you should act like we're playing for all the marbles
or just Win No. 17.''
</P>
<P>
   And motivational ploys, the Lefthander knows, can fizzle. He
recalls Dave Bing, who was such a focal point that the Davidson
coach was oblivious to all else. Recently Driesell played golf with
Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim. The 1966 NCAA Tournament was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in that game,'' Boeheim said. ``I scored 16 points.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember Bing,'' Driesell said. ``I don't remember
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it was a while ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
