<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDIA-TECH-WORKERS-2T     02-28 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-TECH-WORKERS-2TAKES(1070)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S BEST BRAINS ARE RETURNING WITH MONEY AND HIGH HOPES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ During the past generation, tens of thousands of
Indian engineers left home for America and many got rich _ some
fabulously rich _ in the high technology boom. Along the way, they
became symbols of a brain drain that scholars believed was sucking
the best and brightest minds out of Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   But an increasing though still modest number of India's biggest
American success stories, whose lives are now firmly rooted in the
United States, are beginning to come home to India, too, and not
just to visit relatives, but to start companies, invest their
capital and indulge their philanthropic instincts. Some say they
should no longer be seen as proof of the brain drain, but as signs
of a brain trust _ a view economists say is still overly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in an era when airplanes, telephones, e-mail and fax
machines have transformed the lives of prosperous immigrants,
economists say that the linear idea of a one-way brain drain is
giving way to a different paradigm of brains that circulate between
native and adopted countries.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern is now emerging in India, which watched as perhaps
25,000 of its top graduates since the late 1960s moved to the
United States. In the years when the technology explosion hit
America, these Indians emerged as major players and now run more
than 750 technology companies in California's Silicon Valley alone.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who got away was Kanwal S. Rekhi, 54, who now
periodically comes back for what he calls his ``missionary work in
India.'' He said he went to America so his brain wouldn't go down
the drain in socialist India, made $300 million as an entrepreneur,
executive and private investor in Silicon Valley and retired five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the request of the prime minister's office in an India
that is more market driven, he is among those trying to raise $1
billion for the six Indian Institutes of Technology, elite public
universities here known as IITs, which produced the thousands of
graduates who left for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants say they are returning now because many of them
have succeeded as entrepreneurs and have money to spare, because
there are economic opportunities in the increasingly open Indian
economy and because the Hindu nationalist-led government that has
been in power since 1998 is more open to their participation in the
country's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   It has, for example, challenged them to raise the billion
dollars for the IITs that educated them at India's expense before
they went to the United States, where they enriched the American
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're credible, successful people,'' Rekhi said. ``Many of us
are worth hundreds of millions of dollars. We're available to the
Indian government and we provide a bridge to the United States. I
do fund-raisers at my house for congressmen all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of these to-and-fro millionaires abound.
</P>
<P>
   There's Desh Deshpande, 49, philanthropist. His high technology
telecommunications company, Sycamore Networks, was listed on the
Nasdaq in October. His net worth has since skyrocketed to $4
billion to $6 billion _ depending, he said, on the stock market and
which day the money gets counted. He and his wife plan to give $100
million over 20 years to their alma mater, IIT in Madras.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that emotional tie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pradeep Singh, 42, a graduate of IIT, New Delhi, said his
``lottery ticket came through'' during 8 years as  manager earning
stock options at Microsoft. He quit in the mid-1990s to start his
own company, Aditi, that provides customer service via e-mail from
India for corporations abroad. He now has two companies, lives 4
months a year in Bangalore, 8 months in Seattle, and employs 600
people _ 350 of them in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad died recently,'' he said. ``He was proud of what I did
overseas, but that was nothing like what he felt about what I've
done here. He clipped all the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's Rakesh Mathur, 43, a graduate of IIT, Bombay. He and
three other Indians founded the Silicon Valley company, Junglee.com
_ the original comparison shopping engine on the Web. The company
was sold in 1998 to Amazon.com in a stock deal that has made Mathur
$90 million richer.
</P>
<P>
   He still has homes in Mountain View, Calif. and Seattle, but
last year he also bought one in Pune. He has given $1 million to
his alma mater and started a new company, Purpleyogi.com, with
offices in Bangalore and Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Bombay, he ventured back to the 500-acre
IIT campus here, driving down a grand main road lined by towering
bottle palms and past the new Kanwal Rekhi School of Information
Technology now under construction, named for the American-made
Indian philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   For Mathur, who has the casual style of a Californian, it was a
double homecoming. He went to college here and grew up on the
campus because his father was a professor. He was back to visit a
troika of ambitious IIT students who are determined to get rich off
the Internet _ and who had succeeded in making him their mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Over 10-cent cups of coffee at a little outdoor cafe on campus,
these young men had hatched their ideas, then pursued Mathur
whenever he visited the campus and skipped a week of classes once
to meet with him when he was in Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're different than our classmates because we realized
there's opportunity here in India,'' said Kashyap Deorah, 20.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates of the IITs _ which are far harder to get into than
Harvard _ have formed a transcontinental good-old-boy network (most
of the students are still male) that connects Bombay, Bangalore and
Hyderabad to Silicon Valley, Seattle and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The IITs themselves are among the few institutions in India that
are still seen as meritocracies, unsullied by political influence.
Admission is based solely on a grueling national entrance exam.
Last year, of the 98,000 students who took it, only 3,000 won
admission.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States continues to exert a magnetic pull on
Indian students and other Indian professionals. Last year, a third
of the 115,000 visas the United States issued to skilled workers
went to Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I be frank?'' asked Suman Kar, a 20-year-old senior at IIT
Bombay, as he explained why he has accepted a job in Silicon
Valley. ``It's the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kar said his new job will pay about $60,000 a year, 7 times what
he would have earned here.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   IIT graduates have been the most sought after Indians in Silicon
Valley _ and Indians there have done very well, indeed. AnnaLee
Saxenian, an economist at Berkeley, documented in an analysis of a
Dun &AMP; Bradstreet database that 750 companies there are run by
Indians. Those companies produce more than $3.5 billion in sales
and employ more than 16,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   And as Indians have risen to positions of influence in corporate
suites throughout the American economy, they have played a crucial
role in giving credibility to business people based in India who
are selling software services to U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Indian guy comes knocking at your door, selling
something, the first thought on your mind isn't snakes and
elephants,'' said Singh, formerly of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Exports of software from India have been growing by more than 50
percent a year in the 1990s as businesses here have found a niche
in employing high-skilled, low-wage computer engineers in India to
write computer code for businesses abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The industry now employs 280,000 people and is expected to have
$4 billion in revenues this year, the majority from sales to
American companies, according to the New Delhi-based National
Association of Software and Service Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Saxenian had once thought that few of them would take their
money or themselves back to India, but a recent visit to Bangalore
changed her view.
</P>
<P>
   She ran into an Indian entrepreneur from the valley, Sanjay
Anandaram, and learned that he had returned to help start a new
company that will develop and finance Indian technology ventures _
and he was not exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is happening fast,'' she said. ``At every level, you
see personal and business connections to India that were not there
even two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The declining financial situation of the IITs is one of the
factors drawing them back. In 1993, the government cut its funding
of the IITs and for the first time allowed individuals to donate
money directly to the institutes. The alumni in the United States
have given most of the millions raised so far for the IIT in
Bombay. The Indus Entrepreneurs, a group founded by Indians in
Silicon Valley, has been instrumental in raising the money.
</P>
<P>
   Economists who had once seen the brain drain as harmful, now see
the diaspora it has spawned as a source of strength to developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emigres often work as a Trojan horse, lobbying on your
behalf,'' said a Columbia University economics professor, Jagdish
Bhagwati, himself a native of India. ``They use external
opportunities to succeed prodigiously in different occupations. And
they can bring their skills and funds home to assist the country in
its economic take-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathur, the Web entrepreneur, is such a person. He wants to do
something for India, he said, because it interests him.
</P>
<P>
   The three IIT students he advises came up with an idea that
caught his imagination. On his recent visit, they formally
presented their proposal for a Web site called iportia.com. _ the
contents were still a trade secret _ in a conference room in a
downtown Bombay hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Mathur and another prominent IIT graduate, Nandan M. Nilekani,
chief operating officer of Infosys Technologies, and Deepak B.
Phatak, head of the computer science department at the IIT in
Bombay, listened attentively.
</P>
<P>
   When the students finished, the older men asked them to leave
the room, then considered whether to make this the university's
first attempt to incubate a student business that it would partly
own.
</P>
<P>
   The students stood outside waiting nervously. Would Mathur put
up the $250,000 on the university's behalf that would let them make
their dream real?
</P>
<P>
   After a half hour, the students were summoned back. The
grown-ups had decided that the young men had a great idea so simple
it could be expressed in five words, yet so sophisticated that it
would generate an entire Web world.
</P>
<P>
   The grinning students took turns shaking hands with Mathur, who
turned to the IIT professor, and exclaimed, ``Phatak, Sahib, they
have to make at least $100 million for you!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
