<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1276 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-VACCINE-BOS &LR;      02-28 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS SHRINK TUMORS USING VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   German researchers have dramatically shrunk advanced tumors in
some kidney cancer patients using a vaccine strategy developed at
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute &UR;  &LR; in Boston. Institute scientists say
they are launching similar trials here.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, which spurred the patients' immune systems to
attack their tumors, eliminated cancers that had spread to other
organs in 4 of 17 patients, says a report being published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other patients had partial shrinkage of their cancers and in
another patient, some cancerous lesions shrank while others
continued to progress.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the potent anti-cancer action of the vaccine caused
no serious adverse effects, says the report Nature Medicine. The
lead author is Dr. Alexander Kugler, a urological surgeon at the
University of Gottingen.
</P>
<P>
   Kugler said in an interview that a total of 23 patients have now
been treated (six of them since the report was written) and that
the cancer has been eliminated in five. Those patient have gone as
long as 20 months without their cancer returning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the results, DFCI researchers have already launched a
trial of the vaccine in breast cancer, another for malignant
melanoma and are planning one for kidney cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive results are a shot in the arm for cancer
vaccines, which, unlike those that prevent infectious diseases, are
targeted at an existing cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Many cancer vaccines are under development and all have the same
goal: to make the cancer cells more ``visible'' to the body's
immune system, and to stir up a strong immune response against the
tumor. But few vaccine candidates have thus far lived up to their
promising early results.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the small number of patients, the impressive outcomes
will need confirmation in larger studies before the vaccine can be
considered a promising candidate for clinical use, said the
researchers from The University of Gottingen and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Already, however, a Boston-area biotech company has obtained an
option to license the method exclusively from DFCI. A spokeswoman
for Genzyme Molecular Oncology of Framingham said the company is
sponsoring a trial of the vaccine in breast cancer at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The reported experiments were the first human trials of the
vaccine approach, which was developed in the laboratory of Dr.
Donald Kufe at DFCI and tested in animals in 1997. Kufe, in a
commentary published along with the Nature Medicine report, said
that if the effectiveness of the vaccine is confirmed, it could
mean an ``unprecedented advance'' in treating life-threatening
cancers that have spread beyond their original site.
</P>
<P>
   To make the vaccine, researchers surgically removed the
patients' kidney tumors and combined some of those cells with
immune cells extracted from blood donors. The immune cells, called
dendritic cells, were fused with the tumor cells by passing an
electric current through them.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a ``hybrid'' immune cell that could recognize the
patient's specific tumor cells when injected back into the body.
The hybrid vaccine cells strongly stimulated the patient's immune
defenses to seek out and break apart the cancer cells wherever they
had traveled inside the body.
</P>
<P>
   One reason previous vaccines have failed is that scientists
couldn't find identifying structures, or antigens, on the surface
of cancer cells so that the immune system could recognize them as
the enemy. Instead of trying to identify what antigens marked the
kidney cancer cells, the scientists simply fused the entire cell
with the immune system cell, so that the cancer cell ``taught'' the
immune cells how to identify the cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the German research, Dr. David Berd, a cancer
vaccine researcher at Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia
called it ``a very nice piece of work and I find it extremely
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that it confirms his belief that the most promising
cancer vaccines are those tailored to each patient by using cells
from his or her own cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this vaccine is better than many others under
development can't be said at this point, added Berd, who said he
had recently reviewed the literature on cancer vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of vaccines that seem to produce regression of
metastases (cancers that have spread) in some percentage of
patients in small trials,'' said the researcher in an interview,
but few of them have been validated in larger studies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unsolved questions facing Kufe and the German
researchers is why the vaccine proved so potent in some patients
yet achieved no results in other patients. Kufe said that issue is
being investigated. ``We can make the vaccines better,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
