<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GRISHAM-NOVELS-ART-2T     02-28 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRISHAM-NOVELS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRISHAM LEGAL THRILLERS OBEY LAWS OF COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT14, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to business, John Grisham provides no
suspense. Each February he turns out a novel with a first printing
of 2.8 million copies. Instantly it becomes the nation's No. 1 best
seller; movies, paperbacks, and foreign editions follow apace.
</P>
<P>
   His 11 novels, from ``A Time to Kill'' in 1988 (a two-year
hiatus followed) to ``The Brethren'' just the other day, have added
up to some 90 million Grisham works in circulation, kept him on
best-seller lists for hundreds of weeks and brought in a worldwide
gross of upwards of $1 billion. By comparison, popular producers
like Michael Crichton, Danielle Steele and Tom Clancy are barely
making do.
</P>
<P>
   The only uncertainty about the Grisham enterprise seems to be
whether he may be overproducing. In a 1998 interview with
Publishers Weekly, he recalled a period when ``The Chamber'' was
the No. 1 hardback seller; ``The Firm,'' ``The Pelican Brief'' and
``A Time to Kill'' were the No. 1, 2 and 3 paperbacks respectively;
and a movie version of ``The Client'' had lately hit the theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked a lot about overexposure,'' he said, ``and worried a
lot about it and still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily for Doubleday, his hardcover publisher, and for Dell,
his paperback publisher, his concern has not slowed him down or
discouraged his customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Grisham audience, however, does have its boundaries. He is
not among the heavy hitters of literary entertainment, like Graham
Greene or John le Carre, but is several cuts above the sex and
violence purveyors. Although he's unlikely to inspire many term
papers, no one need be ashamed to carry the latest Grisham in its
own dust jacket. In some circles his books make for elevated
dinner-party conversation. Trying to fathom the Grisham magic, I
have lately gone through five of his works. Grisham's specialty is
the legal thriller; if he did not create the genre, he assuredly
gave it a new dimension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brethren,'' for the latest example, has to do with three
felonious former judges who operate a blackmail scheme from inside
a federal prison and find themselves involved in a presidential
campaign. The plot is as up-to-date as tomorrow's newspaper, with
allusions to presidential polls and debates, campaign financing,
money laundering and offshore financial finagling and the
stockpiling of plutonium by Russian hardliners. Add to those
tantalizing ingredients the steady action, with some clever
surprises and occasional interludes for recapitulation or a touch
of romance or humor (not Grisham's strongest suit) or just to fill
360 pages.
</P>
<P>
   You get a rush of events without undue regard for plausibility;
an easy-to-take prose style that is not likely to strain readers
but evidently keeps millions awake; and characters who do not run
deep but are constantly on the run, conspiring and being conspired
against in atmospheric locales around the world as they contribute
to plots that have a ring of relevance without the distractions of
reality. The violence is mild by today's standards, and the sex
tends to be friendly and politely veiled.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the blurbs that adorn the paperback editions, the
books' main appeal is those unstoppable plots. Here are a few plugs
for ``The Firm'': ``The accelerating tempo of paranoia-driven
events is wonderful''; ``Reads like the whirlwind''; ``Keeps the
reader hooked''; ``Gripping''; ``A mean and lean page turner.''
</P>
<P>
   The catchy openings live up to the advertising. Last year's
entry, ``The Testament,'' begins with the 10th richest man in the
United States jumping to his death after disinheriting his large
and distasteful family and leaving his fortune to a little-known
daughter who is a missionary in an exceedingly remote South
American jungle. What with three greedy ex-wives, six children and
nine sets of lawyers (``the fees would be enormous''), Grisham is
off and running. But the terrain proves tough. I regret to report
that much of ``The Testament'' turns out to be an interminable
journey down Brazil way by Nate O'Reilly, a lawyer with a spiritual
thirst. Bring on the scoundrels, please.
</P>
<P>
   The books benefit from Grisham's own experience as a lawyer, the
legal give-and-get providing a veneer of authenticity, whether the
players are advocates for the homeless or Supreme Court justices or
straight-out crooks. New characters appear whenever a lapse
threatens the action, among them a sprinkling of millionaires and
masterminds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brethren'' features a superbrilliant CIA chief with access
to incalculable secret funds that he uses to elect a president who
will be sufficiently combative toward the Russians. Unfortunately,
this CIA chief was not in office during ``The Pelican Brief,'' when
the CIA was hard put to track down the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   The far-fetched yet controlled plots invite a sort of boys'
magazine writing known among reviewers as ``page turners.'' In
``The Pelican Brief'' the introduction of the terrorist Khamel
tells of ``a man of many names and faces and languages, an assassin
who struck quickly and left no trail, a fastidious killer who
roamed the world but could never be found.'' No, it's not Sherlock
Holmes' nightmare, Moriarty.
</P>
<P>
   This Grisham creation is credited with accomplishments that one
may recall (or imagine he recalls) from the newspapers: ``The
ambush of 17 Israeli soldiers on the West Bank in 1990 ... the 1985
car-bomb murders of a wealthy German banker and his family ... the
1981 attempt to kill the pope.'' Having been thus prepared, the
reader is informed that ``Khamel was about to perform on American
soil,'' and that ``important blood was about to be shed.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such passages lend themselves to rapid scanning,
dismissing them as junk food does not quite do them justice. The
figure of Khamel _ ``He can kill with either hand, either foot, a
car key, a pencil, whatever'' _ must remind many readers of their
excitement on first learning of master criminals and sleuths
engaged in desperate conflicts in exotic places like the Balkans.
What young reader of vulnerable imagination has not been hooked and
ensnared, gripped and propelled by such tales?
</P>
<P>
   Grisham adds to these fond memories contemporary references that
may give the grown-up reader the impression that he is getting the
dirt on how things really work at the highest levels of government,
finance and the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Consider the nasty doings that young Mitch McDeere of ``The
Firm'' finds himself involved with after getting a cushy job at the
seemingly respectable but thoroughly corrupt offices of Bendini,
Lambert &AMP; Locke, or what happens to Michael Brock of ``The Street
Lawyer'' when he unearths a murderous conspiracy at his giant
Washington law firm of Drake &AMP; Sweeney, or the revelations in ``The
Pelican Brief,'' my favorite in my recent sampling, about the
unscrupulous types who run high-powered White &AMP; Blazevich.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham keeps confirming the outsider's worst notions about
lawyers: ``Before the funeral arrangements were complete, the
lawyers were calling.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   So the elements are in place each February for another Grisham
smash hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brethren'' introduces those three former judges who have
wound up in that prison, from which they are extorting tens of
thousands of dollars from gays still in closets. The descriptions
are more colorful than the judges' personalities. ``Two of them
wore shoes. One was eating a saltine. The one with no shoes was
also bare-legged up to his knees, so that below his robe his
spindly legs could be seen. They were smooth and hairless and very
brown from the sun. A large tattoo had been applied to his left
calf.'' As the book's disclaimer puts it, ``Any resemblance to
actual persons, living or dead, is entirely coincidental.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 2 brings on the CIA chief, Teddy Maynard, an eminence
grise in a wheelchair who selects a Congressman, Aaron Lake, to be
America's next president. Little does Maynard, who knows
everything, know that Lake subscribes to gay publications and so is
a target of the ex-judges. We are thus readied for a conflict that
brings in an army of CIA officers, a drunk of a lawyer, Caribbean
bankers and assorted criminals and victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brethren'' became No. 1 upon appearance a couple of weeks
ago and is now bringing prosperity to bookstores everywhere. As a
blurb is bound to put it, ``The pages fly by.'' My Grisham
adventure was not painful, but I confess that I allowed quite a
number of those pages to fly by unread.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
