<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-REPORTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL REPORTER BEING FLOWN TO MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Radio Liberty reporter Andrei Babitsky, whose frank war
reporting from Chechnya angered the Kremlin, was put on a
Moscow-bound plane from Dagestan Monday night, perhaps ending a
mysterious six-week ordeal of disappearance and detention.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Russian authorities planned to release
the reporter or transfer him to detention in Moscow. However, his
return to the Russian capital was announced hours after acting
President Vladimir V. Putin said he thought Babitsky should be
freed.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's wife, Lyudmila, and his lawyer _ both of whom were in
Dagestan's capital Makhachkala to seek Babitsky's release _ were
not informed of the flight. Earlier in the day, the two announced
that the reporter was on a hunger strike to protest his continued
detention.
</P>
<P>
   According to televised reports, Babitsky's flight left
Makhachkala at 8:25 p.m., but several hours later he had not
surfaced in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's cause has been taken up by journalists, human rights
organizations and foreign governments, who have expressed fear that
the crusading reporter's plight was a prelude to a wider crackdown
on free speech in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's colleagues at the US-funded Radio Liberty slammed the
move as the latest in a series of actions by the Kremlin designed
to harass the journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Savik Shuster, Radio Liberty's Moscow Bureau Chief, said it was
``unethical'' to fly Babitsky back to Moscow without informing his
wife. ``It shows the inhuman lengths that the authorities are
prepared to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, 35, disappeared on Jan. 15 from Grozny, Chechnya's
capital. After denying any knowledge of his whereabouts for two
weeks, Moscow announced that Russian forces had detained him for
lacking journalistic accreditation and on suspicion of
collaborating with the Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin later provoked international outrage when it said
Babitsky had been turned over to Chechen rebels on Feb. 2 in
exchange for Russian prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky surfaced last Friday after being detained by police in
Makhachkala, capital of the Russian province of Dagestan, which
borders Chechnya. On Sunday prosecutors there charged him with
carrying a false passport.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's wife Lyudmila, who met with her husband for the first
time since his disappearance, was shocked by the news that he had
been moved to Moscow without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I will fly back to Moscow. I keep trying to see my
husband and they keep moving him someplace else,'' she said in a
televised interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say he is free,'' she said. ``They put him on some
special airplane. They didn't say anything. As far as I am
concerned, until he is home he isn't free.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Putin, who previously said little about the
case, announced that he thought Babitsky should be freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that law-enforcement bodies should be holding
him behind bars,'' Putin said in televised comments. ``If they have
some questions to put to him they should sort them out without
keeping him under arrest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said he thought Babitsky's reporting from Chechnya was
biased, but added that this was not sufficient cause to incarcerate
him. Babitsky's reports had infuriated the Kremlin by focusing on
the plight of suffering civilians and high Russian troop losses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, details of Babitsky's plight over the past six weeks
have begun to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Kusov, a Radio Liberty reporter in the Caucasus who spent
several hours with Babitsky Friday night, said that after the
journalist was detained, he was taken to a detention center at
Chernokozovo, an infamous ``filtration camp'' for suspected Chechen
rebels located 30 miles north of Grozny. Media and human rights
groups have accused Russian authorities of torturing prisoners held
in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Kusov said Babitsky revealed little about what he saw at
Chernokozovo, other than that he wasn't tortured himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not want to talk about that, not because he himself
underwent some kind of physical difficulties, but he saw how other
people, Chechens and women, were suffering,'' Kusov said in an
interview broadcast on Radio Liberty on Saturday. ``The topic is
not very pleasant for him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kusov's account, after Russians turned him over to
unidentified men wearing ski masks, Babitsky was taken to a home in
Chechnya and held there until Friday when men in masks brought him
to Makhachkala.
</P>
</TEXT>
