<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-DRUGTESTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Union trying to organize attacks Delta drug tests
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A flight attendants union trying to organize at Delta
Air Lines is calling on the carrier to reinstate at least a
half-dozen attendants its says were fired because of flawed drug
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's random drug tests are ``resulting in false accusations
of adulteration of urine samples,'' said Patricia Friend, president
of the Association of Flight Attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Clay McConnell, a spokesman for Atlanta-based Delta, declined to
respond directly but defended the drug-testing program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that anyone's been terminated,'' he said. ``But both
Delta and the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services have
examined the science behind this policy and found it to be
completely sound.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue are random drug tests given operational airline
employees to assure safety. Last year Delta fired Yasuko Ishikawa,
based in Portland, Ore., after she submitted a urine sample
following a flight. It was judged ``not consistent with human
urine.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFA says Ishikawa's habit of drinking lots of water during
flights, along with her small size, led to a false finding of a
substituted sample.
</P>
<P>
   The union says the effect of those factors, as well as gender,
ethnicity and diet, haven't been fully tested. It wants the U.S.
Transportation Department to revise testing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Delta Chairman Leo Mullin, Friend said at least
six and as many as 13 Delta attendants have been fired for such
findings. She added the union is aware of only three such firings
among the 47,000 attendants it represents at 26 other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell pointed to a recently released HHS report, prepared at
Delta's request, that supports the scientific guidelines used to
determine if a sample is a substitute. The report said studies of
more than 2,600 diverse people, including some who
``water-loaded,'' produced ``not a single person'' who tested
falsely for a substituted sample.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said Delta uses federally certified labs for drug test
results. He said Delta has tested 14,000 employees since October
1998, with 11 findings of substituted or adulterated samples.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA is seeking to organize Delta's 20,000 flight attendants
and in recent months has used the drug-testing issue in fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
