<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS REBOUND, BUT INTEREST-RATE FEARS REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average rebounded above
10,000 on Monday as investors, at least temporarily, moved back
into blue-chip stocks that had been battered in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also gained ground, helped
in part by the Goldman Sachs market strategist Abby Joseph Cohen,
who said Monday that the slide in the index had left it
undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   But technology stocks, which have continued to rise in the face
of a broad-based decline this year, edged lower Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy continuing to power ahead and the Federal
Reserve Board showing no sign that it has finished trying to slow
it down by raising short-term interest rates, most analysts and
traders said Monday's moves were little more than a temporary
bounce from what had been a sharp sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy the market is up, but it would be nice if I had
some reason to think it is sustainable,'' said Henry Herrmann,
chief investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed, a firm in Overland
Park, Kan., that has $40 billion under management. ``We are due for
a bounce, and we are getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by financial and retail stocks like Citigroup, American
Express and Procter &AMP; Gamble, the Dow rose 176.53 points, or 1.8
percent, to 10,038.65. It was the biggest point gain in the Dow in
nearly two weeks and came after a 2.3 percent decline on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the S&AMP;P 500 gained 14.69 points, or 1.1 percent, to
1,348.05. Exxon Mobil, Qualcomm and American International Group
helped to lift the index.
</P>
<P>
   But investors took some profits in technology stocks. By the
close, the Nasdaq composite index was down 12.65 points, or 0.3
percent, to 4,577.85. At one point in the session, the index had
fallen as much as 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of small-company shares were little changed. The Russell
2000 index gained 0.94, or 0.2 percent, to 557.68.
</P>
<P>
   In her comments Monday, Cohen said the recent slide in the S&AMP;P
500 had left the index about 5 percent undervalued. She maintained
her target of 1,525 for the S&AMP;P 500 by the end of the year because
of continued vigor in the economy and robust corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   In reference to interest-rate fears, Cohen said recent and
expected interest-rate increases by the Fed are aimed ``at slowing
and elongating, not stopping, economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew M. Brooks, head of equity trading at T. Rowe Price
Associates, said, ``Abby's mildly positive comments were a help.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brooks said Monday's move was mostly ``a snap back from a
pretty ugly week.''
</P>
<P>
   Volume was heavy, but not frantic. On the New York Stock
Exchange, just over a billion shares changed hands. Volume on the
Nasdaq stock market was 1.78 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which have been severely battered as interest
rates have risen, did better Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a Dow component, gained 1 3/8, to 49 3/8, after the
United States' biggest financial services company said John S.
Reed, its co-chairman, would retire in April.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan gained 2 1/16, to 77 15/16. Wells Fargo rose 1
7/16, to 34 1/8. Mellon Financial was up 1{, to 34}. Bank of New
York closed at 34}, up 1}. And American International Group rose 3
9/16, to 87 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, EMC and Oracle were among the technology losers
Monday. Cisco fell 2 3/16, to 130 9/16. EMC shed 5, to 118. Oracle
fell 2, to 68 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   And reports that Yahoo was in talks to take a minority stake in
a company that News Corp. is creating to hold its satellite
television assets sent the stock down 3\, to 161 15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
