<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-ART-2TA     02-28 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE BANK ADJUSTS TO A GLOBAL _ AND VIRTUAL _ MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ It is not the future that worries
Rolf-Ernst Breuer, chairman of Deutsche Bank. It is the present.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of one of the world's biggest banks, Breuer is
convinced that the World Wide Web will eviscerate traditional
banking _ but also open huge new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a cavernous warehouse packed with video screens,
Breuer outlined a number of Web-based projects, from portals for
personal finance to electronic trading networks for steel and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   But in a wide-ranging interview in his office at the bank's
headquarters here, Breuer sounded like a man still trapped in
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank is struggling to be one of the top five banking
companies in the world, a position it can lay claim to by virtue of
its size, but one that will require big adjustments to the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank has 1,500 local offices and 7 million retail
banking customers. It has the biggest branch network in Germany,
but that network barely ekes out a profit and consistently drags
down the bank's overall performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a problem which we cannot solve on a stand-alone
basis,'' he acknowledged bluntly, adding that customers flee as
soon as the bank closes branches. ``The only solution is to
consolidate, which means to go together with someone else and,
well, diminish overlaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, consolidation would have implied taking over a
rival. But now, Breuer is hinting at something more radical: the
possibility of giving up a controlling stake in his own branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That depends on the partners,'' he said cagily, when asked
whether he could contemplate letting someone else have a
controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is largely beyond Deutsche Bank's control. Germany
has far too many banks partly because it has a huge sector of
nonprofit savings banks owned by state and local governments, which
keep margins low.
</P>
<P>
   Having separated Deutsche Bank's retail network into a
stand-alone company called Deutsche Bank 24, Breuer has pleaded in
vain for rivals to buy in as minority partners.
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts say Deutsche Bank will simply sell off its branch
network. But Breuer is clearly impatient and also seems convinced
that traditional banking is withering and radical changes are
necessary to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deutsche Bank is a lot like Germany,'' said an executive at
one of its rivals in investment banking. ``It moves slowly for a
long time, but when it does decide to change, it moves incredibly
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Outlining his strategy for electronic banking, Breuer argued
that the Internet would cannibalize conventional banking channels
and lead to a drastic reduction of profit margins in routine
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But, Breuer added, the Internet also opens up new opportunities
for geographic expansion across Europe without buying physical
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, if someone had come and offered me the Credit
Lyonnais on a plate, I would have been interested,'' he remarked.
``But today, I would say no, that's duplicating a problem we have
already in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   France is now a model for building up a virtual market across
Europe. Blocked by French political leaders from buying a French
bank, Breuer set up a skeleton network of offices that cater only
to wealthy customers and rely primarily on electronic services.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer, who took over as chief executive three years ago, knows
he is under pressure. He acknowledges that he is far behind rivals
like Goldman, Sachs and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter as an adviser in
mergers and acquisitions. Even in the German market, Deutsche Bank
has consistently ranked behind both American rivals in making
deals.
</P>
<P>
   He is also behind in electronic banking. Not only is Deutsche
Bank well behind American online brokers like Charles Schwab, it
also has fewer brokerage customers than German rivals like
Commerzbank and ConSors.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Deutsche Bank has only 125,000 online brokerage
customers, compared with about 300,000 for ComDirect, a unit of
Commerzbank, and 176,000 for ConSors, an online start-up that has
been one of Germany's hottest stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some tardiness, Breuer now seems determined. He plans to
invest $300 million in Internet projects this year. He also
hammered out alliances with America Online and Europe's biggest
software company, SAP.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal with SAP, Deutsche Bank plans to set up virtual
marketplaces for corporations to trade products like chemicals and
steel.
</P>
<P>
   It is also setting up a number new portal sites that offer
access to investments and advice from Deutsche Bank as well as
other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is inherently unique. But Breuer has far more money
than most rivals to throw at the project. Bank officials say the
bank's total investment in electronic banking, including the costs
of marketing through its various subsidiaries, could reach $1.4
billion next year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money will come from selling assets in Deutsche
Bank's huge portfolio of industrial stocks. Until recently, the
portfolio was almost impossible to touch because the taxes on
capital gains would have run into billions of dollars. But the
German government is now planning to let companies sell their
holdings tax-free, and Breuer plans to be a major seller.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Chambers, a banking analyst at HSBC Securities in London,
argues that the prospect of electronic banking has abruptly
deflated expectations about the merits of full-blown bank mergers
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three to six months, people are questioning
whether it makes sense to put together brick-and-mortar networks,''
Chambers said. ``What is changing the business most of all right
now is how you reach customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives go further, arguing that Deutsche Bank
should simply sell its retail branches and let an independent
company act as a neutral distribution system for rival banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the structure of banking in Germany, there isn't going
to be room for four big private retail banking networks forever,''
said Andreas R. Dombrett, a former Deutsche Bank executive who is
now a managing director in J.P. Morgan's Frankfurt office. ``What
you need to do is break up the value chain between production,
distribution and transaction processing or information
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the choices are more difficult. With seven million
customers, Deutsche Bank's retail network is a valuable channel for
selling everything from mutual funds to retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, only about 650,000 of Deutsche Bank's customers
use its online services. According to bank executives, about 20
percent of customers say they do not want electronic banking at
all, while 60 percent want both online services and traditional
branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose clients if we close branches,'' Breuer said, noting
that the customers have already balked about staff reductions. ``We
really stretched the patience of our customers to the acceptable
limit. And although we think we did everything possible,
profitability is not comparable to our British or Spanish
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a dilemma: keep the retail network and continue to
drag down the entire bank's profitability, or give it up and risk
losing access to millions of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Deutsche Bank's corporate and investment banking
businesses have been much stronger than its retail business.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Deutsche Bank greatly expanded its American presence
by acquiring Bankers Trust for $10 billion. Though Deutsche Bank
had to spend hundreds of millions of dollars on bonuses to retain
executives at Bankers Trust, most analysts agree that the merger
went surprisingly well.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust gave Deutsche Bank a solid position in arranging
midsize mergers and securities trading. Bankers Trust also owned
Alex Brown, a small but well-respected investment bank specializing
in technology and health care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by torrid growth in the world's capital markets,
Deutsche Bank's net income climbed 50 percent in 1999 to 2.6
billion euros (just under $2.6 billion). Its trading revenues
soared 170 percent, to about 4.8 billion euros, and commission
income from financial services climbed 50 percent, to 8.1 billion
euros.
</P>
<P>
   The one real weak spot is retail banking _ the business of
serving ordinary private customers. Although this area generated
about $2.3 billion in revenues last year, analysts estimate that it
earned only $16 million in operating profit, and some experts
believe it barely broke even.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Deutsche Bank shares have nearly doubled from
their 52-week low of 44.06 euros last March 2, to 88.34 euros
Monday. Part of that reflects actual growth, but much of it
reflects excitement that German tax reform will let Deutsche Bank
cash in on billions of dollars from its industrial holdings. The
bank's portfolio is currently worth about $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But costs continue to climb as fast as revenues. Despite three
separate cost-cutting plans the last two years, Breuer has made
almost no progress toward his stated goal of reducing costs from
about 75 percent to 65 percent of revenues by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the cost performance has been extremely poor,''
said Mark Hoge, a banking analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
in London who recently lowered his rating on Deutsche Bank stock to
underperform.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer's preferred answer to the problem thus far has been to
invite other banks in as partners in Deutsche Bank 24.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea has run aground. Dresdner Bank, Germany's
third--largest bank, began talks last year but abruptly called them
off.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say the plan ran afoul of Dresdner's biggest
shareholder, the German insurance company Allianz. Allianz is
widely believed to be pushing for a merger between Dresdner and
Hypovereinsbank of Munich, Germany's second-largest bank and one in
which Allianz is also a major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Germany's No. 4, Commerzbank. But its chief
executive, Martin Kohlhaussen, has refused to enter any such talks.
</P>
<P>
   Such obstacles have been part of the German landscape, and
Breuer has learned to be patient about things he cannot change
himself. Asked what the solution to his concrete albatross might
be, he gave a mischievous grin and said only one word:
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
