<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow's return to 10,000 fails to impress analysts
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Dow Jones industrial average on Monday popped back
above its psychological benchmark of 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But investors were cautioned against making too much of that
rebound. They were also urged not to make any sudden investment
decisions based on the twists and turns of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have to stick with their long-term strategy,'' said
John K. Lynch, director of investment strategy at Wachovia
Securities. ``Don't get swayed by the day-to-day stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, by the way, gained almost 177 points, or 1.79 percent,
on Monday, after losing 230 points Friday. The Nasdaq composite
closed with a decline of less than 13 points, or 0.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Dow was up 294, on what was widely seen as the
result of investors shifting some money out of technology stocks
and into some of the beaten-down ``old economy'' stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a watershed event,'' Lynch said before
trading ended for the day. He suggested the Dow, up about 250
points at the time, could just as quickly lose that much if the
monthly employment report due Friday is stronger than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch also noted the movement of money from technology stocks to
industrials has a lopsided effect. Because the market value of some
technology companies is much higher than that of old-line
businesses, a little movement can have a big impact on the Dow, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, investors shouldn't expect the market to settle
down until it's clear the Federal Reserve is done raising interest
rates, he and others said.
</P>
<P>
   The other uncertainty is whether a handful of stocks can
continue to lead major market indexes higher, said money manager
Joe Ransom of Trusco Capital Management, a subsidiary of SunTrust
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with looking at the indexes,'' he added, ``is
judging from the indexes what is happening to individual stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   While investors shouldn't try to time the market, Ransom said,
investors can look to the bigger market to help them feel
comfortable as to when to add new money. One signal of a possible
bottom is when bad news stops triggering selling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the current volatility, the fundamentals are still
good, Ransom said, from the strength of the economy, to the level
of interest rates, to the state of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can find reason to be very upbeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So can Lynch, of Wachovia Securities. ``I'm still seeing a
13,000 Dow at the end of the year, and 1,675 on the Standard &AMP;
Poor's (500 index).''
</P>
<P>
   His ballpark prediction for the Nasdaq composite is 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the bullish outlook will be the first-quarter
and second-quarter earnings reports, he said. Lynch expects the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies to report 15 percent growth in
earnings per share for both quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
