<SLUG> BC-BUSH-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign visits Ohio today
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Today it's Texas Gov. George W. Bush's turn to
bring presidential politics to Ohio, with campaign stops in
Cleveland, suburban Columbus and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush is excited to come to Ohio,'' said Orest Holubec,
spokesman for the Bush campaign in Ohio. ``He knows that there is a
huge grassroots effort in place here. He understands that the base
is energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to begin the day at 9 a.m. at the Fatima
Family Center on Cleveland's east side, a Catholic church-sponsored
agency that serves everyone from infants to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Bush is to be at Westerville High School, just outside
Columbus, for a 12:50 p.m. town meeting, said Holubec.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will wrap up the day with an open-to-the-public rally at
Memorial Hall, 1225 Elm St., in Cincinnati at 7:20 p.m. Arizona
Sen. John McCain, Bush's opponent in next Tuesday'sRepublican
primary, spent Saturday in Ohio, a day after Vice President Al Gore
was in Cleveland. Gore opposes former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit to the Fatima Center comes in the wake of a letter
he sent to Roman Catholic Cardinal John O'Connor of New York
expressing regret for not distancing himself from the religious and
racial intolerance at ultra-conservative Bob Jones University in
South Carolina, where he spoke before the South Carolina primary
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Holubec, however, said the stop at the Fatima Center is ``in
line'' with other events Bush has held at church-sponsored agencies
and in keeping with the Texas governor's ``compassionate
conservative'' philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has been exploiting Bush's visit to Bob
Jones. Before last week's Republican vote in Michigan, McCain
supporters called voters reminding them of Bush's bob Jones
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In Columbus on Monday, Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, a national
co-chairman of McCain's campaign, said he does not believe the
national McCain campaign will make similar phone calls to Catholic
voters in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Curt Steiner, a Columbus-based consultant who is advising
the McCain campaign, said that in Ohio the campaign will not send
post cards to Democrats, urging them to vote for McCain in the
Republican primary. Such cards were sent in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Their comments came as the McCain campaign opened an office in
downtown Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see in Ohio is a very fluid situation,'' DeWine said.
``We think we have a genuine chance of winning in Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton area, some Montgomery County Republicans also met
Monday morning to rally support for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Chuck Horn, R-Centerville, a former backer of U.S.
Rep John Kasich, switched to McCain because he believes McCain has
a better chance of winning in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid the Republicans are about to make a big mistake
(nominating Bush),'' Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   Horn pulled together about 20 people to talk about generating
more support from McCain in the coming week. A handful of were from
the University of Dayton College Republicans. Some supported McCain
but Matt LaFontaine, 20, from Chicago, a sophomore studying public
relations, remained in Bush's camp despite the pleadings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain camp is doing a good job running on his image but
when push comes to shove policy-wise, I think the man who can get
it done is George Bush,'' LaFontaine said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
