r p BC-POL-INDEPENDENTS-COX     02-28 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-INDEPENDENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Independents loom large in Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Ohio may have a ``closed'' system for voting in
primary elections, but 5.5 million voters _ or about three-quarters
of those registered _ are considered independent and free to vote
in the primary of their choice without challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain is banking on strong support from these
independents _ Ohio law calls them non-partisans _ in his race
against Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the Republican primary, Sen.
Mike DeWine, a McCain campaign national co-chairman, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Independents _ and Democrats _ helped McCain to victory in
Michigan, where Bush did well among registered Republicans but
still lost by 6 percentage points. But unlike Michigan, Ohio has
both a Democratic and Republican primary on March 7, making it less
likely that Democrats will cross over to vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton-based political consultant James Nathanson, a Bush
supporter, said, many of the 5.5 million voters classified as
non-partisan on voter rolls consider themselves Republicans or
Democrats. Bush will do well with the Republicans and defeat
McCain, predicted Nathanson, former political director for the
Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There is such a large number of independents because of how Ohio
defines Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ohio law, a voter is defined as a Democrat or Republican
if he or she voted in a primary for that party during the past two
years, said Carlo LoParo, spokesman for Ohio Secretary of State J.
Kenneth Blackwell. Otherwise, the voter is classified as
``non-partisan'' or independent he said.
</P>
<P>
   During 1998-1999, 946,958 Ohioans voted in Democratic primaries
and 844,906 voted in Republican primaries. A total of 5,401,546
were registered to vote but did not vote in a primary during the
past two years, LoParo said.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures were as of last September, said LoParo. The number
of independents has grown since then because new voters have been
registered and none have voted in primaries. New figures will be
announced this week, LoParo said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, voters who participated in a Republican or Democratic
primary during the past two years may be challenged if they ask for
the other party's primary ballot. The challenges are carried out
automatically in about half of Ohio's 88 counties, said LoParo.
</P>
<P>
   Because relatively few Ohio voters legally qualify as Democrats
or Republicans, such crossovers are not expected to be as big a
factor here as the ability of the candidates to draw support from
the nearly 5.5 million independents.
</P>
<P>
   Nathanson said that some of these voters were stripped of their
party labels simply because they missed voting in one primary. They
might have voted in the 1996 presidential primary, for example, but
not in a primary during 1998 or 1999, said Nathanson. Turnout
usually is larger during presidential primaries than during other
primaries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted increased participation in the Republican primary
by Republican-inclined voters who usually only cast ballots in
general elections. The advantage among these voters will go to
Bush, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Robert Adams of Wright State University said
that the large number of nonpartisan voters gives McCain an
opportunity in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to turn out that independent group and get them to
vote for him,'' said Adams. ``I think he's riding a tiger but so
far he has been able to stay on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-YOUTH-VOTE-COX     02-28 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youth vote in America may play a greater role
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON _ In the closing weeks of the hot New Hampshire
presidential primary, the one that vaulted Arizona Sen. John McCain
from intriguing bit player to serious contender for the Republican
nomination, the University of Dayton campus was the site of a
battle all its own.
</P>
<P>
   Through a coordinated effort with campus political groups and
other organizations, the office of UD President Bro. Raymond Fitz
led a drive to register students to vote. They had resident
assistants hand out forms in dorm halls, they staffed a table every
day in the cafeteria, they flooded the neighborhood of student
houses near campus with volunteers to knock on every door.
</P>
<P>
   The effort ran from Jan. 18 to Feb. 4 and was punctuated with
McCain's stunning, widely covered, New Hampshire win on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers at UD handed out 9,000 voter registration forms.
</P>
<P>
   They got back about 150.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a great turn-in,'' deadpanned Chris Woodard, a graduate
assistant in the Fitz' office. ``I think there is the underlying
sense that, as a college student, your vote doesn't count.''
</P>
<P>
   But seldom has there been a time when the youth vote in America
could count so much.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the entire cohort known as Generation X _
whose members range in age from 18 to about 35 _ is eligible to
vote. In November they will represent about 40 percent of all
eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting,'' said Nannette Whaley, 24, president of
the Montgomery County Young Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the races will be exciting enough to
lure young voters to the polls. As evidenced by the scene at UD,
which is not atypical, polls show young Americans to be notoriously
disinterested in voting. Although presidential elections tend to
bring higher turn-outs among voters of all age groups, the trend
among young voters is unmistakably down both locally and
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Third Millennium, an advocacy group for young
voters based in New York, only 34 percent of voters between the
ages of 18 and 34 voted in the 1996 election, when the rate for all
ages was 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later in Montgomery County, only 22 percent of
registered 18- to 32 year-olds voted in the November 1998
elections, a Dayton Daily News analysis found. It was the lowest
percentage of any age group, although it comprised the largest
group in terms of sheer numbers. In the age group 57 and older, 65
percent voted.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Association of Secretaries of State, the public
office that manages elections in each state, reported last year
that participation by 18- to 24-year-olds has dropped dramatically
in recent decades. In 1972, half of that age group voted in the
presidential election. In 1996, only 32 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this seem not to be a mystery. In 1972, for
instance, 18- to 24-year-olds were still confronted with the
Vietnam War. But the issues at work in succeeding years are more
complicated and nuanced than simple self-preservation, according to
experts who follow the trends.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of life-or-death issues is one factor, they say. But
the presence in recent decades of high profile political scandal is
another. So is the decline in the quality of public education,
particularly in cities, and in civic lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's been a constant drumbeat of demagoguery against
government,'' said Curtis Gans, who heads the nonpartisan Committee
for the Study of the American Electorate, ``which is not likely to
encourage people to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You put all of that together and there are powerful forces for
why young people aren't participating.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Adinaro, a 21-year-old junior at UD, is a past president of
the school's Young Republicans organization. She grew up in a
conservative household in Cleveland and is fully wired for politics
already.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've literally been passing out literature since I was 10,''
said the marketing major, ``for school levies and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But the apathy of her contemporaries is no secret to her. She
has been in the trenches trying to recruit fellow activists. She
has seen the eyes roll at talk of privatizing Social Security
accounts or rolling back welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my friends don't care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, 18-year-old Brett McDaniel, 18, walked in
unannounced to the headquarters of the Montgomery County Democratic
Party. The senior at Chaminade-Julienne High School is energized
just by the prospect of casting his first vote this year. He has
attended meetings and already is volunteering on the U.S. Senate
campaign of the Rev. Marvin McMickle of Cleveland, one of four
people seeking the Democratic nomination in next Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   But last week he was reminded that many of his peers don't share
his enthusiasm. In a hallway at school, McDaniel approached a
fellow senior to talk about presidential candidates but he was
interrupted by someone who overheard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some girl said I bring that stuff up too much,'' McDaniel
said. ``She said I need to stop worrying about that and let my
parents worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been cases when young voters haven't left it to
their parents, and they have directed the outcome of elections.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ted Strickland, D-Portsmouth, is widely understood to
have retaken in 1996 the seat he'd lost in 1994 by mobilizing
thousands of students at Ohio University.
</P>
<P>
   ``That group of students elected a congressman,'' said Whaley of
the Young Democrats. ``How exciting is that?''
</P>
<P>
   And in a shot heard `round the world, young voters flooded the
polls on Election Day in Minnesota in 1998 to make the mouthy
professional wrestler Jesse Ventura governor. His third-party
assault on the status quo overwhelmed respected candidates from the
Republican and Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was big on FM rock radio stations,'' said Steve Shier,
political science chairman at Carleton College in Minnesota. ``I
would not call any of his ads conventional, which made them much
more likely to appeal to younger voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics from the Minnesota Secretary of State showed an
unusual spike in Election Day registration for a non-presidential
year, and turnout among young voters was remarkably high. Although
the percentages were skewed because of same-day registrants, nearly
80 percent of the 18 year-olds who registered to vote actually
voted.
</P>
<P>
   The Ventura phenomenon was scant on issues. He ran a short
campaign that emphasized his reputation for bluntness and
fearlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just him,'' said Adinaro. ``I'm sure he's very
intelligent, I just can't believe the kids were really listening.
It was all image.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley, the Democrat, agreed. She said Minnesota's young voters
were seduced only by the persona because Ventura's views on things,
such federal student loans, don't match what most young people say
they support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does happen that way,'' she acknowledged. ``I think Bill
Clinton won the youth vote in `92 by putting on sunglasses on
Arsenio Hall. It was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Whaley argues that young voters do have issues
that matter to them, including student loans and universal health
care. She said in many ways young voters are no different from
other voters in that they respond best to issues that hit them
directly, and hit them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Washington like to say Social Security is an issue
that bridges the gap for all voters, but it doesn't,'' she said.
``That's 40 years away for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the bottom line issue campaigns face on the issue
of young voters: to target or not to target?
</P>
<P>
   Third Millennium, the advocacy group, has begun a program called
Neglection 2000 that will study whether presidential candidates are
running campaign ads in places where young voters are likely to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they running them during reruns of the Golden Girls or
during Friends?'' said Richard Thau, 35, president of the group.
``The candidates include their children and grandchildren in
speeches, but they don't speak to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thau says campaigns have a civic obligation to seek out new,
young voters rather than focus on reliable, older voters simply
because it's cheaper for them.
</P>
<P>
   Others dispute this, including Whaley, who said she thinks both
parties may be reluctant to agitate the youth vote unless they can
be sure their candidate is positioned well to capture that vote.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point may be the case of McCain, who is seen by the
experts as having tried the hardest to attract young voters. His
New Hampshire campaign included many visits to college campuses,
and even fraternity houses.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent study by Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press shows that Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al
Gore both drew a higher percentage of the under-30 crowd in
head-to-head match ups.
</P>
<P>
   Schier, the Minnesota professor, said he sees in McCain a
persona-driven cam similar to the one Ventura ran. Heavy on
personality, though not as light on issues, Schier said McCain
could yet spark a youth movement like the one Ventura had.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the wild card, when they move they can move in a big
direction,'' he said. ``But if there is going to be a youth push,
we may not know it until the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
