<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-BRAIN-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOR DUMMIES' PUBLISHER PLEDGES $350 MILLION TO MIT FOR BRAIN
RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A computer publishing billionaire and his
wife pledged Monday to give the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology the largest single donation yet to a university _ $350
million over the next 20 years _ to finance research on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The money, from Patrick J. and Lore Harp McGovern, will create
the McGovern Institute for Brain Research, a center with a staff of
300, including computer scientists, psychologists and molecular
biologists. The donation comes at a moment when neuroscience is
making great advances, powered by recent progress in imaging
technology, cell biology and genomics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have a great interest and fascination with this last
frontier of discovery,'' McGovern said Monday at the signing an
initial agreement on the institute.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, 62, is founder and chairman of International Data
Group, a company known for publishing Computerworld, putting out
the ``For Dummies'' book series and organizing huge computer
industry conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1950s, when he was a mere MIT undergraduate,
McGovern majored in life sciences and studied the human nervous
system. And even before that, he said, when he was a teen-ager
visiting the public library in Philadelphia, he came upon a book
called ``Giant Minds, or Machines that Think'' that changed his
life, infecting him with ideas about how computers could enhance
human reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McGovern, a 55-year-old high-tech entrepreneur, said that
she also traced her interest in the brain back some 50 years, to a
visit to a science museum when she was 5 years old. Her parents
showed her a brain in formaldehyde at a science museum and she
asked, ``Can you touch thought? Does it have physical presence?''
</P>
<P>
   ``And so maybe now we can figure that out,'' she said. ``So let
the journey begin.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the McGoverns had to figure out, they said, was
where to put the institute they had decided to create about three
years ago. They put together an advisory committee and considered
seven universities: Columbia; University of California campuses in
San Francisco, Berkeley and San Diego; the California Institute of
Technology; Stanford and MIT. McGovern acknowledged that his
emotional ties to MIT had played a role in the decision, but said
more objective factors also came into play, including its
neuroscience programs and its ``willingness to be very
collaborative.''
</P>
<P>
   In the style of many Internet-age benefactors, the McGoverns
plan to keep a close eye on the institute and will sit on its
board, along with directors from MIT and outside neuroscientists.
</P>
<P>
   The money will begin to flow as yearly gifts of about $5
million, McGovern said. The amounts will slowly scale up until, at
the end of 20 years, the McGoverns donate the rest of the $350
million to endow the institute in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   The gift beats by $50 million the record for a single donation
to a university, according to a list published by the Chronicle of
Higher Education. The former record-setting donation was $300
million in stock from the Ingram Charitable Fund to Vanderbilt
University, announced in 1998. Last year, the Bill and Melinda
Gates Foundation gave $1 billion to create the Gates Millennium
Scholars program, but the money, intended to encourage minority
students in science and technology, is to be spread among many
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gifts of $100 million are becoming commonplace at certain
institutions,'' said Stacy Palmer, editor of The Chronicle of
Philanthropy. ``But $350 million is still an awful lot of money for
one couple to give.''
</P>
<P>
   The money comes at an opportune time, said Phillip A. Sharp, a
Nobel-laureate molecular biologist who will serve as the
institute's founding director. Among other factors, scientists
seeking to unravel the workings of the brain now have at their
disposal new knowledge about how nerve cells work, he said, and the
soon-to-be-completed mapping of the human genome is expected to
contribute insights as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is a basis upon which, not in the next year, not
even in 10 years, but perhaps in 20 years, we'll be able to draw
out the general and specific functions of the brain in complex
phenomena, like learning behavior, those sorts of processes,'' he
said. ``And it's terribly exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, asked if he had one pet neuroscience problem he would
like to see solved, said it would probably be the causes of
misperception: why the brain takes in or remembers things
incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McGovern said she was most interested in attacking learning
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can tap into the intellectual potential and bring
everyone up to par,'' she said, ``we can create a so much better
society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
