<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New magazines vie for young crowd
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newsstands get a little more crowded this week with the
launching of three new magazines. The bimonthly teenStyle ($4.95),
which proclaims itself ``the biggest hair and beauty magazine for
teens,'' offers a ``flip'' format for the premiere issue. In other
words, half the magazine is upside down until you flip it over and
start from the back. Both halves deal with such weighty topics as
hairstyles, prom preparation, Gwyneth Paltrow's favorite scent and
how Jennifer Lopez maintains her glowing complexion.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis pro Anna Kournikova and other female athletes offer
training tips in the first issue of Sports Illustrated for Women
($3.50). Debuting as a bimonthly publication, the magazine is aimed
at women ages 18-34 who have a passion for sports. In addition to
standard articles on fitness, food and athletic gear, the magazine
talks with Olympic gold medalist skater Tara Lipinski about her new
movie career.
</P>
<P>
   The glossy, ad-packed premiere issue of FHM ($2.99) is aimed at
the same young males who read Maxim, Details and GQ. Along with a
special pullout section on ``The Girls of FHM,'' a collection of
scantily clad models and celebrities such as the above-mentioned
Lopez and Britney Spears, FHM offers a wide selection of service
articles on fashion, grooming and sex, and features on film
director Wes Craven and boxing promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting piece is the graphic account of a
Hawaiian vacation gone terribly wrong in ``Sharks Ate My Wife!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Law and disorder: As expected, Time ($3.50) and Newsweek
($3.50) devote a substantial portion of their issues to the not
guilty verdict in the Amadou Diallo case and the continuing
controversy surrounding the police departments in New York and Los
Angeles. Bronx district attorney Robert Johnson is blamed for
losing the trial, Time says, because race was never brought up as
an issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The truth is out there: Yes, it sounds like something from
``The X-Files,'' but Life ($3.99) reports that a new poll shows
that 49 percent of Americans believe the government is withholding
information about the existence of UFOs. More than 2 million insist
they have had an encounter with beings from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tipper's turn: If Tipper Gore hates Washington as much as she
says she does, why is she campaigning so hard for her husband? New
Yorker ($3) writer Elsa Walsh reports that the reluctant political
wife sees the campaign as a necessary sacrifice. Walsh also reports
that relations with the Clintons are strained, not only because of
the Lewinsky scandal, but because Hillary Rodham Clinton kept Mrs.
Gore waiting for an hour and a half at a Gore fund-raiser last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Who's who: Society isn't dead; just the names and faces have
changed. The Astors and Rothschilds are still in demand at glitzy
parties, but nowadays they're likely to find themselves rubbing
elbows with Madonna and Puff Daddy. In the March issue of W
($4.50), the editors put their heads together to come up with a new
A-list. Along with the usual suspects are Melinda and Bill Gates,
Brad Pitt, David E. Kelley and Michelle Pfeiffer, Prince William of
Wales and Camilla Parker Bowles. And, by the way, even if you're
not interested in fashion, the fabulous 30-page spread that was
shot in Havana is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) questions the
increasing use of psychiatric drugs to control children's behavior.
Such drugs should be a last resort after therapy, some experts say,
not the first step. ... Are Bruce Willis and Julia Roberts really
worth $20 million per film? Apparently so, says Entertainment
Weekly ($2.99), because they are big box-office draws. Not so for
Jodie Foster, who, at $15 million, is not as bankable as Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
