<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIJUANA OFFICIAL SAYS SLAYING SHOWS TRAFFICKERS' POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ One day after gunmen killed the chief of police in
Tijuana, the sprawling city that borders California, the state
governor said that drug traffickers were out of control there
partly because many federal authorities were in their pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs are coming in by land, sea and air,'' Gov. Alejandro
Gonzalez Alcocer of Baja California said in a telephone interview.
``The federal authorities have jurisdiction, but frankly, we don't
have much confidence in them. We worry that if we try to coordinate
operations with them, our plans will be communicated to the
traffickers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, during a visit to Baja California by President
Ernesto Zedillo, Gonzalez urged the president to speak out against
the drug traffickers, who have been blamed for the killings of some
60 people in Tijuana in eight weeks. In a speech later, the
president promised a crackdown, saying, ``We have to make these
criminals understand that they're not welcome in Baja California,
that the only home they deserve are the prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, gunmen in cars ambushed and killed the Tijuana police
chief, Alfredo de la Torre Marquez, as he drove along a freeway. He
was hit by dozens of bullets, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   One reasonable hypothesis, Gonzalez said, was that the
traffickers ordered the police chief's assassination as a dramatic
response to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, a Yale-trained economist who has rarely displayed
personal interest in the narcotics problems, made no reference
Monday to De la Torre's murder in a speech delivered to a
government audience. A spokesman said the president would have no
comment on the situation in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its just a police matter,'' a presidential aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who belongs to the center-right National Action Party,
said that during Zedillo's visit to Baja California last week, he
realized that the president had no plans to mention the rising
narcotics violence in Baja California. As the two drove together to
a joint public appearance in Mexicali, on the border east of
Tijuana, the governor asked the president to address the drug
problem, Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, in his speech, Zedillo promised to send his
interior minister and attorney general to Tijuana to review federal
crime efforts in Baja California. Spokesmen for those officials
said Monday that they would travel to Tijuana on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Zedillo was touring Tijuana on Friday, his Foreign
Ministry was lodging a formal protest against Ambassador Jeffrey
Davidow of the United States, who said last week that Mexico had
assumed a leading role in international drug trafficking. Davidow's
statements provoked an outpouring of recriminations from Mexican
politicians, many from Zedillo's governing party, who view any
commentary about organized crime in Mexico by foreigners as an
attack on national pride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
