<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS29-COX     02-28 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's attempt to make amends with Catholic voters may be too
late
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush hoped for redemption with
his mea culpa to Catholics, but the gesture may be too late to save
him in New York's important March 7 Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was treading water in New York before he sent a letter
Monday to Cardinal John O'Connor that also went to Catholic leaders
in other states. The letter expressed regret for Bush's Feb. 2
appearance at Bob Jones University, an evangelical South Carolina
school that bans interracial dating and has an anti-Catholic
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the flap over the speech will cost Bush votes in New
York _ a Super Tuesday prize with 101 delegates _ isn't known yet.
But some New Yorkers are asking how Bush strategists could have
failed to foresee the potential cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you don't pick your own Willie Horton,'' Lee
Miringoff, head of the New York-based Marist Poll, said of the
tactical move that could hurt Bush as much as the prison furlough
issue helped his father against Democrat Michael Dukakis in 1988.
``Usually, that's something cast upon you. You don't volunteer.''
</P>
<P>
   A Marist College poll taken after the South Carolina primary had
Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain in a statistical dead heat. A
Zogby International poll released Monday _ too soon to gauge the
effect of the controversy _ found McCain leading Bush 45 percent to
39.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, if McCain has a good week, he could impact New
York in a way that no one ever foresaw awhile ago ...'' Miringoff
said. ``Why talk at Bob Jones University? Catholics are the largest
single voting group in New York for Republicans ... The dug-out
chatter is Bob Jones University, so this has gotten very
interesting, very competitive. All bets are off in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   New York has 2.4 million Catholics and they make up an estimated
54 percent of Republican voters. Losing the state would be
especially bruising for Bush because only Republicans can
participate, not the independents and Democrats who thwarted him in
heavily Catholic Michigan last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been fighting the anti-Catholic label since the McCain
campaign paid for calls to Catholic voters in Michigan telling them
that Bush spoke at Bob Jones and emphasizing the school's
anti-Catholic philosophy. McCain initially said that he did not
know about the calls. Later, he said he signed off on the script.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its defense, the Bush campaign sent an opinion piece
to newspapers in Super Tuesday states and Catholic publications
across the country Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to set the record straight about the
governor's record of inclusiveness and his record of welcoming
people of all faiths into politics,'' campaign spokesman Scott
McClellan said of the pieces. ``Despite, promising not to engage in
negative tactics, Sen. McCain is playing upon people's religious
fears in pitting people against one another.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush backers such as New York Gov. George Pataki
took to the airwaves and talked with reporters to defend their
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest that there's either insensitivity or bigotry
anywhere in here is really a gross injustice ...'' said Rep. John
Sweeney (R-N.Y.), who is Catholic. ``It's the kind of divisive
politics that I think, in the end, leads only to bad things and
negativism. Enough of this. Somebody's got to be the adult here and
I think George Bush is doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King (R-N.Y.) said he believes the issue could cost
Bush New York. King, who is Catholic, switched his allegiance to
McCain to protest Bush's decision to speak at Bob Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter is a partial step but I think the way it's being
perceived here in New York ... was that he got the benefit out of
Bob Jones in South Carolina and he waited three or four weeks to
express his regret on the eve of the New York primary,'' King said.
``So, I think it's being looked upon pretty much as a political
move.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who is ill, has seen Bush's letter, but will have no
comment, said Joseph Zwilling, Archdiocese spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Scully, spokesman for the Catholic League for Religious
&AMP; Civil Rights, said that as far as his group is concerned, Bush is
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hammering the governor for not coming out and
disavowing and disassociating himself'' from the university's
anti-Catholic bias, Scully said. ``The best he could do was, 'My
brother's a Catholic, my sister-in-law's Catholic. What we were
looking for was him denouncing the anti-Catholic policies of Bob
Jones University, which he has done. The Catholic League accepts
that and we feel that should settle the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
