<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-GATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS INTERNET NEXT TECHNO BONANZA, GATES SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Microsoft founder Bill Gates, whose acumen at
developing and marketing software has made him the world's
wealthiest man, Monday declared wireless Internet access will be
the next big technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft wants to be there and provide the software that
makes it happen,'' Gates told 25,000 attendees here at the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association's annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   In his first appearance at the annual convention, Gates
announced a new pact with wireless carrier Nextel Communications
that by next month will bring access to Microsoft MSN Web content _
including its popular Hotmail electronic mail service _ to Nextel
subscribers, among them tens of thousands of Greater Boston users.
</P>
<P>
   And without divulging exact figures, Gates, who recently moved
from chief executive to chief software architect, said the company
has decided that of the billions of dollars it invests annually in
product development, ``the wireless area would receive the greatest
increase of all the things we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that this is an industry sitting on the verge
of unbelievable opportunity,'' he said in an opening keynote
address of Wireless 2000. ``Wireless is really the key component
that's going to take these kinds of (Internet) empowerment that
we've always believed in and make them a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Microsoft's alliance with Nextel, people who have Nextel
phones _ which feature a two-way radio capability that makes them
popular with businesses _ will be able to use the phone to read
their Hotmail messages and get access to other services at the MSN
Web portal such as news, weather, and stock quotes. Pricing for the
service has not yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Hotmail, a free e-mail service, has more than 56 million active
accounts, Gates said. By setting up filters at the Hotmail portal,
subscribers could choose to have alerts sent to their phones when
they get messages from certain recipients, then click a button on
the phone to read the messages if they want. Users could respond to
messages by forming short text responses with the telephone keypad,
pressing numbers 1 to 4 times to make letters.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna Sanford, a senior Microsoft executive, said the Nextel
pact ``is just kind of the start for us'' and the company is eager
to extend the new MSN Mobile 2.0 service to all carriers serving
each US market. Microsoft announced a similar pact with Vodafone
AirTouch, which chiefly serves Western US markets but is combining
its US operations with Bell Atlantic mobile.
</P>
<P>
   People with digital cell phones that can send and receive e-mail
already can gain access to Hotmail through the www.mobile.msn.com
site, but Sanford acknowledged the company has not aggressively
promoted it. One advantage to linking Hotmail with Nextel and
AirTouch service is that many wireless carriers, including Bell
Atlantic Mobile and Sprint PCS in Boston, require people to have
separate e-mail accounts for their phones.
</P>
<P>
   Also addressing the convention was William E. Kennard, chairman
of the Federal Communications Commission, who said wireless is
emerging as ``the premier network for the 21st century. . . . I
believe we will look back and remember this as the time when the
Internet migrated out of clunky, cumbersome machines called PCs and
into a wide array of handheld wireless devices.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennard said growth is running up against limits caused by a
shortage of radio-wave spectrum. While the FCC plans this year to
sell space now used by television channels 60 to 69 and ``C-block''
spectrum owned by bankrupt carriers for new wireless uses, Kennard
said problems of ``spectrum drought'' loom.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he has directed FCC staffers to develop efforts to
create a secondary market for reselling and buying allocated but
unused spectrum, including a Web site listing all available
frequencies by licensee. The FCC also will promote
``software-defined radios'' to make better use of existing
frequencies, Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Zeglis, chief executive of AT&AMP;T Wireless, for which AT&AMP;T
is expected to offer a tracking stock in what could be a $10
billion-plus offering, told convention attendees that the wireless
industry now ``is about where black-and-white televisions were in
the 1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two percent of Americans now use wireless communications
devices, a ratio that could double if US usage reaches the usage
levels in parts of Scandinavia, and Zeglis noted that growth is
almost entirely due to ``the first application. This is only on
voice.'' As wireless data applications grow, Zeglis predicted
another huge wave of growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
