<SLUG> BC-MIT-ENDOWMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALUMNUS TO GIVE MIT $350M FOR BRAIN STUDY INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An alumnus who made his fortune publishing such books as
``Internet for Dummies'' said Monday that he and his wife will give
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology $350 million to establish
an institute for the study of the human brain.
</P>
<P>
   The gift from International Data Group founder Patrick J.
McGovern Jr. and his wife, entrepreneur Lore Harp McGovern, is
believed to be the largest ever pledged to a US university.
</P>
<P>
   The McGoverns considered six other schools before selecting MIT.
The director for the McGovern Institute for Brain Research will be
Phillip A. Sharp, who won a Nobel Prize in medicine in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The previous record for a donation to a US university appears to
have been 1998's gift of stock from the Ingram Charitable
Foundation to Vanderbilt University that the Chronicle of Higher
Education estimated to be worth about $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts can be tricky to measure, said Chronicle managing editor
Douglas Lederman. They can be doled out over time, and assets such
as stock shares can appreciate or fall in value.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the late Sir Harold Acton donated a large Italian
estate and a Renaissance art collection to New York University.
Estimates of the gift's value have varied widely, ranging from $250
million to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Emory University received a gift valued at $295
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of MIT, the McGoverns have agreed to donate $5
million annually over 20 years, along with an adjustment for
inflation. The bulk of the gift, or an estimated $250 million, will
be donated in the final year of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The McGoverns said they only learned last week that their gift
could be the largest ever to a university. The gift's size was
based solely on their estimates of what it would cost to establish
a 300-person research center, they said.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the typical case of a rich alumnus giving to his
alma mater. In looking to establish the McGovern Institute for
Brain Research, the couple evaluated seven universities as they
searched for the ideal environment and academic culture where their
institute could flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Among other schools considered were the California Institute of
Technology, Columbia University, and Stanford University _ but not
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year evaluation process led to the selection of MIT,
which has made advances in neurosciences a strategic priority.
</P>
<P>
   While Patrick McGovern acknowledged an emotional bias toward his
alma mater, he said, ``MIT won on the merits.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, MIT was selected because of its expertise in such
disciplines as neuroscience, molecular neurobiology,
bioengineering, cognitive sciences, computation, and genetics.
</P>
<P>
   The McGoverns declined to detail how also-rans were winnowed
out. When asked which school was runner-up, they had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The McGoverns said they hoped the selection process would focus
more attention on neurosciences on other campuses and inspire other
philanthropists to follow their example.
</P>
<P>
   As for the institute itself, the McGoverns said they hope it
will yield findings about human behavior that someday will reduce
misunderstanding, distrust, and conflict among individuals,
societies, and nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move into the knowledge economy, we hope that the
interdiscipliniary research at the McGovern Institute will lead to
improvements in receiving, analyzing, associating, storing,
retrieving, and communicating information,'' said Patrick McGovern,
62, who graduated from MIT in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   MIT president Charles M. Vest said the McGoverns' gift will have
major significance for the university.
</P>
<P>
   The brain institute, he said, ``will launch one of the most
profound and important scientific ventures of the next century and
what will surely be a cornerstone of MIT's scientific contributions
in the decades ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McGoverns said they have been fascinated by the workings of
the human brain since childhood. As a teenager in Philadelphia,
Patrick McGovern said one of his favorite books described the brain
as a ``machine that thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Germany, Lore McGovern recalled a visit to a
museum where a human brain was preserved in formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my parents, `Can I touch thought?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of establishing an institute for brain research is one
they've thought about for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Both McGoverns have connections to the Whitehead Institute, an
MIT research center for biomedical study. Their experience at
Whitehead convinced them that a center of similar size and scope
could make big strides in neurosciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen how much scientific progress can be achieved in an
institute dedicated to a specific mission,'' Lore Harp McGovern
said. ``It is my hope that in our lifetime, we will be able to
point proudly to the McGovern Institute for Brain Research and its
important contributions to enhancing human learning,
communications, and quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for director Sharp to assemble a team of 16
investigators to study the brain, including 10 new faculty members.
In all, the institute would employ about 300 people and have an
annual budget of around $20 million, with much of the financing
coming from research grants. At some point, a building will be
constructed for the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Monday was the 36th anniversary of the
incorporation of Patrick McGovern's company, IDG. Boston-based IDG
operates about 250 Web sites and publishes about 300 magazines,
including Macworld and PC World. IDG had 1999 revenues of about
$2.56 billion. In October, Forbes magazine estimated McGovern's
worth at $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lore Harp McGovern, meanwhile, has headed companies that have
produced educational materials and feminine hygiene products. She
also is an inventor who holds several patents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
