<SLUG> BC-CITIBANK-RETIRE-ART-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP CO-CHIEF EXECUTIVE SAYS HE WILL RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 1,2,22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending one of the most extraordinary careers in American
finance, John S. Reed, co-chief executive of financial services at
the giant Citigroup, said Monday that he plans to retire on April
18 after the company's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Upon the departure of the 61-year-old Reed, the chief
executive's reins at the company will be held solely by Sanford I.
Weill, who helped Reed orchestrate the megamerger of Reed's
Citicorp and Weill's Travelers Group to create Citigroup in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Weill, 66, suggested that he may retire from the company in two
years, at which time he hopes that a new chief executive will be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who was named to a
non-executive, senior position at Citigroup late last year
reiterated that he will not be a candidate for the job. ``I said I
had no intention of being the CEO and I will not be the CEO,''
Rubin said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's retirement was not forced by the bank's board, nor did it
arise from any personal animosity between Weill and Reed, according
to both executives and to others at Citigroup. Instead, the move
was a recognition that power-sharing at the top of Citigroup was
failing badly and was a poor way to manage a complex, globally
based corporation still beset by internal turf wars resulting from
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Reed's departure only signals that similar, hard-minded
decisions about how to manage Citigroup effectively still lie
ahead. ``There are too many coaches and people have been
complaining,'' said a senior Citigroup executive who requested
anonymity. ``It hasn't been a pleasant place to work.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, turf battles haven't prevented Citigroup from turning in
superior financial results at a time when many other big banks have
stumbled badly. Although Citigroup has not met the earnings targets
promised when the merger was announced, it has already demonstrated
that it has the ability to pump out billions of dollars in profits
each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's announcement was sudden, but not entirely a surprise.
Last year he and Weill divided their managerial duties. Reed was
given authority over Citigroup's Internet strategy and other
technology initiatives. Weill, in a move that cemented his power at
Citigroup, was given the corporate equivalent of the crown jewels:
responsibility for supervision of all other operational lines at
the bank and the all-important right to determine compensation
packages for his managers.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Weill had essentially outmaneuvered Reed, a view
held by many at the company and on Wall Street, although one that
Reed, a wily corporate survivor, may not have shared.
</P>
<P>
   Guessing about Weill's possible successor was the game of the
day on Wall Street Monday, and many inside and outside Citigroup
speculated that the issue would ultimately be resolved through a
merger. In that regard, American Express' well-regarded president
and designated chief executive, Kenneth I. Chenault, is a
particularly compelling candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Chenault on board would represent a trifecta for Weill.
American Express has considered merging with Citigroup in the past,
and a deal would beef up Citigroup's already gargantuan credit-card
portfolio and card-processing network; Weill has long espoused the
need for greater black representation on Wall Street, and Chenault
is black; and Weill left American Express in the 1980s after a
falling-out with then chairman James Robinson, so buying American
Express would be a dramatic finish to a career of deal-making for
Weill.
</P>
<P>
   American Express said its policy is not to comment on ``market
rumors.'' Chenault does not take over as chief executive at
American Express until next year, and if a deal is made with
Citigroup, it is likely to happen after that.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jay S. Fishman, head of Citigroup's property and casualty
insurance unit, is seen by many Citigroup insiders as a strong
internal candidate to succeed Weill. Some analysts also thought
that Rubin's thinking on the matter might evolve, despite his firm
denials.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Citigroup rose $1, or 2 percent, to $49, in extremely
heavy trading _ an implicit signal by the market that Reed's
retirement is a strong step toward resolving some of the company's
managerial woes.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Reed leaves Citigroup after a 35-year career in which
he wore and bore the mantle of a wunderkind after becoming
Citicorp's chief executive in 1984 when he was just 45. His career
has witnessed giddy highs and some notable lows, but it ends on a
note of unique accomplishment in an industry that has sorely lacked
visionaries and risk-takers such as Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the world change,'' Reed said in an interview Monday,
noting how banking has been transformed by innovation and by the
blurring of traditional lines between commercial and investment
banking _ a shift marked by the creation of Citigroup. ``When I
started in this business, we had fixed-rate loans and played a lot
of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The polestars of Reed's business life at Citicorp were a
fascination with consumer banking and a strong international bent.
To achieve his goals, he went in many different directions: hired
marketing wizards with no banking experience; coolly churned
through a series of talented executives before leaving them by the
wayside; pursued with monkish determination such nascent banking
technologies as automated teller machines; and ignored, and then
sharply scaled down, a once formidable corporate banking business
that nearly brought Citicorp to ruin in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The final act of his career, and one that was characteristically
risky, was the merger with Travelers, a move that created the
world's largest financial services concern, recommitted Citicorp to
corporate banking, and hitched the merged company's fortunes to the
unproved virtues of cross-selling financial products.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said in an interview Monday that his fondest memories of
the bank will be the consumer business he built and the people he
worked with _ the latter being a surprising comment from someone
who has often had a somewhat eccentric detachment from his
colleagues. He said his worst memories were of the real-estate and
international lending fiascos that left the bank teetering in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's decision to retire began in conversations with Weill
after Citigroup's board meeting about five weeks ago and continued
through a recent management retreat in Arizona. Reed and Weill
presented the decision at a meeting with Citigroup's board on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although some at Citigroup said the board meeting was rancorous,
Reed, an engineer by training, said he made the decision for one
reason: because it made sense. In that capacity, Reed will leave
the banking industry as he once came in _ coolly analytic and
rational.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
