<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NY-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SUPPORTERS IN NEW YORK QUESTION STRATEGY, CHANCES IN
PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also NY-POLL) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the New York primary just one week away, many of Bill
Bradley's top supporters have become bewildered by his strategic
decisions and pessimistic about his chances in a state that had
once been seen as the vanguard of his presidential hopes. Bradley's
decision to spend six consecutive days in Washington state is
increasingly being viewed as an emblem of a campaign that has lost
its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is he doing in Washington? Nobody knows,'' one of his
senior New York supporters said, simmering with frustration. ``He
should be in New York. We have made the best case we could. I don't
understand it. There's nothing to win in Washington,'' the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you find out why they are there, please let me know,'' said
Ed Koch, the former mayor of New York, reflecting what has become
the consensus among state Democrats who had once enthusiastically
defied the party establishment in New York to endorse Bradley. ``If
you look at it, and you want to be honest, you have to say that
things are getting worse, not better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the retiring Democrat of New York
and Bradley's most prominent supporter in the state, has repeatedly
expressed his frustration to Bradley and his associates in recent
days, but to no avail, according to Bradley's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said that he still believed Bradley could win, but only
if he returned to New York, and that a victory there was essential
to the future of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He absolutely has to win New York,'' Moynihan said. He
asserted that a victory remained possible, but added, ``it will
take intensive campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Bradley had not announced a date for returning
East. He campaigned in Seattle before heading for California in
preparation for a debate there Wednesday. Vice President Al Gore,
Bradley's opponent, was in New York last Thursday, and plans to be
in the state for parts of Thursday, Saturday, Sunday and Monday, an
aide said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In focusing on Washington, Bradley's aides have argued that the
former senator needed to win an election to be taken seriously, and
that Washington appeared to offer the chance for that. And Bradley,
speaking at a women's health clinic in Seattle Monday, dismissed
the complaints, arguing that he had maintained a regular, if
long-distance, presence in New York state through paid
advertisements and satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been everywhere, while I've been here,'' Bradley said.
``And that's one of the advantages of politics today.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual in presidential campaigns for leaders in one
state to grouse that their candidate is spending too much time in
others. But Bradley's decision to devote so much attention to a
contest that most Democrats view as marginal _ it is a nonbinding
vote; no delegates will be chosen _ has shaken some supporters.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly because many believe that their candidate
has _ though some now say had _ a real chance of defeating Gore in
New York, if he had devoted a significant amount of time and energy
there.
</P>
<P>
   It was once difficult to imagine a state more hospitable to
Bradley and his campaign than New York. The former senator from New
Jersey is the popular sports hero from the state next door, the
kind of earnest Democrat that does well with New York's primary
voters. And he is running against a Southerner, giving him a
cultural advantage in this resolutely Northern electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Polls had once suggested that New York was a state where Bradley
might indeed defeat the vice president. But a New York Times/CBS
News poll of registered Democrats in New York, taken from Thursday
through Sunday, when Bradley was moving his small campaign troupe
from one side of Washington to the other, found Gore with a
26-point advantage over Bradley, with 55 percent, compared to 29
percent. (The poll of 382 Democratic primary voters had a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.) In October,
by contrast, a Times/CBS poll found Gore had 42 percent, with 37
percent for Bradley, a statistically insignificant difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are many New Yorkers who take significant
exception to this strategy,'' said Jacques DeGraff, Bradley's
deputy campaign manager and the head of the New York effort. ``I
recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were defending or endorsing the strategy, DeGraff
just sighed. ``I accept it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's national press secretary, Eric Hauser, speaking from
Washington  &QR; 
state, said that Bradley had decided to turn his attention there
after concluding he would be unable to win attention in New York,
California or any of the other large states holding primaries on
March 7, because of the amount of interest in the Republican
contest between Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The calculation, Hauser said, was that a strong showing in
Washington would light a fire of interest under Bradley's
languishing candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, if we can do really well here in Washington,
and make up a lot of the ground that we're behind, if we can
actually win the state, there could be nothing more helpful in New
York,'' Hauser said. ``If we can win out here, it will create a big
surge.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But a number of factors would appear to be working against what
Rep. Jerrold Nadler, the Manhattan Democrat supporting Bradley,
unenthusiastically described as Bradley's ``Hail Mary pass.'' For
one thing, the contest in Washington has attracted little attention
so far. In addition, three Republican primaries are taking place
Tuesday and given the intense interest evoked by the Republican
competition, they seem certain to overshadow a Democratic contest
where not a single delegate will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bradley wins Tuesday night, it has the potential of
being a shot fired but not heard. The polls in Washington close
after the evening news, and after the first round of deadlines for
East Coast newspapers. On Wednesday, when Bradley might have hopes
of a rebound, he is scheduled to engage in a debate with Gore, the
last before the March 7 primaries, which will almost certainly
compete with the Washington results for attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it will make a difference anywhere,'' said Tony
Bullock, Moynihan's chief of staff and one of the Bradley
supporters who have been critical of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning Bradley's actions, his New York supporters spoke
more in anguish than anger, reluctant to criticize a public figure
that they said they admired, particularly during a time of obvious
strife. Several said they recognized that his campaign was running
out of options, and said they were reluctant to second-guess the
decisions it had made.
</P>
<P>
   But Koch said he could not resist suggesting how Bradley might
have stopped this from being an opportunity lost. ``Get out on the
street,'' Koch said. ``Creating a tumult. Putting his presence on
the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Del Giudice, a co-chairman of Bradley's New York
campaign, said he had accepted the decision made by the candidate
and was doing his best to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to second-guess the national campaign,'' he said
over the weekend, which he spent not at campaign headquarters but
at his weekend home upstate. ``They made a judgment, and we're
going forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
