<HEADLINE>
FOR AIRLINES, INTERNET ISN'T JUST A FARE FINDER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From comparison shopping for fares to giving passengers timely
information on delayed or canceled flights, the airlines say that
the Internet is proving to be a valuable tool that reduces business
costs and speeds information. Eventually, the airlines say, it will
even change how crowds move through airports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest developments is a plan by four American
airlines _ Continental, Delta, Northwest and United _ and 23 others
that have since joined in, to operate a Web site where consumers
can shop for fares on all 27 airlines and, eventually they hope,
all other airlines as well. The site has yet to be named, but it is
expected to be launched in late spring, and may eventually sell
shares to the public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Burnett, a vice president of the Boston Consulting Group,
which is managing the startup, said that each airline would
independently set fares and that the site would present
side-by-side the best fares available, including specials that each
airline now only offers at its own Web site and that are often 5
percent to 10 percent lower than the lowest published fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the site will give more choices to the consumer,''
Burnett said &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most major airlines already know one another's published fares,
because each participates in the four major reservations systems _
Amadeus, Galileo, Sabre and Worldspan. The airlines hope to sell
more seats on the new Web site and wean ever more customers from
travel agents, who charge the airlines commissions. Taking
reservations by phone, they say, is also more expensive than having
individuals make their own online arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are trying to lure customers to their Web sites by
giving out inexpensive benefits, like extra frequent flier miles,
for buying e-tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the airline industry supports the joint Web
site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When airlines decide to work together, consumers should
beware,'' said Richard Branson, the founder of Virgin Atlantic
Airlines, which is not involved in the project. ``Airlines'
creating an Internet site together is generally anticompetitive, or
could become anticompetitive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In time, others are expected to follow Continental and Alaska
Airlines in installing airport kiosks, connected to the Internet,
where passengers can buy tickets, select seating and obtain
boarding passes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also proving useful in other ways, some not so
obvious to passengers. When a January 1999 storm shut down Midwest
airports, stranding some passengers on grounded planes in Detroit
for more than five hours, United Airlines used the Internet to
announce to employees and passengers much more rapidly than ever
what decisions they made about which flights to cancel and how to
reroute passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The computer took less than a second to decide which flights to
cancel, which planes to reposition and to make other changes that
reduced the numbers of passengers stuck on planes by diverting them
to other airports, said Kurt Ebonhoch, a United spokesman. ``It
took us about 24 hours to get back to normal operations, not three
or four days'' as it would have a few years earlier, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has tried to find out the status of a flight on a
day when weather interferes with schedules knows, airline workers
often lack accurate information, especially at the gate. But United
has integrated its flight information so thoroughly that when a
flight from Omaha to Chicago is canceled by officials in Nebraska,
the arrival and departure boards in the airports at both cities are
automatically updated within seconds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While that kind of coordination of information may take years to
become a standard at the airlines, a related service made possible
by the Internet is being adopted much more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Continental, Northwest and United now instantly send notices
about delayed and canceled flights by e-mail to passengers who sign
up for this free service at their Web sites; other airlines are
expected to follow quickly. Those passengers whose e-mail is
integrated with their pagers or cell phones get the news about
delays or cancellations within moments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of opportunity to use the Internet to reach out
to our mobile passengers,'' those who use cell phones and palm
computers, said Kevin McKenna, Continental's director of electronic
marketing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon, McKenna said, are e-tickets allowing travel on more
than one airline and transfer to another airline when a flight is
canceled, as well as customized timetables that can be downloaded
to wireless hand-held computers and advanced cell phones. Such
timetables will allow passengers to see what other flights are
scheduled to their destination and to book a flight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet means personalization, customization and actively
reaching out to you,'' McKenna said. ``These improvements will
mean, within 10 years, that when you arrive at the airport, you
will be able to check yourself in, and the only line you will have
to stand in is the one going down the aisle of the plane to your
seat.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
