<SLUG> BC-GORE-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S INTERVENTION RESTORES CARE FOR ILL BABY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ In all the hyperbole of political campaigns, it is rare
that a candidate gets quick, tangible results, but Vice President
Al Gore seems to have done it, persuading the nation's biggest
health insurance company to show more generosity to one of its
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours of Gore's appeal to the company, Aetna Inc., to
continue coverage for a 6-month-old baby born with severe brain
damage, the company agreed to do so, reversing an earlier decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur N. Leibowitz, chief medical officer of Aetna US
Healthcare, a unit of Aetna Inc., said the company would continue
to cover private-duty skilled nursing care as long as the child
needed it.
</P>
<P>
   The child, Ian Malone of Everett, Wash., cannot eat or swallow
normally. He receives nutrition through a feeding tube and requires
continual assistance to help him breathe.
</P>
<P>
   On a campaign trip to Seattle on Sunday, Gore met with members
of the Malone family and then highlighted their plight in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, Dylan Malone, a graphic artist, rejoiced on
Monday. ``The vice president literally saved Ian's life,'' he said
in an interview. ``I couldn't have exposed Aetna's behavior without
Al Gore's help.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Malone on Feb. 15, the regional director of Aetna
US Healthcare said, ``Ian does not qualify for the private duty
nursing care benefit'' offered under the family's health plan.
Aetna suggested that Malone and his wife, Christine, hire nurses or
provide sophisticated medical care to the baby themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier letter denying coverage, Aetna told Malone, ``This
is the final level of administrative appeal available to you under
your health plan, and this means that your administrative remedies
have been exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Leibowitz said: ``The vice
president's involvement and the publicity surrounding this case
over the weekend led us to make a decision in an expedited fashion.
We don't normally work on Sunday nights. These are truly agonizing
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Aetna had suggested that he put his son up for
adoption so that the state or someone else could take financial
responsibility for Ian's medical care.
</P>
<P>
   But, Leibowitz, a pediatrician, said, ``It's a surprise to hear
that statement.'' He said he did not know what Ian's case manager
might have told the family, but he insisted that ``it is
absolutely, positively not'' the policy of the company to recommend
the adoption of children requiring expensive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Malone said that an accident had occurred at the time of
Ian's birth, as he was delivered by a licensed midwife at a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The midwife made several mistakes,'' and the baby was taken
immediately to a hospital for emergency care, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Malone case comes amid a furious national debate over
managed health care and patients' rights. Both houses of Congress
passed bills last year defining a wide range of patients' rights,
including the right to appeal decisions denying coverage. The House
version, but not the Senate's, would also allow injured patients to
sue insurers and health maintenance organizations. Negotiators from
the two chambers will meet soon in an effort to iron out the
differences.
</P>
<P>
   The Malone case illustrates a question at the heart of the
national debate over patients' rights: What is the definition of
``medical necessity,'' and who defines what is medically necessary?
</P>
<P>
   At a rally on Monday in Denver, Gore said: ``It's time to say to
insurance companies and HMOs that decisions on health care must not
be made by the accountants and bureaucrats, who don't have a
license to practice medicine or to play God. The decisions should
be given back to doctors and nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said that the vice president
called Leibowitz on Monday and thanked him for the company's latest
decision. Gore told Aetna that the marketplace often rewarded
companies for being compassionate and responsive to consumers,
Lehane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
