<SLUG> BC-NY-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 POLL SHOWS CLOSE RACE BETWEEN BUSH AND McCAIN IN NEW YORK  
(sw) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle for the Republican presidential nomination remains
tight in New York state, and most voters might still change their
minds, according to the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Among registered Republicans who say they would probably or
definitely vote on March 7, 46 percent support Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas and 36 percent favor Sen. John McCain of Arizona. Alan
Keyes is preferred by 3 percent, and 15 percent have not yet
decided.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide telephone poll was conducted Thursday through
Sunday with 1,034 registered voters, of whom 281 said they were
Republican primary voters. Since there is a margin of sampling
error of plus or minus 6 percentage points for each candidate, a
candidate needs to be ahead by at least 12 points for the lead to
be statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   Half of McCain's supporters consider their minds made up, but
two-thirds of the Republicans who favor Bush said it was ``still
too early to say for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Most New York voters favor an open primary, and almost half of
non-Republican voters in the state might vote in the Republican
primary next week if they could do so legally. McCain would receive
the support of 48 percent of these hypothetical non-Republican
primary voters and Bush would be the choice of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in New York state are almost evenly divided on
whether a Republican candidate who appeals to Democrats and
independents in open primaries has a better chance of attracting
voters across the board in the general election. with 42 percent
saying that drawing Democrats and independents during the primary
season will help in November and 39 percent saying it will not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
