<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REV-DOLLAR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-police chief fails to follow his own order to return $1,000
gift to church
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before leaving the department, former Fulton County
Police Chief Louis Graham told 100 of his officers they should not
spend $1,000 checks given to them by a church until questions about
their legality had been answered.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham retired from the department shortly after his order,
and took the check from World Changers Ministries with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not received a check from him,'' said police Chief
George Coleman, who took over the job when Graham retired in
November. ``There has been no statement that he is going to return
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 45 additional officers who received checks and
apparently cashed them, have missed a Feb. 14 deadline to return
the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The officers have asked for an installment plan so they can
repay the money. Under county rules, the officers who don't comply
with the order to return the cash face a range of sanctions,
including termination.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said county officials haven't yet agreed whether to
allow an installment plan or garnish the officers' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who could not be reached Monday for comment, left the
department before the Fulton County ethics board ruled in December
that the officers had to return the money. The board ruled that
keeping the money violated the county ethics code and advised the
officers to return it. The money will be returned to the church,
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what the county can do to force Graham and two
other officers who left the agency before the ruling to return the
money, said H. Michael Harvey, ethics board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   World Changers Ministries, a church led by the Rev. Creflo
Dollar, presented 100 south Fulton officers with $1,000 each during
a November breakfast last year to recognize their service to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Before handing out the checks, Dollar was pulled over in October
by a Fulton County police officer and ticketed for running a red
light in his 1999 Jaguar and failing to have proof of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. K.L. Hawkings urged a magistrate to reduce the two
citations to warnings. Coleman said Monday that Hawkings, a 15-year
veteran, has been given a written reprimand, received additional
training on traffic ticket procedures and is subject to
reassignment for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Coleman said:
</P>
<P>
   _ 48 officers have returned their checks.
</P>
<P>
   _ 45 have said they need an installment plan to return the
money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three officers, including Graham, left the department before
the ethics board ruling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two officers resigned their jobs, for unrelated reasons, after
the ruling. The department has sent them letters asking for the
money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two officers have not responded to Coleman's request to return
the money and are being investigated by internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
