<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRASHEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASHEAR HAS LITTLE RECOLLECTION OF MCSORLEY BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His memory of the incident is nonexistent, which is certainly
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Canucks forward Donald Brashear made his first public comments
during a news conference in Vancouver Monday and discussed his
feelings a week after Bruins defenseman Marty McSorley viciously
swung his stick and connected with Brashear's right temple.
McSorley was suspended for the remaining 23 games of the regular
season _ an NHL record for an on-ice incident _ as well as the
postseason and if he wants to return, he must apply to commissioner
Gary Bettman for reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear, who suffered a Grade 3 concussion (the most severe),
is just trying to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch the tape, you can see I was out before I fell on
the ice,'' said Brashear, who landed headfirst with his helmet half
on, half off.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, there were reports that Brashear was up and
about in the Canucks' medical room. Monday, he said he does
remember waking up, but wasn't sure where. He has headaches every
day, which is consistent with the degree of concussion he suffered,
and isn't supposed to exercise at all for a minimum of two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He's expected to be sidelined for three weeks and depending on
how well he recovers, it could be quite a bit longer. Brashear said
he feels fortunate it wasn't much, much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy that I can walk right now and be on my feet and
see my 4-month-old son, and keep living,'' said Brashear, who had
been playing the best hockey of his career. ``But I'm not going to
feel as good as when I'm going to be able to put my skates back on,
give a hit or take a hit, or get into a fight for my teammates. I'm
not going to change the way I play the game in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley expressed his deep remorse after the incident and
publicly apologized to Brashear. He also tried to privately
apologize to Brashear but was unsuccessful because Brashear wasn't
there to take the call. Brashear said it might not have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would have talked to him,'' he said.
``Sometimes I wonder what went through his mind to do a thing like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brashear was criticized for going to the Boston bench and
flexing his muscles in an effort to taunt the Bruins prior to the
incident. He said he didn't recall that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much I remember,'' he said. ``But I remember that
was a game that I had to play hard, where I was just doing my job.
I remember we got into a fight right off the start. Those are all
things that I have to do during a game. In a game you try to make
people lose their focus by any different way. Certainly not be
hitting someone in the head with your stick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver police are in the midst of an investigation that
could lead to assault charges against McSorley, but Brashear said
he's not concerned with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something I care about, that I think about every
day,'' he said. ``What I think about the most is getting healthy
and getting back in my skates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
