<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSIONER SELIG BANS STRAWBERRY FROM BASEBALL FOR ONE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBA-ARATON-COLUMN) 
(jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry was suspended for one calendar
year Monday by the baseball commissioner Bud Selig, a ruling that
could signal the end of Strawberry's calamitous career.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry flunked a drug test Jan. 19, his third violation of
baseball's drug aftercare program. Selig considered giving him a
chance to return sometime this season _ as he did last year, after
Strawberry's second violation _ but instead applied a firm penalty.
The earliest Strawberry could return to baseball would be Feb. 28,
2001, less than two weeks before his 39th birthday, and only if
Strawberry adheres to the terms of his aftercare program, including
stringent drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry could not be reached for comment. Charisse
Strawberry, his wife, answered the phone at the couple's home here
Monday, and with emotion filling her voice, she declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Selig met with Strawberry and his wife last week in his
Milwaukee office. ``I had no doubt that his remorse and sorrow were
genuine,'' Selig said, in a statement released by Major League
Baseball, ``and I worried about the effect my decision would have
on his health and the welfare of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I could not ignore Darryl's past infractions and
concluded that each of us must be held accountable for his or her
actions. I am hopeful that he will use the time away from the game
productively and will care for himself and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Baseball Players Association is not expected to
contest the decision. Selig called George Steinbrenner, the
Yankees' owner, with his decision Monday afternoon, according to a
baseball official, and as Steinbrenner walked out of Legends Field,
he did not seem surprised or disappointed. ``That's the
commissioner's ruling, that's what we'll abide by,'' he said. ``My
hopes and prayers are with Darryl that he can hold his life
together, and make the changes he has to make and deal with this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was expected to be the Yankees' designated hitter
against right-handed pitching this year, and after his electrifying
return to the team the last two months of last season, teammates
expected him to have a big year. His bat speed was incredible, he
looked great in his off-season workouts, and Bernie Williams and
others spoke of his hitting perhaps 25 to 30 home runs during the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   As he has so many times before in his career, Strawberry dashed
the recent hopes for him. But after teammates learned of his
suspension Monday, they preferred not to speculate on whether he
might play again. Rather, they fretted about what Strawberry would
do next, outside of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   They have come to know Strawberry, through the months of
traveling with him, playing alongside him, seeing him diagnosed
with colon cancer, seeing him sick as he went through chemotherapy.
They know Strawberry's four kids, and that Charisse Strawberry is
pregnant with another. They know how much he loves to play
baseball, how he thrived on those moments when the crowd chanted
and he had a chance to swing big.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to start getting his life in order,'' said Derek
Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop. ``Now he knows what's ahead of him.
If baseball is still in his plans, he can deal with that later.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams called it ``a very sad situation. It seems like nothing
comes easy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Paul O'Neill: ``He has a lot of close friends here, a lot
of friends who would help him any time he needed help. I don't
think anybody in here condones drug use by any means. But on a
personal level, there's a lot of people, including myself, that
would do anything they could to help him through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius' locker at Yankee Stadium was located only a few
feet from Strawberry's, and like Strawberry, he was part of the
team's prayer group. ``It's got to be a tough thing, because I'm
sure baseball was one of the things he was able to use to fight
this,'' said Brosius. ``Now, he's losing the ability to come to the
park, and not only work a job, but to cheer for guys who cheer for
him. There's a support thing there that may not be there on an
everyday basis. At this point, all we can hope for is that he gets
the support he needs, whether it's through us or wherever, and he
can just battle through this thing and look forward to things past
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre repeatedly mentioned how he hoped Strawberry
would find something else to focus on, something else to which he
could dedicate himself, now that he is out of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, where do you proceed from
tomorrow on, without the ability to go out to the ballpark?'' Torre
said. ``That's the important thing right now for Darryl to
straighten out in his mind, and this is where the family takes on a
much more significant role.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry indicated to officials from Florida's Department of
Corrections that he is building a home in this area, and Strawberry
has served about half of an 18-month probation sentence he received
last year, following his arrest and plea of no contest, and he must
complete the last 50 hours of 100 hours of community service. After
Strawberry failed the drug test last month, state officials
recommended that he undergo increased evaluation, counseling and
testing; he is not faced with a jail term for his probation
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who has amassed significant debt, would have been
paid $750,000 in salary this year, and technically, he cannot
receive that money because he is not allowed to play baseball. But
Steinbrenner has looked after Strawberry since he gave the former
Met another chance in baseball in 1995, and he indicated last week
that he will continue to support him; presumably, that might
include some sort of financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, Darryl can hit home runs, but I think George goes beyond
that with his feelings toward Darryl and his family,'' said Torre.
``I'm sure George is wounded by this thing. I'm sure the bigger
feeling is hoping that Darryl is going to be all right, and we
don't know that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
