<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-875&AMP;AD     02-28 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIDER QUITS PARTY LEADERSHIP POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Bowing to international pressure, Joerg Haider resigned
Monday as leader of the anti-immigrant Freedom Party that he had
taken from a marginal fringe group to a powerful national force in
Austria over the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt resignation, just three weeks after the Freedom Party
brought the ire of Europe down on Austria by joining a government
coalition, reflected the country's discomfort at its isolation. But
it also suggested a tactical maneuver consistent with Haider's long
history of keeping his opponents off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, 50, has repeatedly changed strategy since becoming
leader of the Freedom Party in 1986, switching from attacks on the
European Union to pro-European statements, and directing his appeal
alternately to workers and business. In this light, his resignation
may prove to constitute one step back with a view to a more
vigorous advance.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, it will shield him from criticism if the coalition
with the conservative People's Party proves unpopular, while
allowing him to consolidate his credentials as governor of the
southern province of Carinthia. His ultimate aim almost certainly
remains to emerge as Austrian chancellor, should his party come to
dominate national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing his resignation after an emergency party meeting
Monday night in Vienna, Austria, Haider said he did not ``want to
be seen as a shadow-chancellor'' and felt it essential to clarify
that the party's six ministers in the government were not looking
over their shoulders to ``get the approval of the man in
Carinthia.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider added that he felt overburdened with the twin jobs of
Carinthian governor and party leader. But he stated plainly, ``This
is not a withdrawal from politics.''
</P>
<P>
   His statement made no mention of Austria's diplomatic problems.
But the resignation was clearly linked to Austria's growing
realization that punitive measures imposed by the European Union
are serious, and that the country's plight could become acute if
the government does not do everything possible to break out of its
isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 governments of the European Union that have frozen
relations with Austria and downgraded contacts with Austrian
ambassadors to a ``technical level'' will now face the delicate
task of deciding whether Haider's resignation removes the grounds
for these punitive measures.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from European governments, but
it appeared likely that, before making any decision, they would
wish to study what precise role Haider will now play. The character
of the Freedom Party has of course not changed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The intrusion of the European Union on Austria's democratic
choice of government has set off a furious debate on the Continent
over the extent of national sovereignty in a union that has already
pooled its currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, whose energetic and charismatic command over the party
has been little short of absolute, was replaced by one of his most
faithful lieutenants, the current vice chancellor, Susanne
Riess-Passer, 39. So fierce is her loyalty to Haider that she is
widely known in Austria as ``the King's cobra.''
</P>
<P>
   The life of the coalition has already been made extremely
difficult by a series of bristling remarks from Haider, who did not
himself join the government, for tactical reasons. The most
provocative of these _ and a possible reason for his resignation _
was a statement last week that Europe's new shared currency, the
euro, amounted to a ``miscarriage.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the euro is weak, and the new government of
Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel has been trying to impress its
neighbors with its European good faith, Haider could scarcely have
made a more damaging comment.
</P>
<P>
   It coincided with a statement from a leading member of the
Freedom Party, Franz Rauter, that Austria should simply withdraw
from the European Union if the sanctions are not lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, such remarks, pounced on by the Austrian press, made
the already difficult task of Schuessel close to impossible. The
coalition has already shown strains over economic policy,
particularly the issue of how severe austerity measures should be.
</P>
<P>
   The statement about the euro was typical of Haider's sometimes
reckless style, one that has seen him make isolated remarks
praising aspects of the Third Reich, including Hitler's labor
policy, only to turn around and apologize.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath this meandering, sometimes wayward political course,
a real nose for winning Austrian votes has always been evident.
Haider has won the following of the extreme right with his
intermittent revisionism, drawn in many workers by playing to their
fears about immigrants, and attracted entrepreneurs with a
free-market message.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, whose party won 27 percent of the vote in elections last
October and so broke up the 30-year-long domination of the Social
Democrats and People's Party, said that his resignation pointed to
a ``new orientation for the party.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be more specific, but it appeared that the
revisionist and xenophobic remarks that have earned the Freedom
Party notoriety will be excluded from the party's message in an
attempt to establish its credentials as a viable European
government force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Martin Schmidt, a Freedom Party member and the Austrian
transport minister, said Haider's resignation amounted to ``one
step back, two steps forward.'' Peter Sichrovsky, a Freedom Party
member of the European Parliament, said Haider would now be able
``to prove his capacities as a future chancellor'' by concentrating
on his mandate in Carinthia.
</P>
<P>
   A small state tucked away in southern Austria is not likely to
satisfy Haider's ambitions, even if he manages to keep a low
profile for a spell.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Haider said: ``I am tired of this
stupid, noisy scene. After 30 years in government, the Social
Democratic party does not accept a change in Austrian democracy and
has been mobilizing all its friends around the world. They want to
break our government, but they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Christa Zoechling, the author of a book about Haider, said: ``He
quit because he is hurt that foreign governments and media have not
accepted his apologies. He is tired of saying he is sorry and he
wants to be seen as a statesman. The only problem is that he is not
a statesman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
