<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: EYES ON THE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So China is now telling Taiwan: Marry me or I'll kill you. And
Vice President Al Gore is now telling the unions: Vote for me and
I'll get you a better deal with China next time, even though my own
administration negotiated this deal. And together they are making a
God-awful mess of what is a fundamental U.S. interest _ that
Congress ratify China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   It's now going to be very tempting for Congress _ caught between
the right-wingers who have been energized by the threats from
Beijing against Taiwan and the left-wingers who have been energized
by Gore's ambivalent support for his own trade negotiators _ to
walk away from the Clinton deal for bringing China into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be more reckless. This is the time to keep our
eyes on the prize, and the prize remains the stable, steady
transformation of China into a responsible member of the world
trading system and into a more free and open society. Few things
are more important for world stability than that.
</P>
<P>
   The best tool we have for advancing that _ not a foolproof tool,
not the only tool, but the best tool _ is to Gulliverize China by
globalizing China. And that's what this WTO deal helps to do _ by
requiring the Beijing government to permit more Chinese citizens to
do business directly with the outside world and be less dependent
on their own government, by requiring China to allow U.S. Internet
companies to own 50 percent of Internet start-ups in China, and by
requiring China to put in place trade rules where corrupt,
arbitrary officials now hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   The reason China's leaders cracked down this year is because
they are terrified that the personal freedoms the Chinese people
have gained in their lives and jobs during the last decade of
openness will lead to demands for more political freedom. And they
will _ especially with the WTO deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's why if ratifying this WTO accord now means looking past
China's bluster on Taiwan, then so be it. If ratifying this deal
now means ignoring the pandering of the vice president _ who knows
better, who actually understands globalization, and who should be,
and could be, the administration's most articulate, in-your-face
advocate of this deal, but who has bowed instead to the AFL-CIO and
its fatuous nonsense that you improve worker and environmental
standards abroad by dictating them to others, not by free-trading
with them _ then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it means ignoring the self-interested lobbying of the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which just wants WTO passage because it's
good for business _ then so be it. As the Council on Foreign
Relations expert Michael Mandelbaum says: ``Some things are in the
national interest even though the Chamber of Commerce believes
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Our choice with China is not between deterrence and engagement.
You always need both. ``China is not a threat to dominate Asia the
way the Soviet Union was a threat to dominate Europe,'' notes
Mandelbaum. ``It lacks the power, the ideology and the will. The
only place where China threatens U.S. interests is with Taiwan, and
there U.S. military power is tacitly deterring the Chinese and must
continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But we keep this deterrence card hidden so as not to embolden
the sometimes reckless Taiwanese into thinking that they can
achieve independence and security without negotiating their
relationship with Beijing. China is bellowing now precisely because
it wants negotiations and is trying to strengthen its hand for
these inevitable talks. China is so dependent on Taiwan and America
today for investment and trade that it cannot afford to invade
Taiwan without paying a devastating price. China still may invade.
Countries do crazy things. But Beijing will think about it a lot
longer than you imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy is about playing the odds. And since we are already
deterring China militarily, the odds say that the best way to
reinforce that is by bringing China into the WTO, increasing the
costs for Beijing of any military adventure, and fostering the
internal changes inside China that might one day make it more like
Taiwan, and therefore better able to solve its differences with
Taiwan peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are in our favor, if we play our cards smart. That
means understanding China's bluster for what it is, and it means
understanding Gore's pandering for what it is, and looking beyond
both with our eyes on the prize.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
