<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: MORE MEETINGS
</P>
<P>
   Britain's secretary for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, met
with Catholic and Protestant leaders in Belfast to try to unblock
the stalled peace agreement. Britain suspended the power-sharing
Ulster government Feb. 11 because of the Irish Republican Army's
refusal to start disarming. Sinn Fein's president, Gerry Adams,
said it was up to Britain to restore the administration. The Ulster
Unionist leader, David Trimble, said it was up to Sinn Fein to make
a move on IRA weapons first.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PASSPORTS FOR PETS
</P>
<P>
   Britain has begun allowing animals with ``pet passports''
proving that they are free of rabies to enter the country without
having to spend six months in quarantine. The animals must be
fitted with an identity microchip, and be vaccinated and tested by
a licensed veterinarian to ensure that the vaccine is working. If
there is no outbreak of rabies in Britain within the next year, the
plan, which applies to dogs and cats traveling to Britain from 22
western European countries, will be expanded to include pets from
the United States, Canada and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CUBAN ON HUNGER STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban diplomat expelled from the United States after being
accused of spying was on a hunger strike on Monday at the Cuban
Embassy in Ottawa. The diplomat, Jose Imperatori, 46, caught
Canadian officials off guard when he bolted from the airport in
Montreal for the Cuban Embassy in Ottawa, leaving his wife and
3-year-old son to fly on to Havana. Lloyd Axworthy, the Canadian
foreign minister, said that Imperatori was in Canada on a transit
visa and that he expected him to leave for Havana shortly.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MONEY LAUNDERING NETWORK
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities said they had dismantled a money laundering
network used by a drug gang that controls the production and export
of methamphetamines. The gang, headed by the Amezcua family, based
in Jalisco and Colima states, set up savings and loan associations
to launder drug profits, which were later invested in real estate,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: ENVOY GOES HOME
</P>
<P>
   With negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians still at
an impasse, the State Department's chief Middle East peace
negotiator, Dennis Ross, said he was returning to Washington to
consult with the White House. His week of meetings with leaders on
both sides did not succeed in ``overcoming the difficulties'' that
have deadlocked the talks, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL: ELECTION RUNOFF LIKELY
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its history, Senegal was expected to hold
a run-off election to choose a president for the next seven years.
Results from voting on Sunday were not expected to be finalized
until later this week. Neither President Abdou Diouf nor his main
rival, Abdoulaye Wade, appeared to be able to garner the 50 percent
of the votes necessary to win in the first round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
