<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BAHAMAS-DEVELOP-ART-N     02-28 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHAMAS-DEVELOP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHAMIANS RESENT LOSS OF BEACHES TO LUXURY DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT19, and a graphic are being sent.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds., spelling variants Wylly and Whylly are CQ) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW PROVIDENCE, Bahamas _ The tourists who scuba dive among the
reefs and tan themselves on the sandy shores have probably seen
more of this island's coastline than Therell Bethell ever has. She
cannot remember the last time she visited a decent stretch of
beach, since the development boom over the last decade brought
gated communities and exclusive resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bahamians do not have access to the beach,'' said Bethel, a
legal secretary in Nassau. ``Bahamians have to have a puddle in our
backyards to swim.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-simmering resentment over the loss of their beaches has
crystallized in opposition to a proposed luxury community on the
longest remaining stretch of undeveloped coastline in New
Providence, the most populated island in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The development, Clifton Cay, would take up nearly two miles of
seaside land for 600 homes built around a marina and interspersed
with amenities like a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Hubert Ingraham supports the
development, in keeping with its policy of wooing newcomers who
bring money and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend that their battle is not only over access to
the beach but also over access to their history. Their cause has
been taken up both by environmentalists, who fear damage to
delicate reefs, and by preservationists. The site is dotted with
the ruins of 18th-century plantations and slave quarters, as well
as the buried artifacts from two Lucayan Indian villages that date
back 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   International preservation and conservation groups have offered
support, saying this is a rare resource of natural beauty and
historical richness. [In February, Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., the
environmental lawyer and son of the late senator, contacted the
project's main backer, a Bechtel family trust, to urge that the
environmental impact be studied in more detail.)
</P>
<P>
   The developers, who plan to begin construction in the next two
or three months, say they will protect the ruins and not harm the
environment. Opponents are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem in the Bahamas today is that our
government does not understand that money is not everything,'' said
Keod Smith, a Nassau lawyer. ``They feel if they show economic
activity, capital injection and tax revenues increase, when you
look at the books, it looks great. But do we sell our heritage just
because we want some money?''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see the site's appeal: turtles and dolphins glide
through the water, and conch shells, iridescently pink, are
scattered on the sandy shore. Thick, inland brush offers protection
from winds and floods, and nearby wetlands are filled each winter
with flocks of migrating kestrels, ospreys and warblers.
</P>
<P>
   Treasures are tucked among the trees or buried under the sand. A
few years ago, Laurie Wilkie, an archaeologist from the University
of California at Berkeley, began to study the remains of an
18th-century plantation owned by William Wylly, who was known for
trying to improve conditions for and extend rights to slaves.
Wilkie found bits of ceramic, tobacco pipes and bottles at one part
of the site. At another spot, she examined the ruins of slave
quarters and a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Her most remarkable find came in the late 1990s after
preservationists expressed alarm that the proposed development
might destroy remains of a Lucayan Indian village, and the
government asked her to research its boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   She said that her findings led her to conclude that a
development should not be built there. Between the information
about early Indian inhabitants and 18th century plantation life,
the site is a veritable Rosetta Stone for understanding life on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents one of those rare arenas where you can study
the whole extent of the human experience in a location, starting
with the Lucayan villages,'' she said. ``I can't think of another
site that contains all this.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the findings are especially valuable because the
government kept good records about slavery during the plantation
period. ``This is so rare,'' she said. ``To look at African history
and talking about individuals, and tie that to archaeological
remains is very unusual. We are not talking about nameless,
faceless people, but individuals who have a very real identity and
experience of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   The descendant of one of those slaves has become one of the most
outspoken opponents of the development. Vivian Whylly, a
38-year-old Nassau businessman, said he had traced his roots to
Esther Whylly, his great-great-great-grandmother, who was a slave
on the Wylly plantation and like many slaves, took the owner's last
name. He filed a claim on the land; it has been unsuccessful so
far, but he plans to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Whylly would like to see the land become a national park, where
people could go to learn about the island's earliest settlers.
Preservationists have started a fund to purchase the land,
obtaining commitments of nearly $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whylly said he often visits the area, to soak up the spirits
that he feels still dwell among the ruins. ``It keeps their spirit
alive to know that this is where the people who would be my
foreparents lived,'' he said. ``Their spirit says don't let us
become enslaved again.''
</P>
<P>
   The project's developers, Chaffin Light &AMP; Associates, said they
were willing to protect the ruins and would create a fund financed
by home and property sales to create a learning center accessible
to the public. They said they were working with the government to
ensure that no environmental harm would come from the construction.
They acknowledged that previous environmental impact statements
were insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The developers have also set aside a 500-foot stretch of beach
for the public, but they contend that the issue of shoreline access
should be reviewed in a broader context.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue we respect,'' said Jim Anthony, president of
the Clifton Cay Co. Ltd. ``But the debate is larger than Clifton
Cay.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate goes even deeper than the vanishing public shoreline
and is touching off passions about the island's identity and its
future. Independent only since 1973, the Bahamas has had much new
foreign development in recent years, thanks to Ingraham's
initiative. Developments like Clifton Cay, officials say, create
jobs _ a priority for the current government.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what our people needed for a better way of life and
education,'' Said Earl Deveaux, the top environmental adviser to
the prime minister. ``What country is concerned about preserving
artifacts when it is scraping by for a living or for food?''
</P>
<P>
   But Sam Duncombe, an advocate here for environmental
preservation, said the developments cater too much to outsiders
without regard to the needs of Bahamians who want to see the
shoreline preserved for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain ilk of American who believes the world is
their oyster,'' Duncombe said. ``We resent it. To them it's money.
To us it's who we are. It's our peace of mind. It's our soul.''
</P>
<P>
   To allow the project to continue, she said, would revive one
tradition _ that of the pirates that used to hide in the inlets not
far from where the homes are planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of pirates still exists,'' she said. ``They no longer
have beards and long coats.'' She said she sees some government
officials as modern-day pirates. ``They are selling us out,'' she
said. ``We need foreign development. But at what price?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
