<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN TARGETS FALWELL, ROBERTSON IN ATTACKS 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. _ John McCain denounced two of the Christian
right's icons in their own home state Monday, calling them ``agents
of intolerance'' to whom Republican politicians pander to the
detriment of GOP traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of Ronald Reagan,'' McCain said, ``not Pat
Robertson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell also was in the Arizona senator's sights
at a high school in the Atlantic coast town, where Robertson's
televangelical empire and the Christian Coalition are based.
Falwell's evangelical church and political arm are based in
Lynchburg in the western part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia holds its Republican primary Tuesday along with North
Dakota and Washington state. Washington also has a nonbinding
Democratic contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed McCain's attempts to cloak himself in the mantle
of former President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan didn't point fingers. He never played to
people's religious fears, as Senator McCain has shamelessly done,''
Bush said in Bellevue, Wash. ``He's playing the religion card.
That's not Reaganesque. It reminds me of the current
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech could prove to be a defining moment in his
effort to broaden the party's appeal to the Democrats and
independents who have largely given him his front-runner status.
McCain narrowly leads Bush in delegates, 96-93, following Bush's
sweep of U.S. territories during weekend primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal Republicans, particularly those who consider themselves in
the religious right, have voted steadily for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain took pains to aim his attack not at conservative
Christian voters but at ``a few of their self-appointed leaders.''
To that end, he was accompanied by former rival Gary Bauer, a
social conservative leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer
reaches of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether
they be Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton on the left or Pat Robertson
and Jerry Falwell on the right,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Robertson and other Bush supporters, as well
as the governor himself, for misrepresenting his views on
campaign-finance reform, abortion and other issues, charging that
the distortions of his record had led party members to label him
``disloyal.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also offered no apologies for his appeal to Democrats and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is the height of foolishness to build a wall
around our party in fear that we are so narrowly defined that new
faces and fresh ideas in accord with our basic principles will
jeopardize our values,'' McCain told a cheering crowd in the packed
gymnasium of the Franklin Cox High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is more than the sum of its divided parts, and so our
party should be.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain also used his speech to condemn ``union bosses'' with
close ties to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Describing them as ``mirror images of Pat Robertson,'' he
accused them of subordinating ``the interests of working families
to their own ambitions'' and ``their desire to preserve their own
political power at all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, we are building a new Republican majority, a
majority to serve the values that have long defined our party and
made our country great. Social conservatives should flock to our
banner,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain went on to boast that he is the only ``Reagan
Republican'' in the race for the GOP nomination capable of
defeating presumed Democratic nominee Al Gore in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Governor Bush is a Pat Robertson Republican who
will lose to Al Gore,'' McCain said, charging that his major
opponent had allied himself with those who practice the ``political
tactics of division and slander.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush took offense at such remarks, saying, ``There's no room in
our process, shouldn't be, for people who ascribe beliefs to me
which I don't believe and I don't share.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Sen. John Warner, a former Navy secretary, criticized
the speech by the former Navy pilot: ``I have to tell my old friend
to pull back on his throttle and quit trying to fire heat-seeking
missiles up everybody's tailpipe.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Robertson and Falwell came after a telephone
campaign they ran in South Carolina and Virginia that painted
McCain as a pro-abortion rights candidate and referred to his
co-chairman, former Sen. Warren Rudman, as a ``vicious''
anti-Christian bigot.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Kennedy, chief of staff to Bush's Washington state
chairman, U.S. Rep. Jennifer Dunn, said recorded calls are being
made all over the state alleging that Bush has stayed silent on his
visit to Bob Jones University, whose leader has made anti-Catholic
statements. Similar calls were made in Michigan before its primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is trailing Bush in Virginia, and some of his aides are
concerned that his harsh attack on the state's leading Christian
leaders will hurt his chances even more.
</P>
<P>
   As for his chances in Virginia, McCain said, ``I'm not worried
at all because I think the majority of Virginians will reject the
politics practiced by Pat Robertson.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign officials did not choose the venue by accident.
By wading into the heartland of GOP Christian supporters, McCain
sought to contrast the visit by Bush earlier this month to Bob
Jones University in South Carolina, where Bush gave his standard
stump speech to a school that bans interracial dating and whose
founder has made virulently anti-Catholic statements.
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy criticism, Bush on Sunday apologized to Catholic
leaders for not repudiating the school's attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
