u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-28 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WINLESS IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It would be nice if Bill Bradley could win the
Washington primary Tuesday. He deserves one really good night from
this campaign. Even Steve Forbes had his presidential moment, for
heaven's sake, when he came in first in the Arizona primary four
years ago. (The Forbes campaign tended to describe that victory,
which involved 34 percent of the vote, in terms normally reserved
for the winning of World War II, or at least the invention of
penicillin.)
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign, although dogged and determined, is getting
to be like Jim Bowie at the Alamo, down to its last round of
ammunition and exhibiting an ominous cough. So a week ago Bradley
made a tactical retreat to the state of Washington, hoping that if
he does better than expected here, the momentum might propel him
back into the voting public's line of vision.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Washington Democratic primary is actually just a
pretend election that's supposed to ``advise'' the party caucuses
in March, the state is used to being ignored. But last week it was
positively crawling with candidates searching for the Big Mo, all
waving brand-new position papers about pipeline safety and
ferryboat subsidies. Al Gore arrived bearing a new TV commercial,
which depicts his recent climb up Mount Rainier in terms usually
reserved for the conquest of Mount Everest, or at least the Steve
Forbes primary victory in Arizona. John McCain bowed to the state's
fierce interest in nature by redefining himself as a ``conservative
conservationist,'' which seems to be a compassionate conservative
who recycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``State's primary suddenly a big deal,'' announced Seattle's
Sunday paper in a banner headline. Everybody has taken sides on the
controversy over whether some of Washington's dams should be
breached to give the endangered salmon a clear path to their
spawning grounds. I will summarize their positions:
</P>
<P>
   McCain: I'm keeping an open mind. What would Teddy Roosevelt
have done? Beware the Death Star, Luke.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush: Save the dams. Let the salmon walk. Usher in the
era of responsibility. Got a great wife. Love my kids. Klaatu,
barada nikto.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley: As a U.S. senator, I freed salmon in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore: Did I show you the pictures of me at the top of Mount
Rainier?
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has drawn some good crowds here, but the campaign has to
be driving him nuts. His themes are the classic priorities for
women voters _ health care, the environment and gun control _ but
he's suffering a serious gender gap in the polls. There's never
been a white candidate for president more focused on racial
healing, yet the black vote is going to Al Gore. While Bradley has
been busy denouncing Gore as a closet conservative and trying to
herd his natural constituents back, the rest of the flock has
broken to the right and run off to follow John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Bradley, I'd be tearing my hair out,'' agreed Jim
McDermott, a Seattle congressman who is Bradley's star local
supporter. Generally buoyant, McDermott has developed a tendency to
note in rather mournful tones that Bradley is ``a very serious guy
who'd make a great president'' and then begin reminiscing about
Walter Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   It is unarguably crazy that voters who believe in things like
gun control and universal health coverage and abortion rights would
rally around McCain, who doesn't. ``He doesn't even  &UR; have &LR;  a health
care policy,'' Bradley said rather plaintively. On the other hand,
the McCain campaign offers the promise that fighting for reform can
be exciting and fun, while Bradley gives it the aura of a slightly
depressing duty, like tooth-flossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed wicked smart, but he's not, like, a wow,'' one
student told his friend as they staggered away from a Bradley
speech on economics at Columbia University last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is the ant who planned his campaign meticulously, while
McCain is the grasshopper whose staff didn't check until last week
to see what primaries come after March 14. It is an excellent
example, people, in how life is unfair. Or maybe this is just Fate,
evening the cosmic score. Remember Princeton, Bill? The Rhodes
scholarship? The Olympic medal? The Knicks championship? The
Senate? It's payback time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
