<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upcoming Georgia primary draws little interest from lawmakers
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At Georgia's Capitol _ like much of the state _ you
would hardly know there's going to be a presidential primary next
week.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the Golden Dome's politicos long since committed to
one front-runner or the other, the presidential contest is a matter
of distant interest as the session rolls on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of fell into the Bush camp, and sit there quietly,''
Sen. Tom Price, a former Elizabeth Dole supporter said. He might
not be the only Republican legislator in a similar posture.
</P>
<P>
   McCain fever may be spreading elsewhere in Georgia, but Rep.
Clint Smith of Dawsonville was a lonely figure sporting a McCain
pin in the House on Monday. Despite being vastly outgunned by the
forces of Gov. George W. Bush, Smith was undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   He planned to speak for McCain the morning of March 7 at the
Senate GOP caucus. So far, Charles Tanksley, the governor's
Republican floor leader, is the only senator supporting McCain, but
Smith was confident that with enough time, more Republican
legislators would come around.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he acknowledged, is that the primary's only a week
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had citizens calling the McCain headquarters and wanting
to get active,'' Smith said. ``I think it'll be an interesting
week.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, just about all the interest in next
Tuesday's primary can be summed up in a single question: Why is
Terry Coleman supporting Bill Bradley?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a buck-the-trend attitude,'' the House Appropriations
chairman said, explaining his decision to buck Vice President Al
Gore, the choice of Gov. Roy Barnes, Speaker Tom Murphy and the
rest of the Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman and Rep. Tyrone Brooks, who don't often vote in the
minority together in the House, are on Bradley's Georgia steering
committee. That list may not be long on legislators but it's chock
full of names from other circles: the King scholar David Garrow,
Alliance Theater director Kenny Leon, Atlanta City Councilman C.T.
Martin, R.E.M. attorney Bertis Downs and Atlanta Newspapers
Chairman Anne Cox Chambers, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman remained cordial in his opposition, saying Bradley has
served a useful role as a ``sparring partner'' for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor was giving me the devil about it the other day,
and I told him if he didn't have Bradley in the race, the vice
president would have been very overconfident, and he'd still be way
behind (Bush) in the polls,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   A dull, predictable Gore victory next week would be to Rep.
Calvin Smyre's liking, but even the vice-president's state chairman
acknowledged wistfully that it would have been nice if Georgia
weren't voting in a traffic jam next week, to ``define it more and
give it some thump.''
</P>
<P>
   How to put more ``thump'' into the front-loaded nomination
process was the subject of the Democratic National Committee
regional hearing Saturday. For this year, if there's going to be
any thump, it will have to come from the voters' own initiative.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
