<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNSET LIMITED SHUFFLE LEAVES SAN ANTONIO OUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PHILIP CAUTHON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak plans later this year to scrap passenger
train service connecting Houston, San Antonio and El Paso, instead
rerouting the Sunset Limited Line north from Houston through Dallas
and Fort Worth, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is part of nationwide expansion of rail service
that will make Fort Worth a major hub in the nation's financially
shaky passenger rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials also announced plans to begin daily passenger
service between San Antonio and Monterrey, Mexico, and providing
daily departures on the Texas Eagle connecting San Antonio and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak President George Warrington said San Antonio would be
eliminated as a stop on the east-west Sunset Limited as soon as
fall. The line _ which connects Orlando, Fla. and Los Angeles _
will be rerouted north from Houston to serve more populous markets
in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a difference in Amtrak is about making money,''
Warrington said, addressing the substantial loss of service to West
Texas and other rural areas. ``Sometimes you have to make some
difficult calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrington said that the Sunset Limited's doomed southern route
serves only about 30,000 customers a year. He predicted the
northern route will generate increased ridership.
</P>
<P>
   Helping boost that ridership would be plans to extend passenger
service from Meridian, Miss., through Shreveport, La., and Dallas
to Fort Worth, he said. Meridian is a stop on Amtrak's Southern
Crescent line between New York and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas and chairwoman of the Senate
Surface Transportation subcommittee, said, ``I would like to see us
keep the Houston-San Antonio line as the southern route but not in
lieu of the route that would go north into Dallas-Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
