<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HSIA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATIONS TO BEGIN IN GORE FUND-RAISER'S CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: R.I., Calif.)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After listening to testimony for nearly three
weeks, a federal jury will begin deliberating Tuesday over the fate
of Maria Hsia, a longtime fund-raiser for Vice President Al Gore
who is charged with operating a scheme to disguise campaign
donations to Gore and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Both the prosecution and Hsia's defense completed their final
arguments to the jury Monday. Hsia and her lawyers did not put on
any witnesses of their own, relying solely on cross-examinations of
the government's witnesses to make their case that she is not
guilty of the five felony counts she faces.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Hsia was at the center of an
operation in which she persuaded fellow Asian-Americans to make out
checks to either the Clinton-Gore campaign, the Democratic National
Committee or the re-election effort of Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, a
Rhode Island Democrat. The government said that those people who
wrote the checks were then reimbursed by people who were the real
donors and who could not legally contribute for a variety of
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Luque, Hsia's lawyer, told the jury that her client
``never told anyone to break the law or give donations in the name
of another person.''
</P>
<P>
   Luque sought to narrow the case before the jury to the five
counts, which do not specifically charge Hsia with the scheme of
finding false donors. The indictment charges that Hsia caused other
people to file false reports with the Federal Election Commission.
Luque argued that Hsia never even spoke with any of the campaign
treasurers who filed the reports.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnany, a prosecutor with the Justice Department's special
task force that is investigating fund-raising irregularities during
the 1996 election, said that the evidence showed that Hsia was
aware of the system of arranging for ``conduits'' or straw donors
to conceal the real contributors and stood silent as false reports
were filed with the election commission.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hsia, in the prosecution's view of the case, who arranged
for the April, 1996, visit of Gore to the Hsi Lai Temple, a
Buddhist place of worship in Hacienda Heights, Calif. Gore's visit
to the temple and the resulting political donations he reaped from
it have proved a deep embarrassment for him and a political
opportunity for his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The event raised more than $100,000 and Hsia is charged with
funneling $55,000 from the temple itself through false donors
including several monks and nuns at the temple. As a tax-exempt
religious institution, the temple is prohibited from making
political donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore initially asserted that the temple visit during the
campaign was not a fund-raising event but rather ``community
outreach.'' He later acknowledged he knew it was
``finance-related.''
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of Gore's appearance at the temple was introduced as
evidence and the Republican majority on the House Government Reform
and Oversight Committee has sought to obtain a copy of it. Judge
Paul Friedman, who is presiding at the trial, agreed to a request
from Luque that the Gore videotape not be released until the end of
the trial lest it be used in political advertisements which might
be seen on television by the jury.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the government's case is the notion that Gore as
well as a succession of Democratic Party fund-raisers were duped by
Hsia, who was really the mastermind of the scheme. The prosecution
presented evidence that at the end of Gore's appearance at the
Buddhist temple, Hsia was told by John Huang, a party fund-raiser,
that there was disappointment that the revenue from the event was
less than $50,000. Huang told Hsia, according to testimony, that
there was an expectation the event would net at least $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Hsia handed Huang an envelope with checks totaling
$100,000, many of them written by nuns and monks of the temple.
Those people were later reimbursed and the government argued that
Hsia was surely aware of what happened and allowed others to file
false reports as to the source of the donations.
</P>
<P>
   But Luque offered a starkly different portrait of the event and
Hsia's role in it. She said that Gore's visit was, in fact, to make
political contact with Asian-Americans and the videotape shows he
did not say any of the things typically associated with a
fund-raising visit, like thanking people for their support.
</P>
<P>
   As to the envelope that was handed the next day to Huang with
$100,000 in checks, Luque said that it was sealed and the
prosecution presented no evidence that Hsia knew what was in it.
``She never saw those checks, she never knew how they were
solicited and she didn't know that anybody was reimbursed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
