<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MUSIC-STORES-NYT &LR;      02-28 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STORES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD RETAILERS SEE DOOMSDAY IN DOWNLOADED MUSIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Texas)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advent of e-commerce and the prospect that consumers will
buy music by downloading it directly from the Internet has strained
the traditionally congenial relations between record labels and
record stores and set off a power struggle between them.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that for all the newfound efficiencies imagined by
a world in which consumers download music from the comfort of home,
it is a doomsday scenario for record retailers, whose livelihood
depends on consumers leaving home to buy their music in a store.
</P>
<P>
   There is little concern that downloading music will become a
major factor in the market for recorded music within the next two
years. Still, the record stores say the labels owe much of their
success to the marketing expertise and customer-relations skills of
the retailers, and as a group they have vowed to fight aggressively
to preserve their place in the sales chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the record companies want to start marginalizing the
retailers, then retailers will start looking to become labels
themselves and signing up bands themselves,'' said Pamela Horovitz,
president of the National Association of Recording Merchants, or
NARM.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a threat many take seriously, although Best Buy, one
of the nation's largest music retailers, has already purchased its
own record label. Even so, it suggests the depth of the feelings at
NARM's annual convention, taking place this week in San Antonio.
Participants say the emergence of online commerce is the dominant,
if not the single, topic of conversation. The mood, they say, is a
mix of some optimism about the prospects for online sales and a
sense of urgency that the record stores are quickly losing ground
in the e-commerce world.
</P>
<P>
   The record labels have the brakes on digital downloads at least
until the middle of the year while they wait for technology that
will protect their copyrighted material from being easily pirated
online. But a more immediate concern is growing competition from
e-retailers like Amazon.com and CDNow and from the labels
themselves, which are increasingly selling compact discs online for
delivery via mail.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Web sites of Trans World Entertainment, one of
the nation's largest record store chains whose properties include
Record Town and Coconuts, logged a mere $246,000 in online sales
during the Christmas quarter, said Gary Balter, a music retail
analyst with DLJ, the New York-based brokerage house. By
comparison, Amazon.com racked up $96 million in music sales during
its fourth quarter, Balter said, illustrating that retailers ``need
to have a more coherent Internet strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Music Land Group, a chain of 1,350 stores in the U.S. with
headquarters in Minneapolis, launched its commercial Web sites for
chains like Sam Goody and Sun Coast at the end of June. Best Buy
has been selling music online since 1997, but it was a bare bones
effort until last summer, when the company named a president of its
online business. It plans to re-launch its site in May.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes will be much higher when consumers can download music
digitally. The record labels, at least in theory, will be able to
sell music directly to consumers, bypassing the retail stores that
have long been the labels' interface with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The record companies say they have no intention of bypassing the
record stores, and, in fact, there are scenarios under which the
stores could thrive in the digital music market. For example,
in-store kiosks could offer customers music downloaded and recorded
on a CD or loaded directly into the flash memory of a digital music
player. Such technologies would reduce stores' inventories while
enabling them to offer greater selection.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Gilbert L. Wachsman, vice chairman of Musicland, said
that e-commerce had already taken a toll on his company _ not in
sales, which have been growing, but in the perception of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Musicland's annual earnings rose from 40 cents a share in 1997
to $1.60 a share last year. But the company's stock price fell 45
percent last year and has fallen 17 percent this year, said Balter,
who noted that Trans World's stock also fell 45 percent in 1999,
also despite strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the stock market is discounting the future of
companies like ours because there is a belief of the threat of
disintermediation,'' said Wachsman. ``Disintermediation'' is the
removal of middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the record retailing industry say they bring a
great deal of value to the market by creating a physical conduit
between the recording industry and consumers and by applying
expertise in merchandizing, inventory and marketing. ``A lot of
companies think that throwing a button on a Web site makes you a
retailer,'' Horovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite these nods to optimism, the record stores aren't
taking any chances. On the last day of January, NARM sued Sony
Music Entertainment accusing the label of using the Internet to
compete unfairly against the record stores.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that in some of its compact discs, Sony is
including a link to its Web site where consumers can buy music.
Thus, the merchants say, when they sell a Sony disc they are
effectively selling a marketing tool for the online retail
component of Sony, a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like if WalMart had to put up a sign referring
people to Target,'' Wachsman said.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the lawsuit, Sony has boycotted the convention.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Sony said NARM has ``singled out Sony Music on
which to project fears and misgivings about the Internet's role in
the future of the music business.''
</P>
<P>
   NARM officials don't entirely dispute that assessment. Horovitz
said the suit was ``looking down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, there is a growing dispute over who will own
the customer information when a digital download does take place.
For instance, if a consumer downloads a song from a retailer's
site, Horovitz said, the retailers are concerned that the labels
will want the information for their own databases, enabling the
labels to market directly to the retailer's customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concerns they won't be able to resist using it for
marketing,'' she said. ``This is exploding into a huge issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
