<HEADER>
A1387 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-2TAK     02-28 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CRACKS DOWN ON CORPORATE TAX SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government on Monday issued new rules to
discourage abusive corporate tax shelters. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers said the proliferation of such shelters ``may
be the most serious compliance issue threatening the American tax
system today.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulations are aimed at forcing the disclosure of new kinds
of tax shelters as soon as they are created so that they can be
reviewed by the IRS and, if found improper, can be banned before
they become widespread. This would replace the current practice of
uncovering the abuses through audits, often years later, and trying
to undo them in court, one case at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations, effective immediately, are intended to curb
the use of accounting methods that have no legitimate business
purpose and are designed solely to lower a company's taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Summers cited one newly uncovered arrangement
that is apparently spreading quickly. A company makes two loans of
equal amounts at equal interest rates to a partner. Later the
interest rate on one loan is dropped to zero, while the interest
rate on the other loan is doubled. The loan on which no interest is
being paid can be counted as a loss on the company's tax return,
while the loan at the doubled interest rate is placed on the books
of an overseas affiliate not taxed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said such transactions ``are devoid of economic
substance'' and serve no purpose except evading taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations would require corporations to disclose
shelters on their tax returns if any two of six conditions are met.
One of those conditions would be that a fee of more than $100,000
was paid to an outside firm for help in creating the shelter. Many
accounting, law and Wall Street firms arrange shelters for a fee.
Another condition would be any understanding that the technique
would be confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations would also require that the firms that arrange
such shelters disclose the deals to the IRS as soon as they begin
offering them. The firms would be required to keep records for
seven years of who bought these shelters, and details of how they
work, and to make these files available to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   To dissuade lawyers and accountants from recommending dubious
tax shelters, the rules that govern the conduct of professionals
representing clients before the IRS will be tightened in the next
six months. Both professionals and their firms will be subject to
suspension and ``in extreme cases'' may be barred from all IRS
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Summers said, a special squad of IRS auditors will
analyze tax shelters and help those who examine corporate tax
returns identify abusive transactions.
</P>
<P>
   He also said meetings will be held to encourage business leaders
to support the attack on tax shelters. This may include calling on
the chief executives of companies that engage in questionable
shelters, and the heads of firms that promote them, to tell them
that their conduct is out of line, said Jonathan Talisman, the
acting assistant secretary for tax policy.
</P>
<P>
   Abusive tax shelters cost the government $10 billion annually,
according to the official Treasury estimate, but Summers said in a
speech Monday that this ``is just the tip of the iceberg'' and the
actual figure may be many times larger.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2100EST &QL; 
