<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-1STL     02-28 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC CENTURY CYBERWORKS TO PURCHASE HONG KONG TELEPHONE
COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: new lede, complete update and rewrite of early version) 
(jt) 
 By ANDREW SORKIN with MARK LANDLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The hometown hero beat the foreign interloper
Tuesday in the battle for Hong Kong's telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   The British parent company of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT voted to
accept a $35 billion stock-and-cash offer from Pacific Century
CyberWorks, an Internet upstart, according to several executives
briefed on the decision. Pacific Century won the bidding over a
similar offer from Singapore Telecommunications, the state-run
phone company in Hong Kong's main Asian financial rival.
</P>
<P>
   The board of Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC, meeting Monday night in
London, selected Pacific Century's bid, despite the seeming
riskiness of such a choice. Pacific Century, which is only nine
months old, has no experience in telecommunications and few
tangible assets. But the board was apparently persuaded by Richard
Li, the company's 33-year-old founder who has emerged as one of
Asia's Internet stars.
</P>
<P>
   Li is the son of Li Ka-shing, a legendary Hong Kong tycoon and
one of the most politically connected businessmen in Asia.
Executives close to Singapore Telecommunications complained Tuesday
that politics played a role in their defeat. Hong Kong and mainland
China authorities had cast a cold eye on Singapore's campaign to
take over Hong Kong's dominant local telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Century marshaled impressive resources in the course
of the serpentine three-week battle. The company lined up $13
billion in loans from a consortium of banks, including Bank of
China, HSBC Holdings, Bank Nationale de Paris and Barclays. It also
raised $1 billion in a share placement in less than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the company said Pacific Century's $35
billion offer consists of about $12 billion in cash and $23 billion
in stock. Cable &AMP; Wireless owns 54.4 percent of Cable &AMP; Wireless
HKT, which means it would receive slightly over $6 billion in cash.
Cable &AMP; Wireless will also receive Pacific Century shares, giving
it a stake of between 10 percent and 20 percent in Li's company.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Hong Kong on Tuesday morning Li said he planned to
turn Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT into a regional power. ``We've got some
very good plans for HKT,'' he said. ``The company has always been
told that it had to stay in Hong Kong because its parent was
expanded internationally. What we plan to do is expand the company
regionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century also made an all-stock offer, which values Cable
&AMP; Wireless HKT at $38.5 billion. But people briefed on the deal
said the British parent company and other shareholders were likely
to opt for stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's victory came after furious last-minute
maneuvering by Singapore Telecommunications. The company announced
that Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. would invest $1 billion in its
campaign. News Corp. also set up an Internet, television and
mobile-phone joint venture with the company.
</P>
<P>
   But Murdoch's involvement was not enough to turn the tide of
sentiment against Pacific Century, which had managed to became the
front-runner for Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT from the moment it announced
its interest in the company on Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pacific Century barged into advanced merger
negotiations between Singapore Telecommunications and Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT, the prospect of such a deal had failed to excite many
people here _ either inside the Hong Kong company, in the
government, or in Hong Kong's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting bigger doesn't necessarily mean they get better,''
said Dylan Tinker, an analyst at Deutsche Securities here said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Telecommunications is perceived as a solid but stodgy
company in a small and still-closeted telecommunications market.
Although Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT had fallen out of favor with many
analysts, it has been competing in Hong Kong's market, which has
been deregulated more rapidly than Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Singapore Telecommunications was not popular
either. Although the Hong Kong government declared it would not
stand in the way of the deal, it was clear that neither Hong Kong
nor the mainland Chinese welcomed the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century, on the other hand, offers the alluring prospect
of turning Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT into the platform for a regional
Internet giant. Li has already assembled a portfolio of stakes in
Internet start-ups that rivals Softbank of Japan and CMGI of the
United States. In two months, he plans to begin a
satellite-delivered Internet-access service known as Network of the
World.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about creating an Internet powerhouse in Asia, with
its roots in Hong Kong,'' said a senior Pacific Century executive,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The more we examine it, the
more we see the strengths of HKT.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, managing a lumbering former monopoly with tens of
thousands of employees will be a steep challenge for Pacific
Century, which is run with all the cheerful chaos of any Internet
start-up. Helping Li somewhat will be his chief deputy, Alex Arena,
who is the former head telecommunications regulator in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts speculate that Pacific Century will carve up Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT _ selling the less attractive local and long-distance
phone business to another phone company, while keeping the
company's Internet-related holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of similar to AT&AMP;T buying up cable assets in the
United States,'' Greg Feldberg, a technology analyst at Indosuez
W.I. Carr Securities in Hong Kong said last week. ``They see that
they need partnerships with local operators, so they feel more
comfortable owning stakes in companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT set up a joint venture with
Star TV, which is owned by News Corp., to create a pay-television
and Internet service. The future of that venture, however, is now
in doubt. News Corp. threw its support behind Singapore
Telecommunications in the battle, and Murdoch might unravel the
venture, rather than go into business with Li.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major imponderables for Cable &AMP; Wireless in the next
few days will be the value of Pacific Century's shares. Under the
stock portion of the deal, the British company will receive 0.71
Pacific Century share for each HKT share. The cash portion will be
7.23 Hong Kong dollars, or 93 cents United States a share.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Century's shares have been suspended for two trading
sessions, which has had the effect of locking in the value of its
stock offer. Some market experts said the stock would plummet once
it begins trading again. One market watcher noted that there was
evidence in the grey market that investors had begun borrowing
Pacific Century shares to short-sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that the shares would have been substantially
lower than they were last week, said Marc Faber, the head of an
investment firm here.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, Faber said he thought Li was wise to use his
stock to bid for a company with genuine assets. Aside from a
portfolio of investments in Internet start-ups, Pacific Century
CyberWorks is a company that exists largely in blue-prints. It has
no customers and no operating profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heyday of Hong Kong Telecom is over,'' Faber said. ``But
when you've got free money like Richard Li does, any purchase is
better than none.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
