u i BC-IRAQ-PILGRIMAGES-NYT &LR;      02-28 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PILGRIMAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN WANTS U.N., NOT SADDAM, TO CONTROL MONEY FOR MECCA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan, in a decision
that is unlikely to be welcomed in Baghdad, has devised a plan to
pay for Iraqi pilgrimages to Mecca without letting the government
of Saddam Hussein disperse the money.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council began discussions on the
secretary-general's plan on Monday. But there were concerns that
the Iraqis might provoke a confrontation if they were denied the
money on their terms. The pilgrimages start this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis, whose foreign earnings are controlled by the United
Nations, are permitted to draw money for the pilgrimages from oil
sale earnings. They had asked for $2,000 for each of the 24,700
pilgrims authorized to visit Mecca by the Organization of the
Islamic Conference. And they wanted the total of $49.4 million to
be deposited in Iraq's central bank so it could be distributed by
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   But Iraq, whose financial dealings are handled through an escrow
account, is not normally given such a large sum of money to handle
as it wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq now says that only about 7,000 Iraqis may make the trip.
But whatever the number, Annan has not agreed that the money should
pass through Iraqi hands. He is proposing that pilgrims be given
about $250 each for the trip out of Iraq, to be supplied through
U.N. offices in Baghdad. The remainder of the money would be
deposited with designated agencies in Jordan or Saudi Arabia, to be
drawn on by Iraqis when they arrived there.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis are now also permitted to fly to Mecca under the December
Security Council resolution, an exemption from a ban on commercial
flights to and from the country. But Iraq has not announced any
flights, and has said only that pilgrims will go by bus, beginning
Tuesday. Six bus groups are planned during the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Annan met on Monday with Hans von Sponeck, the U.N. relief
coordinator in Iraq, who announced earlier this month that he was
resigning on March 31 because he could not do the job of helping
Iraqis under the current sanctions, despite a more liberal
oil-sales program that lifted the ceiling on exports of oil and
made buying civilian commodities easier.
</P>
<P>
   After the 35-minute meeting, U.N. officials said that Annan, who
appeared businesslike and unsmiling as he greeted von Sponeck, made
clear to him that ``United Nations policy on the oil-for-food
program is set by the Security Council.'' But the secretary-general
said he would discuss von Sponeck's views with all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   A report by officials of the oil-sales program here is to be
presented to the Security Council on March 10. It is expected to
show that considerable quantities of not only food and medicines
but also a range of goods to improve schools, hospitals, farms,
water systems and electricity generation are arriving in Iraq
despite holds placed on many contracts by the United States and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Americans in particular are concerned that Iraqi imports are
increasing and becoming more diversified at a time when there are
no arms inspectors on the ground. Without inspections, there is no
way to verify that sophisticated equipment, chemicals or other
materials are not finding their way into weapons programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
