<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-H     02-28 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Ken Caminiti isn't feeling well.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Don't fret; it's just flu-like symptoms this time, which is a
far cry from the acute sinus infection that hospitalized him last
spring and got his homecoming season in Houston off to a rocky
start. Caminiti would prefer the similarities between last season
and this one end right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most frustrating years of my career,'' said
Caminiti, who missed 79 games because of a calf injury.
</P>
<P>
   It was so frustrating he considered retirement, a thought
teammate Jeff Bagwell found hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was he going to go? You can only work on so many cars,''
Bagwell joked, referring to Caminiti's hobby of restoring classic
cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Caminiti insists he was serious, and he's even more serious
when he says 2000 may be his last season in the big leagues. After
11 years of pushing his body to the limit, Caminiti sees the end
nearing, and he has no intention of tarnishing what has been a
wonderful career.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti has seen some of his peers play past their prime and
wants to avoid that.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the final year of a two-year, $9 million contract; the
Astros hold an option for 2001 at $5.5 million. The club can buy
out the option year for $500,000. Caminiti, who turns 36 in April,
turned down a three-year, $21 million offer from Detroit to sign
with the Astros after the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the Astros) want to take care of me and pick up the
option year on my contract, I'll play (in 2001), but I'm not
begging them,'' he said. ``I'm not going to beg to get on a team
anymore. If things work out, fine; if they don't, that's fine, too.
I've already told my wife and a lot of my friends that this is
probably my last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play anywhere else. I started my career in
Houston, and it would be nice to end it in Houston. In my mind,
this was my last contract. I'd like to play next year, I think. But
I don't know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how this year goes. I'm going to have a whole bunch
of fun, let my hair down and play as hard as I can play. Hopefully,
if I'm healthy, everything will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker declined to speculate on
Caminiti's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm focused on this year and trying to win an
unprecedented fourth consecutive National League Central Division
title,'' Hunsicker said. ``Ken is a key part of our club. I'd like
to get past this season before we deal with anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   But if 2000 is as frustrating for Caminiti as 1999 was, he'll
make the decision himself.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries limited Caminiti to 78 games, but he was productive
when he played, hitting .286 with 13 home runs and 56 RBIs.
However, when you're just three years removed from a Most Valuable
Player season (1996 with San Diego), that's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I'm not producing, and I'm getting paid, I always
feel like I'm stealing a paycheck,'' said Caminiti, who hasn't
exceeded 146 games since 1991. ``I've had a good career. I've saved
my pennies, and financially I'm OK. I'd probably go crazy without
the game, because I've never gone without it. But it's getting
close to the end of my career, and I'm trying to go out on a
positive note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think I'm that kind of player (that he was in 1996),
but I don't want to stay in the game longer than I should. It's up
to me to know when that is. Right now, I really believe I've still
got it; it's just a matter of finding it and staying healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying healthy is a tall order for Caminiti, even during the
offseason. All he can do is laugh when the conversation shifts to
the freakish accident in which he fell out of a tree blind during a
hunting trip last fall. He cracked three bones in his back in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid,'' Caminiti said. ``That's all that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker cracks a smile, too. ``That's just
Cammy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Caminiti's offseason mishap sounds worse
than it was. Then again, this is a player some say has the highest
tolerance for pain in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Caminiti is so miffed by last season's injury, which
was first termed a calf strain. An MRI later revealed a muscle in
his calf was partially torn, rather than strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frustrating part about it is that I know myself, and
I know what I can play with in terms of pain,'' he said. ``I've
played with just about everything, but I couldn't play with this. I
couldn't do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was just a strain, and I felt (soft) for not
being able to play with that. Reflecting back on my career, the one
thing I'm most proud of is how my peers view me. They see me as a
guy who's going to play, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Once healthy, Caminiti made up for lost time. He hit .322 with
seven homers and 27 RBIs over his final 28 games and was one of the
Astros' few bright spots in their Division Series loss to the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti hit .417 in the playoffs with three homers and eight
RBIs. The Astros scored 15 runs in the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the only reason I'm here right now,'' Caminiti
said of his strong finish. ``I thought about leaving (the game)
last year. That's how frustrated I was. I know I have a lot to
offer; it's just that injuries have slowed me down the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a good career, and I just don't want it to end in a
frustrating way. As long as I feel like I have something to offer,
I'm going to play, and right now I still feel like I can offer
something to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
