<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1410 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-2NDT     02-28 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: times larger.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The speech, to the Federal Bar Association, an organization of
lawyers who practice before federal agencies, was to have been
delivered by an aide. But Summers decided to deliver it personally.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month an article in The New York Times reported
that the tax burden on individuals rose in recent years while the
burden on companies fell, and a major reason cited was the
proliferation of tax shelters. The article included IRS data
showing that had companies paid taxes in 1997 at the same rate as
in 1990, they would have paid $60 billion more in 1997 alone, while
if individuals had paid in 1997 at the same rate as in 1990, they
would have paid $80 billion less.
</P>
<P>
   Summers began his address by declaring that ``our aim is to curb
illegitimate tax avoidance.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We have no quarrel with the natural desire of
companies and individuals to minimize their tax burden by
legitimate means.''
</P>
<P>
   He quoted Judge Learned Hand's observation: ``There is nothing
sinister in arranging one's affairs to keep taxes as low as
possible. Everybody does so.'' Summers said he agreed with that as
a matter of both law and morality, but added that ``we must draw
the line at the pursuit of engineered transactions that are devoid
of economic substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers also renewed a call for Congress to pass legislation to
help deter abusive shelters, including a 25 percent excise tax on
fees collected by firms arranging such shelters and a doubling, to
40 percent from 20 percent, of the penalty on taxes improperly
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated his call for Congress to enact the ``doctrine
of economic substance.'' That doctrine, created by judges in tax
cases, holds that transactions whose primary benefit is tax
avoidance are not legitimate. Summers said enacting that doctrine
would help ``fight abusive tax shelters on a universal rather than
case-by-case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who chairs the House Ways and Means
Committee, criticized Treasury for not issuing regulations sooner,
noting that Congress passed an abusive-tax-shelter law three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stop abuses and shut down illegal tax shelters,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tara Bradshaw, a spokeswoman for Sen. William V. Roth Jr.,
R- Del., who chairs the Senate Finance Committee, said the senator
would not comment on the proposals until he had studied them. She
said the committee would hold hearings within a month on corporate
tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Rossotti, the IRS commissioner, said that early
disclosure of tax shelters ``will give us better information to
focus our resources'' and will speed up ``a pretty slow and
indirect process'' of hunting for abusive shelters one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that tax shelter promoters keep lists of clients
will allow the IRS, when it finds one tax shelter, to identify all
such shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Summers' call to crack down on illegal tax shelters was praised
by Mike Murphy, executive director of the Tax Executives Institute,
which represents top tax officials at 2,800 companies. But Murphy
said the institute does not agree with each of the techniques
Treasury proposed. For example, Murphy said that doubling the
penalty for abusive shelters may not be effective and may result in
more litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Some institute members, Murphy said, are eager for the
government to attack abusive shelters because they are feeling
pressure from their superiors to match the tax-avoidance strategies
of competitors, even if they must engage in shams.
</P>
<P>
   Summers noted that while individual income tax revenues surged
6.2 percent last year, corporate income tax payments fell 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Treasury was also considering allowing companies to
notify the IRS in advance of tax-avoidance transactions and to
obtain a ruling on their validity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
