<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF PRIMARY, BRADLEY MAKES FINAL PITCH IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The tall, serious man buttoned the top of his
raincoat, and stepped out of the University of Washington
administration building to the cheers of a rally that may have
marked the validictory of his campaign for president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley put on his cheerful campaign face for the boistrous
crowd. On a blustery day, about 2,000 students showed up to cheer
the former New Jersey senator who has bet the future of his
Democratic insurgency on a strong showing in Tuesday's Washington
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we're behind, but (those) people aren't here,''
Bradley told the crowd. ``They don't feel your energy. They don't
feel your idealism.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a day after his front-running opponent for the
Democratic presidential nomination, Vice President Al Gore, had
left town, Gore was still able to make news in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign reported Monday that he had successfully stared
down an insurance company during his visit to Seattle the previous
day.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare said it would continue nursing coverage
for a severely ill six-month-old Everett boy whose parents met with
Gore at Franklin High School. The company had informed Dylan and
Christine Malone that nursing care would end on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't cut off this child's coverage!'' Gore shouted to a rally
after the meeting. As a result of birth injuries, Ian cannot
swallow and deep sunctioning of his nose and throat is required to
keep him alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to make it clear that Aetna U.S. Healthcare will
not cut off any of the coverage that we put in place for this
child,'' Dr. Arthur Leibowitz, chief medical officer of Aetna U.S.
Healthcare, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reviewed this case thoroughly and have determined that
continued coverage is in the best interests of the child. As a
pediatrician, I empathize with this family and believe we've made
the right decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called Aetna to thank the company, then put out the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case shows why we need a real patient's bill of rights,
so that the voices of all families like the Malones will be
heard,'' Gore said in a statement. ``Families need to know they
have somewhere to turn when they are denied health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has staked the future of his campaign on Tuesday's vote,
seeing the Democrats' beauty contest primary as a way to regain
momentum lost as media coverage has focused on Republicans John
McCain and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has often seemed to be trying to run for president
without raising his voice. Monday, before one of his campaign's
best crowds, he spoke in a shout. The wheezy public address system
carried his message of populism to all corners of the university
square.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party can be ``a protector of established
interests,'' Bradley intoned, alluding to a Gore nomination, or it
can ``once again resume its role in campaigning against
selfishness, complacency and indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 10 days, Bradley has given the state its closest,
most extended look at a candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   While describing Gore as a ``conservative Democrat'' from his
days in Congress, Bradley has laid out a liberal reformist agenda.
He has called for federal programs ranging from registration of all
handguns, to scholarship and loan forgiveness to draw talented
young people into the teaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   His delivery has varied with his mood. At an NAACP dinner on
Saturday, in a half-filled Westin Hotel dining room, Bradley
appeared listless, and failed to mention the host organization.
Other times, including a Friday speech in Bellingham and Sunday at
the First A.M.E. Church, he has spoken intensely and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ignored Bradley's challenge for months last year. No more.
He has twice roared into the state for arm-waving speeches
extolling economic successes of the Clinton-Gore administration.
The vice president has echoed a classic message pioneered by
Franklin D. Roosevelt: Don't change horses in mid-stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to keep the prosperity going, but I want to
go beyond that,'' he said Sunday. ``I don't want to see anybody in
America left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has chosen to ignore darker parts of the administration
record, such as its fund-raising excesses of 1996 and his visit to
a fund-raiser held at a Buddhist temple in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked for campaign finance reform for more than 20
years, before any of the other candidates in this race,'' he said
in a Sunday interview. ``I have co-sponsored more than a dozen
pieces of legislation. I support more sweeping provisions than the
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has tried to establish a gap between what Gore promises
and his performance, and between his past actions and present
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Al Gore in the past and Al Gore in the
present, it is hard to know where his convictions lie,'' Bradley
said at a previous University of Washington appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has mocked his foe. On Saturday, the vice president quoted
criticism from the Christian Coalition. ``One critic attacks me as
too conservative, and the Christian Coalition attacks me as too
liberal. We must be doing something right,'' Gore shouted to an
appreciative audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign copied its candidate's in-your-face strategy
for defending against the former New York Knicks forward.
</P>
<P>
   It has trotted out interests groups at every turn, and used
liberal icons like ex-Gov. Mike Lowry to counter Bradley's attempt
to argue that Gore was ``much more conservative than people know''
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley hit hard Gore's votes to restrict federal funding of
abortions while a House member in the late 1970s. On Sunday, Gore's
campaign responded by trotting out the state director of the
National Abortion Rights Action League to stand on the stage and
read an endorsement resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley went after Gore on the environment, citing his less than
stellar 64 (out of 100) scorecard on votes from with the League of
Conservation Voters. Gore's campaign countered with a news
conference by leaders of the Sierra Club and Conservation
Strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has promised to press on whatever happens in today's
primary. ``I knew it would be difficult and it has been,'' he said
yesterday, vowing to fight on next Tuesday when 16 states choose
delegates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
