<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR THE GOOD OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-YANKS-STRAWBERRY) 
(jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a caring American and concerned parent, I was relieved to
know that Major League Baseball was right on top of the scourge
that is Darryl Strawberry's sickness or stupidity, depending on
one's chosen level of compassion, or understanding.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the most sensible take on this debate from any
enlightened source has always been John Lucas'. On the likes of
Strawberry, pro basketball's addict-cum-counselor/coach long
maintained that the man doesn't have a drug problem as much as he
has a ``living problem.''
</P>
<P>
   We all do, to some extent. Most sportswriters I know stress out
on deadline by ingesting serious quantities of cholesterol,
caffeine or nicotine, and afterward, wish they hadn't. In those
moments when Strawberry has sought escape from whatever haunts his
sense of self-esteem, preservation and respect, he apparently
resorted to the demon powder, and afterward, has been painfully
sorry he did.
</P>
<P>
   You can smartly argue that enough apologies were accepted,
though it is useful to remember that the more moral among us were
voicing objections before he ever played a game for the Yankees.
Lucas has often said that it is easy to call for one's banishment
until it is your loved one.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who embraced Strawberry as their prodigal child,
were convincing when they said they cared about him more than they
needed him, because, the truth was, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In weighing his decision to ban Strawberry for one year with no
time off for good behavior, it seems that the commissioner, Bud
Selig, heard the pious news media more than the pleas of Joe Torre
and David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A painful decision for me to make,'' Selig concluded Monday.
``In the end, I could not ignore Darryl's past infractions and
concluded that each of us must be held accountable for his or her
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. I kind of liked having Strawberry around as an example
of the damage and waste drugs can bring. The suspension could mean
the last of Strawberry, while only proving that Selig can knock a
60-mile-an-hour fastball out of the park, or a pimple off
baseball's face.
</P>
<P>
   And while it took him less than a week to cut on Strawberry,
Selig is deep into his second year on a more vexing problem,
enhancement compounds, the snappy curve ball he has been looking at
for nothing but strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a study commissioned by baseball resulted in
the report that revealed that moderate amounts of androstenedione
taken over seven days increased testosterone levels in men. If you
missed this important story, it was, in part, because baseball
released it with a successful and self-serving spin.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the commissioner's office and the players
association agreed (now there is a statement in itself) that the
study offered no evidence to support the contention that ``the
levels of testosterone were sufficient to produce enhanced
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't said was that the scientists were never commissioned
or financed to extend the study that far. In the interests of
protecting Mark McGwire's home run record, baseball proudly
announced that it had proved its case by doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   That not half the stink was raised over scientific proof that
andro changes blood levels and poses long-term health risks as
there has been over one man's relapse told Don Gatlin that ``either
the public hasn't figured out what's going on or it doesn't care
that so many athletes are on performance-enhancement drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, athletes (Tom Gugliotta of the Phoenix Suns, to name
one) and, more frighteningly, young wannabes everywhere continue
taking over-the-counter substances about which they have not a
clue.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin, director of the Olympic Analytical Laboratory at UCLA,
was one of the secondary collaborators in the baseball study, led
by Dr. Benjamin Leder and Dr. Joel Finkelstein of the Massachusetts
General Hospital. While more cautious than Gatlin in advising
people against the use of andro, Finkelstein agreed Monday that
this is a ``serious public health issue, beyond being a sports
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said last season that he had ceased using andro, but
didn't denounce the product and baseball didn't ban it and now is
merely supporting more federally financed research that Gatlin said
will take ``three or four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, who could've been McGwire, will be a memory
by the time baseball has to admit it was years behind other sports
on this issue. Some day, baseball may even have to put an asterisk
next to McGwire's name in the record book. In the meantime, the
improvident Strawberry has been sent away, perhaps forever, for the
good of the game, and as an example for the country's imitative
youth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
