A1416 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TERROR-U.S.-500(2TAKE     02-28 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-U.S.-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOILED TERROR PLOT LINKED TO BIN LADEN AIDE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Middle Eastern and American officials say they
believe that a key lieutenant of Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile,
coordinated a terrorist plot that targeted Western and Israeli
tourists in Jordan in December.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the man played a critical role in directing the
operation from Pakistan, and fled to Afghanistan a day or two after
Jordanian authorities foiled the plot and arrested 13 people.
</P>
<P>
   American and Middle Eastern investigators say they believe that
the suspect, Abu Zubaydah, was also in contact with Algerians who
have been charged in a separate attempt to bomb unspecified targets
in the United States in December. It is not clear whether Zubaydah
played an active role in that plot, these officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But they say that the emerging evidence about Zubaydah provides
an important development in their effort to establish that bin
Laden is a commanding figure in terrorist plots against the West.
</P>
<P>
   These investigators say they believe that bin Laden and his
group were trying to land two blows at once against Western
interests. These attacks, they say, would have been their first
large terrorist actions since the 1998 bombings of two American
embassies in East Africa, for which bin Laden has been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators began working on the theory that bin Laden was
behind the alleged plots as soon as arrests were made in Jordan and
the United States. They quickly discovered that some of those
people held in Jordan had been trained in camps operated in
Afghanistan by the Saudi exile. They also found that the Algerians
in Canada had taken direction from a Mauritanian man related by
marriage to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said the role of Zubaydah, from the Gaza
Strip, is the most significant evidence to date that bin laden was
directly behind the two operations. Zubaydah is a trusted member of
bin Laden's inner circle, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Eastern intelligence officials describe Zubaydah as the
coordinator of bin Laden's ``external operations,'' which they
describe as the group's terrorist activities outside Afghanistan.
Bin Laden has been using Afghanistan as his base and as a haven
from international efforts to bring him to court.
</P>
<P>
   Operating from Peshawar, Pakistan, Zubaydah was in charge of
communications between bin Laden's organization in Afghanistan and
terrorist cells around the world, investigators now suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that bin Laden's organization employs stringent
security measures, and that sensitive information about its
operations is closely held by an inner circle of trusted aides. As
a result, rank-and-file members can betray few details if they are
arrested.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zubaydah's role fits a pattern that investigators say they
recognize, particularly in the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania in
1998. Middle Eastern intelligence officials say they believe that
an Egyptian radical and bin Laden lieutenant, named Mohammed Atef,
helped coordinate the embassy attacks. They say he was in contact
with the cells in Kenya and Tanzania that carried out the
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Atef is thought to have disappeared into Afghanistan after the
embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Middle Eastern intelligence officials say that Zubaydah
took Atef's place, just in time for the plots of last December.
</P>
<P>
   Both operations failed after members of both cells were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, the Jordanian authorities said they had arrested 13
members of a group planning attacks against an American hotel and
three tourist sites frequented by Israelis and Westerners. Jordan
may have been targeted because it is a pro-Western neighbor of
Israel but terrorists might also have seen it as easier to
infiltrate than Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian officials said they had evidence that the suspects
received terrorist training in Afghanistan and were tied to the bin
Laden network.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordanian authorities have concluded that a total of 28
individuals were involved in the plot, including some who remained
in Afghanistan after the arrests in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a separate plot was unraveling along the
U.S.-Canadian border. On Dec. 14, authorities arrested an Algerian
named Ahmed Ressam, whose car contained a military explosive and
homemade detonators.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities say Ressam, known by the nom de guerre Abu
Reda, had received military training at camps in Afghanistan and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam's arrest has prompted an investigation by the American
and Canadian authorities to determine whether the group was
planning an attack in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have so far charged four Algerians with
taking part in the plot. While U.S. officials have speculated that
the Canadian case is connected to bin Laden, they have publicly
offered few specifics to support that linkage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new information about Zubaydah is helping the authorities to
see a clearer picture.
</P>
<P>
   Zubaydah is the alias of Mohammed Hussein Zein-al-Abideen. Born
in 1973, he went to Afghanistan as a teenager, where he reportedly
linked up with bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   From Peshawar, on the Pakistani-Afghan border, Zubaydah has
played a critical role in the development of bin Laden's
international networks in the last two years, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, they say, Zubaydah acted as gatekeeper for the
Afghan training camps operated by bin Laden and his militant
allies. Intelligence officials have been told that leaders of local
cells around the world would contact him to request training in
Afghanistan for members of their cells. The cell members would then
travel to Peshawar and meet Zubaydah, who would then decide whether
they would be given training and in which camps, according to these
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cell leaders with whom he was in direct contact was
Khader Abu Hosher, the leader of the plot to attack four tourist
sites in Jordan during millennium celebrations, according to Middle
Eastern intelligence officials. Zubaydah told Hosher which sites
were to be picked for attack, Middle Eastern intelligence officials
have learned.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials have discovered that Zubaydah had a joint
bank account in Peshawar with Khalil Deek. He is a naturalized
American citizen of Palestinian descent who has been jailed in
Jordan in connection with the millennium plot there. The bank
account contained between $1,860 and $3,100, officials said. Deek,
who is now in jail in Jordan, is charged with having played a role
in arranging the travel between Afghanistan and Jordan for those
involved in the Jordan plot.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say Zubaydah was also in contact with Ressam and
his group in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The ties between Zubaydah and the Canadian group seem less
clearly understood than are his links to the Jordan cell. But one
connection between Zubaydah and the Ressam group apparently went
through an Algerian in Canada named Fateh Kamel, some Western
intelligence officials state.
</P>
<P>
   Kamel, who had ties to Ressam's group, also had ties to a group
of militant Islamic veterans of the Afghan war who are now in
Bosnia. In turn, that group was in contact with Zubaydah, according
to a European intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
   Another link found between bin Laden's organization and the
Canadian group was through a man named Mohambedou Ould Slahi, a
Mauritanian who lived for a time in Montreal, where he met
frequently with Mokhtar Haouri, an Algerian charged with directing
Ressam in the bomb plot.
</P>
<P>
   Ould Slahi's brother-in-law is a close associate of bin Laden.
In addition, Ould Slahi has been in frequent contact with the
representatives of a construction company in Sudan owned by bin
Laden; investigators have concluded that the company served as a
front for bin Laden's terror network. Ould Slahi was arrested in
Mauritania last month, but has since been released.
</P>
<P>
   American and Middle Eastern intelligence officials are more
certain of the links between the Jordan plot and bin Laden. Hosher
was a veteran of the Afghan war who later became a member of Jaish
Mohammed, or Mohammed's Army, a radical Islamic group that mounted
terrorist acts in Jordan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   After his release from prison in Jordan in 1993, he moved to
Yemen, where he came in contact with members of Egyptian Islamic
Jihad, a radical group now allied with bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Hosher's assistant in the Jordan plot was Raed Hejazi, who
traveled on an American passport and worked for a time as a taxi
drive in Boston. Hosher is now in jail in Jordan, and Hejazi is at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the Jordan operation began in 1998, officials have
learned. That would suggest that bin Laden's organization may have
begun plotting soon after the African embassy bombings in August
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hosher sent some members of his group for training in
Afghanistan in 1999, officials said. Cell members were then given
false passports and traveled individually along a circuitous route
from Afghanistan, to Yemen, Syria and then Jordan, officials have
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cell in Canada, the group in Jordan appears to have had
links to terrorists in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian officials found that a man living in Britain named
Omar Abu Omar, also known as Abu Kutada, played a role in backing
the Jordanian cell. Britain has rejected Jordan's requests to
extradite him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
