<SLUG> BC-SEARS-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE WILL CREATE ONLINE MARKETPLACE FOR SEARS AND CARREFOUR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., France)  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Oracle Corp. said Monday that it will join
with Sears, Roebuck and Co. and Carrefour of France to create a
global online marketplace for the retail industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other retailers will be invited to join the founding partners in
the new venture, which will be called GlobalNetXchange. The joint
venture initially will focus on the combined $80 billion in
purchases that Sears and Carrefour make from 50,000 suppliers,
partners and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement follows Oracle's creation of a similar exchange
for automakers, initially with Ford, but recently joined by General
Motors and Daimler-Chrysler. Such Web-based purchasing systems are
expected to trim costs and speed the purchasing process for many
different industries.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares closed Monday at $68.625, down $2, on Nasdaq.
Sears closed at $27.3125, up $1.4375, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Oracle is moving aggressively to lock up whole
industry categories in the hot business-to-business electronic
commerce market, known as B2B. But some said Monday's announcement
was less significant than the automotive venture, and questioned
whether other retailers would even be willing to turn over
purchasing to a collective that includes competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For retailers, purchasing ``is very strategic in nature,'' said
Richard Church, an analyst with Solomon Smith Barney. ``There
aren't many industries where procurement costs are a higher
percentage of sales than in retail. I'm not sure Wal-Mart is going
to be willing to participate in what is essentially a purchasing
cooperative,'' he said. ``But maybe it can be successful by
bringing in smaller retailers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Sears and Carrefour initially will share the majority interest
in GlobalNetXchange, while Oracle will hold a minority interest and
will provide software, implementation and support. Using Oracle
Exchange, Oracle's online purchasing software, the new company is
expected to become operational within 30 days with its own
management, employees and capitalization. Sears and Carrefour
indicated they may begin doing buyers' auctions on the site within
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a revolution in retail,'' Arthur C. Martinez, Sears
chairman and chief executive, said in a conference call. ``It will
forever redefine supply-chain processes, increase collaboration
with suppliers and reduce supply-chain costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers already do much of their purchasing
electronically, using so-called electronic data interchange
networks. But such programs are proprietary in nature, meaning that
one maker's program cannot interact with another, so a company must
get all of its suppliers to sign on or the system does not work. In
contrast, Web-based exchanges are accessible to anyone with a
standard browser and require no specialized software or hardware
for buyers or sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming close on the heels of the auto announcement, the retail
venture illustrates Oracle's strategy in the business-to-business
market. Although Oracle operates a general purpose procurement
service called Oracle Exchange, with more than 1,000 suppliers
selling all kinds of products, the company's main thrust will
increasingly be in specialized offerings for so-called vertical
markets, like automobiles, retail, or healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these verticals do is allow us to differentiate our
services much more,'' said Ray Lane, Oracle's president and chief
operating officer, in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   By partnering with the major players in an industry, ``we can do
direct procurement,'' rather than serving as a middleman. ``That
differentiates us from Ariba or CommerceOne, which do only
indirect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that Ariba and CommerceOne are moving toward
the kind of vertical strategy pursued by Oracle. Chemdex, an early
B2B player specializing in research materials for drug companies,
last week announced the formation of Ventro, a parent company that
will create a series of vertical market partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing number of platform players, whether Oracle,
CommerceOne, Ariba or Ventro, are all going to be chasing very
large companies to partner with to take over a very significant
piece of an industry's purchasing,'' said Bruce Temkin, an analyst
with Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oracle has some inherent advantage here because they are a
software company, and they are installed at most of the large
companies with which they want to get involved in this area,''
Temkin said. ``On the flip side, their architecture was built from
this from the ground up, like a CommerceOne or a Ventro. They have
to make it work, and they have to prove they have a market-making
platform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Breyer, managing partner of Accel Partners, a venture
capital firm based in Palo Alto, Calif., that helped form
Walmart.com, said Oracle, Sears and Carrefour had not made a
convincing case for other retailers to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flaw is really about corporate governance,'' he said. ``It
is unclear who is calling the shots. Is the goal to build a world
class independent marketplace or to build a business that will be
complimentary to the partners who have built the consortium?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
