<SLUG> BC-DOTCOMS-AD-COLUMN-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A FORD CAMPAIGN WILL COMBINE TV AND ONLINE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford is overhauling a highly visible element of a big campaign
for an important new car line as the company seeks to become part
of a hot trend: transforming television advertising into a hybrid
of the TV and online media that could be called dot-commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and a longtime agency, J. Walter Thompson, plan to
introduce next month a series of live commercials for Focus, the
new line of ``entry level'' compact cars aimed at younger drivers,
with interactivity as a core element. The spots are intended to
work with a Web site, www.focus247.com, so that viewers can help
determine what their content will be.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-commercials come after a skein of live Focus spots that
Ford ran last fall, which were widely deemed to have fallen short
in several crucial creative and production aspects. For one thing,
many of them were so stilted that they seemed taped rather than
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had wanted it to be a little more spontaneous,'' Jan Klug,
marketing communications manager at the Ford division of Ford Motor
Co. said in a telephone interview Monday from Dearborn, Mich. ``The
spots were a little too scripted and a little too clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fall helped us learn what we needed to know about exciting
live advertising,'' she added. ``I think we're going to have a lot
more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford is not alone in making significant changes to high-profile
ads as they continue to be presented to consumers. Perhaps the most
notable current example of such a ``midcourse correction'' is a
revamped campaign for United Airlines, part of UAL Corp., by Fallon
McElligott in Minneapolis, a unit of Publicis SA, which scrapped an
unconventional theme, ``Rising,'' for a more traditional approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at this as `Live II,' but as a way of making
true interactive television,'' said Bruce Rooke, executive vice
president and executive creative director for the Ford domestic
business at the Detroit office of Thompson, part of the WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than have people sitting passively at their sets,
watching for mistakes,'' he added, referring to the vagaries of
producing live commercials, ``we want them to get involved, control
the way the spots go forward, tell us what the scripts ought to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford is also not alone in bringing out dot-commercials, which
are indicative of the growing interest among marketers and media
companies in capitalizing on the migration of consumers to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Nike Inc. has already been running a series of
television commercials for the Air Cross Trainer II shoe, created
by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., that invite viewers to a Web
site (www.whatever.nike.com) to view alternate endings for the
spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Pizza Hut unit of Tricon Global Restaurants is sponsoring a
promotion with CDnow.com that offers customers the chance to order
free customized compact discs from the CDnow Web site. And the NBC
unit of General Electric Co. is promoting a Web site,
www.JustJack.com, devoted to a character from the sitcom ``Will and
Grace.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Interactive spots make sense for Focus because the line is aimed
at drivers under the age of 35, Rooke said, ``people who love
getting product information off the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can drive them to the site and keep them there in an
interesting way,'' he added, ``instead of just running a spot
showing a Web address under the logo and hoping people will go
there, Focus will benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Thompson have scheduled four dot-commercials during
each of these four nights: March 8, March 15, March 23 and April 5.
They will run during prime-time series on ABC, a unit of Walt
Disney Co., like ``The Drew Carey Show,'' ``The Norm Show,''
``20/20,'' ``Two Guys and a Girl'' and ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is for viewers to shape the spots by voting on the
Focus Web site, making content decisions like which of five cast
members will appear on screen, what they will wear and whether they
will pitch the Focus coupe, sedan or station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can end the first spot with a question like `What should
this person say?''' Klug explained, ``and then we'll take the best
line viewers suggest and say it in the next spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The five cast members, who were described by Klug as unknown
actors, will replace Annabelle Gurwitch, a 30-something television
personality from the TBS Superstation cable network, who was the
spokeswoman in the live spots last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get more flexibility, more reality, with more people,''
Klug said, adding: ``Annabelle was terrific for what we needed her
for, but didn't ring as true with the target audience as we'd
wanted. Part of it was our fault; we were loading her lips with
things people don't normally say, to make sure we got in all the
product mentions.''
</P>
<P>
   For viewers not thrilled at the prospect of becoming
dot-commercial contributors, Julie Roehm, the Focus brand manager
said, there will be more tangible incentives to participate: more
than 500 prizes worth $100,000 offered in a ``co-branding
partnership'' with Sony, including ``a Sony Limited Edition
Focus.'' People can win the prizes by accumulating points for
visiting and voting on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will be promoted with print ads in newspapers and
magazines as well as banner ads appearing on Web sites operated by
Ford's Internet partners, which include Bolt, DEN, iVillage and
Yahoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
