CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash., Minn., Calif.)  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   THE ABSENTEE VOTE: Election officials expect that, if past
voting patterns hold, perhaps half the votes cast in Tuesday's
primaries in Washington state will be absentee. In addition to
one-time requests for mail-in ballots, the state permits voters to
be sent absentee ballots automatically before each election; that
distribution list already includes about a third of the state's
voters. One problem is that balloting rules this year are
especially complex, requiring special care in marking and mailing
ballots if they are to count. Early indications are that some
voters are mismarking their ballots and envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   A DECISION NOT TO RUN: Tim Penny, the Minnesotan Democrat who
left the House in 1994 saying he was disappointed with the
political process, said Monday that he would not seek the
Democratic nomination to oppose Sen. Rod Grams, the incumbent
Republican. Penny, who had been expected to run, had come under
considerable criticism from members of his party who viewed him as
too conservative. Penny had voted to restrict abortion, and has
called for the privatization of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Dirk Johnson
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   GAY MARRIAGE BAN SUPPORTED: A CNN/Time poll of likely California
primary voters conducted on Friday and Saturday by Yankelovich
Partners found that 56 percent of respondents supported the ballot
initiative to ban gay marriage. Thirty-four percent opposed it.
Among Republicans, 77 percent supported the proposed ban, while 16
percent opposed it. Among Democrats, 42 percent supported the
initiative, and 45 percent opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Stockton, Fresno and Bakersfield, Calif.
</P>
