<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ISSUES-EDUC-ART-2TAKE     02-28 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUES-EDUC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CANDIDATES' DO THEIR HOMEWORK ON SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Gore in Pueblo, Colo., is being sent.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Gov. George W. Bush's model schoolhouse, every student would
have to sit for an annual state test, and those students whose
schools consistently failed to make the grade would be given a
government check that they could use to attend a parochial or other
private school.
</P>
<P>
   If Sen. John McCain were the nation's principal in chief, there
would be an even larger program of federally-financed vouchers, but
states would decide individually whether to use standardized tests
to make high-stakes decisions about who could get the vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley would be as concerned with testing the
teachers as he would the students. Vice President Al Gore would
test teachers only in their first year, and then shower them with
federally subsidized goodies, including raises and signing bonuses
of up to $10,000 each, especially for those working in
hard-to-staff districts.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that improving education ranks atop most voters' wish
lists, the four leading contenders for the presidency have each
weighed in with their ideas, enough so that it is possible to
compare how teachers and students might fare under their
administrations. Though distinguishing the Republican proposals
from the Democrats is generally easier than making comparisons
between the candidates within each party, some aspects of the four
plans do not fit neatly into ideological frames.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bush, a Republican, and Bradley, a Democrat, would
be the most punitive of the four candidates on schoolwide
performance. The Texas governor would hold the threat of a federal
voucher over the heads of schools that fail to improve, while
Bradley, a former senator from New Jersey, would wield the hammer
of state takeover. Both are responding to the same polls, which
plumb the depths of minority discontent with the most incorrigible
neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a Democrat, and McCain, a Republican, would be reluctant
to tie federal dollars to a school's academic standing. But while
the senator from Arizona seems intent on pleasing the conservative
wing of the Republican Party by extracting the federal government
from most school-level spending decisions, the vice president has
not challenged the nation's powerful teachers' unions, which have
endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the platforms of all four candidates is a central
frustration: with the federal government responsible for
contributing only 7 cents of every dollar spent in public schools,
each candidate is struggling to demonstrate how he would improve
performance from a perch so removed from the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leverage possibilities for the president to impact on
student achievement, which is what everyone's concern is, are
limited,'' said Christopher T. Cross, the president of the Council
for Basic Education, a nonpartisan organization.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to increase that leverage, the candidates have, for
the most part, worked within parameters that have defined their
respective parties for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican candidates feature more decision-making by
parents and by state officials,'' said Michael Kirst, a professor
of education at Stanford University. ``The Democrats feature less
decision-making by parents and more grants that are tied to
specific purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and McCain envision creating the nationwide voucher
program that conservative politicians and many minority parents
have demanded _ though Bush, in a grasp for the political center,
has avoided using the politically laden term ``vouchers,'' and
instead says federal education money should be ``portable.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's proposal would create the most ambitious voucher
experiment yet, spending $5.5 billion over three years to present
one million students with vouchers of up to $2,000 annually. To
counter the argument that vouchers siphon money from public schools
when students leave, McCain would create a new source of financing:
the tax money now spent, through loopholes, as subsidies for the
oil and gas industry, sugar growers and ethanol manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has yet to define how the vouchers would be awarded,
but he has said the poorest children in the worst schools would be
immediately eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would, in effect, give vouchers of up to $1,500 each to
students in low-performing schools that fail to improve after three
years. But these vouchers would be financed with money drawn from
the $8 billion Title 1 program, which was established in the
Johnson administration to help low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Both voucher proposals would probably face stiff opposition in
Congress. Not only would the industries targeted by McCain fight to
retain their share of subsidies, but the Republican-led House, as
recently as last fall, declined to consider a proposal that would
have created the very vouchers Bush seeks.
</P>
<P>
   The main differences between Bush's proposal and McCain's center
on the federal role in managing school spending. McCain has said he
would present most federal education money to states in
unrestricted block grants _ he would include an additional $500
million earmarked broadly for teachers' merit pay _ and leave it to
the states and districts to spend as they see fit. Bush favors
block grants as well, but would insist on annual tests for
elementary and middle-school students _ although the states would
write the tests and decide what constitutes improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley envision a federal government far more
involved in education than one run by either of their Republican
opponents. Bradley would double the $8 billion spent annually on
Title 1 schools. Also, with an eye on the looming teacher shortage,
Bradley would offer annual scholarships of up to $7,500 to high
school seniors who commit to teach in an urban or rural school, or
in fields like special education, for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Gore would burrow the federal government into the local
collective bargaining process in ways never before seen, offering
federally-financed raises of up to $10,000 to teachers in districts
that commit to aggressive reform programs. He would also offer
signing bonuses of up to $10,000 to 75,000 new teachers annually
who pledge to work in short-staffed districts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley, swayed by the demands of minority parents, has
been more receptive to the prospect of an experimental voucher
program than Gore, who says his opposition is absolute, their
biggest differences lie in their approaches to expanding preschool.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would add 400,000 children 1 to 5 years of age to the
Head Start program, which already provides intensive early
education to 800,000 children. But Gore would guarantee preschool
for all three million children who are 4 years old, and many who
are 3.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said he would finance his proposal, an additional $115
billion over 10 years, by tapping 10 percent of the estimated $1.04
trillion federal surplus _ though he would face fierce opposition
in Congress. Bradley would spend an extra $175 billion over 10
years, and has said he would find much of that money in the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two candidates' proposals, Bradley's emphasizes only a
few areas: expanding Title 1 and ensuring a high-quality teaching
force by requiring teachers to have majored in their subjects or to
take a test to demonstrate proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's educational portfolio seemingly has something for
everyone, with provisions to reduce class sizes, build and renovate
schools and offer tax breaks for college savings accounts. That has
even some loyal Democrats worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spread federal dollars too thinly,'' said Amy
Wilkins, a principal partner of the Education Trust, a nonpartisan
research and lobbying organization, ``you risk not doing anything
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
