<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1433 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-     02-28 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Subtracts Seats to Add Legroom &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coach passengers on American Airlines will soon have as much
legroom as they did more than a decade ago. The airline is spending
$70 million to remove two rows of seats from each of its 700
jetliners, giving passengers some extra legroom, the airline says.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American's overhaul comes after United Airlines announced last
August that it would make a similar increase in legroom, but only
for the first nine rows of coach seats, which it reserves for
full-fare coach passengers and its most frequent travelers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airlines measure legroom by seat pitch _ the distance from the
back of a seat to the back of the next seat. In recent years, coach
passengers have been squeezed into seats with a pitch of 31 inches
and, in a few cases, 29 inches. Most of American's coach seats,
like the first nine rows of coach at United, will now have a
34-inch pitch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These moves come as American and United, the nation's two
largest carriers, are halfway through five-year programs to replace
all seats on all but their newest planes with new ones designed to
be more comfortable, especially on long flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More legroom comes at a price. The likelihood that the middle
seat in each row will be occupied will rise, and for those not
paying full fare or not having elite status in frequent-flier
programs, so will the risk of being assigned to these seats, which
are designated B and E on single-aisle jets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fewer rows will also mean more competition for free tickets in
frequent-flier programs. American is removing about 6.4 percent of
its seats; in recent years, analysts say, travelers using
frequent-flier awards have occupied about 11 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art of the Old West, Mythical and Realistic &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Old South is meeting the Old West at the Mississippi Museum
of Art in Jackson, where ``The American West: Out of Myth, Into
Reality,'' an exhibition of 117 paintings and sculptures, is on
view through June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from 67 public and private collections, the works trace
the development of the West from 1825 through 1925, as seen by
artists like Frederic Remington, Charles Russell and Albert
Bierstadt.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more of the frontier west of the Mississippi River
opened, artists flocked there to capture the spectacular scenery
and the promise of Manifest Destiny. Works like Bierstadt's
``Buffalo Trail: The Impending Storm'' and Charles Deas's
``Solitary Indian, Seated on the Edge of a Bold Precipice,'' both
in the exhibition, helped shape the popular view of the West.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes they offered a romantic image that obscured
reality, and ``The American West'' attempts to counterbalance that
with works depicting the less savory aspects of the West's
settlement, like N.C. Wyeth's ``Gunfight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American West'' will also travel to the Terra Museum of
American Art in Chicago (June 24 to Sept. 17) and the Toledo Museum
of Art (Oct. 8 to Dec. 31).
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Museum of Art, 201 East Pascagoula Street, is
open daily 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., till 8 p.m. on Tuesday and Thursday.
Admission is $8. Information: (877) 662-9378.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It's Spring in the South, Time for House Tours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Charleston and Virginia can tour a variety of
historic houses and private gardens during the 53rd Festival of
Houses and Gardens in Charleston, S.C., and Historic Garden Week in
Virginia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walking tours are the mainstay of the Charleston festival, from
March 16 to April 15. Itineraries include visits to the garden of
the William Gibbes House at 64 South Battery, with its 18th-century
parterres, magnolias, wax myrtles and noisette rosebushes. Morning
tours of Charleston's Historic District stop at the 18th-century
Georgian-style St. Michael's Church and the original South Carolina
Statehouse, among other sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Glorious Gardens tour, offered every Thursday during the
festival and on March 26, explores 10 private homes and gardens
bursting with azaleas, wisteria and magnolias throughout the
Historic District and the Ansonborough neighborhood _ the first
suburb of once-walled Charleston. Also scheduled are plantation
oyster roasts, on March 27 and April 4 and 12, at the splendid 1783
Drayton Hall plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Each festival event costs $40. For information and reservations:
(843) 722-3405 and www.historiccharleston.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, families across Virginia, from the Chesapeake Bay
to the Shenandoah Valley, are inviting visitors to tour their homes
as part of the state's 67th Historic Garden Week, April 22 to 30.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historic James River plantations, including Brandon, Westover
and Belle Air _ all between Richmond and Williamsburg _ are among
the more than 250 sites that will be open to benefit the
restoration of historic grounds and gardens statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites include Tuckahoe plantation the boyhood home of
Thomas Jefferson, in Goochland County; Epping Forest, the restored
18th-century home of George Washington's mother in Lancaster
County, in the Northern Neck by the Chesapeake; and a 400-acre
thoroughbred farm in Upperville, in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden Club of Virginia, which sponsors the weeklong event,
offers a guidebook of homes, gardens and landmarks for a $5
donation to Historic Garden Week, 12 East Franklin Street, Richmond
23219.
</P>
<P>
   For ticket prices and schedules: (804) 644-7776 or
www.vagardenweek.org.
</P>
<P>
   Alisha Berger. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Weekend for Those Who Really Like Cheddar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred dollars may seem a stiff price for a hunk of
cheese, but at Shelburne Farms in Vermont, it comes with a
three-day cheese-making workshop and a two-night stay at the
luxurious Inn at Shelburne Farms. On May 12, 13 and 14, the farm
will put on a residential course, Pasture to Palate: The Art of
Cheese Making.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne Farms, on Lake Champlain, is a 1,400-acre working
dairy farm, a National Historic Site and a nonprofit environmental
education institution. It includes a turn-of-the-century Queen Anne
cottage, once owned by Dr. William Seward Webb and his wife, Lila
Vanderbilt, on grounds landscaped by Frederick Law Olmsted, the
designer of Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The house has been refurbished and is open mid-May through
mid-October as an inn. The farm is also home to a prize-winning
cheese-making operation, producing cheddar from the farm's own herd
of registered Brown Swiss cows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the course will tour the farm's pastures, visit
local organic farms and dine with cheese makers, farmers and other
agricultural experts. The purpose, according to the course
description, is to ``introduce the complex and dynamic relationship
between land, climate, grass, animals and milk that produces a vast
array of cheeses.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meals will be served at the inn and, on one evening, at Mary's
of Baldwin Creek in Bristol, and will feature Vermont products. On
Sunday, participants will help make cheese at the farm's imposing
five-story Farm Barn. The cheese they help make will become
two-pound blocks of cheddar and, after being aged for six months,
will be shipped to participants for the winter holidays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fees are $525 to $550 a person double occupancy, and $595 to
$650 single, and include accommodations, meals, course material,
taxes and tips. Space is limited to 12.
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to register, contact Hillary Sunderland
at Shelburne Farms, 1611 Harbor Road, Shelburne, Vt. 05482, or
(802) 985-8686, or at hsunderland(AT)shelburnefarms.org.
</P>
<P>
   Marialisa Calta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
