<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY HUNDLEY LIKES THE DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Todd Hundley is not spending most of his days
in the trainer's room with his elbow packed in ice. He's catching
regularly, firing balls to second base during drills and, unlike
last year, there's no reason to hide how he really feels.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's right elbow is fine. The pain in his left wrist, which
kept him from hitting right-handed at the end of last season, is
gone. He finally feels like the player who set a major-league
record for homers by a catcher when he played with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind's at ease,'' said Hundley, who hit 41 homers in '96.
``Now, it's a normal spring training baseball season. Spring
training's always tough but not as tough as it usually is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're doing everything we normally do, but usually
there's a week where you're hurt and sore and can't move, and then
you get going from there. This year it's not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hundley said and did all the right things. He's not
one to complain, point fingers or make excuses, which is why he has
the utmost respect of his teammates. But his mental health was as
poor as his physical health. After an offseason of conditioning,
including lots of throwing, he feels much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doubts and all that stuff are gone and I'm able to get in
quality work without missing days,'' Hundley said. ``Last spring I
wasn't able to throw every day. I had to take days off from
throwing, especially the bases. Last year I missed a bunch of days
in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough (to hide it), but it's something you just do.
It's getting to know these guys early on, where last year there
were some of these guys I didn't catch during spring training. That
makes it very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's sore elbow also had an adverse affect on him
offensively. It limited his work in the batting cage, which hurt
his timing. For it, Hundley went through the worst season of his
career. Despite hitting 24 homers, he drove in only 55 runs and
batted .207.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is to go out and play and get the job done,''
Hundley said. ``I'm not worried about anything. I'm just happy to
be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wait a second? Monday's intrasquad game gave Mark
Grudzielanek his first chance to play second base in a game-type
situation and he admitted the feeling was strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely weird,'' the former shortstop said. ``My
first steps were toward shortstop. I almost was going to go out and
take infield and throw the ball to third. Just as a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Grudzielanek had little action. He caught the lone pop fly
hit his way before leaving after two innings because he fouled a
ball off his foot. He iced it and he's fine.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Johnson said it's likely Carlos Perez, who
pitched a scoreless inning Monday, would see his first Grapefruit
League action next Monday against Baltimore. Right-hander Darren
Dreifort pitched a scoreless inning. Paul LoDuca, fighting for the
backup catcher's job, homered in the intrasquad scrimmage off Jim
Bullinger. Left-hander Jeff Granger, trying to impress at every
interval, had a rough outing. He allowed five runs on five hits. .
. . Adrian Beltre's agent, Scott Boras, and Dodgers managing
general partner and CEO Bob Daly were expected to arrive in
Dodgertown late Monday to begin discussing a multi-year contract. .
. . Right-handers Chan Ho Park and Terry Adams are the featured
pitchers in today's intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
