<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. ISSUES REGULATIONS TO CONTROL TAX SHELTERS
</P>
<P>
   The government issued new rules to discourage abusive corporate
tax shelters. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the
proliferation of such shelters ``may be the most serious compliance
issue threatening the American tax system today.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules are aimed at forcing the disclosure of shelters as
soon as they are created, so that they can be reviewed by the IRS
and, if found improper, can be banned before they become
widespread. This would replace the current practice of uncovering
the abuses through audits, often years later, and trying to undo
them in court, one case at a time.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER PROFIT RISES 16 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said that its profit for 1999 increased 16
percent, in line with analysts' expectations, as it benefited from
cost cuts, stronger vehicle sales and a rich mix of high-profit
models. For the fourth quarter, DaimlerChrysler's increased 32
percent. Investors were cheered by the results, lifting shares of
DaimlerChrysler by $2.1875, or 4.4 percent, to $65.6875.
</P>
<P>
   DOW AVERAGE RISES ABOVE 10,000
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rebounded above 10,000 as
investors moved back into blue-chip stocks that have been battered
recently. The Dow rose 176.53 points, or 1.8 percent, to 10,038.65.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also gained ground, rising
14.69 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,348.05. But investors took some
profits in technology stocks. The Nasdaq composite index fell 12.65
points, to 4,577.85.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET STRAINS MUSIC RELATIONSHIP
</P>
<P>
   The advent of electronic commerce and the prospect that
consumers will buy music by downloading it directly from the
Internet has strained the traditionally congenial relations between
record labels and record stores.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE MARKET SITE FOR RETAILERS
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said that it would join with Sears, Roebuck and Carrefour
of France to create a global online marketplace for the retail
industry. Other retailers will be invited to join the venture,
GlobalNetXchange, which will focus on the combined $80 billion in
purchases that Sears and Carrefour make from 50,000 suppliers,
partners and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   SENATOR PROPOSES FEE REDUCTION
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, who heads the Senate Banking Committee,
introduced legislation that would substantially cut the fees that
companies and investors pay the Securities and Exchange Commission
to register and trade stock. The bill would also give many
professionals at the SEC, including lawyers and accountants, raises
of up to 40 percent to help stem the brain drain at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELIS CONCERNED ABOUT EXCHANGE
</P>
<P>
   When Frank G. Zarb, the chairman of the Nasdaq stock market,
visited Israel recently, he was not a traveling salesman drumming
up business. He was more like a potentate inspecting the outer
realms of a fast-expanding empire. Nearly as many shares in Israeli
stocks are traded on Nasdaq as on the Tel Aviv stock market, and
Israeli securities dealers worry that Nasdaq's Israeli portfolio
could soon eclipse the entire Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, both in
sheer size and in growth prospects. The only alternative, they say,
is to authorize automatic listings in Tel Aviv for Israeli
companies traded on Nasdaq and other U.S. markets, a proposal
resisted by government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP MORRIS BACKS SOME LIMITS
</P>
<P>
   A top Philip Morris executive said that the cigarette maker
would no longer oppose some government regulation of the tobacco
industry in areas like selling to young people, disclosing the
ingredients in cigarettes and conducting research on safer
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   NISOURCE TO BUY COLUMBIA
</P>
<P>
   Energy NiSource, the owner of Indiana's largest utility, agreed
to buy Columbia Energy Group, based in Herndon, Va., for $6
billion, creating a utility with the most natural-gas customers
east of the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
</TEXT>
