<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEC-TRADING-FEES-NYT &LR;      02-28 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-TRADING-FEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR SEEKS REDUCTION IN FEES SEC PUTS ON TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Day traders and lawyers for the Securities and Exchange
Commission will each get a raise, if Sen. Phil Gramm has his way.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, R-Texas, who heads the Senate Banking Committee,
introduced legislation Monday that would substantially cut the fees
that companies and investors pay the SEC to register and trade
stock. The bill would also give many professionals at the SEC,
including lawyers and accountants, raises of up to 40 percent to
help stem the brain drain at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 10 years, the legislation would cut fees for
companies and traders by almost $15 billion, Gramm predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those taxes are paid by Americans who are trying to save and
invest,'' Gramm said. ``They are a tax on accumulation, thrift and
retirement security.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the cost of the fees is hardly even a rounding error
for investors, amounting to about $3 for a $100,000 trade. But
securities firms argue that the fees, along with the somewhat
larger fees that the SEC charges companies to register their
shares, amount to a hidden tax on investors. Nasdaq market makers,
which must pay the fees on shares they buy and sell for their own
account, are especially anxious to see the fees reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chances are uncertain. The legislation has some
strong Democratic supporters, including Sen. Charles Schumer of New
York. Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC, also spoke out
strongly in its favor at a hearing Monday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House, which is worried about the loss of a
relatively painless revenue source, has not yet indicated whether
it will support the bill. At Monday's hearing, Schumer said he was
``getting vibes that the administration will not be supportive on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The fees are supposed to finance the commission's operations.
But because they are tied to the dollar value of the shares that
are registered or traded, the fees have soared along with the
markets since 1995. They are now much larger than the SEC's budget,
creating a windfall for the federal government. In 1999, the fees
totaled almost $2 billion, more than five times the cost of running
the SEC. The excess was spent on general government expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gramm's legislation, the fees would be cut to roughly the
amount necessary to pay the SEC's budget. Charges for registering
stock would immediately fall by about 75 percent, and trading fees
would probably drop by about half, according to Levitt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cutting fees, Gramm's bill would give the SEC the
chance to raise salaries for many of its lawyers and accountants to
the levels already offered by the Federal Reserve Board and Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. For example, a second-year lawyer with the
SEC makes about $66,000, while a member of the FDIC staff with
similar experience can be paid as much as $91,000, or 39 percent
more.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt called raising salaries essential in light of soaring
salaries for lawyers and accountants in private practice. Levitt
said his agency had lost one-fourth of its top professionals in the
last two years. ``We are in the midst of a terribly serious
staffing crisis,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
