<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      02-28 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: MR. McCAIN'S CHALLENGE  
(sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, After weeks
of debate over the role of religion in American politics, Sen. John
McCain issued a courageous challenge on Monday to both his opponent
and his party to end their entangling alliances with
``self-appointed leaders'' of the religious right like Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell. The challenge, issued in Virginia,
followed by one day George W. Bush's attempt to defuse the
controversy over his visit to Bob Jones University in South
Carolina with a regretful letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York. On Monday, however, McCain rolled right past the Bush
apology, hardly acknowledging its existence while pounding his
rival as a ``Pat Robertson Republican'' and asserting that the time
had come to free the Republican Party from two decades of
subservience to the ``union bosses'' of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual primary season, this was an extraordinary moment.
All of a sudden some people, McCain included, are talking about a
struggle for the soul of the Republican Party, with McCain seeking
to marginalize the religious right while Bush seeks to include it
in a Republican tent not unlike that fashioned by Ronald Reagan and
embraced by Bush's father. This may indeed be happening, and if it
is, it may well turn out to be healthy for a party that has for too
long been tied to the cramped ideology of the Falwells and the
Robertsons. But what is also going on is a short-term struggle for
the hearts and minds of voters in the forthcoming New York primary.
</P>
<P>
   By speaking out against Robertson and Falwell in Virginia, a
stronghold of Christian conservatism, McCain seemed willing to risk
modest political punishment there in exchange for a sizable boost
among Republican moderates in New York, including Catholic voters
angered by Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University, an
evangelical institution that prohibits interracial dating and
promotes anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush seemed to have exactly the same audience in
mind when he sat down to write an explanatory letter to O'Connor,
the archbishop of New York and the de facto leader of American
Catholics. His letter was welcome as an assertion of what Bush says
are his true racial and religious values. But this was a tactical
apology, not a muscular engagement of the university's philosophy
or its long history as a seedbed for bigotry wearing a theological
disguise. With his letter Bush was bowing, no more deeply than
absolutely necessary, to two political realities. One is that the
Bob Jones episode had acquired a political afterlife stronger than
anyone expected. The second is that Bush had to try to clean up his
record before facing millions of increasingly restive Catholic
voters in New York and other states with big Catholic
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   With these exchanges, the Republican campaign has seen an
extraordinary turnabout. McCain is looking like a progressive,
while Bush, who campaigned for months on a message of social
inclusiveness and ``compassionate conservatism,'' now finds himself
writing letters that try to argue he is not a social reactionary,
but in language carefully crafted not to offend the leaders and
activists of the religious right by challenging their divisive
zealotry.
</P>
</TEXT>
