<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DIALLO-NYT &LR;      02-28 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DIALLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MESSAGE OF THE DIALLO PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 29:
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of marchers who filled New York City streets last
weekend were shocked and pained by the verdict acquitting four
police officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo. They were
understandably outraged that an innocent man had been shot down in
his own doorway by officers who thought he was acting suspiciously.
But even for those who accept the jury's verdict as legally sound,
the marches sent a powerful message that many New Yorkers,
especially in minority communities, think the police are a threat
to their lives and safety. Indeed, it is hard to believe that a
white resident, standing in his own vestibule, would have been
gunned down under similar circumstances by the four white officers.
The Diallo case, and the restrained weekend protests it inspired,
are an urgent call for police reforms designed to minimize the
likelihood of another such tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The protests show the deep wounds that have been created by
aggressive police tactics in minority neighborhoods. Every year
tens of thousands of blacks and Latinos have been subject to ``stop
and frisk'' tactics by the police. The fear, given the Diallo case,
is that any one of those encounters could turn deadly if the police
misread the situation and a citizen makes a sudden move.
</P>
<P>
   The case is far from over. The Diallo family is expected to file
a civil lawsuit against the city for the killing. The U.S.
Attorney's office is reviewing all aspects of the case for possible
civil rights violations. The four officers also still face a
departmental investigation into their actions.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend protests were passionate, but demonstrators and the
police showed admirable restraint in avoiding physical
confrontation. The Diallo family and the Rev. Al Sharpton set a
peaceable tone by urging the crowds to shun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also made temperate remarks after the
verdict, showing sympathy for the Diallo family and citing the need
for all police procedures to be open to review. But on Monday, he
focused less on policy changes than on what he deemed to be unfair
criticism of the police. Still, the Police Department has to be
held accountable for its mistakes. Many who do not quarrel with the
verdict believe this killing could have been averted if the
officers were better trained, knew the neighborhood well and were
of a mindset less apt to suspect criminality in the most innocent
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir need to examine
precisely how police attitudes and procedures may have contributed
to this killing. They need to modify the department's ``stop and
frisk'' policies that are intruding on the rights of law-abiding
people. They need to increase training on how to avoid turning a
tense situation into a deadly one. Only the most intense efforts to
reform police procedures can assure New Yorkers that a similar
incident will not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Some policy changes are under way. Late last year Safir
decentralized the Street Crime Unit. That may help officers get to
know the neighborhoods better. Efforts to recruit minorities to the
department have increased. More Street Crime officers are now in
uniform, making it less likely that civilians will mistake the
police for robbers.
</P>
<P>
   These reforms came out of Amadou Diallo's death. But the fact
that an innocent life had to be lost before changes were made has
driven a public concern by no means limited to minority
communities. Giuliani needs to show he understands that concern by
pushing new reforms in the department's training and
community-relations policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NY     02-28 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN SHOWS END WITH: WEB-SAVVY VERSACE, KNOWING LAGERFELD,
ROMANTIC FERRETTI, SPORTIVE PRADA AND VERSATILE ARMANI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Donatella Versace, who still has people chuckling
over the on-the-air call she made to a local radio station to
complain that its impersonator did not sound a bit like her, gave
the world-weary fashion crowd something new to talk about on Friday
night. At the conclusion of her racy show, Versace came out in a
see-through pants ensemble that, top to bottom, left little doubt
about where the sun shines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simple, a vision of gold,'' was how the perennially
tanned Versace sweetly summed up her outfit, which consisted of
black chiffon and strips of snakeskin sewn here and there but not
necessarily in the right places, as she arrived for a post-show
dinner at the family's palazzo. By then, she had changed into a
relatively tame-looking silver sequined halter number.
</P>
<P>
   Versace, whose publicists insist that she is really a shy
person, has struggled to prove that she is more than her late
brother Gianni's impudent little sister. With this collection, she
has shown she has a pretty good idea about what, in this age of
live Internet links and short attention spans, millions of ordinary
people expect from fashion. They want glamour, fun, fast clothes,
laser lights shooting out of the mouths of Medusas, and girls,
girls, girls _ lots of models whose expressions of withering
contempt would make some poor guy checking out the action on
Vogue.com grin with idiot fright.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a simple idea. After all, there aren't enough people
who have the patience, much less the style of life, for the
ladylike clothes, tweeds and expensive furs that have been
streaming down the runway with the opulent reserve of Edith Wharton
pruning her roses.
</P>
<P>
   And sophistication: what can the term mean to consumers who are
buying up stuff at such a frenetic rate they don't have time to
consider whether it's gauche or marvelous? One can argue that
Versace's new clothes for fall 2000 _ the skintight silk pants with
fur bombers, the slinky jersey dresses twisted in a knot at the
bosoms, the glimmering Medusa-head belts _ are for a woman whose
sense of sophistication is still in its provincial stages.
</P>
<P>
   But there again, the world is awash with people nobody has heard
of, making staggering amounts of money in ways nobody ever dreamed
of, and increasingly they seem to be saying, like Versace with her
up-and-out ensemble, What's the point of having it all if not to
enjoy, be noticed?
</P>
<P>
   So Versace hit a nerve with this collection, her most confident
since taking over the designs of the house. There were grid-pattern
coats, swanky furs in pastel sheared mink with snakeskin belts, and
chiffon blouses and shirt dresses in swirling hues that suggested
ecstatic IQ puzzles. The show had spunk, not the least because of
Aretha Franklin belting out her female anthem ``Respect'' on the
soundtrack, but what it really had was a flesh-and-blood feeling of
life.
</P>
<P>
   The number of designers who infuse their clothes with genuine
wit and sophistication, who are well read and can constantly relate
the present to something they know in the past, is down to a few
and fading fast. The other day in the Fendi showroom, surrounded by
Midas-size tables laden with gold bracelets and chains, Karl
Lagerfeld was sipping a Coke, perusing the latest French Vogue and
discussing Alan Seeger, an American poet whose letters and World
War I diary he plans to publish this year, illustrated with
Lagerfeld photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld's ability to throw out a lot of references and keep
them spinning is dazzling. His show for Fendi, on Thursday,
incorporated such cool items as Fendi logo-tattooed stockings and
gold-heel boots in electric blue and green with butterscotch
leather skirts, graphic knits in Sonia Delauney prints and fur
coats in brilliant acid-hue geometric blocks. The coats and knits,
made by piecing together strips of material in a pattern, showed
off Fendi's craftsmanship, but it was Lagerfeld's alert, chaotic
mix _ here a sleek black fur coat over zingy stripes, there a
glitter of gold chain nestled in a glam-white mink _ that gave the
clothes their knowing edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Marni show on Friday was pretty, with childish colors and
posy prints mixed with funky khaki trousers, Carnaby stripes and
silver sequined cardigans, but its artsy-craftsy style seems a bit
threadbare right now. The theme at the Moschino show was ``The
Wizard of Oz.'' That meant ruby-red shoes and other giddy
accessories mixed with fairly straightforward frock coats, studded
leather and striped knits that seemed to have no relation to one
another. As an editor said on the way out the door, ``It was
Munchkin ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Italian fall season ended with strong showings by
Alberta Ferretti, Miu Miu and Giorgio Armani. Among the trends
emerging from the Milan shows were vintage-inspired looks from the
1940s and '70s, tight turtlenecks, black mixed with chocolate brown
and camel, acid hues, belted waists, flaring skirts and lots of
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Ferretti kept things romantic, in her fashion, with wispy
dresses detailed with pleats and worn under lanky tweed coats. A
coat in a gold cloque fabric with a dark fur collar seemed to
spring off the zebra-striped 1960s-era banquettes at El Morocco,
but with almost everything this season circa-something, it was in
the groove.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone familiar with images of the Duke and Duchess of
Windsor posed in summer clothes in their garden, the Miu Miu
collection, designed by Miuccia Prada, will recall something of
their fondness for sportive French dressing.
</P>
<P>
   With peaked little burlap hats on their heads, the models came
out in red-striped cotton knit tops with flaring skirts in white
twill cotton (finished at the waist with bias tape), sleeveless
dresses and swing jackets in worn-looking gray and maroon tweed,
and lingerie tap pants worn with sleeveless tweed tops tied in the
front sailor style. Combined with drowsy oboe music and
bobby-pinned hair, the show was a bit of a dowdy-rama through an
old folks' home, yet charming in its singular vision.
</P>
<P>
   Armani needs a bit to champ at _ for a while, the bit was his
rival Gianni Versace; these days, it's the popularity of Prada and
Gucci, whose clothes he thinks are revivalist. ``When Miuccia needs
an idea for a collection, she opens her closet,'' he scoffed in an
interview. When asked if he thought his stance was just a case of
sour grapes, Armani calmly replied that it might be if his clothes
didn't sell, adding that ``it's normal for every era to have an
`it' name.''
</P>
<P>
   Armani should hardly worry. His collection smoothly covered all
the bases, emphasizing cut, particularly in jackets and
close-fitting leather separates, which are strong for fall, and
subtle mixes of velvet and chenille textures. There were flashes of
color, but Armani wisely dealt out black, cobalt and gray. After an
Ascot finale of beaded black and white evening dresses and pants,
Armani appeared out of the darkness, grinning and sitting
cross-legged on a platform like a levitating genie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
