<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCUNION-HMO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE'S DOCTORS WANT MORE CLOUT WITH HMOs  &HT;     BY TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Doctors in private practice in California have taken a major step
toward forming the equivalent of a union by asking the state
Legislature to provide their trade associations the power to
negotiate fees and contracts with health maintenance organizations.
<P>
   State Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough, who introduced the
legislation, said California HMOs have forced physicians to accept
such low fees that doctors are caught between their duty to
patients and the realities of how much insurers are willing to pay
for care.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMOs in California have created this green-eyed monster, and
we, at least, want to pluck its eyes out,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lewin, chief executive of the California Medical
Association, which represents 34,000 doctors, said patients will
benefit if physicians have more bargaining power when setting
contracts with HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imbalance right now is such that physicians have little or
no authority in the negotiating process,'' Lewin said. ``It's take
it or leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   But HMO lobbyist Bill Wehrle, with the California Association of
Health Plans, called the bill a ``brazen power grab'' that would
lead to higher insurance costs and more expensive health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors would have you believe this is all about patients and
improving quality, but it's not,'' Wehrle said. ``They're asking
for a license to collude. This is California's answer to OPEC.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier's bill, the Quality in Health Care Contracts Act, is
modeled on a Texas law that went into effect in September. Five
other states and the District of Columbia are considering similar
legislation, which takes advantage of court decisions that allow
states to make certain exemptions from federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   California Medical Association legislative director Norman
Plotkin said Speier's bill would define the circumstances under
which doctors, who are generally organized as professional
corporations, can be exempted from antitrust laws that prevent
businesses from setting rates or terms of service.
</P>
<P>
   In the physicians' setting, the rates usually pertain to the
fixed monthly amount that doctors receive for every HMO member in
their care. The terms of service might spell out what sort of
approval is needed before a doctor can refer a patient to a
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law, a doctor or a medical group could
designate the medical association or some other nonprofit entity to
bargain with the HMO on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   This third-party negotiator would have to be certified by the
state attorney general, who would also decide whether the HMO would
have to negotiate with the doctors' representative.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of an impasse, the attorney general could order an
arbiter to settle the dispute. The medical association's Plotkin
said consumers would be protected against price gouging because the
attorney general would have to approve any rates or terms that
resulted from such negotiations or arbitrations.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Court, a spokesman for the watchdog group Consumers for
Quality Care, in Santa Monica, gave the proposal a lukewarm
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a grave imbalance between HMOs and physicians
that something needs to be done,'' said Court, who noted that he
was still concerned about possible price fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Powers, president of the Pacific Business Group on Health,
the San Francisco group that represents large insurance buyers,
objected to Speier's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think competition between health care practitioners is one
of the ways we have to hold down costs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Speier's bill and similar bills in other states,
legislation has been introduced in Congress by Rep. Tom Campbell,
R-Campbell, to exempt doctors from antitrust laws at the national
level.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration antitrust officials have testified
against Campbell's proposal on the grounds that it would lead to
higher health-care costs. Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the
American Association of Health Plans, the national HMO lobby, said
the same critique applies to Speier's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors can already form practice associations or medical
groups that are quite large,'' she said. ``They don't tell you that
in many cities one or two medical groups already bargain for most
of the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the California Medical Association's Lewin said that in
California, where a few HMOs handle most of the patients, doctors
are being forced to accept contracts that lower the amount they can
collect for services. He said a medical association study showed
that from 1990 to 1993, doctors received an average $45 per month
for every HMO member in their care. By 1997-99, that per-month
compensation had dropped to $29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be a union, but there has to be some equity
in the negotiations between doctors and HMOs,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
