<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-LOSS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAISER REPORTS NARROWER LOSS FOR 1999  &HT;       
 BY TOM ABATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The Kaiser Foundation Health Plan was only $6 million in the red
last year, as the HMO giant continued to show signs that it has
turned the corner after huge losses in the two preceding years.
<P>
   The nation's largest and oldest health maintenance organization,
Kaiser reported a shocking $266 million loss in 1997, its first in
nearly 50 years of operation. In 1998, the health giant reported an
even larger net loss of $288 million.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to insurance rate hikes in the neighborhood of 10
percent, and the divestiture of some money-losing subsidiaries in
the Northeast and North Carolina, Kaiser managed to narrow its 1999
loss to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser officials said that if it discounted the costs associated
with selling the unprofitable units as well as some other one-time
charges, the HMO actually enjoyed a net income of $466 million last
year. Kaiser reported total revenues of $16.8 billion in 1999,
compared with $15.5 billion for the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a long way to go,'' said Kaiser Chief Financial
Officer Dale Crandall, ``but the prognosis for a complete recovery
over the duration of our multiyear turnaround plan is good.'' The
nonprofit health organization said it expects its total revenue to
increase 8 percent this year, while costs increase about 6 percent.
Its rates are expected to increase by roughly 8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said its California division, still the heart of the HMO,
reported an operating surplus of $280 million, a ``significant
improvement'' over the unit's $354 million operating deficit in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said that division had added 185,389 members, bringing
total state enrollment to nearly 6 million. Nationwide, membership
slumped 2.5 percent, to 8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said its other divisions in Hawaii, the Northwest,
Colorado, Kansas City, Ohio and Georgia reported positive financial
results. But the HMO said its mid-Atlantic division, which insures
540,000 people in Virginia, Maryland and the District of Columbia,
still lost money in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser spokeswoman Beverly Hayon said the HMO has a plan in
place to reverse the losses in the mid-Atlantic and has no plans to
eliminate a division that remains ``important strategically,
financially and politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle wire services contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
