r f BC-YAHOO-MURDOCH-SFCHRON     02-28 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-MURDOCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO MAY EXPAND TIES WITH MURDOCH  &HT;       
 BY VERNE KOPYTOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
As old and new media continue to explore joining forces, Yahoo, the
most popular Internet site, and News Corp., Rupert Murdoch's media
conglomerate, have held talks that may lead to a broad alliance
between the two companies, according to a magazine report.
<P>
   The Yahoo and News Corp. talks come a month after giant online
service America Online and Time-Warner, the media empire, announced
their merger. Some analysts believe that Yahoo and News Corp. are
trying to find a way to counter that proposed marriage between
their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance could allow Yahoo to make many of News Corp.'s
publications and television programming available through its Web
site. News Corp. has a rich stable of content _ everything from the
brash Fox Network to action films produced by 20th Century Fox to
newspapers like the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo could also get preferred access on a satellite-based
Internet delivery service that News Corp. is developing. The
service would allow consumers to to access the Internet from their
television, eliminating the need for a computer or telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   In return, News Corp. could gain greater visibility on the
Internet and a Web portal for its satellite service. Until now, the
company has had minimal success in creating a presence on the Web.
Its Web portal, Iguide, launched in 1995 with help from MCI, the
telephone company, was closed in 1997 after losing millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo co-founder Jerry Yang and News Corp. President Peter
Chernin have held several discussions covering a ``wide-ranging
alliance,'' according to the New Yorker magazine, which reported
the news in its March 6 issue. The two executives have yet to sign
a contract.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an agreement, it will not be for several weeks, an
executive quoted in the New Yorker article said. News Corp. and
Yahoo already have a marketing alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Yahoo and New York's News Corp. would exchange
stock in the deal. But neither investment would come close to a
controlling interest, the magazine said. It is unclear how far the
discussions have progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies declined to comment on the record.
</P>
<P>
   But one News Corp. executive said her company has talked with
several firms about developing a satellite network. She declined to
name those companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Enderle, a technology analyst with Giga Information Group,
called Yahoo's alliance discussions ``just another indication that
Yahoo is very concerned about the AOL-Time Warner merger.'' He said
Yahoo wants to join News Corp.'s satellite project in case AOL
tries to lock it out of the cable Internet system it is developing
with Time-Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, Yahoo has been steadfast in remaining
independent as many of its competitors joined forces with other
companies or were bought out. For example, Alta Vista is mostly
owned by the venture capital firm CMGI, and Disney bought the
Internet portal Infoseek in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While an alliance with News Corp. would fall short of ending
Yahoo's neutrality, Enderle said, it does signal a change in
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they are becoming less and less independent,''
Enderle said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Li, an Internet industry analyst with Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass., agrees that Yahoo is interested in
the satellite access, but not out of fear of AOL. She said Yahoo is
trying to increase its growth in places like Asia, where satellite
Internet service through television has a big potential because
phone lines are inadequate and many people do not have computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo is very determined to stay independent,'' Li said. ``I
see no advantage to them for offering just Fox content.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has already reversed its long-held policy against creating
its own online magazines and newscasts. The company has recently
started hiring people to staff a financial news show that it plans
to produce and broadcast on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of trading yesterday, Yahoo's stock had declined
$3.19, to $162. News Corp.'s stock increased $2.94, to $51.19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
