<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL TIME TO ADD AN IRA  &HT;       
   
 BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Question: I've already filed my 1999 income tax return. I did not
put any money into my deductible individual retirement account for
1999. May I still do that?
<P>
   Answer: Yes, you may do it between now and the due date for your
1999 return, which most likely is April 17.
</P>
<P>
   But because you already sent in your return, you will have to
file an amended return to claim the deduction for your 1999 IRA
contribution, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   You can amend the return using IRS Form 1040X, which you can
download from the IRS Web site at  &LR; www.irs.gov. &LR;  Or, get a copy by
calling the IRS toll-free telephone number: (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   Weller cautions that if you have a refund coming on the return
you already filed, you should wait until the refund check arrives
before filing your amended return. If the amended return reaches
the IRS while it is still processing your original return, ``it
will delay processing of the initial refund,'' Weller says.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't be fair to you, because _ assuming you figured
your taxes correctly _ you are fully entitled to that initial
refund. You will get an additional refund after you send in the
amended return with the IRA contribution deducted from your income.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Archaeology
</P>
<P>
   Q: You recently discussed how investors can find historical
stock prices on the Internet for stocks that are still listed. But
what about historical prices of companies that no longer trade
because they have merged _ such as Alumax, which was acquired by
Alcoa? This sort of research can help determine the cost basis of
stock for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A: I was able to find quotes for Alumax starting in 1993 and
ending in 1998 _ when it stopped trading _ on the FinancialWeb site
at  &LR; www.financialweb.com. &LR;  Go to that site, then click on the link
for ''Stocks.'' On the next page, enter the ticker symbol (`'AMX''
in the case of Alumax) and indicate that you want ``Historic
Price/Vol.'' You then will be prompted to enter the date
parameters.
</P>
<P>
   One hitch: I found that you must already know the former stock
symbol for Alumax, because FinancialWeb's ticker-search function
couldn't look it up for me. Evidently a stock must still be trading
to be included in the ticker search.
</P>
<P>
   If for some reason FinancialWeb doesn't help you find past
prices of a particular delisted stock, you might _ and I hesitate
to suggest this in the cyberage _ put on your shoes and go
outdoors. Go over to the nearest public library, and ask to look at
the appropriate back issues of The Chronicle or any other newspaper
that publishes daily stock prices. That's one way people did stock
research in the ancient past _ say, the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   I hope this advice won't brand me as a Luddite.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Deduction
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife suffers from hydrocephalus and lives in an
assisted-care facility because she cannot completely operate on her
own. Is this deductible in whole, or in part, as a nursing home
would be?
</P>
<P>
   A: IRS spokesman Weller says it doesn't matter whether the sign
on the front of the building says ``nursing home'' or
``assisted-care facility.'' There is nothing magical about the name
for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The key consideration, he observes, is whether your wife
receives medical services there.
</P>
<P>
   If the primary purpose for lodging your wife in this facility is
for medical treatment, Weller says, then the full cost of her stay
_ not only the medical treatment, but also room and board _ can be
classed as a deductible expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she needs around-the-clock medical attention, and the only
other option is hiring a nurse at your home, that's medical, not
personal,'' Weller remarks.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be able to demonstrate to the IRS that the primary
purpose of your wife's stay is for medical treatment. If you hope
to do this, you probably ought to enlist the help of a professional
tax preparer.
</P>
<P>
   If medical reasons are not the primary purpose of her stay,
Weller adds, you still qualify for a deduction for any medical
services your wife receives at the facility. He suggests that you
ask the management to list the medical costs separately when they
bill you.
</P>
<P>
   Medical expenses, which you enter on Schedule A of Form 1040,
are not fully deductible from income. You can deduct them only to
the extent that they exceed 7.5 percent of your adjusted gross
income for the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
