<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DONOR-FUND-SFCHRON &LR;      02-28 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONOR-FUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUNDS HELP NEWLY RICH SHARE WEALTH WITH CHARITIES  &HT;       
 BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The booming economy and rocketing stock prices have made a lot of
ordinary people affluent and a lot of affluent people rich. Now,
many of them are looking for the best way to give some of their
superfluous money to charity.
<P>
   To serve this expanding philanthropic market, three big
financial-service companies _ Charles Schwab, Fidelity Investments
and Vanguard _ sponsor what are known as charitable endowment
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwab Fund for Charitable Giving began operating five
months ago and has accumulated $50 million in assets from more than
1,000 donors. It has paid out 1,000 grants, averaging more than
$3,500 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's endowment fund has $143 million under management from
1,100 donors _ an average of $130,000 each. The fund has made 2,200
charitable grants, averaging about $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Fidelity Charitable Gift Fund, formed seven years ago, is
the oldest of the three and the largest, with 21,000 donors and
$2.2 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   All these funds differ in details _ most notably, the minimum
amounts that individuals can contribute _ but all are designed to
make charitable giving hassle-free and tax-efficient for the newly
generous.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can make tax-deductible _ but irrevocable _
contributions to the funds up front, then take their time about
parceling out money to specific charities. The funds send out the
donations and do all the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   One enticing feature of the charitable fund is &LR;   &LR; that it permits
donors to contribute to virtually any charity of their choice,
rather than being limited to a list of charities such as those
offered by the United Way and other community charitable
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Charitable funds are similar to foundations, but without the red
tape. Individuals who create foundations often find themselves
under intense scrutiny from the tax authorities, drawing heavily on
the services of lawyers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwab, Fidelity and Vanguard funds insulate their
participants from any such unpleasantness. In return, they charge
fees ranging up to 1 percent of fund assets annually.
</P>
<P>
   The for-profit charitable funds are stirring up the charitable
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   They are drawing contributions away from the many nonprofit
community foundations that have been fixtures of the
charitable-giving scene for decades, says Robert Walker, director
of the Management Center consulting firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Community foundations operate much the same as for-profit
charitable funds, setting up tax-deductible accounts for individual
clients and handling all the paperwork. But they generally limit
their focus to local charities, while the charitable funds donate
money worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sterling Speirn, president of the Peninsula Community
Foundation in San Mateo, claims that the for-profit funds are less
threatening than they may seem. He says their heavy marketing
campaigns have generated a lot of interest in charitable giving,
and this will benefit all types of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is very stimulating,'' Speirn says.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in a charitable fund can contribute either cash or
securities.
</P>
<P>
   If they contribute securities that have appreciated in value
since they were purchased _ likely after the long bull market _
they are entitled to a tax deduction for the full value and are
excused from paying capital-gains taxes on the appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Each individual who donates to a charitable fund is assigned a
separate account and can choose from an array of mutual funds in
which the money will be invested, pending donation to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Donors can name successors to their accounts _ their children,
perhaps, or other family members _ who can carry on the giving
after they die.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't choose to name a successor, the charitable fund
will ask them to recommend a list of charities to inherit the
balance of the money in their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Although donors can claim a charitable tax deduction as soon as
they put money in the fund, they are permitted to spend weeks,
months, even years deciding which charities will receive their
largesse.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if the mutual funds do their jobs right, the original
donations will grow, increasing the money available for giving.
</P>
<P>
   While the donors are permitted to advise the fund where to
donate the money, the final decision is left to the fund's
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, however, the directors probably will approve
donations to any of the hundreds of thousands of charities that are
registered in the United States. (That can include U.S.-registered
foreign charities.)
</P>
<P>
   Donors who aren't sure where they want their money to go can
sort through capsule profiles of more than 650,000 registered
nonprofits on a database compiled by GuideStar, an organization
specializing in philanthropic research.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwab Fund for Charitable Giving provides a link to the
database on its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Campbell, 55, a retired computer consultant in Palo Alto,
says he and his parents have contributed over the years to
``various charities.'' But, ``Due  &LR; t &LR; o the stock market and
real-estate appreciation, we have begun taking philanthropy more
seriously than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Already an owner of Vanguard mutual fund shares, Campbell
decided to sign up with the Vanguard Charitable Endowment Program
soon after it was established two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make some contributions immediately,'' he says,
``but we liked the idea of an endowment program because we also
wanted to set up a fund from which we could make donations over an
extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   To participate in the Vanguard program, donors must initially
contribute at least $25,000 worth of cash or securities. Later
contributions to the fund must amount to at least $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and his parents contributed more than $100,000
initially, ``and we continue to give,'' says Campbell. ``It takes
time to develop gift-giving skills. The Vanguard program is
appealing because we get immediate tax deductions, but can make the
disposition of funds as our understanding of philanthropy
evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of the money that Campbell and his parents put
into the fund already has been paid out _ ``to environment and
education. We've set up a number of scholarships at Foothill and
DeAnza, the local community colleges, and to the Windy Hill Open
Space Preserve in Portola Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Vanguard endowment fund's most important roles, says
Ben Pierce, the fund director, is to smooth the way for
contributions to smaller charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many smaller charities _ maybe your local church, for example
_ are not set up to handle gifts of appreciated stocks,'' he
observes. They may not have a procedure for selling the stocks, or
the capability to keep the proper records and credit the donor with
the appropriate tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``By centralizing your donations with us, in one spot, the
stocks you give us will be liquidated by us and go out to charity
in the form of checks,'' says Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   The newly hatched Schwab Fund for Charitable Giving has
generated considerable interest. ``We're seeing people from across
the spectrum and across the United States,'' says David
Engelbrecht, vice president of the fund. ``A lot of Baby Boomers,
retirees, dot-com secretaries. There are a lot of affluent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab requires an initial contribution of at least $10,000, and
allows subsequent contributions as small as $1,000. The smallest
donation that participants can direct to a single charity is $500.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab charges an administrative fee of 0.75 percent annually on
accounts of less than $500,000, with the fees scaled down for
larger accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ellis, 63, a venture capitalist who lives on Telegraph Hill
in San Francisco, decided to use the Schwab fund after having his
arm twisted by his neighbor, Peggy Ross, who happens to be the
fund's executive director. He had previously considered operating a
foundation but concluded that it would be too much bother.
</P>
<P>
   He contributed a ``substantial'' sum to the Schwab fund at the
end of last year and is ``just starting to distribute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis plans to give away about half the money in his account
this year and then replenish it. Among the charities he favors are
the San Francisco Opera and the Farmland Trust. He also is
interested in helping various charities in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Egan, president of the Fidelity Charitable Gift Fund,
says it was the third-largest charitable fund-raiser in the United
States last year, ranking behind only the Salvation Army and the
YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can contribute as little as $10,000 initially, and
$1,000 subsequently. The minimum allowable grant to any particular
charity is $250.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity charges an administrative fee of 1 percent for accounts
smaller than $500,000, with the fee scaled down to as little as
0.25 percent for larger accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Egan insists that participants get their fee's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you have someone who is on his own and wants to contribute
to 10 different charities,'' she observes. ``That's 10 different
transfers of assets, 10 separate receipts. If you're donating
appreciated securities, there's more paperwork to account for that.
With our fund, you make a single contribution and we take care of
the rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
