<HEADER>
A1471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CONGO-NYT &LR;      02-28 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RISKS AND REALITIES IN CONGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 29:
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council gave its unanimous support last week
to an American-backed plan to send a peace-monitoring mission to
Congo. In principle, the decision is sound. The ruinous war there
must be brought to an end, and international engagement will be
essential to untangling a conflict that involves at least six
countries and multiple rebel groups and proxy militias. But the
dangers associated with the creation of a credible U.N. force are
daunting, and the Security Council is right to move ahead with
caution.
</P>
<P>
   This mission is not an attempt to impose a peace on unwilling
combatants, nor to disarm them. No outside force could impose a
peace on Congo's far-flung armies scattered across a territory the
size of Western Europe, much of it devoid of paved roads. The war
began in 1998 as a series of rebellions, backed by Uganda and
Rwanda, against the government of Laurent Kabila, who had ousted
the longtime despot Mobutu Sese Seko barely a year earlier. Angola,
Zimbabwe and Namibia soon came to Kabila's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The limited objective of the U.N. effort is to foster conditions
that will reinforce the will of these states to institute a peace
accord they signed last year in Lusaka, Zambia. All sides in the
war have violated the accord, but large parts of Congo are
relatively stable. Under the Security Council plan, a team of 500
U.N. observers, protected by 5,000 troops and support personnel,
would be sent to four strategic areas to document violations of the
cease-fire and to help arrange the movement of the various armies
and militias to defensive positions. The aim is to expand peaceful
areas and enhance trust on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   No American troops would be involved. The participants would be
recruited mostly from Africa and Asia. The mission carries a
start-up cost of $41 million, with America billed roughly
one-third.
</P>
<P>
   But even this limited plan involves considerable risks. Fighting
persists across much of the north and eastern Congo, and the
potential for renewed violence elsewhere is high. The good faith of
political and military leaders is far from certain, and many
combatants are motivated by the profits they are extracting from
Congo's lucrative gold, copper and diamond mining assets. There
remains the difficult problem of how to disarm the ethnic Hutu
militias and former army troops from Rwanda who found sanctuary in
Congo after participating in Rwanda's genocide in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Not least, there is a pattern of ill-defined and ineffective
peacekeeping missions that have undermined the U.N.'s credibility
in the past, from Somalia and Rwanda to Bosnia. The composition of
the Congo force is still in doubt, and there is a danger of a
poorly trained force under wobbly command that would be vulnerable
to attack by a larger force.
</P>
<P>
   Without effective international support for Congo's tenuous
peace accord there is every likelihood of a wider war. There is
reason to hope that the difficulties can be eased enough to create
acceptable circumstances for the U.N. mission to proceed. But the
U.N. must be sure that it is not embarking on a futile operation,
for a failed mission would be worse than no mission at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
