<HEADER>
A1472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-N     02-28 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER UNDER GLASS AND OVER THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC invited its new best friend, Vince Carter, Skywalker, to a
national party on Sunday. It was a belated invitation; NBC's
original schedule did not include the game between Carter's Toronto
Raptors and Phoenix. NBC placed it in the 12:30 p.m. slot earlier
this month, to be seen by parts of the country not slated to see
the Knicks play Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter's ineffable performance as a slam-dunker on Feb.
12, one day before the National Basketball Association All-Star
Game, NBC shifted the Toronto game to a national broadcast, moving
the Knicks into a regional slot at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Having made the change, NBC repeatedly told viewers that this
was Carter's NBC national coming-out party. If ever you forgot the
day's significance, the announcers Tom Hammond and Steve Jones
offered these reminders:
</P>
<P>
   ``The royal vestments of Prince Vince await.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince Carter flexes his muscles on NBC for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You think he might know this is his NBC coming-out party?''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has not been ignored by national TV. The slam-dunk
contest was on TNT, which is available in 76 million cable homes.
TBS has carried one Toronto game this season (the 1.4 rating
equaled the network's average) with one more, on Monday, coming up.
TNT, TBS's sister network, has two Toronto games scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   So NBC threw Carter's biggest debutant ball, heralding,
fortuitously, a 51-point performance.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's play gives the NBA hope that he is the true successor
to Michael Jordan, providing a type of new Air transfusion that
``next Jordans'' like Grant Hill, Penny Hardaway and Kobe Bryant
have not.
</P>
<P>
   And NBC gave him the star treatment, which is hard to avoid
doing when the star is scoring 51.
</P>
<P>
   He starred in a 3-minute-50-second pregame feature (with baby
pictures and the illustration ``He's Half-Man, Half-Amazing,'' a
kind of hoops centaur). In an interview, Ahmad Rashad offered some
rare wit, telling Phoenix's Jason Kidd that with all the hype
around Carter, ``I didn't know you'd be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough about Vince. What about Vince?
</P>
<P>
   During the game, his name was uttered 165 times. NBC's cameras
found him 105 times for close-ups, replays, reaction shots, moments
when he was doing nothing, walking to and from the court or sitting
on the bench with a towel on his head. Total Prince Vince Face
Time: 12:39.
</P>
<P>
   When the second quarter ended, Rashad didn't interview Butch
Carter, the Raptors' head coach, or Scott Skiles, Phoenix's rookie
head coach. There was evidently no need to hear Skiles discuss how
to stop Carter. So there was Carter again, our newfound TV love,
questioned for 25 seconds. Has Rashad discovered a new pal for
pregame pajama parties?
</P>
<P>
   Carter worship reached its acme in the fourth quarter, when he
was mentioned 62 times, and the camera found him 38 times for 5:47
of Face Time. He was NBC's go-to guy for replays and five-replay
video montages. When another player's image was seen before NBC
went to commercials, it was a shock. To Hammond, Carter was
``Vin-credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a freebie, Tom: Use ``con- &UR; vince- &LR; ing'' any time you
want.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, NBC showed Carter in five different ways, for 38
seconds, as Hammond said, ``Prince Vince celebrates a big-time
message victory.'' Rashad concluded NBC's royal anointment with 36
seconds of happy chat with Carter.
</P>
<P>
   As strongly as NBC pitched Carter, it couldn't force people to
watch. The overnight Nielsen rating proved that despite Carter's
skills, he is not yet a household name or a subject for appointment
viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a beginning,'' said Ken Schanzer, the president of
NBC Sports. ``The one thing is people had to say, `Did you see what
Vince Carter did?' That's how it starts.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3.4 overnight rating was the lowest of NBC's tripleheader.
Granted 12:30 p.m. Eastern games usually suffer from the early
hour, but the rating never went past a 3.9 in any complete
half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   NBC filled its 3 o'clock slot by regionalizing the
Knicks-Philadelphia and Utah-Portland games, and earned a 4.6
rating. At 5:30, the regional combination of the Houston-Los
Angeles and San Antonio-Minnesota games yielded a 4.8.
</P>
<P>
   The tripleheader rated a cumulative 4.2, down 25 percent from
three games in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto games are a slight problem for NBC. Canadian ratings do
not count in U.S. calculations. No matter how big Carter gets, NBC
won't benefit from his home market. With 2.3 million households,
Toronto would be the sixth largest U.S. market, representing 2.3
percent of the country. Still, even a huge Toronto rating wouldn't
budge national ratings much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy is transcendent, his impact will find its way to
increased ratings in all markets,'' Schanzer said. ``It's more
important to have a great talent than he be necessarily located in
one market.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ratings winner was Tiger Woods, even in defeat at the
Andersen Consulting Match-Play Championship. As long as Woods looks
capable of winning, viewers respond. The tournament's 5.6 rating on
Sunday from 2 to 6 p.m. represented a 33 percent improvement from
1999. And it signifies the threat that a Woods-in-the-hunt
tournament poses to rival networks' programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's demonstrated enormous national appeal, like Jordan, and
he's drawing casual viewers to golf,'' Schanzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for NBC, it is carrying the next five PGA Tour
events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
