<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-GIULIANI-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR REACTS TO CRITICISM OF HIM OVER DIALLO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After three days of attacks from protesters and black
clergy infuriated by his defense of the police and the Amadou
Diallo verdicts, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani fought back Monday and
called remarks made by the Rev. Calvin Butts, his former ally,
``extremely political'' and ``hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor added that fears in the black community about police
brutality were not borne out by the facts and that New York City
police officers were ``a model of restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sermon at the Abyssinian Baptist Church on Sunday, Butts
said that there was ``an evil that permeates the place called City
Hall'' and that Giuliani ``is simply reinforcing white supremacy''
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remarks were hateful, they were intended to divide and
they were extremely political,'' Giuliani said during a news
briefing Monday morning on the Lower East Side, where he also
criticized Butts for, in effect, endorsing his opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, for U.S. Senate. Giuliani called Butts' remarks
against him ``a hate-filled attack on another candidate from the
pulpit of a church.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks were in sharp contrast to his conciliatory
statements on Friday expressing sympathy for Diallo's family after
the verdicts acquitting the four white officers were announced. On
Monday the mayor said repeatedly that his critics were prejudiced,
that criticism of the police was unfair and that he was proud of
the way he and Police Commissioner Howard Safir had handled a case
that had clouded his administration for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said that he had reached out to the city's black
community in ``a hundred hours of meetings'' since the killing last
February of Diallo, an unarmed African immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the city's black leaders disputed his version, saying
that Giuliani agreed to see them only under pressure more than six
weeks after Diallo's death _ when civil rights demonstrations
against the shooting were growing daily at police headquarters _
and that they had not met with him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no regular dialogue and interaction between the
mayor and myself,'' said C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem, the dean of New York's
congressional delegation, said Monday that Giuliani came to see him
in his office immediately after Giuliani was elected mayor in 1993,
promising that the two would work together, but that he had not
been back since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mayor has missed one great opportunity to bring
some healing to a city that is polarized,'' Rangel said, adding
that Giuliani needed to give assurances that a killing like
Diallo's ``would never, ever, ever happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, a Democrat who was among the first to urge Clinton to
run for the Senate seat, said that the mayor had isolated himself
from the city's black community and did not understand its anger.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Friday, the mayor expressed extremely personal sentiments,
noting in a soft voice that there was nothing worse for a parent
than the death of a child. But on Monday, the mayor, a former U.S.
attorney for the Southern District of New York, seemed to pride
himself on what he described as his rational, unemotional response
to reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   When Gabe Pressman, a political reporter at WNBC-TV, asked
whether there was something wrong with a system that led to a
killing like Diallo's, Giuliani said: ``You have to look at, is
this actually systemic? Systemic means something more than just
prejudicial emotion. It means something logical.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he said, ``If you're asking me to respond as an
intelligent, caring individual, I have to give an intelligent
response, not just a sort of prejudiced, emotional response.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added that police killings of innocent victims happened
less often now than when he took office _ statistics show that New
York City police officers fire their weapons less often at suspects
than do officers in many other large police departments _ and that
``the real risk that we face in this city is from other citizens of
the city, not from the New York Police Department.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
