<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD INTERESTS YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The New York Yankees, looking for a left-
handed-hitting left fielder, have turned their attention to the
Angels' Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   According to a New York Times report, a Yankees official said
the club can make a deal now but would have to give up highly
touted prospect Alfonso Soriano, a shortstop, and left fielder
Ricky Ledee. The Yankees initially said no.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, though, remain interested in Erstad and are talking
with the Angels, even though Erstad has struggled since making the
All-Star team in 1998. Last season, Erstad hit just .253 with 13
homers and 53 RBI. His lifetime average is .282.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees like about Erstad, 25, is his attitude and his
hard-nosed approach, much like they have in right fielder Paul
O'Neill. The Yankees had been talking to the Angels about Jim
Edmonds, but the two sides could not agree on a return package to
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman will not speak on trade
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back to Phillies: The Angels are faced with an interesting
situation regarding 22-year-old pitcher Derrick Turnbow. Turnbow
was acquired by the Angels in December in the Rule V draft from the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not make the 25-man roster to begin the season, the
Angels by rule must then offer him back to the Phillies. If the
Phillies don't take him back, he must clear waivers _ meaning every
team has an oppotunity to claim him _ before the Angels can then
reclaim him.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels feel Turnbow could be special _ he has a fastball
clocked in the low 90's _ but they know it will be difficult to
find a spot on the staff for him. One option would be to go to a
12-man staff, but Turnbow's opportunities would be limited and his
development would be slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a great arm,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ''You
really like to have a guy like that in your organization, but you
have to evaluate the cost of it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Early rotation: The Angels will hold an intrasquad game this
afternoon. Ramon Ortiz will start against Ken Hill and they will
pitch one inning each. Scott Schoeneweis will start Wednesday
night's game against Arizona State, and Jarrod Washburn is
tenatively slated to start the Angels' Cactus League opener Friday
against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Tim Salmon was excused from Monday's workout so he
could attend the funeral of his grandmother. He is expected back
today. . . . The Angels signed catcher Bengie Molina, pitcher Lou
Pote, outfielder Norm Hutchins and first baseman Larry Barnes for
the 2000 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
