<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS THAT HALF IN STATE DISAGREE WITH DIALLO VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTOR and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Half of all adults in New York state disagree with
the verdict acquitting four New York City police officers in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo, according to the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany, N.Y., trial over the shooting of Diallo, an unarmed
immigrant from Guinea who was fired on 41 times in the vestibule of
his apartment building in the Bronx, received a great deal of
attention, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three-quarters of New Yorkers statewide followed the
case, 28 percent very closely and 44 percent somewhat closely.
Forty-five percent of black New Yorkers said they had followed the
case very closely.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of the respondents polled Saturday and
Sunday had already heard about the verdict on Friday in the Diallo
trial. The telephone survey was conducted with 911 adults
throughout New York state and has a sampling error of plus or minus
3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 50 percent disapprove of the jury's not-guilty verdict
for the four officers, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss
and Richard Murphy, while 30 percent agree with the verdict and 20
percent are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   White New Yorkers are divided in their assessment of the
verdict, while blacks throughout the state overwhelmingly disagree
with the jury's decision to clear the four white officers on all
charges. More than three-quarters of blacks statewide consider the
verdict wrong. Forty percent of whites agree with it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the wide disparity between whites and blacks,
there are smaller differences in the reactions of men and women,
younger and older people and New York City residents and people who
live outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Younger New Yorkers are much more likely to disagree with the
verdict. While 60 percent of people under 30 consider the acquittal
wrong, people age 65 and older are closely split: 41 percent of
them said it was correct to clear the officers of all charges and
37 percent said it was wrong. Most women oppose the verdict, but
men are more divided. Fifty-five percent of women oppose the
verdict, as do 44 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of New York City are more inclined to regard the
verdict as wrong, while people who live in the suburbs and upstate
are closely divided. Sixty percent of people living in New York
City say the jury reached the wrong verdict, compared with 43
percent of people living in the rest of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RADIOACTIVE-STUDEN     02-28 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RADIOACTIVE-STUDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION IN STUDENT COUPLE'S ROOM BAFFLES
COLUMBIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a puzzle baffling enough to furrow the brow of
scholarly types, and serious enough to raise concerns of New York
City and federal officials about a lapse in security at biological
research laboratories using nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, several weeks ago, a highly radioactive stain of
phosphorus-32 ended up on a pillow belonging to a young married
couple in Manhattan. The couple are graduate students at Columbia
University, she a doctoral candidate in biology, he is pursuing a
doctorate in computer science.
</P>
<P>
   The husband and wife, Lei Liu and Yao Cheng, who met at Columbia
while on student visas from China, said in interviews Monday and in
briefings with investigators that they had reported the suspicious
radiation in their university-owned apartment at 542 West 112th
Street, and that they had had nothing to do with the radioactive
material found there.
</P>
<P>
   But Columbia's radiation safety inspectors and radiation experts
at the New York City Health Department suspect otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   According to identical letters sent by the university
administration to the couple on Feb. 24, the students have been
barred from the campus and suspended because an investigation
determined that they ``appear to have some responsibility for the
radiation incident.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters and a Feb. 21 report on the radiation stain by the
university's office of environmental health and radiation safety
have been distributed widely within the university administration.
Copies were provided to the city's Health Department, which is
responsible for investigating releases of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia officials said there was no indication that the couple
or anyone else was harmed by the phosphorus-32, which is widely
used to diagnose and treat certain diseases and in biology
experiments to mark cells or bits of genetic material. The pillow
was removed two weeks ago, and the apartment has since been
inspected several times with no new signs of radiation, Columbia
officials said. Only very low levels of contamination were found on
Cheng and Liu, officials said: traces of phosphorus-32 on their
hands and hair, and on Cheng's chin.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Columbia's investigators concluded that the stain
must have been intentionally deposited on the pillow, that the
phosphorus was too highly concentrated to have been a result of
some unknowing swipe by a contaminated hand, for example. The
report also noted that the lack of any other similarly tainted
places in the apartment suggested that no one had touched the
pillow after it had been contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded: ``The amount of contamination on the
pillowcase immediately raised the suspicion that the contamination
was not an accidental event, but rather the result of a deliberate
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Mullin, a spokeswoman for the Health Department, said,
``What we found is very consistent with Columbia's own
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though phosphorus-32 cannot legally be possessed by someone
without a Health Department license for radioactive materials, the
department has not referred the case to prosecutors or the police,
while the university continues with its inquiry, Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng and Liu say they have done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never brought radioactive substances home, and we don't know
how the pillow became radioactive,'' said Cheng, sitting in the
couple's apartment in a 10-story dormitory. The university has not
asked them to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue my studies,'' Liu said, adding, ``I don't
want to upset the university.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials have yet to find any reason or opportunity
for someone other than the couple to have put the material on the
pillow, said Virgil Renzulli, a spokesman for Columbia. ``How do
you get it into a locked apartment?'' he asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The incident began to unfold on Feb. 8, according to the report
by Columbia's environmental health and radiation safety department.
On that day, a routine check after Cheng did some laboratory work
showed she had slight contamination on her hands and chin, and on
one spot on her hair.
</P>
<P>
   The report said she worked in a complex of laboratories in the
Fairchild building at the north end of Columbia's main campus. She
worked on a floor where phosphorus-32 is used in many experiments,
so many that new sets of vials are ordered every week, said one
official involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the routine tests showed some contamination, the
report said, Cheng borrowed a laboratory Geiger counter and scanned
her apartment, where she told investigators she found that one spot
on one pillow was ``very hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up tests by radiation specialists from the university and
the city's Health Department confirmed that one spot on the surface
of a pillow was very radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   Phosphorus-32 used in biological work is stored in a liquid
solution in vials typically holding 0.25 milliliters of the
isotope, and investigators have estimated that the contents of one
vial were poured onto the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   The stain was emitting radioactivity at 200 millirems an hour,
said officials involved in the investigation. The normal background
level of radiation, which varies by altitude, averages about 0.02
millirems an hour in New York, one ten-thousandth of the amount
radiating from the surface of the pillow. That average totals 175
millirems a year. The acceptable safe limit for the public is 100
millirems a year above that, according to federal health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia officials said Monday that they were certain that the
material could not have come from Yao Cheng's laboratory, where an
inventory turned up no shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents and workers in the Columbia dorm were disturbed
to hear that an apartment there had been tainted with
radioactivity. ``I am reporting this to my union right now,'' said
the building superintendent, Rudy Hamarik, 48, who has worked in
the dorm for 23 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
