<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SAYS MURDER SUSPECTS DISCUSSED DUMPING A BODY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (nk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man who said he was mistreated by the mother and
son accused of killing an Upper East Side woman testified Monday
that the pair stopped on a New Jersey roadside on their way to New
York and discussed disposing of a dead body.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Jose A. Alvarez, said he began working for Sante
and Kenneth Kimes in Florida on May 13, 1998, and the three of them
left for New York a month later. As they neared New York on the
second day of the trip, Kimes pulled the car to the side of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about how this was a perfect place to dump a
body, because the police would never find it there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes first pointed out the site to his mother and then turned
to the backseat where Alvarez had been sleeping and told him, in
Spanish, about the spot, Alvarez testified.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses are accused of concocting a scheme to steal the
Upper East Side town house of Irene Silverman, who disappeared on
July 5, 1998, killing her, and then disposing of her body, which
has never been found. On the witness stand Monday, Alvarez did not
identify the precise location in New Jersey where Kimes discussed
dumping a body. But after the police first interviewed Alvarez in
August 1998, investigators unsuccessfully searched an overgrown
field on the outskirts of Jersey City, N.J., for the body.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, 26, testified that when he began working for the
Kimeses, the three of them stayed at the Palm Beach Polo and
Country Club in Wellington, Fla. Alvarez testified that he found a
gun under the pillow of the bed that Mrs. Kimes shared with her
son.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez also testified that once they arrived in New York, the
Kimeses continued to share a bed in the apartment Kimes rented in
Silverman's town house.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the apartment, Alvarez testified that the Kimeses
stationed him by the apartment door and told him to look through
the peephole, watch the security camera monitor and take notes on
who entered and left the building. But after four days of sneaking
in and out with Kimes, hiding from visitors in the kitchen and
standing for hours in front of the peephole, Alvarez said he
decided to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bothering me and they didn't want to pay me,''
Alvarez said. ``They had me there as a slave.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said that after he took a job with the Kimeses, he
signed a contract that he said was written by Mrs. Kimes. The
contract, which was introduced into evidence, said Alvarez would
work in return for room and board only. Alvarez, who is originally
from Cuba, said he does not read any English and was told by the
Kimeses that he would be paid at least $350 a week. Alvarez said he
still has not been paid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Mrs. Kimes was convicted of federal slavery charges for
enticing young women from Mexico to come work for her, refusing to
pay them and preventing them from leaving. Mrs. Kimes served three
years of a five-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said he fled into Central Park and stayed there for
three and half days, until he ran into Kimes.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes asked Alvarez to return to work and told him that he and
his mother were planning to leave shortly for Canada, Alvarez said.
Alvarez refused and asked again to be paid. Kimes gave him $30,
which Alvarez used to take a bus to New Jersey to cash a check from
a previous employer. With that money, Alvarez bought a bus ticket
to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the gun, prosecutors had Alvarez identify a knife
and brass knuckles as belonging to Kimes. Out of the presence of
the jury, Michael A. Hardy, a lawyer for Mrs. Kimes, objected to
the prosecution trying to introduce the weapons into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circumstantial evidence is circumstantial evidence, garbage is
garbage,'' Hardy said. ``And we are in the garbage stage now.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers are to cross-examine Alvarez Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
