<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SPURS HUGE JOB GROWTH IN NEW YORK AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Internet-related jobs in the New York area are
growing at an explosive rate, to 250,000 now from 106,000 in 1997,
and are responsible for an $8.3 billion payroll that has tripled
during that period, according to an industry-sponsored survey
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the growth in new-media jobs is outpacing that
of traditional media companies and other key industries, the survey
showed. It was commissioned by the New York New Media Association,
a trade group, and conducted by PricewaterhouseCoopers, the
accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The survey defined New York's $9.2 billion new-media business as
a broad category encompassing Internet-related jobs in publishing,
advertising, telecommunications and software design as well as
newer dot-com companies. In more than half of the 8,534 companies
included in the survey, the core business did not involve the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the home to more than a third of these companies (3,148, up
from 2,128), Manhattan remains dominant in this industry. But these
businesses are proliferating at a faster rate in New Jersey _ to
2,398 today from 974 three years ago, the survey said. Nearly half
operate in more than one location. About 1,700 companies in the
survey had moved to New York during the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the survey's most surprising finding, 60 percent of
the companies said they showed a profit in 1998. These tended to be
smaller companies that design Web sites and provide other services
to high-profile companies that are spending heavily to develop a
brand, said Brian Horey, the president of Equity Growth Management,
a venture capital company, and a founder of the New York New Media
Association. Indeed, more than half of the companies reporting
profits said they made less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of new jobs has not closed the racial and gender
gap, however, even in this tight labor market. The Internet work
force in New York is overwhelmingly white (74 percent) and male (62
percent), but not as young as it is in the popular imagination.
According to the survey, the average age is 35, with 33 percent
younger than 30 and 29 percent older than 40. Of the 249,639 jobs
identified in the survey, 185,617 were full-time positions, a big
increase from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another change since then, said Alice Rodd O'Rourke, the
executive director of the New York New Media Association, is that
the industry no longer feels it is being ignored. ``People are more
optimistic, more positive, about the role that government has
played,'' she said. As one example, she cited Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's proposal to repeal the commercial rent tax.
</P>
<P>
   Although the survey does not compare geographical regions _ or
make special claims for New York _ Horey said the region leads the
nation in creating material for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's no question that we're the primary hub for
content,'' he said. ``The West Coast is the hub for infrastructure
and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a more skeptical report issued in October 1998, the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York said that it might be premature to
declare that New York is a new-media hub.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenal expansion may just represent a shift in the way
traditional media companies are operating. ``Accordingly,'' that
report said, ``one could argue that New York City's new-media boom
essentially reflects an Internet-technology-driven boom in the
city's traditional media industries _ industries that represent a
large share of the city's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bram, an economist and one of the authors of the Federal
Reserve Bank's report, said New York's Internet role should not be
overstated. ``For years and years, New York City has traditionally
been behind the nation in new media, but we're sort of catching
up,'' he said. ``Maybe we are ahead, in the overall scheme of
things, but we're not Silicon Valley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
