<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE CHANTING, NO MORE TOMORROWS
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-YANKS-STRAWBERRY) 
(nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It was a warm September evening in 1990 and Darryl
Strawberry had just sent everyone home from Shea Stadium with a
titanic two-run homer off Lee Smith. After missing the press
elevator, I tried to hustle down to the clubhouse to interview
Strawberry and ran into every Darryl fan in Flushing clogging the
runways, screaming his name and making it impossible to budge.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever wanted to leave the seats when Strawberry was
hitting. Fresh beers could wait. So could trips to the bathroom.
But these fans did not want to leave afterward, either. They
chanted ``Darryl, Darryl,'' holding on to the moment as if it was
theirs, because it was.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sunny afternoon last November and a weeping Strawberry
was standing behind a lectern at City Hall. A Yankee now, he was
thanking Manager Joe Torre for being supportive during a trying
year in which Strawberry had been arrested, and his words turned
into sobs. The fans slowly serenaded him with ``Darryl, Darryl,'' a
classy gesture. Torre jumped out of his seat and cradled
Strawberry, patting him on the chest the way a father would calm a
newborn.
</P>
<P>
   It was quiet at Legends Field on Monday, the day Strawberry was
suspended from baseball for a year, an action that could bring a
depressing end to his career. The field was empty one hour after a
trivial intrasquad game. No one chanted anything.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Strawberry's impending suspension had been floating
around all afternoon, but the official news came when Yankee
interns put news releases on laptop computers throughout the press
box. Three paragraphs later, Strawberry, as central a figure as any
athlete in New York sports in the last two decades, was gone.
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to be the next Ted Williams. He was supposed to
coast from Compton to Cooperstown. He was supposed to treat the
baseball world to years and years of power and panache. Instead,
Darryl was bounced out of baseball for the third time after 15
unforgettable seasons, countless questions hovering over his bald
head. What if? The questions will never leave Strawberry. What
could Darryl have been?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what that is,'' a subdued Torre said.
``Obviously having his career interrupted brings up that question,
how much more he could have done in his career. There could have
been some records that could have fallen if he had played from
start to finish and was available every inning of every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Hernandez was sitting on a container of baseballs in Port
St. Lucie, Fla., on Sunday when he was quizzed about Strawberry. He
lowered his head, struggled for the proper words and was silent for
several seconds. Hernandez fought with Strawberry during Mets
picture day 12 years ago, but now he called him a friend and an
incredible athlete. An athlete whose career needed life support too
many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been a 500-plus home run guy,'' Hernandez said.
``It just didn't work out that way. The two greatest young players
I ever saw were Darryl Strawberry and Garry Templeton, and both
squandered it.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Eugene Strawberry was the first player chosen in the 1980
amateur draft, and he has been in the spotlight ever since, mainly
in New York. Sometimes moody, often rowdy and always interesting
with the Mets, he was the player we wanted to watch because his
sweet swing produced 400-foot homers.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was 21 years old when the Mets summoned him in 1983,
a power hitter so fearsome that Frank Howard, then the Mets'
manager, who had 382 homers of his own, said, ``If we're wrong
about this guy, we better all hang it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, no one was wrong, since Darryl made it, belting 252
homers in 8 years and winning a World Series ring with the Mets in
1986. Darryl signed a $20 million free-agent deal with the Los
Angeles Dodgers before the 1991 season, went home and made foolish
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever think Darryl was innocent,'' Hernandez said. ``He
was streetwise. He was not naive.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a stunning rebirth on the Yankees for Strawberry,
starting in 1995. The next year Torre did not want him on the team,
but the Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner, turned into
Strawberry's savior and forced him onto a strong club on July 4.
Steinbrenner warned Strawberry never to cross him by abusing drugs
or alcohol, which the soon-to-be 38-year-old has done twice in the
last 10 months. Even Strawberry's teammates feel it is essential
for him to worry about his life, not his career.
</P>
<P>
   All was quiet here an hour after the announcement that probably
squashed Strawberry's career. When a phone call was placed to
Strawberry's house Monday, Charisse, his wife, answered with a
quivering voice. She quickly said she could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   No one chanted for Darryl. Most likely, Strawberry's career and
the ``Darryl, Darryl'' chants died with Monday's decision. The
final memory could be the worst one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate we didn't get to see him play enough in his
career,'' Torre said. ``I think it was a disservice to him and to
the sport because of what he had to offer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2232EST &QL; 
