<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY TEST SPOTS TUBE CRACK AT NUCLEAR PLANT THAT LEAKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ A preliminary inquiry into a radiation leak
this month at the Indian Point 2 nuclear plant suggests that a
single crack in a steam-generator tube was responsible,
Consolidated Edison officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tests conducted over the weekend gave no hint of why the leak
occurred, or whether the crack was part of a larger problem, the
officials said. But if further tests conclude that the radiation
escaped from only one tube and there are no other surprises or
problems, the officials said, Con Edison may be inclined to reopen
the plant and not shut it, as some local officials and residents
have urged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we understand about the leak, the better off we are
from an ability to suggest appropriate repair options,'' said
Stephen Quinn, a Con Edison vice president who once managed the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 15 leak at the plant in Buchanan, about 35 miles north
of Manhattan, forced Con Edison, the plant's owner, to issue an
alert _ the second-lowest of four levels of nuclear emergency _ for
the first time since the plant opened in 1974. And although the
utility later insisted that no radiation ever escaped the plant and
that there was never any serious threat to public health, many
local residents were livid that they were not notified sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before the incident, Con Edison had proposed selling
the plant, prompting some longtime opponents of nuclear power to
argue that the utility was more concerned about profits than
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Point 2 has four steam generators, all of which have been
in place since the plant opened. Normally, clean water is pumped
into the generators, where the water is heated by super-hot tubes
holding radioactive fuel and turned into steam, which then runs the
turbines that generate the electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But on Feb. 15, one of the more than 3,000 tubes inside the
generator cracked, allowing radioactively contaminated water to mix
with clean water, according to the preliminary tests. Quinn said
that the size of the crack was not known yet, but that it was big
enough to allow 75 gallons per minute to escape, for a total of
perhaps 5,000 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were conducted over the weekend only at the one
generator that was known to have leaked, using eight cylindrical
robotic devices to check the tubes. The other three generators did
not leak, officials have said, but Quinn said that the many tests
to be conducted over the next few weeks would include checks of
those generators with the robots and with magnetic and fiber-optic
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn sounded a bit relieved that only one crack was found, near
the top of the tube, which resembles an upside-down U, as opposed
to dozens of cracks in several tubes, which might suggest a larger
problem or a domino effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``As somebody that's looking for a needle in a haystack, it's
really nice when you find the needle,'' Quinn said. ``There's a
sense of relief, that OK, we found a leak, and it fits, kind of,
the profile we thought we would see.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and other
nuclear-energy analysts also will be looking at the test results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that it was limited to one tube failing, but it's
bad that the tube failed at all,'' said David Lochbaum, a nuclear
safety engineer with the Union of Concerned Scientists, in
Washington. ``You're supposed to plug and replace these tubes
before they break, so it could mean that one cracked faster than
people thought. Or it could mean that the inspection process is not
rigorous enough to prevent the occasional failure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
