<SLUG> BC-OBIT-IRWIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN N. IRWIN II, FORMER AMBASSADOR, DIES AT 86 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Nichol Irwin II, a Manhattan lawyer and diplomat who served
under Gen. Douglas MacArthur during World War II and later became
ambassador to France, died on Monday at a hospital in New Haven,
Conn. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who lived in New Canaan, Conn., held numerous government
positions starting in 1947, when he was appointed a member of the
staff of the joint Philippine-American Finance Commission during
the Truman administration.
</P>
<P>
   From 1958 to 1961, Irwin was deputy assistant secretary of
defense for international security affairs under President
Eisenhower. President Johnson appointed him as the U.S.
representative for Panama Canal negotiations from 1965 to 1968.
President Nixon appointed him as his envoy to Peru in a
nationalization dispute in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was under secretary of state from 1970 to 1972 and deputy
secretary of state from 1972 to 1973. In 1973, he was appointed
ambassador to France, a position he held until the following year.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded the Medal of Freedom by Nixon, and the Legion
d'Honneur by the French government.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was born in Keokuk, Iowa, on Dec. 31, 1913 and graduated
from the Lawrenceville School and Princeton University. He received
a master's degree from Oxford University and a law degree from
Fordham University in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served in the Army in the Pacific as a
member of MacArthur's staff and reached the rank of lieutenant
colonel. After the war, Irwin practiced law at two Manhattan firms.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin spent many years on the boards of directors of IBM and of
the U.S. Trust Co. He also was a trustee of the Lawrenceville
School, Princeton, the Wildlife Conservation Society, The
Metropolitan Museum of Art, The American Museum of Natural History,
Union Theological Seminary, the National Gallery of Art, and the
French American Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Jane, died in 1970. He is survived by his second
wife, also named Jane; a daughter, Jane W.I. Droppa of Ellicott
City, Md.; a son, John N. Irwin III of Greenwich, Conn.; three
stepsons: Watkins W. Reynolds III and Thomas B. Reynolds of Fort
Worth, Texas, and Carl D. Reimers III of Greenwich, Conn., and 12
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
