<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-VIET-VETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: MCCAIN EASES THE STIGMA OF VIETNAM
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's not go overboard on this one. It isn't as if
the entire generation of Vietnam War veterans parades around now in
faded Army fatigues, buttonholing everyone in sight and nattering
on about those scary marches through the rice paddies and elephant
grass.
</P>
<P>
   But after long years of hunkering down in the darker recesses of
America's military past, Vietnam veterans are finally coming into
their own for their sacrifices in an unpopular war. The change has
been under way for a while. But some veterans feel it kicking into
higher gear with the rise of Sen. John McCain, whose presidential
candidacy has enabled them to bask in the reflected glory of an
honest-to-goodness war hero of their generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain phenomenon has rippled through the veterans
community,'' said Vincent McGowan, founding president of the
Manhattan chapter of Vietnam Veterans of America. The senator's run
for the White House, whether or not you like his politics, has
``shined the light of public attention on the commitment that
Vietnam veterans made back then,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   John Rowan, president of the Vietnam Veterans' New York State
Council, feels much the same way. ``It is interesting to see vets
being chased by the politicians for a change,'' Rowan said.
``Definitely, it's going around a little bit _ that to have served
is a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   To repeat, there is no need to go overboard. Main Street U.S.A.
isn't exactly tossing a parade for everyone who slogged through the
Mekong Delta. Don't hold your breath waiting for a Vietnam-era
version of ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Still, popular attitudes are
far from what they were in the 1960s and '70s, when returning
veterans found themselves ignored at best and spit on at worst,
denounced as baby killers by some war protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Many felt the scorn as recently as the mid-'80s, when New York
City dedicated the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, a wall of glass
blocks on a plaza between Water and South Streets in Lower
Manhattan. Over the years, the plaza has become a bit ragged. Many
blocks have eroded or are pockmarked _ from BB's fired at them,
McGowan said, by young vandals and disgruntled veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration is so extensive that there are plans for a $6
million redesign, which McGowan said might begin in May. But one
element will definitely not change, he said. As ever, the glass
wall will be etched with haunting reflections on war by Vietnam
grunts themselves, in poems and in letters home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother, I am cursed _ I'm a soldier when soldiers aren't in
fashion,'' wrote Sgt. Thomas Oathont, who was with the 173rd
Airborne Brigade in 1970 and '71. Elsewhere on the wall was this
thought from a Navy lieutenant, Richard W. Strandberg: ``One thing
worries me _ will people believe me? Will they want to hear about
it, or will they want to forget the whole thing ever happened?''
</P>
<P>
   McGowan, a former marine, looked back on the memorial's
dedication in 1985. Even then, he said, ``nobody cared what we had
been through.''
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, images of Vietnam veterans tended to focus
on, for want of a better phrase, the Lost Boys. You know them from
news photos and TV clips: straggly-haired men with beards and
droopy mustaches who would stand forlornly in front of the Vietnam
wall in Washington, their body language screaming that their lives
would never be put back together.
</P>
<P>
   No question, the Lost Boys are still out there and in need of
help, veterans who are homeless, on drugs or trapped in the bottle.
But there are many others, too, and they are often overlooked,
McGowan said. ``Vietnam vets have become mainstream,'' he said.
``You see them everywhere, from middle management on up.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you get more mainstream than running for president?
McCain's candidacy ``certainly makes service in that war more
palatable,'' Rowan said, though he added, ``I don't know about
glamorous yet.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to presidential candidates, we have moved directly
from the World War II generation to the Vietnam class _ from Bob
Dole four years ago to McCain and Vice President Al Gore. The
1950-53 Korean War has been pushed to the sidelines _ once again,
dismayed veterans of what some call ``the forgotten war'' will tell
you. With the clock running, that conflict seems unlikely to
produce a future president.
</P>
<P>
   But to McGowan, it is not a question of one war being better or
worse. ``Young people in the country are seeing now that service is
important,'' he said. ``I think for a while, we lost that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
