<SLUG> BC-NY-PET-STERILIZATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK BACKS LAW TO STERILIZE PETS FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration and several
prominent City Council members are supporting legislation that
would require all dogs and cats sold at pet shops in the city and
any animals adopted or reclaimed from city shelters to be
sterilized. Officials said such a law would sharply reduce the
number of animals euthanized in the city each year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 60,000 cats, dogs and other animals entered the
city-financed animal shelter system, and 65 percent of them were
put to death, while most of the others were adopted or returned to
their owners, said Marilyn Haggerty-Blohm, executive director of
the Center for Animal Care and Control, a city contractor. A few
wild animals were released.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed legislation, which was endorsed Monday at a
City Council hearing by the city Department of Health and a number
animal-welfare advocates, pet stores and the shelters would be
required to spay or neuter dogs or cats before selling them,
releasing them for adoption or returning them to their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions would be allowed if dogs or cats are intentionally
used for breeding or if the sterilization would endanger an
animal's life.
</P>
<P>
   Sterilization programs have worked in other cities. In Denver,
for instance, where similar legislation was adopted in 1993, the
number of impounded animals decreased by 18 percent, or about 2,000
animals, over a four-year period. The number of animals that had to
be euthanized decreased by 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 39,000 animals euthanized in New York City last year,
about 72 percent were killed because of old age, injuries,
temperament problems or other conditions. Haggerty-Blohm said that
with a sterilization program in place, the city could eventually
avoid the destruction of as many as 11,000 animals a year.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also require the city to expand its animal
shelter system, to increase its capacity to provide sterilization
and animal adoption services, and to offer round-the-clock animal
drop-offs in all boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Only Manhattan now has an animal shelter that is open 24 hours,
although a Brooklyn shelter will expand to similar hours by April,
city officials said. Staten Island has a shelter that is open 12
hours a day, but unlike the ones in Brooklyn and Manhattan, it is
too small to offer sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Animal Care and Control is planning to open a new
shelter in South Ozone Park, Queens, within two years, using $2.7
million in city money that has already been appropriated,
Haggerty-Blohm said. The search for a Bronx site has not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
   City officials did not say Monday how much the expanded animal
shelter system would cost and how quickly it could be set up. The
current operation costs about $8.5 million, and the American
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals estimated that the
price of the expanded system could reach $20 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
