<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTOR-     02-28 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX DISTRICT ATTORNEY DEFENDS DIALLO PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recasts lede; in optional material, names juror who
questioned prosecutors; minor editing elsewhere.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bronx district attorney, facing criticism for
failing to get a conviction of the four officers charged with
murdering Amadou Diallo, repeatedly insisted Monday that his
prosecutors had presented a strong case for conviction and
suggested that he did not understand the jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can say is these 12 people gave their best effort,''
the district attorney, Robert T. Johnson, said, ``but that doesn't
satisfy the people, the real people, the people of the entire
state, in knowing that justice worked the way it's supposed to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference he called to address criticisms of his
handling of the case, Johnson also said the justice system broke
down when an appeals court ordered the case moved to Albany, and he
faulted the judge's instructions to the jury on how to consider the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   But seven of the jurors, in a group interview Monday on NBC's
``Today'' show, said they had no choice but to acquit based on the
law and the facts presented to them.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, Lavette Freeman, said the prosecution had given her
no basis on which to convict. ``For me that hurts,'' Freeman, who
is black, said. She added that while she understood the anger of
those protesting the verdict, ``I have to take it back to the
district attorney's office; they didn't give me anything _
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, addressing the criticism directed against him, said:
``You know, there have been some who said that Robert Johnson
should resign. I think somebody who policed in the way these four
officers policed that night, they should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Their mistakes, their misjudgments, their
preconceptions, led to the violent and horrible death of an
innocent person.''
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Johnson insisted that the prosecution had
offered evidence warranting a conviction, showing that the
vestibule of the Bronx apartment building where Diallo was shot was
well lighted, that there was a pause in the police gunfire, and
that Diallo had been on the ground when most of the shots were
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We painted the picture, and I think we painted it loud and
clear, that Amadou Diallo was prejudged,'' Johnson said. ``That
they made judgments about Amadou Diallo that were incorrect. They
made assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, speaking of the jurors, he added, ``And I don't think
anybody can say that they couldn't come to those conclusions if
they wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson suggested several times that the officers may not have
been entirely truthful in their testimony. For example, he said the
officers' assertion that they had not moved Diallo's body after the
shooting strained credulity because, ``You know, there was a search
for a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers, he said, ``were testifying in front of each other
so that if they wanted to weave a case together, they could.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem his office faced, he said, was that ``basically
there are only five people who actually saw this'' _ the four
officers and Schrrie Elliott, a Bronx woman who testified for the
defense and whom Johnson implied his office did not find credible.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He also said prosecutors did not cross-examine Dr. James J.
Fyfe, an expert on police procedures who was the defense's last
witness, because he felt Fyfe did only ``minor damage'' to the
prosecution's case. At least one juror, Helen Harder, has said she
was surprised that prosecutors did not cross-examine Fyfe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand people differing with us on strategy,''
Johnson said, ``but please, no one underestimate the amount of
commitment we had to do justice in this particular matter.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said prosecutors did not raise the issue of race because
there was no ``overt proof'' that it motivated the officers'
actions, although, he said, ``there is very good reason to believe
that some doctor on Park Avenue would not have been shot reaching
for his wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He also answered criticism that prosecutors should have asked
the judge to instruct jurors to consider each of the shots
individually, on the grounds that perhaps the initial shots were
justified, but 41 were not. But Johnson said prosecutors did not
pursue that issue because ``every shot was unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Justice Joseph C. Teresi, Johnson said that prosecutors had
objected to the judge allowing the officers to claim three separate
kinds of legal justification for the shooting, two of which
presumed that Diallo was committing a crime, and Johnson reiterated
that there was no evidence of that. He also said he objected to the
judge re-reading to the jury each of the three kinds of
justification six times.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the way the judge charged the jury reflected
the way the criminal justice system protects defendants, and he
reminded people angry about the verdict that the system similarly
protects average defendants in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said reports that the judge visited defense lawyers at
their bed-and-breakfast after the trial, if true, were ``extremely
disturbing, because that kind of action can destroy confidence in
the people and the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney reserved his harshest criticism for an
appellate division's decision to move the trial to Albany from the
Bronx. Calling the change of venue ``horribly wrong,'' he said, ``I
think it is going to go down in history as one of the greatest
assaults on confidence in the criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some community leaders and elected officials have been rallying
to Johnson's defense. The Rev. Roger Hambrick said the Bronx Clergy
Task Force was going to meet with Johnson to hear his assessment of
the case. ``It's easy to point fingers now,'' he said. ``But
listen, we all knew it was going to be a very difficult task for
him to win up there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, agreed, saying
that while a dialogue was useful, Johnson should not resign.
</P>
<P>
   As he did after the officers' arraignment 11 months ago,
Johnson, who is black, addressed the larger discussion about police
conduct and procedures that the Diallo case has raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the Bronx since I was 16; I have a 19-year-old
son who lives here,'' he said. ``I know that when I get stopped,
and I have a couple of times, I have to say my license is in my
back pocket; the registration is in the glove compartment. That
kind of fear that some people have has to be addressed. And even if
it's not a policy thing, it's an attitudinal thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mind,'' he said, ``must be open to innocent
interpretations of people's conduct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
