<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITY AGREES TO DELAY SALE OF TWO NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Va.)  (See also NY-NUKE-INQUIRY) 
(mk) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The New York Power Authority agreed Monday to
delay the planned sale of two nuclear power plants to a New Orleans
company after lawmakers asked the authority to explore a higher,
last-minute bid from another company.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Authority's board was scheduled to vote Tuesday
morning on the sale of the plants _ located in Buchanan, in
Westchester County, and on Lake Ontario _ after three months of
exclusive negotiations with Entergy Corp. But Dominion Resources,
based in Virginia, made an unsolicited offer last week for $686
million. The Power Authority has said that Entergy's bid is worth
$638 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Zeltmann, president and chief operating officer for the
Power Authority, told legislators at a hearing that he had not
contacted Dominion and could not negotiate with any company other
than Entergy until Tuesday evening under an exclusivity agreement.
But he said his staff was reviewing Dominion's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Petralia, a spokesman for the Power Authority, said
later that the board had decided Monday evening to discuss the
agreement with Entergy at a meeting on Tuesday but would not take
any final vote on the sale of the power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard L. Brodsky, a Democrat from Westchester
County who is chairman of the Environmental Conservation Committee,
criticized the Power Authority for rushing to sell some of the
state's valuable assets. ``How can you responsibly close on a deal
when you can't talk to one of the bidders?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeltmann and other Power Authority officials have said that
they had negotiated a detailed agreement with Entergy that not only
brought a fair price for the nuclear power plants but also
safeguarded the jobs of the plants' 1,700 employees, among other
things. While Zeltmann defended the selection of Entergy through a
careful screening process, he emphasized that Dominion's offer
still would be considered. ``I never wanted to foreclose the
opportunity for someone to come in at the last moment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
