<HEADER>
A1503 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-BOEING-777X-SPI &LR;      02-28 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-777X-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO ANNOUNCE LAUNCH OF 777X PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Though many of the engineers and technicians who work
on the project are on strike, Boeing executives Tuesday will
announce in New York the long-awaited launch of two super
long-range versions of the popular 777.
</P>
<P>
   The planes are targeted for Asian airlines looking for 21st
century widebody jets that have the range to fly more than 300
passengers non-stop between Asia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing landed around 30 firm orders worth more than $5 billion,
so the company's board of directors gave the go ahead Monday to
formally launch the two planes, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 15 to 20 orders are pending, the sources said. If they
become firm, Boeing would have nearly $10 billion worth of orders
for the jets, which will compete against two Airbus planes that
already are in development.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing had been expected to launch the planes soon,
Tuesday's announcement comes in the midst of a three-week-old
strike by about 18,000 of the company's engineers and technical
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is kind of awkward,'' said Peter Jacobs, aerospace
analyst with the Ragen MacKenzie Group in Seattle. ``It's kind of
ironic that the engineers and technical workers who are key to
designing and developing these planes are out on strike and feel
alienated by the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bofferding, executive director of the Society of
Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace, which represents
about 14,000 of the engineers and technicians, questioned how
Boeing can expect go forward with the project when its engineers
aren't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement underscores how critical Boeing technical
workers are to their long-term success,'' he said. ``They (Boeing)
need to send some people to the negotiating table that are wilLing
to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediation to settle the increasingly bitter strike broke down
over the weekend, and no new talks are scheduled. The strike is
sure to be raised as an issue Tuesday when Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit and Commercial Airplanes boss Alan Mulally join Jack Welch,
chairman of General Electric, in making the launch announcement at
Welch's office in New York's Rockefeller Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing last year selected General Electric as exclusive supplier
of the powerful engines that will be needed for the new planes.
Also, the aircraft leasing unit of General Electric is believed to
be one of the launch customers for the new jets. Other possible
launch customers that Boeing has been talking with include EVA
Airways of Taiwan, Air France, All Nippon Airways, Cathay Pacific,
Singapore Airlines, Japan Airlines and International Lease Finance
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been getting very enthusiastic response from customers
for going ahead with the project,'' Mulally said in an interview
earlier this month with the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Boeing planes face significant challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is well into the development of two ultra-long-range
planes. The A340-500 will go head to head with the 777-200X, and
the A340-600 will compete with the 777-300X. Both Airbus planes
should be in service by September 2002, while Boeing will not
deliver the first of its new jets until the spring of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   David Venz, Airbus spokesman in the United States, said Monday
the European airplane maker has more than 100 firm orders and
commitments for the A340-500/600.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surprised they are coming in so late,'' he said of
Boeing's decision to finally launch the 777X jets.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had hoped to launch its two planes in 1997, but customer
response was lukewarm, in part because the planes lacked the range
and performance that many Asian airlines wanted. Many improvements
have since been made to the design, and Boeing now has the orders
to proceed with a launch.
</P>
<P>
   The 301-seat 777-200X will be able to fly up to 10,100 miles,
and the 359-seat 777-300X up to 8,314 miles. The 777-300X is seen
as a replacement for older models of the 747.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those customers Boeing has been courting, such as
Malaysia Airlines, are unhappy that General Electric will be the
sole supplier of the new engines for the planes.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric builds the GE-90 engine for existing 777-200s
and 777-300s.
</P>
<P>
   But most airlines that fly the 777 use engines built by
Rolls-Royce or Pratt &AMP; Whitney. Malaysia Airlines, which had
committed early on in 1997 to the 777X, is now reportedly leaning
toward the Airbus planes because they will be powered by
Rolls-Royce, as are other 777s in Malaysia's fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing chose General Electric in part because it did not believe
the market for the 777X planes _ about 500 total _ is big enough to
justify having three engine makers. Also, General Electric is
offering substantial financial support toward Boeing's developments
costs. Boeing will not disclose those total costs, but industry
analysts say they likely will be close to $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analysts welcomed the launch decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing has needed to get this into the market for a while
now,'' said Joe Campbell of Lehman Brothers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a plane they envisioned from day one when they were
designing the 777.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other analysts also said the launch means Boeing
Commercial Airplanes will see some increased spending on research
and development.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Boeing spends from 3 percent to 5 percent of revenue
on research and development, depending on where it is in the
manufacturing cycle.
</P>
<P>
   During the last three months of 1999, research and development
for Commercial Airplanes was only $89 million, or less than 1
percent of the group's revenue of $10 billion. It was $222 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the numbers explain why many Boeing engineers have
griped that the company appears more bent on making a profit and
pleasing shareholders than on taking financial risks on new
aircraft development programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This launch (of the 777X) will mean engineers will have an
exciting project to work on once they come back,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Smart, a 777X structures engineer who is on strike, said
she is pleased Boeing finally decided to launch the project. She
was part of the development team back in 1997 when the project was
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right time to bring these planes to market,'' she
said Monday. ``Now is the time to do it. We have the right
airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it curious they would launch with the engineers out.
... This is the correct step (the 777X launch) to take to preserve
the company, but it's frustrating they did not want to settle with
us before going ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Paul Nyhan contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
