<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON PRIMARY ARRIVES WITH AL GORE ON CRUISE CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Enjoying a big lead in key states that hold March
primaries, Al Gore is opting more for motion than matter these days
as he works to motivate loyalists without stirring up controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's travel itinerary is as busy as ever _ he
had four events in two Western states before flying to Los Angeles
late Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic presidential front-runner's speeches rarely
contain any new themes, and he has not unveiled any substantial
policy recommendations recently.
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow him can recite by memory his standard lines,
such as, ``We've just begun to fight,'' and ``The presidency is not
an academic exercise, not a seminar on some grand theory.''
</P>
<P>
   To guard against unpredictable headlines, Gore also has not held
a news conference in months, foreclosing opportunities by the media
to press him on timely issues.
</P>
<P>
   Often the only thing that changes from one campaign stop to
another is Gore's wardrobe, which alternates between dark suits and
earth-toned slacks and sports shirts.
</P>
<P>
   While his rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, continues to slam
Gore, increasingly the vice president is not returning the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say an unkind word about my opponent,'' he
told supporters at an airport rally in Pueblo, Colo. Rather, he
said, voters should vote for him because ``I'll do a better job and
I'm the one who came to Pueblo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has invested nearly a week in Washington state in
preparation for Tuesday's nonbinding primary there, said in
Seattle, ``I knew it would be difficult, and it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised to plow ahead to the March 7 ``Super Tuesday''
primaries, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not even bothering to spend the last two days before the
Washington primary in that state, although he conducted interviews
with Seattle and Spokane television stations Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president swung through the Seattle area last weekend,
but he quickly moved on to Colorado, which holds its primary March
10, and then later to Arizona, which holds its Democratic contest
March 11.
</P>
<P>
   At campaign stops in Colorado, Gore sounded very much like a
general election candidate, aiming his criticism squarely at the
Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faulted John McCain for opposing abortion rights,
environmental controls and gun control. Although on the day that
the vice president visited McCain's home state of Arizona he also
acknowledged he agreed with the senator's support of campaign
finance reform and anti-tobacco measures.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president raised the issue of gun control at a downtown
Denver rally when he spoke about last year's shootings at nearby
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming he did not want to politicize the tragedy, he
nevertheless blasted the GOP candidates for being ``in the hip
pocket of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore contrasted the booming economy under the Clinton
administration with the doldrums of the Reagan-Bush years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were in power before, they ran our economy into the
ground,'' he said in Pueblo. ``We don't want to go back to those
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also gloated over a decision by Aetna
insurance company to continue health coverage for the son of a
Washington state couple who met with the vice president in Seattle
on Sunday. Gore had publicized their plight at a rally there and
publicly chided Aetna for denying coverage to the 5-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president told a Seattle station that he was glad that
the publicity he gave the case forced the health insurer to back
down.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley started the day before dawn in Seattle, searching for
votes among commuters at the ferry terminal. He left the state on a
high note after a rainy but spirited rally at the University of
Washington that drew about 1,000 supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said that whatever happens Tuesday is ``not determinate of
March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   From Washington, Bradley headed to California for a
day-and-a-half courtesy call. Gore leads by a whopping 5-to-1
margin in the latest polls gauging California's March 7 jackpot
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley then planned to turn his focus for the final days before
``Super Tuesday'' to New York and New England, where he has shown
stronger appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX $$$
</P>
