<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-DEBATE-1STLD-W     02-28 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SOWS CONFUSION WITH PULLOUT FROM CALIFORNIA DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change `largest' to `most populous' in lede graf.)  
(See also MCCAIN-RIGHT, BUSH) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT4, 5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To Californians, it was all a little baffling. Why
would Sen. John McCain pull out of the only Republican debate
scheduled in the nation's most populous state the week before the
highest-stakes primary on the political calendar?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't fathom it for a moment,'' said Zev Yaroslavsky, a
Democrat on the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors. ``It's
been promoted quite a bit already, and to me, even though it's in
California, it's a national debate. McCain must feel he has a
darned good reason for pulling out of what is the last debate
before Super Tuesday. But I don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's decision to withdraw from the forum this Thursday in
Los Angeles took everyone by surprise, including the debate's
sponsors, CNN and The Los Angeles Times, which appeared to be
holding out hope Monday that McCain would reconsider. It also
caused dissension in McCain's own campaign: His communications
director, Daniel Schnur, was quoted in several California
newspapers Monday as saying that the withdrawal was ``definitely a
mistake'' and ``a tactical error at the staff level.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to McCain announced on Sunday that he was pulling out of
the event to campaign in New York, which also holds a primary on
March 7. They complained that while they agreed to the encounter
weeks ago, their opponent, Gov. George W. Bush, only consented last
Wednesday, the day after his losses in Michigan and Arizona, and by
then, McCain had made other plans.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, McCain's senior strategist, said the campaign had
decided to stick to its new schedule _ which includes a ride Friday
on McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus by the ``Today''
show _ because it offers far more free media exposure. ``I'm going
for the bigger ratings, the bigger audience,'' Murphy said. Howard
Opinsky, a McCain spokesman, added that the campaign suggested
instead that the two debate on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' this
Sunday, in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Bush were happy to reinforce the impression being
left in California that with polls showing the governor with a huge
lead among Republican voters, McCain decided to head east, where
his chances looked better on March 7. New York, Massachusetts and
Rhode Island are among the states in which the senator has said he
expects a strong showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you can interpret it,'' said Gerry Parsky,
the Bush campaign chairman in California, ``other than that the
McCain campaign is writing off California or treating it much less
importantly.'' Ari Fleischer, a Bush campaign spokesman, said, ``I
don't think he had a scheduling conflict; he had a polling
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican tacticians were troubled by McCain's pullout.
The Los Angeles debates _ the Democrats are to go head to head in a
similar forum on Wednesday _ were expected to be galvanizing
encounters in a diffuse week of campaigning. The tacticians
wondered if McCain's action would hurt his standing among those
drawn to his candidacy because he seems different from other
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more dangerous for McCain because McCain voters want
to see him,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster. ``There's an
intensity to the McCain voter who is highly interested in the
campaign and anxiously wants to hear everything he has to say. They
are more likely to be turned off than a typical Bush supporter.''
</P>
<P>
   If timing is everything, the withdrawal could not have come at a
less desirable juncture for McCain in the battle for the 162
delegates in California's winner-takes-all Republican balloting; it
has forced him into the defensive argument that he is not conceding
California, when, in fact, the campaign has devoted a lot of time
and money to the state.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's political director, said the campaign was
spending $3 million on advertising in California, the largest
commitment it was making anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Despite McCain's action, the news organizations said the forum
would go on with Bush and Alan Keyes participating. It was not
clear, however, if the sponsors would allow McCain to participate
from a remote location, as he did for an earlier debate in Phoenix,
or if they would opt for a theatrical flourish and set up a chair
or podium for him, on the off chance of a last-minute entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign seemed to support the idea. Fleischer said
that before Bush had agreed to participate, the organizers were
threatening to do the same to him: ``When we were advising The Los
Angeles Times that we could not give them a decision, they said it
would be McCain, Keyes and an empty chair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
