<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1635 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     02-28 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV05-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WITH THE OLD: SHOPPING ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 5)  
(lb) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One spring long ago, my husband and I flew to London on a
Swinging Weekend charter flight, sharing a sleepless night with
friends, casino-bound New Jerseyans and a Broadway star, her
husband and her lawyer. The star was going to London to buy an
African carving; the three were pooling their duty-free allowance
so it would enter the United States without tax. Returning, they
carried their trophy aboard in delight.
</P>
<P>
   Spring must stimulate human acquisitive instincts: It is a busy
season for buying, whether at flea markets, shops, auctions or
shows.
</P>
<P>
   A major show of American works, the Philadelphia Antiques Show
at the 33rd Street Armory, will be held from April 8 to 12. In
London, the Chelsea Antiques Fair runs from March 17 to 26 at the
Old Town Hall on the King's Road, and the British Antique Dealers'
Association Fair, a new event at the Duke of York's Headquarters on
the King's Road, is March 22 to 28. The Grosvenor House fair will
be held June 14 to 20 on Park Lane; the Fine Art and Antiques Fair
June 8 to 18 at the Olympia on Hammersmith Road. (Information at
www.londontown.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Some people travel to buy, as the Broadway star did; most people
buy antiques, old books and art to retain memories of their trip.
But when one progresses from flea-market tables into serious
buying, things grow less casual. Here are some aspects requiring
attention from those stepping into bigger purchases abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Buyer Beware
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, if you like an object and it is in acceptable
condition, you won't go too far wrong buying at a show like those
above. The British Antique Dealers and similar associations select
their peers carefully; one unscrupulous merchant hurts them all.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the case in London's Bermondsey market or other
strips of shops and stands, where part of the fun is the
eccentricity. You may get guidance from ``Antique and Flea Markets
of London and Paris'' by Rupert Thomas and Egle Salvy (Thames &AMP;
Hudson, $19.95). This 1999 paperback has charming photographs and
phrases like ``covetable junk'' that indicate what you may find in
a given area.
</P>
<P>
   If you are spending a considerable sum, you probably want some
expert help, and electronics has made it easier. The ability to
transmit electronic images has revolutionized the world of art and
antique evaluation, according to John A. Hays of Christie's in New
York, who specializes in fine American furniture.
</P>
<P>
   He said that electronic inquiries referred to his department had
risen ``from zero two years ago'' to a steady stream now. A
Sotheby's spokeswoman, Lindsey S. Pryor, said that she gets 100
e-mail inquiries a day.
</P>
<P>
   Hays says he gets inquiries from England, South America and even
South Africa about furniture that proves to be American. It's a
result, he says, of a thriving ``venture cargo'' business in
earlier centuries: Half of what furniture makers created was loaded
onto vessels for sale down the line.
</P>
<P>
   However, the word ``appraisal'' is not properly applied to a
response given by a reputable dealer to an electronic photograph
and inquiry, despite the use of the term in the names of some
services. Rather it is an informed opinion. Dealers' formal
appraisals, made for estates or gifts, are given after inspection
and are done for a fee; the organization stands behind such an
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said that Sotheby's does not evaluate objects that people
are considering buying, but will give a range of what similar
objects have brought at auction recently. Christie's characterized
its evaluations as ``preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither organization charges for this service. The time needed
for a reply depends on the backlog.
</P>
<P>
   The Christie's site, www.christies.com, provides phone numbers
for its departments; until the auction house departmentalizes its
e-mail addresses, shoppers should phone the department first and
ask where to send an electronic inquiry. Sotheby's is also
preparing to sort its e-mail to particular experts; meanwhile, the
Web site, Sothebys.com, gives one e-mail address for both formal
and informal inquiries: appraisalsna(at)sothebys.com.
</P>
<P>
   With all inquiries, several photographs, measurements and a
description are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Faster opinions on the value of a proposed purchase is the goal
of a service just started by Leslie Hindman, a cable-channel expert
who owned a big auction house in Chicago that was bought by
Sotheby's in 1997. Hindman's service, called eppraisals, intends to
provide prompt evaluation on the basis of an electronic image,
measurements and a description _ for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Decker, a journalist with a background in antiques, has
the title of ``chief community strategist'' for eppraisals. He said
that three experts in New York could call on a network of
specialists, and since the image moves electronically,
consultations are quick. The company, which started operating Feb.
1, charges $20 for its evaluation, which it guarantees to provide
at the start of the fourth business day after the image is
received, as clocked in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Decker has advice for inexperienced buyers. ``Be sure you have a
tape measure,'' he said. ``Get a good description of the condition
of the object.'' For those without a digital camera, which is the
fastest way to go, a conventional photograph can be taken to a
short-order photo-processor and a transmittable image obtained. Or
a regular print can be scanned into a computer. More information:
www.eppraisals.com.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pedigree Papers
</P>
<P>
   The seller should provide satisfactory documentation of what has
been bought and for how much. The object's age is quite important,
particularly for duty in the United States. The seller usually
includes a description of the condition, especially if the object
has been mended or dented, lest the buyer say something was
concealed. The probable place of origin can be noted.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the worst part _ getting the object home. My hairiest
experience was arriving for a flight from London to Dublin,
carrying on a huge tea set neatly tied up in several boxes, and
discovering that the police at the London airport wanted to unwrap
every piece to be sure I was not running arms.
</P>
<P>
   The major shows anticipate this. At the British Antique Dealers'
Association Fair this month, among others, professional packing and
shipping companies will be present. Gander &AMP; White, with an office
in New York as well as London and Paris, is one such outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O. Aiston, the U.S. director of the company, said that for
objects of some size, professional shipping was essential. ``It
comes inside our container,'' he said. ``It is never handled on the
dock.'' Gander &AMP; White ships a container to New York every two to
three weeks, he said, so it is four or five weeks before the object
is in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for packing and shipping, Aiston said, are based on the
size of the object, its insurance value and some modest customs
charges, although there is no duty for objects 100 years old or
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never assume that something is going to be insured
automatically,'' Aiston said. ``We insure if we are asked. That is
because dealers have their own. Insurance stops the
finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Things being shipped professionally have their own customs
forms, prepared by the shipper, and they are not listed on the
travelers' declarations for customs.
</P>
<P>
   For objects being carried away, he said, a dealer will usually
offer to get it wrapped for the buyers. Aiston said his company's
representatives at the major shows do not charge for such services.
The hand-carried parcel should come with export documentation, to
prevent the undoing experience I had in London.
</P>
<P>
   When items are packed for carrying on the buyer's request, the
charge is hourly, Aiston said. Packing my tea set at today's rates,
he said, would probably have cost me $160, and probably would have
been worth it to have documents certifying what it was. Aiston's
company's site is www.ganderandwhite.com.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Customs regulations affecting art and antiques are many
and arcane. For most amateur buyers, a free booklet called ``Know
Before You Go, Customs Regulations for U.S. Residents'' can help.
The current edition, printed in May 1997, is about to be replaced.
The version on www.customs.ustreas.gov was due for revision this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The duty-free limit is still $400 a person, but another level,
at which a plain passenger changes into an importer and must fill
out more complex documents, was adjusted upward to $2,000 on Jan.
1, 1998. A single object for which over $2,000 was paid may require
the bigger form.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Mushinske, the Customs Service specialist on art and
antiques, said that duty rates on most objects had been dropping 10
percent a year, too, and the booklets no longer include such rates
for this reason.
</P>
<P>
   An object still has to be 100 years old to qualify as an antique
for Customs purposes. The service interprets ``circa'' as five
years either way, so ``circa 1900'' will not cut it, although
``circa 1895'' will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object must have existed 100 years ago the way it is
now,'' Mushinske said. ``If a 100-year-old vase has been turned
into a lamp, it will not classify as an antique.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Tourist Authority says that antiques _ 100 years old
_ are not subject to the British value added tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0541 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-RIGHT-3RDLD-WR     02-28 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RIGHT-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN DENOUNCES LEADERS OF RELIGIOUS RIGHT AS `AGENTS OF
INTOLERANCE'
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Changes ``30 miles'' to ``a few miles'' in 3rd graf. Inserts
2 new grafs, beginning ``But a subtext ...'') 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT4-5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. _ Taking his presidential campaign to a
stronghold of Christian conservatism, Sen. John McCain of Arizona
delivered a harsh attack Monday on the ``self-appointed leaders''
of the religious right, depicting them as intolerant empire
builders who ``have turned good causes into businesses'' while
attempting to exclude all but ``card-carrying Republicans'' from
the party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain singled out for criticism two of the Christian right's
best-known leaders, Pat Robertson, the founder of the Christian
Coalition, and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, the founder of the Moral
Majority. He compared Robertson to ``union bosses who have
subordinated the interests of working families to their own
ambitions,'' and he accused both men of attempting to distort his
position on abortion and ``smear the reputations of my
supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of division and slander are not our values,''
McCain said during a somber address to some 4,000 people who packed
a high school gymnasium here only a few miles from the headquarters
of the Christian Coalition. ``They are corrupting influences on
religion and politics and those who practice them in the name of
religion or in the name of the Republican Party or in the name of
America shame our faith, our party and our country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's remarks came on the eve of another primary day in what
has become a bitter battle with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, a
fight that has become increasingly focused on the appeals Bush made
to religious conservatives in winning the South Carolina primary.
And while McCain's statements Monday may cost him votes among the
religious right in Virginia, whose contest is one of three to be
held on Tuesday, his aides were counting on media coverage to
attract more moderate voters in New York, Ohio and California _ who
vote on March 7 and are more crucial to McCain's overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Washington state Monday, Bush dismissed McCain's
remarks. ``This is a political game that Senator McCain is trying
to play by pitting one group of people against another,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a problem-solver,'' he added. ``It sounds like he's a
finger-pointer.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson could not be reached for comment, but the Christian
Coalition released a statement saying, ``Christian Coalition will
rise above this transparent effort to divide one American from
another on the basis of religion. Our pro-family message of faith
and freedom will draw citizens to the polls in record numbers as we
encourage all people of faith to continue their active involvement
in the process we call Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Falwell said he would have no comment. During
his address, and again in interviews with reporters, McCain
repeatedly framed his speech not as an attack on the Christian
right, but as an appeal to religious conservatives to join him in
condemning political tactics pursued by Robertson and Falwell on
behalf of Bush..
</P>
<P>
   As he has for weeks, McCain on Monday accused Robertson of
slandering his national campaign co-chairman, former Sen. Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., in telephone calls to voters, by calling him a
``vicious bigot'' for criticisms he had made of the religious
right. McCain also suggested that leaders of the religious right
may have been behind other calls and e-mails to voters accusing him
of fathering children out of wedlock and pointing out that he and
his wife, Cindy, have adopted a daughter from Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party,'' he added, ``should be defined by pandering to
the outer reaches of American politics and the agents of
intolerance, whether they be Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton on the
left, or Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political intolerance by any political party is neither a
Judeo-Christian nor an American value,'' he also said.
</P>
<P>
   On his campaign bus, he told reporters, ``Before South Carolina,
I don't think I would have given a speech like this.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides said the speech was partly intended to
reemphasize Bush's avid support from Christian conservatives one
day after he expressed regret, in a letter to Cardinal John
O'Connor of New York, for an address he gave at Bob Jones
University, a bastion of the religious right in South Carolina
whose leaders have spoken harshly of Catholics and banned
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   McCain referred to Bush in his speech as a ``Pat Robertson
Republican who will lose to Al Gore,'' and later, his press aides
distributed a packet of campaign materials and news reports that
they said showed numerous links between Bush's campaign and top
officials at Bob Jones University. One Bush flyer quoted Bob
Taylor, a dean at Bob Jones University, praising Bush for his
``pro-family leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But a subtext of the speech was McCain's campaign finance
proposals, including limits on advertisements by advocacy groups.
Robertson and anti-abortion advocates have said those restrictions
would stifle their influence and were one reason they opposed
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech McCain said of them: ``They distort my pro-life
positions and smear the reputations of my supporters. Why? Because
I don't pander to them, because I don't ascribe to their failed
philosophy that money is our message.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, McCain described his speech as part of an effort
to redefine the Republican Party itself, to move it closer to the
center, much as President Clinton tried to do to the Democratic
Party during his 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of Ronald Reagan, not Pat Robertson,'' McCain
said in his speech. ``We are the party of Theodore Roosevelt, not
the party of special interests. We are the party of Abraham
Lincoln, not Bob Jones. Join us. Join us.''
</P>
<P>
   As he concluded, the crowd _ half of which were high school
students _ stood and applauded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Bush scoffed at the senator's claims: ``Ronald Reagan didn't
point fingers. He never played to people's religious fears, as
Senator McCain has shamelessly done.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Leslie Goodman, a Republican political consultant
in Sacramento who backs Bush, said of McCain: ``Truly, the prince
of candor has turned into the king of media pander. But what he is
really doing is confirming to rank-and-file Republicans that he's
at war with everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   According to McCain's aides, the idea of the speech was first
suggested by McCain's campaign manager, Rick Davis, during a flight
on Friday from San Diego to Cleveland. As McCain's senior advisers
debated whether to make a campaign stop in Maryland or Virginia,
Davis suggested going to Virginia and making a speech some place
like Lynchburg, where Falwell is based. But the campaign settled on
Robertson's back yard instead. ``It's not just a major moment in
this campaign, it's a major moment for social conservatives,'' said
Marshall Wittman, a former legislative director for the Christian
Coalition who advises McCain and joined the campaign for the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
