<HEADER>
A1639 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-28 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS! CAMERA! ARPAIO! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - No sooner did an Arizona production company announce
its plans to make a ``cute or fun'' movie about Maricopa County
Sheriff Joe Arpaio when serious casting problems set in.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arpaio sees Robert DeNiro or Al Pacino in the title role of a
film to be based on his book, America's Toughest Sheriff, though he
says he's willing to settle for Joe Pesci.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, producers have floated the name of Roseanne's
ex-husband, Tom Arnold, perhaps because the late Jackie Gleason
isn't available to reprise the Sheriff Buford T. Justice character
he perfected in Smokey and the Bandit.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning of the casting quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Who will play Arpaio's right-hand man, double-dipping Deputy
Dave Hendershott?
</P>
<P>
   Don Knotts is still alive, but anyone who knows Hendershott can
tell you Knotts isn't a big enough actor to fill the deputy's
shoes, or any other part of his wardrobe. Still, the role cries out
for the performer who immortalized Barney Fife.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the chief executive officer of Desert Winds
production company told The Republic that the movie of Arpaio's
life will be ``cute or fun.``
</P>
<P>
   But what about David Michael Pecard? Who'll play the AWOL
soldier from Fort Huachuca who talked his way into the sheriff's
inner circle, obtained keys, a badge and an office, and even posed
as Arpaio's bodyguard?
</P>
<P>
   I hear O.J.'s available.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the deputies who say they were forced out of
their jobs by henchmen trying to purge news leaks from the
Sheriff's Office? Perhaps they could play themselves. They need the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll get the ``cute or fun'' role of Wayne Bates, the postal
worker who was hauled off to jail in front of TV cameras for using
pepper spray on a pair of fenced-in dogs? No charges were filed,
though Bates did file a whopping lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   And who will they cast as Tim Griffin, a one-time inmate at
Joe's jail who was denied medical treatment for a perforated ulcer
after begging for help? A Superior Court jury ordered the county to
pay him $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll play George E. Sullivan and Gene Miller, experts who
produced reports on the brutality in Joe's lockups?
</P>
<P>
   A convincing young actor is needed to portray Jeremy Flanders.
He was beaten by inmates at Joe's Tent City jail and later awarded
more than $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Richard Post? He's a paraplegic abused while in
sheriff's custody and later paid $800,000. There aren't many actors
who can do ``cute or fun'' from a wheelchair, particularly when
being roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be especially difficult to cast the part of County
Attorney Rick Romley. The local prosecutor recently joined the long
list of those who've filed suit against Arpaio. It's all part of a
two-man feud that's been nastier, longer-running and more
entertaining than the one made famous by Boss Hogg and the Dukes of
Hazzard.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the problem of financing. Movies are expensive
propositions. They require the support of wealthy investors.
</P>
<P>
   I'm personally acquainted with a nice couple who recently came
into $8.25 million. Jaron and Deena Norberg received the cash from
Maricopa County to settle a lawsuit they'd filed after their son
died horribly at the hands of Joe's guards.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, even if some of that $8.25 million was used to solve
money problems for producers of the ``cute or fun'' movie they'd
still be left with a tricky casting dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll play Scott Norberg? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona Republic.com or at (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-00 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000228.0543 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1641 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-RIGHT-ART-3RDL     02-28 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RIGHT-ART-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
VIRGINIA BEACH, Va.: the speech.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday McCain's speechwriter, Marc Salter, began drafting the
address, and revisions continued until an hour before the speech.
There was an air of anticipation about McCain as his bus pulled up
to Cox High School. McCain, who likes to encourage the view that he
is a straight talker who refuses to pander to audiences, said he
relished the prospect of taking on Robertson in what one aide
described as a ``target-rich environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit,'' McCain said before getting off the bus, ``that
being on the Death Star is an environment we've become comfortable
with.''
</P>
<P>
   But while McCain was offering up jaunty Star Wars metaphors and
insisting he was unconcerned by the political risks of criticizing
the leaders of the religious right, he and his aides took several
steps to minimize the chances that some would interpret his words
as an attack on all Christian fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   They made certain to stud the speech with signposts of McCain's
conservative record _ from his eagerness to ban partial birth
abortions, to opposition of tax increases, to his admiration for
Ronald Reagan. And during his speech, McCain was careful to praise
several leaders of the religious right, including Chuck Colson,
founder of Prison Fellowship, an evangelical group that ministers
to inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' McCain said. ``Evangelical leaders are
changing America for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   He also brought along with him a well-known social conservative,
Gary Bauer, a former Republican presidential candidate and once the
executive director of the Family Research Council. ``If this were
an attack on Christian voters I wouldn't be here today,'' said
Bauer, who endorsed McCain shortly after he dropped out of the
race.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, there was no disguising the extraordinary sight of a
major Republican candidate so directly and vehemently denouncing
two highly visible leaders from the very wing of the party that for
nearly 20 years has been a dominant force in getting Republicans
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was concerned that his speech might rupture the
Republican Party, McCain flipped the question around toward
Robertson and Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've already ripped the party apart with what they did in
South Carolina and other campaigns,'' he said as his campaign
airplane left Virginia for the West Coast. ``I'm trying to bring
the party back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Several aides pointed out that reconciliation was central to the
one passage in the speech that brought a hush over the otherwise
squirming high school students. In the passage, McCain recounted
the time he was tied up in ``torture ropes'' and left in an empty
room after his capture in the Vietnam War. A guard, he said,
loosened the ropes, then tightened them before his ``less
humanitarian comrades returned.''
</P>
<P>
   Months later, McCain said, the two of them stood together in the
prison courtyard on a Christmas morning. Without uttering a word,
McCain said, the guard drew a cross in the dirt with his sandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is my faith,'' McCain said. ``The faith that unites and
never divides, the faith that bridges unbridgeable gaps in
humanity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
